// Englische Erklärungen (kuratierter Satz). Key = `<dialektId>.<ausdruckId>`.
// Wird von js/util/translations.js lazy geladen, wenn Erklärungs-Sprache = en.
// Fehlende Keys → Fallback auf die deutsche Original-bedeutung.
// Pflege/Erweiterung: node tools/translate.mjs --lang=en (zeigt Abdeckung + fehlende Keys).

export default {
  // Hessisch — vollständigerer Satz
  'hessisch.h-001': `The best-known Hessian greeting. "Guude" comes from "guten Tag" (good day); the "Ei" is a characteristic intensifying particle. Used at any time of day — morning, noon or night.`,
  'hessisch.h-002': `The iconic, usually blue-grey stoneware jug in which Frankfurt cider (Ebbelwoi) is served. A symbol of Hessian drinking culture — typically with pretzels and Handkäs cheese.`,
  'hessisch.h-003': `In Hessian, "babbeln" means to talk or chatter. "Babbel net" is a friendly but direct way of saying "stop talking nonsense" — though it can also express genuine indignation.`,
  'hessisch.h-004': `The Hessian form of the first name Georg. Often the epitome of the typical Hessian man — easy-going, down-to-earth, with a fondness for cider.`,
  'hessisch.h-005': `An affectionate term for a small child. The ending "-sche" is the Hessian diminutive (equivalent to standard German "-chen").`,
  'hessisch.h-006': `An exclamation of surprise or mild dismay, derived from "almighty God". Heard in everyday situations — anywhere from "great!" to "oh dear".`,
  'hessisch.h-007': `In Frankfurt people distinguish "Hibbdebach" (this side of the Main, the north bank) from "Dribbdebach" (the far side, south bank / Sachsenhausen). A typical bit of Frankfurt local colour.`,
  'hessisch.h-008': `Literally "yellow sausage". In Frankfurt a traditional, mild cooked sausage. Colloquially also used for something trivial or a petty quarrel.`,
  'hessisch.h-010': `The classic Hessian pronunciation of "Wurst" (sausage) — with a soft "r" and a "d" instead of "t" at the end. Also a saying: "Des is mer worschd" = "I couldn't care less".`,
  'hessisch.h-011': `A "Schwätzer" is someone who talks non-stop or superficially. Good-natured or mildly disparaging depending on context. "En alder Schwätzer" (an old chatterbox) often describes a talkative neighbour.`,

  // Je ein ikonischer Ausdruck pro weiterem Dialekt
  'berlinisch.b-001': `The Berlin word for "I" (me) — a longer, stressed form of "ick". "Icke, dette, kieke mal" is seen as the epitome of Berlin dialect.`,
  'bayerisch.by-001': `An all-purpose greeting and farewell across Bavaria and Austria, used both on meeting and on parting. From the Latin "servus" ("servant"), but no longer hierarchical.`,
  'saechsisch.s-001': `A classic Saxon way of agreeing. "Nu" is like "well", "freilich" an old emphatic "of course". Often delivered in a cosy, dry tone.`,
  'schwaebisch.sw-001': `The classic southern German greeting, often formal. In Swabian it's frequently softened to "Grüß Gott'le".`,
  'koelsch.k-001': `People in Cologne greet each other with "Tach!" at any time of day — a relaxed, falling-tone short form of "Tag" (day), casual and warm. You hear it on every corner of the Veedel (neighbourhood).`,
  'plattdeutsch.p-001': `The all-purpose northern German greeting — morning, noon, evening or night. It comes from "mooi" ("nice"), not from "Morgen" (morning). In the true North, "Moin Moin" already counts as chit-chat.`,
  'schwizerduetsch.ch-001': `The Swiss polite greeting. Plural: "Grüezi mitenand!". In Bern also "Grüessech".`,
  'wienerisch.w-001': `"Servus" is the universal greeting, formal or informal alike. "Grüß Gott" is more polite and traditional.`,
  'fraenkisch.fr-001': `"Gell" is a tag particle at the end of a sentence inviting agreement, like "right?". Widespread in Franconian (as in Bavarian and Hessian), with a distinctive lilt — often drawn out: "Geelll?".`,
  'ruhrdeutsch.ru-001': `In the Ruhr area people greet with "Moin" (from Low German) or the clipped "Tach". Both work any time and are warm without being stiff — the brevity is pure Ruhr directness: no unnecessary fuss.`,
  'alemannisch.al-001': `The Alemannic morning greeting sounds warmer than standard "Guten Morgen", thanks to the lowered "e" and a sing-song tone. The standard morning greeting in Baden and Alsace, used by young and old alike.`,
  'pfaelzisch.pf-001': `The typical Palatinate greeting with French roots, noticeably friendlier than the northern "Moin". It reflects centuries of French influence on the Palatinate, especially under Napoleon. Charmingly border-crossing.`,
  'tirolerisch.ti-001': `The everyday Tyrolean greeting among acquaintances, from "grüß dich". For several people you say "Griaß enk", more formally "Griaß Gott".`,
  'saarlaendisch.sl-001': `"The main thing is to eat well" — the Saarland motto for life: as long as the food's good, all's right with the world. It captures the Saarlanders' relaxed, food-loving attitude.`,
  'ostfriesisch.of-001': `The omnipresent East Frisian greeting — morning, noon and night. It comes not from "Morgen" (morning) but from a word for "good". A single "Moin" is plenty.`,
  'badisch.bad-001': `The Alemannic word for "that" or "those". "Sell isch guet" means "that's good". One of the most typical Baden words — it instantly gives away a local.`,
  'vorarlbergerisch.vb-001': `"Gsi" means "been" — "I bin det gsi" means "I've been there". The word is so typical that Vorarlbergers are nicknamed "Gsiberger" in the rest of Austria.`,
  'steirisch.st-001': `The everyday Styrian greeting among acquaintances. For several people you say "Griaß enk", more formally "Griaß Gott" — a warm, Bavarian-style greeting.`,
  'kaerntnerisch.kt-001': `The everyday Carinthian greeting among acquaintances, with a sing-song lilt. For several people you say "Griaß enk", more formally "Griaß Gott".`,
  'thueringisch.th-001': `The typical Thuringian "yes" — it means "yeah" or "of course". Asked whether they're coming, a Thuringian simply replies with a convinced "Nu".`,
  'mecklenburgisch.mk-001': `The omnipresent northern greeting, used at any time of day. A single "Moin" is enough — to some, the double "Moin moin" already sounds too chatty.`,
  'brandenburgisch.br-001': `The emphatic "I" of Berlin-Brandenburg. "Icke, dette, kieke mal" is a well-known phrase. It stresses oneself with a touch of pride.`,
  'oberpfaelzisch.op-001': `The everyday Upper Palatinate greeting among acquaintances. For several people you say "Griaß enk", more formally "Griaß God" — a warm Bavarian greeting.`,

  // Weitere Ausdrücke populärer Dialekte
  'berlinisch.b-004': `Watch out for confusion! In Berlin a "Pfannkuchen" is what's called "Berliner" or "Krapfen" elsewhere — a sweet yeast pastry with jam filling. A pancake, by contrast, is called "Eierkuchen" here.`,
  'berlinisch.b-006': `The Berlin swap of "g" for "j" is legendary: "janz" for "ganz" (whole), "jut" for "gut" (good), "Jurke" for "Gurke" (cucumber).`,
  'berlinisch.b-007': `An exclamation of surprise or mild indignation. "Meier" stands in for "somebody" — an old, very common family name.`,
  'bayerisch.by-002': `The more formal, traditional greeting in Catholic Bavaria and Austria. Even for the non-religious: a polite phrase used at any time of day.`,
  'bayerisch.by-005': `A universal Bavarian exclamation — depending on tone it expresses admiration, sympathy or mild annoyance. "Mei, is des schö!" (how lovely!) or "Mei, war ma des aanstrengend!" (how exhausting!).`,
  'bayerisch.by-009': `Half-joking, half-scolding: someone doing something silly or crazy. "Du Damischer!" is more affectionate than insulting.`,
  'saechsisch.s-003': `Saxon for "look here!" / "guck mal!". Often spoken with a pronounced vowel colour — "Guggemal!" or "Guggesdumal!".`,
  'saechsisch.s-004': `Saxon for "Hochgenüsse" (great delights) — a vivid example of the typical Saxon vowel shift (the "o" becomes a long, drawn-out "e"). Made legendary by a famous GDR-era cabaret.`,
  'saechsisch.s-005': `Saxon for "once / one time". A classic vowel change — "ei" becomes "ee", as in "Heem" (home) and "Klee" (small).`,
  'schwaebisch.sw-002': `The Swabian motto for life — work hard, save up, build your own little house. A self-ironic stereotype of Swabian diligence and thrift.`,
  'schwaebisch.sw-003': `The diminutive of "Haus" (house) with the typical Swabian "-le" ending. Often said with pride: one's own little house, frequently self-built.`,
  'plattdeutsch.p-002': `Literally "shit weather". In the North a matter-of-fact, honest description of rain, wind and grey skies — i.e. much of the year.`,
  'plattdeutsch.p-004': `Low German for "small / little". Also in the Hamburg dockworkers' drink "Lütt un Lütt" (beer + grain schnapps). Related to English "little".`,
  'wienerisch.w-002': `A Viennese farewell. Casual and friendly, pronounced roughly "pa-ba". Also playfully lengthened: "bababa".`,
  'wienerisch.w-005': `Austrian for scrambled eggs. Traditionally served with chives and dark bread.`,

  // Vertiefung: Kölsch, Schwizerdütsch, Fränkisch, Ruhrdeutsch, Alemannisch
  'koelsch.k-003': `In the wider sense a "madman", in the narrower sense a carnival reveller. "Jeder Jeck is anders" (every fool is different) is a core philosophy of life in Cologne — everyone is different, and that's a good thing.`,
  'koelsch.k-004': `A "Bützje" (little kiss) is handed out generously during carnival — on the cheek, no ulterior motive. "Bützen" is something of a folk sport during the "fifth season".`,
  'koelsch.k-005': `Article 3 of the "Cologne Constitution": "It's always turned out fine so far" — the Cologne philosophy of serenity. Why fret? It'll work out.`,
  'koelsch.k-006': `Article 2 of the "Cologne Constitution": "What's gone is gone." Advice on acceptance — what's lost won't come back, so move on.`,
  'schwizerduetsch.ch-002': `Swiss-German way of saying thanks — French "merci" plus German "vielmal" (many times). Very typical of the francophone influence.`,
  'schwizerduetsch.ch-003': `Swiss German for bicycle (from French "vélo"). Standard across German-speaking Switzerland; hardly anyone says "Fahrrad".`,
  'schwizerduetsch.ch-004': `The "Znüni" is the Swiss mid-morning snack at 9 o'clock — a croissant, apple or muesli. A fixed part of the daily routine and of break culture at many workplaces.`,
  'fraenkisch.fr-002': `The Franconian all-purpose formula of composure. Whether something's not quite right, you overpaid, or it's only half-finished — "Bassd scho" (it's fine) smooths it over. Pragmatic, relaxed, unflappable.`,
  'fraenkisch.fr-003': `Franconian form of "we have". Typical is the leading "h" that standard German drops after "wir" — a feature that clearly sets Franconian apart from neighbouring Bavarian.`,
  'fraenkisch.fr-004': `The Franconian form of the demonstrative "das" (that/the), where the "a" has often become an open "e". One of the most common words in everyday Franconian — in nearly every sentence.`,
  'ruhrdeutsch.ru-002': `The traditional miners' greeting and an emblem of Ruhr culture. It wished the miner that the seam would open before him and that he'd return safely to daylight. Today a symbol of the region's whole mining identity, used at gatherings and farewells.`,
  'ruhrdeutsch.ru-003': `In the Ruhr a universal exclamation — amazement, outrage, delight or simply getting attention. As a form of address it's neutral-to-friendly, used for men and women alike; the tone decides whether it's delight or real outrage.`,
  'ruhrdeutsch.ru-004': `In the Ruhr the "Flappe" is the mouth, usually paired with a call for silence. "Halt die Flappe!" is blunter than "be quiet", but not necessarily hostile here. From Low German, widespread across Westphalia.`,
  'alemannisch.al-002': `A Baden farewell from the Alemannic region, probably derived from "Gott befohlen" (God keep you); the fast speech rhythm makes it sound like a single word. Especially common in Freiburg and the Breisgau.`,
  'alemannisch.al-003': `The Alemannic tag question added to the end of a sentence (southern Baden, Swabia, Switzerland), expecting agreement. It sounds softer and more questioning than its Franconian counterpart, thanks to the sing-song lilt.`,
  "hessisch.h-013": "„Daddrich“ describes someone who is a bit dreamy, clumsy or scatterbrained. Not meant unkindly, more amused and sympathetic. „Sei doch ned so daddrich!“ (“Don't be so daddrich!”) the grandmother calls out to her grandson, who has knocked over a Bembel again.",
  "berlinisch.b-008": "Berliners use the dative where standard German requires the accusative — „dir“ instead of „dich“. A classic Berlin saying: „Ick liebe dir, ick liebe dich, wie't richtig is, dit weeß ick nich.“ (“I love you [dat.], I love you [acc.], which one is right, that I don't know.”)",
  "bayerisch.by-011": "A very traditional, slightly old-fashioned form of greeting. Shortened from „Habe die Ehre“ (“I have the honor”). Today it comes across as charming and elegant.",
  "saechsisch.s-006": "An affectionately ironic name for Saxon Switzerland or the Ore Mountains — no real high mountains, but for Saxony they're quite something.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-004": "The Swabian specialty par excellence: soft, fresh egg noodles, scraped from a board or pressed. „Käsespätzle“ with mountain cheese and fried onions is a national dish.",
  "koelsch.k-007": "Watch out, it's a trap! Not half a chicken, but a rye roll with Dutch cheese, mustard and gherkins. A classic in the brewery tavern.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-005": "Low German for a young girl or a young woman. „Lütte Deern“ = „little girl“. It is still used affectionately today.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-005": "The „Zvieri“ is the Swiss snack at 4 p.m. — the sibling of the „Znüni“. Classically: bread with cheese, chocolate or a piece of fruit. A firm part of everyday Swiss life.",
  "wienerisch.w-006": "In Austria, apricots are called Marillen. „Marillenknödel“ (apricot dumplings) and „Marillenmarmelade“ (apricot jam) are part of Viennese cuisine.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-005": "The Franconian causal particle, contracted from „des“ (das/that) and „deswegen“ (therefore). A typical example of the Franconian tendency toward sound shift and slurring. It is often placed at the beginning or end of a sentence.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-005": "„Maloche“ refers to hard physical labor, the kind that was everyday life in the mining and steel industries of the Ruhr region. The word comes from Hebrew (via Rotwelsch, the thieves' cant) and originally means „work, toil“. It carries a certain dignity: whoever malocht toils honestly for their bread.",
  "alemannisch.al-004": "„Jo“ is the Alemannic form of „ja“ (yes) and sounds very characteristic due to its open „o“ and the often drawn-out pronunciation. It can mean simple agreement, but also confirmation, surprise or understanding. „Jo, jo“ (doubled) often expresses thoughtfulness or cautious agreement.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-002": "The „Riwwele“ are the crumble topping on a Palatine cake — especially on the famous Riwwelkuche, a fluffy yeast dough with butter-and-sugar crumbles. „Mei Oma backt die beste Riwwelkuche far weit und breit.“ (“My grandma bakes the best Riwwelkuche far and wide.”) From the dialect word for „rub“ — the crumbles are rubbed together with the fingers. A Sunday pastry, family tradition, symbol of Palatine baking culture.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-002": "Pfiat di is the farewell and goes back to „behüte dich Gott“ (“may God protect you”). To several people one says Pfiat enk. A warm, typically Tyrolean farewell greeting.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-002": "Geheischnis denotes the need for security, closeness and being cared for. An untranslatable Saarland word of the heart, of which the region is especially proud.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-002": "Moin moin is the doubled greeting. Many East Frisians already regard the double Moin as idle chatter, since a simple Moin is actually enough.",
  "badisch.bad-002": "ebbis means something; its counterpart is nüt (nothing). Ebbis Rechts lerne means to learn something sensible. A basic Alemannic word in Baden everyday life.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-002": "Hoi is the casual Alemannic greeting that Vorarlberg shares with Switzerland. You greet friends and acquaintances with a quick Hoi. The more formal version would be Grüß Gott.",
  "steirisch.st-002": "Pfiat di is the farewell, from „behüte dich Gott“ (“may God protect you”). To several people one says Pfiat enk. A warm Styrian farewell greeting.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-002": "Pfiat di is the farewell, from „behüte dich Gott“ (“may God protect you”). To several people one says Pfiat enk. A warm Carinthian farewell greeting.",
  "thueringisch.th-002": "The Roster is the Thuringian grilled sausage (Rostbratwurst), grilled over charcoal and placed in a bread roll with mustard. A culinary landmark of Thuringia that is on no grill missing.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-002": "plietsch means smart, clever and bright. En plietsch Kind is a clever child. A typically North German compliment for cleverness and capability in life.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-002": "wat is the Berlin-Brandenburg version of „was“ (what). Wat is n los? means „what's going on then?“. One of the most distinctive phonetic features of the dialect.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-002": "Pfiat di is the farewell, from „behüte dich Gott“ (“may God protect you”). To several people one says Pfiat enk. A warm Upper Palatine farewell greeting.",
  "hessisch.h-014": "Refers to a lot of talk, fuss or noise. „Mach kaan Schwall!“ = „Don't make a fuss!“.",
  "berlinisch.b-009": "Berlin form of „das“ (that/it). It is often combined with „icke“ and „kieke“ into the trio „icke, dette, kieke mal“.",
  "bayerisch.by-012": "A Bavarian pork-belly specialty, often seasoned and smoked or roasted whole. A classic at the tavern and on the Brotzeit (snack platter).",
  "saechsisch.s-007": "A jocular, vulgar expression. Part of the coarse Saxon humor — typical among buddies, never meant seriously.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-005": "Swabian filled pasta pockets with a meat, spinach or sausage-meat filling. Legend has it that monks hid meat in them during Lent — hence the nickname „Herrgottsbscheißerle“ („little cheaters of the Lord“).",
  "koelsch.k-008": "Both the top-fermented Cologne beer (served in the slim 0.2-liter Stange glass) and the dialect. „Kölsch is dat einzige Bier, dat man trinken un sprechen kann.“ (“Kölsch is the only beer you can both drink and speak.”)",
  "plattdeutsch.p-006": "Low German for „boy“, parallel to „Deern“ (girl). „Lütte Jung“ means „little boy“, „mien Jung“ affectionately „my boy“. In North German families it is the standard form of address for sons, and also grandsons. Audibly related to the English „young“ — the Low German–English linguistic kinship shows clearly here. One of the most quintessentially Low German words.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-007": "Swiss German (from French) for the hairdresser. A classic Helvetism.",
  "wienerisch.w-007": "Literally „Erdäpfel“ (“earth apples”) — the apt Austrian term for potatoes. Whoever says „Kartoffel“ outs themselves as a tourist.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-006": "The Franconians' own name for the historical region of Franconia, which today is divided into the administrative districts of Upper, Middle and Lower Franconia. Franconians have a strong regional identity and like to emphasize that they are not Bavarians — even though they belong politically to Bavaria.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-006": "The verb „malochen“ describes hard, physically demanding work. In the Ruhr region, malochen at the colliery or in the steelworks was the life of an entire generation of workers. Whoever malocht is respected — it's not complaining, but an expression of diligence and working-class pride.",
  "alemannisch.al-005": "„Jetzt isch guet!“ is the Alemannic formula for „enough is enough“ — calmer than its North German equivalents, but just as firm. It is said when a situation is over or when someone should stop. The tone is decisive: spoken calmly it is a statement, spoken sharply it is a warning.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-003": "The „Saumache“ — the Saumagen (“sow's stomach”), the Palatine national dish and the favorite food of former Chancellor Helmut Kohl. „Saumache mit Kraut und Kartoffel, des is mei Sonndagsesse!“ (“Saumagen with sauerkraut and potatoes, that's my Sunday meal!”) Pork stomach stuffed with minced meat, potatoes, chestnuts and spices, cooked in broth. A classic at every Palatine wedding and at the wine festival. Hearty, savory, utterly unmodern — and proud of it.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-003": "Hawediehre comes from „habe die Ehre“ (“I have the honor”) and serves as a refined greeting both for hello and goodbye. It is often used half jokingly, half deferentially.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-003": "Gell is the constant reassurance at the end of a sentence and expects agreement. One of the most frequent Saarland words of all, in almost every other sentence.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-003": "Adjüs (from the French adieu) is the Low German farewell greeting. At the coast one often also hears the phrase Tschüss un Adjüs when parting.",
  "badisch.bad-003": "Brägele are fried potatoes, a Baden specialty, often with bacon and onions. The verb brägele accordingly means to fry. A staple of Baden cuisine.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-003": "Habidere comes from „habe die Ehre\" (I have the honour) and serves as a refined greeting. It is used both on arrival and jokingly-politely in everyday life.",
  "steirisch.st-003": "Kernöl is the dark green Styrian pumpkin seed oil, a protected emblem of the region. It goes on salads, on vanilla ice cream and even into spreads.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-003": "Lei means only or just and is probably the most typical Carinthian word. Lei net means „just not\", lei so „just like that\". It runs through the entire dialect.",
  "thueringisch.th-003": "Kließ are the Thuringian dumplings made from raw and cooked potatoes, served with roast meat and gravy. The Sunday dish par excellence in Thuringia.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-003": "En Dösbaddel is a dreamy, slow-witted person, a fool. The word is used in a good-natured, mocking way, derived from dösen (to doze, to daydream).",
  "brandenburgisch.br-003": "det (also dette) is the Berlin-Brandenburg word for „das\" (that/it). Det is doch klar! emphasises something self-evident. Together with wat, a hallmark of the dialect.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-003": "Zoigl is the bottom-fermented beer brewed communally in old communal brewhouses and served in turns. A jagged beer sign (the Zoiglstern) shows where Zoigl is freshly available.",
  "hessisch.h-016": "The „gell\" is a tag question at the end of a sentence, comparable to „ne?\" (right?). Very typical in the southern Hessian area and in Frankfurt. „Des is doch klar, gell?\" can be heard at every table in Bembel country.",
  "berlinisch.b-010": "One's own residential district with everything that goes with it — pub, late-night shop, baker, playground. In Berlin it is identity-forming: „Mein Kiez, meine Welt\" (My Kiez, my world).",
  "bayerisch.by-013": "The iconic one-litre vessel for beer, above all at the Oktoberfest. „A Mass\" — one, yes one, Maß (litre mug).",
  "saechsisch.s-008": "Saxon pronunciation of the word „Pfirsich\" (peach) — „pf\" becomes „p\", „i\" becomes „ä\", the ending softened. A classic phonetic example.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-007": "Swabian for to talk, to chat. „Mer dud bloß a bissle schwätza!\" = „We're just chatting a little!\".",
  "koelsch.k-010": "The Cologne form of „Mädchen\" (girl). It is also often used for young women — friendly, never derogatory.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-008": "Even though it is now standard German: „Tschüss\" (bye) originates from Northern German and comes from the Spanish „adiós\" via the Low German „atschüs\".",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-008": "From French — in Switzerland the standard word for the pavement/sidewalk. „Geh ufs Trottoir!\" (Get on the pavement!).",
  "wienerisch.w-008": "Diminutive of „Sack\" (bag) — the typical shopping bag. „A Sackerl Semmeln, bitte.\" (A bag of bread rolls, please.).",
  "fraenkisch.fr-007": "The Franconian pronunciation of Nürnberg (Nuremberg), the largest city in Franconia. The „ü\" becomes an open „ä\" and the final „g\" turns into a soft „ch\" — typical of the Franconian sound shift. For centuries Nürnberg was one of the most important Free Imperial Cities of the Holy Roman Empire.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-007": "The „Schicht\" (shift) is the miner's unit of work — early shift, late shift, night shift. The miner lived by the rhythm of the shifts, and the family arranged itself accordingly. „Schicht im Schacht\" means „knocking-off time\" or, figuratively: now it's over, now that's enough.",
  "alemannisch.al-006": "The Black Forest cherry cake (Schwarzwälder Kirschtorte) is the most famous pastry of the Black Forest and a worldwide symbol of German cuisine. It consists of chocolate sponge, kirsch (cherry brandy), whipped cream and sour cherries. The name is not EU-protected, but the kirsch content is regulated by the confectioners' guild — at least 70 ml of kirsch per cake.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-004": "The „Dubbeglas\" — the traditional Palatine wine-spritzer glass, a thick-walled 0.5-litre glass with characteristic dimples („Dubbe\"). „A Schorlestoss aus em Dubbeglas, des is Pfalz pur!\" (A spritzer from the Dubbeglas, that's pure Palatinate!). The dimples provide a better grip and originally arose so that the glass would not slip from the hand even when drunk. A symbol of Palatine wine culture and indispensable at every wine festival.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-004": "Servas is the casual greeting among friends, derived from the Latin „servus\" (servant). It is said both on arrival and on leaving.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-004": "Unni means down or downwards, its counterpart being uffi (upwards). Whoever goes „unni in de Keller\" descends into the cellar. A typical directional word.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-004": "A Kluntje is the large white rock sugar that is placed first into the cup during the tea ceremony. When the hot tea is poured over it, the Kluntje crackles audibly.",
  "badisch.bad-004": "Es Weckle is the bread roll. In the morning you fetch fresh Weckle from the baker. The diminutive ending -le is characteristic of Baden and Swabian dialects.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-004": "Pfüot di is the farewell greeting, from „behüte dich Gott\" (may God protect you). To several people one says Pfüot ich. A heartfelt greeting when parting.",
  "steirisch.st-004": "Sterz is a crushed flour or buckwheat dish roasted in fat, such as Heidensterz made from buckwheat. A traditional, filling Styrian farmer's dish.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-004": "Lei-Lei is the famous battle cry of the Villach carnival. One person shouts Lei, the crowd answers Lei. An expression of exuberant Carinthian carnival joy.",
  "thueringisch.th-004": "The Mutschekiepchen is the ladybird, an affectionate Thuringian-Saxon word. Children let the Mutschekiepchen fly off their finger and make a wish.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-004": "En Dwarsdriewer is someone who always lies crosswise (dwars) and knows everything better. A vivid Low German word for a stubborn, contrary spirit.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-004": "The Bulette is the meat patty (Frikadelle), a classic of Berlin-Brandenburg cuisine. Ran an die Buletten! means figuratively „let's go, get stuck in!\". From the French boulette.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-004": "The Zoiglstubn is the simple tavern room in which a communal brewer serves his Zoigl, often only on a few days. A unique part of the Upper Palatinate inn culture.",
  "hessisch.h-017": "Literally a crow; figuratively also a cheeky, forward girl. Used affectionately and mockingly.",
  "berlinisch.b-013": "Berlin slang for a bottle, especially of beer or schnapps. „Volle Pulle\" means „at full power\".",
  "bayerisch.by-014": "Twofold: the traditional Bavarian-Austrian folk dress (Dirndl), but also a girl — the words are related.",
  "saechsisch.s-009": "Saxon for something soft and mushy. Also a specialty: a cake with a particularly soft base.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-008": "Swabian for rushed, sloppy, hectic. „Hudla net so!\" = „Don't be in such a rush!\".",
  "koelsch.k-011": "Affectionate Cologne term for children, especially for a group of children. „De Pänz sin am Spillen.\" (The kids are playing.)",
  "plattdeutsch.p-009": "A Northern German specialty: a fresh bread roll with Bismarck herring, fried or smoked fish, plus onions and remoulade. A must-do at the harbour.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-009": "The „Chuchichäschtli\" (= kitchen cupboard) is the famous Swiss tongue-twister word — a test for every non-Swiss. Three guttural sounds in a row. Whoever can pronounce it belongs.",
  "wienerisch.w-009": "A cup — usually large, often with a handle. \"A Häferl Kaffee\" is a cup of coffee. Also used as a synonym for \"loudmouth\".",
  "fraenkisch.fr-008": "The Franconian pronunciation of Würzburg, the capital of Lower Franconia. The city lies on the Main and is famous for the Residence (UNESCO), Franconian wine and the Old Main Bridge. The characteristic Franconian dialect shows in the softening and lengthening of the vowels.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-008": "The Zeche is the mine where hard coal is extracted. For over 150 years the Ruhr region was the most important hard-coal district in Europe, with hundreds of collieries. Names like Zeche Zollverein (UNESCO World Heritage), Zeche Consolidation or Zeche Auguste Victoria are part of the Ruhrpott identity.",
  "alemannisch.al-007": "The Wähe is an Alemannic and Swiss German dish: a flat cake or bake made from shortcrust pastry with a sweet or savoury topping. There is onion Wähe, tomato Wähe, plum Wähe and many other varieties. Unlike the quiche, the Wähe is thinner and uses a different dough.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-005": "The \"Schorle\" — the Palatinate national drink, wine with sparkling mineral water in a 1:1 ratio. \"A Schorle bitt!\" The Palatinate is a stronghold of German white-wine production, and the Schorle is the everyday way of drinking it. Variations: \"süße Schorle\" (with lemonade), \"saure Schorle\" (with sour water), \"rote Schorle\" (with red wine). Appropriate at every wine festival, in every tavern, at any time of day.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-005": "The Marende is the hearty Tyrolean afternoon snack, often with bacon, cheese and bread. The word comes from the Romance language area and is especially common in South Tyrol.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-005": "The Schwenker is both the swinging grill suspended on chains and the marinated pork grilled on it. Schwenken over an open fire is a sacred Saarland institution.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-005": "The Wölkje is the little cloud of cream that you carefully let glide into the tea against the rim of the cup. Under no circumstances may it be stirred in — that is how the typical Wölkje forms.",
  "badisch.bad-005": "A Muckeseckele is the tiniest possible amount — literally the scrotum of a mosquito. A lovingly exaggerated Baden word for a minute portion.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-005": "Käsknöpfle are the Vorarlberg cheese spätzle, made with plenty of mountain cheese and fried onions, served with apple sauce. The national dish of the Ländle and at home on every alpine pasture.",
  "steirisch.st-005": "The Styrian Käferbohne is a large, speckled bean served lukewarm as a salad with pumpkin-seed oil and onion. A protected regional product.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-005": "Kasnudl are large, half-moon-shaped filled dumplings, stuffed with curd cheese, potatoes and mint, with the edges artfully crimped. The quintessential Carinthian national dish.",
  "thueringisch.th-005": "Plinse are thin pancakes made in the pan, eaten sweet with sugar or apple sauce. A popular simple dish in Thuringia and Saxony.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-005": "Deern is the girl or young woman, an affectionate northern German word. Its male counterpart is de Jung. Lütt Deern means little girl.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-005": "The Stulle is a slice of bread with a topping, the open sandwich. Eine Stulle mit Wurst goes along to work. A typical Berlin-Brandenburg word.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-005": "Broud is the bread, with the inverted diphthong typical of the Upper Palatinate. A Stickl Broud is part of the Brotzeit. A hallmark of the North Bavarian pronunciation.",
  "hessisch.h-018": "Hessian apple wine is the national drink of Hesse and especially of Frankfurt. Unlike sparkling wine or grape wine, Ebbelwoi is made from fermented apple juice and has a tart, fizzy character. It is poured from the Bembel into the ridged Schoppen glasses and is a fixture of every tavern in Sachsenhausen.",
  "berlinisch.b-014": "The \"Berliner Schnauze\" is legendary — direct and quick-witted. \"Schnauze!\" on its own is already enough as a command (\"Shut your trap!\").",
  "bayerisch.by-017": "The dialect's own name for itself. \"A boarischer Bua red boarisch\" — a Bavarian boy speaks Bavarian.",
  "saechsisch.s-010": "As in Bavarian, a universal expression of emotion — usually with a drawn-out stress. \"Meeei, is' das schön!\" (\"Oh my, how lovely!\").",
  "schwaebisch.sw-009": "A tongue-in-cheek Swabian term for a couple — \"hen and rooster\". Also a classic tavern name.",
  "koelsch.k-013": "\"Op Kölsch jesäht\" introduces a Cologne saying. More generally also an attitude to life: easy-going, warm-hearted, with a twinkle in the eye.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-010": "In Low German not a food snack but a chat. \"En lütten Snack\" = a short conversation.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-010": "Swiss German for \"a little\" or \"a bit\". Often combined with other diminutives.",
  "wienerisch.w-010": "Viennese slang for a cigarette. A famous Austrian novel by Wolfgang Herrndorf also bears this title.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-009": "The Franconian pronunciation of Bamberg, the World Heritage city of Upper Franconia. Here too, the \"g\" at the end is softened to a gentle \"ch\", as throughout Franconian. Bamberg is known for its smoked beer (Rauchbier), its gardeners' quarter and its cathedral.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-009": "The \"Pütt\" is the affectionate, colloquial term for the mine or colliery. The word comes from the Dutch \"put\" (well, pit) and reflects the Westphalian-Lower Rhenish linguistic influences. To work \"auf dem Pütt\" meant to devote one's life to mining.",
  "alemannisch.al-008": "In Alemannic, onions are called \"Zibele\" — a term closely related to the Swiss German \"Ziibelemärit\" (onion market in Bern). The Zibele is an indispensable seasoning in Baden cuisine, especially in sausage salad (Wurstsalat) and onion Wähe. Fresh Zibele are sold daily at the Freiburg Münstermarkt.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-006": "\"Bissel\" — the Palatinate form of \"bisschen\" (a bit), one of the most common everyday words. \"A bissel mehr Wein, bitte!\" Used countless times a day — when ordering, when paying compliments (\"A bissel hübsch isch des Madel\" — that girl is rather pretty), when wanting less of something. Intensification: \"A klää bissel\" (a tiny bit) or \"A ordentlich bissel\" (a good amount). A relaxed, typically Palatinate way of stating quantities.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-006": "Graukas is a lean, pungent sour-milk cheese from the Zillertal, traditionally dressed \"sour\" with vinegar, oil and onion. A classic of Tyrolean alpine cuisine.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-006": "Lyoner is the Saarland term for the ring-shaped meat sausage, which is a staple food here. It is often bought as a Lyonerkranz (ring of Lyoner) and eaten cold or fried.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-006": "Theetied is the sacred East Frisian tea time. Several times a day, strong black tea is drunk with Kluntje (rock sugar) and Wölkje (a swirl of cream) — an intangible cultural heritage of the region.",
  "badisch.bad-006": "Es Bobbele is the baby or small child, also a doll. A tender Baden word that young parents constantly have on their lips. The plural is die Bobbele.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-006": "Riebel is a flour-and-semolina dish roasted golden brown in the pan, then crumbled and eaten sweet with apple sauce. A traditional Vorarlberg farmers' dish.",
  "steirisch.st-006": "Verhackert is a savoury spread made from finely chopped, smoke-cured bacon, spread on farmhouse bread. A hearty speciality of the Styrian Brettljause (cold platter snack).",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-006": "Reindling is a twisted yeast cake with cinnamon, sugar and raisins, baked in a Reine (a baking dish). At Easter, the Reindling belongs on every Carinthian table.",
  "thueringisch.th-006": "A Bemme is a slice of bread with a topping, the open sandwich. A Fettbemme is spread with lard. An everyday East Central German word.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-006": "Jung is the boy or lad, also used as a familiar form of address: Na, Jung? Together with Deern it is the usual word pair for children in Low German.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-006": "The Schrippe is the crusty wheat roll. In the morning you fetch fresh Schrippen from the baker. The standard word for bread rolls in Berlin and Brandenburg.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-006": "Kniedla are the dumplings, in North Bavarian pronunciation. Whether as bread dumplings (Semmelkniedla) or potato dumplings (Kartoffelkniedla), they go with roast and gravy. A cornerstone of the cuisine.",
  "hessisch.h-019": "A pejorative, but often also affectionately humorous term for an older, poorly dressed or weathered-looking woman. The term is widespread in the Hessian language area and is also used self-deprecatingly among female friends. The Zibbbe is not meant nastily — she's simply the quirky old lady next door.",
  "berlinisch.b-015": "When Berliners talk about \"the capital\", they mean themselves — no matter who's listening.",
  "bayerisch.by-018": "Short form of Theresia — also the name from which the Oktoberfest takes its festival grounds (\"Theresienwiese\", named after the wedding of King Ludwig I to Therese von Sachsen-Hildburghausen in 1810).",
  "saechsisch.s-011": "A jocular Saxon term for the legs, e.g. \"Da kriegste die Glemmbier hoch!\" (\"That'll get your energy up!\").",
  "schwaebisch.sw-010": "An intensifying Swabian expression. Literally \"swinishly good\" — that is, truly excellent.",
  "koelsch.k-014": "The title of a Bläck Fööss song and at the same time a Cologne philosophy of life: no one should be left alone — come over, have a drink, be part of it.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-011": "The Low German word for \"kitchen\" — comparable to English \"kitchen\" and Danish \"køkken\". It shows the linguistic kinship of Low German with English and the Nordic languages. In northern German farmhouses, the \"Kööken\" with its tiled stove was the heart of the home — here people cooked, talked and ate. A central Low German word.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-011": "\"Adieu\" (formal) or \"Tschüss/Tschau\" (informal). Also \"Uf Widerluege\" in Bernese German.",
  "wienerisch.w-012": "Viennese for \"arse\" — often used as an exclamation: \"Du Oasch!\" (rather among friends) or \"Oasch g'hobt!\" (\"Got lucky!\" — literally: \"Had a backside!\").",
  "fraenkisch.fr-010": "Fürth is the neighbouring city of Nuremberg and has its own proud identity. The rivalry between Nuremberg and Fürth is legendary — 1. FC Nürnberg against SpVgg Greuther Fürth is one of the most tradition-steeped German derbies. The people of Fürth always insist: \"Mir sein kaa Nämbercher!\" (\"We're no Nurembergers!\").",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-010": "The \"Kumpel\" was originally the fellow miner to whom you had to entrust your life — underground, people depended on one another. The word comes from the Polish \"kumpan\" (companion) and reflects the strong immigration from Poland into the Ruhr area. Today \"Kumpel\" is the general term for a true, dependable friend.",
  "alemannisch.al-009": "Knöpfle are the Alemannic and Swabian variant of Spätzle: smaller, rounder dough dumplings pressed through a grater or a Spätzle press. The name comes from \"Knopf\" (little button), because of their round shape. In Baden, Knöpfle are often served as a side dish with roasts or baked au gratin with cheese as Käsknöpfle.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-007": "A \"Hannebambel\" is a lovable fool, a somewhat dim but harmless fellow. \"Du Hannebambel, du hosch ja dei Gummischuh verkehrt rum!\" (\"You Hannebambel, you've got your rubber boots on the wrong way round!\"). It's used not maliciously but almost affectionately — mostly within the family or among friends. Linguistically related to \"Hannes\" (a typical Palatine first name) and \"bambeln\" (to dangle, swing). Classic Palatine self-deprecation.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-007": "Melchermuas is a filling Alpine dish of the milkers, made from flour, cream, milk and butter, fried golden brown in the pan. It used to be served to the herdsmen as a hearty meal.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-007": "Dibbelabbes is a hearty bake of grated raw potatoes, bacon and leek, cooked in a pot (Dibbe). A classic Saarland poor man's dish, today a delicacy.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-007": "Köm is the clear schnapps, often caraway or grain brandy, drunk on the coast against wind and weather. A Lütt un Lütt combines beer with a Köm.",
  "badisch.bad-007": "Bibbeleskäs is the quark or fresh cheese, gladly eaten with chives and onions alongside Brägele (fried potatoes). A classic Baden term from country cooking.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-007": "Sura Kees is a lean, savoury sour-milk cheese from the Bregenzerwald, dressed sour with vinegar and onion. A protected specialty with a long tradition.",
  "steirisch.st-007": "The Brettljause is a cold snack with bacon, Verhackert (spread of minced bacon), cheese and horseradish, served on a wooden board. The highlight of any visit to a Buschenschank (wine tavern).",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-007": "Strankerln are the green garden beans. As Strankerln salad with pumpkin-seed oil or in a stew, they belong to the down-to-earth Carinthian cuisine.",
  "thueringisch.th-007": "The Hitsche is a low footstool on which you rest your feet or, as a child, sit. A widespread Thuringian-Saxon word for furniture.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-007": "lütt means small. En lütt Pause is a little break. One of the most characteristic words of Low German, omnipresent also in the north of Mecklenburg.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-007": "A Molle is a glass of beer. Eene Molle und een Kurzer is beer with a shot of schnapps. A convivial word from the Berlin-Brandenburg pub culture.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-007": "Erdäpfi are the potatoes, in Upper Palatine pronunciation. From Erdäpfi you make Kniedla (dumplings), salad or fried potatoes. A staple food of the region.",
  "hessisch.h-020": "The Struwwelpeter is a world-famous children's book character by the Frankfurt physician Heinrich Hoffmann (1845) — a child with wild hair and long fingernails. The book originally came about as a Christmas present for Hoffmann's son. Today \"Struwwelpeter\" colloquially refers to someone with an unkempt appearance.",
  "berlinisch.b-016": "North German-Berlin word for \"to look\". It migrated from Low German into Berlin dialect.",
  "bayerisch.by-019": "A hard-to-translate intensifying particle. \"Des is fei wahr!\" = \"That really is true!\". It lends emphasis to statements.",
  "saechsisch.s-012": "Classic Saxon pronunciation of \"Fernseher\" (television) with a drawn-out \"ä\". A popular tongue-twister test.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-011": "An exclamation of disgust or indignation. \"Deifel\" = \"devil\". It's uttered in a forceful tone.",
  "koelsch.k-015": "The living mascot of 1. FC Köln — a billy goat named Hennes (currently Hennes IX). Named after coach Hennes Weisweiler.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-012": "The Low German \"house\" — pronounced almost like English \"house\". An important word: \"rin in't Hus!\" = \"in into the house!\".",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-012": "Swiss German for the carrot. Also in \"Rüeblitorte\" — a Swiss carrot-cake specialty.",
  "wienerisch.w-013": "Ambiguous: on the one hand a sweet yeast bun, on the other a good line or joke. \"A Wuchtl reißen\" = to crack a joke.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-011": "The Franconian national dish par excellence: a roasted pork shoulder (with the blade bone) with a crispy crust, usually served with a dumpling and gravy. Every Franconian inn has its own recipe and guards it like a treasure. A Schäufele on Sunday is family tradition.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-011": "In the Ruhrpott, \"Kohle\" means both the black mineral and, colloquially, money. \"Ich hab keine Kohle\" means \"I'm broke\". This double meaning is typical of the Ruhrpott, where hard coal was literally the engine of prosperity — no wonder it became a synonym for money.",
  "alemannisch.al-010": "Maultaschen are Swabian-Alemannic filled pasta pockets, stuffed with minced meat, spinach, bread and spices. They are jokingly also called \"Herrgottsbscheißerle\" (\"little God-cheaters\"), because they were used to hide the meat from God on Good Friday. As a Swabian cultural dish, they have held EU protected status as a regional specialty since 2009.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-008": "The \"Goggelschmeer\" — the Palatine word for scrambled eggs, made up of \"Goggel\" (egg) and \"Schmeer\" (smear). \"Zum Frühstick gibt's a Goggelschmeer mit Speck.\" (\"For breakfast there's scrambled eggs with bacon.\"). Characteristic of the hearty Palatine breakfast culture. \"Goggel\" derives from \"Gockel\" (rooster) — everything that comes from the chicken is \"Goggel-something\". The loving, vivid language of Palatine country cooking.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-008": "A Schmankerl is a special culinary delicacy or specialty. By extension it also means any pleasing extra. An affectionate word of Alpine cuisine.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-008": "Hoorische (\"the hairy ones\") are dumplings made from raw, grated potatoes, which take on a \"hairy\" appearance from the grater. Their counterpart is the Gefillde, made from cooked dough.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-008": "Deern is the girl or young woman, an affectionate North German word. The male counterpart is de Jung. Lütte Deern means little girl.",
  "badisch.bad-008": "Gsälz is jam or preserve, for example blackberry Gsälz on bread. A word shared by Baden and Swabia, derived from salting and boiling down.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-008": "Mostbröckle is air-dried, cured beef, sliced wafer-thin. A Vorarlberg specialty that is gladly served with a glass of cider (Most).",
  "steirisch.st-008": "A Buschenschank is the seasonal tavern of a winemaker who offers his own wine and a cold snack. A bundle of branches (Buschen) hung out signals that it is open.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-008": "Ritschert is a hearty stew of pearl barley, beans and smoked meat. A filling winter dish of rustic Carinthian cuisine.",
  "thueringisch.th-008": "The Stippe is the sauce or dip into which you dunk dumplings or potatoes. A good Stippe is an absolute must with the Sunday roast.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-008": "Schietwedder is lousy, wet and cold weather, such as often prevails on the Baltic coast. Bi Schietwedder you'd better stay indoors. A blunt, fitting description.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-008": "knorke means great, terrific, super. Det is ja knorke! is an enthusiastic praise. A traditional word of appreciation from Berlin and Brandenburg.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-008": "The Brotzeit is the hearty cold snack of bread (Broud), sausage and cheese, ideally with a Zoigl beer. Brotzeit machn means taking a snack break. A fixed part of the day.",
  "hessisch.h-021": "A typically Hessian formula of invitation or encouragement. The \"emol\" corresponds to standard German \"mal\" and softens the request in a friendly way. \"Kumm emol rüwer\" means a warm invitation to one's home or to a particular place.",
  "berlinisch.b-017": "A classic at the Berlin snack stand: hot bockwurst, sharp mustard, crusty Schrippe (bread roll) — simple, cheap, perfect.",
  "bayerisch.by-021": "A traditional folk-costume adornment made from the beard hairs of the chamois, worn on Bavarian hats. The Gamsbart is considered a status symbol and a mark of the skilled hunter or proud wearer of traditional dress. Especially magnificent specimens are passed down and can fetch considerable collector's prices.",
  "saechsisch.s-013": "Used throughout German, but especially favored in Saxon dialect. \"Ne Affnhitze is heude!\" (\"It's a sweltering heat today!\").",
  "schwaebisch.sw-013": "Borrowed from French — used in Swabian as well as in Switzerland for the pavement/sidewalk. \"Geh ufs Trottoir!\" (\"Walk on the pavement!\").",
  "koelsch.k-016": "The Kölsch form of \"Junge\" (boy), also used as a form of address among friends. \"He Jung, watt machste?\" (\"Hey, lad, what are you up to?\").",
  "plattdeutsch.p-013": "Low German for the landlord of an inn (= \"Krog\", tavern). Also a common family name in the north.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-013": "Swiss German word for croissant (= \"Hörnchen\"). A classic breakfast pastry.",
  "wienerisch.w-014": "Viennese slang for \"great\" or \"terrific\". \"Des is leiwand!\" — the highest approval.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-012": "The Nuremberg Rostbratwurst is protected by an EU designation of origin: only 7 to 9 centimeters long, made of finely seasoned pork with marjoram. Traditionally three or six are served on a pewter dish with sauerkraut or potato salad. A symbol of Nuremberg worldwide.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-013": "The \"Ruhrpott\" is the affectionate nickname for the Ruhr region, Germany's largest metropolitan area. It unites cities such as Dortmund, Essen, Bochum, Duisburg and Gelsenkirchen. The term \"Pott\" probably comes from the cauldron-like topography or by analogy to the melting pot of cultures. People of the Ruhrpott are proud of their Pott.",
  "alemannisch.al-011": "The Baden potato soup is called Grumbeersuppe in dialect, since potatoes are called \"Grumbeer\" (ground pear) in the Baden and Palatinate regions. The soup is prepared with bacon, onions and marjoram and is a classic poor people's meal that is today valued as a regional specialty. In the Breisgau it is a winter dish.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-009": "The \"Lewwerknepp\" — the Palatinate liver dumplings, smaller and finer than the Bavarian liver-dumpling-soup versions. \"Lewwerknepp in dr Brüh, des isch a Klassiker.\" (\"Liver dumplings in broth, that's a classic.\") Made of pork liver, bread, onions and spices, often served in a clear broth. A wedding and Sunday meal for generations. Also written \"Lewwerknödel\" with a double \"l\". Palatinate farmhouse cooking pure and simple.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-009": "Muas denotes a porridge made of flour or semolina, a simple, nourishing farmer's dish. Terms like Melchermuas or Riebelmuas are derived from it.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-009": "Gefillde are stuffed potato dumplings, usually with minced meat inside, served in a bacon sauce. A Saarland Sunday dish and counterpart to the Hoorische.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-009": "Jung is the boy or lad, also used as a familiar form of address among men: Na, Jung? Together with Deern (girl), it forms the usual word pair for children in Low German.",
  "badisch.bad-009": "Grumbiere (ground pears) are the potatoes, the basis of Brägele and potato salad. The word is widespread throughout the Alemannic and Franconian regions.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-009": "Es Ländle is the affectionate pet name the people of Vorarlberg use for their own federal state. To be at home in the Ländle is an expression of pride in one's homeland and a sense of belonging.",
  "steirisch.st-009": "Schilcher is a tart, rosé-colored wine made from the Blauer Wildbacher grape, a specialty of western Styria. Its tangy character is unmistakable.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-009": "Frigga is a dish of fried Gailtal alpine cheese with bacon, eaten straight from the pan with polenta or bread. A specialty from the Gail valley.",
  "thueringisch.th-009": "A Dippel is a bump, for example on the head after a knock. Da hast dr aber an ordentlichen Dippel gehauen (\"You've given yourself a proper bump there\"). A vivid word for the body.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-009": "Dat Schummern is the twilight, the time between day and night. In dat Schummern sitten means sitting cozily together at dusk.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-009": "dufte means great, swell or fine. Een dufter Typ is a decent, likable fellow. An old Berlin word that lives on in Brandenburg too.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-009": "A Schmankerl is a special culinary delicacy. Upper Palatinate cuisine has many a Schmankerl to offer, from the Bradl (roast) to the Mehlspeis (sweet dish). An affectionate word.",
  "hessisch.h-022": "The Hessian word for hump or back; it can denote both the body part and an actual hump. \"Rutsch mir den Baggel runter!\" is a blunt rebuff (\"Get lost!\"). The term is also used for a stooped, small person.",
  "berlinisch.b-019": "In Berlin youth slang, an affectionate term for one's best female friend or a woman one is very fond of. The word sounds coarse but is meant positively — similar to \"Mädel\" (gal) or \"sister\". \"Meine Keule\" expresses genuine affection and familiarity.",
  "bayerisch.by-022": "It can mean both \"crazy\" and \"absolutely thrilled\" — the tone decides. \"I bin narrisch auf dich!\" is a declaration of love, while \"bist du narrisch?!\" expresses real astonishment. The word comes from \"Narr\" (fool) and is deeply rooted in the Bavarian feel for language.",
  "saechsisch.s-014": "Ambiguous: the dairy product and, in Saxon, \"nonsense\". \"Mach kein Quark!\" = \"Don't do anything silly!\".",
  "schwaebisch.sw-015": "\"Fei\" is a Swabian-Bavarian intensifying particle with no direct standard-German equivalent — it is inserted into sentences to emphasize or nuance a statement. \"Des isch fei wahr!\" (\"That really/truly is true!\"). \"Du muscht fei aufpasse!\" (\"You really must watch out!\"). It stems from Middle High German \"fein\" (exactly, precisely). It is pronounced with a short \"i\". One of the trademark Swabian words that everyone knows.",
  "koelsch.k-017": "A classic Kölsch pronunciation. \"Stroß\" for \"Straße\" (street) — a typical Ripuarian sound pattern.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-015": "Low German for \"sun\" — when it does shine, that is. \"Wenn de Sünn lacht, lacht ok de Norden.\" (\"When the sun laughs, the North laughs too.\")",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-014": "Actually quite clear: Schoggi is Schoggi (chocolate). Swiss chocolate is world-famous — Lindt, Toblerone, Cailler.",
  "wienerisch.w-015": "A kiosk selling tobacco products, lottery tickets and newspapers — usually in tiny shops. A Viennese institution.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-013": "The quick Nuremberg snack: three small grilled bratwursts in a bread roll (Weggla), with mustard. A Nuremberg classic, served at stands in front of the Frauenkirche or at the Hauptmarkt. „Weggla\" is the Franconian word for bread roll — from the Middle High German „Weggli\".",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-014": "Currywurst with fries is the national dish of the Ruhr region — a fried bratwurst with tomato sauce and curry powder, served with fries and mayonnaise. At every snack stand, in front of every stadium and in every clubhouse this dish is indispensable. In the Ruhr region people like to order „Curry mit Schranke\" (with fries).",
  "alemannisch.al-012": "The Wurstsalat is a classic of Baden and Alemannic cuisine: meat or Lyoner sausage cut into strips with a vinegar-and-oil dressing, red onions and often Emmental. In Switzerland it is simply called „Wurstsalat\" and eaten as a starter. It is simple, filling and belongs to every inn in the region.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-010": "A „Pälzer\" is someone from the Palatinate — anyone born there or who has lived there a long time, with all the accompanying outlook on life. „Da Helmut Kohl war a echta Pälzer.\" (Helmut Kohl was a true Palatine.) The Palatine identity is strong: wine, sausage, spritzer, the relaxed banter. „Pälzer Buwe\" (Palatine boys) are the typical, somewhat sturdy lads, „Pälzer Mädel\" the rosy-cheeked, fun-loving girls. A proud regional identity.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-010": "Goggele is the affectionate children's word for an egg, derived from the clucking of the hen. Used within the family and at breakfast with children.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-010": "Grumbeere (literally „ground pears\") are potatoes, the basis of many Saarland dishes from Dibbelabbes to Hoorische. A word widespread throughout the Rhine-Franconian area.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-010": "lütt means small. En lütte Pause is a short break, een Lütten a shot of schnapps. One of the most characteristic words of Low German altogether.",
  "badisch.bad-010": "Knöpfle are short, round Spätzle, pressed into the water from a board or through a sieve. A popular part of Baden home cooking.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-010": "Dr Bueb is the boy or young man. Also used as an appreciative form of address. The female counterpart is s Modle. A basic Alemannic word.",
  "steirisch.st-010": "Backhendl is a crispy breaded and deep-fried chicken, a classic of Styrian and Austrian inn cuisine, often served with lamb's lettuce (Vogerlsalat).",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-010": "Hadn is buckwheat, from which Hadnsterz or Hadnmuas is made. Formerly an important grain of the barren Carinthian mountain soils.",
  "thueringisch.th-010": "The Ranzn is the belly, often used with a wink for a full stomach. After eating, the Ranzn is properly full. The school satchel is also called this.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-010": "tüdern means to tether, for instance a goat to a stake so it can graze. From it derives tüdelig (confused). An old rural word.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-010": "A Jöre is a child, often a lively or cheeky girl. Die Jören spielen uffm Hof (the kids are playing in the yard). An affectionately mocking word of the region.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-010": "D Brezn is the pretzel, freshly baked with coarse salt. For a snack (Brotzeit) or with beer a Brezn always fits. A classic of Bavarian baking.",
  "hessisch.h-023": "In Hessian slang an enthusiastic term for something great or a particularly good idea. „Des is ne Granate!\" (That's a grenade!) is the highest praise. Possibly adopted from football jargon, where a powerful shot is called a „Granate\".",
  "berlinisch.b-020": "An informal form of address among friends, comparable to „Alter\" or „Bro\". Originally from the hip-hop scene in Berlin-Neukölln, „Digger\" has become a universal Berlin form of address. It sounds casual and urban — it can be appreciative or just serve as a filler word.",
  "bayerisch.by-023": "Actually a dessert (Kaiserschmarrn), but used figuratively for nonsense or worthless stuff. „Red koan Schmarrn!\" means „Don't talk nonsense!\". A versatile Bavarian word that expresses rejection and disdain.",
  "saechsisch.s-015": "Saxon for a thick feather duvet with pronounced volume — cozy, soft, perfect for winter.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-016": "In Swabian with the typical pronunciation and often spoken as „Brezg\". The Swabian lye pretzel is world-class.",
  "koelsch.k-018": "Kölsch form for „today\". „Wat maach mer hück Ovend?\" = „What are we doing this evening?\".",
  "plattdeutsch.p-016": "Northern German for a bucket or a hole. In the Ruhr region „Pütt\" also denotes a coal mine.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-015": "A Swiss phrase of reassurance — comparable to the Cologne saying „Et hätt noch immer jot jejange\" (it has always turned out fine). A laid-back attitude to life.",
  "wienerisch.w-016": "Thickened plums (Zwetschken) as a fruit spread. Used in Powidltatschkerl or Powidlbuchteln.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-014": "In Franconia the unit of measure for beer is the Seidla — a mug of half a liter, unlike the Bavarian Maß (1 liter). The Franconian beer culture is enormously rich: Franconia has the highest density of breweries in the world, especially in Franconian Switzerland around Bamberg.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-015": "The Schmalzbrötchen is a simple, filling workers' meal: a bread roll spread with pork lard, often with crackling and a little salt. It was the classic breakfast of the miner before his shift, because it keeps you full for a long time and is cheap. Today it is regarded as a nostalgic cult dish of the Ruhr region.",
  "alemannisch.al-013": "The Vesper is, in the Alemannic-Swabian area, the afternoon snack between meals, comparable to the Bavarian Brotzeit or the English afternoon tea. One eats bread, sausage, cheese and drinks wine or must with it. The term comes from the Latin „vesper\" (evening) and originally denoted the evening meal.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-011": "„Schee\" — the Palatine variant of „schön\" (beautiful/nice), with a swallowed „ö\". „Was a schee's Wetter heut!\" (What lovely weather today!) Similar to Bavaria, but with a somewhat softer initial sound. Intensifications: „graod schee\" (quite nice), „verflucht schee\" (very nice), „schee zammgschtellt\" (nicely put together). One of the most common evaluative adjectives of everyday Palatine speech, expressing everything from „okay\" to „great\".",
  "tirolerisch.ti-011": "gschmackig describes something especially tasty and flavorful. A gschmackiges meal is high praise for the cook.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-011": "Quetschekuche is the plum cake, for Quetsche means plum (Zwetschge). In late summer a fixed part of every Saarland coffee table, best with cream.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-011": "Schiet denotes dirt, but also trouble or nonsense. De ganze Schiet means the whole lot. A hearty, good-naturedly used all-purpose word.",
  "badisch.bad-011": "luege means to look or to peek. Lueg emol! means „take a look!\". An Alemannic verb that Baden shares with Swiss German.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-011": "S Modle is the girl, the Alemannic diminutive. An affectionate word for a girl or young woman, the counterpart to the Bueb.",
  "steirisch.st-011": "Kletzn are dried pears, which go into the Kletzenbrot at Christmas time. A sweet, long-keeping winter store fruit of Styrian farm cooking.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-011": "Klachelsuppe is a hearty soup made from pork bones (Klacheln), often with dumplings (Knödl). A robust, traditional dish of the Carinthian home slaughter.",
  "thueringisch.th-011": "Schmand is the thick sour cream that goes over Plinse (pancakes) or into the Stippe (sauce/dip). A common word of East German cuisine for the dairy product.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-011": "De Knust is the crusty end piece of the bread, the heel. Some like the Knust with butter best of all. A cozy northern German bread word.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-011": "Fisematenten are nonsense, whims or unnecessary fuss. Mach keene Fisematenten! means not to do anything silly or make any fuss. An old word of the region.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-011": "Da Bua is the boy or young man, plural Buam. Also used as an appreciative form of address. A central word of the Bavarian vocabulary.",
  "hessisch.h-024": "A noun derived from \"babbeln\" — it denotes unnecessary, superficial or gossipy chatter. \"Des is alles nur Gebabbel!\" dismisses a statement or conversation as meaningless. Closely related to the word \"babbeln\", which means to talk/chatter throughout the Central German region.",
  "berlinisch.b-021": "An exclamation of the highest surprise or enthusiasm — both positive and negative. In Berlin dialect, \"der Hammer\" is the strongest intensifier for something extraordinary. The combination with the Berlin \"det\" makes the expression authentically local.",
  "bayerisch.by-024": "The grilled or roasted chicken, an indispensable part of every folk festival. Every year, hundreds of thousands of Hendl are eaten at the Oktoberfest. The word comes from \"Henne\" (hen) and refers to the whole bird, traditionally prepared on a spit or in the oven.",
  "saechsisch.s-016": "Belly, especially a fat one. \"Mach' nich die Plauze voll!\" = \"Don't eat so much!\". Comes from the East Central German language area.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-017": "Swabian for mouth — usually used pejoratively for a cheeky person. \"Halt dei Gosch!\" = \"Shut your mouth!\".",
  "koelsch.k-019": "With a wink, people from Cologne call the plain blood sausage on a rye roll their \"caviar\". The dish is not a delicacy in the classic sense, but for true Cologne natives it is a treat. The self-deprecating name reflects the typical Cologne humour: people don't take themselves too seriously, yet still celebrate the simple as the best.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-017": "A classic Hamburg street call: \"Hummel Hummel!\" — answer: \"Mors Mors!\". It alludes to the Hamburg water carrier Hummel, mocked by children — the reply: \"Mors!\" (backside).",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-016": "A cosy taproom or a small inn. Small, personal, often with a regulars' table and regional cuisine.",
  "wienerisch.w-017": "A snack between meals — comparable to the Bavarian Brotzeit. Sausage, cheese, bread, often with beer.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-015": "The wine from Franconia, recognizable by its characteristic bulbous Bocksbeutel bottle. The main growing region is the Maindreieck around Würzburg, with the Stein as its best-known vineyard site. Silvaner, Müller-Thurgau and Bacchus are typical Franconian grape varieties. The wine is dry and mineral — just like the Franconians themselves.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-016": "A \"Bochumer\" is the typical Ruhr native: direct, warm-hearted, football-crazy and proud of their city. Bochum is the city of VfL Bochum, the Schauspielhaus theatre and the German Mining Museum. Herbert Grönemeyer's song \"Bochum\" is practically the anthem of the city and of the Ruhr region as a whole.",
  "alemannisch.al-014": "Spundekäs is a creamy soft cheese made from quark, cream cheese, onions and spices, widespread in the Rheingau and in the cuisine of northern Baden. The name comes from the \"Spund\" (the wooden bung of a barrel) — the cheese is said to have once matured in such barrels. It is served as a bread spread or as a dip with pretzels.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-012": "A \"Beischt\" — Palatine for a small tavern or a simple inn. \"Im Beischt um d'Eck gibt's die beste Worschtsoss.\" (\"The little tavern round the corner has the best sausage sauce.\") Related to the Austrian \"Beisl\". In contrast to the larger \"Wirtschaft\", the Beischt tends to be small, cosy, often with regular clientele. Examples: the neighbourhood Beischt at the weekly market, the corner Beischt in the residential quarter. Home of Schorle, sausage sandwiches and political debates.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-012": "The Krautinger is a traditional schnapps made from white turnips, which may only be distilled in the Wildschönau. A strong, primal Tyrolean distillate with an idiosyncratic taste.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-012": "Whoever \"die Flemm hat\" is in a bad mood or doesn't feel like doing anything. A very common phrase in Saarland for a grumpy mood and listlessness.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-012": "Buddel is the bottle. The Buddelschiff is the famous ship in a bottle. On the coast, many a Buddel of Köm (caraway schnapps) gets emptied. A primal, old word.",
  "badisch.bad-012": "verzelle means to tell or to recount. \"Verzell doch mol!\" invites someone to tell something. A common verb in convivial Baden company.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-012": "Dr Götti is the godfather, s Gotta the godmother. Götti and Gotta play an important role in family life and give presents to their godchildren. An Alemannic word.",
  "steirisch.st-012": "A Krügerl is a half-litre glass of beer, the handled mug. At the inn you order a Krügerl, while s Seidl is the smaller third-of-a-litre.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-012": "A Maschger is a costumed, masked figure at carnival who goes from house to house. The Maschgern is an old Carinthian carnival custom.",
  "thueringisch.th-012": "nüschd means nothing. \"Da is nüschd zu machn\" means \"there's nothing to be done\". One of the most common East Central German words, shared with Saxon.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-012": "En Kniffte is a thickly topped open sandwich, a hearty buttered bread for on the go. You take en Kniffte with you to work. A North German word.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-012": "jwd stands for \"janz weit draußen\" (\"way out in the middle of nowhere\") and refers to a very remote place far outside the city. \"Det liegt ja jwd!\" complains about a far-flung address. Typical of Berlin-Brandenburg.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-012": "A Diandl is a girl or a young woman, and at the same time the traditional dress. \"Beim Kirwa tanzn d Diandl in da Tracht.\" (\"At the parish fair, the girls dance in traditional costume.\") A Bavarian word.",
  "hessisch.h-025": "A slightly pejorative word for someone who behaves stupidly or unwisely. In everyday Hessian use, it is often employed without any real malice — among friends, more of a tongue-in-cheek scolding. The word is of Middle High German origin and is widespread well beyond Hesse.",
  "berlinisch.b-022": "The expression conveys that one is completely fed up with something. The \"Berliner Schnauze\" (Berlin gob) gives it its name — whoever \"die Schnauze voll hat\" says so just as directly. In Berlin, this statement is regarded as a clear signal that a limit of patience has been reached.",
  "bayerisch.by-025": "The Bavarian word for bread roll — while in northern Germany people say \"Brötchen\", in Bavaria and Austria it's called \"Semmel\". The word comes from the Latin \"simila\" (fine flour). Whether Laugensemmel, Kaisersemmel or Mohnweckerl — the variety is impressive.",
  "saechsisch.s-017": "The Saxon pronunciation of the article \"der\" — the \"e\" becomes \"o\". One of the most unmistakable identifying features.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-018": "The Swabian self-designation. Used with pride or ironically — \"A echter Schwob spart bis zum Schluss.\" (\"A real Swabian saves to the very end.\")",
  "koelsch.k-020": "The Flönz is the Cologne blood sausage — an indispensable part of Rhenish cuisine. It is fried in the pan with onions and lard or eaten cold on bread. Together with Rievkooche (potato pancakes) and a Kölsch, the Flönz is the unofficial Cologne national dish. The name is known only in Cologne and its surroundings.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-018": "Unnecessary odds and ends, bits and bobs. \"Bring dien Tüddelkram weg!\" = \"Put your clutter away!\".",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-017": "The Swiss German word for dinner — literally \"zur Nacht\" (\"towards night\"). Together with Zmorge (breakfast), Znüni (mid-morning snack), Zmittag (lunch) and Zvieri (afternoon snack), Znacht forms the complete Swiss meal system, which clearly names every time of day in language. This systematic approach is typical of the precision of Swiss everyday life.",
  "wienerisch.w-018": "Viennese form of address among friends. \"Hawara, geh weida!\" = \"Come on, mate!\".",
  "fraenkisch.fr-016": "Nuremberg Lebkuchen (gingerbread) are among the oldest and best-known baked goods in Germany and are protected by an EU designation of origin. They have been made in Nuremberg since the 14th century, originally by monastery brothers. Elisenlebkuchen, the finest variety, contain at least 25 % nuts and no flour.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-017": "Dortmunder are the inhabitants of the largest city in the Ruhr region and BVB fans through and through. Dortmund has one of the oldest town charters in Germany and was a member of the Hanseatic League. Today, Dortmund is known for the Signal Iduna Park, the Dortmunder U and a lively cultural scene.",
  "alemannisch.al-015": "Baden is one of the warmest and most northerly wine-growing regions in Germany and produces well-known wines from sites such as the Kaiserstuhl, the Markgräflerland and the Ortenau. Kaiserstuhl Spätburgunder (Pinot Noir) is considered one of the best German red wines. Baden wine is traditionally drunk with the Vesper (snack) or with Wurstsalat (sausage salad).",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-013": "s'„Worschtbrot\" — the Palatine sausage sandwich, a thick slice of farmhouse bread topped with good sausage. \"A Worschtbrot mit Senf und Saure Gurke — Pfalz pur!\" (\"A sausage sandwich with mustard and a pickled gherkin — pure Palatinate!\") A classic snack in the Beisl or up on the vineyard. The Palatine Worscht is famous: Leberworscht (liver sausage), Blutworscht (blood sausage), Bratworscht (frying sausage) — every region has its speciality. With a Schorle alongside, this farmer's feast is best enjoyed outdoors among the vines.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-013": "Bua is the boy or young man, plural Buabm. Also used as an appreciative form of address among men. A central word of the Bavarian-Tyrolean vocabulary.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-013": "Maa is the man or husband. \"Mei Maa\" means \"my husband\". A basic word of everyday Saarland life, often used in family conversations.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-013": "tüdelig describes someone who is muddled, forgetful or slightly confused. From this also comes the Tüddelkram. A friendly word for a bit of absent-mindedness.",
  "badisch.bad-013": "gschwind means fast or quick. I bi gschwind im Lade means \"I'm quickly at the shop.\" A widely used word for speed in the southwest.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-013": "luaga means to look or to peek. Luag emol! means \"have a look!\". A typically Alemannic verb that Vorarlberg shares with Switzerland and Baden.",
  "steirisch.st-013": "A Seidl is the small beer glass holding around three deciliters. Those who don't want too much order a Seidl instead of a Krügerl. A common Austrian tavern measure.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-013": "D Pfoad is the shirt. Zieh da a saubere Pfoad o means to put on a clean shirt. An old Bavarian-Carinthian word for clothing.",
  "thueringisch.th-013": "A Gör is a child, often a lively or cheeky one. Die Gören toben durchn Hof (the kids romp around the yard). A word for offspring widespread in eastern Germany.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-013": "De Pott is the pot or the cup. En Pott Kaffee is a cup of coffee. To Pott kamen means to get to the point. A versatile everyday word.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-013": "mang means among or between, a Low German legacy. Mang die Leute jehen means to mingle among people. An old Mark Brandenburg word.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-013": "D Muada is the mother. She cooks the Kniedla (dumplings) and holds the family together. Together with Voda one of the most important family words.",
  "hessisch.h-026": "The Hessian pronunciation of \"gar nichts\" (nothing at all) — especially stressed and drawn out to underline the complete negation. \"Des is gaa-nix wert!\" (that's worth nothing at all) sounds more devastating than any Standard German phrasing. The lengthening of the first vowel is typically Hessian.",
  "berlinisch.b-023": "A typical example of Berlin sound assimilation: \"ich esse\" (I eat) becomes \"ick isse\", with the \"ch\" turning into \"ck\" and the words flowing together. This slurring is characteristic of the fast, relaxed speech tempo of Berlinese. Such forms sound authentic and unmistakable.",
  "bayerisch.by-027": "Great fun and exuberant enjoyment — \"Des war a echte Gaudi!\" (that was real fun!) is the highest praise for an event. The word is full of joie de vivre and expresses that one had a splendid time. In Bavaria, Gaudi is no trifle but a genuine spirit of merrymaking.",
  "saechsisch.s-018": "\"Gomm mol her!\" (come here!) is the classic Saxon command with the typical consonant softening: the hard \"K\" becomes the soft \"G\". This sound shift is the most striking feature of the dialect and runs through all of Saxon. The particle \"mol\" (mal) makes the request softer and friendlier.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-019": "Swabian (and Bavarian) term for a boy or young man. \"Bua\" is used both affectionately toward one's own son and as a general form of address among young men. \"Hoi Bua, was machst du?\" (hey lad, what are you doing?) sounds warmer than the Standard German \"Junge\".",
  "koelsch.k-021": "The Riefkooche is the Cologne potato pancake — grated raw potatoes with egg and onions fried in the pan. At carnival, the Christmas market and in the brewery kitchen the Riefkooche is everywhere. Applesauce or sour cream go well with it. For many people of Cologne, the smell of freshly fried Riefkooche is the smell of home.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-019": "Dönekens (also: Dönekes) are funny, sometimes slightly exaggerated anecdotes and stories told while sitting together sociably. The word is typically North German and refers above all to the kind of stories that get a little embellished in the telling. Knowing a good Döneken is an art cultivated in the Klönschnack (cozy chat).",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-018": "The Swiss breakfast — literally \"toward morning\". A hearty Zmorge with Gipfeli, Zopf, muesli, butter, honey and jam is an important ritual in Switzerland, especially on Sunday mornings. In hotels the breakfast buffet is often offered as a highlight. The word reflects the Swiss German habit of naming meals after the time of day.",
  "wienerisch.w-019": "A Viennese idiom for a dull, sad or depressing evening — \"Des war ein tschechischer Film\" (that was a Czech film) means it was boring or joyless. The expression dates from the time when Eastern European arthouse films were considered especially melancholic. It is slightly disparaging but is used jokingly for any kind of disappointing experience.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-017": "In Franconian, apples are often simply called \"Äbbärn\", derived from an old regional term. Franconia has a rich culture of traditional orchard meadows, and apple wine as well as apple brandy play an important role in regional cuisine alongside the ever-present beer and Franconian wine.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-018": "The Revierderby between Borussia Dortmund (BVB) and FC Schalke 04 is one of the most passionate derbies in Europe. Dortmund fans wear black and yellow, Schalke fans royal blue — both sides would give anything for a derby win. The derby splits the Ruhr region into two camps and shapes everyday life across the whole area.",
  "alemannisch.al-016": "Kirschwasser is the characteristic Black Forest fruit brandy made from fermented sour cherries. It is an indispensable ingredient of Black Forest cherry cake and is drunk as a digestif after the meal. Genuine Black Forest Kirschwasser is protected and must be produced in the region.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-014": "The \"Weinprinzessin\" (wine princess) — the annually chosen representative of a Palatinate wine village, a charming ambassador of regional viticulture. \"D'Weinprinzessin vum Bad Dürkheim hot heut a paar Foddos gemacht\" (the wine princess from Bad Dürkheim took a few photos today). At wine festivals she is elected Palatinate wine queen — the highest title in the region. She wears traditional dress, gives speeches, opens festivals. A tradition since the 1930s, today modernized with educational requirements.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-014": "Diandl refers to a girl or young woman and at the same time the traditional dirndl dress. An affectionate, folksy word of the Alpine region.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-014": "Fraa is the woman or wife, mei Fraa means my wife. Together with Maa one of the most common words for people in Saarlandic.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-014": "Tüddelkram is useless stuff, odds and ends or fussy nonsense. Mach kien Tüddelkram means not to bother with trivialities.",
  "badisch.bad-014": "wüescht describes something ugly, unsightly or bad weather. Es wüeschts Wetter is dreadful weather. An expressive Alemannic word.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-014": "gschiid means clever or sensible. Sei gschiid! urges reason. Talking übertrieben gschiid daher (in an overly clever way) can also come across as know-it-all.",
  "steirisch.st-014": "A Spritzer is wine with mineral water, the standard summer drink and at the Buschenschank (wine tavern). A gspritzter Schilcher is especially popular.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-014": "A Putscherl is a young animal, often a piglet or calf, meant affectionately. Sometimes people also jokingly call children Putscherl.",
  "thueringisch.th-014": "fei is an intensifying particle for emphasis, something like \"but\" or \"really\". Das is fei wahr stresses that something is genuinely true. Especially widespread in southern Thuringia.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-014": "Rotspon is French red wine that traditionally matures in oak barrels in the Hanseatic cities such as Wismar and Rostock. A North German wine specialty with history.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-014": "A Luch is a moist lowland, a marsh and bog landscape, like the Havelland Luch. A typical word for the water-rich nature of Brandenburg.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-014": "Da Voda is the father. He works on the farm or in the business. Together with Muada and the children he forms the Upper Palatinate family.",
  "hessisch.h-027": "The Hessian word for potato — literally \"ground pear\", since the potato grows underground. This old term is common in large parts of Hesse and the Rhineland. For centuries the potato was the staple food of the rural Hessian population.",
  "berlinisch.b-024": "The Berlin \"g\" is consistently turned into \"j\" — so \"grün\" (green) becomes \"jrün\", \"groß\" (big) becomes \"jroß\" and \"gut\" (good) becomes \"jut\". This sound change is the best-known feature of the Berlin dialect and makes it instantly recognizable. The rule applies both at the start of a word and within it.",
  "bayerisch.by-028": "A Bavarian word for boisterous fun or a prank — often with a slightly cheeky or high-spirited undertone. \"Des war a Hetz!\" expresses that something amusing happened. Closely related to the verb \"hetzen\" (to chase), but in Bavarian it has taken on the meaning of merry goings-on.",
  "saechsisch.s-019": "The Saxon pronunciation of the plum (Zwetschge) shows the dialect's typical vowel coloring. In Saxony plums are happily turned into Zwetschgenkuchen (plum cake), baked on a tray and crowned with crumble. Especially in the Ore Mountains, plum cake is a fixed part of the coffee table.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-021": "The Swabian \"Vesper\" is a snack meal, usually in the afternoon or as a light evening meal — bread, sausage, cheese and lard. The word derives from the church Vesper hour (evening prayer). Craftsmen and construction workers traditionally take their \"Vesperpause\" (snack break), and the \"Vesper\" is a fixed part of the Swabian working day.",
  "koelsch.k-022": "The Senfpott is mustard served in a little pot — in the Cologne brewery it automatically accompanies many dishes. It is set on the table with the Halve Hahn, the Flönz or the Mettwürstchen. Cologne has a long history of mustard production, and mustard is a fixed part of the local table culture.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-020": "A North German expression of agreement and affirmation, often said upon a handshake — comparable to \"Deal!\" or \"Agreed!\". In seafarers' German \"Topp!\" was said when two parties sealed a bargain. To this day it is a clear, short pledge: one keeps one's word.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-019": "Swiss cheese fondue is more than a dish — it is a social ritual. In winter, families and friends gather around the Caquelon (fondue pot) of melted Gruyère and Vacherin cheese. Whoever loses their bread in the cheese has to buy a round of wine or a schnapps. Fondue was promoted as a national dish by the Swiss Cheese Union in 1930 and is today UNESCO cultural heritage.",
  "wienerisch.w-020": "The Viennese short form of \"pfiat di\" or \"pfiat Gott\" — a heartfelt farewell that originated from \"behüte dich (Gott)\" (may [God] protect you). It is warmer and more personal than a plain \"Tschüss\" and expresses genuine affection. \"Pfiat\" is heard above all from older Viennese and in traditional circles, but younger people use it too in familiar situations.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-018": "A traditional Franconian cherry bake or cherry cake, baked above all during harvest time with fresh sour cherries. The word is a fine example of the Franconian sound coloring: \"Kirsch\" (cherry) becomes \"Kerschdn,\" and \"Staller\" is a regional term for a bake or porridge.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-019": "\"Auf Schalke\" means at the stadium of FC Schalke 04 in Gelsenkirchen. The Veltins-Arena is one of the most modern stadiums in Germany, with a retractable roof. Going \"auf Schalke\" is a ritual for Schalke fans and is synonymous with a home game, emotions and royal blue color everywhere.",
  "alemannisch.al-017": "The Gugelhopf is a traditional ring-shaped cake, especially popular in the Alemannic region (Baden, Alsace, Switzerland). It is baked in a characteristic ring mold and can be sweet (with almonds and raisins) or savory. In Alsace it is called Kougelhopf and is a symbol of Alsatian baking culture.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-015": "The \"Wengerd\" — the vineyard, often simply called \"Berg\" (hill) in Palatine usage. \"Mei Vadder isch im Wengerd, hot d'Trauwe geschnitte\" (My father is in the vineyard, has cut the grapes). The Palatinate is Germany's second-largest wine region, with around 23,000 hectares of cultivated area. In autumn the Wengerd is the setting of the \"Wimmet\" (grape harvest). Palatine vineyards often offer a view across the Rhine plain to the Black Forest. The lifeblood of the region.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-015": "Gscheade (literally \"the shorn ones\") is the mocking term used by Tyroleans for lowlanders and newcomers. An allusion to the formerly close-cropped hair of the city dwellers.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-015": "Mädsche is the diminutive of Mädchen (girl) and an affectionate term for a girl or a young woman. The male counterpart is the Bub (boy).",
  "ostfriesisch.of-015": "A Klönschnack is a cozy, casual chat, often over tea. The Klönschnack nurtures the sense of community and is part of everyday life in northern Germany.",
  "badisch.bad-015": "En Dotsch is a clumsy, somewhat simple-minded person. The word is used in a good-natured, teasing way. A thick potato fritter can also be called a Dotsch.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-015": "ebbas means something; its counterpart is nüd (nothing). Whoever has learned ebbas Rechts (something proper) has learned something worthwhile. A basic Alemannic word.",
  "steirisch.st-015": "Most is fermented apple or pear juice, a traditional drink of the farmsteads. At the Mostschank, home-pressed Most is served.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-015": "S Häusl is the toilet, formerly the outhouse in the yard. I muass aufs Häusl means \"I have to go to the toilet.\" A common everyday Austrian word.",
  "thueringisch.th-015": "gugge means to look or to glance. Gugg mal! means \"take a look!\" A frequent verb of everyday East Central German life.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-015": "De Buddel is the bottle. Dat Buddelschipp is the ship in a bottle. Many a Buddel of Rotspon (red wine) is emptied over long evenings. An age-old word.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-015": "A Fließ is a narrow, natural watercourse, like the countless Fließe in the Spreewald. On the Fließe the punts glide through the floodplain landscape.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-015": "D Hax is the leg, plural Haxn. While hiking you can twist d Hax (your leg). A robust Bavarian word for the limbs.",
  "hessisch.h-028": "In Hessian usage often used affectionately-chidingly for a cheeky or sly person. It can literally denote someone who smells unpleasant, but is more often used in a figurative sense. Children are often lovingly called \"du klaaner Stinker\" (you little stinker).",
  "berlinisch.b-025": "Berlin slang word for money — probably derived from Rotwelsch (thieves' cant) or Yiddish. \"Pinke\" sounds like the jingling of coins. \"Ich hab keine Pinke mehr\" means that the money is gone. In use in Berlin's neighborhood milieu for decades.",
  "bayerisch.by-029": "Describes someone as intelligent, sensible or capable — but also something that was done properly or correctly. \"Lern gscheid!\" means \"Learn properly!\" and is a classic parental phrase. A \"Gscheider\" is someone who sees through things and acts with sense.",
  "saechsisch.s-020": "In Saxon usage \"quälen\" (to toil) is often used for laborious work: \"Ich quäl mich de janzen Dag damit\" (I toil with it the whole day). The word describes the patient but strenuous work that was customary in the Saxon craft tradition. The miners and textile workers of the Erzgebirge knew toiling from their own experience.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-022": "The endearing Swabian form for a little boy — more affectionate and warmer than the standard German \"kleiner Junge.\" The suffix \"-le\" is the most important diminutive suffix in Swabian and makes almost any term more endearing. Grandmothers tenderly call their grandsons \"mein Büble\" (my little boy).",
  "koelsch.k-023": "The Plunz are large, round potato dumplings — a traditional Rhenish side dish, served above all with braised dishes. The term is regionally limited and, with its round shape, already sounds like a plump dumpling. In some areas \"Plunz\" also denotes a plump, cozy person.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-022": "In the literal sense a knot — in the figurative sense a small, stocky person or a cheeky little boy. \"So'n lütten Knüüt\" (such a little Knüüt) is said affectionately-mischievously about a bright child who behaves as if it were bigger than it is. The image comes from the ropework of sailors, where knots meant strength and compactness.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-020": "Raclette comes from the Valais and is one of the best-known Swiss winter dishes: half a wheel of Valais cheese is melted directly over the fire or under the raclette device and scraped onto boiled potatoes, gherkins and silverskin onions. The word comes from the French \"racler\" — to scrape. In Switzerland, raclette is a communal experience that can last for hours.",
  "wienerisch.w-021": "A Viennese exclamation of surprise, amazement or mild indignation — positive or negative depending on the tone. \"Na sowas!\" can express admiration (at good news) or stunned head-shaking (at bad behavior). The Viennese intonation does it all: drawn out and gentle it is amazement, sharp and short it is reproach.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-019": "Franconian (as well as Hessian) for potatoes, derived from \"Grundbirne\" (ground pear) — the old German term for the tuber that grows out of the earth. In Bavarian they are called \"Erdäpfel,\" in other regions \"Kartoffeln.\" The \"Grumbeer\" is a sure sign that one is in Franconia or Hesse.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-020": "The term \"Reviersport\" describes football in the Ruhr area as an overall phenomenon — from the district league to the Bundesliga. The Revier has an incomparable football culture: more professional clubs in a confined space than anywhere else in Germany. Reviersport is also the name of a well-known regional sports magazine.",
  "alemannisch.al-018": "The linden is the Alemannic village tree par excellence: under the village linden people danced, held court and negotiated. \"Linden\" appears frequently in Alemannic place names. Friedrich Schiller's song \"Am Brunnen vor dem Tore\" and numerous folk songs immortalize the linden as a symbol of home and community.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-016": "The \"Wimmet\" — the grape harvest, the most important event in the Palatine winegrower's year. \"Wann hosch denn dei Wimmet vor?\" (When are you planning your Wimmet?). It takes place depending on the weather from late August to October, often with helpers from the entire family and circle of friends. \"Wimmet helpers\" are rewarded with wine, sausage sandwiches and lunch. A tradition with centuries-old roots. Before modern machinery, the Wimmet was a weeks-long event.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-016": "Mandl is the diminutive form of Mann (man) and denotes a little man, often with a wink. Figures or cairns on the mountain are also called this.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-016": "Klää means small. Der Klää or die Klää is also a pet name for the youngest child of the family. A versatile everyday word.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-016": "klönen means to chat in a relaxed and leisurely way. One klönt with neighbors about everything under the sun. The corresponding noun is the Klönschnack.",
  "badisch.bad-016": "En Bäbber is a sticker or label, from bäbbe (to stick). Children collect Bäbber, and the vignette sticks to the car as a Bäbber. An everyday word.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-016": "nüd means not or nothing. Des isch nüd wohr means \"that is not true.\" One of the most frequent negation words in Alemannic Vorarlberg.",
  "steirisch.st-016": "Vogerlsalat is lamb's lettuce, dressed with pumpkin seed oil and pumpkin seeds and gladly served with Backhendl (fried chicken). A typical component of Styrian cuisine.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-016": "A Tschick is a cigarette, from the Italian cicca. A Tschick rauchn means to smoke. A colloquial word widespread throughout Austria.",
  "thueringisch.th-016": "A Mädel is a girl or a young woman. Das Mädel geht zur Schule (The girl goes to school). A common, friendly word in Thuringian family life.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-016": "De Snut is the mouth or the snout. Hool de Snut means \"shut your mouth.\" Whoever sulks also pulls a Snut. A blunt word for a body part.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-016": "The Kahn is the flat wooden boat with which one is punted along the Fließe in the Spreewald. A Kahn ride is part of every visit to the Spreewald.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-016": "D Goschn is the mouth, often in the sense of brash talking. Hoit dei Goschn! means \"be quiet.\" A blunt everyday word of the Bavarian region.",
  "hessisch.h-030": "A typical Hessian forest inn that often serves as a destination for families and hikers. The Waldschlösschen embodies Hessian cosiness in the midst of nature — Apfelwein (apple wine), home-made food and fresh forest air. Many Hessians associate it with childhood memories of Sunday outings.",
  "berlinisch.b-026": "Walking around your own neighbourhood, meeting people, visiting shops — that's „auf'n Kiez gehen\" (going to the Kiez). The Kiez is the Berliner's second family. Whoever knows their Kiez knows the lady who owns the Späti (late-night corner shop), the kebab guy and the regulars' table at the corner pub.",
  "bayerisch.by-030": "A strong but commonly used insult for someone who is behaving foolishly or unwisely. „Bist du deppert?!\" (Are you stupid?!) is an indignant exclamation. The word is related to „deppich\" and possibly has its origin in Yiddish. In Bavaria it is used frequently and quite matter-of-factly.",
  "saechsisch.s-021": "Saxon colloquial term for the head — meant rather jokingly and coarsely. The word is closely related to Central German dialects and often describes a thick or misshapen head. In children's speech you occasionally also hear „Gubbel\".",
  "schwaebisch.sw-023": "The Swabian form of the first person plural of „können\" (can/to be able to) — a characteristic example of dialect conjugation. Swabian reshapes many verb forms in its own way. „Mir gönnich des mache\" (We can do that) sounds odd to non-Swabians, but is grammatically consistent.",
  "koelsch.k-024": "For people from Cologne, Carnival is not an event — it is a season of its own, the fifth. From the start of the Carnival season on 11 November until Ash Wednesday, Cologne lives in a state of exception. The streets fill with Jecken (revellers), music is in the air, and the Kölsch beer flows freely. Whoever knows Cologne without Carnival knows only half the city.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-023": "In Low German, „wüst\" describes a state of disorder, wildness or recklessness. „Dat geiht wüst to!\" means that things are getting fierce or chaotic. It can describe both a messy home and wild behaviour. The word has a slightly reproachful note and is often used by older North Germans.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-021": "The Swiss national dish par excellence — grated or coarsely shredded potatoes fried in butter until they form a golden-brown crust. Rösti even divides Switzerland: the „Röstigraben\" (Rösti ditch) denotes the cultural border between German- and French-speaking Switzerland. Bernese Rösti sometimes contains bacon or cheese.",
  "wienerisch.w-022": "The Wiener Schnitzel is Austria's most famous dish — a thin, pounded veal cutlet breaded in egg and breadcrumbs, fried golden-brown in clarified butter. A genuine Wiener Schnitzel is made of veal, not pork (that would be „Schnitzel Wiener Art\"). It is served with lemon, potato salad or parsley potatoes. Every Viennese has a favourite Beisl (pub) for the best schnitzel.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-020": "In Franconian, „Schnitz\" means a piece or a slice, but can also mean the schnitzel. The word is related to the verb „schnitzen\" (to carve/whittle) and generally refers to something cut off. In the kitchen: a piece of bread, a slice of cheese or indeed a schnitzel.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-021": "The „Rote Erde\" (Red Earth) was the historic sports ground of BVB Borussia Dortmund before the Westfalenstadion was built. The name derives from the red cinder track. Today „Rote Erde\" is still the name of a small secondary ground next to the Signal-Iduna-Park and stands symbolically for the roots of Dortmund football.",
  "alemannisch.al-019": "The Black Forest is the heart of the Alemannic homeland — a low mountain range in Baden-Württemberg with dense fir forests, cuckoo clocks, spas and the source of the Danube. The high ridge with the Feldberg (1493 m) is the highest peak in Germany outside the Alps. In winter it attracts with skiing, in summer with hiking and thermal springs.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-017": "„Mei!\" — the Palatine all-purpose exclamation for surprise, regret, mild fright or simply as a filler. „Mei, was hot a sich denn dabei gedacht?\" (My, what was he thinking?). Used with different intonations for quite different meanings: astonished, sympathetic, reproachful, appreciative. Similar to the Bavarian „Mei\", but with a Palatine colouring. A classic part of every Palatine pub conversation.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-017": "Hax is the leg, plural Haxn. Whoever injures themselves while skiing may have „bröselt\" (smashed) their Hax. A hearty word for the limbs.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-017": "ebbes means something and is omnipresent in the Rhine-Franconian area. Its counterpart is nix (nothing). Whoever learns „ebbes Rechtes\" learns something sensible.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-017": "Dat Watt is the seabed that falls dry at low tide, the Wadden Sea. A Wattwanderung (mudflat hike) leads out at low water. Defining for the nature and tourism of the coast.",
  "badisch.bad-017": "Es Vesper is the cold snack of bread, sausage and cheese. Accordingly, vespere means to have a snack. A fixed part of the Badenese daily routine.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-017": "S Stüble is the panelled, heated living room of the farmhouse, often with a tiled stove. A cosy retreat where the family gathers.",
  "steirisch.st-017": "A Gschropp is a small child, often meant affectionately and with a wink. D Gschroppm are the children romping about the house. A Bavarian-Styrian word.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-017": "A Bichl is a small hill or rise. Aufn Bichl (on the hill) there is often a Kapelln (chapel). Many Carinthian place and field names contain the word Bichl.",
  "thueringisch.th-017": "The Karnickel is the rabbit, which was formerly kept in the barn in many farmsteads. The Karnickel like to nibble on lettuce. A widespread animal word.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-017": "klönen means to chat in a relaxed and leisurely way, for instance over a Pott (mug) of coffee. The sociable klönen nurtures the neighbourhood. A central North German word.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-017": "The Spreewaldgurke is the famous, pickled gherkin from the Spreewald, a protected trademark of Brandenburg. Crunchy and tangy, a piece of home in every jar.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-017": "A Watschn is a slap in the face. The threat „du fangst glei a Watschn\" (you'll get a slap in a moment) is a well-known phrase. A hearty Bavarian word.",
  "hessisch.h-031": "A hearty Hessian term for someone who is slow-witted, scatterbrained or sluggish. The word combines „dösen\" (to doze/dream) with „Baddel\" (a clumsy oaf). It sounds stronger than „Daddrich\" and conveys a more emphatic rebuff.",
  "berlinisch.b-028": "In Berlin youth slang, someone who is inexperienced, naive or clueless — a newcomer who doesn't know how things work. The word comes from the plant Lauch (leek), which looks pale and not very robust. „Du bist so'n Lauch\" (You're such a leek) is a mild insult among peers.",
  "bayerisch.by-031": "A deep, heartfelt expression of thanks of religious origin — literally „May God repay it (to you)\". Used above all by older generations, it sounds warmer and more sincere than a simple „Danke\". Still widespread in rural Bavaria.",
  "saechsisch.s-022": "The Dresdner Eierschecke is a three-layered tray cake made of yeast dough, a quark filling and a firm egg-cream layer. It is indispensable in any Dresden bakery and is regarded as the cult pastry of the region. Outside Saxony it is hardly known — whoever has tasted it once understands why Saxons are proud of it.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-024": "The Swabian form of the demonstrative pronoun „das\" (that) — one of the most common words in Swabian. „Des isch guad\" (That's good), „des geht net\" (that doesn't work), „des mach ich nit\" (I won't do that) — „des\" carries the sentence. It sounds more compact and terse than the High German „das\" and makes Swabian sentences unmistakable.",
  "koelsch.k-025": "Rose Monday (Rosenmontag) is the climax of the Cologne street carnival — the Rosenmontagszug (Rose Monday procession) is one of the largest carnival parades in the world. Over a million people line the streets to catch Kamelle (sweets) and Strüßjer (little bouquets). The name „Rosen-Montag\" has nothing to do with roses, but derives from „rasen\" (to rampage).",
  "plattdeutsch.p-025": "Hagelslag — chocolate sprinkles on buttered bread — is a cult breakfast that originates from the Netherlands and became popular in the Dutch-influenced North German coastal region. In the Low German border area with Holland, the sweet bread with sprinkles is well known. The name sounds like „Hagelschlag\" (hailstorm) — fitting for the Nordic weather.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-022": "The Swiss Zopf is a buttery-soft, braided yeast pastry — the classic Sunday breakfast bread of German-speaking Switzerland. Traditionally it is eaten only on Sunday and bought fresh from the baker. The braiding patterns vary by canton. With the Zopf, plenty of butter is a must, and sometimes jam.",
  "wienerisch.w-023": "The Viennese goulash is thicker, darker and juicier than the Hungarian original — with lots of onions, paprika, marjoram and caraway, braised for hours. It is served in the coffee house and is the classic midnight dish after the opera or the Heuriger (wine tavern). „A Saftgulasch mit a Semmel\" (a juicy goulash with a bread roll) is the simplest and most satisfying Viennese meal.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-021": "The Franconians' own name for their dialect. Franconians are proud of their vernacular and stress that Franconian has nothing to do with Bavarian — despite both belonging administratively to Bavaria. „Fränggisch\", with its double „g\" and soft „sch\", sounds quite different from standard German.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-022": "„Hau ab!\" (Get lost!) is a direct call to leave, ranging from mild (jokingly) to sharp (meant seriously). In the Ruhr region, directness is a virtue, and this phrase is less offensive than elsewhere — the tone makes the music. Whoever grew up in the Ruhr area knows whether it is meant seriously or humorously.",
  "alemannisch.al-020": "Freiburg im Breisgau is the Alemannic capital of southern Baden, known as the city of the sun with the highest amount of sunshine in Germany. The Freiburg Minster with its Gothic towers dominates the skyline of the old town. The Bächle — little channels running through the pedestrian zones — are a unique feature of the city and a landmark.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-018": "„Es g'hört sich\" — a Palatine saying about decorum and custom. „Bei a Hochzeit g'hört sich a guad Gschenk\" (At a wedding a good present is the proper thing). It expresses what is appropriate in a given situation — social convention, an unwritten law. Negation: „Des g'hört sich net\" (that's not done). Central to Palatine social etiquette — manners, politeness and proper conduct are held in high regard.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-018": "Goschn is the mouth, often in the sense of cheeky talk. The order „hoit dei Goschn\" means to be quiet. A hearty everyday word.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-018": "A Hannebambel is a simple-minded, clumsy or overly compliant person. An affectionately mocking insult that is widespread in the Saarland and the Palatinate.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-018": "A Priel is a water channel in the mudflats that carries water even at low tide. Priels can quickly become dangerous when the tide comes in — caution when mudflat hiking.",
  "badisch.bad-018": "The Schäufele is the cured and smoked pork shoulder, a Baden festive dish, traditionally served with potato salad. The name comes from the shovel-shaped shoulder bone.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-018": "The Schopf is a shed or open lean-to attached to the house, where wood, tools or the car can be kept. An Alemannic word for the outbuilding.",
  "steirisch.st-018": "A Diandl is a girl or young woman, and at the same time the traditional dress. At the Aufsteirern many a Diandl wears her finest Dirndl. A Bavarian word.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-018": "schiach means ugly, unsightly or also angry (schiach wern). A schiachs Wetter is nasty weather. A versatile Austrian word.",
  "thueringisch.th-018": "Worschd is the sausage, in Thuringia especially the Bratworschd and the Mettworschd. Das is mr Worschd means figuratively \"I couldn't care less.\"",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-018": "Schiet refers to dirt, but also trouble or nonsense. So en Schiet! is an exclamation of displeasure. A hearty, good-naturedly used all-purpose word.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-018": "Plinse are thin pancakes from the pan, eaten sweet with sugar or apple sauce. A popular simple dish in Brandenburg and Lusatia.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-018": "deppat means stupid or dumb. So a deppate Gschicht is a foolish affair. Derived from Depp, it is used throughout the Bavarian-speaking area.",
  "hessisch.h-032": "A typically Hessian virtue word — the ability to deal with one another directly and warmly, without formalities or fuss. Hemdsärmeligkeit (shirtsleeve manner) is no insult in Hesse but a mark of quality: down-to-earthness and directness without frills.",
  "berlinisch.b-029": "The Berlin \"no\" — short, curt, non-negotiable. \"Nö\" is the most direct form of refusal in Berlin dialect and needs no further explanation. It reflects the famous Berlin directness: you say what you think, without beating around the bush.",
  "bayerisch.by-032": "The Munich household name for the Oktoberfest, named after the Theresienwiese, where it takes place. It has been held there since 1810 — originally to celebrate the wedding of King Ludwig I. Today the Wiesn is the largest folk festival in the world, with over six million visitors a year.",
  "saechsisch.s-023": "The Ore Mountains (Erzgebirge) on the border with the Czech Republic were for centuries one of the most important mining regions in Europe. After the decline of mining, a rich folk tradition developed: candle arches (Schwibbögen), incense smokers and nutcrackers from the Erzgebirge are known worldwide. Since 2019 the Erzgebirge Mining Region has been a UNESCO World Heritage Site.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-025": "The Swabian \"nix\" is the short form of \"nichts\" (nothing) — short, curt and unmistakable. In everyday Swabian conversation it expresses both complete negation and annoyed refusal. \"Nix isch\" (there's nothing) or \"des bringt nix\" (that's no use) are standard phrases.",
  "koelsch.k-026": "Cologne bears the nickname \"Domstadt\" (cathedral city) — named after Cologne Cathedral, the Gothic masterpiece that took over 600 years to build. The cathedral is the city's landmark and a World Heritage Site. People from Cologne are proud of their cathedral: \"Wenn der Dom in Kölle jeht, dann geiht Kölle met\" (If the cathedral goes, Cologne goes with it) is a popular saying.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-026": "The Smörbrodt (after the Danish smørrebrød) is a familiar word in the North Frisian and Schleswig-Holstein region for the open-faced buttered sandwich — testimony to the long cultural interweaving between Denmark and northern Germany. It can be topped simply with butter and cheese or elaborately with salmon, egg and cucumber. The border region has preserved its own culinary identity.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-024": "The Cervelat is the Swiss national sausage — a smoked scalded sausage made of beef, pork and bacon. It is grilled, fried or eaten cold. Traditionally it is cut crosswise at each end so that the ends curl open when grilled. When meat supplies ran short in 2008, there was a national debate about the Cervelat — that is how important it is to Swiss identity.",
  "wienerisch.w-024": "Tafelspitz is the most elegant meat dish of Viennese cuisine — the tip of the beef rump, slowly simmered in vegetable broth, served with chive sauce, apple-horseradish and fried potatoes (Rösterdäpfel). Emperor Franz Joseph I is said to have eaten Tafelspitz every day. The dish stands for culinary modesty at the highest level: no fillet, no roast — just perfectly prepared boiled meat.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-022": "A typically Franconian closing phrase that expresses resignation or affirmation. Franconian composure in three words — you take things as they come. It can be meant approvingly, but also fatalistically: there's nothing to be done about it anyway.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-023": "\"That's enough!\" is the explosion of Ruhr-area patience: direct, clear and without beating around the bush. The Ruhr person endures a lot and says little — but when he says it, he means it. It is no empty threat, but the clear announcement that a line has been crossed.",
  "alemannisch.al-021": "Freiburg Minster (Münster Unserer Lieben Frau) is one of the most important Gothic cathedrals in Germany and was described by the art historian Jacob Burckhardt as \"the most beautiful tower on earth.\" Construction began in the 13th century and lasted over 300 years. Every Saturday the traditional Münstermarkt is held around the minster.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-019": "The \"Brodes\" — roasting fat from the roast, used as a tasty base for a spread. \"A Schee's Brodesbrot mit Salz und Pfeffer!\" (A nice Brodes bread with salt and pepper!) Country cooking at its purest — what drips off during roasting is not poured away but used as the basis for a dripping sandwich. With bread, onions, spice seeds — a Palatine snack speciality. Economic past and culinary tradition combined.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-019": "Wadl is the calf (of the leg). When mountaineering and cycling, the Wadl is put under heavy strain. Wadlbeißer (calf-biter) is the jocular name for a small, snappy dog.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-019": "The Bobbes is the bottom. Whoever \"uff sei Bobbes fallt\" lands on his backside. A good-natured, everyday word for a body part, also popular in children's language.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-019": "De Deich (the dyke) protects the low-lying land from the North Sea. Wat nich will dieken, mutt wieken (Whoever will not build dykes must yield) is an old coastal proverb.",
  "badisch.bad-019": "Flädle are pancakes cut into fine strips, added as a garnish to Flädlesupp (pancake soup). A popular Baden-Swabian soup for festive occasions.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-019": "Es Tobel is a narrow, wooded gorge with a stream, of the kind common in the Vorarlberg mountains. Many place and field names contain the word Tobel.",
  "steirisch.st-019": "Da Bua is the boy or young man, plural Buabm. Also used as an appreciative form of address among men. A central Bavarian word.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-019": "narrisch means crazy or beside oneself. Narrisch wern means to lose it with joy or anger. A lively word for emotion.",
  "thueringisch.th-019": "The Semmel is the bread roll. At the bakery you fetch fresh Semmeln in the morning. A word for the baked good widespread in eastern and southern Germany.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-019": "Tüffel are the potatoes, a Low German word. Tüffel mit Fisch (potatoes with fish) is a typical meal on the Baltic coast. The basis of many hearty dishes.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-019": "The Buddel is the bottle. Eene Buddel Bier (a bottle of beer) is opened by the campfire. A Low German word that is in common use throughout the region.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-019": "gscheid means clever or proper. Sei gscheid! urges someone to be reasonable. A gscheide Brotzeit is a proper snack. A versatile word.",
  "hessisch.h-033": "The medlar (Mispel) is an old fruit tree that still grows frequently in gardens and along waysides in Hesse. The fruit only becomes edible after the first frost (a process called \"bletting\") and has an apple-like, sweet-sour taste. In Hessian folk medicine, medlars were used against digestive complaints.",
  "berlinisch.b-030": "The Berlin \"was\" (what) — a typical feature of the dialect, where the \"w\" is preserved but the \"a\" is spoken short and hard. \"Wat is det?\" (What is that?) is the classic Berlin question. Also used as a query: \"Wat?!\" when you can't believe or understand something.",
  "bayerisch.by-033": "Despite its name, Bavarian Leberkäs contains neither liver nor cheese — it consists of finely ground pork and beef baked in a rectangular mould. Hot from the oven, cut into a Semmel (roll), with mustard — that is the classic Leberkas treat. An indispensable snack at Bavarian butcher's counters.",
  "saechsisch.s-024": "A mildly scolding Saxon word for a clumsy or not very bright person. The \"Döbsch\" is not a wicked person, just someone who doesn't quite get it. Through its soft consonants the word sounds more harmless than its standard German equivalent — typically Saxon.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-026": "The Swabian \"au\" corresponds to standard German \"auch\" (also) and is a typical shortening in the dialect. It is used unstressed as a filler word, but can also lend emphasis: \"Ich will au!\" (I want to too!) sounds childishly insistent. The word is phonetically closely related to the Alemannic and Swiss German linguistic area.",
  "koelsch.k-027": "The Heinzelmännchen are Cologne legendary figures — little, industrious beings who did the Cologne people's work at night while everyone slept. When a curious tailor's wife scattered peas on the stairs to see them, they stumbled, grew angry and disappeared forever. The Heinzelmännchenbrunnen (fountain) in the old town commemorates the legend.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-027": "On the North Sea coast the flood (Flut) is no abstract event but a reality twice a day. Ebb and flow govern work, traffic and safety. Storm surges have wiped out entire stretches of land in northern Germany's history — the Grote Mandränke of 1362 cost tens of thousands their lives. Even today coastal protection is understood as a vital communal task.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-025": "Rivella is a unique Swiss soft drink — made from milk serum (whey), a by-product of cheese making, combined with herbal extracts. It tastes slightly sweet and has a pale golden colour. Produced since 1952, Rivella is Switzerland's national drink and a cult beverage that often baffles foreigners. It comes in the varieties Red (Classic), Blue (Light) and Green (Green Tea).",
  "wienerisch.w-025": "Kaiserschmarrn is a typically Viennese sweet dish — a fluffy, torn-up pancake batter with raisins, fried in butter and dusted with powdered sugar, served with stewed plums (Zwetschkenröster) or apple sauce. The name derives from Emperor Franz Joseph, who reportedly loved the dish very much. Today it appears on every Austrian menu and is known on mountain huts in Germany.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-023": "A firm affirmation common in Franconian as well as in Bavarian. „Freilich\" comes from Middle High German „vrîlich\" (free, unhindered) and expresses something taken for granted. In Franconian it is often emphasized somewhat more soberly than in the Bavarian region.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-024": "„Knorke\" is an old-fashioned Berlin and West German expression for something great or excellent. In the Ruhr area it was used especially in the 1950s and 1960s. Today it is meant nostalgically and slightly ironically — older generations still use it, while younger ones use it more for a chuckle.",
  "alemannisch.al-022": "Lake Constance (Bodensee) is the largest lake in Germany (shared with Austria and Switzerland) and is affectionately called the „Swabian Sea\". It lies at the tri-border area and has a mild climate that allows for fruit and wine growing. Konstanz, Meersburg and the flower island of Mainau are the best-known destinations on the lake.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-020": "The „Pfälzerwald\" (Palatinate Forest) — the largest contiguous forest area in Germany, a UNESCO biosphere reserve, home of the Palatines. „Mer mache a Wanderung dorch en Pfälzerwald.\" (We're going on a hike through the Palatinate Forest.) With castles, rock formations, hiking valleys and small villages. Sandstone formations like the „Teufelstisch\" (Devil's Table) are tourist magnets. Preserving songs, hut culture, wine and hiking define the Palatine way of life in this forest.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-020": "A Watschn is a slap in the face. The threat „du fangst glei a Watschn\" (you're about to get a slap) is a classic saying. A Watschnbaam would figuratively be someone from whom slaps rain down.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-020": "The Schniss is the face or a contorted expression. Someone who „e Schniss zieht\" (pulls a Schniss) is sulking. A vivid word for the facial expression.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-020": "Dat Schapp is the cupboard. In the Schapp, dishes, linen or supplies are stored. A common piece of furniture vocabulary in the Low German household.",
  "badisch.bad-020": "Bräschtling is the strawberry, especially in the southern Baden and Alemannic region. In summer people look forward to sweet, ripe Bräschtling from the field.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-020": "The Walser are descendants of the settlers who immigrated from the Valais in the Middle Ages, for example to the Großes Walsertal. Their Walser dialect and culture remain distinct to this day.",
  "steirisch.st-020": "fesch describes someone or something as pretty, smart and appealing. A fesches Diandl is a pretty girl. A popular Austrian compliment.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-020": "Erdäpfel are potatoes, the Austrian word. They fill the Kasnudl and come to the table as Erdäpfelsalat (potato salad). A staple food.",
  "thueringisch.th-020": "heeßt is the Thuringian pronunciation of „heißt\" (is called), with the typically drawn-out ee. Wie heeßt n das? asks for the name of a thing. An everyday verb.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-020": "achtern means at the back, its counterpart being vörn (at the front). Achtern Huus means behind the house. The Achtersteven (the stern) of a ship is also derived from it.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-020": "The Plautze is the belly. Sich die Plautze vollschlagen means to eat heartily. A hearty Berlin-Brandenburg word for a body part.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-020": "fei is a flavoring word used for emphasis, something like „but\" or „really\". Des is fei wahr stresses that something is actually true. Particularly frequent in the Upper Palatinate.",
  "hessisch.h-034": "A typically Hessian expression for spontaneous enthusiasm and determination — you set off at once, without long hesitation. The „nix\" is the Hessian form of „nichts\" (nothing), and the whole phrase expresses impulsive readiness to act.",
  "berlinisch.b-031": "A small beer in the 0.33-liter bottle or glass — the „Köpke\" is the Berlin term for the small format. Anyone who doesn't want a full half-liter bottle orders a Köpke. The term is especially common in Berlin corner pubs and expresses relaxed, moderate enjoyment.",
  "bayerisch.by-034": "The white boiled sausage made of veal and pork back fat is the emblem of Munich cuisine. It is traditionally eaten before twelve noon — „the Weißwurst must not hear the noon bells\". It is eaten with sweet mustard, a pretzel and wheat beer; the skin is pulled off with the mouth (zuzeln) or cut open.",
  "saechsisch.s-025": "Saxon term for the handle or grip on a container, bag or bucket. The vowel shift from „ü\" to „ä\" is typical of the dialect. In everyday life you hear: „Halte de Bäggel fest!\" (Hold the handle tight!) when a bucket is being carried.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-027": "In Swabian, the „Säckle\" is both a small bag and colloquially the purse or wallet. Swabians are considered thrifty — and they hold on tight to their „Säckle\". The expression „ins Säckle greifen\" (to reach into the little bag) means to spend money, which for a true Swabian is a serious matter.",
  "koelsch.k-029": "The Cologne „lecker\" means good, pleasant or tasty — and is also used as a general word of approval. „Dat es lecker!\" can refer to food, music or a lovely experience. In the Rhineland „lecker\" is far more versatile than in Standard German and pervades all areas of life as an informal word for beauty.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-028": "A storm surge occurs when a storm pushes the seawater against the coast, raising the normal tide by metres. The storm surge of 1962 devastated Hamburg and cost over 300 people their lives — a collective trauma that marks the city to this day. Helmut Schmidt, then interior senator, earned lasting fame through his crisis management.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-026": "Aromat is the Swiss German all-purpose seasoning mix by Knorr — a blend of salt, monosodium glutamate, starch and spices. It is sprinkled over almost everything: fried eggs, salads, vegetables, meat. Anyone who cooks in Switzerland has Aromat on the table. It is as much a given as salt and pepper and is considered an indispensable Swiss kitchen secret.",
  "wienerisch.w-026": "The Sachertorte is the most famous pastry of Vienna — a dense chocolate cake with a layer of apricot jam, coated in dark chocolate glaze. The original recipe belongs to the Hotel Sacher; for decades the legendary „sweetest dispute in the world\" raged between Sacher and the Demel confectionery over the name. It is served with unsweetened whipped cream — mandatory, not optional.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-024": "The typically Franconian exclamation of inquiry, often drawn out and with rising intonation. It can signal genuine non-comprehension, but also surprise or mild indignation. The tone makes the difference: a short „He?\" is a query, a long „Heeee?\" is astonishment.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-025": "„Dufte\" in Ruhr area slang means roughly „great\" or „super\". The word comes from the Berlin dialect and has established itself in the Ruhr region. It is somewhat dated but still known and is sometimes used nostalgically or ironically — similar to „knorke\".",
  "alemannisch.al-023": "The Kaiserstuhl is a volcanic massif in the middle of the Rhine plain, known for its loess walls, rare reptiles and excellent wines. The name comes from a rock on which emperors are said to have once resided. Kaiserstuhl Pinot Noir and Pinot Gris are among the best German wines — favoured by the southernmost wine-growing climate in Germany.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-021": "A „Dappschädel\" — Palatine for a fool, but in an affectionately reproachful way, never truly mean. „Du Dappschädel, du hosch ja s'falsche Bahn-Ticket!\" (You numbskull, you've got the wrong train ticket!) From „dappen\" (to walk slowly, clumsily) and „Schädel\" (skull). It is used among friends, within the family — rarely as a serious insult. Related to the Bavarian „Damischer\". A classic piece of Palatine linguistic endearment.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-021": "Tschurtsch (also Tschurtschn) is the fir or spruce cone that you collect in the forest, for example to light a fire. A typically Alpine word from nature.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-021": "schwätze means to talk or to chat, without the pejorative undertone of Standard German. Mer schwätze Platt means we speak dialect.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-021": "Someone who is fix un fardig is completely exhausted and at the end of their strength. A very common North German expression after hard work.",
  "badisch.bad-021": "D Schnooge is the mosquito. On the Upper Rhine and in the floodplains there are many Schnooge in summer — hence the famous Schnoogebekämpfung (mosquito control). A widespread word from nature.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-021": "zmorga denotes breakfast or the time of day in the morning. Z Morga essa means to have breakfast. Correspondingly there are zmittag and znacht for the other meals.",
  "steirisch.st-021": "deppat means stupid or silly. So a deppate Gschicht is a stupid affair. Derived from Depp (fool), it is common throughout the Austrian region.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-021": "A Krügerl is a glass of beer of half a litre. By the lake in summer people like to order a kühls Krügerl (a cool half-litre). A common Austrian pub measure.",
  "thueringisch.th-021": "ufn is the slurred form of „auf den\" or „auf dem\" (on the), typical of the fast Thuringian pronunciation. Ufn Tisch means on the table.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-021": "Pannkoken are pancakes, baked in the Pann (pan), sweet or with bacon. Dicke Pannkoken (thick pancakes) are a popular main dish of North German cuisine.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-021": "Eisbein is the cured, boiled pork knuckle, traditionally served with sauerkraut and pea purée. A hearty traditional dish of Berlin and Brandenburg.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-021": "a weng means a little or a bit. Wart no a weng means „wait a little longer\". A frequent word for quantity and time.",
  "hessisch.h-035": "A Hessian particle that denotes a quick, casual action. \"Geh mäh rüwer\" means \"just pop over there for a sec.\" The word is typical of the Hessian fondness for abbreviation and makes sentences shorter and more direct.",
  "berlinisch.b-032": "In Berlin dialect people say \"auf Arbeit\" instead of \"bei der Arbeit\" or \"auf der Arbeit\" (at work). The missing article is characteristic. \"Ick bin auf Arbeit\" — simple, direct, no frills. This abbreviation reflects the pragmatic Berlin character.",
  "bayerisch.by-035": "The white radish, in Bavaria traditionally cut into thin spiral slices, salted and served as an accompaniment to the Brotzeit (snack) or beer. Salting and waiting makes it soft and mellows the sharp flavor. Cutting the Radi is an art in itself — rotating spiral slices that stay attached in one piece.",
  "saechsisch.s-026": "Saxon Switzerland is a national park and Elbe Sandstone Mountains range between Dresden and the Czech border. The striking sandstone rocks, among them the Lilienstein and the Bastei, attract hikers and climbers from all over Europe. The landscape was discovered in the 18th century by Swiss painters and thereby got its name.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-028": "The Swabian word for jam or preserves — derived from \"eingesalztes\" (preserved/cooked-down) fruit. In autumn, Swabian kitchens cook down tons of apples, plums and currants into Gsälz. Homemade Gsälz is on every Swabian breakfast table.",
  "koelsch.k-030": "One of the best-known Rhineland traditional dishes: fried black pudding (Flönz) on a bed of mashed potatoes and apple sauce. \"Himmel\" (heaven) stands for the apples (which grow up high on the tree), \"Ääd\" (earth) for the potatoes (which grow in the ground). The dish combines sweet and savory in an unexpected yet harmonious way.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-029": "The dike is the most important protective wall against the sea — without it, large parts of northern Germany would lie underwater. Building and maintaining dikes was a communal duty; whoever neglected their stretch of dike endangered everyone. Theodor Storm's novella \"Der Schimmelreiter\" turned the dike into a literary icon. In Low German it is simply called \"Diek.\"",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-027": "The formal farewell in Swiss German — literally \"see you again.\" It is used in business relationships, toward older people and in official contexts. In Bernese German, \"uf Wiederluege\" is especially common. Unlike the German \"Auf Wiedersehen,\" the Swiss German form carries the characteristic vowel sound of the Alemannic dialect.",
  "wienerisch.w-027": "The Prater is Vienna's most famous public park — a sprawling green and recreation area whose centerpiece is the Wurstelprater with its historic Ferris wheel. The Vienna Ferris wheel (built in 1897) is a landmark and film backdrop — most famous through the Orson Welles film \"The Third Man.\" The Prater is the place where Vienna shows its soul: loud, colorful, democratic.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-025": "The Franconian term for sour cherries or cherries in general. Franconia is an important cherry-growing region, and cherries play a key role in regional cuisine: Kirschwasser (cherry brandy), cherry cake, cherry jam. In Franconian Switzerland, cherry cultivation has been a tradition for centuries.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-026": "\"Inne\" is the typical Ruhr-area fusion of \"in der\" or \"in die.\" People say \"inne Bude\" (into the room), \"inne Stadt\" (into town) or \"inne Schule\" (at school). This contraction is one of the most striking grammatical features of Ruhr German.",
  "alemannisch.al-024": "The Hegau is a landscape in Baden-Württemberg west of Lake Constance, known for its conical volcanic peaks and medieval castle ruins. The volcanic basalt cones (such as the Hohentwiel or the Mägdeberg) are visible from afar and shape the skyline. The Hegau is considered one of the most romantic landscapes of Alemannia.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-022": "The \"Weckmann\" — the traditional Palatine yeast pastry in the shape of a little man, with a clay pipe or currants for eyes. \"Zum Martinstag gibt's a Weckmann mit Pfeif\" (On St. Martin's Day there's a Weckmann with a pipe). A classic Saint Martin's and Saint Nicholas pastry. Widespread throughout western Germany, but with its own variations in the Palatinate. Children get it on December 6th or on November 11th (St. Martin's Day). A reminder of the Christian saintly tradition.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-022": "Oachkatzl is the squirrel. The Oachkatzlschwoaf (squirrel's tail) is regarded as a famous shibboleth used to tell locals from outsiders.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-022": "gugge means to look or to peek. The prompt \"guck emol\" means \"have a look.\" A high-frequency everyday verb in Saarland dialect.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-022": "dröge means dry, both in terms of the weather and humor. A dröger guy has a dry, subtle wit. A versatile coastal word.",
  "badisch.bad-022": "D Fasnet is the Swabian-Alemannic carnival with masks, Häs (costumes) and Narrenzünfte (fools' guilds). Its highlight is the Schmutzige Dunschdig (Dirty Thursday). A central Baden custom and festival.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-022": "znacht is the evening meal or the time in the evening. Z Nacht essa means to have dinner. Part of the Alemannic series zmorga, zmittag, znacht (breakfast, lunch, dinner).",
  "steirisch.st-022": "A Watschn is a slap in the face. The threat \"du fangst glei a Watschn\" (you're about to catch a slap) is a classic phrase. A robust Bavarian-Styrian word.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-022": "Most is the fermented apple or pear juice from the farm. A Glasl Most (a glass of Most) belongs to a hearty Jause (snack). A traditional drink in rural Carinthia.",
  "thueringisch.th-022": "gell is the reassurance tag at the end of a sentence and expects agreement, comparable to \"isn't that so?\" Particularly common in the south of Thuringia.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-022": "Plünnen are clothes, often in the sense of old rags. Truck di dröge Plünnen an means to put on dry clothes. A cozy everyday word.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-022": "meckern means to grumble or complain. Der meckert über allet is someone who always has something to find fault with. A trait regarded as typical.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-022": "etz means now. Etz aber gschwind! (now hurry up!) urges haste. A frequent time word in everyday Upper Palatine speech, often at the start of a sentence.",
  "hessisch.h-036": "The Hessian crumble cake — a simple yeast cake on which \"Riwwele\" (crumbs) of butter, sugar and flour are spread. The Riwwelkuche is a classic on every Hessian coffee table and at club festivals. The name comes from \"riwweln\" (to rub/crumble), the process of making the crumbs.",
  "berlinisch.b-033": "When something is so full that you can hardly fit in any more, in Berlin dialect it is \"knüppelvoll\" (packed). The expression comes from the Knüppel (a thick stick) and vividly conveys: as tightly packed as logs in a stack. Used especially for overcrowded subways, clubs or festivals.",
  "bayerisch.by-036": "Someone with \"Schneid\" is plucky, daring and not easily intimidated. The word derives from \"schneiden\" (to cut) and figuratively means grit and determination. In Bavaria, Schneid is a highly valued character trait — anyone who lacks Schneid is considered a coward.",
  "saechsisch.s-027": "The Saxon \"nu\" is a multifaceted filler word: it can express agreement, a prompt, thoughtfulness or mild skepticism. \"Nu?\" on its own can be a question — \"Well? How was it?\" Combined, it forms characteristic phrases: \"Nu freilich\" (well of course), \"nu ja\" (well, yeah), \"nu warte mal\" (now wait a moment).",
  "schwaebisch.sw-029": "A coarse Swabian swear word for someone who gets dirty, is untidy or behaves improperly. In Swabian, even a swear word sounds somewhat earthier and more direct through the dialect than in standard German. It is also used jokingly among friends when someone makes a mess while eating.",
  "koelsch.k-031": "The brewery (Brauhaus) is the social center of Cologne life — here everyone meets, from the craftsman to the entrepreneur, from the tourist to the local. In the Brauhaus, Kölsch is freshly tapped and served in the 0.2-liter Stange (glass); the Köbes (waiter) brings refills unasked until you place the beer mat on the glass. The Brauhaus is cultural heritage and a UNESCO candidate.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-030": "A mudflat hike (Wattwanderung) leads at low tide across the exposed seabed of the Wadden Sea — barefoot through the mud, past mussels, crabs and wading birds. It is a must for North Sea visitors and is always undertaken with a knowledgeable mudflat guide, since the tide comes back quickly and dangerously. The Wadden Sea is a UNESCO World Natural Heritage Site.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-028": "A Swiss German word for a guy or lad — depending on the tone either matey and friendly or slightly derogatory. \"Du Cheib!\" among friends is an affectionate reproach with no serious intent. The word sounds rough but often means affection. In youth slang it is used jokingly as a form of address, similar to \"dude\" or \"mate\" in standard German.",
  "wienerisch.w-028": "The Viennese coffeehouse is an attitude to life, not just a café. You pay for one cup of coffee and may sit for hours reading newspapers, playing chess or debating — at some point the waiter brings an unrequested glass of water. Writers like Arthur Schnitzler and Stefan Zweig wrote in the coffeehouse. It is UNESCO cultural heritage and the most important social living room of the Viennese.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-026": "In autumn, at the time of the new wine (Federweißer), onion tart is a must in the Franconian and Swabian-Alemannic region. The savory tart of shortcrust pastry with onions, bacon and sour cream goes perfectly with the young, slightly sweet Federweißer. A seasonal tradition in wine-growing regions.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-027": "In the Ruhr area, the \"Bude\" is the room, the flat or simply one's own space. \"Meine Bude\" means my home, my room or my realm. The word comes from Middle Low German and is widespread throughout the northern German language area, but especially alive in the Ruhr region.",
  "alemannisch.al-025": "\"Luege\" is the Alemannic and Swiss German word for \"to look\" or \"to watch.\" It is one of the best-known Alemannic dialect words and clearly distinguishes the dialect area from the northern German \"kucken\" or \"gucken.\" \"Lueg emol!\" means \"Look!\" and is a friendly call for attention.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-023": "The \"Buwespitzle\" — hand-shaped potato noodles from the Palatinate, with characteristically pointed ends. \"Buwespitzle mit Sauerkraut, des isch a Klassiker\" (Buwespitzle with sauerkraut, that's a classic). A variation of Swabian Schupfnudeln, but shaped in the Palatine way. Made from cooked potatoes, flour, egg. They are pan-fried in butter and served with bacon, sauerkraut or as a side dish. A wedding and Sunday dish in many Palatine families.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-023": "The Alm is the high-lying mountain pasture where livestock is kept in summer. Life on the Alm shapes Tyrolean culture to this day. Derived from it are Almabtrieb (the cattle drive down from the pasture) and Almhütte (mountain hut).",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-023": "allebott means constantly or every few minutes. Whoever calls allebott rings nonstop. A vivid word for high frequency.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-023": "De Smutje is the cook on board a ship. The mood of the crew depends on the Smutje — a good Smutje is worth a great deal at sea.",
  "badisch.bad-023": "The Häs is the traditional, often intricately carved fool's costume of the Fasnet (carnival). Each guild has its own Häs, which is passed down over generations.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-023": "schwätza means to talk or chat, without any pejorative connotation. In Vorarlberg, schwätza means to speak the dialect. A common everyday verb.",
  "steirisch.st-023": "tschindern means to slide or glide across a smooth sheet of ice in winter. The children tschindern on the frozen pond. A vivid winter pastime.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-023": "fesch describes someone or something as pretty and stylish. A fesches Dirndl is a pretty girl. A popular Austrian compliment.",
  "thueringisch.th-023": "heeme means home or at home, with the typical long Thuringian ee. Ich geh heeme means \"I'm going home\". A warm-hearted everyday word.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-023": "Nu introduces many sentences as \"now\" or \"well\" and gives Low German its rhythm. Nu maak man! means \"go on, do it!\". A common filler word.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-023": "latschen means to walk leisurely, shuffling along. Den ganzen Weg latschen means to trudge a long distance on foot. The Latschen (slippers) also come from this.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-023": "wos is the Northern Bavarian \"was\" (what). Wos host gsagt? means \"what did you say?\". A common question word with the typically dark Upper Palatinate sound.",
  "hessisch.h-037": "Describes a typically Hessian mix of self-confidence, daredevilry and the occasional boastfulness. The Hessian is proud of his origins and shows it. \"Hessisch-uff\" is a half-admiring, half-teasing description of the self-assured Hessian.",
  "berlinisch.b-034": "A self-confident, strong man who is in charge or wants to be. The Macker calls the shots and acts with assurance. In Berlin dialect this can be appreciative — \"der is'n echter Macker\" — or mocking, for someone who thinks more of himself than he is.",
  "bayerisch.by-037": "Describes something boring, dull or monotonous. \"Des war fad!\" after an event is a damning verdict. The word comes from Middle High German \"vade\" and is used throughout the Bavarian-Austrian region. Dishes without seasoning can also be \"fad\".",
  "saechsisch.s-028": "The Saxon pronunciation of \"eigentlich\" (actually) — a prime example of the vowel shift in the dialect. The \"ei\" becomes \"a\" and the final syllable is swallowed. The word is one of the most famous Saxon pronunciation gags and is often imitated by non-Saxons. Anyone who says \"achantlich\" instantly gives themselves away as a Saxon.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-030": "A stronger Swabian exclamation of surprise or fright — comparable to \"Donnerwetter!\". The term is a euphemistic form of a religious exclamation and shows how deeply religiosity is rooted in everyday Swabian speech. It sounds indignant, but never truly angry.",
  "koelsch.k-032": "The Stammtisch in the brewery is the table reserved for regulars — a fixed ritual where the same group meets regularly. In the Cologne brewery the Stammtisch has an almost sacred significance: here political debates are held, gossip is exchanged and Kölsch is drunk. Anyone who gets invited has truly arrived.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-031": "The seagull is the symbol of the North Sea coast — loud, brazen and omnipresent. In Low German \"Möv\" or \"Möwe\", it steals chips off your plate and circles over fishing boats. For North Germans its cry is the sound of home, for tourists sometimes a shock. Seagulls follow ships far out to sea.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-029": "In Swiss German the \"Schnägg\" is first of all the snail — slow, deliberate, with its house on its back. Figuratively, a particularly slow or sluggish person is affectionately or exasperatedly called a Schnägg. \"Mach schnell, du Schnägg!\" is a common phrase from impatiently waiting parents. The snail as a symbol of slowness is widespread throughout the whole Alemannic-speaking region.",
  "wienerisch.w-029": "The Melange is the classic Viennese coffee — half espresso, half foamed milk, topped with a touch of milk foam, often served in a glass or a cup with a handle. It is not identical to café au lait or cappuccino, but has its own, milder Viennese character. Anyone who orders \"a coffee\" in Vienna has to be more specific — the menu is long.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-027": "In Franconian a \"Spitz\" is a small glass of schnapps or grain spirit — the Franconian version of the Bavarian Stamperl. Franconia has a long tradition of fruit brandies and marc spirits, especially from Franconian wine. A Spitz after a meal is considered to aid digestion.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-029": "A \"Pottmensch\" is someone who not only lives in the Ruhr area but really comes from there and has internalized the Ruhrpott mentality. Direct, warm-hearted, football-crazy and not squeamish — those are the attributes of a true Pottmensch. Newcomers can also become Pottmenschen after years, if they adopt the values.",
  "alemannisch.al-026": "\"Chlii\" is the Alemannic and Swiss German form of \"klein\" (small) and shows the typical Alemannic sound shift of the \"k\" to \"ch\" at the start of a word. It is one of the clearest phonetic features of Alemannic and makes the dialect hard to understand for North Germans. \"En chlii\" means \"a little bit\".",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-024": "A \"Hesseschdier\" — a Palatine swear word for someone from Hesse, half jokingly, half in rivalry. \"Du Hesseschdier, lass mer mei Glas in Ruh!\" The rivalry between the Palatinate and neighbouring Hesse is legendary — especially between local football clubs. Not really an insult, but local patriotism with a wink. It speaks to the strong regional identity of the Palatines.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-024": "The Stodl is the barn or hay shed where hay and equipment are stored. A central building on every Tyrolean farm, alongside the stable and the farmhouse.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-024": "Babbe is the father or dad, an intimate family word. Together with Mamme it is the usual way of addressing parents in Saarland and the Palatinate.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-024": "Fischkopp is the jokey nickname for the coastal inhabitants of northern Germany. The Fischköpp wear it with pride — a good-natured teasing from the south.",
  "badisch.bad-024": "Narri Narro is the traditional fools' call of the Alemannic Fasnet. One person calls Narri, the crowd answers Narro. A battle cry of the fifth season.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-024": "A Gugg is a bag or paper sack, for instance for sweets or shopping. A word common throughout the Alemannic and Bavarian regions.",
  "steirisch.st-024": "A Gstetten is an overgrown, unkempt embankment or a fallow plot full of scrub. A typically Austrian word for wild nature on the edge of things.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-024": "deppat means stupid or silly. So a deppate Gschicht is a stupid affair. Derived from Depp (fool), it is used throughout the Austrian region.",
  "thueringisch.th-024": "Die Mudder is the mother, with the typical Thuringian pronunciation. Together with der Vadder, it is one of the most common family words in everyday life.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-024": "Whoever has de Murr is grumpy and in a bad mood. Een murrige Keerl is a grouchy fellow. A vivid word for North German taciturnity in the morning.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-024": "Pampe is a thick, unappetizing mush or sludge. In a thaw the path turns into Pampe. A failed meal can also be called Pampe.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-024": "dahoam means at home. Dahoam is dahoam expresses the attachment to one's homeland. A warm-hearted word from the Bavarian region.",
  "hessisch.h-038": "An affectionate word for a charmingly cunning person who always manages to make the best of everything. The Schächer does not act with malice — he is simply cleverer than the others. The word has religious roots (Schächer = robber in the Bible), but is used humorously today.",
  "berlinisch.b-035": "The Berlin form of \"weiß ich nicht\" (I don't know) — the \"i\" in \"weiß\" is stretched to \"ee\". A classic Berlin shrug. Sometimes also used as an evasive manoeuvre when one doesn't feel like answering a question. It sounds more honest than any standard German equivalent.",
  "bayerisch.by-038": "The Bavarian verb for arduous climbing or clambering up — especially in nature, over rocks, slopes or steep paths. \"Kraxeln\" sounds like effort and adventure at once. In the Alpine region it is an indispensable word for anyone who loves the mountains.",
  "saechsisch.s-029": "The Saxon bratwurst differs from the Thuringian one in its finer blend of spices and its pork. At the market and at food stalls in Dresden and Leipzig, the Bratwurscht is an everyday snack. The pronunciation with the soft final consonant \"scht\" is characteristic of Upper Saxon.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-031": "A \"Krätzer\" is a sharp, sour wine — often a young wine or a wine of poor quality. In Swabian the term is used both mockingly and affectionately for a robust, rough wine from the Wengert (vineyard). Besides fine vintages, Württemberg also produces many such down-to-earth Krätzer wines.",
  "koelsch.k-033": "The Cologne pronunciation of \"Gemeinde\" (community/parish) with the typical \"J\" instead of \"G\" at the start — a characteristic feature of Ripuarian. Community plays a central role in Cologne: clubs, brewery gatherings and carnival societies hold the Jemeinde together. \"Mir sin alle eine Jemeinde\" is not just a pious sentence, but lived Cologne reality.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-033": "Almost like in standard German, but pronounced slightly differently. On the North Sea coast rain is not an exception but a permanent state — which also explains the Schietwedder. In the agriculture of the marsh regions, however, rain is vital for the fertile soils. North German children learn early on: rain is no reason to stay at home.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-030": "A Swiss German follow-up formula — \"Tscheggsch?\" is the shortened form of \"tscheggsch das?\" (do you get it?). The verb \"tscheggge\" (to check, to understand) is borrowed from English and has caught on in the youth slang of the whole German-speaking part of Switzerland. \"Tscheggsch?\" at the end of a sentence works like \"ne?\" or \"got it?\" and asks for agreement or feedback.",
  "wienerisch.w-030": "The Einspänner is a strong black mocha, served in a tall glass with a generous cap of whipped cream (Schlagobers). It is said to be named after the single-horse Fiaker coachman, who got his coffee in a glass so he could drink it while driving. The Einspänner is bold, elegant and typically Viennese — caffeine with charm.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-028": "The Franconian term for a boy or young man, similar to the Bavarian „Bua\". In Franconian the word is pronounced with a short „u\" and is a friendly, ordinary form of address for boys. Also common as a fatherly way of addressing a son or as a team name among men.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-030": "„Am Start sein\" means to be ready and available — whether for a meeting, a task or an adventure. The expression comes from sports, where the athlete waits at the start line. In Ruhr-area slang it is a general word for availability and readiness for action.",
  "alemannisch.al-027": "In Alemannic, „echt\" is used as an intensifier especially often and with a particular drawl: „echt guet\", „echt schön\", „echt toll\". It corresponds to standard German „wirklich\" (really) or „sehr\" (very) and is a typical filler word in Baden youth slang. In Freiburg you hear it on every corner.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-025": "„Aaschloch\" — the Palatine pronunciation of „Arschloch\" (asshole), a coarse swear word. „So a Aaschloch hot mei Geld behoidn!\" (Some asshole kept my money!) The Palatine person curses quite coarsely, but usually with a certain self-irony. It is rarely understood as a truly serious insult, more as an emphatic exclamation of frustration. „A blöder Aaschloch\" (a stupid asshole) as an intensified form. Genuine insults, however, are rare in Palatine usage.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-025": "The Almabtrieb is the festive driving home of the cattle from the alpine pasture in autumn. If the summer passed without accidents, the cows are adorned with flowers and bells. A great Tyrolean folk-tradition festival.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-025": "Mamme is the mother or mum. The Mamme cooks, cares and holds the family together — a loving, everyday word.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-025": "Matjes is a young, mildly salted herring, a delicacy on the coast. Fresh Matjes with onions and bread is a feast in early summer.",
  "badisch.bad-025": "Es Mädle is the girl, an affectionate diminutive. Its male counterpart is der Bub. An everyday family word in the Baden-Swabian region.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-025": "Dr Öpfel is the apple, from which the cider (Most) is also pressed in the Ländle (Vorarlberg). The Alemannic pronunciation with Ö is typical and distinguishes Vorarlberg from the rest of Austria.",
  "steirisch.st-025": "A Marterl is a small wayside cross or a picture panel at the roadside, often in memory of someone who died in an accident. They shape the landscape in the Alpine region.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-025": "leiwand means great or super. Des is leiwand! is an enthusiastic praise. Originally Viennese slang, today widespread throughout Austria.",
  "thueringisch.th-025": "Der Vadder is the father. Mei Vadder geht in die Arweit (My father goes to work). Together with der Mudder he forms the Thuringian family. A familiar word.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-025": "De Buur is the farmer who works the wide expanse of the Mecklenburg fields. De Buurfru is the farmer's wife. Agriculture shapes the region to this day.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-025": "nu introduces many sentences as „nun\" (now) or „na\" (well). Nu komm schon! (Come on now!) urges haste. A common filler word that gives speech its rhythm.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-025": "D Goaß is the goat, kept on the meagre pastures of the Upper Palatinate. Aus da Goaßmilch macht man Käse (Cheese is made from the goat's milk). A word from the rural world.",
  "hessisch.h-039": "A large, often ostentatious vehicle. Originally the Karosse denoted a magnificent carriage of the nobility — today the word is used humorously for an oversized car. „Der hat ne Karosse\" (He's got a Karosse) can sound admiring or mocking.",
  "berlinisch.b-036": "Berlin is divided into twelve districts, and each has its own character and pride. Mitte, Prenzlauer Berg, Neukölln, Kreuzberg — each district has its own identity and its residents identify strongly with it. „Welcher Bezirk?\" (Which district?) is, in Berlin, a serious question of belonging.",
  "bayerisch.by-039": "The Bavarian word for „Ei\" (egg) — a striking example of the vowel shifts in Bavarian, where „ei\" becomes „oa\". „Drei Oa\" are three eggs. Also in compounds: „Rührei\" (scrambled egg) becomes „Rühr-Oar\". Still very much alive in everyday speech.",
  "saechsisch.s-030": "The Zeisig is actually a small green songbird, but in Saxon vernacular it is used as an affectionate term for a person from Leipzig. The origin is unclear, possibly referring to the lively, chirping manner of the people of the trade-fair city. Leipzig and its inhabitants are considered somewhat more cosmopolitan and quicker than the rest of Saxony.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-032": "The Gugelhupf is a traditional ring-shaped cake with its characteristic form, popular in Swabia, Bavaria, Austria and Switzerland. In Swabia it is often baked with raisins and rum. The name derives from „Gugel\" (cap, hood) and „Hupf\" (little hop) — the cake looks like a hopping monk's cowl.",
  "koelsch.k-034": "The Cologne word for „nichts\" (nothing) — more compact and rounder than its standard German counterpart. „Nüscht\" appears in many Cologne phrases: „Do es nüscht\" (there's nothing there), „Nüscht wie hin!\" (nothing but go there!). It is one of the most frequent words in Kölsch and shows how the dialect expresses everyday matters concisely and directly.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-034": "The Landgang is the sailor's short excursion ashore from the ship while it lies in harbour. After weeks at sea, Landgang means fresh food, family, pubs and the feeling of solid ground underfoot. Figuratively, Hamburg people also jokingly call an outing into the countryside a „Landgang\".",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-031": "In Swiss German „glatt\" does not only mean physically smooth, but also „clear\", „unambiguous\" or „self-evident\". „Das isch glatt falsch\" means „That is plainly wrong\". It reinforces statements without circumlocution — typical of the direct Swiss communication style. „glattweg\" (flatly, without ado) is a related Swiss expression too.",
  "wienerisch.w-031": "The Austrian word for whipped cream — „Obers\" is the general Austrian word for cream (Rahm), and „Schlagobers\" is the whipped variety. In Vienna, Schlagobers belongs with almost every pastry, unsweetened and plentiful. Anyone who orders a cake in a Viennese café gets Schlagobers automatically — without Schlagobers a pastry is only half finished.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-029": "The Franconian diminutive form for girl, similar to the Bavarian „Madl\". In Franconian the ending „-la\" is used as a diminutive suffix, while Bavarian often uses „-l\" or „-erl\". A „Madla\" is a young woman or a girl — friendly and without any derogatory undertone.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-031": "„Halt die Fresse\" is a coarse demand to be silent. In the Ruhr area, directness is honesty, and sometimes there's no beating about the bush even with insults. Among friends it can sound less harsh than between strangers. It remains a crude expression and should be used with care.",
  "alemannisch.al-028": "„Uff die Gass!\" means „onto the street\" and is a call to leave the house and go out among people. The term „Gass\" for street or alley is typically Alemannic and Swiss German. The invitation is friendly and lively and expresses that life takes place outside.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-026": "A „Hatscheliebche\" — a spoiled, beloved child, often the youngest in the family. „Du bisch mei Hatscheliebche, du krigsch alles!\" (You're my darling, you get everything!) From „hätscheln\" (to pamper) and „Liebche\" (little darling). It denotes someone who is especially pampered — it can be meant lovingly or slightly reproachfully. In some Palatine families it is clearly settled who the Hatscheliebche is. Classic family vocabulary.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-026": "A Hetz is fun and amusement. To do something „aus Hetz\" means to do it for the fun of it. A central word for the sociable, life-loving side of the Tyroleans.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-026": "Schlabbe are the slippers or house shoes that you slip into at home. Whoever shuffles around „in de Schlabbe\" is making themselves comfortable.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-026": "Stuten is a slightly sweet white or raisin bread, often eaten with tea. The raisin Stuten is especially popular on festive occasions.",
  "badisch.bad-026": "hano is a typically Baden exclamation of hesitation or astonishment, something like „well, what now\" or „well then\". A filler word that nicely captures Baden's easy-going nature.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-026": "Dr Most is the fermented apple or pear juice, a traditional drink. On many farms their own Most is pressed and stored in the cellar.",
  "steirisch.st-026": "Almrausch is the alpenrose, which colours the mountain slopes red in summer. When the Almrausch blooms, the most beautiful season on the alpine pasture has arrived.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-026": "A Watschn is a slap in the face. The threat „du fangst glei a Watschn\" (you'll get a slap in a moment) is a well-known saying. A coarse word from the southern Bavarian area.",
  "thueringisch.th-026": "Beene are the legs, singular Been. Nach dem langen Weg tun mr die Beene weh (After the long walk my legs hurt). A common body word of the East Central German dialect.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-026": "tofreden means content. Ik bün tofreden means „I am content\". The calm, modest contentment is considered typical of the Mecklenburg temperament.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-026": "Die Mark is the landscape of the Mark Brandenburg with its pine forests, lakes and sandy soils. In de Mark rausfahren means to drive out into rural Brandenburg.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-026": "heuer means „this year\". Heuer is da Zoigl guad gratn means this year the beer turned out well. In common use throughout the Bavarian area.",
  "hessisch.h-040": "Literally a small, flat or leathery face — but mostly used affectionately for a child or a familiar person. \"Du Läbbchen!\" is meant warmly. The word has a soft contour in Hessian and, despite its origin, sounds tender.",
  "berlinisch.b-037": "An approving expression for someone for whom everything is going well. \"Läuft bei dir\" can be genuinely enthusiastic or slightly ironic. In Berlin slang it has become a general comment on successes or lucky coincidences, often accompanied by an approving nod.",
  "bayerisch.by-040": "The traditional church consecration festival, celebrated with great effort in Bavarian villages. Carousels, beer tents, music and dancing are part of it. The word is a shortening of \"Kirchentag\" and refers to the patronal feast of the village church — today mostly a secular folk festival.",
  "saechsisch.s-031": "Leipzig is the largest city in Saxony and a cultural center of European rank. The trade-fair city was a hub of commerce, Bach's place of work at the Thomanerchor, the birthplace of Wagner and the setting of the Peaceful Revolution of 1989. The Monday demonstrations on Karl-Marx-Platz (today Augustusplatz) heralded the end of the GDR.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-033": "The Black Forest cherry cake (Schwarzwälder Kirschtorte) is one of the most famous German cakes worldwide and comes from the Alemannic-Swabian Black Forest. It consists of chocolate sponge, cherries, cream and the characteristic Black Forest Kirschwasser (cherry brandy). The recipe is legally protected: genuine Black Forest cherry cake must contain Kirschwasser.",
  "koelsch.k-035": "The Carnival Prince is one of the three figures of the Cologne Triumvirate (Dreigestirn) and symbolically reigns over the fools' people during the carnival season. He wears golden armor and a cloak and stands for joy and exuberance. The choice of the prince is a social event — traditional societies and carnival clubs present him ceremonially in November.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-035": "In Low German and in the Hamburg seafaring tradition, the sailor was the backbone of the merchant navy. Young men from northern Germany went to sea to see the world — and returned with stories, souvenirs and sometimes foreign languages. The image of the sailor in a striped jumper and cap is inseparably linked with Hamburg.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-032": "The Swiss German word for to look or to watch — \"lueg mal!\" means \"look here!\". It is one of the most common verbs in everyday life and has many uses: \"ga luege\" (to go and have a look), \"lueg dass du pünktlich bisch\" (make sure you're on time). In Switzerland people never say \"gucken\" — that's too northern German. \"Luege\" is the Alemannic standard.",
  "wienerisch.w-032": "Buchteln are soft, fluffy yeast dumplings made from Germteig (yeast dough), filled with Powidl (plum butter) and baked in butter, served with vanilla sauce. They are the ultimate Austrian comfort food — warm, sweet, fragrant. In Vienna they are equally appreciated as dessert and as a main dish. The name probably comes from the Czech \"buchta\" — a sign of the diversity of Viennese cuisine.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-030": "A Franconian term for a clumsy, oafish person. Less harsh than other insults, more humorously reproachful. \"Du Dalkert!\" is gladly used among friends or in the family for small mishaps. The word comes from \"dalken\" (to blunder, to be clumsy).",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-032": "\"Wat willste machen\" is a fatalistic sigh expressing resignation or equanimity. When the weather is bad, the bus is late again or the team loses: Wat willste machen. It is not a call to passivity, but Ruhr-region composure in the face of the uncontrollable.",
  "alemannisch.al-029": "\"Simsalabim\" is a magic word that has its origins in the Alemannic-Jewish sphere and spread from there into international entertainment culture. In Alemannic popular speech it is a playful exclamation of surprise or is used when something unexpectedly works out. Its origin is disputed — possibly from Arabic or Hebrew.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-027": "D'\"Worschtbrieh\" — the hearty broth in which Palatine sausages are cooked. \"Lewwerknepp in Worschtbrieh, des wärmt im Winter.\" From the cooking water of Saumagen, Bratwurst, liver dumplings — it doesn't go down the drain but is reused as soup. Soaked with bread, a classic of the winter Brotzeit (snack meal). Practical farmhouse cooking without waste — typical Palatine thriftiness.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-027": "A Gschtanzl is a short, often mocking four-line verse sung at festivals, gladly in a contest. The quick-witted Gschtanzln take aim at the village and the authorities.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-027": "Bagaasch (from the French bagage) means sometimes disparagingly a dubious crowd, sometimes jokingly the whole extended family. Its closeness to French is typical of the Saarland.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-027": "proten means to talk or to speak. Platt proten means to speak Low German. Whoever veel proot talks a lot. A central verb of Low German.",
  "badisch.bad-027": "pressiere means to hurry or to press, from the French presser. Es pressiert means \"it's urgent\". French loanwords are common in Badisch.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-027": "gampa or gampfa means to wobble or to rock, when something doesn't stand firmly. Dr Tisch gampet means the table wobbles. A vivid word of movement.",
  "steirisch.st-027": "Da Greißler is the small corner shop in the village, where you can get groceries and everyday items. Many Greißler have disappeared, but they are regarded as a piece of home.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-027": "A Diandl is a girl or a young woman, and at the same time the traditional dress (Tracht). Beim Kirchtag tanzn d Diandl in da Tracht (at the parish fair the girls dance in their Tracht). A Bavarian word.",
  "thueringisch.th-027": "Der Kopp is the head. Sich den Kopp zerbrechen means to rack one's brains. A common body word that Thuringian shares with many dialects.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-027": "Water is water, omnipresent on the Baltic coast. Op dat Water kieken means to look out to sea. A basic Low German word.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-027": "Die Atze is the good buddy or brother, a familiar Berlin-Brandenburg word. Na, Atze? is a casual greeting among friends.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-027": "Reng is rain, in northern Bavarian pronunciation. Bei Reng bleibt ma dahoam (when it rains you stay at home). A common weather word of the Upper Palatinate.",
  "hessisch.h-041": "An archaic exclamation for great noise and commotion — originally a medieval cry for help in cases of crime and fire. \"Zetter\" and \"Mordio\" are old calls for help. Today the expression is used figuratively for exaggerated excitement over trifles.",
  "berlinisch.b-038": "A versatile Berlin exclamation of surprise, indignation or enthusiasm. \"Alter\" is the form of address for another person (whether old or young), \"ey\" is a filler word from Berlin slang. Together they make up the Berlin all-purpose exclamation for all strong emotions.",
  "bayerisch.by-041": "An informal or secret love affair, also a crush or a fling. The word sounds slightly roguish and expresses that it is not an entirely serious, official relationship. \"Er hat a Gspusi\" means that someone has an affair or a flirtation going on.",
  "saechsisch.s-032": "Der Bömmel is the woolen pompom on a knitted cap or a tassel on a scarf. In the Erzgebirge, traditional costumes feature such Bömmel as decoration. The word is a diminutive and, thanks to its round shape, sounds especially cozy. Children love to pull at the Bömmel.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-034": "The Swabian Alb is the heart of the Swabian natural landscape — a limestone plateau with juniper heaths, romantic castle ruins and deep caves. Here the oldest art of humankind was found: the ivory carvings from the Geißenklösterle cave are over 40,000 years old. The Alb is a hiking paradise and a way of life for millions of Swabians.",
  "koelsch.k-037": "The \"kölsche Jong\" is the epitome of the true native of Cologne — warm-hearted, direct, carnival-crazy and devoted to Kölsch. \"Kölsche Jongs\" are at home all over the world, but never forget their hometown. The song \"Mer losse d'r Dom in Kölle\" by the Bläck Fööss is the unofficial anthem of the Cologne lads abroad.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-036": "The Low German word for ship is \"Schipp\" — almost like the English \"ship\". For centuries Hamburg was one of the most important maritime cities in the world; ships brought spices, fabrics and prosperity. Even today the Port of Hamburg is the third largest in Europe. Pride in the seafaring tradition is deeply anchored in the northern German self-image.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-033": "The Swiss German word for \"nothing\" — pronounced with the characteristic long vowel and the soft \"t\". \"Ich weiss nüüt\" (I know nothing), \"das isch nüüt\" (that's nothing). The word appears in countless idioms and is indispensable in everyday life. In Bernese German it sounds slightly different from Zurich German, but both say \"nüüt\".",
  "wienerisch.w-033": "The Austrian word for bread roll — anyone who says \"Brötchen\" in Vienna immediately gives himself away as a northern German. The Semmel is the daily bread of the Viennese: round, crusty, fresh from the baker, indispensable in the morning. \"A Semmel mit Butter\" is the simplest breakfast, \"a Semmel mit Wurst\" the classic snack (Jause). The word comes from the Latin \"simila\" — fine wheat flour.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-031": "The Franconian pronunciation of \"Dreck\" (dirt), with the \"e\" slightly opened and the \"r\" rolled. Typically Franconian. It can literally mean dirt, but also figuratively something worthless or bad: \"Des is doch aller Dräck!\" (That's worthless!).",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-033": "\"Inner Pott\" is the shortened form of \"in dem Pott\" and means the same as aufm Pott — namely the Ruhr region. These contractions are characteristic of Ruhr German, which gladly fuses prepositions and articles. Inner Pott is home, is homeland, is identity.",
  "alemannisch.al-031": "\"Mauli\" is the affectionate Alemannic diminutive of \"Maul\" (mouth) and is used especially with children or lovingly when dealing with animals. It is meant warmly and not pejoratively: \"Des Kätzschen macht es Mauli auf\" (The kitten opens its mouth). As a term for the human mouth, it is colloquial.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-028": "\"Hisch\" — Palatine pronunciation of \"hier\" (here), often with a double \"s\". \"Komm hisch her, ich muss dir was zeige.\" One of the basic locative markers, frequently fused into verbs: \"hischehn\" (to be here), \"hischehauen\" (to hit toward here). Also central in Palatine directional behavior. A characteristic vowel flattening — \"ie\" becomes \"i\", which makes the language quicker and more direct.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-028": "The Schuachplattler is the traditional folk dance in which the lads rhythmically slap their shoes, knees and thighs. A highlight of every traditional-costume festival in Tyrol.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-028": "The Kerb is the church consecration festival, the biggest village fête with music, dancing and Schwenker (grilled marinated meat). A highlight of the Saarland festival calendar, often celebrated over several days.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-028": "Ebbe un Floot, the constant alternation of the tides, governs life on the coast. Nach Ebbe kummt Floot (after the ebb comes the flood) is also a consoling proverb for bad times.",
  "badisch.bad-028": "Es Trottwar is the pavement (sidewalk), from the French trottoir. A nice example of the many French influences in the Baden vocabulary near the border.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-028": "huara is a crude but very common intensifier in the sense of \"extremely\" or \"very\". Huara guat means \"really good\". Ubiquitous among younger people.",
  "steirisch.st-028": "tschinageln means to work hard and persistently, to toil. Den ganzen Tag tschinageln means to slog away all day. An expressive Austrian word.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-028": "Da Bua is the boy or young man, plural Buabm. Also used as an appreciative form of address among men. A central Bavarian word.",
  "thueringisch.th-028": "schwätzn means to talk or to chat. Die zwee schwätzn schon den ganzen Tag (those two have been chatting all day). An everyday verb of Thuringian speech.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-028": "De Sünn is the sun. Wenn de Sünn schient, sitt man giern an Strand (when the sun shines, you like to sit on the beach). A friendly nature word of the Low German dialect.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-028": "kieken means to look or to watch. Kiek mal! means \"look!\". Inseparable from the famous Icke, dette, kieke mal. A Low German legacy.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-028": "D Sunna is the sun. Wenn d Sunna scheint, sitzt ma gern vor da Zoiglstubn (when the sun shines, you like to sit in front of the Zoigl tavern). A friendly nature word of the Bavarian dialect.",
  "hessisch.h-042": "Someone who is constantly lost in thought elsewhere and overlooks what is right in front of them. The term comes from Struwwelpeter by Heinrich Hoffmann — the character \"Hans Guck-in-die-Luft\" walks into the river because he is not paying attention. In Frankfurt this figure is common cultural property.",
  "berlinisch.b-039": "Berlin contraction of \"in die\" or \"in der\" — \"inne Stadt\" means \"into town\" or \"in town\". This merging of preposition and article is typical of fast Berlin speech. \"inne Kneipe\", \"inne U-Bahn\" and \"inne Schule\" are also common forms.",
  "bayerisch.by-042": "A chronically ill-tempered person who grumbles about everything and is never satisfied. The Grantler is a fixed figure of the Bavarian folk character — half insult, half affectionate portrait. Closely related to \"grantig\" (grumpy). \"Alter Grantler!\" is often more a characterization than an insult.",
  "saechsisch.s-033": "The Saxon variant of \"kommandieren\" (to command) shows the classic consonant softening: the hard \"k\" becomes a soft \"g\". Someone who \"gommandiert\" gives orders or bosses people around too much. \"Hör uff zu gommandieren!\" is a typical objection to an overly bossy fellow.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-035": "A \"Hockerla\" is a small, stocky little man — often used for a garden gnome, a wooden figure, or as a jocular term for a small, chubby person. The word derives from hocken (to crouch) and describes the typical pose of these squat figures. In Swabian folk tales such Hockerla like to play tricks.",
  "koelsch.k-038": "A polite Cologne formula of apology — one asks permission or politely apologizes for a direct statement that is about to follow. \"Met Verlaub, dat stimmt nit!\" introduces a matter-of-fact objection. It is one of the phrases that show how Kölsch, despite its directness, places great value on politeness.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-037": "\"Anker liggen\" means that a ship is at anchor — it has dropped its anchor and lies quietly on the water. Figuratively, in the North one says of someone who has settled down or does not move on: \"He liggt ankert.\" It is an image of settledness and steadfastness.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-034": "The Swiss German word for \"today\" — short, clear, Alemannic. \"Was machsch hüt?\" (What are you doing today?) is the most common everyday question. The word shows the characteristic sound change of Swiss German: the High German \"heute\" becomes \"hüt\" through a vowel shift. Together with \"morn\" (tomorrow) and \"gester\" (yesterday) it forms the temporal framework.",
  "wienerisch.w-034": "The Manner wafer slices are Vienna's best-known confectionery product — thin wafer layers with a hazelnut cream filling, in the characteristic pink packaging. They have been made in Vienna since 1898; the factory was at Stephansplatz (today in Hernals). They are the unofficial souvenir snack for every Vienna visitor and as much a staple in Austrian supermarkets as bread.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-032": "A Franconian (and generally folksy) term for a strict, quarrelsome housewife who makes her husband's life difficult. The dragon as a mythical creature stands here for terror and unpredictability. Today dated and with sexist connotations, but still known in regional vernacular.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-034": "In the Ruhr region the scrapyard is not just a place for disposal but a cultural symbol of industrial transformation. Whole steelworks, collieries and machines ended up on scrapyards after the mines closed, or were converted into industrial monuments. In everyday Ruhrpott life the scrapyard is the place where you get cheap car parts.",
  "alemannisch.al-032": "\"Chüngel\" is the Alemannic and Swiss German word for rabbit. It derives from the Latin \"cuniculus\" and is a fine example of the Alemannic preservation of old loanwords. At the market and in dialect poems the Chüngel appears often — a lovable animal in Alemannic folk culture.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-029": "s'\"Naachbarschaftsfest\" — the traditional summer festival of a street or neighborhood, often with wine on tap, sausages on the grill and live music. \"Naachbarn vorbeibringe, do gibt's Schorle und Wurschtbrot!\" (Bring the neighbors along, there's spritzer and sausage sandwiches!) It nurtures Palatine neighborly culture, which is very pronounced anyway. Every street holds its festival once a year, a participatory tradition across generations. It connects long-established residents with newcomers.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-029": "A Tschoch is a laborious, exhausting job. Whoever says \"des is a Tschoch\" means that something is a real hassle. An expressive word for hard drudgery.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-029": "The Schorle is wine mixed with mineral water, the standard drink at festivals. In the Saarland and the Palatinate the Schorle is part of conviviality.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-029": "De Butt is the flatfish, such as the plaice or flounder. From the fairy tale we know the Butt that grants wishes. A typical fish of the North Sea.",
  "badisch.bad-029": "Es Bähnle is the little local or narrow-gauge railway, such as the Sauschwänzlebähnle in the Black Forest. An affectionate diminutive for nostalgic trains.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-029": "A Bürle is a round bread roll or Weckle. In the morning you fetch fresh Bürle from the baker. The diminutive ending -le is typically Alemannic.",
  "steirisch.st-029": "D Haxn are the legs, singular Hax. Reiß d Haxn zsamm! (pull your legs together!) calls for proper bearing. A robust Bavarian-Styrian word for the limbs.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-029": "A Gschropp is a small child, often meant affectionately and with a wink. D Gschroppm toben durchs Haus (the kids romp through the house). A Bavarian-Carinthian family word.",
  "thueringisch.th-029": "loofen means to walk or to go on foot. Mir loofen den ganzen Weg (we walk the whole way). The pronunciation with oo instead of au is typically East Central German.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-029": "Rain falls often and abundantly on the coast. Bi Regen blifft man binnen un drinkt Tee (when it rains you stay inside and drink tea). A frequent weather word in the North.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-029": "ooch is the Berlin-Brandenburg \"auch\" (also), with the drawn-out oo. Ick will ooch mit! means \"I want to come too!\". A typical phonetic feature.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-029": "Da Baam is the tree, plural Baam. Unter am Baam findt ma im Summa Schattn (under a tree you find shade in summer). A common nature word of the North Bavarian region.",
  "hessisch.h-043": "\"Es is zum de Erbarme\" — a dramatic Hessian exaggeration for a pitiful state. The word describes something so bad or sad that one can only feel pity. The Hessian dialect coloring gives the expression a special emotional depth.",
  "berlinisch.b-040": "The Arabic word for \"my dearest\" or \"my friend\" has become a general expression of friendship in Berlin — especially in Neukölln and Kreuzberg. Berlin-Arabic slang that is now used by all population groups. A sign of Berlin's multicultural urban culture.",
  "bayerisch.by-043": "Describes a foul, irritable mood — someone who is \"grantig\" does not want to be disturbed and finds fault with everything. The adjective is ubiquitous in Bavarian everyday life and is regarded as an honest expression of feeling. \"I bin heut grantig\" is a warning that is taken seriously.",
  "saechsisch.s-034": "A coarse Saxon term for the head — stronger than \"Gubber\", but rarely truly malicious. \"Pass uff mit dem Nischel!\" warns against a collision. The word also appears in the phrase \"Nischel einziehen\" (to duck one's head). In cabaret shows of the GDR era \"Nischel\" was a popular stylistic device.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-036": "The Swabian pronunciation of \"Schweiß\" (sweat) — the \"ei\" is shifted to \"oa\", which is typical of the Alemannic sound system. After hard work or sport the Swabian says: \"I bin ganz verschwetzt!\" — and the Schwoaß stands on the brow. Physical work and honest Schwoaß are seen as a sign of diligence.",
  "koelsch.k-039": "The Cologne \"prima\" (great) expresses agreement and enthusiasm — it sounds upbeat and positive. People from Cologne are known for their joie de vivre and their ability to see the good in things. \"Prima!\" as an answer to good news is short, warm and typically Cologne.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-038": "Karnüffel is one of the oldest known card games in the world — first mentioned in 1426 in southern Germany, but played in northern Germany well into the 20th century. It was the game of ordinary people: miners, sailors and farmers. The cards had fixed rankings, and the game was known for its \"Karnüffel\" — the most powerful card.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-035": "The Swiss German word for \"tomorrow\" — formed by shortening the High German \"Morgen\". \"Morn früe\" means \"tomorrow morning\", \"morn Abig\" means \"tomorrow evening\". Not to be confused with morning as a time of day, which is also called \"Morge\" in Swiss German. The shortening is typical of the economy of the Alemannic dialect.",
  "wienerisch.w-035": "The Fiaker is the traditional Viennese horse-drawn carriage — a two- or four-wheeled vehicle pulled by two horses and steered by the bearded Fiaker coachman in a top hat. Fiaker have been driving through Vienna since the 17th century and today are mainly a tourist attraction around Stephansplatz. The term \"Fiaker\" also referred to a particular strong black coffee with schnapps.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-033": "In Franconian, a \"Schbundl\" refers to an untidy, sloppy or slovenly person. The word sounds coarse and is used accordingly. It can allude to a messy way of working or a careless appearance. In context, it is a moderately strong insult.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-035": "Mülheim an der Ruhr is a city in the southern Ruhr area, located right on the Ruhr. It is known for the Witthausbusch recreation area, the Theater an der Ruhr and a somewhat more bourgeois atmosphere. By Ruhr-area standards, the people of Mülheim are considered a bit more sedate — which often leads to friendly mockery.",
  "alemannisch.al-033": "The Bächlein (also Bächle) are a characteristic feature of Freiburg im Breisgau: narrow water channels that flow through the old town. In the Middle Ages they served as firefighting water and for waste disposal. Today they are a popular meeting spot in summer — children play in them, and according to local legend, anyone who steps into one must marry a Freiburger.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-030": "\"Pfia di\" — a Palatine farewell formula related to the Bavarian-Austrian forms. \"Pfia di, mer sähn uns am Wengerdfest!\" (\"Bye, see you at the vineyard festival!\"). Shortened from \"behüt dich Gott\" (\"may God protect you\"), similar to the Bavarian \"Pfiat di\". In the Palatinate it is often imbued with extra warmth — \"Pfia di, du Lieber\", \"Pfia dich, alde Freund\". It is also used as a greeting, depending on tone and region. A versatile, heartfelt farewell.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-030": "heuer means \"this year\" and is widespread throughout the southern German-Austrian region. The counterpart for last year is fern or firn.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-030": "uffbasse means to pay attention or to take care. The warning \"bass uff!\" means \"watch out!\". A common verb in everyday life and in traffic.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-030": "sutje (also sachte) means slowly, carefully, with calm. Sutje an means to approach something at a leisurely pace — fitting for the laid-back coastal mentality.",
  "badisch.bad-030": "hocke in Badisch simply means to sit, not just to crouch. Mir hocke zsamme means \"we are sitting together\". A central verb of sociable gatherings.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-030": "Dr Bsuach is the visit/the visitors. When Bsuach comes, the table is laid generously, because hospitality is held in high regard in the Ländle. Auf Bsuach goh means to visit someone.",
  "steirisch.st-030": "D Goschn is the mouth, often in the sense of cheeky talking. Hoit dei Goschn! means \"be quiet\". A robust everyday word of the Bavarian-speaking region.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-030": "heuer means \"this year\". Heuer is da See warm means: this year the lake is warm. Used throughout the Austrian region.",
  "thueringisch.th-030": "horchen means to listen or to hark. Horch ma! means \"listen!\". A verb of paying ear common in the Thuringian-Saxon region.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-030": "De Boom is the tree, plural Bööm. Ünner den Boom find man Schatten (under the tree one finds shade). A Low German word that appears in many place names.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-030": "allet means everything. Allet jut! means \"all good!\". One of the most common words of the Berlin-Brandenburg vernacular, often combined with jut.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-030": "Wåssa is the water, with the dark North Bavarian a. A Glasl Wåssa zum Zoigl schadt ned (a glass of water with the Zoigl beer doesn't hurt). An everyday basic word.",
  "hessisch.h-044": "A stubborn, unyielding person who won't change their mind — like a battering ram (Rammbock), a heavy beam used to break down gates. The word expresses a combination of obstinacy and force. \"Du bist en richticher Rammbock!\" is criticism and respect at once.",
  "berlinisch.b-041": "A coarse Berlin swear word for a repulsive or unfriendly face. \"Bratze\" is Berlin slang for face (from the Low German word), and \"Kack-\" intensifies the negative character. It is shouted in arguments or out of frustration — not for the faint of heart.",
  "bayerisch.by-045": "The Bavarian short form of the name Matthias — a very typical Bavarian first name. The \"Hias\" often stands as a representative of the down-to-earth, rural Bavarian par excellence. In literature and folk theater he appears as the type of the honest, somewhat naive countryman.",
  "saechsisch.s-035": "The Kaffeeklatsch is far more than just drinking coffee in Saxony — it is a social ritual with a fixed time of day (usually 3 p.m.), home-baked cake and extensive gossip. Saxons have one of the oldest coffeehouse cultures in Germany, and drinking coffee together connects generations. Without a Kaffeeklatsch, the Sunday afternoon is incomplete.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-037": "A lively, restless child who is constantly on the move — a real whirlwind. Through its onomatopoeia, the word itself sounds like a whirl and perfectly describes the spirited, sometimes annoying bustle of small children. Swabian grandmothers shake their heads and say: \"So a Schnurrdiburr!\"",
  "koelsch.k-040": "The Kölsch demonstrative pronoun \"dat\" corresponds to the standard German \"das\". It is one of the most common words in Kölsch and runs through every situation in life: \"dat Kölsch\", \"dat Wetter\", \"dat es nix\". The spelling with \"d-a-t\" is characteristic of Ripuarian and distinguishes it from other German dialects.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-039": "The motto of Schleswig-Holstein — in Low German — literally means \"Wide heart, free Kimming (horizon)\". It expresses the North German mentality: openness, a sense of freedom and a gaze into the distance. The \"Kimming\" is the nautical term for the horizon at sea. The saying appears on the state coat of arms and is the life motto of many North Germans.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-036": "The Swiss German word for \"now\" — short and to the point. \"Chum jitz!\" means \"Come now!\" and leaves no doubt about the urgency. In Zurich German you also often hear \"jetzt\" (borrowed from standard German), but in many other cantons \"jitz\" is the natural word. It is one of those little words that instantly reveal whether someone is really Swiss.",
  "wienerisch.w-036": "The Ringstraße is Vienna's most famous boulevard — laid out in 1857 by Emperor Franz Joseph I to replace the medieval city walls. Along it stand the Opera, the Kunsthistorisches Museum, Parliament, the City Hall and the Burgtheater. Franz Joseph wanted to make Vienna the most magnificent capital in Europe. \"Ringstraßenepoche\" today denotes a style of exuberant historicist splendor.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-034": "In Franconian, \"gehen\" (to go) is often replaced by \"laafm\" (to run/walk), as in other German dialects. \"Ich geh laafm\" does not mean that one runs, but simply that one goes on foot. Typical of many dialects in which \"laufen\" carries the general meaning of moving about.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-036": "The blast furnace (Hochofen) is the symbol of the steel industry and stands for the second pillar of the Ruhr area alongside mining. In Duisburg, Dortmund and Bochum, blast furnaces shaped the cityscape for decades. Many of these industrial monuments have been preserved, such as the blast furnaces in the Landschaftspark Duisburg-Nord.",
  "alemannisch.al-034": "\"Heimelig\" in Alemannic and Swiss German means roughly cozy, homely or comfortable. It is a typically Alemannic word and expresses a deep sense of well-being and security. The English term \"homely\" may have been influenced by it. A heimelig parlor is warm, cozy and inviting.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-031": "Da \"Riesling\" — the most famous Palatine white wine variety, with aromas of green apple, peach and mineral freshness. \"A trockener Pfälzer Riesling zum Spargel, des is Sommer pur.\" (\"A dry Palatine Riesling with asparagus, that's summer pure.\") The Palatinate is Germany's second-largest growing region for Riesling, world-famous with vineyards such as Forster Jesuitengarten, Wachenheimer Belz and Deidesheimer Hohenmorgen. Spätlese, Auslese, Beerenauslese — a variation for every occasion.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-031": "A Fleck is a warm woollen or carriage blanket with which one covers oneself on the bench or in the sleigh. A practical word from rural everyday life.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-031": "The Grub is the coal mine that shaped the region over generations. Those who worked \"uff da Grub\" worked underground. A central word of Saarland's industrial history.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-031": "De Lepel is the spoon. In the tea ceremony it plays a special role: if you place the Lepel in the cup, you politely signal that you are full and no longer want any tea.",
  "badisch.bad-031": "Wii is the wine, omnipresent in Baden — from the Markgräfler Gutedel to the Kaiserstuhl Spätburgunder. Es Viertele Wii (a quarter-litre of wine) is part of the Badisch way of life.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-031": "D Muotter is the mother. She holds the family together and cooks the Käsknöpfle. Together with Vatter, one of the most important family words in the Ländle.",
  "steirisch.st-031": "Erdäpfel are potatoes, the Austrian word. Erdäpfelsalat with pumpkin seed oil is a Styrian specialty. The basis of many down-to-earth dishes.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-031": "A Buschenschank is the tavern of a farmer or winegrower serving their own wine, must and cold platters. The hung-out bunch of twigs (Buschen) shows that it is open.",
  "thueringisch.th-031": "meckern means to grumble or to constantly find fault with something. Der meckert über alles (he grumbles about everything). A widespread word for grouchy behavior.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-031": "De Katt is the cat, which makes itself comfortable by the warm stove. De Katt fangt de Müüs (the cat catches the mice). A common Low German animal word.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-031": "nüscht means nothing. Da is nüscht zu machen means \"there's nothing to be done\". A common word of the region that reveals its Low German origin.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-031": "D Muich is the milk, with the typical pronunciation. Frische Muich hoit ma vom Bauern (you get fresh milk from the farmer). A staple food of the rural Upper Palatinate.",
  "hessisch.h-045": "Someone who spoils others' joy and fun — a spoilsport. The word is common throughout the German-speaking world, but in Hesse it has a particular sharpness. You fend off a spoilsport in Hessian style: \"Babbel net rum und mach mit!\" (Stop yapping and join in!).",
  "berlinisch.b-042": "The Berlin \"g → j\" in full effect: \"gut\" becomes \"jut\". A word that demonstrates the entire Berlin sound shift. \"Alles jut?\" is the Berlin form of \"Alles gut?\" (All good?) — the friendly everyday question with which you greet someone in the Kiez.",
  "bayerisch.by-046": "The Bavarian forms for father and mother — \"Voda\" and \"Muada\". These old terms are characteristic of the Upper Bavarian dialect and sound familiar and warm. Especially in rural areas these forms are still alive and are preferred over the standard German \"Papa\" and \"Mama\".",
  "saechsisch.s-036": "The Dresden Christstollen is known worldwide and has enjoyed EU-wide protection as a geographical indication since 2010. It is baked from yeast dough with raisins, almonds, candied lemon peel and plenty of butter, and dusted with icing sugar after baking. The Dresden Stollen Festival during Advent, in which a giant stollen is carried through the old town, is a cultural highlight of the city.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-038": "In Swabian, \"g'scheit\" primarily means sensible, judicious and wise — not merely intelligent. \"Sei g'scheit!\" is a call to reason, not a compliment on one's education. A g'scheit person does nothing foolish, thinks ahead and acts prudently. It is one of the most important adjectives in the Swabian value system.",
  "koelsch.k-041": "The Cologne \"och\" is the equivalent of standard German \"auch\" (also) and appears in countless sentences. \"Kumm och met!\" (Come along too!) or \"dat well ich och!\" (I want that too!) are typical expressions. \"Och\" can also be used as a filler word or as a mild affirmation: \"Och ja\" — a gentle agreement without much enthusiasm.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-040": "A North German wisdom that recalls the experience of seafarers: the weather turns, plans change, nothing is guaranteed. The short saying expresses sober realism and at the same time a certain composure — you make the best of whatever comes. \"Nix is fix\" (Nothing is fixed) is a philosophy of life in three words.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-037": "The Swiss German verb for \"to go\" — pronounced short and open. \"Ich gah\" (I go), \"er gaat\" (he goes), \"mir gönd\" (we go). The conjugation differs markedly from standard German. \"Gah go luege\" (go and look) is a typical construction: two infinitives together, which would be ungrammatical in German but sound entirely natural in Swiss German.",
  "wienerisch.w-037": "To \"go to the Heuriger\" means to visit a wine tavern on the outskirts of Vienna — in Grinzing, Heiligenstadt or Stammersdorf, where vintners serve their new wine themselves. With it comes a cold Jause: Liptauer cheese, bread, ham. A fir branch on the gate indicates that the Heuriger is open. This culture is a UNESCO World Heritage and part of the Viennese soul.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-036": "In Franconian, \"Seggendorf\" (sometimes also \"Hinterdupfing\" or similar) jokingly stands for a small, insignificant village somewhere out in the sticks. It is an expression of remoteness and insignificance — a place no one has heard of. Today it is mostly used humorously.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-037": "The steelworks were, alongside the coal mine, the most important employer in the Ruhr region. Krupp in Essen and the Hoesch ironworks in Dortmund employed tens of thousands of workers. The closure of the steelworks in the 1980s meant an existential crisis for many families and shaped the social history of the Ruhrpott.",
  "alemannisch.al-035": "In Alemannic, \"feschd\" means both the adjective \"fest\" (firm/solid) and, as an adverb, \"very\" or \"really\". \"Des haut feschd nei\" means \"That really packs a punch\". As an intensifier it shows the Alemannic penchant for directness and emphasis. People also say \"feschd feiern\" for celebrating exuberantly.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-032": "The \"Spundekäs\" — a Palatine cheese spread made from quark, onions, paprika and spices, often served on pretzels or bread. \"Beim Weinfest gibt's immer Spundekäs mit a frische Brezel!\" (At the wine festival there's always Spundekäs with a fresh pretzel!). Creamy, savoury, with the typical orange colour from the paprika. A speciality of the entire Rhine-Main region, but especially popular in the Palatinate and in Mainz. A classic accompaniment to the Schoppen (wine).",
  "tirolerisch.ti-032": "\"zach\" describes something tough or arduous, whether a tough piece of meat or a tiresome matter that drags on endlessly. A versatile everyday word.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-032": "The \"Hütt\" is the iron and steelworks, alongside the \"Grub\" (mine) the region's most important employer. The Völklinger Hütt is today a World Heritage Site. A key word of the Saarland.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-032": "\"leep\" means bad, wicked or evil. \"Dat is leep\" means that's awful. An old Low German word for an unpleasant situation.",
  "badisch.bad-032": "\"schaffe\" means to work. \"Schaffe, schaffe, Häusle baue\" (work, work, build a little house) describes the proverbial diligence of the south-west. Whoever schaffts achieves something worthwhile.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-032": "\"Dr Vatter\" is the father. He works, toils on the farm or in the business. Together with \"Muotter\" (mother) and the children he forms the Alemannic family.",
  "steirisch.st-032": "\"Paradeiser\" are tomatoes, the Austrian word derived from \"Paradiesapfel\" (paradise apple). Fresh Paradeiser come from one's own garden into the salad in summer.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-032": "\"a so\" is a frequent exclamation of understanding or astonishment, something like \"ah, I see\" or \"really\". Drawn out in tone, it conveys Carinthian cosiness.",
  "thueringisch.th-032": "\"weeßte\" is the slurred form of \"weißt du\" (you know) and often introduces a sentence. \"Weeßte was?\" means \"you know what?\". Typical of the rapid pronunciation.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-032": "\"Dat Peerd\" is the horse, which once ploughed the fields. Mecklenburg is known for its horse breeding. An important word of the rural world.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-032": "\"koofen\" means to buy, with the typical \"oo\". \"Ick jeh koofen\" means \"I'm going shopping\". The KaDeWe is jokingly also called \"Koofhaus\" (department store).",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-032": "\"schee\" means beautiful/nice. \"Des is schee!\" is an enthusiastic compliment. \"A schee Madl\" (a pretty girl), \"a schee Landschaft\" (a beautiful landscape) — a versatile adjective.",
  "hessisch.h-046": "A worn-out, ill-fitting or thick old pair of glasses. \"Batz\" denotes in Hessian something messy, sticky or inferior. The Batzbrill is a hallmark of the eccentric old-timer or of a shabby appearance — often meant in an affectionately mocking way.",
  "berlinisch.b-043": "Stralau is a peninsula in the Berlin district of Friedrichshain-Kreuzberg — and \"Stralauer\" is an old, almost forgotten term for true natives of Berlin. In Berlin folklore the Stralauer fisherman is regarded as the archetype of the original Berliner, before the big city arrived.",
  "bayerisch.by-047": "Colloquial Bavarian term for one's own wife (Oide) or husband (Oider) — literally \"the old one\". It sounds rustic and down-to-earth, but is not meant pejoratively. \"Mei Oide\" (my old lady) is an affectionate, if rough, way of speaking about one's partner.",
  "saechsisch.s-037": "The Rennsteig is the historic ridge crest of the Thuringian Forest, which once formed the border between Saxon and Franconian territories. The hiking trail along the Rennsteig is one of the best known in Germany and runs nearly 170 kilometres through dense forests. On the Rennsteig, Saxon, Thuringian and Franconian cultures meet.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-039": "The Mutschel is a traditional Swabian festive pastry in the shape of a small round roll or a pretzel. Especially on Epiphany and during the carnival season, the Mutschel was used as a lucky symbol in a dice game — whoever won got it. Today the Mutschel is still available as a bakery product in some regions.",
  "koelsch.k-042": "The Cologne \"nit\" corresponds to standard German \"nicht\" (not) — short, clear and unmistakable. \"Dat geiht nit\" (that won't do), \"ich well nit\" (I don't want to) or \"do nit hin!\" (don't go there!) are typical Cologne negations. The word is more closely related to the Dutch \"niet\" than to standard German \"nicht\" and reveals the West Germanic origin of Kölsch.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-041": "An old Low German word for someone who limps or suffers from a walking impairment — today obsolete and no longer used in a neutral sense. It appears in historical texts, fairy tales and folk songs. The Low German language preserves many such old words that have long since vanished from standard German.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-038": "The Swiss German verb for \"to come\" — the pronunciation with the soft \"ch\" at the beginning is characteristically Alemannic. \"Ich chume\" (I come), \"chum her!\" (come here!), \"er chunnt\" (he comes). The verb is indispensable in countless everyday situations. Especially typical is \"choo go\" — to come in order to: \"Chum go luege!\" (Come and look!).",
  "wienerisch.w-038": "The Viennese verb for to freeze — \"i g'frier mich\" means \"I'm freezing\". The inserted \"g'\" is typical of the Central Bavarian dialect area. In Vienna the winter can get cold, the wind from the Vienna Woods whistles through the alleys, and the Viennese complain about it verbosely. \"I g'frier mich auf den Tod\" (I'm freezing to death) is a slight exaggeration — typically Viennese.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-037": "Archaic, but still known in the Franconian language area: the \"Maid\" was the maidservant or farmhand maid on the farm. In Middle High German, \"maget\" generally denoted a virgin or unmarried woman. Today the word still appears in field names and place names.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-038": "\"Glück auf, der Steiger kommt\" (Good luck, the foreman is coming) is the best-known miners' song in Germany and the unofficial anthem of the Ruhr region. It was sung underground and played at celebrations to strengthen solidarity. The Steiger was the foreman in the mine, who oversaw safety and order.",
  "alemannisch.al-036": "The Narrenkleid (or Häs) is the traditional costume of the Alemannic Fasnet (carnival) and is often crafted by the fools' guilds from wood, fabric and handiwork. Each guild has its own unmistakable Narrenkleid with mask and cap. Putting on the Narrenkleid is a ritual and marks the transformation into the fool figure.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-033": "The \"Pfälzer Wurschdsalad\" — the famous Palatine sausage salad made from Lyoner sausage, onions, vinegar, oil, with or without cheese. \"A Pfälzer Wurschdsalad zum Mittagessen, des wärmt im Herbst.\" (A Palatine sausage salad for lunch, that warms you up in autumn.) A classic way for Palatine housewives to use up leftovers, today a standard dish in every Beischt (wine tavern). Variations: with hard cheese (\"Käsesalat\") or without (\"Strammer Max\"). With bread and Schorle (wine spritzer) a complete lunch.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-033": "The \"Goaß\" is the goat, which is kept on the steep Tyrolean slopes. The Goaßmilch (goat's milk) is processed into cheese. A common word of the mountain farmers' world.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-033": "\"naut\" means nothing and is a Moselle Franconian form that is widespread in the northern Saarland. Whoever has \"naut\" has nothing at all. The counterpart to \"ebbes\" (something).",
  "ostfriesisch.of-033": "\"De Klock\" is the clock and the time. \"Wo laat is de Klock?\" asks for the time. \"Klock teihn\" means ten o'clock. A common Low German everyday word.",
  "badisch.bad-033": "Es Bueble is the little boy, an affectionate diminutive of Bueb. The female counterpart is s Mädle. A tender family word in everyday Baden life.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-033": "Es Chind is the child, plural d Chinder. The Alemannic pronunciation with Ch is typical and closely links Vorarlberg to Swiss German.",
  "steirisch.st-033": "oba means but. Des is oba schee! means \"but that's beautiful!\". A frequent conjunction that sounds broad and drawn-out in Styrian.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-033": "Marille is the apricot, the Austrian word. From Marillen you make jam, dumplings and schnapps. A popular summer fruit.",
  "thueringisch.th-033": "Reen is the rain, with the drawn-out Thuringian pronunciation. Bei dem Reen bleibmr lieber drinne (In this rain we'd rather stay inside). A common weather word.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-033": "Dat Huus is the house, often an old brick house with a thatched roof. Na Huus gahn means to go home. A central Low German word.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-033": "Die Schnauze is the mouth, proverbial for the direct Berlin manner (Berliner Schnauze). Halt die Schnauze! means \"shut up!\". A blunt word.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-033": "oiwei means always or constantly. Der kummt oiwei z spät means \"he always comes too late\". A frequent time word in Bavarian speech.",
  "hessisch.h-047": "The plain sandwich with sausage — a classic in Hessian school bags and on building sites. The Worschtbrot embodies Hessian down-to-earthness: no haute cuisine, but honest, filling and good. With homemade sausage on fresh farmhouse bread it is a real treat.",
  "berlinisch.b-044": "A typically Berlin reaction to a statement one finds unimpressive or unfinished. „Watt nu?\" calls for a continuation or expresses indifference. It's the Berlin way of saying: \"Fine, but what's your point?\"",
  "bayerisch.by-048": "A heavy, sudden downpour — the name already sounds like the pattering of raindrops. In the Bavarian Alpine foothills strong thunderstorm rains are common, and the „Prackerer\" hits unprepared hikers and festival-goers with particular force. „Jetzt kommt a richtiger Prackerer\" is a serious weather warning.",
  "saechsisch.s-038": "The Schäferstündchen originally denoted a romantic encounter under the open sky — from the tradition of Baroque pastoral poetry. In Saxon vernacular it is used today jokingly for a short break, a midday nap or a secret hour of love. The word sounds delicate and old-fashionedly mischievous.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-040": "The „Viertel\" is ambiguous in Swabian: either the city quarter (district) or the classic measure of wine of 0.25 litres. „Auf ein Viertel gehen\" means to go and drink a glass of wine — preferably at a Besenwirtschaft. The Besenwirtschaft, where vintners serve their own wine, is Swabian cultural heritage.",
  "koelsch.k-043": "The Cologne „wann\" takes on both the function of „wenn\" (conditional) and of „wann\" (temporal) in standard German. This dual function is typical of Ripuarian and can be confusing for non-Cologne speakers at first. „Wann de küss, ruf an\" can mean either „wenn du kommst\" (if you come) or „wann du kommst\" (when you come) depending on context.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-042": "In Low German „Witsch\" is a swear word for an evil, quarrelsome or insufferable old woman — the sound is pejorative, but widespread in popular speech. Witch trials in the 16th and 17th centuries also took place in northern Germany; the term has deep historical roots. Today it is used rarely and rather jokingly.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-039": "A Schnurre is an entertaining, often slightly exaggerated story or anecdote — similar to the North German Döneken, but with Swiss German charm. Telling „en gueti Schnurre\" is an art cultivated in good company. The word is onomatopoeic — like a cat's purr or the purring of a good storyteller.",
  "wienerisch.w-039": "The Hawerer (also: Hawara) is a close friend or buddy in Viennese — a trusted person one confides in and spends time with. The term has a long history and appears in Viennese song lyrics and literature. It is warmer than „Bekannter\" (acquaintance) and more informal than „Freund\" (friend) — the Hawerer is the one you tell everything.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-038": "The Knecht was the male worker on the farm, the counterpart to the Maid. In the trades, a journeyman is sometimes still called „Knecht\" in old expressions. The word lives on in figures such as Knecht Ruprecht (companion of St Nicholas), who plays an important role in Franconian customs.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-039": "The coal dust is the dark, literal legacy of Ruhr mining: it settled on windows, laundry and lungs. Many miners fell ill with silicosis, the dreaded dust lung. Today the coal dust has disappeared, but it stands symbolically for the hard labour and the health sacrifices of the miners.",
  "alemannisch.al-037": "The Fasnet (also Fasnacht or Fastnacht) is the Alemannic counterpart to the Rhenish carnival and differs greatly in style and tradition. The Swabian-Alemannic Fasnet is older, more original and less politically satirical than the Cologne carnival. It begins on Schmutziger Donnerstag and ends with the Funkenfeuer on Funkensonntag.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-034": "„Hawwl\" — Palatine adjective for shabby, worn-out, untidy. „Des Auto schaut a wenig hawwl aus, oder?\" (The car looks a bit shabby, doesn't it?) Used for both objects and people. From the Middle High German stem, related to „Lümmel\" or „Stümper\". An affectionate term with an ironic character. Intensified: „A ganz hawwliger Bursch\" (a pretty shabby fellow).",
  "tirolerisch.ti-034": "A Tschegg is originally a piebald ox, but is also used mockingly for a clumsy or simple-minded person. A vivid Tyrolean swear word.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-034": "Eppel refers to apples or, in the dialect, also to potatoes; regionally the term denotes a hearty salad served as a side dish. Such compounds with Eppel are widespread in Saarland.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-034": "Tied is time. Ik heff keen Tied means \"I have no time\". Bi de Theetied one deliberately takes Tied. A central word of the relaxed coastal mentality.",
  "badisch.bad-034": "Spätzle are the scraped or pressed egg noodles, a pillar of Baden-Swabian cuisine. Fresh Spätzle go with roast meat, lentils or as Kässpätzle (cheese spaetzle).",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-034": "Es Wätter is the weather, often changeable in the mountains. Bei schö Wätter you go hiking, bei schlecht Wätter you stay home. A common nature word.",
  "steirisch.st-034": "leiwand means great, fantastic or super. Des war leiwand! is an enthusiastic praise. Originally Viennese slang, today widespread throughout Austria.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-034": "Powidl is plum spread cooked down without sugar, used in Powidltascherl (plum dumplings) or on bread. Figuratively, des is mir powidl also means \"I don't care\".",
  "thueringisch.th-034": "Kraut is the cabbage, above all the sauerkraut served with the Bratel (roast). Kraut un Kließ are part of the Thuringian Sunday meal.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-034": "De Disch is the table at which the family sits and eats. Den Disch decken means to set the table. An everyday furniture word.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-034": "Die Eckkneipe is the simple local pub on the street corner, where you drink your beer and your Molle. A piece of Berlin-Brandenburg conviviality.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-034": "S Ohrwaschl is the ear. Schreib da des hinter d Ohrwaschl means to memorise something well. A vivid Bavarian body word.",
  "hessisch.h-048": "The Hessian pronunciation of „Geist\" — with a soft „ei\" and a voiced ending. Denotes both the human mind and ghosts and spectral apparitions. In rural Hessian folklore there are numerous Geischt stories about forest spirits, will-o'-the-wisps and wandering souls.",
  "berlinisch.b-045": "In Berlin speech „Typ\" is very frequently used for any male person, similar to „Kerl\" or „Mensch\". It is value-neutral and expresses no judgement. „Kennste den Typ?\" simply asks about a person, without positive or negative evaluation.",
  "bayerisch.by-049": "The twelve nights between 25 December and 6 January — a time full of old peasant customs, oracles and legends. During the Rauhnächte the Wild Hunt is said to ride through the air, and special rules apply: no hanging out laundry, no making important decisions. Smoking the house with incense is meant to drive away evil spirits.",
  "saechsisch.s-039": "The greeting „Glückauf\" is the traditional miners' greeting and wishes the comrade that he comes back up out of the gallery safe and sound. In the Erzgebirge and the Mansfeld region the greeting is still alive today — and is used at festivities, club meetings and sometimes even as a table greeting. The Saxon pronunciation softens the „k\" to a „g\".",
  "schwaebisch.sw-041": "The Swabian phrase „auf d'Nacht\" means „am Abend\" (in the evening) or „heute Abend\" (this evening) — a lovely linking of a time reference and the approaching darkness. „Was isch auf d'Nacht?\" asks about supper. It shows how the Swabian language expresses everyday things poetically.",
  "koelsch.k-044": "The „Kaygass\" — from „Katze\" (cat) and „Gasse\" (alley) — is a narrow, winding alley in the old fabric of Cologne. Cologne has many such historic alleys in the old town, which still reveal the medieval layout of the city. The term is also used for any confusingly narrow street.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-043": "The childlike, colloquial word for urinating — widespread throughout northern Germany and having passed into all German regions. It is one of the words from Low German that have become established in standard German without many people knowing it. For children it is the normal word, for adults rather the jocular expression.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-040": "„Goofe\" is the Lucerne word for children — affectionate, slightly onomatopoeic and unmistakably Central Swiss. Outside Central Switzerland many Swiss know the word, but only people from Lucerne and Central Switzerland use it in everyday life. „Die Goofe mached en Lärm!\" (The kids are making a racket!) sounds indulgent despite the complaint.",
  "wienerisch.w-040": "A colloquial Viennese term, today often perceived as derogatory, for a motley music band or group that plays loud, folksy music. The term reflects Vienna's history as a melting pot of the Danube Monarchy, where people from Bohemia, Hungary, Croatia and other crown lands came together. Today it is used mainly self-ironically or in a historical context.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-039": "The Hafenmarkt in Würzburg on the Main is a historic marketplace where pottery (Hafen = pots) was once traded. Such markets were central to economic life in the Franconian region. In Würzburg, the area by the Main is today a popular meeting place and event venue.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-040": "The Ruhr is the river that gives the Ruhr region its name. Today it is clean again and surrounded by green spaces, cycle paths and bathing lakes. The renaturation of the Ruhr shows that the Pott is long since more than coal and steel — a green leisure river right in the middle of industry.",
  "alemannisch.al-038": "The masked ball is a highlight of the Fasnet (carnival) season: a dance ball at which all participants appear in costumes and masks. In Alemannic towns and villages there are often several masked balls during the carnival season. The masked ball makes it possible to transcend social boundaries, since the mask conceals one's identity.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-035": "A „Schtremel\" — a Palatine swear word, meaning a fool or oaf. „Du Schtremel, hosch mei Schorle umgschüttet!\" (You Schtremel, you knocked over my Schorle!). It is used like the Bavarian „Damischa\" or „Dappschädel\" — usually affectionately reproachful within the family. From the Middle High German „strebel\" meaning streak/stripe. Also as a verb: „rumschtremele\" — to stumble around. Classic Palatine vocabulary.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-035": "Erdäpfel are potatoes, the Austrian word for them. From Erdäpfel one makes Knödl (dumplings), Gröstl or Erdäpfelsalat (potato salad). A staple food of Tyrolean cuisine.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-035": "schaffe means to work. In the Saarland, where the mine (Grub) and the steelworks (Hütt) shaped life, schaffe is a central concept: whoever schafft (works) achieves something.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-035": "Dat Wedder is the weather, a constant topic on the coast. Bi good Wedder geiht man na buten (in good weather you go outside), bi leep Wedder blifft man binnen (in bad weather you stay indoors). Wind and rain determine the day.",
  "badisch.bad-035": "Maultasche are large filled pasta pockets stuffed with sausage meat and spinach. Cooked in broth or pan-fried with egg, they are a popular speciality of the southwest.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-035": "Dr Reaga is the rain, which falls frequently in the Bregenzerwald. Bei Reaga zieht man d Gummistiefel a (when it rains you put on the rubber boots). An everyday weather word of the Ländle.",
  "steirisch.st-035": "heuer means „this year\" and is in common use throughout the Austrian region. Heuer war a guate Weinernte means this year's harvest was a good one.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-035": "A Palatschinke is a thin, filled pancake, sweet with jam or quark (Topfen). A dessert dish that is popular all over Austria.",
  "thueringisch.th-035": "The Bratel is the roast, the centrepiece of the Thuringian Sunday meal, with Kließ (dumplings) and Stippe (gravy). A good Bratel needs time in the oven.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-035": "De Hand is the hand, plural Hannen. Een Hand wäscht de anner (one hand washes the other) is a well-known proverb. A Low German word for a body part.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-035": "Sonnabend is Saturday, more commonly used in the east and north than Samstag. Am Sonnabend wird eingekauft und geputzt (on Saturday people shop and clean). A traditional word.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-035": "D Kerwa is the church consecration festival, the biggest village celebration with music, dancing and beer. Auf da Kerwa (at the Kerwa) the whole village gathers. A highlight of the festive calendar.",
  "hessisch.h-049": "A self-ironic term for the Hessian — often used with a wink. The Hessian knows that he sometimes comes across as stubborn, blunt and a loner, and turns it into a joke. „Ich bin halt ne echte Hesselappe\" (I'm just a real Hesselappe) is both a self-admission and a declaration of love for the homeland.",
  "berlinisch.b-046": "Schnodderigkeit is the cultivated art of Berlin directness — cheeky, quick-witted, without regard for social niceties. It is not a sign of bad manners but the famous Berlin charm. „Berliner Schnauze\" (Berlin big mouth) and Schnodderigkeit go together like a Schrippe (bread roll) and a Bulette (meatball).",
  "bayerisch.by-050": "A warning call — shortened from „Acht geben\" or „Achtung\" (pay attention/watch out). Omnipresent in Bavarian daily life: „Obacht, da is a Stufe!\" (Watch out, there's a step!) or „Gib Obacht auf dich!\" (Take care of yourself!). Also used as a warm parting phrase, to tell someone to look after themselves. Sounds immediate and authentically Bavarian.",
  "saechsisch.s-040": "Something that is „verhunzt\" is thoroughly spoiled or ruined — of poor quality or done wrong. The word derives from „Hund\" (dog) and expresses a certain indignation at the poor quality. Saxons are known for their blunt criticism: „Das ist doch verhunzt!\" (That's totally botched!) rarely has a gentle meaning.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-042": "The Swabian form of „jetzt\" (now) — with an appended „-at\" that is typical of Alemannic. „Jetzat\" sounds more urgent and emphatic than the standard German „jetzt\". Combined, it produces phrases like „jetzat aber los!\" (now get going!) or „was isch jetzat?\" (what is it now?). Over time the short form „jetzt\" has also become established, but „jetzat\" is still alive.",
  "koelsch.k-045": "Jan von Werth is one of the best-known figures of Cologne folk legend — a cavalry general of the Thirty Years' War who, as a young stable boy, courted the girl Griet, who rejected him. When he returned as a commander, Griet had fallen into poverty. „Jan, wärst de bliva!\" (Jan, if only you had stayed!) has been called out ever since as a reminder to seize one's chances. A fountain on the Alter Markt commemorates him.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-044": "The Dutt is the hair bun tied at the nape of the neck — also known as „Dutt\" in standard German, but the word comes from Low German. In the past, fisherwomen and farmwomen wore their Dutt as a practical hairstyle while working. Today the Dutt is fashionable and equally popular among men and women.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-041": "A „Fäger\" is someone who enthuses, who carries others along, who has a strong personality — a great guy or a great person. The word comes from the verb „fäge\" (to sweep, to make a strong impression) and expresses admiration. „Was en Fäger!\" (What a Fäger!) is a genuine compliment in German-speaking Switzerland, especially in youth slang. It is positive and enthusiastic — it is not usual to use it ironically.",
  "wienerisch.w-041": "A „Grantscherbn\" is a person who is always grumpy — that is, grumbles, grouses, scolds — a typically Viennese character study. „Grantig sein\" means to be sullen or grouchy; the Grantscherbn has elevated this state to a permanent condition. Vienna has a long tradition of famous grumblers: the Viennese Grantscherbn complains about the weather, the government and the youth — and does so with great rhetorical relish.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-040": "The Nuremberg Christkindlesmarkt is one of the best-known and oldest Christmas markets in the world, first documented in 1628. The Christkind as the market's opener — a blonde, crowned figure — is a unique feature of Nuremberg. The market on the Hauptmarkt attracts two million visitors every year.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-041": "The Halden are the artificial hills made from the spoil of mining — the barren rock that accumulated during coal extraction. In the flat Ruhr region the Halden are sometimes the only elevations and have been transformed into vantage points and art projects. The Halde Hoheward and the Halde Haniel are well-known examples.",
  "alemannisch.al-039": "The Narrenzunft (fools' guild) is the organised association of the Fasnet fools in Alemannic towns and villages. It preserves the tradition of the fool's costume, the fool figures and the Fasnet customs from year to year. In old towns such as Rottweil, Überlingen or Villingen there are Narrenzünfte that look back over centuries.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-036": "s'„Hambacher Schloss\" — the former castle in the Palatinate, cradle of German democracy. „Beim Hambacher Schloss is jedes Jahr a großes Fest.\" (There is a big festival at the Hambach Castle every year.). In 1832 the Hambach Festival took place here — 30,000 people demanded German unity and democracy under the black-red-gold flag. Today it is a museum and tourist magnet in the Wengerd-Land (wine country). A symbol of the Palatinate's liberal tradition.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-036": "Paradeiser are tomatoes, a typically Austrian word derived from Paradiesapfel (paradise apple). Fresh Paradeiser come from one's own garden in summer.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-036": "De Bub is the boy or son. Mei Bub means my son. Together with Mädsche (girl), it is the common word pair for children in Saarland family life.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-036": "De Storm is the storm, often associated with storm surges on the North Sea. Bi Storm bleibt man besser an Land (in a storm it's better to stay on land). A word that describes the rough side of the coast.",
  "badisch.bad-036": "Bredle are the small Christmas cookies baked during Advent. Every family has its own Bredle recipes for cinnamon stars and the like.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-036": "D Sunna is the sun. Wenn d Sunna scht (when the sun shines), one likes to sit by the lake. A friendly word that heralds the warm season at Lake Constance.",
  "steirisch.st-036": "D Jause is the cold snack in the mid-morning or afternoon, often with bread, bacon and cheese. A hearty Jause is part of any excursion.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-036": "A Germknödel is a fluffy yeast dumpling filled with Powidl (plum jam) and topped with vanilla sauce and poppy seeds. A warm dessert dish, often served in the ski hut.",
  "thueringisch.th-036": "aamol means once or just, often as a prompt. Komm aamol her! means „come here for a moment!\". A frequent flavouring word of Thuringian speech.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-036": "eten means to eat. Wat gifft dat to eten? asks what there is to eat. Dat Eten is also the meal itself. A central everyday verb.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-036": "The Kiez is the familiar residential neighbourhood with its shops and neighbours. Im Kiez kennt man sich (in the Kiez everyone knows each other). A central word of Berlin-Brandenburg identity.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-036": "dees is the North Bavarian word for „das\" (that) or „dieses\" (this). Dees do mecht i means „I want that one there\". A frequent demonstrative word of the dialect.",
  "hessisch.h-050": "Originally a children's soup specialty with alphabet noodles — but figuratively also a jumble of words or unintelligible gibberish. \"Des is ja alles nur Buchstabensupp\" means that something is confusing and makes no sense. In Hesse, a humorous way to dismiss something complicated.",
  "berlinisch.b-047": "The Berlin form of \"ich kenne das\" (I know that) — with the typical case mix-up (dit instead of det) and the Berlin \"ick\". Often used to express agreement or sympathy: \"Ick kenn dit!\" means \"I know exactly what you mean!\" or \"I know that too!\".",
  "bayerisch.by-051": "In Bavarian, the \"Hawara\" is the close friend, the loyal companion. The word probably stems from the Hebrew \"chaver\" (companion) and entered Bavarian via Rotwelsch (thieves' cant). \"Mei Hawara\" is said affectionately about someone you trust. Unlike the plain \"Freund\" (friend), \"Hawara\" carries a warm, comradely tone.",
  "saechsisch.s-041": "A Saxon insult for someone who behaves especially stupidly or recklessly. The combination of \"knallen\" (in the sense of loud, conspicuous) and \"Depp\" (dimwit) makes for a forceful insult. In everyday Saxon, it sounds somewhat softer through the dialect than in standard German — but the meaning is unmistakable.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-043": "In Swabian, the \"Räpple\" is the smallest amount of money — comparable to the Rappen in Switzerland. To have \"kein Räpple\" means to be completely broke. Swabians are known for their thriftiness, and the Räpple is the symbol of this virtue. \"Jedes Räpple umdrehen\" (to turn over every Räpple) stands for utmost frugality.",
  "koelsch.k-046": "The Cologne question \"Wievill Uhr es et?\" (What time is it?) shows the typical sound structure of Ripuarian: \"Uhr\" remains almost unchanged, \"es et\" (ist es / is it) shows the merging of verb and pronoun. People from Cologne ask this question directly and without fuss — time is precious in Cologne too, even if during Carnival it sometimes seems to stand still.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-045": "Grütze is, on the one hand, a traditional grain porridge made from oats, barley or buckwheat — North German home cooking. On the other hand, in the North \"Grütze\" stands for brains: \"Hast du Grütze im Kopf?\" means \"Are you clever?\" The Rote Grütze is a North German dessert of red berries with cream, which is now popular far beyond the North.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-042": "The Zürichberg is the wooded ridge east of the city of Zurich — and one of the most exclusive residential areas in Switzerland. Villas, embassies and wealthy families shape its image. \"Am Züriberg wohne\" (to live on the Zürichberg) is a status symbol. In common parlance, the word stands for wealth, aloofness and Zurich's social elite.",
  "wienerisch.w-042": "The Viennese \"ned\" is the negation particle — shorter, softer and more melodious than the standard German \"nicht\". It appears in nearly every other sentence: \"des is ned wahr\" (that's not true), \"i mag ned\" (I don't want to), \"bitte ned!\" (please don't!). The Viennese negation never sounds hard or harsh, always slightly melodic — that's the difference between Viennese charm and North German directness.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-041": "Hans Sachs (1494–1576) was the most famous Nuremberg Meistersinger, shoemaker and poet. He wrote over 6,000 master songs, gnomic verses and farces. Richard Wagner immortalized him in the opera \"Die Meistersinger von Nürnberg\" (1868). Sachs is an emblem of Franconian civic culture, artistic sensibility and craftsmanship.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-042": "In Ruhr region slang, \"Tetra Pak\" is the jokey name for wine from a carton. Anyone in the Ruhr region who has no great expectations of their wine or is heading out to party happily reaches for Tetra Pak wine. The term is humorously self-deprecating and reflects the pragmatic attitude towards enjoyment.",
  "alemannisch.al-040": "The Schmutziger Donnerstag (also Schmotzige Donnstag or Weiberfastnacht) is the official start of the Fasnet (Carnival) in many Alemannic towns. The word \"schmutzig\" does not come from Schmutz (dirt), but from the Alemannic \"Schmotz\" (lard/fat) — it is \"Fat Thursday\", on which the Carnival feasting begins. Early in the morning, the fools start to make a racket.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-037": "\"Deidesheim\" — one of the most famous wine villages of the Palatinate, on the German Wine Route. \"In Deidesheim hot da Helmut Kohl gar die ausländische Politik empfangen\" (In Deidesheim, Helmut Kohl even received foreign politicians). Famous for top Riesling sites and wineries such as Bürklin-Wolf, Reichsrat von Buhl and Dr. Bassermann-Jordan. Drittsiegervogelschießen, almond blossom festival in spring. A romantic old town with traditional sandstone houses.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-037": "Topfen is quark (curd cheese), the basis in Austria for Topfenknödl (curd cheese dumplings), strudel and spreads. A versatile dairy product of Tyrolean cuisine.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-037": "Kinner are the children. \"Die Kinner spiele drauße\" means the children are playing outside. A common word in any Saarland household with a family.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-037": "De See is the sea, the North Sea. \"Op See gahn\" means to head out to sea. The life of the coastal dwellers has always been closely tied to the sea.",
  "badisch.bad-037": "Es Gutsle is a sweet or a cookie, a treat for in between. Grandma likes to slip the children e Gutsle. An affectionate word.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-037": "Dr Schnee (the snow) falls abundantly in the mountains in winter and tempts people to go skiing. Lots of snow means good slopes in the Montafon or the Bregenzerwald.",
  "steirisch.st-037": "A Kipferl is a curved croissant-like roll made from yeast dough, eaten for breakfast with butter and jam. The Vanillekipferl is a popular Christmas pastry.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-037": "A Häferl is a cup or mug, for example for drinking coffee. A Häferl of coffee in the morning is a must. A common Austrian word.",
  "thueringisch.th-037": "The Nischel is the head, a word common in the Thuringian-Saxon region. \"Halt den Nischel still!\" (Keep your head still!) is said jokingly. Also well known from the Karl Marx head in Chemnitz.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-037": "snacken means to talk or speak. \"Platt snacken\" means to speak Low German. De Snack is the conversation or the chatter. One of the most central Low German verbs.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-037": "jut means \"gut\" (good), with the j instead of g typical of the region. \"Allet jut!\" or \"Na denn jut!\" are everyday phrases. The initial j for g is the best-known sound feature of the dialect.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-037": "Wòld is the forest, with the dark a shifted towards o that is typical of North Bavarian (Wald becomes Wòld/Wòòld). Unlike in Central Bavarian, the l is retained. A hallmark of Upper Palatinate pronunciation.",
  "hessisch.h-054": "Eintracht Frankfurt — \"Eintracht\" or \"die Adler\" (the Eagles) for short — is the football club of the city on the Main and an object of identification for the people of Frankfurt. Founded in 1899, they play in the Deutsche Bank Park (formerly the Waldstadion). The 2022 UEFA Cup victory in Seville triggered euphoria in Frankfurt. \"SGE — Schwarz-Weiß bis zum Tod!\" (Black and white until death!) is the rallying cry.",
  "berlinisch.b-048": "The Berlin pronunciation of \"auch\" (also) — the diphthong \"au\" becomes a broad, long \"oo\". A small word with a big effect: \"Det stimmt ooch\" (That's true too) sounds unmistakably Berlin. Together with \"ick\", \"det\" and \"jut\", \"ooch\" is one of the most reliable markers of genuine Berlinese.",
  "bayerisch.by-052": "A \"Lausbua\" is a boy who gets up to mischief — but in a lovable, roguish way. The term comes from \"Laus\" (the insect) and \"Bua\" (boy), yet it does not describe a louse-ridden boy but a cheeky, lively lad with a mischievous sense of humor. In Bavaria, a certain tenderness clings to the word — Lausbubenstreiche (boyish pranks) are part of a proper Bavarian childhood.",
  "saechsisch.s-042": "A \"Kabber\" is a quarrel or a heated argument, often loud and emotional. \"Die ham einen Kabber gehabt\" means that two parties have come into conflict. The word is widespread in the Central German region and, despite its meaning, sounds almost cozy — typically Saxon in tone.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-044": "A \"Gschmäckle\" is an unpleasant aftertaste — not in the culinary sense, but figuratively: something smells fishy, has a moral blemish or seems dubious. \"Des hat a Gschmäckle\" is a typically Swabian way of expressing quiet skepticism. The word is frequently used in the political sphere.",
  "koelsch.k-047": "The \"Veedel\" is the Cologne neighborhood — and more than that: it is home, the local community, the sense of belonging. People from Cologne identify strongly with their Veedel. Whether Nippes, Ehrenfeld, Lindenthal or the Südstadt — each Veedel has its own character, its own pub and its own Carnival society. \"Mer blieve im Veedel!\" (We stay in our Veedel!) is a declaration of allegiance.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-046": "A classic North German stew: green beans, pears and bacon, often with potatoes — the sweet-salty-hearty combination is typical of North German cuisine. In Hamburg the dish is also called \"Birnen, Bohnen und Speck\" (pears, beans and bacon) and is an autumn tradition, when new beans and pears are ripe. It is modest, filling and unmistakably North German.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-043": "The Bundesplatz in Bern is the political heart of Switzerland — located in front of the Bundeshaus (Federal Palace), a place of demonstrations, the popular water fountains in summer and the Christmas market in winter. The square is a symbol of Swiss democracy. Anyone in Bern who goes \"to the Bundesplatz\" steps into the center of public life of the federal city.",
  "wienerisch.w-043": "The Viennese \"wos\" is the question word \"was\" (what) — with the typical open, slightly sung vowel of the Viennese dialect. \"Wos is des?\" (What is that?), \"wos willst du?\" (What do you want?). It never sounds aggressive, always curiously friendly. In the Viennese dialect, many standard German \"a\" sounds become an open, \"o\"-like vowel — a characteristic of the Central Bavarian dialect.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-042": "Albrecht Dürer (1471–1528) is Nuremberg's most famous son: painter, draughtsman, engraver and humanist. His self-portrait of 1500 is one of the most iconic works in the history of art. Dürer's birthplace still stands today in Nuremberg's old town and is a must-see. He links Franconian civic culture with the spirit of the Renaissance.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-043": "The Mettbrötchen is a Westphalian cult food: a bread roll topped with raw, seasoned minced pork (Mett). In the Ruhr region it is served at almost every club or family celebration. The spice mix of onions, salt, pepper and caraway makes the Mett a regional specialty.",
  "alemannisch.al-041": "August Schneckenburger (1809–1849) is the poet of the famous Badnerlied (\"Das Badnerlied\") and one of the most important Alemannic dialect poets. Born in Taldorf (now Ravensburg), the poet wrote his songs in Swabian-Alemannic. The Badnerlied is the unofficial anthem of Baden and is sung loudly at sporting events.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-038": "D'\"Mandelblüh\" — the annual almond blossom along the German Wine Route in spring, a Palatinate natural wonder. \"Wann die Mandelblüh kummt, is die Pfalz im Paradies\" (When the almond blossom comes, the Palatinate is in paradise). It takes place in March/April, with thousands of almond trees bathed in pink and white. Almond blossom festivals in Gimmeldingen, Wachenheim, Bad Bergzabern. Now with a photo-tourist boom. An early-summer highlight in the Palatinate calendar.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-038": "Obers is whipped cream or cream. A dollop of Schlagobers goes on the coffee or the Kaiserschmarrn. A common Austrian kitchen word.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-038": "Lait are the people. \"Viel Lait wore do\" means a lot of people were there. An everyday word for people in the community.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-038": "De Strand is the sandy beach on the coast and the islands. On the beach you sit in a Strandkorb (roofed wicker beach chair). In summer, the beach attracts many visitors.",
  "badisch.bad-038": "Es Viertele is the quarter-litre glass of wine you enjoy after a day's work. Going for a Viertele is part of Baden's sociability and way of life.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-038": "Dr Senn manages the alpine pasture in summer and turns the milk into mountain cheese. The work as a Senn is hard, but it is part of Vorarlberg's tradition.",
  "steirisch.st-038": "Faschiertes is minced meat, from which you shape Faschierte Laibchen (meat patties). A basic term of Austrian cuisine, from Faschieren (putting through the mincer).",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-038": "In Austria, der Sessel is the plain chair, not the upholstered armchair. Setz di auf an Sessel means to sit down on a chair. An Austrian peculiarity.",
  "thueringisch.th-038": "Die Gusche is the mouth, often used somewhat coarsely. Halt die Gusche! means \"be quiet!\". A common word in the East Central German area, also widespread in Saxon.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-038": "suutje means gently, slowly and carefully. Man suutje! urges calm and an unhurried approach. A typically North German word for the deliberate pace.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-038": "uff is the Berlin-Brandenburg version of \"auf\" (on/open). Uffm Hof (in the yard) or mach die Tür uff (open the door) show the dulled vowel. A consistent phonetic feature of the region's colloquial speech.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-038": "Stoa is the stone, plural Stoana. The Middle High German diphthong ei appears in North Bavarian as oa, as also in Boa (leg) or hoaß (hot). A widespread basic word of the region.",
  "hessisch.h-055": "FFM is the affectionately concise abbreviation for Frankfurt am Main, the metropolis on the Main and financial capital of Germany. With its skyscrapers — \"Mainhattan\" — it offers a unique skyline. Home of the European Central Bank, Germany's largest airport and the Frankfurt Book Fair. Real Hessians often simply say \"die Stadt\" (the city) when they mean Frankfurt.",
  "berlinisch.b-049": "A Berlin exclamation of utmost astonishment or indignation — when something is so incredible that you doubt your own sanity. \"Spinnen\" in German colloquially means \"to be crazy\". The Berlin form with \"ick\" and \"gloob\" is especially expressive and conveys genuine bewilderment.",
  "bayerisch.by-053": "The Lederhosn is THE symbol of Bavarian traditional dress — made from deer or cowhide, decorated with traditional embroidery (deer motifs, oak leaves). A real pair of leather trousers is worn for decades and gains in value with every patina. The short form (above the knee) is common in Upper Bavaria, while the knee-length breeches (\"Bundhose\") are worn more in Lower Bavaria. A must at the Wiesn.",
  "saechsisch.s-043": "A complete failure or a crushing defeat — \"Debakel\" is a popular word in Saxon for sporting and everyday defeats. The word is actually a Gallicism (from French), but has firmly established itself in German and Saxon usage. \"Was für ein Debakel!\" (What a debacle!) expresses stunned horror.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-045": "The Swabian Sauerbraten is a beef dish marinated in a vinegar-red wine marinade for several days before being slowly braised. Served with red cabbage and potato dumplings, it is a festive dish. In the Rhineland there is the well-known variant with raisins in the sauce, which Swabians mostly reject.",
  "koelsch.k-048": "The Cologne word for school — with the dropping of the final \"e\" typical of Ripuarian. Children go to the \"Schull\", and parents accompany their Pänz (kids) there. In Cologne's school system, dialect traditionally plays a role: many Cologne schools have carnival projects and promote the Cologne cultural heritage.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-047": "The Low German form of the pancake — thin, large and fried in the pan. In the North, Pannkoken are traditionally eaten with beet syrup, apple sauce or sugar. In Hamburg, \"Pannkoken\" also denotes the thin crêpe-like flatbread, while the Berliner Pfannkuchen (jam doughnut) is called \"Berliner\" there.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-044": "The Rütli is a meadow on Lake Lucerne in the canton of Uri — the legendary founding site of the Swiss Confederation in 1291. The Rütli oath of the original cantons is said to have taken place here. Today the Rütli is a national shrine and excursion destination, reachable by boat. On 1 August (National Day), members of the Federal Council and citizens gather there to celebrate.",
  "wienerisch.w-044": "The Viennese \"hoid\" is the modal particle \"halt\" — it expresses resignation, matter-of-factness or inevitability. \"Des is hoid so\" means \"that's just the way it is, nothing can be done about it\". \"Hoid\" is the Viennese shrug in word form — a philosophical attitude towards the unalterable that balances between fatalism and serenity.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-043": "A resident of the Free Imperial City of Nuremberg, who was subject directly to the emperor and not to a territorial prince. Until 1806, Nuremberg was one of the most important Free Imperial Cities. The imperial-city tradition still shapes the civic pride of Nuremberg and the self-assurance of the Franconian metropolis today.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-044": "The Radler is a mix of beer and lemon soda — especially popular in the Ruhr area on hot summer days and after long shifts. In northern Germany it is sometimes also called \"Alsterwasser\". Ruhr mates like to drink it at the beer garden or after work as a refreshing alternative to plain beer.",
  "alemannisch.al-042": "The Badnerlied (incipit: \"Was schenkt uns Gott für schöne Stunden, wir wohnen an des Rheines Strand\") is the unofficial anthem of the former Grand Duchy of Baden. It is sung loudly at football matches, Fasnet (carnival) and regional festivals. The refrain \"Viva, viva, viva Baden!\" is one of the best-known Alemannic communal songs.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-039": "D'\"Strausswirtschaft\" — a temporary Palatine tavern run by a winegrower, marked by a brushwood bunch (\"Strauss\") at the entrance. \"D'Strausswirtschaft beim Winzer öffnet wieder, mer gehe heut Abend hin.\" (The winegrower's Strausswirtschaft is opening again, we're going tonight.) Open only a few weeks a year, often in the grower's own yard or garden. Schorle, Saumagen, snacks — all from the winegrower himself. Similar to the Austrian Heuriger. A classic Palatine tradition since the 18th century.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-039": "Marilln are apricots. From ripe Marilln you make jam, dumplings and schnapps. A popular summer fruit in the Alpine region.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-039": "E Kerl is a man or fellow, often used appreciatively for a capable person. E ganze Kerl is a real fellow. A down-to-earth word for a person.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-039": "Dat Boot is the boat. With dat Boot you go out onto the mudflats or fishing. From the small rowing boat to the cutter, boats shape the coastal scene.",
  "badisch.bad-039": "Es Stüble is the cosy parlour or small tavern where people sit together over a Viertele. A place of conviviality in the Baden village.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-039": "D Suppa is the soup, often as a first course or a light supper. A warmi Suppa is good in cold weather. An everyday kitchen word.",
  "steirisch.st-039": "Karfiol is cauliflower, from the Italian cavolfiore. Baked or breaded, Karfiol is a popular side dish of Styrian cuisine.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-039": "Der Polster is the pillow on which you sleep. A weicher Polster makes for good sleep. The Austrian word for the pillow.",
  "thueringisch.th-039": "Der Knust is the end piece of the loaf, the heel of the bread. Den Knust mag nich jeder (not everyone likes the heel). The word goes back to Middle Low German and is widespread in the Central German area.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-039": "De Büx is the trousers. De Büx antrecken means to put on the trousers. Whoever sik in de Büx maakt (wets their pants) is getting scared. A primordial Low German word for clothing.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-039": "wa is the typical tag question \"nicht wahr?\" (isn't it?) or \"oder?\" (right?). Schön heute, wa? (Nice today, isn't it?) expects agreement. A worn-down form of \"nicht wahr\" that can round off almost any sentence.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-039": "Schòuf is the sheep, in the North Bavarian pronunciation with the shifted diphthong ou. On the meagre pastures of the Upper Palatinate many Schòuf used to be kept. A word of the rural world.",
  "hessisch.h-056": "Johann Wolfgang von Goethe (1749–1832) is Frankfurt's most famous son and one of the most important German poets of all time. Born at the Großer Hirschgraben, he spent his youth here and wrote works such as \"Götz von Berlichingen\" and \"The Sorrows of Young Werther\". The Goethe House is now a museum, and Goethe University bears his name. Goethe is said to have loved Frankfurt Grüne Soße (green sauce).",
  "berlinisch.b-050": "A typically Berlin-North German farewell or sending-off cry — \"man tau\" comes from Low German and means something like \"off you go\" or \"let's go\". \"Na denn man tau!\" ends a conversation and sends someone on their way. It sounds warm, down-to-earth and unmistakably Berlin.",
  "bayerisch.by-054": "Tracht encompasses traditional Bavarian dress with regional variants: Miesbach Tracht, Werdenfels Tracht, Chiemgau Tracht. Each region has its own colour scheme, embroidery and its own hat. Tracht is worn at festivals, weddings, church fairs (Kirtag) and funerals — it is not a costume but heartfelt regional clothing of belonging. Traditional-costume associations preserve this heritage.",
  "saechsisch.s-044": "In Saxon, \"Kaffeekuchen\" denotes quite generally any cake served with the afternoon coffee — whether streusel, poppy seed or buttercream cake. The afternoon coffee break with cake is a sacred tradition in Saxon families and offices. Whoever fails to bring a Kaffeekuchen when coming to visit is in a poor standing.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-046": "In the Swabian Remstal and around Stuttgart, intensive viticulture is practised — the steep vineyards are called \"Wengert\". The word derives from Middle High German \"wingarte\". Württemberg is one of the most important German wine regions, known for Trollinger, Lemberger and Riesling.",
  "koelsch.k-049": "When something has gone particularly well — a goal by 1. FC Köln, a passed exam or good news — the Cologner breaks into a spontaneous dance of joy. This can be a real dance or meant metaphorically. At carnival the dance of joy is literally to be seen: with good music, Cologners spontaneously dance in the street.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-048": "Knipp is a Bremen speciality: a dark grits sausage made of pork offal, oat and buckwheat grits, onions and spices. It is sliced and fried in the pan, served with fried egg and potatoes. Knipp belongs to Bremen cuisine like the Schnoor quarter belongs to the city — inseparable and peculiar at once.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-046": "In Swiss German, \"seckle\" means to hurry or run — \"seckle, seckle!\" is what you call to someone who is slow. The word sounds energetic and urgent. Etymologically it is related to the verb \"sacken\" (to sink, to drop) and became a call to action. It is in use throughout German-speaking Switzerland and has a slightly pressing but not unfriendly tone.",
  "wienerisch.w-045": "A typically Viennese reply to any request or commitment — \"schaun mer mal\" (let's see) means neither yes nor no, but rather the elegant keeping-open of all options. It is verbalized non-commitment, considered a Viennese virtue. Whoever says \"schaun mer mal\" has no desire to commit — and does so with a smile that nips any objection in the bud.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-044": "The Franconian Jura (Fränkische Alb) is a limestone landscape in northern Bavaria with valleys, caves, castles and typical juniper heaths. The Franconian Switzerland (Fränkische Schweiz) around Pottenstein, Tüchersfeld and Gößweinstein is especially well known. With the highest density of breweries in the world and countless hiking trails, it is a paradise for nature lovers.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-045": "\"Hammer!\" is an exclamation of enthusiasm in the Ruhr area — it means that something is exceptionally good or impressive. The connection to the blacksmith's hammer from the steel and mining tradition is no coincidence: what is hammer-hard is strong. In everyday life, a good goal, a tasty meal or a great evening can be a real \"Hammer\".",
  "alemannisch.al-043": "The bailiwick (Vogtei) was an administrative unit in the Middle Ages in which a bailiff (Vogt, administrator) exercised authority. In the Alemannic region there are many place and field names that point to old bailiwicks. The system of bailiwicks was important for administering the numerous monasteries and noble domains in southern Baden.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-040": "The \"Weisswurschd\" (white sausage) — also popular in the Palatinate, with its own regional touch. \"Zum Mittag a Weisswurschd mit Brez, des is no a Klassiker\" (a Weisswurschd with a pretzel for lunch, now that's a classic). It also denotes a special white boiled sausage from Palatine butchers. It is eaten with sweet mustard and a pretzel, often as a second breakfast. Also in the phrase \"Weisswurschd-Equator\" — the border between northern and southern Germany runs here.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-040": "Ribisel are currants, red or black. From Ribisel one makes juice and jam. The word is common throughout the Austrian region.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-040": "Es Hus is the house. \"Heem ins Hus geh\" means to go home. Building one's own Hus was for a long time an important life goal in the Saarland.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-040": "De Kutter is the sturdy fishing boat with which the shrimp fishermen put out to sea. At the harbour you can buy shrimp directly from the Kutter.",
  "badisch.bad-040": "De Buckel is the back. \"Mir tuet de Buckel weh\" means \"my back hurts\". Whoever has \"en breite Buckel\" (a broad back) can put up with a lot. A vivid word for a part of the body.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-040": "Es znüni is the small snack in the morning, around nine o'clock. \"Beim znüni gibts a Brot und an Kaffee\" (at the znüni there's bread and a coffee). An Alemannic word, shared with Switzerland.",
  "steirisch.st-040": "Fisolen are green garden beans. Boiled as a side dish or in a stew, Fisolen are part of Styria's summer home cooking.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-040": "D Tuchent is the thick feather duvet under which one snuggles in winter. A warm Tuchent is part of the Austrian bedroom.",
  "thueringisch.th-040": "The Demse is oppressive heat or sultriness, such as on a hot summer day. \"Bei der Demse bleibmr lieber im Schatten\" (in the Demse we'd rather stay in the shade). A vivid Thuringian weather word.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-040": "Dat Schapp is the cupboard. \"In dat Schapp liggt dat gode Tüüg\" (in the cupboard lies the good stuff). A common Low German word for furniture, which is still alive in northern German High German too.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-040": "\"doof\" means stupid, dumb or also boring. \"Stell dir nich so doof an!\" (don't be so stupid about it!) is a common reproach. The word comes from Low German and spread out from Berlin.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-040": "Woong is the cart, with the dark Northern Bavarian a (Wagen becomes Wòòng/Woong). \"Früher ist der Heuwoong vom Ross zogn worn\" (in the old days the hay cart was pulled by the horse). An everyday word from farming.",
  "hessisch.h-057": "The Frankfurt Book Fair is the world's largest book fair and takes place every year in October. With its roots in the 15th century (shortly after Gutenberg's invention), it is the oldest fair of its kind. Publishers from all over the world trade licences here, and on the weekend the public streams onto the fairgrounds. The Peace Prize of the German Book Trade is traditionally awarded during the Book Fair.",
  "berlinisch.b-051": "A Berlin expression for \"great\" or \"terrific\" — like \"knorke\", but somewhat newer. The word probably comes from the Yiddish \"toff\" (good) and has been widespread in Berlin since the 1920s. In the East Berlin of the 1970s and 80s, \"dufte\" was the buzzword par excellence; today it sounds slightly nostalgic.",
  "bayerisch.by-056": "The \"Goschn\" is the mouth in Bavarian — coarser, louder, ruder than the standard German \"Mund\". The famous \"bavarian Goschn\" stands for the direct, unvarnished way of speaking. \"Halt dei Goschn!\" (shut your trap!) is a crude demand for silence, while \"a freche Goschn habn\" (to have a cheeky Goschn) describes someone who likes to talk and is forward. It isn't necessarily insulting, but it's never refined.",
  "saechsisch.s-045": "A small, narrow alley in the old town — typical of the historic city centres of Dresden, Meißen or Bautzen. The diminutive form \"-chen\" makes the word especially dainty. Such Gässelchen are often picturesque and connect squares and streets by the shortest route. In Dresden's Neustadt there are many such charming Gässelchen.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-047": "The Trollinger is the most widely grown red wine variety in Württemberg and is considered the Swabian red wine par excellence. It produces a light, fresh and slightly tart red wine that goes well with Swabian home cooking. The name derives from \"Tirolinger\" — the vine originally came to Württemberg from South Tyrol.",
  "koelsch.k-050": "The \"Ävebäätche\" — literally something like \"one who prays / begs his way through life\" — is a jocular Cologne term for an unemployed person or someone who prefers to leave the work to others. The term is not meant maliciously, but describes, with typical Cologne humour, a situation one shouldn't take too tragically. A true Cologne native stays in good spirits even as an Ävebäätche.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-049": "The Hamburg eel soup (Aalsuppe) is one of the oldest and most peculiar dishes of northern German cuisine — a sweet-and-sour soup with eel, dried fruit, bacon and vegetables. Contrary to its name, the original version sometimes contained no eel at all: \"Aalsuppe\" may derive from \"allens\" (everything) — the soup made from everything the larder had to offer.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-047": "In Swiss German, \"huere\" is a colloquial intensifier — similar to \"sau-\" in German or \"mega-\" in youth slang. \"Das isch huere guet!\" means \"That is incredibly good!\". Etymologically the word has vulgar roots, but in modern Swiss everyday life it has largely faded and is used without a second thought. It is one of the most popular intensifying words in youth slang.",
  "wienerisch.w-046": "A Viennese exclamation of indignation, admiration or incredulous astonishment — depending on the tone. \"Des is a Wahnsinn\" (that's madness) can describe the beauty of a sunset or the audacity of a driver. The Viennese superlatives often work through the negative: madness, catastrophe, scandal — but always with a touch of irony and an inner wink.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-045": "The Altmühl valley (Altmühltal) is one of the most beautiful river landscapes of Franconia, where the Altmühl meanders through deep limestone valleys. The Altmühltal cycle path is among Germany's most popular cycling routes. The Solnhofen limestone slabs, on which Archaeopteryx fossils were found, come from this region. The valley combines natural beauty with geological history.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-046": "The drinking kiosk (Trinkhalle) — in the Ruhr area also called \"Büdchen\" or simply \"Kiosk\" — is far more than a grocery shop: it is the social heart of the neighbourhood. Here you buy cigarettes, newspapers and cold drinks, hear the news from the area and talk about BVB. The Trinkhalle is an institution that keeps the sense of community in the Ruhr region alive — and is often open until late into the night.",
  "alemannisch.al-044": "Rappoltstein (French Ribeaupierre) is a castle ruin in Alsace that in the Middle Ages was the centre of the county of Rappoltstein. The counts of Rappoltstein ruled over large parts of the Alemannic border area between Baden and Alsace. The castle stands symbolically for the close cultural interweaving between Baden and Alsace.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-041": "The \"Kerschen\" — Palatine pronunciation of Kirschen (cherries), characteristic with its soft \"r\" and short \"e\". \"D'Kerschen aus em Garten, die schmecken doppelt so gut!\" (the cherries from the garden taste twice as good!). The Palatinate has extensive cherry cultivation in the Vorderpfalz lowlands. Variations: sweet cherry, sour cherry (\"Sauerkersch\"). Harvest time is June to July. Processed into cakes, compote, liqueur. Proverb: \"Es is besser mit em Spatz in da Hand wie mit da Taub auf em Kerschbaum\" (a sparrow in the hand is better than a pigeon in the cherry tree).",
  "tirolerisch.ti-041": "Fisolen are green garden beans. Boiled as a side dish or in a stew, Fisolen are part of the summer home cooking in Tyrol and throughout Austria.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-041": "The Stubb is the good parlour or the living room, where the family sits together and visitors are received. A cosy focal point of the house.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-041": "Dat Reep is the rope or line with which the boat is tied up. On board, every Reep has to be well stowed. An important word of seafaring.",
  "badisch.bad-041": "E Hampfle is a handful, that is, as much as fits into one hand. \"E Hampfle Nuss\" means a handful of nuts. A vivid word for a quantity.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-041": "Es zvieri is the snack in the afternoon, around four o'clock. \"Beim zvieri trinkt man Kaffee und isst ebbas Süaßes\" (at the zvieri you drink coffee and eat something sweet). The counterpart to the znüni in the morning.",
  "steirisch.st-041": "Ribisel are currants, red or black. From Ribisel one makes juice and jam. The word is common throughout the Austrian region.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-041": "A Sackerl is a small bag or pouch, for example for shopping. \"Tua de Semmeln ins Sackerl\" (put the bread rolls in the Sackerl). A typically Austrian word.",
  "thueringisch.th-041": "A Funzel is a poorly burning, weak light source that gives off hardly any light. \"Bei der Funzel siehste ja nüschd\" (you can't see anything with that Funzel). The word is colloquially widespread in the central German region.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-041": "De Mors is the backside, the bottom. \"Beweeg dien Mors!\" (move your behind!) is a coarse demand to hurry up. A hearty word for a part of the body, well anchored in Low German.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-041": "Keule is a familiar form of address for a friend or brother, comparable to Atze. \"Na Keule, allet fit?\" (hey Keule, all good?) greets a pal. A genuine Berlin word that also lives on in Brandenburg.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-041": "Vuugl is the bird. In western Northern Bavarian the o is raised to u, hence Vuugl instead of the more southern Voogl. Plural Viigl. A vivid example of the Upper Palatine vowel colouring.",
  "hessisch.h-061": "The Schwälmer Land in northern Hesse is a region rich in tradition, known for its unique costume — the red Schwälm bonnets and the long traditional skirts are world-famous. The Brothers Grimm are said to have found their inspiration for Little Red Riding Hood here. The Schwälm people keep their customs alive to this day and wear the traditional costume at festivals and church occasions.",
  "berlinisch.b-055": "The Berlin S-Bahn is the city's rapid-transit rail system and connects the outer districts with the center. Unlike the U-Bahn, it mostly runs above ground. The Ringbahn (S41/S42) circles the inner city and is affectionately called „der Hundekopf\" (the dog's head) — because of its characteristic shape on the map.",
  "bayerisch.by-058": "„Saupreiß\" is the famous Bavarian term for northern Germans, especially Prussians. Composed of „Sau\" (pig) and „Preiß\" (Prussian), it sounds coarser than it is usually meant today — a jocular insult with a historical background (Bavaria lost to Prussia in 1866). Today it is mostly used humorously for northern Germans in general. Real Bavarians can pronounce the word with every possible intonation.",
  "saechsisch.s-046": "A jocular Saxon term for a particularly bushy or unkempt chin beard. The word vividly combines the gorilla as a symbol of something wild and untamed with the anatomical term. In Saxon humor, physical appearance is often commented on in this direct, pictorial way.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-048": "The unofficial national dish of the Swabians — brown lentils in a thick broth, served with homemade Spätzle and Saiten (Vienna sausages). On New Year's Eve the dish is said to bring luck, since the round lentils are reminiscent of coins. The dish is plain, filling and symbolizes Swabian modesty.",
  "koelsch.k-051": "The full Cologne battle cry, shouted during Carnival and on every occasion of Cologne identity. „Alaaf\" derives from the Middle High German „al af\" (all off, all away) — Cologne above all. At Carnival sessions the cry rings out three times in a row, growing ever louder.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-050": "The Heringsschmaus (herring feast) is a traditional northern German festive meal for Carnival or Rose Monday — pickled herring in many variations: Bismarckhering, Rollmops, cream and mustard herring. Especially in Hamburg and Schleswig-Holstein, the Heringsschmaus is a sociable event that brings friends and family together. For centuries, herring was the „bread of the sea\" for poor coastal dwellers.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-048": "A typical Swiss German youth slang expression — „geile Siech\" means a cool, great guy. „Siech\" in itself originally meant a sick or poor person (from Middle High German „siech\"), but has shifted to a neutral or positive form of address. In the youth language of German-speaking Switzerland, „Siech\" is today a synonym for „guy\" or „bloke\" without negative connotation.",
  "wienerisch.w-047": "A direct Viennese comeback when one is being stared at — less aggressive than it sounds, more of an invitation to communicate. „Wos schaust?\" (What are you looking at?) is not necessarily a reproach, but can also be meant playfully. In Vienna, direct eye contact on the street is no cause for hostility, but sometimes an invitation to a chat — the Viennese way.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-046": "The Schäuferla (or Schäufele) is the national dish of Franconia — a pork shoulder slowly roasted in the oven with a crispy crust, served with a dumpling and sauerkraut or red cabbage. The name comes from the shape of the shoulder blade, which resembles a little shovel. No church fair, no family celebration without Schäuferla. It is on the menu in every Franconian inn — and every landlord claims to serve the best.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-047": "„Aufm Pott\" means: here with us in the Ruhr region. „Der Pott\" is the affectionate self-designation for the region — not derogatory, but meant with pride. Anyone who grew up „aufm Pott\" belongs to the community of Ruhrpott folk, who stay loyally attached to their homeland despite all the changes. „Aufm Pott läuft des anner als woanders\" (Things work differently in the Pott than elsewhere) is considered a proud statement about one's own uniqueness.",
  "alemannisch.al-045": "„Badisch gschproche\" means something like „speaking Badisch\" or „speaking in dialect\". It is a self-confident assertion of Alemannic dialect identity. People from Baden are proud of their soft dialect and like to emphasize the difference from Standard German or from the Bavarian language area. „Mir rede halt badisch!\" (We just speak Badisch!) is an avowal of one's homeland.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-042": "„Babbel ned!\" — a Palatine request for quiet. „Babbel ned, ich muss nachdenke!\" (Don't chatter, I need to think!). It is the negation of the verb „babbeln\" (to talk, to chatter). Direct, but not meant as an insult. Variations: „Babbel mir net ständig dazwische\" (don't keep interrupting me). It is also used ironically when someone talks too much without saying anything of substance. A classic Palatine saying.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-042": "Karfiol is cauliflower, from the Italian cavolfiore. Baked or with breadcrumbs, Karfiol is a popular side dish of Austrian cuisine.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-042": "The Schdroß is the street. Uff da Schdroß (out on the street) the children used to play football. An everyday place-word of the Saarland dialect.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-042": "Plünnen are clothes, often in the sense of old garments or rags. Truck di dröge Plünnen an means to put on dry things. A cozy everyday word.",
  "badisch.bad-042": "D Kehrwoche is the weekly rotating cleaning duty in an apartment building, for the stairwell and the pavement. An almost proverbial institution of the Swabian-Badensian love of order.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-042": "Es Hus is the house. Hei is Hus goh means to go home. In the Ländle (Vorarlberg) people like to build their own Hus with plenty of wood. A central place-word.",
  "steirisch.st-042": "S Häusl is the toilet, formerly the outhouse in the yard. I muass aufs Häusl means „I have to go to the toilet\". A common everyday word.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-042": "D Trafik is the small shop for cigarettes, newspapers and tickets, often run by a Trafikant (tobacconist). An Austrian institution.",
  "thueringisch.th-042": "Die Ficke is the trouser pocket. Steck das in die Ficke! (Put that in your pocket!). An old word for the pocket on a garment, preserved today above all in the East Central German dialects.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-042": "Fofftein literally means fifteen and refers to the (work) break. Fofftein maken means to take a break — what is meant is the fifteen-minute breakfast break.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-042": "In Berlin and Brandenburg, a Pfannkuchen is the round, jam-filled deep-fried pastry that elsewhere is called a Berliner or Krapfen. At New Year's Eve, Pfannkuchen are an essential part of the celebration.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-042": "Schnèj is the snow. The long vowel of Middle High German has become the diphthong „ej\" in North Bavarian, unlike the Central Bavarian Schnèè. In winter there is often a lot of Schnèj in the Upper Palatinate.",
  "hessisch.h-068": "The Hessischer Rundfunk (HR) is the public broadcasting corporation for Hesse, based in Frankfurt. It is known for programs such as „Hallo Hessen\", the Hessian Tatort episodes and „Die Hessen-Schau\". HR3 is one of the most popular radio stations in Hesse. The HR actively cultivates the Hessian dialect with dialect programs such as „Bei Bachmann\".",
  "berlinisch.b-056": "With more than 150 km of track network, the Berlin U-Bahn is one of the largest in Europe. Some lines like the U1 run partly above ground — the famous elevated railway along Skalitzer Straße in Kreuzberg is a landmark. Each line has its own character: the U8 is legendary for its colorful crowd, the U6 connects Reinickendorf with Tempelhof.",
  "bayerisch.by-059": "The „Goaßmaß\" (also „Goaß\") is a Bavarian mix: pale lager with cola and a shot of cherry liqueur — a full liter in all. An Oktoberfest specialty that has become very fashionable in recent years. The name „Goaßmaß\" probably comes from the friction pattern of goatskin lederhosen or from the comparison with the multi-peaked mountain goat („Goaß\" = nanny goat). Strong and sweet at once — caution is advised.",
  "saechsisch.s-047": "A „Schlappschwanz\" is someone who shows no backbone, who is cowardly or listless. The word is known throughout the German-speaking world, but in Saxon it is used with particular indignation. Saxons value drive and directness — anyone who shirks quickly earns this label.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-049": "In autumn, sweet chestnuts are gathered and roasted on the Swabian Alb and in the Schönbuch — the „Keschde\" are a seasonal culinary treat. In the Stuttgart area there are chestnut festivals where roasted Keschde are combined with a Viertele of wine. The word comes from the Latin „castanea\".",
  "koelsch.k-052": "The Funken are the traditional Carnival soldiers of Cologne — the Roten Funken (founded 1823) are the oldest corps and wear red uniforms with white breeches. They parody the Prussian town-soldier tradition and are among the most venerable Carnival societies. To be a Funke is a Cologne honor.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-051": "Labskaus is the classic sailor's dish of northern Germany — salted meat mashed with potatoes, beetroot and onions into a pink purée, garnished with a fried egg, Rollmops and gherkin. Originally ship's fare (cured to keep for centuries), today a Hamburg restaurant classic. Its appearance takes some getting used to, its taste is legendary. „Labskaus\" is pure Hamburg identity.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-050": "Appenzeller stands for several things: the spicy hard cheese with the orange rind, treated with a secret herbal brine; the canton of Appenzell with its Landsgemeinde; and the singsong, particularly pronounced Appenzell dialect. Appenzell Innerrhoden was the last canton without women's suffrage until 1990. Appenzeller cheese is exported worldwide, but the recipe of the herbal brine remains secret.",
  "wienerisch.w-048": "A Viennese term of abuse for a group of people regarded as base, dishonorable or unreliable — coarse, but in everyday Vienna less harsh than in Standard German. „Des Gsindl!\" is an exclamation of genuine indignation. The word has historical roots in the Gesinde (domestic servants), who were held in low social esteem. Today it is a strong but commonly used term of abuse.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-047": "In medieval Franconia, the „Zeidler\" was a forest beekeeper: he climbed trees to take honey from wild bees and tended beehives in the forest. The Zeidler trade was a respected craft with its own guilds and rights. Nuremberg was the center of German beekeeping — the imperial city granted the Zeidler special privileges. Today the Zeidler museum in Feucht near Nuremberg commemorates this almost forgotten craft.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-048": "„Schicht im Schacht\" was the call of the foreman when the work shift underground was over: the miners could come up to daylight. Today the expression is used generally for the end of something — knocking-off time, finished, all done. It stands for Ruhrpott humor: short, direct, with a wink. Anyone who says „Schicht im Schacht\" means: now there's peace, now we've made it.",
  "alemannisch.al-047": "The Black Forest traditional costume is not a single garment, but a regionally diverse system: each community has its own costume with its own colors, cuts and ornaments. Costumes are worn at festivals, church fairs and Fasnet (Carnival). Costume associations actively preserve this knowledge. A complete costume can cost several hundred euros and is often passed down as a family heirloom.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-043": "„Es geht uns gut\" (We're doing fine) — the typical Palatine affirmation of life, spoken with cozy resignation. „Wie geht's? — Es geht uns gut, kennsche?\" (How are you? — We're doing fine, you know?). It is often used as a standard answer, regardless of how one actually feels. At the same time, it expresses the Palatine love of life — wine, family and Wengerd (vineyards) are enough for contentment. Variation: „Es geht uns prächtig\" (We're doing splendidly) for special days.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-043": "Faschiertes is minced meat, from which one shapes Faschierte Laibchen (meatballs/patties). A basic term of Austrian cuisine, from faschieren (to put through the mincer).",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-043": "De Bach is the small watercourse that flows through the village or valley. Am Bach (by the brook) the children liked to play. Many place names in the Saarland end in -bach.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-043": "Tüffel are the potatoes, a Low German word. Tüffel mit Stippels means potatoes with gravy. The basis of many hearty coastal dishes.",
  "badisch.bad-043": "gschafft refers to someone who is exhausted and tired from work. I bi heit total gschafft means \"I'm completely worn out today.\" The state of being gschafft comes from all the schaffe (working).",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-043": "D Schual is the school. D Chinder gönd in d Schual (the children go to school). An everyday word that shapes the daily routine of many families.",
  "steirisch.st-043": "A Tschick is a cigarette, from the Italian cicca. A Tschick rauchn means to smoke. A colloquial word widespread throughout Austria.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-043": "D Stiege is the staircase. Über d Stiege (up the stairs) you go to the first floor. A word for the stairwell that is widespread in the Austrian region.",
  "thueringisch.th-043": "Die Quetsche is the plum or damson, from which cake and jam are made. Im Spätsommer sin die Quetschn reif (in late summer the plums are ripe). A common fruit word in the Central German region.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-043": "De Wruke is the swede (rutabaga). In lean times it was an important staple food in the north. Wruken mit Fleesch (swedes with meat) is a hearty, traditional dish.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-043": "Hackepeter is raw, seasoned pork mince spread on a Schrippe (roll) and eaten with onions. A hearty Berlin-Brandenburg classic for breakfast or buffets.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-043": "wòam means warm, again with the typically dark a shifted toward o characteristic of North Bavarian. Wenn d Sunna scheint, wirds glei wòam (when the sun shines, it soon gets warm). A common everyday adjective.",
  "hessisch.h-069": "A typically Hessian exclamation of refusal — used when someone proposes or claims something one does not want to accept. „Bei mir net!\" makes it clear: count me out, I'm not going along with that. It sounds resolute and unmistakable, yet thanks to the Hessian intonation never truly aggressive. A classic of Hessian self-assertion.",
  "berlinisch.b-059": "The Berlin Wall divided the city into East and West from 1961 to 1989 — for 28 years a symbol of German division and the Cold War. Over 140 people died trying to cross it. Today the East Side Gallery, the Bernauer Straße Memorial and the Mauermuseum at Checkpoint Charlie commemorate this dark era. The 9th of November 1989 — the fall of the Wall — remains unforgettable.",
  "bayerisch.by-060": "„Obatzda\" (or „Obatzter\") is the famous Bavarian cheese spread: mashed ripe Camembert or Brie blended with butter, paprika, salt, pepper, caraway and chopped onions. Invented in the 1920s in Bayreuth or at the Tegernsee — its origin is hotly disputed. Served at the Brotzeit (snack) with Brezn (pretzels) and Radieserl (radishes). A protected geographical indication.",
  "saechsisch.s-048": "Originally the male billy goat, „Geißbock\" is also used in Saxon as a mild term of abuse — for a stubborn, obstinate or none-too-bright person. In football the Cologne Geißbock is known as the club mascot, but in Saxon the word carries a rather derogatory connotation.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-050": "The „Viertele\" is the quintessential Swabian wine measure: 0.25 litres of wine, served in a bulbous glass. In Stuttgart's Besenwirtschaft scene the Viertele is the social currency — people meet for a Viertele. The Besenwirtschaften, where winegrowers serve their own wine, are a Swabian cultural treasure.",
  "koelsch.k-056": "The „Müllemer Böötche\" is an old Cologne folk song about the ferry boat that once carried people from Cologne to Mülheim before the Mülheim Bridge was built. Today it is a classic of the Cologne song repertoire and is often sung at carnival sessions. The melody is melancholic yet cheerful, typical of Cologne dialect music.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-052": "The Rollmops is a pickled herring fillet, rolled around a gherkin and marinated in vinegar with onions, mustard seeds and bay leaf. It has been a North German classic since the 19th century — originally a Berlin invention, but today at home all along the coast. A popular hangover cure: allegedly healing after a night of heavy drinking. Perfect with black bread and schnapps.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-051": "Migros is the largest supermarket chain in Switzerland, founded in 1925 by Gottlieb Duttweiler. It is organised as a cooperative and effectively belongs to its customers. Migros sells no alcohol and no tobacco — a tradition since its founding. „M-Budget\" is the inexpensive own brand, „M-Classic\" the mid-range one. Migros is more than a supermarket — it is part of Swiss identity.",
  "wienerisch.w-049": "The Schottenfeldgasse lies in Vienna's 7th district, Neubau — a Grätzl (neighbourhood) known for its coffee houses, antiquarian bookshops, small boutiques and the Vienna Volkstheater. Neubau is the district of students, artists and creatives — a place where old Vienna meets young Vienna. The Schottenfeldgasse stands as a symbol of the typical, unglamorous, authentic Vienna.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-048": "The Kirchweih (Franconian: „Kärwa\") is the most important village festival in Franconia — originally the annual celebration of the anniversary of the church's consecration, today a multi-day folk festival with a beer tent, carousel, folk music and traditional dishes. In September and October thousands of Kirchweih festivals take place — every village has its own. Schäuferla, dumplings and Franconian wine are obligatory components. The „Nürnberger Altstadtfest\" and the „Erlanger Bergkirchweih\" are the most famous.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-049": "The Currywurst is not only known in Berlin — in the Ruhr region it is just as much of a cult. Fried or steamed sausage, sliced or whole, with ketchup and curry powder. At snack stands beside collieries and steelworks the Currywurst was the worker's lunch par excellence. In Bochum there is even an offshoot of the German Currywurst Museum, and Dortmund proudly carries on its own Currywurst tradition.",
  "alemannisch.al-048": "„Mersi\" is the Alemannic adoption of the French „merci\" — in the border region with France and in Switzerland fully integrated into Alemannic. In Freiburg, in Alsace and along the Hochrhein people naturally say „Mersi!\" instead of „Danke\". The word illustrates the centuries-old interweaving of the Alemannic and Romance language areas along the Upper Rhine.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-044": "Da „Maisbock\" — the Palatine bock beer brewed and served in May, with a higher alcohol content. „A Maisbock zum Vesper, des wärmt im kühlen Frühling\" (a Maisbock with the snack, it warms you in the cool spring). A Palatine brewing tradition with its own hop and malt blends. Some breweries organise a „Maisbockanstich\" (tapping) with a festive procession. Strong, malty, often dark. A variation alongside the usual Palatine beer (Park Bräu, Bellheimer).",
  "tirolerisch.ti-044": "Gselchtes is smoked and cured meat, from selchen (to smoke). Gselchtes mit Knödl und Kraut (cured meat with dumplings and sauerkraut) is a hearty Tyrolean main course.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-044": "De Wald surrounds the Saarland villages and invites people to take walks and pick mushrooms. In the past, gathering wood in the forest was an important job.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-044": "De Snut is the mouth or snout. Hool de Snut means \"shut your mouth\". Likewise, eine Schnute ziehen means to sulk in offence.",
  "badisch.bad-044": "bäbbe means to stick or be gluey. Der Teig bäbbt an de Finger (the dough sticks to your fingers). From it also comes der Bäbber, the sticker. A vivid everyday verb.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-044": "goh means to go. I goh hei means \"I'm going home\". A central verb that appears in many expressions, such as go luaga (to go and look).",
  "steirisch.st-044": "A Sackerl is a small bag or pouch, for example for shopping. Tua d Erdäpfel ins Sackerl (put the potatoes in the bag). A typically Austrian word.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-044": "Jänner is January, the first month of the year. Im Jänner liegt am Berg viel Schnee (in January there is a lot of snow on the mountain). The word is customary throughout Austria.",
  "thueringisch.th-044": "nee is the everyday negation and means no. It is the widespread counterpart to the affirmative nu and is in common use throughout Central Germany. Nee, das mach ich nich (no, I won't do that).",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-044": "gnatterig means irritable, whiny and bad-tempered. En gnatterig Kind (a grumpy child) whines from tiredness. A vivid Low German word for a peevish mood.",
  "brandenburgisch.br-044": "The Schusterjunge is the dark, hearty rye roll, the counterpart to the pale Schrippe. A traditional Berlin-Brandenburg bakery word that preserves the old baking culture.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-044": "schiach means ugly, unattractive or unpleasant, also of bad weather. A schiachs Wetta is foul weather. Widespread throughout the Bavarian region, with the Upper Palatine pronunciation schiach.",
  "hessisch.h-070": "The ultra-short Hessian greeting — derived from „guten Tag\", but radically shortened to a single syllable. „Gude\" works at any time of day, from morning to evening, and expresses warm familiarity. Sometimes the greeting is even simply tossed out as „Gude!\", without the person addressed having to respond directly.",
  "berlinisch.b-060": "The Eckkneipe is a Berlin institution: usually small, cosy, located on a street corner, with regulars and a landlord who knows everyone. Draught beer, Bockwurst, rounds of Skat and political debates are part of it. Many traditional Eckkneipen have fallen victim to gentrification; the ones that remain are defended as cultural assets.",
  "bayerisch.by-061": "The „Brez'n\" is one of the most important symbols of Bavarian baking — a yeast dough dipped in lye in its characteristic shape. The shape symbolises crossed arms (a medieval posture of supplication). In Bavaria the Brezn is dark, almost black at the spots where it is thicker, and is traditionally eaten with the Weißwurst for breakfast. Salt is a must.",
  "saechsisch.s-049": "The Kurrende is a traditional boys' choir that originally arose in Saxony during the Reformation. Pupils walked singing through the streets and collected alms for poor fellow students — today the Kurrende is a firm part of Saxon church life. The Thomanerchor Leipzig is the best-known Kurrende tradition, reaching back to the 13th century.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-051": "The VfB Stuttgart — founded in 1893 — is Swabia's largest football club. Five-time German champion, three-time cup winner. Home ground: the MHPArena (formerly the Mercedes-Benz Arena) in Bad Cannstatt. Famous players: Jürgen Klinsmann, Hansi Müller, Mario Gomez, today Serhou Guirassy. Club colours red and white. „Hier in der Region steht der VfB ganz oben\" (here in the region the VfB stands at the very top) — a Swabian sporting religion.",
  "koelsch.k-057": "The 1. FC Köln — in Cologne dialect „FC Kölle\" — is the most important football club in the city, founded in 1948. The club colours red and white and the mascot Hennes the billy goat are Cologne identity. „Mer stonn zo dir, FC Kölle\" (we stand by you, FC Kölle) is the club anthem and at the same time a creed of the fans. Whether promotion or relegation — the FC is home.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-053": "The Wadden Sea along the North Sea coast is, with over 11,500 km², the largest continuous tidal flat area in the world — a UNESCO World Natural Heritage Site since 2009. At low tide it lies dry, at high tide it is flooded. Home to seals, harbour porpoises and 10 million migratory birds. Mudflat hikes with certified guides are an unforgettable experience. Never go into the mudflats without a guide!",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-052": "Coop is the second-largest supermarket chain in Switzerland and Migros's great rival. Unlike Migros, Coop sells alcohol and has a broad organic line („Naturaplan\"). The Coop cooperative has over 2.5 million members. Swiss people often have a favourite chain — either Migros or Coop — and this choice says a lot about them.",
  "wienerisch.w-050": "The Viennese \"I mog di\" is gentler, warmer and less binding than a direct \"I love you\" — it expresses deep affection without the drama of a love confession. Between parents and children, grandparents and grandchildren, old friends: \"I mog di\" covers everything. It is the emotional essence of Viennese — heartfelt, direct and yet tender.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-049": "\"Mee\" is the Franconian form of \"mehr\" (more) — a small word with great character. In Franconian, High German sounds softer, with drawn-out vowels replacing sharp consonants. \"Willste noch a mee?\" (Would you like a little more?) is a typical host's question at the Franconian dinner table. The word exemplifies the gentle melody of Franconian, which is often perceived as friendlier and less harsh than other Southern German dialects.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-050": "The mining settlements (also called \"Colonien\") are a defining architectural feature of the Ruhr region: workers' settlements built by mining companies with uniform brick houses, gardens and communal facilities. They emerged from the 1850s onwards to house miners near the collieries. Today many of these settlements are listed monuments and sought-after residential areas — Gelsenkirchen-Bismarck, Dortmund-Hörde, Essen-Altenessen.",
  "alemannisch.al-049": "\"Ade\" is the classic Alemannic and Swabian farewell formula, derived from the French \"adieu\" (to God). The word migrated into Alemannic through centuries of contact with the Romance-speaking region. In Baden, \"Ade\" is the standard goodbye, also common in the written language. The folk song \"Ade zur guten Nacht\" is one of the best-known German folk songs.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-045": "The \"Schnookeloch\" — Palatine word for a mosquito-infested swamp or an inhospitable place. \"Im Sommer is es Schnookeloch am Fluss schwer zu ertragen.\" (In summer the Schnookeloch by the river is hard to bear.) \"Schnook\" is Palatine for mosquito. Used affectionately mocking or seriously, depending on the context. Also used figuratively for a boring village or a disliked dwelling: \"Mer wohnt im Schnookeloch.\" (One lives in the Schnookeloch.)",
  "tirolerisch.ti-045": "The Gröstl is a hearty pan dish made of roasted potatoes, onions and leftover meat, often with a fried egg. A classic Tyrolean way of using up the previous day's leftovers.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-045": "The Sunn is the sun. When the Sunn shines, people sit outside. A friendly nature word that promises good spirits.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-045": "De Kopp is the head. \"En dicken Kopp hebben\" means to be stubborn (literally: to have a thick head). The teacup is also called Kopp — puns included. A versatile word for a body part.",
  "badisch.bad-045": "Dehäm means at home. \"Dehäm isch dehäm\" (Home is home) expresses the bond with one's homeland. A warm-hearted word of the southwest.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-045": "Cho means to come. \"Chuscht du au?\" means \"Are you coming too?\". A basic Alemannic verb that Vorarlberg shares closely with Switzerland.",
  "steirisch.st-045": "A Häferl is a cup or mug. A Häferl of coffee in the morning is part of the routine. A common Austrian word for a drinking vessel.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-045": "Topfen is quark, the basis of many flour-based dishes such as Topfenstrudel or the filling for the Kasnudl. A versatile Austrian dairy product.",
  "thueringisch.th-045": "Dittschen means to dip something into a liquid, such as a biscuit into coffee. In Thuringian everyday life it is a common verb for briefly dunking pastries into a drink.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-045": "Tüdelkram is useless odds and ends, all sorts of bits and bobs and clutter. \"Räum mal dien Tüdelkram weg!\" (Tidy up your junk!) Related to tüdern and tüdelig (confused).",
  "brandenburgisch.br-045": "Schnafte means great, splendid or terrific, in the same vein as knorke and dufte. \"Det is ja schnafte!\" (That's just great!) expresses enthusiasm. An old Berlin word of praise that still lives on in the region.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-045": "D Housn is the trousers, with the North Bavarian \"ou\" for High German \"o\". \"A neie Housn brauchst zum Kirwa.\" (You need new trousers for the church fair.) An everyday word from the realm of clothing.",
  "hessisch.h-071": "The original Frankfurter Würstchen (Frankfurt sausages) have been protected by the EU since 1860 — only in Frankfurt am Main and its surroundings may the original be produced. The slim, beechwood-smoked scalded pork sausages are traditionally only heated in hot water, not boiled. With mustard and bread or potato salad they are a Hessian classic — and the model for American hot dogs.",
  "berlinisch.b-065": "Prenzlauer Berg, \"Prenzlberg\" for short, was once the artists' district of East Berlin; today it is regarded as a gentrified showcase neighborhood with young families from Swabia and Munich. The Kollwitzplatz area with its restored old buildings has become expensive. Nevertheless, the district retains its charm thanks to its dense café and restaurant life.",
  "bayerisch.by-062": "The \"Schweinshax'n\" is the Bavarian national dish par excellence: a pork knuckle roasted in the oven and baked until crispy, with its layer of rind. Crisp on the outside, juicy on the inside — served with dumplings and coleslaw. A whole Hax'n easily weighs a kilo. On the menu in every Bavarian tavern. Cutting through the crispy rind produces the famous crackle.",
  "saechsisch.s-050": "Today Saxons stand by their dialect with a certain irony and at the same time with pride, even though it is often considered unattractive in nationwide comparison. According to studies, Saxon has repeatedly been voted the least popular German dialect — but it is precisely this that has led many Saxons to consciously cultivate and defend it. \"Mir reden sächsisch, und des bleibt so!\" (We speak Saxon, and that's how it stays!)",
  "schwaebisch.sw-052": "Daimler — today the Mercedes-Benz Group — is Stuttgart's most important employer and a symbol of Swabian economic success. In 1886 Gottlieb Daimler invented the first automobile in Cannstatt. The Stuttgart-Untertürkheim plant is the parent factory. \"Working at Daimler\" is a lifelong status symbol for Swabians. The three-pointed star is a global brand. Mercedes sedans and trucks are Swabian identity on wheels.",
  "koelsch.k-058": "The Müngersdorfer Stadion (today officially RheinEnergieStadion) is the home ground of 1. FC Köln in the Müngersdorf district. It holds over 50,000 spectators and is one of Germany's most atmospheric stadiums. At home games the South Stand is ablaze with atmosphere, and \"Hennes\" the billy goat marches in with the team.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-054": "Hamburger SV — HSV for short — is Hamburg's traditional club, founded in 1887. Until 2018, HSV was the only club to have played continuously in the Bundesliga since its founding in 1963. The famous stadium clock in the Volksparkstadion counted the years of top-flight membership. After relegation to the second division in 2018: a trauma for HSV fans. \"Nur der HSV!\" (Only HSV!) remains the supporters' battle cry.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-053": "The yellow postal bus is a Swiss institution — since 1906 it has connected remote mountain villages with the rest of the country. The famous post bus horn (three notes: C sharp–E–A) sounds before bends on narrow mountain roads. Today PostAuto AG operates over 900 routes. A post bus trip through the Alps — for instance over the Furka or the Glaubenbielen — is an authentic Swiss experience.",
  "wienerisch.w-051": "The Würstelstand (sausage stand) is a Viennese institution: a small kiosk where Burenwurst, Käsekrainer, Bosna and Frankfurter are sold with mustard and a roll. Classics like the \"Bitzinger\" on Albertinaplatz or at Schwedenplatz are meeting points for politicians, artists, students and taxi drivers. Here the Viennese \"Schmäh\" (charming banter) is celebrated in its purest form.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-050": "The Fränkische Schweiz (Franconian Switzerland) is a limestone landscape in Upper Franconia between Forchheim, Bayreuth and Bamberg — named after Switzerland because of its rugged rocky scenery. It is regarded as the region with the highest brewery density in the world: over 200 breweries in a very small area. Castles, caves (Teufelshöhle, Sophienhöhle), climbing rocks and idyllic valleys make it a hiker's paradise. In autumn the hop gardens glow golden yellow.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-051": "Horst Schimanski (played by Götz George) was the Duisburg Tatort detective who shaped the image of the Ruhr region on television from 1981 to 1991. With his denim jacket, his casual manner and his blunt way, he represented the Ruhrpott man par excellence. His famous \"Scheiße!\" (Shit!) and his rough methods made him a cult figure. Even after his death in 2016, Schimanski remains a symbol of the Ruhr region.",
  "alemannisch.al-050": "The Winzer is the winegrower — a central profession in the Alemannic region. Kaiserstuhl, Markgräflerland, Ortenau and Lake Constance have a winegrowing tradition thousands of years old, going back to the Romans. Many winegrowing families have farmed their estates for generations. The winegrowers' cooperatives of the Kaiserstuhl are among the best in Germany — their Pinot Noir and Pinot Gris enjoy international renown.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-046": "A \"Werzel\" — Palatine word for carrot or root vegetables in general. \"Wäsche mir Werzel zum Gulasch, mei Schatz?\" (Will you wash some carrots for the goulash, my dear?) Also used figuratively for a sturdy, root-like person. From Middle High German \"wurzel\". Central to Palatine farmhouse cooking — added to almost every dish. Variations: rote Werzel (carrot), gelbe Werzel (parsnip), Petersilien-Werzel (root parsley).",
  "tirolerisch.ti-046": "Speckknödl are hearty dumplings made of stale bread and bacon, served in soup or with sauerkraut. A flagship of Tyrolean dumpling cuisine.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-046": "De Reje is the rain. When it rains, people prefer to stay at home. A frequent weather word in the rainy Saarland.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-046": "Dat Been is the leg, plural de Beene. \"Op de Beene blieven\" means to stay on one's feet. A Low German basic word for the limbs.",
  "badisch.bad-046": "Glei means right away or at once. \"I kumm glei\" means \"I'm coming right away\". A frequent time word with which one announces an imminent action.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-046": "Macha means to do or to make. \"Was machsch?\" means \"What are you doing?\". One of the most frequent verbs in everyday Vorarlberg speech.",
  "steirisch.st-046": "D Marille is the apricot, the Austrian word for it. From apricots one makes jam, dumplings and schnapps. Common throughout the Austrian region.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-046": "Obers is whipped cream or cream. A coffee comes with a dollop of whipped cream (Schlagobers). A common Austrian kitchen word.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-046": "Dröög means dry, both in terms of the weather and of dry humor. \"En dröög Humor\" is a dry, subtle wit. The opposite of natt (wet).",
  "brandenburgisch.br-046": "Sense appears in the expression \"Dann is Sense!\" meaning \"then it's over\" or \"that's the end of it\". The vivid word (literally: scythe) proclaims a definitive end, for instance of one's patience or of a matter.",
  "oberpfaelzisch.op-046": "Fertn (also fert) means \"last year\". The old Upper German word is also found in Firn, the snow from the previous year. \"Fertn wars no koid\" means \"last year it was still cold\". Common in the Bavarian region.",
  "hessisch.h-072": "Term for someone with conspicuously large, protruding eyes, or for staring at someone with wide-open eyes. \"Mach kaa Glubschauche!\" (Don't make goggle eyes!) is said to someone who stares incredulously or dumbly. The word combines \"glubschen\" (to stare) with \"Auche\" (Hessian for eyes) and is meant affectionately mocking.",
  "berlinisch.b-068": "Berlin-Mitte is the historic and political centre of the capital, with the Museum Island, the Brandenburg Gate, the Reichstag and Friedrichstraße. This is where the government quarter lies, with the Federal Chancellery and the Reichstag building. The district is at once a tourist magnet, an economic centre and a residential area for the better-off. The Hackesche Höfe are an architectural jewel within the district.",
  "bayerisch.by-063": "The „Knödl\" is the Bavarian side dish par excellence: a round dumpling made of potatoes, bread rolls or a mixture of both. There is the „Erdäpfelknödl\" (potato dumpling), the „Semmelknödl\" (made with stale bread) and the „mixed\" Knödl. Sweet variants: apricot or quark dumplings. To swirl half a dumpling around in sauce is high Bavarian culinary art. In Bavaria and Austria a staple food.",
  "saechsisch.s-051": "Frederick Augustus I of Saxony (1670–1733), known as „Augustus the Strong\", was Elector of Saxony and King of Poland. Famous for his physical strength (he is said to have broken horseshoes) and his 354 children (a legendary, exaggerated figure). He shaped Baroque Dresden: the Zwinger, the Frauenkirche, the Augustusburg and the Green Vault are his creations. Under him Saxony experienced a cultural heyday.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-053": "After Daimler, Bosch is Stuttgart's second most important corporation — founded in 1886 by Robert Bosch. Known for spark plugs, household appliances, tools and automotive supplies. Bosch is 92% owned by the Robert Bosch Foundation — a Swabian peculiarity that makes Bosch a more public-good-oriented corporation. The Bosch headquarters are in Gerlingen near Stuttgart. Swabian tinkerer heritage in its purest form.",
  "koelsch.k-059": "The Rhing is the Cologne form of the Rhine — the lifeline of the city and its cultural heart. Cologne lies on the left bank of the Rhine and has looked out over the river for two millennia. The Rhine promenade, the Rhine kilometres and the annual „Kölner Lichter\" fireworks display over the Rhing shape the Cologne way of life. „Born on the Rhing\" is a profession of identity.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-055": "FC St. Pauli is Hamburg's cult football club, with its skull-and-crossbones flag and left-alternative image — a „neighbourhood club\" (Kiezclub) with a worldwide fan base. Home stadium: the Millerntor-Stadion on the Heiligengeistfeld. St. Pauli stands for anti-fascism, animal welfare and multiculturalism. It is regarded as the most political football club in Germany. „Promotion and relegation\" are part of the club's history — what matters is that Pauli stays Pauli.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-054": "The SBB (Swiss Federal Railways) is the national railway company — punctual, clean and with a dense network. Over 3,000 km of track connect even the tiniest villages. SBB punctuality is legendary (over 90% of trains run on time). The GA (general season ticket) entitles holders to unlimited use. Swiss commuters love and sometimes hate the SBB — but it is part of their self-image.",
  "wienerisch.w-052": "In Viennese, the „Sandler\" is a homeless person, someone who lives on the street. The term comes from the sand on which Sandler used to sleep, or from the word „sandeln\" (to play in the sand, to be idle). In Viennese the word is mostly used without a pejorative tone — rather with a mixture of pity and understanding for failed existences. Part of the character of the city of Vienna.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-051": "The 1. FC Nürnberg, affectionately called „Der Club\", is Franconia's best-known football club — founded in 1900, nine-time German champion (though the last title dates from 1968). Home stadium: the Max-Morlock-Stadion. Players such as Max Morlock and Stefan Reuter are club legends. The Club has seen many promotions and relegations, yet remains a core of Nuremberg's identity. „Auf gehts, Glubb!\" is the Franconian battle cry.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-052": "Tatort is Germany's most popular crime series — broadcast on Das Erste every Sunday at 8:15 p.m. since 1970. The Ruhr region has its own Tatort teams: Dortmund with Faber, Bönisch & Co., and earlier Schimanski in Duisburg. The Ruhr Tatort episodes authentically portray the industrial heritage, the working-class neighbourhoods and the region's blunt mentality. On Sunday evenings Tatort gathers millions in front of the television.",
  "alemannisch.al-051": "SC Freiburg is southern Baden's football club — founded in 1904. Under coach Christian Streich (2011–2024) it was regarded as the most likeable club in the German Bundesliga. Club colours: red and black. Home stadium: the newly built Europa-Park Stadion. Known for sustainable management, good youth development and fair play — the „Breisgau Brazilians\" are a modern model for German football.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-047": "A „Schoofseggel\" — a Palatine fool or idiot, literally „sheep-sack\" (a sheep's scrotum). „Was bisch du fer a Schoofseggel, hosch s'falsche Auto wegge!\" (What a Schoofseggel you are, you've towed away the wrong car!). A drastic swear word, but mostly used in an affectionately exasperated way, not really insulting. A classic Palatine folk saying. Similar to „Saukerl\" or „Dappschädel\" — part of the rough but warm-hearted Palatine vocabulary.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-047": "Kaspressknödl are flat, pressed dumplings made with Graukas (grey cheese), pan-fried and served in beef broth. A Tyrolean speciality.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-047": "De Dorscht is thirst. Ich hann Dorscht means „I am thirsty\". A cold spritzer (Schorle) helps against the Dorscht. An everyday word for a bodily need.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-047": "groot means big, the counterpart of lütt (small). En grooten Kerl is a big fellow. One of the most common adjectives in Low German.",
  "badisch.bad-047": "ebbe is the filler word „eben\" or „halt\" (just, simply), which presents a matter as a given. So isch s ebbe means „that's just how it is\". It expresses Baden's easy-going composure.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-047": "schaffa means to work. Viel schaffa müaßa means „to have to work a lot\". Hard work is held in high esteem in the Ländle (Vorarlberg).",
  "steirisch.st-047": "Topfen is quark, the Austrian word for it. Topfen is used to fill strudel and dumplings or to make a spread. A basic ingredient in many flour-based dishes.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-047": "A Beisl is a small, simple tavern or pub where you can eat and drink cheaply. Ins Beisl geh means to go to your local pub.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-047": "De Kieker is the binoculars, derived from kieken (to look). In the expression een op den Kieker hebben it means to keep a close eye on someone.",
  "hessisch.h-074": "The Hessian Quetschekuche (plum cake) is a classic on every coffee table in late summer and autumn. A tray bake made of yeast dough or shortcrust pastry, densely topped with halved, pitted plums and often sprinkled with crumble or cinnamon sugar. Some Hessian housewives claim that the best Quetschekuche is baked with yeast dough.",
  "berlinisch.b-071": "Marlene Dietrich (1901–1992) was a world-renowned actress and singer born in Schöneberg. With „The Blue Angel\" (1930) she became a Hollywood legend. She refused to work for the Nazis and supported the Allies as a US soldier — many Berliners hated her for that for a long time. Today she is an icon of Berlin, buried at the Stubenrauchstraße cemetery in Friedenau.",
  "bayerisch.by-064": "The Maibaum (maypole) is a tall, decorated tree trunk that is put up in the village centre on 1 May — colourful ribbons, guild signs and the green crown showcase the diversity of the place. During the „maypole stealing\" neighbouring villages try to steal the tree — it is then returned in exchange for beer and a snack (Brotzeit). A central Bavarian folk tradition that strengthens the village community.",
  "saechsisch.s-052": "The Frauenkirche is Dresden's most emblematic building — a Baroque domed church, built 1726–1743. It was destroyed in 1945, lay as a heap of rubble for 45 years and was rebuilt after the fall of the Wall with enormous donations (completed in 2005). The Frauenkirche stands for German reconciliation and resurrection. Its black-and-white speckled façade — where old and new stones mingle — is its trademark.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-054": "Porsche is Stuttgart's third great automobile corporation — founded in 1931 by Ferdinand Porsche. The plant in Zuffenhausen produces the famous 911s. The Porsche Museum in Zuffenhausen, with its spectacular architecture, is a tourist magnet. Anyone who „works at Porsche\" enjoys special recognition. The 911 is a symbol of German-Swabian engineering.",
  "koelsch.k-060": "The Hohenzollern Bridge is the most heavily used railway bridge in Germany and connects the main station with the right bank of the Rhine. Famous are the tens of thousands of love padlocks that couples attach to the bridge railing. With the cathedral in the background, it is one of the most photographed motifs in Cologne.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-056": "The Reeperbahn is Hamburg's most famous street — the „most sinful mile in the world\" in St. Pauli. Here there are theatres, bars, clubs, the erotic trade and restaurants. The name comes from „Reeper\" (rope-maker) — ship's ropes used to be made here. In the 1960s the Beatles played their first concerts in the clubs of the Reeperbahn. The Reeperbahn Festival is today one of the most important music festivals in Europe.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-056": "The „Älpler\" or „Senn\" is the Swiss mountain farmer who spends the summer on the alpine pasture — tending the livestock, milking the cows and producing alpine cheese directly in the herdsman's hut. A dreamy yet hard existence, marked by early rising, dependence on the weather and solitude. In September comes the Alpabfahrt (the Swiss equivalent of the cattle drive down from the mountains). The Älpler culture is part of the Swiss self-image and a UNESCO heritage.",
  "wienerisch.w-053": "„Bobo\" is a modern Viennese term for the urban, well-off bohemian-bourgeois class — academics with beard oil, organic lattes, a cargo bike and an apartment in the 7th district. The word comes from English, but has taken on a typically Viennese colouring with a slightly ironic undertone. Viennese Bobo culture is concentrated around the Neubaugasse, the Mariahilfer Straße and the Karmeliterviertel.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-052": "The „Bratwurst-Glöckle\" is a traditional sausage stall located right beneath the bell tower of the Sebalduskirche in Nuremberg. Nuremberg grilled sausages have been grilled here since 1313 (!) — one of the oldest fast-food traditions in the world. Three or six of the little sausages in a pewter dish with sauerkraut are a cult classic. Generations of Nurembergers and tourists have had their bratwurst experience here. A genuine Nuremberg institution.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-053": "Bochum Total is Europe's largest free city-centre festival, held every year in early July in Bochum's city centre. More than 100 bands perform on several stages — indie, rock, pop. 800,000 visitors come from all over the Ruhr region. The festival is a symbol of Bochum's music scene and of the young, creative Ruhr region. After Herbert Grönemeyer's anthem „Bochum\", Bochum Total is the second most important Bochum experience.",
  "alemannisch.al-052": "The Europa-Park in Rust (Baden) is Germany's largest amusement park and, after Disneyland Paris, the second most popular in Europe. Founded in 1975 by the Mack family — economically one of the most successful family businesses in southern Germany. With 18 themed areas based on European countries, over 100 attractions and 5.7 million visitors a year. It lies between Freiburg and Strasbourg — French and Swiss families come too.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-048": "„Speyer\" — episcopal and cathedral city on the Rhine in the Palatinate. „Da Speyerer Dom, des is UNESCO-Welterbe.\" (The Speyer Cathedral is a UNESCO World Heritage Site.) Famous for the largest Romanesque cathedral in Germany (begun in 1030), the Museum of Technology and the Altpörtel tower. A member of the SchUM cities (Jewish World Heritage). A historic Palatine episcopal residence with a magnificent old town. The wine festival, the pretzel festival and the Emperor Days are its annual highlights.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-048": "Zelten is the rich fruit bread with figs, nuts and dried fruit that is baked at Christmas time. A traditional Tyrolean and South Tyrolean pastry.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-048": "Die Worschd is the sausage, in Saarland especially the Lyoner or the Bratworschd from the barbecue (Schwenker). Des is mir Worschd means, figuratively, „I couldn't care less\".",
  "ostfriesisch.of-048": "gau means fast or quick. Man gau! means „quick!\". Whoever is gau hurries up. A common word for speed on the coast.",
  "badisch.bad-048": "noi means no, the opposite of jo (yes). It can range from a decisive Noi! to a drawn-out hesitation. An everyday word for answering.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-048": "hüt means today. Hüt han i frei means „today I have the day off\". Together with moarn (tomorrow) and gescht (yesterday) it is an important word for time.",
  "steirisch.st-048": "S Obers is cream, and when whipped it is Schlagobers. On the coffee cup (Kaffeehäferl) or the cake goes a Schlagobers. A common Austrian word.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-048": "Vogerlsalat is lamb's lettuce (corn salad), often dressed with pumpkin seed oil and potatoes. A popular side dish in Carinthian and Austrian cuisine.",
  "mecklenburgisch.mk-048": "bregenklöterig means sullen, muddled or slightly addled in the head. It is made up of Bregen (brain) and klötern (to rattle) — as if one's brain were rattling.",
  "hessisch.h-075": "In Frankfurt people fondly and tongue-in-cheek call the Main river „de Bach\" (the brook) — which Frankfurters see with mild self-irony: the Main is of course no brook, but a sizeable river. The Hibbdebach-Dribbdebach distinction (see h-007) builds on this. Outside Frankfurt too, „Bach\" is the normal word for a small stream.",
  "berlinisch.b-072": "The Spreepark in the Plänterwald was, in GDR times, the only permanent amusement park of East Berlin. After reunification it fell into ruin and became a Lost Place with a rusty Ferris wheel — a cult object for photographers and urban explorers. The site is currently being redeveloped as an art and culture park, and the Ferris wheel is to be restored.",
  "bayerisch.by-065": "The „Almabtrieb\" is the traditional driving of the cows down from the summer Alpine pasture into the valley, usually at the end of September. If the cattle have survived the summer weeks without mishap, the cows are decorated especially festively — with flowers, wreaths and large bells („Glockenkühe\", bell cows). In the village they are celebrated. A central Bavarian-Alpine custom and event that attracts tourists.",
  "saechsisch.s-053": "The Semperoper is Dresden's most famous opera house, built 1841–1878 by Gottfried Semper. It is the home of the Sächsische Staatskapelle Dresden and is regarded as one of the most beautiful opera houses in Europe. Destroyed in the war, it was reopened in 1985. Famous premieres: Wagner's „Tannhäuser\" (1845) and „Der Fliegende Holländer\" (1843). Tickets are highly sought after — going to the opera is part of Dresden's high culture.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-055": "Stuttgart 21 is Germany's most controversial railway project — Stuttgart's above-ground main station is to be rebuilt into an underground station. Planned since 1994, originally estimated at 2.5 billion euros, now at over 11 billion. „Black Thursday\" in 2010, with police action against demonstrators in Stuttgart's Schlossgarten, is a symbol of civic resistance. The opening has been repeatedly postponed.",
  "koelsch.k-068": "Kamelle are the sweets and candies thrown from the floats into the crowd during the Rose Monday parade. The shout „Kamelle!\" belongs to every procession. Children spend hours collecting them in bags and pouches they bring along. Nowadays chocolate, biscuits and small toys are thrown too — all of them together are called „Kamelle\".",
  "plattdeutsch.p-057": "Hamburg's Speicherstadt is the largest contiguous warehouse complex in the world — built on oak piles, with red-brick architecture in the style of North German brick Gothic. Erected 1883–1927 as a duty-free warehouse for coffee, tea, spices and oriental carpets. A UNESCO World Heritage Site since 2015. Today it houses the Speicherstadtmuseum, the International Maritime Museum and the HafenCity right next door.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-057": "Yodeling is an Alpine vocal art in which one switches rapidly between chest and head voice — without words. Originally a means of communication between Alpine herdsmen across the mountain slopes, today it is an independent musical form. There is the „Naturjodel\" (improvised, artful) and the „Jodellied\" (with lyrics). Swiss yodeling clubs keep the tradition alive. Yodeling is UNESCO cultural heritage.",
  "wienerisch.w-054": "„Tachinieren\" is Viennese for lazing about, doing nothing, indulging in idleness. The word has a likeable ring to it — tachinieren is no reproach, but a respectable Viennese art of living. The coffeehouse patron who sits for three hours over a single Einspänner reading the newspaper is practising tachinieren at a high level. Goethe called it „noble idleness\" — the Viennese call it tachinieren.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-053": "The Nuremberg Kaiserburg (Imperial Castle) towers above the old town — one of the most important imperial castles of the Holy Roman Empire. Since the 11th century emperors and kings (33 emperors in all, from Conrad III to Charles V) received guests here. The Sinwellturm (keep, 1200) and the double chapel are highlights. The deep castle well, 50 metres down, is a feat of engineering. Today a museum and a landmark of Nuremberg.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-054": "Herbert Grönemeyer (born 1956 in Göttingen, raised in Bochum) is Germany's most successful German-language musician — his album „Mensch\" (2002), with over 4 million copies sold, is the best-selling German album of all time. His hit „Bochum\" (1984) became the unofficial anthem of the Ruhr-area city. His committed style and his attachment to the Pott make him a Ruhr-region icon.",
  "alemannisch.al-053": "Karlsruher SC is northern Baden's traditional club — founded in 1894. It played in the Bundesliga for over 30 years, but since the 2000s it has been a classic „yo-yo club\" bouncing between the 1st and 2nd divisions. Home ground: the Wildparkstadion. Famous players: Oliver Kahn (goalkeeping legend), Mehmet Scholl, Sean Dundee. „Liebe gewinnt!\" (Love wins!) is the KSC battle cry — a club with a loyal fan base despite a chequered career.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-049": "D'„Kuhblum\" — the Palatine term for dandelion, literally „cow flower\". „Im Frühling stehen die Kuhblumen am Wegrand.\" (In spring the dandelions stand by the roadside.) From the farming tradition — cows like to eat them. Also used as a salad plant, a wild vegetable. Young leaves make a tangy spring salad. The roots are used in natural medicine. The yellow flower is valued as bee fodder. A Palatine childhood memory of blowing-the-seed-head games.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-049": "Schwammerl are the mushrooms one gathers in the forest, such as Eierschwammerl (chanterelles). Hunting for Schwammerl is a popular pastime in autumn.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-049": "De Weck is the bread roll. At the baker's (Beck) you fetch fresh Weck in the morning. A Lyonerweck is a roll with Fleischwurst (Lyon sausage), a popular snack.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-049": "bannig is a strong intensifier in the sense of „very\" or „enormously\". Dat is bannig good means „that is very good\". A typically North German word.",
  "badisch.bad-049": "D Schnägg is the snail that nibbles the heads of lettuce in the damp garden. Schnägg is also used for someone who is slow on the move.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-049": "moarn means tomorrow, the coming day. Bis moarn! (See you tomorrow!) is said when parting. Its counterparts are hüt (today) and gescht (yesterday).",
  "steirisch.st-049": "Kren is horseradish, grated sharp and served with the Brettljause (cold platter), with ham or Selchfleisch (smoked meat). Styrian Kren is a well-known regional product.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-049": "A Tschurtschn is a fir or spruce cone that you pick up in the forest. Jokingly, a clumsy person is also called „du Tschurtschn\" (you Tschurtschn). A typically Carinthian word.",
  "hessisch.h-076": "A „Lumbe\" is actually a rag (an old scrap of cloth), but in Hessian it is often used figuratively for a slovenly, unreliable person. „Du aler Lumbe!\" (You old Lumbe!) can be mildly chiding, but also genuinely scolding. In some areas it is almost an affectionate expression among friends.",
  "berlinisch.b-073": "Schönefeld Airport was, in GDR times, the main airport of East Berlin. Since October 2020 it has been part of the new BER airport (Berlin Brandenburg Willy Brandt). The BER itself is legendary for its 14-year construction delay and its cost explosion — it is regarded as a symbol of German mega-projects that can go wrong. Berliners still mock the airport to this day.",
  "bayerisch.by-066": "The „Wirtshaus\" (inn/tavern) is the soul of every Bavarian village — meeting point, Stammtisch, banquet hall and eatery all in one. Here people eat, drink, discuss and play cards. The „Stammtisch culture\" — the reserved table for a fixed group of regulars — is sacrosanct. A good Wirtshaus has a landlord with character, an honest Bavarian menu and a cool Helles from the wooden barrel.",
  "saechsisch.s-054": "The Dresden Zwinger is a Baroque edifice commissioned by Augustus the Strong, completed in 1728 by Matthäus Daniel Pöppelmann. Today it houses important museums: the Gemäldegalerie Alte Meister (Old Masters Picture Gallery, with Raphael's Sistine Madonna), the porcelain collection and the Mathematisch-Physikalischer Salon. Badly destroyed in the war, the Zwinger was among the first buildings to be rebuilt. The famous Kronentor (Crown Gate) with the Polish royal crown is an icon.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-056": "The Cannstatter Volksfest (colloquially „die Wasen\") is Swabia's answer to the Oktoberfest — Germany's second-largest beer festival, with over 4 million visitors a year. It has been held since 1818, originally as a harvest festival. Today it features beer tents, fairground rides and the famous 26-metre-high Fruchtsäule (fruit column). Swabians come in Lederhosen and Dirndl — but: the litre of beer is called „Krug\" here, not „Maß\"!",
  "koelsch.k-069": "Strüßjer are the small bouquets of flowers thrown from the floats during the Rose Monday parade. They are traditionally part of the throwing material and are especially prized to catch. Whoever catches a Strüßje is considered blessed for the carnival. Strüßjer are also popular at the Geisterzug (ghost parade) and other carnival processions.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-058": "The Elbphilharmonie — „Elphi\" for short — is Hamburg's spectacular concert hall on top of an old quay warehouse in the HafenCity. Opened in 2017 after 10 years of construction and 866 million euros in costs. The wave-shaped glass architecture looks like a ship. The acoustics of the Großer Saal (Grand Hall) rank among the best in the world. The Plaza at 37 metres up is a public viewing terrace overlooking the harbour and the city.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-058": "Roger Federer (born 1981 in Basel) is, with 20 Grand Slam titles, one of the greatest tennis players of all time and is considered a Swiss national hero. Known for his elegant, seemingly effortless game. He retired in 2022 — his farewell match at the Laver Cup, with Rafael Nadal as his doubles partner, produced emotional scenes. Federer stands for Swiss values: modesty, quality, international class.",
  "wienerisch.w-055": "The „Watschn\" is the slap in the face — a quintessentially Viennese word that is also used in Bavaria. In Vienna, however, the Watschn has a particular cultural depth: it is the symbol of direct disciplinary consequence, once a matter of course, today mostly only metaphorical („Da hab i mir a Watschn ghoid\" — I caught myself a slap there). Omnipresent in Viennese songs, jokes and proverbs. „A gscheide Watschn\" would be a hearty slap in the face.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-054": "Richard Wagner (1813–1883) chose the Franconian town of Bayreuth as the site for his Festspielhaus — the only theatre in the world built solely for his works. The Bayreuth Festival has been held here since 1876 — the most important Wagner festival in the world. Tickets are booked out 10 years in advance. „Tannhäuser\", „Tristan und Isolde\" and „Der Ring des Nibelungen\" are performed here with unique acoustics. A Wagner pilgrimage site.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-055": "The Westfalenstadion — today officially the Signal Iduna Park — is the home of Borussia Dortmund. With 81,365 seats it is Germany's largest football stadium. The famous Südtribüne (South Stand, the „Yellow Wall\") with 25,000 standing places is the largest standing terrace in Europe and offers one of the most intense atmospheres in world football. Champions League matches here are legendary — reporters come from all over the world for the atmosphere.",
  "alemannisch.al-054": "Markgräfler wine is grown in the Markgräflerland between Freiburg and Basel — historically the land of the Margraves of Baden. The most important grape variety is the Gutedel (called „Chasselas\" in Switzerland) — a variety grown in Germany almost exclusively here. Mild, floral, low in alcohol. Spätburgunder (Pinot Noir) and Müller-Thurgau also thrive splendidly. The winegrowers' cooperatives in Ehrenkirchen, Müllheim and Auggen are recognised worldwide.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-050": "s'„Gschiss\" — the Palatine word for unnecessary fuss, drama, or commotion. „Mach kein Gschiss, des is nur a Kratza!\" (Don't make a fuss, it's only a scratch!) Shortened from „Gscheiss\" (Geschiss), a vulgar origin used with an affectionately annoyed tone. Often said to children or dramatic adults. „A großes Gschiss\" for „a big commotion\". A classic Palatine saying used in every family.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-050": "Moosbeer are the blueberries that grow on the Alpine pasture floors in summer. From Moosbeer one makes compote, cake and schnapps. A sought-after forest fruit.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-050": "De Woi is the wine, in the Saarland often drunk as a spritzer (Schorle). An da Saar un Mosel wächst guder Woi (Good wine grows on the Saar and Moselle). Part of the sociable way of life.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-050": "De Buur is the farmer who works the land in the marsh behind the dyke. De Buurfru is the farmer's wife. Agriculture shapes East Frisia to this day.",
  "badisch.bad-050": "Es Kätzle is the kitten, the young cat. The diminutive in -le is typical of Badisch for everything small and dear, as with the Kätzle too.",
  "vorarlbergerisch.vb-050": "guat means good. Des isch guat gsi means „that was good\". One of the most common adjectives, also in the greeting alles Guate (all the best).",
  "steirisch.st-050": "D Stiege is the staircase, the Stiegenhaus the stairwell. I geh d Stiegn aufi means „I'm going up the stairs\". A common Austrian word.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-050": "D Pratzn is the big, coarse hand or paw. Wasch da amol deine Pratzn means to wash your dirty hands. A hearty South Bavarian word.",
  "hessisch.h-077": "In Hessian usage, \"kaputt\" is used not only for broken objects but also for exhausted people. \"Ich bin total kaputt!\" means you are completely worn out after a tiring day. The word comes from the French \"capot\" (beaten, defeated) — whoever is kaputt simply has no reserves left.",
  "berlinisch.b-075": "Berlin form of \"diese\" (these) — part of the famous trio \"icke, dette, kieke mal\". \"Detten\" is an old plural form that today appears almost only in proverbs and cabaret sketches. It shows the historical depth of Berlin dialect, which has preserved many forms from Middle High German.",
  "bayerisch.by-067": "The \"Goaßlschnalzn\" is an Alpine folk art: rhythmic cracking sounds are produced with a long leather whip (\"Goaßl\") — solo or in groups. Originally herdsmen used the Goaßl to guide their cattle; today Goaßlschnalzn is an independent traditional sport with clubs and competitions. At festival processions or the cattle drive down from the mountains (Almabtrieb) there are Goaßlschnalzn performances — loud and impressive.",
  "saechsisch.s-055": "Räuchermännchen (smoking figurines) are wooden figures from the Erzgebirge in which small incense cones are burned — the smoke comes out of the mouth or a pipe. Classic motifs: miner, forester, carter, tailor. Made since the 19th century in the villages around Seiffen, Olbernhau and Annaberg — usually as family craft. During Advent, every Saxon home is adorned with Räuchermännchen. UNESCO heritage.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-057": "The Schwäbische Alb is a low mountain range in the south of Baden-Württemberg, celebrated by geologists as the \"Swabian karst highland\". Shaped by limestone, caves, sheep farming and ancient juniper heaths. On the Alb stand medieval castles such as Hohenzollern, Lichtenstein and Teck. The UNESCO World Heritage site of the oldest art (Vogelherd Cave, Hohle Fels) lies here. Hohenzollern Castle is considered the \"most beautiful castle in Germany\".",
  "koelsch.k-071": "Ash Wednesday marks the end of Cologne carnival and the beginning of Lent. Symbolically the \"Nubbel\" — a life-sized straw doll — is burned to shift onto it all the sins of the carnival season. With a fish meal in the brewery taverns and quiet mourning for the fifth season, the foolish revelry comes to an end.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-059": "Ostfriesland (East Frisia) is the northwesternmost region of Lower Saxony on the North Sea — flat marshland with dikes, sheep and Frisian islands (Borkum, Juist, Norderney, Baltrum, Langeoog, Spiekeroog, Wangerooge). The East Frisians have their own humour, their own language (Low German and East Frisian Low German) and the world's highest tea consumption (300 litres per capita per year). Ostfriesentee (East Frisian tea) is a cult.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-059": "Toblerone is the most famous Swiss chocolate brand — invented in 1908 by Theodor Tobler and Emil Baumann in Bern. The triangular prism is meant to symbolize the peak of the Matterhorn, and a bear is even hidden in the city coat of arms of Bern. Honey and almond pieces make up the original recipe. At Geneva airport, Toblerone is bought in vast quantities as a souvenir — Swiss chocolate, a worldwide brand ambassador.",
  "wienerisch.w-056": "St. Stephen's Cathedral — affectionately called \"Steffl\" — is the Gothic landmark of Vienna on Stephansplatz in the 1st district. The 137-metre-high south tower dominates Vienna's skyline. The roof is covered with 230,000 colourful tiles depicting the double-headed eagle. Severely damaged in the war in 1945, the cathedral was rebuilt in a national effort. More than just a church — a national symbol.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-055": "The Bayreuth Festival Hall on the Green Hill — built in 1876 according to Wagner's plans — is an architectural one-off: the orchestra pit is hidden, the acoustics are incomparable, the seats are wooden and uncomfortable (Wagner wanted no comfort to distract from the work). Tickets are allocated via a waiting list — patience of 10+ years is needed. One of the most spiritual theatre experiences in the world.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-056": "The Veltins-Arena (formerly Arena AufSchalke) is the stadium of FC Schalke 04 in Gelsenkirchen. With 62,271 seats it is one of the most modern stadiums in Europe — with a retractable roof and a pitch that can be slid outside. The arena opened in 2001 and hosted several World Cup matches in 2006. Even though Schalke currently play in the 2nd division — the Veltins-Arena remains a place of pilgrimage for the royal-blue fans.",
  "alemannisch.al-055": "The Gutedel is the favourite grape of the Alemannic region — one of the oldest grapevines in Europe, cultivated as far back as Phoenician times. In the Markgräflerland it is made into a dry white wine — mild, floral, low in acidity. In Switzerland it is called Chasselas (Fendant), in France Chasselas. The Markgräfler Gutedel has a protected designation of origin and is regarded as the perfect summer wine.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-051": "\"Hilft nix\" — pragmatic Palatine acceptance of unchangeable circumstances. \"Da Regen heut, hilft nix, mer müsse halt drin bleiwe.\" (The rain today, it can't be helped, we'll just have to stay inside.) Short, resigned, but without bitterness. Reflects the relaxed Palatine philosophy of life. Variant: \"Was hilft's\" (what's the use). It is said in many situations, from complaints about the weather to financial difficulties. A classic Palatine belief in fate.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-051": "Murmele is the marmot, which lives high in the mountains and whistles loudly when danger threatens. In the past, a healing ointment was made from the fat of the Murmele.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-051": "Es Dippe is the pot in which one cooks — for example the Dibbelabbes, which takes its name from the Dippe. A basic word of Saarland cuisine.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-051": "De Kark is the church, often an old brick church with a free-standing bell tower. Sünndags geiht man na de Kark (On Sundays one goes to church). The centre of many East Frisian villages.",
  "badisch.bad-051": "Es Häfele is a small pot or jug. Jedes Häfele find sei Deckele (Every little pot finds its little lid) is a well-known proverb: there is a suitable partner for everyone.",
  "steirisch.st-051": "Da Schmäh is a joke, a witty remark or the typical charm. An guatn Schmäh führn means to talk wittily and charmingly. A well-known Austrian word.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-051": "D Goschn is a coarse word for the mouth or maw. Holt di Goschn means \"be quiet\". A große Goschn hom means to be cheeky or loud-mouthed. A word in use throughout the south.",
  "hessisch.h-078": "A short, casual Hessian greeting among people who know each other — common above all in the Frankfurt area. \"Bei!\" is often combined with \"Gude!\" or used on its own, especially among young people. The greeting is informal and warm, but can also serve as a call for attention: \"Bei, hörste mer zu?\" (Hey, are you listening to me?).",
  "berlinisch.b-076": "The Stulle is the Berlin sandwich — a thick slice of bread with butter and cold cuts. Unlike the southern German Brotzeit or the northern German Bemme, the Berlin Stulle is simple, hearty and not pretentiously elaborate. Schinkenstulle, Wurststulle, Käsestulle — the variations are endless. A must in every Berlin school break.",
  "bayerisch.by-068": "The \"Schuhplattler\" is the traditional Bavarian-Tyrolean folk dance: men slap their shoes, knees and thighs rhythmically — a powerful, virtuosic choreography. Originally the Schuhplattler was a courtship dance of young lads; today it is kept alive by traditional costume clubs. At folk festivals, weddings and the district music festival, the Schuhplattler is a must. The women meanwhile dance a calmer round dance.",
  "saechsisch.s-056": "The Schwibbogen is a candle arch from the Erzgebirge that is placed in the window during Advent. It symbolizes the miners' longing for daylight, which they had to do without down in the depths. The oldest Schwibbögen date from the 18th century, traditionally made of cast iron, today mostly of wood. The motifs show miners, lacemakers and the \"Glück auf\" symbol. Lit with one candle per \"arch\".",
  "schwaebisch.sw-058": "Friedrich Schiller (1759–1805) is Swabia's most famous poet — born in Marbach am Neckar, died in Weimar. \"Die Räuber\", \"Wilhelm Tell\", \"Don Carlos\", \"Maria Stuart\" — classics of German literature. Together with Goethe he founded Weimar Classicism. In Marbach stands the German Literature Archive holding Schiller's handwritten estate. Swabians are proud of their poet — even if Goethe later became more popular.",
  "koelsch.k-072": "The Nubbel is a life-sized straw doll that hangs in front of brewery taverns and pubs during carnival. On Carnival Tuesday at midnight it is ceremonially burned — and with it, symbolically, all the sins committed during carnival. \"Wer war's? — De Nubbel!\" (Who was it? — The Nubbel!) is the ritual answer.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-060": "The East Frisian tea ceremony is UNESCO World Heritage — black Assam tea, brewed in a fine porcelain pot and served with \"Kluntje\" (large rock-candy crystals) and cream. The cream is not stirred — it forms cloudy patterns. Three cups are obligatory (otherwise you are considered impolite). East Frisians drink an average of 300 litres of tea per year — more than the British! Tea is part of the East Frisian way of life.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-060": "The Zurich Bahnhofstrasse is one of the most expensive shopping streets in the world — 1.4 km from the main station to Bürkliplatz on Lake Zurich. Here luxury boutiques (Bucherer, Cartier, Tiffany) and major Swiss banks (UBS, Credit Suisse — now UBS) line up one after another. The Bahnhofstrasse is car-free and a symbol of Swiss prosperity. Beneath the street: the banks' gold bars in the vaults.",
  "wienerisch.w-057": "Schönbrunn Palace is the former summer residence of the Habsburgs in Vienna's 13th district. With over 1,400 rooms, the Schönbrunn Zoo (the oldest zoo in the world, founded in 1752), the Gloriette and the gardens, it is UNESCO World Heritage and Vienna's most visited sight. Marie Antoinette and Empress Sisi grew up here. Today it is a popular place for walks, concerts and palace tours.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-056": "Würzburg is the Franconian university town on the Main — known for the Residence (UNESCO World Heritage, with the Tiepolo fresco), the Marienberg Fortress on the hill, the Old Main Bridge with statues of saints, and the wines of Würzburg. With 130,000 inhabitants, it is a charming medium-sized town. Almost completely destroyed in the Second World War, it was then rebuilt at great effort. The university is one of the oldest in Germany.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-057": "The Zeche Zollverein in Essen is probably the best-known symbol of the structural change in the Ruhr area. Until 1986 the largest hard-coal mine in the world, today it is UNESCO World Heritage (since 2001) and a cultural centre with museums, restaurants and events. The Bauhaus architecture of the winding tower is an icon. The silhouette of the double-bock tower is the landmark of the Ruhr area par excellence.",
  "alemannisch.al-056": "The Hexenfeuer (witch fire) is an Alemannic tradition — on Walpurgis Night (30 April) and on Funkensonntag (the first Sunday after Carnival) large fires are lit on the mountains. The tradition goes back to pre-Christian spring customs and symbolized the driving away of the winter spirits. Today it is still kept up in many Black Forest villages. In the evening, families hike to the fire site with torches.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-052": "Da \"Bobbes\" — Palatine word for bottom, behind. \"Hock dei Bobbes auf de Stuhl, ned auf da Bodde!\" (Put your behind on the chair, not on the floor!) Used affectionately and cheekily, especially with children. Also in the saying \"A Tritt in da Bobbes\" — a well-deserved punishment. Related to the Hessian \"Babbes\" and the Bavarian \"Hintern\". Part of the rich Palatine vocabulary of body language.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-052": "The Föhn is the warm, dry downslope wind that blows across the Alps and makes the weather change. Many complain of headaches and tiredness when the Föhn is blowing.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-052": "The Pann is the pan in which one fries and bakes. In da Pann mache mer Brägele oder Spiegeleier (In the pan we make fried potatoes or fried eggs). An everyday kitchen word.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-052": "En Döntje is a short, humorous story or anecdote that one tells while chatting (Klönen). East Frisians are known for their dry Döntjes.",
  "badisch.bad-052": "arg serves as an intensifier in the sense of \"very\". Des isch arg schee means \"that is very nice\". An intensifying word omnipresent in the southwest.",
  "steirisch.st-052": "gscheit means clever or sensible, and as an intensifier also \"properly, thoroughly\". Sei gscheit! urges someone to be sensible, gscheit regnen means to rain heavily. A Bavarian-Austrian word.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-052": "tschentschn means to whine, grumble or complain plaintively. Heer auf zan tschentschn means to stop the whining. An onomatopoeic Carinthian word.",
  "hessisch.h-079": "The Hessian affectionate term for father — corresponds to the standard German \"Papa\", but sounds broader and softer. \"Mei Bappe\" is the typical way of addressing one's own father in Hessian family life. The word combines warmth and respect and is handed down from generation to generation. With small children: \"Bei zum Bappe!\" (Come to Daddy!)",
  "berlinisch.b-077": "In Berlin dialect, the \"Olle\" is either the wife (in an informal, sometimes annoyed tone) or an older woman. \"Meine Olle\" is what a Berlin husband says with a knowing familiarity — a declaration of love, Berlin-style. In the plural, \"die Ollen\" can also mean old acquaintances. It sounds crude, but is usually meant affectionately.",
  "bayerisch.by-069": "The Tegernsee is one of the most beautiful lakes in Upper Bavaria, nestled among the foothills of the Alps 50 km south of Munich. The region around the lake is considered Bavaria's celebrity and high-price corner: the Söder family lived there, and many Munich artists and entrepreneurs have houses here. The Tegernsee brewery produces one of the best-known Bavarian Helles beers. In clear weather, the mountains are reflected in the water.",
  "saechsisch.s-057": "The Trabant — affectionately called \"Trabbi\" — was the iconic car of the GDR, built from 1957 to 1991 at the Sachsenring factory in Zwickau. With its Duroplast body (often mocked as \"cardboard\") and its two-stroke engine, it wasn't the best design, but it was the symbol of an entire generation. When the Wall fell in 1989, Trabbis struggled their way to West Berlin — images that went around the world. Today it's a cult classic car.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-059": "Georg Wilhelm Friedrich Hegel (1770–1831) — born in Stuttgart — is one of the most influential philosophers of all time. His \"Phenomenology of Spirit,\" \"Science of Logic\" and the philosophy of right have shaped philosophy to this day. Hegel attended the famous \"Tübinger Stift\" together with Hölderlin and Schelling. The Swabian educational tradition, with its scholarship seminaries, produced world-class philosophers.",
  "koelsch.k-073": "The Karnevalssitzung is the typical Cologne form of indoor carnival: a stage program lasting several hours with comedic orators (Büttenredner), dance corps, bands and sketches. The sessions of the great societies such as the Rote Funken or the Treue Husaren are legendary. Women wear costumes, men suits and medals — a mix of tradition and silliness.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-061": "Grünkohl (kale) is THE northern German winter dish — the secret kale recipes of East Frisia, Lower Saxony and Schleswig-Holstein vary from family to family. Cooked with Pinkel (groats sausage), Mettenden, Kassler and bacon. Harvested only after the first frost, because the frost makes the kale sweet. Kale walks with Boßeln (a ball-throwing game) and a hearty meal are social highlights of the winter.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-061": "Lake Zurich stretches southeast of Zurich — 40 km long, from the city into the Linth region. The wealthy \"Goldküste\" (the right shore on the sunny side) and the \"Pfnüselchüschte\" (the left shore, cooler and damper) — the unequal shores are a running joke. In summer, swimming in the crystal-clear water is popular; in winter, the walks with their Alpine panorama are famous. The boat to Rapperswil is a classic.",
  "wienerisch.w-058": "The Hofburg in the center of Vienna was, from the 13th century onward, the main residence of the Habsburgs and is today the seat of the Austrian Federal President. With its 18 wings, 19 courtyards and 2,600 rooms, it is one of the largest palace complexes in the world. It also houses the Spanish Riding School, the Imperial Treasury and several museums. The Hofburg embodies the imperial history of Austria.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-057": "The Würzburg Residence is one of the most important Baroque palaces — built from 1720 to 1744 by Balthasar Neumann for the Würzburg prince-bishops. The staircase, with its 600 m² ceiling fresco by Giovanni Battista Tiepolo, is considered the most important ceiling painting in the world. A UNESCO World Heritage Site since 1981. Severely destroyed in the war, the fresco miraculously survived. Today it is one of the most visited palaces in Germany.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-058": "The Landschaftspark Duisburg-Nord is a unique symbol of the structural change in the Ruhr region — on the grounds of a decommissioned blast-furnace works, a huge public park arose with preserved industrial colossi. You can climb the blast furnaces, divers dive in old gasometers (!), and at night the whole site is spectacularly lit in color. A flagship project of the IBA Emscher Park.",
  "alemannisch.al-057": "The Schemenrennen is an Alemannic Fasnet tradition in Imst (Tyrol) and Telfs — every 4–5 years, masked men run through the town, pursued by \"Roller\" and \"Scheller.\" A UNESCO World Heritage. A wild, original form of the Fasnet. The Schemen masks are masterpieces of craftsmanship, often centuries old. An archaic, breathtaking tradition that takes place only every few years.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-053": "The \"Pälzer Worschdmark\" — the largest wine festival in the world, held every September in Bad Dürkheim. \"Am Worschdmark gehen mer mit der ganzen Familie!\" (\"We go to the Worschdmark with the whole family!\") Over 500,000 visitors in 8 days. First mentioned in 1417. With festival tents, wine bars, sausage stalls and a carousel. A classic Palatinate tradition with culinary specialties and live music. Known for the largest \"Schoppen\" consumption volume in Germany.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-053": "Patschn are the slippers you slip into at home. A flat tire is also colloquially called a Patschn. A cozy everyday word.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-053": "gscheit means clever or sensible. Sei gscheit! is an admonition to be reasonable. Ebbes Gscheites lerne means to learn something proper. A versatile word.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-053": "vertellen means to tell. Vertell maal! invites someone to recount something. Over tea, people love to chat for hours (vertellt). A central verb of the Klönschnack (cozy chatting) culture.",
  "steirisch.st-053": "D Hackn is the work or the job; hackeln means to work. In d Hackn gehn means \"to go to work.\" A colloquial word common throughout the Austrian region.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-053": "A Tschoppale is a clumsy, awkward person, usually meant in a good-natured, teasing way. To a clumsy child one says affectionately a kloans Tschoppale. A Carinthian expression.",
  "hessisch.h-080": "The Hessian counterpart to \"Bappe\" — the affectionate term for the mother. \"Mei Mamme\" has a warm, familiar ring to it and expresses the close family bond of the Hessians. Grandmothers are often called \"Großmamme\" or simply \"Oma.\" With small children: \"Bei zur Mamme!\" (\"Come to Mommy!\") is often the first word.",
  "berlinisch.b-078": "In Berlin dialect, the mother is quite naturally called \"Mutti\" — even by grown-ups. The famous \"Berliner Mutti\" is an institution: resolute, warm-hearted, with a clear opinion and good food. Even Chancellor Angela Merkel was fondly called \"Mutti\" — a term that combines affection and respect.",
  "bayerisch.by-070": "The Chiemsee — called the \"Bavarian Sea\" because of its size — is the third-largest lake in Germany. With three islands (Herreninsel with Ludwig II's Herrenchiemsee Palace, Fraueninsel with its famous monastery, and Krautinsel), it is an excursion paradise. The old Chiemsee railway and the historic paddle steamers still run today. In summer it is full of sailors, surfers and bathers.",
  "saechsisch.s-058": "RB Leipzig — officially \"RasenBallsport Leipzig\" — was founded in 2009 by the Red Bull corporation and rose in just 7 years from the 5th to the 1st Bundesliga. Home stadium: the Red Bull Arena (formerly the Zentralstadion). Many football fans regard RB as a \"plastic club\" because of its corporate financing. Nevertheless, RB is today a firmly established top Bundesliga club with Champions League experience. A Saxon identity for Leipzig fans.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-060": "Friedrich Hölderlin (1770–1843) is Swabia's lyric poet — born in Lauffen am Neckar, died in Tübingen. His hymns, odes and the novel \"Hyperion\" have shaped German poetry. He spent the last 36 years of his life in the \"Hölderlin Tower\" by the Neckar, mentally deranged but still writing poetry. The tower is today the Hölderlin Museum and a landmark of Tübingen. \"Whoever trusts neither the wind nor the sea ...\"",
  "koelsch.k-074": "The Bütt is the lectern in the shape of a barrel from which the Büttenredner deliver their rhymes and political satire at carnival sessions. The Büttenrede is an art form in its own right — pointed, satirical and always in verse. Famous Büttenredner become known beyond the carnival season and perform for years.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-062": "The Krabbenbrötchen is a simple but royal specialty of the North Sea coast — a fresh bread roll, thickly topped with North Sea shrimp (more precisely, small pink brown shrimp) and a dollop of remoulade. The shrimp are caught in the North Sea, peeled by hand in the Netherlands and Morocco, and then shipped back to Germany — which explains the high prices. A good Krabbenbrötchen costs 8–12 euros — and is worth every cent.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-062": "The Matterhorn (4,478 m) is the best-known mountain in the Alps and the national symbol of Switzerland. With its unmistakable pyramid shape, it towers over Zermatt in the Valais. First ascent in 1865 by Edward Whymper — the triumph turned into tragedy when four of his companions fell to their deaths during the descent. Today it is one of the most photographed mountains in the world. It also adorns the Toblerone packaging.",
  "wienerisch.w-059": "The Naschmarkt is Vienna's largest and best-known market, located along the Wienzeile between the 4th and 6th districts. Across 2.3 hectares there is everything: fruit, vegetables, cheese, fish, spices from all over the world, as well as numerous restaurants and snack stands. On Saturdays a flea market is also held. The name does not come from \"naschen\" (nibbling) but from \"Asch\" (a wooden pail for milk). Multicultural and lively.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-058": "Coburg is a historic residence town in Upper Franconia — until 1918 the capital of the Duchy of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha. The Veste Coburg, the \"Franconian Crown,\" is one of the largest castles in Germany. Coburg is famous for its connection to the European high nobility: Prince Albert (of Coburg) married Queen Victoria, through which the Coburgs spread worldwide. Today it is questionable: an AfD town. But historically and culturally significant.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-059": "\"Tiger and Turtle — Magic Mountain\" is a walkable steel sculpture in Duisburg, opened in 2011. It looks like a roller coaster — but visitors can walk it on foot (except for the loop, which is only for looking). The view over the Ruhr region is breathtaking. A modern symbol of the creative reinvention of the industrial region. Illuminated at night, it is spectacular.",
  "alemannisch.al-058": "The Black Forest cuckoo clock is the best-known export product of the Alemannic region — a mechanical wall clock with a wooden cuckoo that springs out and calls on the hour. Invented around 1730 in Schönwald in the Black Forest by Franz Anton Ketterer. Genuine Black Forest clocks are certified by the VdS association. The Clock Museum in Furtwangen tells the history. A worldwide cult — especially among American and Japanese tourists.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-054": "A \"Spitzbu\" — a rascal, a scamp, often with an affectionate note. \"Du Spitzbu, hosch widder die Apfelpie geklauft!\" (\"You rascal, you've swiped the apple pie again!\") It is used especially for children and young men. It means someone with cunning wit, harmless mischief. Related to the standard German Spitzbube. A classic Palatinate family saying. Also the Spitzbuben cookie — a Christmas cookie with a jam filling.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-054": "A Sackerl is a small bag or pouch, for example for shopping or for an ice cream. A typically Austrian word that is heard throughout the country.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-054": "hann means to have. Ich hann, du hasch, mir hann — the Saarland conjugation. Ich hann kä Zeit means \"I have no time.\" A central auxiliary verb.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-054": "Pannkoken are the pancakes, baked in the Pann (pan), sweet or with bacon. Thick Pannkoken are a popular main course of northern German cuisine.",
  "steirisch.st-054": "A Trumm is a large piece or a massive chunk. A Trumm Brot is a thick hunk, a Trumm Kerl a burly man. A Bavarian-Austrian word.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-054": "gach means abrupt, sudden or steep. Es is ma gach gwordn means that someone suddenly felt dizzy or unwell. A gacher Steig is a steep path.",
  "hessisch.h-081": "A \"Schoppe-Pedder\" (Schoppen-Peter) is a die-hard Frankfurt apple-wine connoisseur and regular in the Sachsenhausen taverns — usually an older gentleman who knows all about every variety and has his exact favorite tavern. The Schoppe-Pedder is a Frankfurt institution: humorous, quick-witted and always with a Geripptes (ribbed apple-wine glass) in hand.",
  "berlinisch.b-079": "The Berlin form of \"Vater\" (father) — just as with \"Mutta/Mutti,\" the father becomes the \"Vatta.\" The double-T reinforces the Berlin brevity and clarity. \"Mein Vatta\" is a familiar term with family pride. In Berlin family culture, parents are figures of respect, but always approachable on equal footing.",
  "bayerisch.by-071": "The Zugspitze (2,962 m) is the highest mountain in Germany and lies in the Wetterstein range on the border with Austria. It can be reached by the cog railway from Garmisch or by the cable car from the Eibsee. At the summit: the German summit cross, a mountain restaurant, a weather tower and, in clear weather, a view of four countries. In winter it is a ski area with a glacier lift. The black-white-blue summit panorama is a Bavarian landmark.",
  "saechsisch.s-059": "Dynamo Dresden is THE traditional club of Saxony — founded in 1953, 8-time GDR champion. After reunification came a deep fall through the 2nd and 3rd divisions. The fans in the Rudolf-Harbig-Stadion are legendary for their loyalty and atmosphere — the black-and-yellow fan choreographies are among the most intense in Germany. Even when success fails to come — Dynamo remains Dresden's love.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-061": "Tübingen is Swabia's university town — founded in 1477. The Eberhard Karls University of Tübingen is one of the oldest universities in Europe. The old town, with the Hölderlin Tower, Hohentübingen Castle and the collegiate church, is worthy of World Heritage status. Tübingen is considered left-alternative — governed by Boris Palmer (Greens). Punting tours (Stocherkahn) on the Neckar are a tourist must.",
  "koelsch.k-076": "The Hänneschen-Theater is the traditional Cologne rod-puppet theater, founded in 1802. The main character Hänneschen is the cheeky Cologne boy, surrounded by Tünnes, Schäl, Bärbelchen and other folk characters. The plays are in Kölsch and convey Cologne history and folk wisdom. Generations of Cologne residents grow up with the Hänneschen.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-063": "The shrimp cutter is the iconic fishing boat of the North Sea coast — 8 to 15 meters long, often painted in bright colors, with the typical gallows over the stern for hoisting the nets. In harbors like Greetsiel, Neuharlingersiel or Cuxhaven, tourists see the cutters in port. Shrimp fishing is hard — especially in winter — and regulated by EU quotas. A dying craft.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-063": "The Sechseläuten is Zurich's spring festival on the third Monday in April. The highlight: the burning of the „Böögg\" (a snowman straw figure) at 6:00 p.m. (six chimes of the bells — hence the name). The faster the head explodes, the better the coming summer (according to popular belief). The guilds parade through the city in historical costumes. A UNESCO cultural heritage and Zurich's largest festival.",
  "wienerisch.w-060": "Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart (1756–1791) spent almost half his life in Vienna — here he composed „The Marriage of Figaro\", „Don Giovanni\", „The Magic Flute\" and his last symphonies. Vienna is full of Mozart traces: the Mozarthaus in the Domgasse, his grave at St. Marx Cemetery, the Mozart Monument in the Burggarten. The Mozartkugeln (actually from Salzburg) are world-famous. Mozart and Vienna belong inseparably together.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-059": "The Bocksbeutel is the characteristic bulbous, flat wine bottle of Franconian wine — a protected bottle shape reserved exclusively for Franconian quality wines. The shape goes back to the medieval drinking vessel. With 0.75 liters of content, the Bocksbeutel stands for Franconian wine tradition — Silvaner, Müller-Thurgau, Bacchus. At the Bocksbeutel-Stadl restaurant in Würzburg it is the home of Franconian wine culture.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-060": "„Kappes\" is the word for white cabbage in the Ruhr area and the Rhineland. From the Latin „caput\" (head — the head of cabbage). Sauerkraut, pickled white cabbage, is a central element of Ruhr and Rhenish cuisine. Potato pancakes with Kappes, stew with Kappes, boiled Kappes with bacon — the variations are endless. „Schief gewickelt sein wie ein Kappes\" (to be wrongly wrapped like a cabbage) — an idiom for confusion.",
  "alemannisch.al-059": "The glassblowing tradition in the Black Forest goes back to the Middle Ages — the abundance of wood made glassblowing possible here. The Höhenmoos glassworks and the Wolfach glassworks are still in operation. Black Forest glass art — drinking glasses, vases, Christmas tree ornaments — has been an export good for centuries. Today, a few family businesses keep this craft alive. Mouth-blown Black Forest glass is a collector's item.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-055": "„Gulla\" — Palatine word for gully, drainage shaft. „Schau, da Gulla is verstopft, da läuft Wasser zurück.\" (Look, the gully is clogged, water is running back up.) From the English „gully\". Also used figuratively: „A Mund wie a Gulla\" (a mouth like a gully) — someone who talks a lot and loudly. Standard vocabulary in everyday Palatine — every homeowner knows the Gulla.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-055": "D Stiege is the staircase. You go up the Stiege to the first floor. A word for the staircase in a house that is widespread throughout the Alpine region.",
  "saarlaendisch.sl-055": "esse means to eat — and fittingly, in line with the motto Hauptsach gudd gess (the main thing is to eat well), people in Saarland eat with pleasure and eat well. Mir esse zsamme means „we eat together\".",
  "ostfriesisch.of-055": "Grog is hot rum with water and sugar that warms you on cold days. Rum mutt, Water kann, Zucker draf nich fehlen (rum must, water may, sugar must not be missing), goes the well-known saying.",
  "steirisch.st-055": "Schöpsernes is the meat of the Schöps, the castrated ram, that is, mutton. As Schöpsernes mit Kraut (mutton with sauerkraut), it used to be a traditional tavern dish.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-055": "A Hatscher is a long, arduous walk or trek on foot. Bis auffi af d Hüttn is a ordentlicher Hatscher (it's quite a trek up to the hut). Someone who hatscht walks slowly and laboriously. An Austrian word.",
  "hessisch.h-082": "An affectionate Hessian term for a little girl or the youngest daughter — also used as a pet name for one's partner. „Mei Klaane\" (my little one) has a very tender ring to it. In larger families, distinctions are often made: „die Klaane\" (the youngest daughter), „die Mittler\" (the middle one) and „die Groß\" (the oldest).",
  "berlinisch.b-080": "A coarse Berlin term for the face, especially an unattractive or sullen one. „Zieh nich so 'ne Bratze!\" (Don't pull such a Bratze!) urges someone to look friendlier. The word probably comes from Low German and is known throughout northern Germany. Combined into „Kackbratze\" — see entry b-041 — it becomes a real swear word.",
  "bayerisch.by-072": "FC Bayern München, with over 32 German championship titles, six Champions League titles and an annual turnover of more than 800 million euros, is the most successful German football club. Founded in 1900, the club plays in the Allianz Arena (Fröttmaning). Players like Beckenbauer, Müller, Maier, Rummenigge, Lahm and today Müller, Kimmich, Musiala are legends. „Mia san mia\" (we are who we are) is the club's motto and attitude to life.",
  "saechsisch.s-060": "Johann Sebastian Bach (1685–1750) spent the last 27 years of his life in Leipzig as Thomaskantor at the Thomaskirche. Here he composed the St. Matthew Passion, the Mass in B minor and a large part of his cantatas. His grave is today in the Thomaskirche. Leipzig cultivates the Bach legacy in the Bach Society, the Bach Archive and the annual Bach Festival. Bach is Saxony's greatest son.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-062": "Hohenzollern Castle near Hechingen is one of Germany's best-known castles — the ancestral seat of the Hohenzollern dynasty, who later became kings of Prussia and German emperors. In the 19th century it was rebuilt in its present form as a „fairytale castle\". It stands majestically on an 855-meter-high conical peak and is visible from afar. One of the most photographed castles in Germany.",
  "koelsch.k-077": "The Heimatovend is a Cologne event format — usually organized within the Veedel (neighborhood), with Kölsch music, dialect readings, dancing and the cultivation of customs. Heimatovende are held by carnival societies, citizens' associations or parishes. They are smaller than carnival sessions, but just as important for Cologne culture and identity.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-064": "The „Friesennerz\" (Frisian mink) is the mockingly affectionate name for the yellow raincoat of northern Germans — especially the Frisians. In any northern German weather (that is, constantly), you see people in the yellow rain outfit from Helly Hansen, Driza-Bone or similar brands. The Friesennerz is a symbol of northern German pragmatism: practicality before beauty, function before fashion. Tourists are recognizable anyway.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-064": "The Swiss Federal Council consists of seven members with equal rights who together form the head of state — a model unique in the world. Every year the Federal President changes, but all seven have equal standing. They are elected by the United Federal Assembly. Concordance (the magic formula) ensures proportional representation of the parties. Federal councilors are addressed as „Frau Bundesrätin\" or „Herr Bundesrat\".",
  "wienerisch.w-061": "The Viennese waltz is Austria's musical calling card — emerging in the early 19th century, perfected by the Strauss dynasty (Johann Strauss the elder, Johann Strauss the younger). „On the Beautiful Blue Danube\" is Austria's unofficial anthem. The Viennese waltz is danced in three-quarter time at 60 bars per minute — faster and livelier than other waltz styles. Mandatory at the Opera Ball.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-060": "Silvaner is the classic Franconian wine grape variety — first documented in Franconia as early as 1659. Spicy, mineral, with nuances of pear and hay. The Franconian wineries in the Main valley (Castell, Bürgerspital Würzburg, Iphofen) produce world-renowned Silvaner. It is traditionally served in the Bocksbeutel. With the GG classification (Grosses Gewächs) it ranks among Germany's top wines. A pasta companion par excellence.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-062": "Father's Day (Ascension Day) is its own institution in the Ruhr area: groups of men set off into nature with a handcart full of beer, going from one drinking station to the next. It usually ends late and merrily drunk. A tradition spread throughout Germany, but particularly pronounced in the Ruhr. The „Vatertagstour\" (Father's Day tour) is part of a man's year like beer is part of the Pott.",
  "alemannisch.al-060": "The Schwarzwaldverein (Black Forest Association) is Germany's tradition-steeped hiking club — founded in 1864 in Freiburg. It maintains 24,000 km of hiking trails in the Black Forest and provides the signposts, shelters and maps. With over 67,000 members, it is one of the largest hiking organizations in Europe. The „Westweg\" (Pforzheim–Basel) and the „Mittelweg\" are its best-known long-distance trails. Black Forest hiking is organized and signposted by it.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-056": "the „Bauchwehrum\" — Palatine word for stomachache, often in children. „Mei Klainer hot Bauchwehrum nach em Kuche-Esse.\" (My little one has a stomachache after eating cake.) Also used figuratively — „A Bauchwehrum um eppes\" means worries or a queasy feeling about something. A classic family word. Also in the question: „Hosch Bauchwehrum?\" (Do you have a tummy ache?) as an expression of sympathy.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-056": "The Greißler is the small corner shop in the village, where you can get everything for daily life. Many Greißler have disappeared today, but they are regarded as a piece of home.",
  "ostfriesisch.of-056": "De Mettwust is the hearty, smoked Mettwurst sausage that goes on bread or into the kale. A savory component of northern German cuisine.",
  "kaerntnerisch.kt-056": "D Jause is the small snack in the late morning or afternoon, often bread, bacon and cheese. The word comes from the Slovenian južina and is in common use throughout Austria.",
  "hessisch.h-084": "A humorous, affectionate Hessian term for the bottom — used especially with children and in a relaxed family atmosphere. „Setz dei Bobbes hin!\" (Sit your bottom down!) is a friendly, direct request to sit down. The word is soft and harmless and never appears in polite conversation, but constantly in everyday life.",
  "berlinisch.b-081": "Berlin expression for the discreet, inconspicuous disappearance — when you leave a party without saying much of a goodbye, you „verkrümelt\" yourself (slip away). The vivid expression refers to the scattering of crumbs, which one hardly notices. It is not a flight, but an elegant strategy for getting away.",
  "bayerisch.by-073": "The Allianz Arena in the north of Munich (Fröttmaning) is the home stadium of FC Bayern, opened in 2005. With its famous outer shell of 2,874 diamond-shaped ETFE foil cushions, it can glow in the colors red (Bayern), white and blue. 75,000 seats. One of the most modern stadiums in Europe and a landmark of Munich. Also the home stadium of the German national team for important matches.",
  "saechsisch.s-061": "Karl May (1842–1912) is Saxony's most famous writer — born in Ernstthal near Chemnitz. His adventure novels about Winnetou and Old Shatterhand shaped generations of German readers, although May himself never set foot in America. In Radebeul near Dresden stands the Villa „Shatterhand\" with the Karl May Museum. The Karl May Festival in Bad Segeberg is a German cult phenomenon.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-064": "The „Swabian salute\" — derived from Goethe's Götz von Berlichingen — is the most famous Swabian insult: „Leck mi am Arsch!\" (Kiss my arse!) or in full: „Er aber, sag's ihm, er kann mich am Arsch lecken!\" (Tell him he can kiss my arse!) Actually coarse, it has taken on a certain courtly form in Swabian usage — almost a phrase of familiarity between friends. Never meant seriously, but always forceful.",
  "koelsch.k-078": "A Krätzje is a short, pointed Cologne story or joke, often in rhyme. Krätzjer are told at carnival sessions, at the regulars' table or at family celebrations. They have a long tradition and are part of Cologne's storytelling culture. The punchline is usually risqué but harmless and ends in Cologne laughter.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-065": "Boßeln is a traditional northern German folk sport — a mix of bowling and hiking. A group rolls a ball or plastic ball along a country road. Whoever gets the farthest wins. In between, beer or schnapps is drunk — the convivial character is paramount. At the kale dinner, Boßeln is a must. Also proof: you can still drink even while doing sports.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-065": "The Swiss franc (CHF) is one of the strongest currencies in the world — a symbol of stability and prosperity. The banknotes depict Swiss personalities and themes: Le Corbusier, Sophie Taeuber-Arp, Alberto Giacometti. The Swiss National Bank (SNB) artificially pegged the franc's exchange rate to the euro for years — in 2015, the removal of the peg caused shockwaves. The Swiss have an almost emotional relationship with their currency.",
  "wienerisch.w-062": "SK Rapid Vienna — founded in 1899 — is Austria's record champion with 32 titles. The club colors are green and white, the „Block West\" is the fan section, the Allianz Stadion in Vienna-Hütteldorf is home. The „Rapid-Viertelstunde\" — the last 15 minutes in which Rapid traditionally steps up a gear — is a Viennese sports myth. Fierce city rival: FK Austria Vienna. The Vienna derby is one of the oldest and most emotional in Europe.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-061": "Rauchbier (smoke beer) is a Bamberg beer specialty — the malt is smoked over a beechwood fire, which gives the beer an unmistakable smoky flavor. The Schlenkerla brewery in Bamberg's old town has brewed the most famous Rauchbier since 1405 (!). The taste takes some getting used to — some find it reminiscent of ham. Anyone who has once been hooked can't do without it.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-063": "Düsseldorf — sometimes disparagingly set apart from the Ruhr as a „Schickimicki-Stadt\" (posh, flashy city) — is the state capital of North Rhine-Westphalia, seat of many insurance companies and home of the Königsallee. Düsseldorf and the Ruhr area have a traditional rivalry: Düsseldorf is seen as elegant, the Pott as down-to-earth. Düsseldorf's Altbier vs. Kölsch in Cologne and Helles in the Pott — each has its own peculiarities.",
  "alemannisch.al-061": "Donaueschingen is a town on the southern edge of the Black Forest and is considered the source of the Danube — here the Brigach and Breg rivers join to form the Danube. In the palace park there is an official \"Donauquelle\" (Danube source) fountain owned by the municipal utility. Donaueschingen is famous for the Donaueschingen Music Days (a modern classical festival) and the palace of the Fürstenberg family. The famous Fürstenberg beer is also brewed here.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-057": "The \"Kerwe\" — the Palatine village festival celebrating the church's patron saint, the most important occasion in the village calendar. \"D'Kerwe is dies Jahr widder a Wahnsinn!\" (The Kerwe is amazing again this year!). With a festival tent, wine serving, dancing, often with the \"Kerweborsch\" (Kerwe lads) as the main protagonists. Every village has its own date, usually in late summer/autumn. A tradition since the Middle Ages. Related to the Bavarian \"Kirta,\" but with its own Palatine character. Even Ludwig II of Bavaria attended the Palatine Kerwe.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-057": "Jänner is January, the first month of the year. The word is common in Austria and Tyrol, where in January deeply snow-covered mountains beckon for skiing.",
  "hessisch.h-085": "The \"Pleitegeier\" (bankruptcy vulture) is a vivid metaphor for looming financial difficulties or financial ruin. \"Der Pleitegeier kreist über mir\" (The bankruptcy vulture is circling over me) is what one says when debts get out of hand. The word is known throughout the German-speaking world, but in the Hessian merchant context (Frankfurt as a financial center) it has a particular resonance.",
  "berlinisch.b-082": "In Berlin dialect, as in many other German dialects, items of clothing are simply called \"Klamotten.\" The word comes from Rotwelsch (thieves' cant) and originally meant \"rags.\" Berliners usually say \"Klamotten\" instead of \"Kleidung\" (clothing) — it sounds more casual and unpretentious. Going to \"buy new Klamotten\" is especially popular among young people.",
  "bayerisch.by-075": "The \"Föhn\" is a warm, dry downslope wind that blows down from the Alps into the Bavarian foothills. It brings extremely clear visibility (you can see the Alps from 100 km away) and unusually high temperatures — even in winter. But it gives many people headaches, makes them lethargic or irritable (\"Föhnkrank,\" Föhn-sick). When Munich residents complain about being in a bad mood, the Föhn is often to blame.",
  "saechsisch.s-062": "\"Quarkkeulchen\" are a Saxon specialty: small pancakes made from quark, potatoes, flour and eggs, fried golden brown in the pan. They are served with sugar, cinnamon, applesauce or plum jam. The dish is a classic way of using up leftovers — leftover potatoes from the previous day are used this way. Every Saxon family has its own recipe. Today it is a highlight of Saxon cuisine.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-065": "The Spätzle board is the traditional Swabian kitchen tool for making Spätzle: a flat wooden board onto which the dough is spread and scraped with a knife into thin strips into the boiling water. Real Swabian grandmothers only make Spätzle with the board — the modern Spätzle press is considered uncouth. The skilled \"scraping\" is a high Swabian culinary art. It requires practice and experience.",
  "koelsch.k-079": "Mähschen is the Cologne diminutive of Mädchen (girl) — warm, friendly and carefree. It is used for little girls, but also for young women, always affectionately and never disparagingly. The ending \"-schen\" is typical of the Cologne diminutive and turns every word into something endearing.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-066": "\"Hamborg\" is the Low German form of Hamburg. With almost 2 million inhabitants, it is Germany's second-largest city — a Hanseatic city with over 1,000 years of history. Harbor, the Elbe, the Alster, the Reeperbahn, the Speicherstadt: Hamburg combines maritime tradition with a modern metropolis. The Hanseatics are proud of their independence (city-state) and their North German pragmatism. The \"Hamborger Veermaster\" shanty is a classic.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-066": "\"Stutz\" is the Swiss colloquial term for francs — just as \"euros\" can colloquially become \"dough\" (Kohle). Nobody says \"costs twenty Swiss francs\" — everyone says \"twenty Stutz.\" The term comes from the medieval \"Stutzgulden\" or \"Schtutzer.\" In negotiations, salaries and prices, \"Stutz\" is the everyday word. A million Stutz is a \"Mio.\"",
  "wienerisch.w-063": "The Vienna subway comprises five lines (U1, U2, U3, U4, U6) and takes Viennese and tourists across the city. The Vienna network is considered one of the best in the world. The historic Stadtbahn (today's U4) was built in 1898 by Otto Wagner — the stations are Art Nouveau works of art. The Vienna subway is the city's lifeline — open 24 hours on weekends.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-062": "Kellerbier is an unbunged, naturally cloudy beer served directly from the brewery cellar — a quintessential Franconian classic. Especially in the beer cellars of Franconian Switzerland (Forchheim, Bamberg), Kellerbier is stored in wooden barrels and served straight from the cellar in the beer garden. Low acidity, gently sparkling, with a slightly yeasty taste. Best accompaniment: a Schäuferla.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-064": "\"Datt\" is the Ruhr area variant of \"das\" — with the characteristic double-T instead of the standard German \"das.\" Accompanied by a rolling intonation and the typical direct pronunciation. \"Datt is doch klar!\" (That's obvious!), \"Datt geht so nich!\" (That won't work like this!). The word is a hallmark of Ruhr German — whoever says \"datt\" identifies as a Pott person. A little word with a big identity.",
  "alemannisch.al-062": "The Council of Constance (1414–1418) was one of the most important events of the late Middle Ages — here the schism of the Catholic Church was ended, three rival popes were deposed and Martin V was elected the new pope. The reformer Jan Hus was also burned here. For 4 years Constance was the political center of Europe. Today the Imperia statue in the harbor (a satirical courtesan holding a pope and an emperor in her hands) commemorates the era.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-058": "The \"Aabaagschdäbbel\" — Palatine word for the evening blessing, the last glass of Schorle (wine spritzer) before going to bed. \"A Aabaagschdäbbel zum Abschluss, dann zu Bett!\" (An Aabaagschdäbbel to finish, then off to bed!). A classic Palatine drinking tradition — the last glass, often bid farewell with a singsong. Variation: \"Schlummertrunk\" (nightcap) in standard German. Whoever can actually pronounce the word is sober enough for one more. A classic Palatine tongue-twister test.",
  "tirolerisch.ti-058": "The Hoagascht is the relaxed evening get-together in the parlor, with talk, music and stories. An old Tyrolean word for cultivated conviviality.",
  "hessisch.h-086": "An affectionately mocking Hessian term for someone with a stuffy, sniffling nose — usually in winter during a wave of colds. \"Du klaaner Schniefnas!\" (You little sniffler!) is sympathetic and teasing at the same time. The word combines \"schniefen\" (to sniffle) with \"Nas\" (nose) and belongs to the Hessian health vocabulary.",
  "berlinisch.b-083": "Berlin dialect for shoes, often with a slightly disparaging or ironic undertone — either old, worn-out shoes or slippers. \"Mach deine Latschen aus!\" (Take your Latschen off!) is what one says at the entrance. The term has spread beyond the Berlin language area and is today understood in almost all of Germany.",
  "bayerisch.by-076": "A \"Wadlbeißer\" is in Bavarian a quarrelsome, aggressive person — literally one who bites you in the Wadln (calves) like a small dog. The image is apt: not big, but tough and unpleasant. In Bavarian politics the term is often used for rebellious backbenchers. Also in sports: a tough, combative player can be a Wadlbeißer.",
  "saechsisch.s-063": "\"Leipziger Allerlei\" is a vegetable dish made from young peas, carrots, asparagus, cauliflower and morels — traditionally served with crayfish and dumplings. The dish is said to have been invented in Leipzig in the 18th century, when wealthy Leipzig merchants gave beggars and tax collectors only this finely chopped vegetable mixture. Today it is a festive dish of Saxon cuisine.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-066": "Stuttgart is the Swabian capital — the state capital of Baden-Württemberg. 630,000 inhabitants, headquarters of Mercedes-Benz, Porsche, Bosch. The city lies in a basin and has 18 districts. Famous: the Schlossplatz, the TV tower (1955, the world's first TV tower), the New Palace, the Wilhelma (zoo). Stuttgart has a marked economic strength and at the same time Swabian understatement.",
  "koelsch.k-080": "Fott is the Cologne expression for backside or bottom — direct, earthy and blunt, like Cologne humor in general. The word appears in many Cologne phrases: \"op de Fott setze\" (to sit down) or \"op de Fott jevalle\" (fallen on one's backside). Stippeföttche is the best-known carnival dance featuring this word.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-067": "Bremen is Germany's smallest city-state and, together with Bremerhaven, home of the northwest German port. A Hanseatic city with over 1,200 years of history. Famous: the Roland (the city's emblem since 1404), the Town Musicians of Bremen (figures from the Grimms' fairy tale), the Schnoor quarter and the Böttcherstraße. Werder Bremen is the local football club. Bremen people are classically North German: reserved, warm-hearted, with their own pride.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-067": "Ticino is the southernmost, Italian-speaking canton of Switzerland — Mediterranean climate, palm trees, granite mountains and Italian way of life. Lugano, Locarno, Bellinzona and Ascona on Lake Maggiore are the main towns. Over the Gotthard you reach another world. Wine, polenta, risotto, mortadella — Ticino cuisine is Italian-influenced. A favorite holiday destination of German-speaking Swiss.",
  "wienerisch.w-064": "The Danube flows through Vienna and is at once lifeline, recreation area and symbol. The Danube Island — 21 km long — was created in the 1970s as flood protection and is today Vienna's largest recreation area. Every year the Danube Island Festival takes place here — Europe's largest open-air festival with free admission. The Old Danube (a backwater) is also a popular summer bathing area.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-063": "\"Ungespundeter\" is a non-pressurized beer served directly from the open wooden barrel in the cellar — therefore milder and softer than modern beer with artificial carbonation. This Franconian brewing tradition is still practiced today in the cellar woods around Bamberg and Forchheim. \"En Seidla Ungespundeter\" (a Seidla of Ungespundeter) with a Schäufela or a sausage sandwich is Franconian food culture in its purest form.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-065": "\"Dasse\" is in the Ruhr area the contracted form of \"dass du\" (that you) — with the typically swallowed \"du.\" \"Mein' dasse jetzt schon gehs?\" — \"Meinst du, dass du jetzt schon gehst?\" (Do you mean that you're already leaving?). This merging comes from the fast, direct speaking style of the Ruhr area. The language is efficient — no unnecessary syllables.",
  "alemannisch.al-063": "The Lake Constance shipping service is a tradition-rich link between Germany, Austria and Switzerland — the \"White Fleet\" of the BSB (Lake Constance Shipping Company) has served the most important shore towns since 1824. Constance, Meersburg, Friedrichshafen, Lindau, Bregenz, Romanshorn — all are connected by ship. A boat trip in summer with a view of the Alps, Mainau and Reichenau is a Lake Constance classic.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-059": "\"Geesch ned\" — Palatine form of \"geht nicht\" (won't do/isn't possible), a direct refusal. \"Drei Schorle in zehn Minuten? Geesch ned!\" (Three Schorle in ten minutes? No way!). Used to reject suggestions or to assess something as impossible. Variations: \"Geesch ned uff\" (won't open, won't work out), \"Geesch ned an\" (won't go, isn't acceptable). Classic Palatine negative vocabulary.",
  "hessisch.h-087": "\"Räs\" describes in Hessian usage a cheese that is very ripe, savory and sharp in taste — Handkäs mit Musik in particular is described this way. A \"räser Käs\" is not for the faint of palate. The word has a positive connotation for cheese lovers — the räser, the better! The term is related to the Swabian \"räs.\"",
  "berlinisch.b-084": "Coming from Yiddish, \"Tacheles reden\" means to speak plainly, without beating around the bush. Berliners love Tacheles — directness is part of the city's culture. \"Reden wir mal Tacheles!\" (Let's talk Tacheles!) introduces any frank, honest conversation. The former Tacheles art house in Mitte was a symbol of Berlin's alternative art scene.",
  "bayerisch.by-077": "A \"Pfundskerl\" is a thoroughly likeable, reliable and capable man — the highest Bavarian praise for a fellow. The word \"pfund\" comes from the coinage system and here means \"valuable\" or \"first-rate.\" A Pfundskerl is helpful, honest and always there when you need him. The female form would be \"Pfundsweib.\"",
  "saechsisch.s-064": "Saxons are famous throughout Germany as \"Coffee Saxons\" — the Saxon coffee culture is legendary. Saxon coffee is proverbially thin (\"Bliemchenkaffee,\" little-flower coffee). The Coffee Saxons have perfected the coffee-klatsch tradition. In Dresden, Leipzig and Chemnitz there are numerous traditional pastry shops where coffee is served with Stollen, Eierschecke and other Saxon specialties. Coffee time is sacred.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-067": "In Swabia one says \"Heimspiel\" (home game) for the situation when you are among Swabians and may finally speak Swabian again — without having to justify the dialect. Swabians are aware that their dialect is sometimes ridiculed in northern Germany, and they enjoy the \"Heimspiel\" atmosphere when they are among their own kind. A word full of identity and pride.",
  "koelsch.k-081": "Köpp is the Cologne form of Kopf (head) — the same in singular and plural. It appears in many phrases: \"dat geiht mer op de Köpp\" (that gets on my nerves/head) or \"Köpp huh!\" (Chin up!/Head up!). The Cologne native often speaks of \"Köpp\" when reminding someone of common sense: \"Benutz ding Köpp!\" (Use your head!).",
  "plattdeutsch.p-068": "Werder Bremen is Bremen's football club, founded in 1899 — four-time German champion. Home stadium: the Weserstadion on the Weser. The club is regarded as a likeable North German underdog with tradition. Club colors green and white. Coaching legends like Otto Rehhagel and players like Marco Bode shaped the successful years. \"Lebenslang grün-weiß\" (Green and white for life) is the fans' rallying cry.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-068": "\"Bündner\" denotes an inhabitant of the canton of Graubünden — and also the famous \"Bündnerfleisch\": dried, air-cured beef served in wafer-thin slices. In the Engadine and in Davos it is still traditionally produced today. Graubünden is trilingual (German, Italian, Romansh) and has world-famous ski resorts such as St. Moritz, Davos and Arosa. The Bündner are considered tough and close to nature.",
  "wienerisch.w-065": "Viennese cabaret is a supreme form of stage art — shaped by Schmäh (Viennese wit), self-irony and political sharpness. Greats such as Karl Farkas, Helmut Qualtinger (\"Der Herr Karl\"), Werner Schneyder, Andreas Vitásek and today Josef Hader have shaped the genre. Viennese cabaret is never merely funny — always also melancholic, socially critical and deeply rooted in the Viennese mentality.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-064": "The Erlangen Bergkirchweih, popularly known as \"Berg,\" is, with over 1.5 million visitors, one of the largest beer festivals in southern Germany — after the Oktoberfest. It has been held annually at Whitsun on the Erlangen Burgberg since 1755. On the Berg there are beer cellars (all unbunged!), Brotzeit (snacks), carousels and a special down-to-earth character. From your table you enjoy the view over Erlangen.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-066": "In the Ruhr region people say \"ich geh nach Aldi\" instead of \"zu Aldi\" — a grammatical peculiarity that bypasses Standard German. Also: \"nach Schalke gehen\" (to Schalke). This preposition makes Ruhr German an unmistakable regiolect. Linguists study this \"Ruhrpott grammar\" as a legacy of Slavic and Low German influences.",
  "alemannisch.al-064": "The flower island of Mainau in Lake Constance is a subtropical garden world — 45 hectares with palm trees, a butterfly house, a rose garden and rare trees. Owned by the Swedish noble family Bernadotte. Mainau Castle and the unique flora attract millions of tourists every year. In summer a sea of blossoms, in winter with the Mainau Flower Show. One of the top attractions on Lake Constance.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-060": "The \"Pälzer Bibliothek\" (Palatine Library) — a collective term for Palatine literature, dialect poetry and stories. \"D'Pälzer Bibliothek spans generations from the wine poem to the novel trilogy.\" Famous authors: Paul Münch, Fritz Claus, Lina Sommer (dialect poetess). Publishers such as the Pfälzer Verlag maintain the literary heritage. Palatine dialect theatre has a lively scene. The connection of wine, homeland and identity is a recurring theme.",
  "hessisch.h-088": "The Advent season has a special significance in Hesse — the Christmas markets in Frankfurt (Römerberg), Wiesbaden (Sternschnuppenmarkt) and Marburg are among the most beautiful in Germany. Mulled wine, Bethmännchen (Frankfurt marzipan pastries) and bratwurst are part of it. The Frankfurt Christmas market is one of the oldest in Germany, documented since 1393.",
  "berlinisch.b-085": "A Berlin term for a mushy, sludgy mass — it can refer to a botched meal, slushy snow or a spoiled mush. \"Det is doch 'ne Pampe!\" is a critical remark about the quality of something. Also common in Saxon and Northern German.",
  "bayerisch.by-078": "The Bavarian word for shoes — singular and plural are the same. The typical vowel shift from \"uh\" to \"ua\" is audible. \"Mei Schuach drucken\" means \"my shoes pinch\". During the Schuhplattler dance the Schuach are indeed slapped — the word belongs to the basic Bavarian vocabulary. Also compounded: \"Bergschuach\" (hiking boots), \"Haferlschuach\" (traditional costume shoes).",
  "saechsisch.s-065": "The Sandmännchen (Little Sandman) is a German TV character who has been telling children bedtime stories every evening just before 7 p.m. since 1959. The GDR version was broadcast on the DFF (Deutscher Fernsehfunk) — today on the RBB. The figure comes from the fairy tale book \"Ole Lukoie\" by Hans Christian Andersen. For Saxons and all East Germans, the Sandmännchen is a piece of childhood — everyone knows the signature tune.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-068": "\"Bissle\" is the Swabian and Alemannic variant of \"Bisschen\" (a little bit) — a classic diminutive with the characteristic \"-le\". A \"Bissle Geduld\" (a little patience), \"a Bissle hier\", \"a Bissle dort\" — the word runs through everyday Swabian life. It expresses Swabian caution and modesty: nobody wants to exaggerate, everything is made small. Also \"Bisselei\" as an activity (fiddling around).",
  "koelsch.k-083": "Schnüss is the Cologne word for mouth, often in the sense of \"keep your trap shut\". \"Halt de Schnüss!\" is coarse, but among friends it is not meant as an insult. The word has a crude yet warm-hearted touch and is typical of the direct Cologne manner. Also positive: \"En jrooße Schnüss han\" (to have a big mouth, i.e. the gift of the gab).",
  "plattdeutsch.p-069": "\"Köm\" is the Low German word for Korn — a clear grain schnapps, often flavoured with caraway (\"Kümmelköm\"). It is part of Northern German drinking culture, often accompanying a beer (\"Lütt un Lütt\"). People in Hamburg and Bremen drink it at breakfast (with a \"Granatsplitter\" — Korn with ground pepper) or as a digestif after the meal. \"En lütt Köm\" is the Northern German answer to Bavarian schnapps.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-069": "Berchtoldstag (2 January) is an additional holiday after New Year's in many Swiss cantons — ideal for easing into the new year calmly. It is named after Berchtold I, the founder of Bern (1191). In some cantons it is traditionally celebrated with nuts, lucky charms and family gatherings. In modern Switzerland it serves above all as an extra day off.",
  "wienerisch.w-066": "The Buschenschank is a traditional Viennese and Lower Austrian tavern where a winegrower is allowed to serve his own wine and cold dishes. The word comes from the \"Buschen\" — a pine bough hung above the door to indicate that the Heuriger is open. \"Ausg'steckt is'\" means: the Buschenschank is open. The typical Viennese Buschenschanken can be found in Grinzing, Sievering, Stammersdorf and Nußdorf.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-065": "Lebkuchen-Schmidt from Nuremberg is probably the best-known brand for Nuremberg Elisen gingerbread — founded in 1927. The hand-signed gingerbread tins, shipped throughout Germany in time for Christmas, are a cult item. Genuine Nuremberg Elisen gingerbread must contain at least 25% nuts, far more than ordinary gingerbread. The tradition goes back to medieval Nuremberg — honey, spices and monastery recipes.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-067": "\"Tachchen\" is a warm, friendly Ruhr region greeting — an endearing form of \"Tach\" (Tag, day). It sounds cordial without being childish. Used between acquaintances and neighbours when passing by, while shopping or at the kiosk. The diminutive \"-chen\" makes the greeting softer and more personal — typical Ruhr directness with a human touch.",
  "alemannisch.al-065": "The island of Reichenau in Lake Constance is a UNESCO World Heritage Site — an important monastic island since the 7th century. In the Middle Ages the Benedictine monastery was a centre of Christian culture and of book illumination. Today three Romanesque churches can be admired (St. Maria und Markus, St. Peter und Paul, St. Georg). Reichenau is also Germany's largest vegetable-growing area — the \"Reichenauer Salate\" (Reichenau lettuces) are famous.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-061": "The \"Grumbeere\" are the potatoes — literally \"ground pears\", because they grow underground. \"Heut gibt's Grumbeere mit weißem Kees un Leinöl!\" (Today there's potatoes with quark and linseed oil!) One of the best-known Palatine words of all and a staple food of the region. Famous is the dish \"Grumbeere un weißer Kees\" (boiled potatoes with quark). The Vorderpfalz is a large growing area, and the \"Pfälzer Frühkartoffel\" (Palatine early potato) is even a protected brand. Without Grumbeere there is no genuine Palatine meal.",
  "hessisch.h-089": "Bethmännchen are small marzipan pastries with three almond halves around them, a Frankfurt Christmas speciality. They were allegedly invented by the confectioner of the banker Bethmann — the three almonds symbolise the three sons. Today they are available in every Frankfurt bakery during Advent. Sweet, almondy and with a crispy top.",
  "berlinisch.b-086": "A Berlin word for a strong craving, an intense longing for something. \"Ick jieper nach 'ner Currywurst\" describes more than mere hunger — it is a real ravenous craving. The word has become rather rare today, but is still alive among older Berliners. Sonorous and expressive — typically Berlin.",
  "bayerisch.by-079": "The diminutive of Vogel (bird) — typically Bavarian with the -erl suffix. \"A Vogerl\" is a small, cute little bird. By extension it is also used affectionately for young girls: \"A liabs Vogerl\" (a dear little birdie). In the tavern one also knows the \"Vogerlsalat\" — lamb's lettuce, which is especially tender in spring. The diminutive with \"-erl\" is one of the characteristic features of Bavarian.",
  "saechsisch.s-066": "The Vogtland in western Saxony (on the border with Bavaria, Thuringia and the Czech Republic) is a low mountain region with its own charm. Known for Plauen lace (UNESCO heritage), musical instrument making in Markneukirchen (violins, violas) and the spa resorts of Bad Elster and Bad Brambach. The Vogtland is considered Saxony's \"land of music\" — Carl Maria von Weber came from this region.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-069": "\"Net hudla\" is a Swabian piece of wisdom — \"don't rush\", but do everything calmly. \"Hudla\" comes from \"hudeln\" (to do something hastily). Swabians are famous for their pragmatism, which takes time — quality before speed. \"Net hudla, schaffe!\" is the Swabian maxim: don't rush, but work properly. An attitude cultivated in the workshops of Daimler, Bosch and Porsche.",
  "koelsch.k-084": "Knoll is the Cologne expression for a big nose — usually meant in a humorous, hearty way. A \"rote Knoll\" (red Knoll) points to too much Kölsch. The word is also alive in phrases like \"op de Knoll falle\" (to fall on one's nose). The term reflects the Cologne love of coarse, vivid language.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-071": "Sylt is the northernmost island of Germany — a 38 km long North Sea island near the Danish border. Famous for its endless sandy beaches, the village of Kampen with celebrity villas, the celebrity venue \"Sansibar\" and the Wadden Sea. Sylt is synonymous with German luxury beach life — property prices are the highest in Germany. The Hindenburg Dam has connected the island to the mainland since 1927.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-070": "1 August is the Swiss National Day — commemorating the Rütli Oath of 1291, with which the founding cantons of Uri, Schwyz and Unterwalden established the Confederation. On the eve, bonfires burn everywhere on the mountaintops, followed by fireworks. Switzerland celebrates its independence, direct democracy and neutrality. Federal councillors give speeches, lanterns decorate the houses.",
  "wienerisch.w-067": "Hans Hölzel, alias Falco (1957–1998), was Vienna's biggest pop star — the first German-language musician with a No. 1 hit in the USA (\"Rock Me Amadeus\", 1986). His mix of Viennese wit (Schmäh), rap and synthesizer was unique. \"Jeanny\", \"Der Kommissar\", \"Out of the Dark\" — classics. Falco died in 1998 in a car accident in the Dominican Republic. In Vienna there are Falco monuments, and his grave at the Central Cemetery is a place of pilgrimage.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-066": "The Nuremberg Christkind (Christ Child) is a teenage girl (16–19 years old) from Nuremberg, newly elected every two years, who opens the world-famous Christkindlesmarkt as a blond-curled Christ Child with a golden crown and a white-and-gold gown. A Nuremberg tradition since 1948. The election is highly coveted — thousands of girls apply. From the balcony of the Frauenkirche the Christkind proclaims the prologue: \"Ihr Männer und Frauen ...\" (You men and women ...).",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-068": "The \"Frittenbude\" (chip shop) is the classic snack institution of the Ruhr region: chips, currywurst, shashlik, schnitzel rolls. Often as a red stall on street corners, in front of stadiums or next to the Trinkhalle (kiosk). The \"Pommesfrau\" or \"Pommesmann\" knows every regular by name and favourite order. A meeting point for workers after their shift, a meeting point for fans after the match.",
  "alemannisch.al-066": "Lörrach is the southernmost town of Baden-Württemberg — only a few kilometres from Basel. 50,000 inhabitants. Situated in the tri-border area of Germany, Switzerland and France, Lörrach is a melting-pot town. Many Swiss work here, many Lörrach residents commute to work in Basel. Famous: the Burghof Festival, the Hebelschule (named after the Alemannic poet Johann Peter Hebel). Gateway to the Markgräflerland.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-062": "The \"Keschde\" are the sweet chestnuts that grow on the slopes of the Palatinate Forest and are sold roasted in autumn. \"Im Oktober gibt's heiße Keschde un neie Woi!\" (In October there are hot chestnuts and new wine!) The combination of Keschde and \"new wine\" (Federweißer) is a firm Palatine autumn tradition, celebrated at dedicated \"Keschdefeschde\" (chestnut festivals). The term comes from the Latin \"castanea\". The Palatinate proudly calls itself the \"land of the Keschde\". Roasted, boiled or made into soup.",
  "hessisch.h-090": "The Hessian diminutive of Brezel (pretzel) — a \"Brieselche\" is a small, cute pretzel. In Hesse, pretzels are part of every breakfast and dinner, often with butter or as a side dish to apple wine. In Sachsenhausen, pretzel sellers walk through the apple-wine taverns with large baskets — a Brieselche with a Geripptes (the ribbed apple-wine glass) is tradition.",
  "berlinisch.b-087": "A Berlin term for excessive fussing over trivia or pedantry. \"Was 'ne Pieselei!\" says the impatient Berliner when someone dwells on details or counts back every cent when paying. The word expresses the Berlin need for pragmatism and speed — Pieselei is not appreciated.",
  "bayerisch.by-080": "In Bavarian, the \"Bockerl\" is the pine or spruce cone that you find in the forest. Children collect Bockerl for playing and crafting, adults for lighting the stove. The famous \"Bockerlbahnerl\" too — the historic narrow-gauge railway into the Bavarian Forest area — is named after the many cones that lay on the tracks. A thoroughly Bavarian word with great charm.",
  "saechsisch.s-067": "Lusatia (Upper Lusatia in Saxony, Lower Lusatia in Brandenburg) is a region with its own Slavic history. Here live the Sorbs — the only officially recognised ethnic minority in Germany. Sorbian place-name signs, Sorbian schools and Sorbian traditional costumes shape the picture. Bautzen is the cultural centre. Lusatia is also a lignite mining area — the structural-policy transformation is underway.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-070": "The \"Wengerter\" is the Swabian word for winegrower — from \"Wengert\" (vineyard). The Württemberg wine country, with its slopes along the Neckar and Rems, has a 1000-year winegrowing tradition. Wengerter are down-to-earth, often traditionalist family entrepreneurs. The Trollinger grape (also called Vernatsch) is Württemberg's favourite variety. Swabian wine is rarely exported — the Swabians prefer to drink it themselves.",
  "koelsch.k-085": "Dösbaddel is a good-natured Cologne term of abuse for someone who doesn't think quite so quickly — similar to \"scatterbrain\" or \"dimwit\". It is used among friends with a wink and is not meant seriously. The term combines \"dösig\" (sluggish) with \"Baddel\" (simpleton).",
  "plattdeutsch.p-073": "Theodor Storm (1817–1888) was Schleswig-Holstein's most famous writer. His work \"Der Schimmelreiter\" (The Rider on the White Horse, 1888) — about the dike reeve Hauke Haien, who challenges the forces of nature — is required reading throughout Germany. Storm lived in Husum, which he called \"the grey town by the sea\". His birthplace in Husum is now the Storm Museum. Northern German melancholy, storm tides and the sea shape his works.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-071": "Cailler is the oldest still-existing Swiss chocolate brand, founded in 1819 by François-Louis Cailler in Vevey. Daniel Peter (Cailler's son-in-law) invented milk chocolate in 1875 — a Swiss world innovation. Today Cailler belongs to Nestlé but is still produced at the factory in Broc (Gruyère). The \"Branches\" variety (chocolate sticks) is a cult item. A chocolate tour through Broc is a tourist must.",
  "wienerisch.w-068": "Sigmund Freud (1856–1939) lived for 47 years in Vienna, mainly at Berggasse 19 (today the Sigmund Freud Museum). Here he developed psychoanalysis, the concepts of the unconscious, the Oedipus complex and dream interpretation. Viennese culture — with its mixture of glamour and melancholy, politeness and aggression — offered him rich material. In 1938 he had to flee the Nazis to London.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-067": "The Käthe Wohlfahrt Christmas village in Rothenburg ob der Tauber is a Franconian tourist attraction — a huge shop for Christmas decorations and figures, open all year round. Founded in 1964, it is a place of pilgrimage for German-American and Asian tourists. The hand-carved Schwibbögen (candle arches), incense smokers and Christmas baubles are souvenirs from \"real Germany\". Käthe Wohlfahrt embodies German Christmas romance worldwide.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-069": "Wrestling is a sport rich in tradition in the Ruhr region — almost every larger village has a wrestling club. The Bochum wrestling scene is successful nationwide, and clubs such as KSV Aalen and the Athletik clubs of Cologne and Mülheim are top wrestling-league teams. Miners used to have the physical substance for this strength sport. Today wrestling struggles with a lack of young talent, but the club tradition lives on.",
  "alemannisch.al-067": "Weil am Rhein is the southwesternmost town in Germany, right at the tri-border point. Famous for the Vitra Design Campus with buildings by Frank Gehry, Zaha Hadid, and Tadao Ando — a place of pilgrimage for architects and designers. The Vitra Design Museum showcases the history of furniture design. Weil am Rhein is also the German home of Swiss commuters — the tram from Basel runs all the way here.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-063": "„Woi\" means wine — the single most important word in the Palatinate, with a swallowed „n\". „A Schoppe Woi am Owend, des g'hört dezu!\" (A glass of wine in the evening, that's a must!) The Palatinate lives off Woi, from cultivation to enjoyment. As the saying goes: „Wer ned Woi trinkt, dem is ned zu helfe.\" (Whoever doesn't drink wine is beyond help.) The „neie Woi\" (Federweißer, young wine) in autumn, the „alde Woi\" (old wine) from the cellar — everything revolves around the Woi. A core concept of Palatine identity and way of life.",
  "hessisch.h-091": "The shepherd is still a living profession in the Hessian uplands — especially in the Rhön and the Vogelsberg. Hessian shepherds tend their flocks on the high pastures and juniper heaths. The Rhön sheep is a traditional Hessian breed. The shepherd's life is hard, but the profession is actively preserved in Hesse as a means of caring for the cultural landscape.",
  "berlinisch.b-088": "Berlin dialect for skin or peel (of sausage, potato, etc.) — but also in the phrase „jemandem auf der Pelle hängen\" (to hang on someone's skin) for being clingy or pushy. „Hängt mir nich so auf der Pelle!\" (Don't be so all over me!) complains the annoyed Berliner about people standing too close. Also „die Pelle voll haben\" (to have one's skin full) means to be drunk.",
  "bayerisch.by-081": "The „Reibradl\" is the Bavarian word for potato pancake or potato fritter — grated potatoes with egg and flour, fried crispy in the pan. Served with applesauce or savory with sauerkraut. In some regions of Bavaria they are also called „Erdäpfelpuffer\" or „Bachuran\". The small, round shape gave the dish its name — a little „Radl\" (wheel) for the pan.",
  "saechsisch.s-068": "The Sorbs are a West Slavic people in Lusatia with their own language (Sorbian — related to Czech and Polish), their own traditional costumes and customs. About 60,000 Sorbs live in Saxony and Brandenburg, of whom around 20,000 speak the language. They have lived in the region for over 1,000 years and are recognized as a minority by the German constitution. The Sorbian Easter Riding (Križerjo) is a well-known tradition.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-071": "„Mausele\" is a term of endearment in Swabian — literally „little mousey\". It is an affectionate form of address for partners, children, and grandchildren. The Swabian „-le\" makes the standard German „Maus\" (mouse) loving and diminutive. „Mei Mausele\" (my little mousey) is what a grandmother says to her grandchild. It may sound odd to non-Swabians, but in Swabia it's perfectly normal and warm.",
  "koelsch.k-086": "Plüschprumm is an affectionately mocking Cologne word for a lazybones or a sluggish person. Literally something like „plush plum\" — someone who sits soft and lazy like a plum in plush. The word reflects Cologne humor: even when scolding, people stay vivid and warm-hearted.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-074": "„Schiet\" is Low German for „shit\" or „crap\" — but it's used more mildly than its standard German counterpart. It expresses annoyance, disappointment, or bad luck without being truly coarse. „So'n Schiet!\" (What a mess!) is a typical northern German exclamation. The most famous example: „Schietwedder\" — bad weather. Schiet belongs to everyday northern German vocabulary like beer belongs to the harbor district.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-072": "The Engadine is a high-alpine valley in Graubünden — from the Maloja Pass to the Austrian Vinschgau. It is divided into the Upper Engadine (St. Moritz, Pontresina, Sils) and the Lower Engadine (Scuol, Zernez). Clear mountain lakes, plenty of sunshine, and the unique sgraffito house decoration make it a postcard region. St. Moritz is synonymous with chic winter-sports society, while the Engadine is at the same time a natural paradise.",
  "wienerisch.w-069": "At Vienna's Christmas markets (on Rathausplatz, in Schönbrunn, on the Spittelberg), punch is the warming drink of choice — usually with rum, tea, sugar, and spices. Unlike German mulled wine, Viennese punch is often made stronger and sweeter. The Punschkrapfen — a pink-red glazed cake with rum aroma — is a Viennese pastry secret. Punch belongs to the Viennese winter.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-068": "Rothenburg ob der Tauber is probably the most photographed town in Germany — an almost completely preserved medieval town with its town wall, towers, gates, and half-timbered houses. During the war it was to be destroyed but was saved by the diplomatic skill of an American general. Today it is a place of pilgrimage for Japanese and American tourists. The Meistertrunk (Master Draught) legend and Schneeballen (snowballs) are further trademarks.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-070": "„Glück Auf! Der Steiger kommt!\" is the most famous German miners' hymn — a folk song sung since the 17th century in all German mining regions. In the Ruhr area it is identity-forming: at miners' funerals, at festivals, at club gatherings. Schalke 04 plays it at home games. The „Steiger\" was the supervising official underground — the foreman over the miners.",
  "alemannisch.al-068": "Johann Peter Hebel (1760–1826) is the most important Alemannic poet — born in Basel, raised in Hausen im Wiesental. His „Alemannische Gedichte\" (Alemannic Poems, 1803) are classic works of dialect poetry. His „Schatzkästlein des rheinischen Hausfreundes\" (Treasure Chest of the Rhenish Family Friend) with short stories is also famous. Hebel was a theologian, teacher, and is regarded as a bridge between the Enlightenment and Romanticism. In Lörrach, the Hebelfest is held in his honor.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-064": "A „Schorlemorle\" is jokingly someone who likes to drink plenty of Schorle (wine spritzer), or generally a cozy Palatine wine drinker. „Du alder Schorlemorle, schun widder am Dubbeglas!\" (You old Schorlemorle, at the Dubbeglas again!) Used affectionately and mockingly among friends at the regulars' table. The word plays on the sound of „Schorle\" and rhymes itself onward, typical of the playful Palatine language. No one takes offense — on the contrary, in the wine region it's almost a title of honor.",
  "hessisch.h-092": "A Hessian exclamation of surprise, astonishment, or friendly greeting. „Mei Lieber!\" (My dear!) is uttered like a little ode to amazement. It can be meant as a direct form of address („Mei Lieber, was machst du da?\" — My dear, what are you doing?) or as a standalone exclamation of surprise. Very typical of older Hessians.",
  "berlinisch.b-089": "A „Hänger\" is a phase of tiredness, lack of drive, or loss of concentration. „Ich hab 'nen Hänger\" (I'm in a slump) is what the Berlin office worker says in the afternoon when energy fades. The word also describes a temporary mental low — not burnout, more like an off day. Coffee is the standard solution.",
  "bayerisch.by-082": "The „Kasspatzn\" are the Bavarian-Swabian answer to cheese noodles: Spätzle (small egg-dough noodles) are mixed with plenty of grated mountain cheese and topped with fried onions. A hearty dish from the Bavarian and Allgäu mountain-hut cuisine. When the Kasspatzn are done right, cheese strings stretch as you serve them, which you have to catch with your fork — part of Kasspatzn etiquette.",
  "saechsisch.s-069": "Plauen lace is a characteristic embroidery from the Vogtland, developed in Plauen since the 19th century. Using special embroidery machines, delicate lace patterns are stitched onto fabric, which is then dissolved in an acid bath — leaving behind the finest, free-floating lace. Plauen lace is a world cultural heritage and adorns royal weddings, cocktail dresses, and bed linens. A Saxon craft marvel.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-072": "Bietigheim-Bissingen is a typical medium-sized Swabian town north of Stuttgart with 43,000 inhabitants. Characteristic features are the well-preserved half-timbered old town, the traditional Bietigheim horse market, and the business location with many medium-sized companies. It stands for many Swabian towns that balance between tradition and industrial modernity — the Swabian success model.",
  "koelsch.k-087": "The kölsche Kavalier (Cologne gentleman) is an ideal type: polite, charming, sociable — the typical Cologne native who knows how to behave. He holds doors open, treats you to a Kölsch, and always has a kind word. The kölsche Kavalier is part of the city's self-image and is celebrated in songs and folk figures.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-075": "„Tüdelig\" is Low German for confused, forgetful, or muddled — usually used affectionately for older people who are having a momentary lapse. It is a tender word that does not condemn human frailty but accepts it. Younger people can also be „tüdelig\" when they are excited or tired. The word „Tüdelkram\" refers to confused chatter or nonsense.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-073": "Ovomaltine is a powder made of malt, milk, eggs, and cocoa, stirred into water or milk — developed in Bern in 1904. Originally intended as a strengthening drink for the sick and for athletes, today it is a Swiss breakfast institution. „Mit Ovomaltine kannst du es nicht besser, aber länger\" (With Ovomaltine you can't do it better, but longer) — the advertising slogan is legendary. The red tin is a design icon. A piece of Swiss pop culture.",
  "wienerisch.w-070": "The Wiener Krapfen is a filled yeast-dough ball, deep-fried in lard and dusted with powdered sugar. The classic filling is apricot jam (Marille), but vanilla, chocolate, and Powidl (plum butter) are also popular. During Carnival season, all of Austria eats Krapfen — the Faschingskrapfen is an obligatory tradition. The best Krapfen are found at Aida, Demel, or at the Vienna Heumarkt.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-069": "In Franconia, traditional dress is often worn even when hiking — Lederhose or Trachtenrock (dirndl skirt), knee socks, and a hat. The Franconian hiking clubs keep this tradition alive especially in the Frankenwald, Franconian Switzerland, and the Franconian Jura. Hiking is a must here — in any weather, with a Brotzeit (snack) and a sip of Frankenwein (Franconian wine). At the beer cellars and snack stops along the hiking trail, the Franconian community comes together.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-071": "Bottroper are the inhabitants of Bottrop — a city of 117,000 in the western Ruhr area. Home of Movie Park Germany (formerly Warner Bros. Movie World) and the Halde Beckstraße with the famous „Tetraeder\" (viewing platform). The city embodies structural change: the collieries are closed, logistics and services are taking over. Bottrop is authentic Ruhrpott, less touristy than Essen or Dortmund.",
  "alemannisch.al-069": "Baden asparagus — above all from the Rhine plain around Schwetzingen and Lampertheim — is considered the best asparagus in Germany. The sandy soils and mild climate are ideal. The asparagus season (mid-April to June 24) is sacred: fresh asparagus daily, with melted butter, hollandaise sauce, or simply with boiled potatoes. Schwetzingen calls itself the „Asparagus Capital of the World\" — with an asparagus museum and asparagus festival.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-065": "„Gell?\" is the Palatine tag question at the end of a sentence, comparable to „isn't it?\". „Schee is es heut, gell?\" (Nice weather today, isn't it?) It is used constantly to seek agreement or to keep a conversation going. Sometimes intensified to „gell ja?\" or „gell, des stimmt?\" (right, that's true?). It belongs to the words by which you can immediately recognize a Palatine. It expresses a sense of community — one seeks consensus, the shared nod over wine and weather.",
  "hessisch.h-093": "A vivid Hessian saying for something that goes to waste, breaks down, or ends badly. „Des geht den Bach runner!\" (That's going down the drain!) means that something falls apart or a project fails. In Frankfurt local color, „Bach\" has a double meaning — the Main river is also called this (see h-075). A frequently used expression.",
  "berlinisch.b-090": "The Berlin children's word for the male member — harmless, diminutive, and common in families. „Hast du dir den Schniepel gewaschen?\" (Did you wash your willy?) the Berlin mother asks at bath time. The word is much more harmless than its coarser relatives and belongs to everyday family language with small children.",
  "bayerisch.by-083": "The „Krautwickerl\" are the Bavarian version of cabbage rolls — minced meat wrapped in white cabbage or sauerkraut leaves, braised in broth and served with mashed potatoes. A classic Sunday dish of Bavarian home cooking. Every Bavarian grandmother has her own recipe, guarded like a treasure. The plural ends, typically Bavarian, in „-l\" instead of „-n\".",
  "saechsisch.s-070": "Augustusburg Castle stands on a mountain above the town of the same name in the Ore Mountains — built from 1568 to 1572 by Elector August of Saxony as a hunting lodge. The mighty Renaissance castle towers over the landscape and is regarded as the „Crown of the Ore Mountains\". Today it houses several museums: a motorcycle museum, a hunting and game museum, and a castle distillery. A ride on the historic funicular up to the castle is an experience.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-073": "„Hokerle\" is a small stool or footstool — a typically Swabian piece of furniture. Swabians like to sit on a Hokerle in the kitchen, in the garden, while doing repairs. The Swabian diminutive „-le\" makes the word affectionate. Whoever sits on a Hokerle is usually in a working pose — pure Swabian practicality. Also used to describe a casual, cozy way of sitting.",
  "koelsch.k-088": "Oma also means grandmother in Cologne dialect — usually pronounced with a long, drawn-out „O\". The Cologne Oma is an institution: she cooks Riefkooche (potato pancakes), sews carnival costumes, and knows every story of the Veedel (neighborhood). In the Cologne family, the Oma is the memory and the soul of the kinship.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-076": "Borkum, at 31 km², is the largest of the seven East Frisian Islands. Its high-sea climate, thanks to its location in the North Sea, makes it a health resort — the stimulating-climate therapy helps with respiratory illnesses. The island is car-free (only residents' cars are permitted), and the island railway from the harbor to the village is part of the tradition. Sunsets on the beach are legendary.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-074": "„Käppi\" is the Swiss German diminutive of „Kappe\" (cap) — with the characteristic -i diminutive. A Käppi protects the head from sun and cold and, as a branded item, is also a fashion statement. Swiss children get a Käppi with embroidery early on — usually with their name — and wear it proudly. A small but charming word of Swiss German.",
  "wienerisch.w-071": "The Habsburgs were the most powerful dynasty in Central Europe — from 1273 to 1918 they provided kings and emperors. Vienna was their capital from 1438. Empress Maria Theresa, Emperor Joseph II, Franz Joseph I, and Empress Sisi shape the Viennese cityscape to this day with their palaces, monuments, and mausoleums. After the First World War, the monarchy ended in 1918. But the Habsburg atmosphere lives on in Vienna.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-070": "The Walberla is the best-known mountain of Franconian Switzerland — a 532 m high limestone table-mountain summit with the Walpurgis Chapel. Every year in early May, the traditional „Walberla Festival\" takes place here — a pilgrimage and folk festival in one. Families from all over Middle Franconia make their way up the mountain, often in traditional dress, and celebrate the arrival of spring with beer and a Brotzeit (snack). A genuinely Franconian tradition.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-072": "Carnival in the Ruhr area has its own style — warmer and more working-class than in Cologne, less touristy. Cities like Dorsten, Recklinghausen, and Bottrop celebrate their carnival with sessions, Rose Monday parades, and the famous mining tradition. The „Bergmännische Garden\" (miners' guards) wear historic miners' uniforms. Pottkarneval is carnival without the glitz, with real people and honest beer.",
  "alemannisch.al-072": "Hinterzarten is a famous winter-sports resort in the High Black Forest — home to numerous German ski jumpers, including Sven Hannawald and Severin Freund. The „Adler-Schanze\" ski jump is among Germany's best training facilities. In summer it is a hiking paradise and a spa resort. A charming Black Forest community with traditional farmhouse charm and an Alemannic-Baden character.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-066": "\"Ebbes\" means \"something\" — one of the most common Palatine words in everyday life. \"Host du ebbes zu esse fer mich?\" (Do you have something to eat for me?). Its counterpart is \"nix\" (nothing). Variations: \"so ebbes\" (something like that), \"ebbes Gscheits\" (something sensible), \"ebbes Klää's\" (something small). From the Middle High German \"etewes\". It is used countless times a day and is almost impossible to imagine a Palatine sentence without. Classic West Central German vocabulary.",
  "hessisch.h-094": "The Hessian Schorle is usually an apple-wine spritzer — Ebbelwoi mixed with mineral water, the ideal refreshing drink in summer. The sour variant is called \"Sauer-Gespritzte\", the version with lemonade \"Süß-Gespritzte\". In Frankfurt's taverns the mixture is made in a 50:50 ratio. A Schorle is lighter than pure apple wine.",
  "berlinisch.b-091": "In Berlin dialect a derogatory word for an arrogant, conceited person who thinks himself better than others. \"So'n feiner Pinkel!\" (What a fine fellow!) says the Berliner about someone who behaves affectedly. The word plays on the double meaning with \"pinkeln\" (to pee) and thus expresses contempt for puffed-up characters.",
  "bayerisch.by-084": "Lake Königssee near Berchtesgaden is one of the most beautiful lakes in the Bavarian Alps — a deep fjord-like lake nestled between the steep rock faces of the Watzmann massif. Turquoise-green, crystal-clear water that is unique in Germany. The electric boats take you to the pilgrimage church of St. Bartholomä — the quintessential picture-postcard motif. At the echo spot the boatman blows a trumpet, and the echo resounds back several times.",
  "saechsisch.s-071": "The \"Striezel\" is a Saxon and Austrian yeast plait — often with raisins, almonds and lemon zest. In Dresden the famous \"Striezelmarkt\" is held every year — Germany's oldest Christmas market (documented since 1434), named after the Striezel-like Stollen. The Christstollen from Dresden is a protected geographical indication. Striezel and Stollen — Saxon baking artistry for the Christmas season.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-074": "\"Brügelimaier\" is, in Swabian, a quarrelsome, troublemaking person — derived from \"Brügel\" (a large stick). Anyone regarded as a \"Brügelimaier\" picks fights everywhere. The term is humorously derogatory and describes a character type everyone knows: the troublemaker, the eternal grumbler. In Swabian stories and jokes the Brügelimaier is an archetypal figure.",
  "koelsch.k-089": "The Cologne grandpa is usually a club man, an FC fan and a regular at the brewery tavern. He tells stories of the old days, of carnival and of the time of the \"Trümmerfrauen\" (rubble women). In Cologne, the relationship between grandchild and grandpa is often especially warm — grandpa takes his time and is blessed with Cologne humour.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-077": "Norderney is the second-largest island of East Frisia and Germany's oldest seaside resort (since 1797). The fashionable island was the summer residence of the Hanoverian royal house in the 19th century. Heinrich Heine, Theodor Fontane and Otto von Bismarck took the cure here. Today it is a mix of tradition and modern beach holidays.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-075": "\"Gäll\" is the Swiss German variant of \"gell\" and \"nicht wahr\" (right? / isn't it?) — a confirmation particle at the end of a sentence. It is used throughout the Swiss German-speaking area and expresses that one expects agreement. In Swiss German it sounds softer than the German \"nicht wahr\": \"Du chunnsch mit, gäll?\" (You're coming along, right?). The particle is as ubiquitous as the Swiss weather — everywhere and always.",
  "wienerisch.w-072": "Elisabeth of Austria-Hungary (1837–1898), affectionately called \"Sisi\", was the wife of Emperor Franz Joseph I and the most dazzling of the Habsburgs. Because of her beauty, her unconventionality and her tragic fate (she was murdered in Geneva in 1898), she became a European pop figure. The Sissi films of the 1950s with Romy Schneider made her world-famous — albeit romanticised. In Vienna, entire museums are dedicated to her.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-071": "\"Schorsch\" is, in Franconian (and Hessian, Palatine), the colloquial form of Georg — very common as a first name and nickname. \"Schorsch\" sounds warm, down-to-earth, typically Franconian. In Franconia everyone knows a Schorsch. The name has an almost comedic quality — perfect for stories and jokes. Schorsch Glanzberger and Schorsch Glanzler are classic Franconian name forms.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-073": "The \"Schalker Gefühl\" (Schalke feeling) is a term used by Schalke 04 fans — an almost religious bond with the club, independent of sporting success. Schalke 04 is more than a football club: it is a piece of Gelsenkirchen identity, a miners' club, a workers' club. The club colours (royal blue and white) and the Schalke crest with its cross are passed down through generations. To go \"auf Schalke\" — to attend a home game — is a lifelong calling.",
  "alemannisch.al-073": "Lake Titisee — about 60 km east of Freiburg — is, at 1.3 km², the largest natural lake in the Black Forest. Crystal-clear, nestled between wooded hills, of glacial origin. In summer there are water sports (pedal boats, swimming, sailing), in winter it partly freezes over. The town of Titisee-Neustadt is a popular tourist destination with shops, restaurants and hotels. A frequent picture-postcard motif.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-067": "\"Alleweil\" means, depending on context, \"right now\", \"currently\" or \"constantly\". \"Alleweil hab ich kää Zeit, kumm spädder!\" (Right now I have no time, come later!). Contracted from \"alle Weile\". Very widespread in the southern German region, with its own colouring in the Palatinate. \"Alleweil is es so weit\" (now the time has come), \"der babbelt alleweil\" (he talks constantly). A flexible time word that, depending on emphasis, expresses the present or duration. A classic Palatine everyday term.",
  "hessisch.h-095": "A typically Hessian location expression — \"vorm Lade\" means in front of the shop or the tavern. The classic is \"die Bank vorm Lade\" — the seating spot in front of the apple-wine tavern, where the regulars drink beer or apple wine in summer and watch the goings-on. A social hub of small Hessian villages.",
  "berlinisch.b-092": "A Berlin expression for unnecessary fuss, exaggerated behaviour or a silly performed scene. \"Mach kein Affentheater!\" (Don't make a monkey show!) is a call not to make such a fuss. The image comes from circus animals that lose their animal dignity. Berliners have little patience with Affentheater — pragmatism is what counts.",
  "bayerisch.by-085": "Garmisch-Partenkirchen is Bavaria's best-known winter sports resort — host of the 1936 Winter Olympics and, every year, of the New Year's ski jumping (Four Hills Tournament). The Zugspitze and the Wetterstein mountains form a dramatic backdrop. Famous: the Garmisch Olympic ski stadium, the Partnach Gorge and the Wank cable car. In summer a hiker's mecca, in winter a ski paradise.",
  "saechsisch.s-072": "Bautzen (Sorbian: Budyšin) is the cultural capital of the Sorbs in Saxony — a historic town with a preserved old-town core. Famous for Bautzen mustard (yes, the famous one!) and the GDR Stasi prisons (\"Gelbes Elend\"/\"Yellow Misery\"). The bilingual Sorbian-German place-name signs shape the picture. The bridge over the Spree with the old-town silhouette is a popular motif. A UNESCO World Heritage candidate.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-075": "The hop and malt land of Swabia has a long brewing tradition — the Tettnang hop region on Lake Constance is the world market leader in aroma hops. The Swabian breweries — Stuttgarter Hofbräu, Dinkelacker, Schwaben-Bräu — are smaller than the big Bavarian breweries, but rich in tradition. \"Hopfen und Malz, Gott erhalt's\" (Hops and malt, may God preserve them) — a Swabian beer-brewer's saying. The Swabian Pils country is less well known than Bavaria, but of high quality.",
  "koelsch.k-090": "The Tant is the Cologne form of Tante (aunt) — often a formative figure in the extended family. Famous is \"Tant Käthe\" from the carnival song by the Höhner. The Cologne Tant is usually warm-hearted, sometimes headstrong and always good for a story. In extended families she is often the go-to person for all the Pänz (kids).",
  "plattdeutsch.p-078": "Spiekeroog is one of the smallest East Frisian Islands and completely car-free — not a single private car. Carriages and bicycles dominate the scene. The historic island church of 1696, with ship models hanging under the ceiling, is famous. Spiekeroog is regarded as the \"Pearl of the North Sea\" and is part of the UNESCO World Natural Heritage.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-076": "Schwingen is Switzerland's national sport — a traditional form of wrestling in which the fighters (\"Schwinger\") grapple by gripping the waistband of short trousers made of coarse cloth. The winner is the one who forces his opponent onto his back, touching both shoulder blades down. The Federal Wrestling and Alpine Festival (\"Eidgenössisches\") takes place every three years — the winner (\"Schwingerkönig\"/wrestling king) becomes a national hero. In the sawdust ring the sport is practised today just as it was 200 years ago.",
  "wienerisch.w-073": "\"Beuschel\" is a classic Viennese dish made from veal lung and heart, finely sliced and served in a cream sauce with capers and gherkins. It is accompanied by a bread dumpling (Semmelknödel) or a \"Servierbrot\". Beuschel used to be considered poor people's food, but today it is a coveted specialty in traditional Viennese taverns (Beisln). The proper preparation requires patience — many a Beisl prides itself on its \"best Beuschel\".",
  "fraenkisch.fr-072": "The depiction of the Virgin Mary is a central motif of Franconian art — Tilman Riemenschneider (1460–1531) from Heiligenstadt created incomparable Madonnas in wood and stone in Würzburg. His carved works in the Marienkapelle (Würzburg), the Herrgottskirche (Creglingen) and many Franconian churches are masterpieces of late-medieval sculpture. Riemenschneider is regarded as the most important German sculptor of his time.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-074": "BVB-Liebe (BVB love) is the black-and-yellow devotion of Borussia Dortmund fans — founded in 1909, eight-time German champions. Borussia stands for passion, tradition and the city of Dortmund. Players like Marco Reus, Mats Hummels and Erling Haaland are/were idols. The \"Borussia family\" with its 200,000 club members is the second-largest membership family of a German sports club (after Bayern).",
  "alemannisch.al-074": "\"Black Forest\" is the English name for the Schwarzwald — internationally a well-known tourism term. The \"Black Forest Cake\" (Schwarzwälder Kirschtorte) is world-famous. English-speaking tourists often know Black Forest better than the German terms. The \"Black Forest\" brand is also exported for Black Forest ham, cuckoo clocks and Bollenhüte (pom-pom hats). Global Black Forest branding.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-068": "The \"Haffe\" is the cooking pot — also the flowerpot or chamber pot. \"Stell de Haffe uff de Herd, mir koche Grumbeersupp!\" (Put the pot on the stove, we're cooking potato soup!). Figuratively, \"a alder Haffe\" also means a rickety car or a quirky person. Related to standard German \"Hafen\" in the sense of a vessel. Indispensable in the Palatine farmhouse kitchen, from the big boiling pot to the small milk pot. A classic kitchen word of the region.",
  "hessisch.h-096": "Boiled potatoes in their skins (Pellkartoffeln) are a standard side dish in Hesse for Green Sauce, Handkäs and many other dishes. Cooked in their skins, then peeled and sometimes served still warm with salt, butter or quark. Older Hessians say \"Grumbeere mit der Pell\" (potatoes with the skin). The potato has been a Hessian staple food since the 18th century — the \"Potato War\" of 1778 was partly fought on Hessian soil.",
  "berlinisch.b-093": "The \"Rummelplatz\" is Berlin slang for a funfair with carousels, shooting galleries and candyfloss. The best-known Berlin funfair is the \"German-American Folk Festival\" and the \"Berlin Christmas Market\" on Alexanderplatz. To \"auf'n Rummel jehen\" (go to the funfair) with children or friends is a genuine Berlin tradition.",
  "bayerisch.by-086": "Berchtesgaden is a market town in the far southeast of Bavaria, at the foot of the Watzmann. The Berchtesgadener Land, with the Königssee, the Kehlstein (\"Eagle's Nest\") and the salt mine, is one of the most beautiful Alpine areas in Germany. Historically burdened by the Obersalzberg, where Hitler had his \"Berghof\" residence. Today a tourist magnet and starting point for mountain hikes in the Berchtesgaden National Park.",
  "saechsisch.s-074": "\"Fei\" is a universal intensifying particle in Saxon (also widespread in Franconian and Bavarian). It emphasizes a statement: \"Des is fei gut\" (That is really good), \"Du hast fei recht\" (You're really right). It is the Saxon way of giving a statement emphasis — polite, but firm. Whoever says \"fei\" wants to be heard.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-076": "Reutlingen is a medium-sized Swabian town with 117,000 inhabitants at the foot of the Swabian Alb. A former Free Imperial City. Famous: the narrowest street in the world, the \"Spreuerhofstraße\", at 31 cm wide (Guinness Book of Records). The Marienkirche (Gothic, 73 m high) dominates the skyline. An industrial location of the textile sector and a stronghold of small and medium-sized enterprises.",
  "koelsch.k-091": "Vatter is the Cologne variant of Vater (father) — a traditional designation that is still alive in the Veedel (neighbourhood) and among the older generations. \"De Vatter\" is, in Cologne family life, often the authority, but also the humorous storyteller at the regulars' table. Today many children say \"Papa\", but \"Vatter\" still has a warm, familiar ring.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-079": "Heligoland is Germany's only deep-sea island — 70 km off the coast, with red sandstone cliffs and a unique flora and fauna. British until 1890, then exchanged for Zanzibar. Almost completely destroyed in the Second World War. Today duty-free: a shopping paradise for tourists. The Lange Anna (a rock pinnacle) is its landmark; common guillemots and northern gannets breed on the cliffs.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-077": "Hornussen is a uniquely Swiss team sport — popular above all in the Emmental and the Mittelland. With a long whip (\"Stecken\"), a plastic projectile (\"Nouss\") is struck across a playing field — the opposing team tries to catch the Nouss out of the air with large wooden boards (\"Schindeln\"). A bizarre mix of hockey, cricket and baseball. Part of Switzerland's UNESCO cultural heritage.",
  "wienerisch.w-074": "\"Schmäh führn\" is the art of Viennese charming banter — a humorous, quick-witted way of talking that is not crudely funny but subtly ironic. Whoever \"Schmäh führt\" flirts, plays and teases — always with the necessary wink. It is a social technique: where the North German is direct, the Viennese weaves his way through life with Schmäh. \"Den Schmäh ham's drauf\" (they've got the Schmäh) is high praise.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-073": "The Pegnitz is Nuremberg's river — it crosses the old town and divides it into Sankt Sebald (the northern part) and Sankt Lorenz (the southern part). Each part has its own church. Famous: the Pegnitz bridges such as the Maxbrücke and the Henkersteg (Hangman's Bridge). The Pegnitz later flows into the Regnitz and thus, via the Main, into the Rhine. The banks of the Pegnitz are the Nurembergers' favourite stroll.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-075": "The miner's funeral in the Ruhr region follows its own traditions: on the coffin often lie a miner's helmet and \"Schlägel und Eisen\" (hammer and chisel — the symbol of mining). Miners in historic uniforms accompany the coffin, and the Steigerlied (miners' song) is sung. This tradition shows: even though the collieries are closed, the miners' culture lives on — and honours its dead with a ritual deeply anchored in the identity of the Ruhr region.",
  "alemannisch.al-075": "\"Heimet\" is the Alemannic and Swiss German form of \"Heimat\" (home/homeland) — a central word of Alemannic identity. \"Mei Heimet isch im Schwarzwald\" (My home is in the Black Forest) — this bond between people and landscape, between language and soil, is deeply rooted. The song \"Heimweh\" is about the longing for the Heimet. An emotionally charged word that expresses the Alemannic rootedness in land and tradition.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-069": "The \"Bobbeschees\" is the baby carriage or doll's pram, from \"Bobbe\" (doll/baby) and the French \"chaise\" (chair/carriage). \"Schieb du de Bobbeschees, mei Arm is mied!\" (You push the pram, my arm is tired!). A fine example of the French influence on the Palatine dialect. Also used mockingly for an old-fashioned or rickety vehicle. Palatine children have been pushed through the village in the Bobbeschees for generations. Charmingly cross-border vocabulary.",
  "hessisch.h-097": "In Hessian taverns, the \"Halbe\" is the standard order for beer — half a liter. Unlike in Bavaria (where the \"Maß\" at one liter is standard) and similar to Franconia, the Hessian drinks his Halbe. Frankfurt's tavern crowd has distanced itself from its Bavarian neighbors here too — apple wine and a Halbe instead of a Maß are the Hessian norm.",
  "berlinisch.b-095": "\"Lili Marleen\" is the most famous German soldier's song of the 20th century, written in 1915 by Hans Leip in Berlin. Marlene Dietrich made it world-famous with her recordings for the US soldiers. The song about a soldier's longing for his beloved at the barracks gate was sung by both sides of the Second World War.",
  "bayerisch.by-087": "Mittenwald is a picturesque little Alpine town between the Karwendel and Wetterstein mountains — famous for its violin-making since the 17th century. Matthias Klotz brought the art of violin-making from Cremona in 1685. To this day, violin-makers in Mittenwald craft high-quality string instruments. The colorful Lüftlmalerei murals on the house facades are world-famous. Also a Karwendelbahn station and a hiking mecca.",
  "saechsisch.s-075": "The \"Annaberger Kät\" is one of Saxony's largest folk festivals — celebrated since the 16th century in the mining town of Annaberg-Buchholz in the Erzgebirge. The festival lasts over a week in July, with a festive parade, showmen, miners in traditional dress and thousands of visitors. The Annaberg miners' parade in historic miners' costumes is a UNESCO-recognized event. Saxon tradition in its purest form.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-077": "Schwäbisch Hall is a charming town of 40,000 inhabitants in the Kocher valley with a rich tradition of salt extraction (hence the name \"Hall\" = an old word for salt). Famous for: the steps in front of St. Michael, the Hällisch-Fränkisches Museum, the open-air theater in summer. Also the seat of the Schwäbisch Hall building society. A Swabian-Franconian mixed zone.",
  "koelsch.k-092": "Mamm is the Kölsch form of \"mother\" — warm and direct. The Kölsch Mamm traditionally stands at the center of the family, cooks the Sunday meal and holds the family together. \"Mamm\" is often used throughout one's whole life, even by grown-up children who visit their mother.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-080": "Husum on the North Sea coast is the \"grey town by the sea,\" as Theodor Storm called it. 23,000 inhabitants, a port town with tradition. Famous for: the crocus meadow in the castle park with 4 million crocuses in spring. Storm's birthplace is now a museum. Husum was the main town of North Frisia and is the gateway to the Halligen.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-078": "Zermatt in Valais is one of the most famous mountain villages in the world — at the foot of the Matterhorn, car-free and only reachable by train. Known for chic winter sports (the ski area on the Theodul Glacier is open 365 days a year), famous hotels and the iconic Matterhorn postcard motif. In summer a mecca for mountaineers — the Hörnli Hut at the foot of the Matterhorn is a mandatory stop. The Gornergrat railway leads up to the 3,089 m high viewing platform.",
  "wienerisch.w-075": "The Vienna Central Cemetery in the 11th district, with 2.5 million people buried there, is one of the largest cemeteries in Europe — and a Viennese curiosity: it is a place for outings, a meeting spot for lovers and a tourist magnet. Beethoven, Schubert, Strauss, Brahms, Falco and countless others lie here. The avenue of honorary graves is impressive. Wolfgang Ambros sang the famous \"Es lebe der Zentralfriedhof\" — a Viennese hymn to transience.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-074": "\"Der Glubb\" is the affectionate Franconian term for the 1. FC Nürnberg — from the word \"Club\" with the typical Franconian \"g\" at the beginning. Fans shout \"Auf gehts, Glubb!\" and the club magazine is called the \"Glubb-Zeitung.\" The name underlines the unmistakably Franconian identity of the club — not a plastic club, but a family with over 120 years of history. Whoever says \"Glubb\" is an insider.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-076": "Duisburg, with 500,000 inhabitants, is the fifth-largest city in North Rhine-Westphalia and home to the largest inland port in Europe — the \"Duisport.\" The steel industry (Thyssenkrupp) shapes the city. Famous for: the Landschaftspark Duisburg-Nord, the Lehmbruck Museum and the Duisburg Inner Harbour promenade. Home of the MSV Duisburg \"Zebras\" and scene of the tragic Love Parade disaster of 2010.",
  "alemannisch.al-076": "The Funkenfeuer is an Alemannic and Vorarlberg customary celebration on the first Sunday after Ash Wednesday — huge wooden towers (\"Funken\") are built on hills and set alight. Symbolism: driving out winter and welcoming spring. A Funken witch made of straw sits enthroned at the top and explodes. In the evening, families walk to the Funken site, mulled wine and sausages included. UNESCO cultural heritage since 2010.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-070": "S'\"Trottwa\" is the sidewalk, taken directly from the French \"trottoir.\" \"Bleib uff em Trottwa, ned uff de Straß renne!\" (Stay on the sidewalk, don't run in the street!) One of the many French loanwords that have been firmly anchored in the Palatinate vocabulary since Napoleonic times. Parents urge their children to stay on the Trottwa. It vividly shows how deeply the French neighborhood has shaped the dialect. It is used quite naturally in everyday life.",
  "hessisch.h-098": "A robust Hessian term for miserable weather — rain, storm, cold or all of it together. \"Sauwedder\" combines the word \"Sau\" (as an intensifier) with \"Wedder\" (Hessian pronunciation of \"Wetter,\" weather). The expression is widespread throughout the German-speaking world, but sounds especially earthy in the Hessian mouth.",
  "berlinisch.b-096": "In Berlin dialect, eyes are often referred to with particular directness. \"Mach mal die Augen auf!\" (Open your eyes!) says the impatient Berliner to someone who overlooks something. The phrase \"große Augen machen\" (to make big eyes) for astonishment is also widespread. In the Berlin \"Schnauze\" (sass), eyes are an important tool — you look and you say what you see.",
  "bayerisch.by-089": "Pumuckl is a famous Bavarian children's book and radio play character — invented by the Munich author Ellis Kaut and made immortal by the voice of Hans Clarin. The cheeky, red-haired goblin lives with the master carpenter Eder in Munich and rhymes incessantly. The stories are a piece of Bavarian cultural identity, and Pumuckl the epitome of Bavarian mischievousness. A whole generation grew up with him.",
  "saechsisch.s-076": "Pulsnitz gingerbread from the Lusatian town of Pulsnitz is one of the most tradition-rich Saxon Christmas specialties — gingerbread has been baked in Pulsnitz since 1558. The protected geographical indication guarantees its quality. Famous Pulsnitz gingerbread bakers still practice the craft today. Classic varieties: glazed, coated with chocolate, filled with jam. Indispensable in every Saxon household during Advent.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-078": "Ulm on the Danube, with 127,000 inhabitants, is an important Swabian city. The Ulm Minster has the tallest church tower in the world at 161.5 m. Albert Einstein was born here in 1879. The city lies on the language border between Swabian and Bavarian. Famous for: the Fishermen's Quarter and the saying \"In Ulm, um Ulm und um Ulm herum\" (In Ulm, around Ulm and all around Ulm).",
  "koelsch.k-093": "The Lange Tünn is the nickname of the Colonia high-rise in Köln-Mülheim, which from 1973 until its demolition in 1991 was the tallest residential building in Cologne. \"Lange Tünn\" stands in Kölsch both for the high-rise and metaphorically for something very large or long. A well-known Cologne personality also bore this nickname.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-081": "Kiel is the state capital of Schleswig-Holstein, a naval base and a university city. 250,000 inhabitants. Kiel Week in June is one of the largest sailing events in the world — over 3 million visitors. The Canal (Kiel Canal / Nord-Ostsee-Kanal) ends here — the most heavily used artificial waterway in the world.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-079": "The Jungfrau (4,158 m) is one of the most famous peaks in the Swiss Alps — together with the Eiger and the Mönch it forms the Bernese triple constellation. The Jungfrau railway runs up to 3,454 m to the Jungfraujoch — the highest-altitude railway station in Europe (\"Top of Europe\"). The UNESCO World Heritage region of Jungfrau-Aletsch is the largest glacier region in the Alps. The Aletsch Glacier is over 22 km long.",
  "wienerisch.w-076": "Karl Kraus (1874–1936) was Vienna's most famous language critic and satirist — publisher of the legendary magazine \"Die Fackel,\" which he wrote almost entirely on his own. His work \"Die letzten Tage der Menschheit\" (The Last Days of Mankind) about the First World War is considered a masterpiece of anti-war theater. Kraus was feared for his sharp tongue and attacked journalists, politicians and Viennese society with precise verbal force. The incarnation of the critical Viennese spirit.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-075": "\"Würschdla\" are the Franconian sausages — above all the famous Nuremberg bratwursts, smaller and finer than other German sausages. The Franconian diminutive \"-la\" (instead of \"-lein\") makes the word affectionate and endearing. \"Bratwürschdla\" or \"Wirschdla\" also belong to the vocabulary. Three Bratwürschdla on sauerkraut are the classic Franconian meal — quick, tasty, traditional.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-077": "Gelsenkirchen, with 260,000 inhabitants, is home to FC Schalke 04 and the Veltins-Arena. Once the \"city of a thousand fires\" because of its coal mines, today it is one of the poorest big cities in Germany — with a welfare (Hartz IV) rate of over 20%. But: a proud mining tradition, the ZOOM Erlebniswelt, Schalke's home stadium. \"Auf Schalke\" is a pilgrimage destination for the royal-blue fans.",
  "alemannisch.al-077": "The Funkenmarschall is the leader of the Funken construction — an honorable position in the Alemannic-Vorarlberg tradition. He organizes the building of the Funken tower (often 30 m high!), coordinates the wood gathering, plans the ignition. A traditional men's task that begins weeks before Funken Sunday. Young men are thus introduced into the village community — an initiation ritual.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-071": "D'\"Schlabbe\" are the house slippers or slippers you slip into at home. \"Zieh dei Schlabbe an, de Bodde is kalt!\" (Put on your slippers, the floor is cold!) Also \"a Schlabbe\" for a defeat in sports (\"a Schlabbe kassiert,\" took a thrashing). Onomatopoeic from the flapping (\"schlappen\") sound when walking. In every Palatinate household the Schlabbe stand ready at the entrance. A classic word for the cozy domesticity to which every Palatine gladly returns home after a day of Wengerd (vineyard) work.",
  "hessisch.h-099": "A humorous Hessian term for alcoholic drinks — usually apple wine or beer — that get you talking. The combination of \"babbeln\" (to chatter) and \"Wasser\" (drink, water) makes it clear: once the Babbelwasser flows, the talking never stops. Meant self-ironically — Hessians know about their fondness for a good chat.",
  "berlinisch.b-097": "The number seven is often pronounced in Berlin dialect as \"sieme\" or \"sieben\" with a soft pronunciation. Berliners count pragmatically and quickly — no Swabian precision, but Berlin directness. \"Sieben Uhr\" (seven o'clock) is the standard quitting time for many Berliners, the \"Sieben-Uhr-Bus\" the morning commuter bus.",
  "bayerisch.by-090": "Markus Söder (born 1967 in Nuremberg) has been Bavarian Minister President since 2018 and CSU chairman since 2019. Known for his media-savvy stagings — costumes, photo ops in the mountains and taverns — and his Bavaria-centered politics. He lives with his family at the Tegernsee. A frequent candidate for the conservative bloc's chancellor candidacy. A polarizing figure in Bavaria — loved and hated in equal measure.",
  "saechsisch.s-077": "Heinrich Schütz (1585–1672) was Saxony's great Baroque composer — court conductor in Dresden and one of the most important German composers before Bach. Born in Köstritz, he worked in Dresden for almost 60 years. His sacred music (psalms, passions, the Christmas Story) shaped German church music. Schütz studied under Giovanni Gabrieli in Venice and brought Italian Baroque music to Germany. His work is a cornerstone of German music history.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-079": "Heidenheim an der Brenz is a Swabian industrial town of 50,000 inhabitants on the eastern edge of the Swabian Jura. Seat of the Voith group (paper machines, hydropower). Hellenstein Castle dominates the skyline. The 1. FC Heidenheim is also a Bundesliga phenomenon — the \"village club\" in professional football.",
  "koelsch.k-094": "Eierfeld is the jocular Kölsch nickname for the district of Ehrenfeld. The name plays with the similar sound and is a good-natured insider joke among Cologne natives. The Eierfeldler take it with humor — Kölsch self-irony is part of the identity. The Eier-Fööss and similar wordplays are part of the Kölsch language culture.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-082": "Lübeck was for centuries the \"Queen of the Hanse\" and the most powerful city in northern Germany. A UNESCO World Heritage Site since 1987. Famous for: the Holsten Gate (on the old 50-DM note), the Hospital of the Holy Spirit, the brick Gothic of the seven-towers skyline. Home of Thomas Mann (\"Buddenbrooks\") and the marzipan capital (Niederegger).",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-080": "The Eiger (3,967 m) in the Bernese Oberland is famous for its north face — one of the most dangerous and iconic climbing walls in the world. First ascent in 1938. The \"Mordwand\" (murder wall) claimed countless mountaineers' lives. Heinrich Harrer (one of the first to climb it) became world-famous with the book and film \"Seven Years in Tibet.\" Today, mountaineers climb the face daily. From the Bernese Oberland valley, you can see the mighty wall rising straight up.",
  "wienerisch.w-077": "Friedensreich Hundertwasser (1928–2000) was one of the best-known Austrian artists of the 20th century. His colorful, organic style with winding lines, glowing colors and spirals is unmistakable. In Vienna he created the famous Hundertwasserhaus (a residential building) and the KunstHausWien. Hundertwasser was also an ecological visionary and a champion of the \"tree tenant\" (trees instead of tenants). His grave lies beneath a tulip tree in New Zealand.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-076": "Erlangen is a university city of 116,000 inhabitants in Middle Franconia. Seat of the Friedrich-Alexander University and a major location of Siemens AG. Known for: the Baroque Huguenot old town (palace, palace garden), the Bergkirchweih and the palace-garden concerts. It has one of the highest proportions of academics in Germany. Innovative and at the same time down-to-earth and Franconian.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-079": "Wuppertal, with 360,000 inhabitants, is famous for the Schwebebahn — since 1901 it has run 13 km above the river Wupper. The only public transport of its kind in the world. Home of the Bayer corporation, of Pina Bausch and the Tanztheater. Friedrich Engels was born here in 1820. It lies on the eastern edge of the Ruhr region.",
  "alemannisch.al-078": "In some Alemannic villages there is the \"Funkenringen\" — young men try to \"steal\" the wood of the Funken before it is officially set alight. A playful tradition with a serious background: the Funken lads have to defend their work, often spending the night at the Funken site. Village-boy friendships are forged here or enmities are born — all in the spirit of the custom.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-072": "D'\"Fisemadende\" are nonsense, flights of fancy or unnecessary fuss. \"Mach kää Fisemadende un kumm endlich!\" (Don't make a fuss and come on already!) The word is said, by folk etymology, to go back to the French \"visiter ma tente\" (visit my tent), but is in fact older. Parents forbid their children from \"making Fisemadende.\" It also means excuses or shenanigans. A wonderfully baroque Palatine word that shows the playful delight in long, sonorous expressions. Used half scolding, half amused.",
  "hessisch.h-100": "A self-ironic yet proud Hessian term for the pronounced regional pride of the Hessians. The \"Hessebabb\" loves his land above all else — Ebbelwoi (apple wine), Grie Soß (green sauce), Eintracht Frankfurt, the Vogelsberg and the down-to-earth nature of his fellow Hessians. \"Ich bin halt en echter Hessebabb!\" (I'm just a real Hessebabb!) is both an avowal and a declaration of love for the homeland. The Hessian sense of identity in a single word.",
  "berlinisch.b-098": "Berlin has a continental climate with long, cold winters. \"Det is heut wieder janz schön kalt\" (\"It's pretty darn cold again today\") is the standard Berlin complaint from November to March. Berliners know the cold and dress accordingly — a hat, scarf and sturdy shoes are a must. Despite the cold, Berliners like to sit outside at cafés in winter, with a blanket and mulled wine.",
  "bayerisch.by-091": "Gerhard Polt (b. 1942) is Bavaria's most famous cabaret artist — born in Munich. His satirical monologues and sketches about the Bavarian petty bourgeois are cult classics. \"Fast wia im richtigen Leben\" (\"Almost like in real life\") and \"Mei is des ärgerlich\" (\"My, how annoying\") are classics. With an incorruptible eye, Polt dissects Bavarian and German sensibilities. Together with the Well-Buam (Biermösl Blosn) he toured for decades. An icon of Bavarian humor.",
  "saechsisch.s-078": "Carl Maria von Weber (1786–1826) was an important German composer of the Romantic era — director of music at the Dresden court opera from 1817 until his death. His most famous work: \"Der Freischütz\" (1821), considered the first German Romantic national opera. With the \"Wolf's Glen scene\" he created a milestone in the history of opera. Weber's house in Hosterwitz near Dresden is now a museum. His grave is in Dresden.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-080": "Heilbronn is the fourth-largest city in Baden-Württemberg, on the Neckar, with 126,000 inhabitants. It is a significant wine-growing center (the largest wine city in Baden-Württemberg) and an industrial hub (Audi, Bechtle, the Schwarz Group = Lidl/Kaufland). It is known for the experimenta (science museum) and the Käthchenhaus (from Heinrich von Kleist's \"Das Käthchen von Heilbronn\").",
  "koelsch.k-095": "Mettwöörtchen is the Cologne diminutive of Mettwurst — a small, seasoned sausage served as a snack in the brewery taverns. With a pot of mustard and a bread roll, the Mettwöörtchen is a classic brewery-tavern snack. In Cologne's food culture, small portions with great intensity of flavor are a tradition.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-083": "Rostock is the largest city in Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania and an old Hanseatic city on the Baltic Sea. It is home to one of the oldest universities in Northern Europe (founded in 1419). The Hanse Sail in August is the largest festival of traditional sailing ships on the Baltic. Warnemünde, the seaside district with its lighthouse, is a popular destination.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-081": "Lake Lucerne (Vierwaldstättersee) is one of the most beautiful lakes in Switzerland — nestled among the four original cantons of Uri, Schwyz, Unterwalden and Lucerne (hence the name). With its branching shape, steep mountains and the Rütli meadow, it is the cradle of the Swiss Confederation. Historic steamships ply the lake. Lucerne, with the Chapel Bridge, is the most important town on the lake. Mark Twain loved the lake — he called it the most beautiful spectacle in the world.",
  "wienerisch.w-078": "Gustav Klimt (1862–1918) is the most famous painter of Viennese Art Nouveau — co-founder of the Vienna Secession. His gold-adorned paintings such as \"The Kiss\" (1908, Belvedere) and the \"Portrait of Adele Bloch-Bauer I\" are icons. Klimt painted sensual portraits of women and mythological scenes with gold leaf and exotic patterns. The story of his looted paintings (Adele) was made into the film \"Woman in Gold.\" The Viennese fin de siècle at its purest.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-078": "Bayreuth, with 73,000 inhabitants, is THE Wagner city — home of the Bayreuth Festival since 1876. It is also rich in cultural history: the Margravial Opera House (UNESCO World Heritage), the Hermitage palace of Margravine Wilhelmine. The University of Bayreuth is young and innovative. The city lies in the Bayreuther Land, a hilly landscape of Upper Franconia.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-081": "Recklinghausen, with 115,000 inhabitants, is the home of the Ruhrfestspiele — since 1947 one of the oldest and most important theater festivals in Europe. The idea: to bring artists and workers together. The festival hall opened in 1965. The Recklinghausen ice arena is also well known. Economically, the city has been hit hard by structural change.",
  "alemannisch.al-079": "In the Black Forest there are over 14,000 traditional schnapps distilleries — private individuals holding distilling rights. Every larger farm has its own small distillery, where kirsch, Williams pear, mirabelle, plum and apple are distilled. These \"schnapps distillers\" are a cultural treasure — the Black Forest has the highest density of private distilleries in Europe. Every fine brandy tells its own story.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-073": "A \"Lalleworscht\" is someone who talks a lot and likes to talk, often with little substance — a chatterbox. \"Die Nochbarin is a richtige Lalleworscht, die babbelt de ganze Daag!\" (\"The neighbor is a real chatterbox, she yaks all day long!\"). It is made up of \"lallen\" (to babble indistinctly) and \"Worscht\" (sausage). Meant affectionately and mockingly, rarely truly mean. A classic example of the vivid Palatine poetry of insults, which is not stingy with sausage comparisons. By the garden fence or in the Beischt (tavern) you'll always run into a Lalleworscht.",
  "hessisch.h-104": "Wiesbaden is the capital of Hesse — an elegant spa town with a rich bathing tradition. It is famous for the Kurhaus with its casino (Dostoevsky gambled away his fortune here), the Kaiser-Friedrich-Therme and the historic market square. It is also the seat of the Hessian state government. In contrast to hectic Frankfurt, Wiesbaden is genteel and somewhat old-fashioned — which is part of the city's charm.",
  "berlinisch.b-099": "The \"Späti-Bier\" is a Berlin institution — the beer you pick up at the late-night corner shop in the evening or at night and drink on the street, in the park or by the canal. Drinking in public is legal in Berlin and is part of the cityscape. Sterni (Sternburg), Beck's or Berliner Pilsner are the classics. In summer by the Landwehrkanal with a Späti beer — that's the Berlin way of life.",
  "bayerisch.by-092": "At the Wiesn (Oktoberfest), the \"Heuwagen\" (hay wagon) is a famous ride — an old-fashioned wooden carousel that looks like a farm wagon and is ridden with funny songs and plenty of beer. A Bavarian variant of the \"Wild Mouse\" or similar. Many Bavarian funfairs have Heuwagen-style rides. A symbol of the rural roots of the Oktoberfest as an original harvest festival.",
  "saechsisch.s-079": "Robert Schumann (1810–1856) is one of Saxony's greatest composers — born in Zwickau, he studied in Leipzig and lived and worked in Dresden. Together with his wife Clara Schumann (née Wieck), one of the most important pianists of her time, he formed a famous artist couple. Works such as \"Kinderszenen,\" \"Dichterliebe\" and his Piano Concerto in A minor are milestones of Romanticism. Schumann suffered from psychological crises and died in a mental asylum.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-081": "Aalen lies on the eastern edge of the Swabian Alb — 68,000 inhabitants. It is the most important Roman site in southern Germany: the Limesmuseum documents the largest cavalry fort north of the Alps. Today it is a university town with a tool industry. The gateway to the Härtsfeld and a popular local recreation area.",
  "koelsch.k-096": "Eiergewuesch is a hearty Cologne breakfast dish — scrambled eggs with bacon, onions and herbs, often served straight from the pan. \"Gewuesch\" means \"mixture\" or \"jumble\" — the word describes the rustic way it is prepared. In the brewery tavern and at Sunday breakfast, Eiergewuesch is a popular dish.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-084": "Stralsund is one of the best-preserved brick Gothic cities in Europe and has been a UNESCO World Heritage Site since 2002 (together with Wismar). The old town with its town hall and St. Nicholas Church has a medieval character. The Ozeaneum on the harbor is one of the most modern aquariums in Europe. The gateway to the island of Rügen.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-085": "Vacherin Mont d'Or is a Swiss soft cheese specialty from the Vaud Jura — produced only from mid-August to March. Ripened in a ring of spruce bark, it has an unmistakably resinous flavor. Classically, it is eaten warmed straight from its wooden box with bread or boiled potatoes — \"boîte chaude.\" A wintertime delicacy that enjoys almost cult status in Switzerland. A rival of the French Vacherin du Haut-Doubs.",
  "wienerisch.w-079": "Egon Schiele (1890–1918) was Klimt's brilliant pupil and one of the most important Expressionists. His ecstatic, often nude self-portraits and his emaciated, sensual female figures broke with all conventions. Schiele died at just 28 of the Spanish flu — a few days after his pregnant wife Edith. His work in the Leopold Museum (in the MuseumsQuartier) attracts hundreds of thousands of visitors every year. The Viennese avant-garde of modernism.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-079": "Hof an der Saale, with 47,000 inhabitants, is the northeasternmost city in Bavaria — right on the border with Saxony and Thuringia. It is known for the International Hof Film Festival (May), one of the most important German film festivals. The city has a harsher climate than the rest of Franconia (\"Bavarian Siberia\"). An industrial city with a history of structural change.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-082": "Castrop-Rauxel, with 73,000 inhabitants, was formed in 1926 by the merger of two municipalities — hence the characteristic double name. It became famous through Loriot's district sketch \"Die Höxter.\" It is home to the Westphalia Olympic training center for boxing. It is known for the city motto \"Stadt im Zentrum der Vest\" (City at the center of the Vest). A pronounced Ruhr-region charm.",
  "alemannisch.al-080": "The \"Edelbrand\" (fine brandy) is the crowning achievement of Black Forest distilling — high-quality fruit brandies made from pure fruit without additives. Unlike a \"Geist\" (fruit macerate), the Edelbrand is distilled from fermented fruit. Famous fine brandies: mirabelle, Williams pear, wild cherry, plum. Black Forest fine-brandy distillers have won world spirits competitions several times. Premium quality as cultural heritage.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-074": "\"Bagaasch\" is a pejorative term for a group of people, a clan or a gang — from the French \"bagage\" (luggage, riffraff). \"Die ganz Bagaasch is widder beim Feschd aufgkreuzt!\" (\"The whole gang turned up at the fair again!\"). It can jokingly refer to one's own large family (\"mei ganz Bagaasch kummt zu Besuch\" — \"my whole tribe is coming to visit\") or mockingly to strangers. Another French loanword. Depending on the tone, it is affectionate or disparaging. It belongs to the colorful Palatine vocabulary for groups of people.",
  "hessisch.h-105": "Rüdesheim am Rhein is a tourist stronghold on the bend of the Rhine — known for the Drosselgasse (a 144-meter-long wine alley lined with restaurants), the Niederwald statue (the Germania monument) and Asbach Uralt (brandy). In summer, tourists from all over the world crowd through the lanes. Honest Hessian Rheingau Riesling and the typical way of life can be experienced here.",
  "berlinisch.b-100": "A humorous, slightly ironic Berlin farewell phrase with a Russian-sounding ending \"-owski.\" \"Tschüssikowski\" or \"Tschüssi\" is said among friends to soften the pain of parting with a wink. The ending recalls Russian surnames and is a legacy of the once-strong Russian presence in Berlin. Popular since the 1990s.",
  "bayerisch.by-093": "The \"Schmaizler\" is the traditional snuff tobacco in Bavarian — a fine-grained tobacco that is sniffed up the nose. Enjoying Schmaizler is deeply rooted in rural Bavarian culture, especially among older men. At the \"Schmaizler snuff competition\" at some Bavarian festivals, the biggest sneezing reflex is awarded a prize. The little tobacco tin is often ornately decorated.",
  "saechsisch.s-080": "Görlitz, on the Polish border, is Saxony's easternmost city — affectionately called \"Görliwood\" for its outstandingly preserved historic old town. Numerous films have been shot here: \"The Grand Budapest Hotel,\" \"Inglourious Basterds,\" \"The Reader,\" \"Around the World in 80 Days.\" The city has preserved over 4,000 architectural monuments from six centuries — from Gothic to Art Nouveau. Together with the Polish town of Zgorzelec, it forms a European city.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-082": "Esslingen am Neckar is a city of 95,000 inhabitants directly east of Stuttgart. The well-preserved medieval old town with its castle, half-timbered houses and city wall is one of the most beautiful in southern Germany. The Esslingen Medieval Market at Christmas time is legendary. A Daimler site and a university town.",
  "koelsch.k-097": "The Kranzkölsch is the typical way of serving in the Cologne brewery tavern: the Köbes (waiter) carries a round \"wreath\" (Kranz) with up to 18 Kölsch glasses — arranged in a circle on a special tray. This way he can efficiently serve many guests at once. The sight of a full Kranzkölsch is brewery-tavern culture in its purest form.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-085": "Wismar, on the Baltic Sea, belonged to Sweden for 200 years and therefore retained an identity of its own. A UNESCO World Heritage Site since 2002. The silhouette of the Wassertorturm above the old harbor is a postcard motif. F.W. Murnau's \"Nosferatu\" was partly filmed here — the town served as a backdrop for German film history.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-087": "Adelboden in the Bernese Oberland is famous for the annual giant slalom ski race on the Chuenisbärgli — one of the most difficult slopes in the World Cup. The village lies picturesquely between the mountains, with a historic church and traditional wooden houses. In summer a hiking paradise, in winter one of the most beautiful ski areas in Switzerland. Marco Odermatt and, earlier, Pirmin Zurbriggen fought for World Cup points here.",
  "wienerisch.w-080": "The MuseumsQuartier (MQ) in the 7th district is one of the largest cultural areas in the world — 60,000 m² with the Leopold Museum, mumok (Museum of Modern Art), Kunsthalle Wien, Tanzquartier, the Architecture Center and many cafés. It opened in 2001 in the former imperial court stables. The colorful \"Enzis\" seating in the courtyard is a cult favorite — in summer a meeting place for young Viennese. A brilliant combination of Baroque facade and modern art.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-080": "Schweinfurt, with 54,000 inhabitants, is an industrial center of the roller-bearing industry (SKF, FAG, Schaeffler) — a world market leader. In World War II it was heavily bombed because of its ball-bearing production. The birthplace of Friedrich Rückert (poet). Home of the bratwurst \"Schweinfurter Bratworscht.\" Genuine working-class Franconia on the Main.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-083": "Herne, with 156,000 inhabitants, is one of the most densely populated cities in Germany. In the 19th century, the small farming settlement grew explosively thanks to mining. It is known for the Cranger Kirmes — one of the largest funfairs in Germany (4 million visitors a year). Home of the \"Westkurve\" supporters of FC Schalke 04. Charmingly industrial.",
  "alemannisch.al-082": "Allgäu cheese is one of the most important export goods of the Alemannic-Swabian region — above all Allgäu mountain cheese, Emmental and Weißlacker. Over 1,800 farms produce Allgäu cheese, many directly on the alpine pastures. A protected designation of origin. The cheese recipes often go back centuries. Allgäu farmers have developed cheese into an art — from alpine farming to a world product.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-075": "\"Maud\" is the mouth or the gob. \"Halt dei Maud un hör zu!\" (\"Shut your gob and listen!\"). Coarse, but used in everyday speech. Idioms: \"a große Maud habe\" (to be a loudmouth), \"die Maud uffreiße\" (to brag). Whoever \"uff die Maud fallt\" (falls flat on their face) makes a fool of themselves. Related to the standard German \"Maul.\" It belongs to the rich Palatine vocabulary for body parts and crops up in many vigorous turns of phrase. Direct and blunt, just the way the Palatine speaks when the mood takes him.",
  "hessisch.h-106": "The Rheingau is one of the most important German wine regions — on the Rhine between Wiesbaden and Lorch. Famous for Spätlese and Auslese Rieslings. Schloss Johannisberg, Eberbach Monastery (with the \"Steinberg\") and Schloss Vollrads are iconic wine estates. The \"Riesling Summer\" Rheingau Music Festival draws tourists. The late-summer grape harvest has been a tradition here for over 1,200 years — Charlemagne ordered viticulture to be established here.",
  "berlinisch.b-104": "The Spreewald, southeast of Berlin, is a unique nature reserve — here the Spree divides into 1,575 km of waterways and channels (Fließe). A UNESCO Biosphere Reserve. Known for the Spreewald gherkins (a protected designation of origin), the typical punt rides with the Stocherkahn and the Sorbian tradition. A popular destination for Berliners' weekend trips.",
  "bayerisch.by-094": "„Ofengwiagn“ — literally „oven cradle“ — is the Bavarian term for the characteristic belly roll that hangs over the waistband on some men. The word refers to the way the belly hangs like a cradle in front of the oven. A humorously crude word used without any real malice, often self-deprecatingly. Bavarian beer culture and good cuisine take their toll.",
  "saechsisch.s-081": "Bautzener Senf (Bautzen mustard) from the Lusatian town of Bautzen is THE mustard of eastern Germany — it has been made in Bautzen since 1866. The spicy, savory variety (medium-hot mustard) is the best known. During the shortages of the GDR era, Bautzener Senf was an almost mythical resource — today it is available worldwide. With a Thuringian bratwurst, a Kassler, or with a cold-cut snack, Bautzener Senf is simply a must — a Saxon-Lusatian tradition.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-083": "Ludwigsburg, north of Stuttgart, is with 96,000 inhabitants the largest Baroque city in Germany. The Residential Palace („Swabian Versailles“) with 452 rooms is the largest surviving Baroque palace in Germany. The palace park annually hosts the „Blühendes Barock“ (Blooming Baroque) and the pumpkin exhibition. Also home to the Baden-Württemberg Film Academy.",
  "koelsch.k-098": "The Cologne „Klüngel“ is the infamous system of personal relationships and favors that shapes Cologne for better and for worse. „You know each other, you help each other“ is the principle. In politics, the Klüngel led to scandals; in everyday life, it makes life more humane. „Et hätt noch immer jot jejange — durch Klüngel“ (It has always turned out fine — thanks to the Klüngel) goes the mocking saying.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-086": "Cuxhaven lies right at the mouth of the Elbe into the North Sea — a strategically important port and Germany's largest North Sea seaside spa. The „Kugelbake“ officially marks the boundary between the Elbe and the North Sea. A popular destination for Hamburg's residents. Mudflat hikes, spa cures, and fishing characterize the town.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-088": "St. Moritz in the Upper Engadine is THE chic Swiss ski resort — twice host of the Winter Olympic Games (1928, 1948). Over 5,000 hours of sunshine per year, the characteristic „champagne climate“ at 1,856 m. The luxury hotels (Badrutt's Palace, Kulm Hotel) are among the best in the world. Winter sports, the Cresta Run, snow polo, ski joring, and horse races on the frozen lake. A meeting point for the rich and famous of the world.",
  "wienerisch.w-081": "The Donauturm (Danube Tower) in Vienna's 22nd district is, at 252 meters, the tallest structure in Austria — built in 1964 for the Vienna International Garden Show. At 150 meters there is a revolving restaurant that completes a full turn in 39 or 26 minutes — in clear weather you can see all the way to Bratislava. A popular viewpoint with bungee jumping from the tower for the brave. A symbol of the modern Donaustadt skyline.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-081": "Aschaffenburg, with 71,000 inhabitants, lies in the northwest of Bavaria on the Main, almost at the Hessian border. Known as the „Bavarian Nice“ because of its mild climate. Famous landmarks: Johannisburg Castle (Renaissance) and the Pompejanum (Ludwig I had a Roman house reconstructed here). A transitional zone between the Franconian and Hessian dialects. An industrial and educational city.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-087": "Ralf Husmann (born 1964) is a well-known German screenwriter and showrunner from the Ruhr area. Creator of the hit series „Stromberg“ (2004–2012), a German adaptation of „The Office“. „Mord mit Aussicht“ and „Beste Schwestern“ also come from his pen. He embodies the intelligent, biting Ruhrpott humor in modern television entertainment.",
  "alemannisch.al-083": "The „Tannzapfeln“ — pinecones — are versatile in the Alemannic-speaking region: kindling, Christmas decoration, raw material in pellet heating. An old tradition: when the Tannzapfeln „chnottern“ (crackle) in September, autumn is announcing itself. Pinecones also appear in folk songs and fairy tales. In the Black Forest, every family collects them for Christmas decoration.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-076": "The „Quetschekuche“ is plum cake — „Quetsche“ is what they call the plum (Zwetschge) in the Palatinate. „Im Herbscht gibt's Quetschekuche mit Schmand!“ (In autumn there's plum cake with sour cream!) A popular seasonal pastry, often baked on a sheet and served with crumble or cream. The plums from Palatine gardens make it especially aromatic. A classic for coffee time in late summer and autumn. Whoever says „Quetsche“ instead of Zwetschge is guaranteed to be from the Palatinate or neighboring Hesse.",
  "hessisch.h-110": "The Hessenpark in Neu-Anspach (Taunus) is Hesse's large open-air museum — 60 hectares with historic houses, churches, mills, and workshops from all over Hesse, reassembled here. Visitors experience Hessian rural life of past centuries. Craftspeople demonstrate traditional arts (blacksmithing, pottery, beer brewing). A unique museum that keeps Hessian heritage alive.",
  "berlinisch.b-105": "The Volkspark Friedrichshain is Berlin's oldest public park — laid out in 1846 as a gift to the people of Berlin. With the Märchenbrunnen (Fairy Tale Fountain), the rubble hill „Mont Klamott“ (made of wartime debris), and the open-air stage, it is a typical Berlin people's park. In summer a meeting point for families, joggers, slackliners, and barbecue crews. In winter a tobogganing slope. Pure Berlin way of life.",
  "bayerisch.by-095": "Aiblinger beer is brewed at the Maxlrain brewery near Bad Aibling in the Mangfall Valley — one of the oldest breweries in Bavaria (founded in 1636). Known for its bottom-fermented beers and the unusual brewing tradition with its own well. Bad Aibling itself is a moor spa town in the Upper Bavarian Alpine foothills — a popular health resort and film backdrop for the TV series „Die Rosenheim-Cops“.",
  "saechsisch.s-082": "Radeberger Pilsner from the town of Radeberg (between Dresden and Bautzen) is Germany's oldest Pilsner — brewed since 1872. „Bismarck's Pilsner“ — the Reich Chancellor drank Radeberger at the Hofbräu in Berlin. King Friedrich August III of Saxony declared it the court beer. The slim, hoppy-bitter Pils is Saxony's proud export beer and conquered the market both in the GDR and after reunification. Today it belongs to the Radeberger Group.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-084": "Volker Häussermann (born 1937) shaped the Swabian cabaret scene and dialect poetry as „the poetizing Swabian“. With works like „I sag's ja“ and „Schwäbisch für Anfänger“ (Swabian for Beginners), he became the voice of Swabian self-reflection and gentle mockery. His texts are required reading for anyone who wants to understand the Swabian soul.",
  "koelsch.k-099": "„Wä?“ is a typically Cologne tag question at the end of a sentence — similar to the Swabian „gell“ or standard German „nicht wahr?“ (right?). It invites confirmation and is an important feature of the Cologne conversational style. „Dat hät et nit jejovve, wä?“ (That didn't happen, right?) — a confirmation is expected.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-087": "In the 19th and early 20th centuries, Bremerhaven was the most important emigration port in Europe — millions of Germans set sail from here to America. The German Emigration Center documents this history. Today it is the largest car-handling port in Europe. The Klimahaus and the German Maritime Museum are further attractions.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-089": "Davos in Graubünden is the highest-altitude town in Europe (1,560 m) — known as a health resort against tuberculosis in the 19th century (Thomas Mann set his „Magic Mountain“ here) and today worldwide as the meeting place of the World Economic Forum (WEF). Every January, heads of state and government, CEOs, and activists gather for the „Davos Forum“. Also a popular ski resort and home of HC Davos (Spengler Cup in ice hockey).",
  "wienerisch.w-082": "The Albertina on Albertinaplatz in the 1st district is one of Vienna's most important art museums — known for one of the largest graphic art collections in the world (1.5 million works). It shows works by Dürer (the famous „Young Hare“), Rubens, Monet, Klimt, Picasso, and Andy Warhol. Housed in the magnificent Palais Habsburg-Lothringen. The Albertina exhibitions change regularly with major special shows.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-082": "Ansbach, with 42,000 inhabitants, is the capital of Middle Franconia and a former margravial residence. Famous landmarks: the Margravial Residence (Rococo) and the Margravial Theatre. Home of the Ansbach Bach Week (one of the most important Bach festivals worldwide). Also militarily significant — a US military base since 1945. A charming small Baroque town in the Franconian style.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-089": "The Emscher flows 83 km right through the middle of the Ruhr area — until a few years ago Europe's largest open sewage canal („Köttelbecke“, turd brook). Since 1991, the major Emscher conversion project has been running: renaturation, underground treatment plants — the river is becoming clean again. A symbol of ecological structural change. By 2021 it was officially „sewage-free“.",
  "alemannisch.al-084": "The maypole is an Alemannic spring tradition — on May 1st a tall, decorated tree is erected in the village center. Erecting the maypole is an honorable men's task. In some villages the maypole is „stolen“ by neighboring villages — a playful rivalry with tradition. Young men dance with the girls around the maypole. A symbol of fertility and community.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-077": "The „Dippche“ is a small pot or little bowl — the diminutive of „Dippe“ (pot). „Gib mir es Dippche mit em Senf riwwer!“ (Pass me the little pot with the mustard!) Also the chamber pot for small children. Related to standard German „Tüpfchen“ and the Rhenish „Dippe“. The ending „-che“ is the Palatine diminutive par excellence. In the kitchen, every ingredient has its own Dippche ready. An affectionate, everyday word of Palatine household language.",
  "hessisch.h-113": "The Eintracht anthem „Im Herzen von Europa“ (In the Heart of Europe), sung by the Hessian singer-songwriter Hans-Jürgen „Hänsel“ Klotz, has been the official club anthem of Eintracht Frankfurt since the 1980s. In the Waldstadion (Deutsche Bank Park), 50,000 fans sing along at every home game. „Eintracht Frankfurt, in unseren Herzen / Im Herzen von Europa“ (Eintracht Frankfurt, in our hearts / In the heart of Europe). Mandatory karaoke for every Frankfurt fan.",
  "berlinisch.b-106": "The Tempelhofer Feld is one of the largest inner-city open spaces in the world — the former airfield of Tempelhof Airport (closed in 2008). 303 hectares of asphalt runways and meadows were opened to the public in 2010. Today: skaters, kite flyers, inline skaters, picnicking families, urban farming projects. For Berliners it is almost a sacred place — attempts to build on it have been rejected several times.",
  "bayerisch.by-096": "Andechs Monastery on the „Holy Mountain“ above Lake Ammersee is one of the oldest pilgrimage monasteries in Bavaria (founded in the 11th century). Famous for its own monastery brewery with the legendary Andechser Doppelbock and its rustic monastery inn. The climb up to the monastery is a popular hiking day for Munich residents — at the top, a Maß and a cold-cut snack are served. Spirituality and beer culture united to perfection.",
  "saechsisch.s-083": "Wernesgrüner Pilsner Legende is one of the oldest and most popular beers in Saxony — brewed since 1436 in the Vogtland village of Wernesgrün. Beyond the GDR era, Wernesgrüner has secured a firm place in the Saxon beer market. The brewery is one of the most tradition-rich family breweries in Germany. A clear, slim Pils with a pleasant hop note. „Bitte ein Wernesgrüner!“ (A Wernesgrüner, please!) can be heard in every Saxon tavern.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-085": "Christoph Sonntag (born 1962) is Stuttgart's best-known dialect cabaret artist. With biting mockery of Swabian idiosyncrasies and southern German politics, he has been filling the halls since the 1990s. His book „Sonntag schreibt“ (Sonntag Writes) and his stage shows „Bezahlt!“ (Paid!) are cult. He embodies the critical, self-ironic side of Swabianness.",
  "koelsch.k-100": "One of the best-known Cologne songs, written by the Bäck Fööss. The title is a declaration of love for the homeland: no matter what the world has to offer — the cathedral and Cologne remain immovable for the true Cologne native. The song is sung as the unofficial anthem of emigrants and returnees and ends every big Carnival session.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-088": "Otto Waalkes (born 1948 in Emden) is one of the most successful German comedians. With his „Ottifanten“ (Ottifants) and the early comedy films, he shaped the humor of a generation from the 1970s on. „Otto — Der Film“ (1985) was the most successful German film of all time at the time. His East Frisian accent and absurd humor are his trademark.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-090": "The Bürgenstock on Lake Lucerne is a famous luxury resort on a rocky plateau, 500 m above the lake. Audrey Hepburn lived here for 14 years. Sophia Loren as well. Today it is run by Qatari investors with five hotels and the highest outdoor lift in Europe — the Hammetschwand lift takes visitors 152 m up the rock face. A breathtaking view of the lake and the Swiss Alps.",
  "wienerisch.w-084": "The Spanish Riding School in the Vienna Hofburg is the oldest and probably most famous classical riding school in the world — for over 450 years, Lipizzaner stallions have been trained here in the „High School“ of classical dressage. The performances in the Baroque Winter Riding School with Mozart music are a unique experience. UNESCO cultural heritage. The Lipizzaners are bred at the Piber stud farm in Styria.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-083": "Schwabach, south of Nuremberg with 41,000 inhabitants, is the German capital of the gold-beating craft — gold leaf has been made here by hand for centuries. Over 80% of German gold leaf comes from Schwabach. The Schwabach script (a precursor of the Fraktur script) also bears its name. A charming small town with great craft significance.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-090": "The Regional Association Ruhr (RVR) is the union of 53 cities and districts of the Ruhr area — founded in 1920 as the „Siedlungsverband Ruhrkohlenbezirk“ (Ruhr Coal District Settlement Association). The largest municipal association in Germany, with 5.1 million inhabitants. Responsible for regional planning, local recreation (slag heaps, routes), and culture. RVR signs with the white tiger gate are landmarks.",
  "alemannisch.al-085": "Vorarlbergerisch is the Alemannic dialect of Vorarlberg (Austria) — linguistically closer to Swiss German and Swabian than to the rest of Austrian German. Vorarlberg historically belonged to the Alemannic area (Habsburg territory, but culturally Swiss-South German). Walgau, Bregenzerwald, and Montafon each have their own dialect variants. Identity-forming in contrast to the „Bavarian“-shaped rest of Austria.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-078": "The „Schniss“ is the face, especially the expression or facial expression. „Mach ned so a saure Schniss, es is doch alles gut!“ (Don't make such a sour face, everything's fine!) Whoever „zieht a beleidigte Schniss“ (pulls an offended face) is sulking. Related to „Schnauze“ (snout). Mostly used in connection with facial expressions. Part of the vivid Palatine body vocabulary. When the Palatine is in a bad mood, you can see the „Schniss“ right away. Direct and expressive like the whole dialect.",
  "hessisch.h-114": "The Frankfurt Book Fair is the largest book fair in the world — held annually in October since 1949. Over 7,300 exhibitors from 100 countries, 250,000 visitors. International licenses are negotiated here, new books are presented, and the Peace Prize of the German Book Trade is awarded. Each year a different country is the guest of honor. For the German book industry, the Book Fair is the most important event of the year.",
  "berlinisch.b-109": "The Großer Müggelsee in the east of Berlin is, at 7.4 km², the largest lake in the capital. In summer a bathing paradise, in winter walkable when frozen. The view from the Müggelturm offers a panorama over half of Berlin. With the Müggelsee steamer you can take boat tours. Popular among Berliners for recreation — free beaches, water sports, restaurants on the shore. Berlin is a „city by the water“.",
  "bayerisch.by-097": "A „Schalk“ is a humorous, witty person with a penchant for little pranks — not malicious, but with twinkling eyes and unexpected punchlines. „Den Schalk im Nacken haben“ (to have the rascal on one's back) describes someone who is about to crack a joke. In Bavarian, this kind of person is beloved — the Bavarian values roguish wit more than crude mockery. Closely related to mischievous boyishness.",
  "saechsisch.s-084": "Freiberg in the Erzgebirge foothills is Saxony's oldest mining town — silver mining since 1168. The Bergakademie Freiberg, one of the oldest technical universities in the world, was founded here in 1765. Famous alumni: Alexander von Humboldt, Werner von Siemens. The historic old town with its cathedral, Freudenstein Castle (home of the Terra Mineralia mineral treasury) and the miners' houses is part of the UNESCO World Heritage Site Erzgebirge/Krušnohoří Mining Region.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-086": "The «Häuslebauer» (house builder) is the quintessential Swabian life goal — the person who builds their own house. The mentality «Schaffe, schaffe, Häusle baue» (work, work, build a little house) is deeply rooted in Swabian culture. The home ownership rate in Baden-Württemberg is one of the highest in Germany. Swabians save for years and often help build it themselves, with relatives and neighbours.",
  "koelsch.k-101": "Cologne Cathedral (the High Cathedral of St. Peter) is the landmark of Cologne and Germany's most visited attraction (6 million visitors a year). Construction began in 1248 and was completed in 1880 — 632 years of building history! At 157.4 m, it was the tallest building in the world in 1880. A UNESCO World Heritage Site. It has housed the relics of the Three Wise Men since 1164. The 533 steps up to the south tower offer a panoramic view over Cologne.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-089": "Hans Albers (1891–1960) was Hamburg's most famous actor and singer — the «blond Hans». His song «Auf der Reeperbahn nachts um halb eins» is a Hamburg anthem. Films like «Münchhausen» and «Große Freiheit Nr. 7» made him immortal. His monument in front of Hamburg's main railway station shows him with a sailor's cap.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-091": "The Swiss army is a militia army — every male Swiss citizen is liable for military service and completes basic training (Rekrutenschule, RS) followed by annual refresher courses (Wiederholungskurse, WK). After basic training, soldiers take the assault rifle (Stgw 90) home with them — a typically Swiss citizen-militia concept. Military service has a socially integrative function. Women may serve voluntarily. The army is firmly rooted among the people.",
  "wienerisch.w-085": "The Vienna Boys' Choir is one of the most famous boys' choirs in the world — founded in 1498 by Emperor Maximilian I. Over 500 years of tradition. Today the choir consists of four choral groups with a total of 100 boys (aged 9 to 14). They tour worldwide, perform on Sundays in the Vienna Hofburg Chapel and are musical ambassadors of Austria. Joseph Haydn and Franz Schubert once sang as choirboys.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-084": "Iphofen, with 4,500 inhabitants, is one of the most important Franconian wine villages — seven vineyard sites producing top wines (Julius-Echter-Berg, Kalb, Kronsberg). The medieval townscape with its town wall, towers and half-timbered houses is exceptionally well preserved. The Knauf group has its headquarters here. A town of art and wine — a little jewel of the Main Triangle.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-091": "«Pott-Liebe» (love of the Pott) is the almost religious attachment of the people of the Ruhr region to their homeland. Unlike other regions that revere individual cities, the people of the Pott love the whole region — from Duisburg to Dortmund, from Essen to Bottrop. This «Pott-Liebe» arose in the mining generations, when solidarity was vital for survival. Today it is an attitude to life.",
  "alemannisch.al-086": "Walliser/Walser German is the most archaic variety of Highest Alemannic — spoken by the Walser, an ethnic group that emigrated in the 13th/14th centuries from the Swiss Valais to Vorarlberg, Liechtenstein and northern Italy. The Kleinwalsertal in Vorarlberg is a German-speaking enclave, reachable only via Austria. Here an ancient Walser German is cultivated — the legacy of Alpine pioneers.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-079": "The «Hergottsbscheißerle» are the Maultaschen — literally «little Lord-God-cheaters». «In de Fasdezeit gab's Hergottsbscheißerle, weil mer s'Fleisch verschteckt hot!» (In Lent there were Hergottsbscheißerle, because the meat was hidden!). According to legend, the meat hidden in the dough was meant to «outwit» the Lord God during Lent. Originally Swabian, but also widespread and popular in the neighbouring Palatinate. A wonderfully pious yet tongue-in-cheek name for a hearty dish. Served in broth or sautéed.",
  "hessisch.h-115": "Frankfurt is Germany's financial metropolis and the seat of the European Central Bank (ECB), the German Bundesbank and more than 200 banks. The Frankfurt skyline, with skyscrapers like the Commerzbank Tower and the Main Tower, is nicknamed «Mainhattan». The location makes Hesse economically strong. Banker jokes are everyday fare in Frankfurt: «What do you call three bankers at a bar? A mandatory meeting.»",
  "berlinisch.b-111": "The Berlin Funkturm (radio tower) — built in 1926, 150 m high — stands on the exhibition grounds at Kaiserdamm. It is a landmark of West Berlin and looks like a little Eiffel Tower. The observation deck and the restaurant at 55 m offer a view over Berlin. Unlike the Berlin TV Tower (at Alexanderplatz), the Funkturm is a symbol of the 1920s — Bauhaus architecture and the pride of the economic miracle combined.",
  "bayerisch.by-098": "The Bavarian verb «pressiern» means «to be in a hurry» or «to press» — from the French «presser». «Es pressiert mi» means «I'm in a hurry» or «it's pressing on me». A typically Bavarian verb with French roots — the language has retained many such loanwords. «Pressiert's?» is the question «Are you in a hurry?».",
  "saechsisch.s-085": "Chemnitz (called Karl-Marx-Stadt from 1953 to 1990) is the third-largest city in Saxony and, in 2025, European Capital of Culture together with Nova Gorica. Known for its industrial history (mechanical engineering, textiles) and the world-famous 7-metre-high Karl Marx head in the city centre (by Lev Kerbel). Despite heavy war damage and socialist architecture, Chemnitz is experiencing a cultural rebirth today. The Gunzenhauser Museum displays an important collection of Expressionist art.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-087": "The «Sparbüchsle» is more than just a piggy bank — it is a symbol of Swabian thrift. Swabian children get a Sparbüchsle early on and learn not to spend money. The word contains the typical Swabian «-le» diminutive. Every penny is turned over twice. The Schwäbisch Hall building society — a symbol of the saving mentality — is not located in Swabia by chance.",
  "koelsch.k-102": "The Hohenzollern Bridge crosses the Rhine right next to the cathedral — the busiest railway bridge in Germany (over 1,200 trains a day!). It is famous for the thousands of love locks that couples attach to the railing. Blown up during the Second World War, it was rebuilt in 1948. With the equestrian statue of Kaiser Wilhelm II at one end, it is a classic Cologne postcard motif with the cathedral in the background.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-090": "Knut (2006–2011) was the world-famous polar bear of the Berlin Zoo, raised by a keeper after his mother rejected him. His name is a classic northern German Viking name and is still frequently given in Schleswig-Holstein today. Knut's story moved the world — he died suddenly at just four years old.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-092": "The Réduit was the strategic idea of the Swiss army in the Second World War — in the event of an attack, to withdraw into the Alpine fortresses and defend the passes. General Henri Guisan announced this strategy in 1940 at the Rütli — the famous «Rütli Report». Huge bunker complexes were built in the Gotthard massif. Today some of the fortresses are museums. The Réduit concept is regarded as a myth of Swiss independence.",
  "wienerisch.w-086": "The Viennese apple strudel is probably the best-known Austrian pastry — a wafer-thin, hand-stretched strudel dough filled with grated apples, raisins, cinnamon and toasted breadcrumbs. True strudel masters can stretch the dough so thin you can read a newspaper through it. It is served warm with vanilla sauce or whipped cream. On the menu in every Viennese coffee house — the benchmark for good patisserie.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-085": "Volkach, with 8,500 inhabitants, lies picturesquely in a bend of the Main («Mainviereck» / Main Square) and is a stronghold of Franconian wine. The pilgrimage church Maria im Weingarten, with the famous «Madonna in the Rosary» by Tilman Riemenschneider, is a place of pilgrimage. An annual wine festival, a charming old town and the best Franconian wines. A way of life on the Main Square.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-092": "A «Pottoriginal» is an authentic Ruhr-area character with a distinctive personality — usually older, with life experience. Plain speech, coarse humour, a warm heart. They sit in the Trinkhalle (kiosk), at the regulars' table or in front of the chip shop. Pottoriginale are known throughout the whole neighbourhood. With structural change they are becoming fewer — but they are the cultural memory of the region.",
  "alemannisch.al-087": "Elsässerditsch is the Alemannic dialect of French Alsace — closely related to the Baden and southern Palatinate dialects. The main language in Alsace until the Second World War, today it has been heavily pushed back by French language policy. Young Alsatians barely speak it anymore. The cultural organisation OLCA fights for its preservation. An endangered language variety with a centuries-old tradition.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-080": "The «Lällebäbber» is a famous landmark from Frankenthal — a fountain face sticking out its tongue. Figuratively, a person who sticks out their tongue or pulls cheeky faces. «Du klää'ner Lällebäbber, streck ned ständig dei Zung raus!» (You little Lällebäbber, stop sticking out your tongue all the time!). From «Lälle» (tongue) and «bäbbe» (to stick/stretch). An endearingly cheeky Palatine expression, used especially towards children. It shows the region's mischievous humour and its delight in mocking grimaces.",
  "hessisch.h-116": "Frankfurt am Main Airport (FRA) is Germany's largest airport and the third-largest in Europe — Lufthansa's hub. Over 65 million passengers a year. The airport is Hesse's biggest employer (over 80,000 staff). The people of Hesse are proud of it — and at the same time annoyed by the aircraft noise. Frankfurt-Hahn (in the Hunsrück, actually in Rhineland-Palatinate) is also often confused with Frankfurt Airport.",
  "berlinisch.b-113": "The KaDeWe (Kaufhaus des Westens) at Wittenbergplatz is the second-largest department store in Europe after Harrods. Opened in 1907, with 60,000 m² of sales floor. Famous: the gourmet floor on the 6th floor with over 1,300 kinds of cheese and delicacies from all over the world. The KaDeWe stands for West Berlin luxury and consumer culture — even in East German Berlin it was a coveted destination for travellers.",
  "bayerisch.by-100": "The Bavarian word «wuid» corresponds to standard German «wild» — but in Bavarian it has a broader meaning. It can mean «boisterous», «crazy», «great» or «excited». «Des is wuid!» is enthusiastic agreement. «A wuide Hetz» is wild, exuberant fun. Young people use it as a positive intensifier — similar to the Swiss «huere» or the northern German «mega».",
  "saechsisch.s-086": "From 1953 to 1990 Chemnitz was called «Karl-Marx-Stadt» — a socialist renaming on the 70th anniversary of Karl Marx's death. With the peaceful revolution of 1989, the citizens decided by referendum to return to the historic name Chemnitz. The huge Karl Marx head in the city centre (called «Nischel» in Saxon — «the Nischel») remained standing and is today a landmark with an ironic aftertaste. A piece of German history.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-088": "The «Putzfimmel» (cleaning mania) is the Swabian passion for cleaning, which manifests itself in the infamous Kehrwoche (cleaning rota). Swabian housewives (and increasingly househusbands too) are famous for scrubbing every nook and cranny. The cleaning culture is deeply rooted — Swabians are considered the cleanest of all Germans. «A schwäbisches Haus isch a sauberes Haus.» (A Swabian house is a clean house.)",
  "koelsch.k-103": "The Cologne Carnival Prince is the official head of the carnival season. Each year a new prince is chosen (together with the Peasant and the Maiden to form the «Dreigestirn» / Triumvirate). At the proclamation on 11 November he is officially installed in office. During his season the prince attends over 400 events, schools and hospitals. An honorary office demanding great effort — and a source of pride for every true Colognian.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-091": "Buttermilk is a traditional northern German drink — slightly sour, low in fat, refreshing. It is produced as a by-product of churning butter. In the countryside, buttermilk is part of breakfast or the afternoon snack. «Saure Buttermilch» (sour buttermilk) is often combined with sugar and black bread. Long a poor man's drink, today it is health food.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-093": "Johanna Spyri (1827–1901) was a Zurich writer who became world-famous with «Heidi's Years of Learning and Travel» (1880) and «Heidi Can Use What It Has Learned» (1881). The story of the Swiss orphan girl in the mountains of Graubünden is one of the most translated German-language children's books. Spyri was the daughter of a doctor and wrote over 50 more books, but Heidi overshadows everything. Her longing for mountains and cheese shapes Switzerland's image around the world.",
  "wienerisch.w-087": "Vanillekipferl are the most famous Viennese Christmas biscuits — crescent-shaped shortcrust cookies with almond or hazelnut, rolled in vanilla icing sugar. They are said to commemorate the Turkish defeat at the gates of Vienna in 1683 (the crescent shape). Every Viennese family has its own recipe, which is jealously guarded. During Advent, all of Vienna smells of vanilla — Vanillekipferl belong in every biscuit tin.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-086": "The Steigerwald is a low mountain range between Würzburg and Bamberg — rolling beech forests, meadow orchards, vineyards along the edge. A nature park with numerous hiking trails. Famous: the Schwanberg monastery complex, Ebrach Abbey (a Cistercian heritage site). A quiet, unspoilt landscape still untouched by tourism — a Franconian secret region.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-093": "«Helga» is a classic woman's name of the 1950s/60s generation — especially common in the Ruhr area. Rarely given to newborns today, but the Helga generations shape the kiosks, chip shops and club offices. It stands for the strong Pott women who managed everyday life during the mining era, while their men were down the pit. A symbol of female Pott toughness.",
  "alemannisch.al-088": "Tübingen High Alemannic is a transitional dialect between Swabian and High Alemannic — spoken southwest of the Swabian Jura. Characteristic: a stronger sound shift of «k» to «ch» than in standard Swabian («Chind» instead of «Kind» / child). The sing-song intonation is also more Alemannic in character. Tübingen students and academics often cultivate a more literary, refined form.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-081": "The «Worschtsupp» is the hearty sausage soup cooked fresh and distributed to the neighbours during home slaughtering («Metzelsupp»). «Beim Metzgersch gibt's heut frische Worschtsupp!» (At the butcher's there's fresh sausage soup today!). An old Palatine custom: whoever slaughters shares with the neighbours. The soup from the sausage kettle, with bread crumbled into it, warms you up in winter. Closely related to the Worschtbrieh, but understood as a complete dish with garnish. Lived village community and Palatine food culture.",
  "hessisch.h-119": "Frankfurter Würstchen are a traditional Frankfurt speciality — fine, long scalded sausages of pork, in a natural casing, lightly smoked. The genuine ones may only be produced within Frankfurt city limits — a protected geographical indication. They are warmed in hot (not boiling!) water — never boiled! Classic side dishes: bread, mustard and potato salad.",
  "berlinisch.b-116": "The Trabant — «Trabbi» for short — was the iconic East German car, ubiquitous in Berlin. With its Duroplast body and two-stroke engine, it was not the best car, but at the same time an identity-defining status symbol of the GDR. At the fall of the Wall in 1989, Trabbis crept in endless columns across the borders towards the West. Today it is a popular classic car — the «Trabbi safari» is a tourist experience through Berlin.",
  "bayerisch.by-101": "«Ozapft is!» (It's tapped!) — the most famous Bavarian phrase in the world — is shouted by the Mayor of Munich after the first blow into the barrel on the Wiesn (Oktoberfest grounds). The tapping cry has officially opened the Oktoberfest since 1950 (introduced by Mayor Thomas Wimmer). The fewer blows the mayor needs for the tapping before «Ozapft is!» can be shouted, the better the political omen — the record holder is Christian Ude with two blows. A phrase that around the world stands for Bavarian joie de vivre.",
  "saechsisch.s-087": "The Spreewald is a unique landscape in southern Brandenburg/Lusatia — the river Spree fans out into more than 1,000 km of waterways. The Sorbian minority shapes the region culturally. By Spreewald barge (a traditional punt trip) you can reach the villages of Lübben, Lehde and Burg. Famous: Spreewald gherkins (a protected geographical indication), Sorbian traditional dress and Easter customs. A fairy-tale landscape.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-089": "\"Pingelig\" (fussy) is a typically Swabian attribute — overly precise, petty, perfectionist. In professional life a virtue (Daimler, Bosch, Porsche!), in private life often exhausting. The Swabian penchant for detail has made the region economically successful. \"Sei net so pingelig!\" (Don't be so fussy!) is praise and reproach at the same time.",
  "koelsch.k-104": "The \"Elfte Elfte\" (Eleventh of the Eleventh) — November 11 at 11:11 a.m. — is the official start of the carnival season in Cologne. Thousands of Jecken (revelers) fill the Heumarkt and Alter Markt, the new Dreigestirn (trio) is proclaimed, the first carnival songs ring out. An unofficial popular gathering. Even though the \"hot phase\" only begins on Weiberfastnacht — the Elfte Elfte gives the kickoff.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-092": "The Friesenrose (Rosa rugosa) is a wild hedge rose that grows ubiquitously along the North German coasts — from Sylt to Rügen. The pink blossoms and thick red rose hips shape the dune landscape. Jam is cooked from the rose hips, and the tea is regarded as a cold remedy. A symbol of the austere beauty of the north.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-094": "A \"Migros-Kind\" (Migros child) is a typically Swiss childhood concept: a child who walks obediently beside the cart during the Migros shopping trip, gets an M-Budget chocolate bar as a reward, and is delighted when the mother redeems the 10th stamp for the Migros points. It stands for a typically modest middle-class Swiss childhood of the 1980s and 90s. Nowadays used somewhat ironically.",
  "wienerisch.w-088": "In Viennese dialect, quark is called \"Topfen\" — a central element of Austrian pastry culture. Topfenstrudel, Topfenpalatschinken, Topfenknödel, Topfenkrapferl, Topfentorte — the uses are endless. Viennese Topfen is usually drier and stronger in flavor than German quark. Anyone who says \"Quark\" in Vienna immediately outs themselves as a non-Viennese.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-088": "The Rhön is a low mountain range between Bavaria, Hesse, and Thuringia — a UNESCO biosphere reserve. Distinctive open high plateaus with sheep farming, volcanic mountains like the Wasserkuppe (highest peak, 950 m). \"Land of open vistas\" because of the wide views. Famous for: Rhön sheep, Rhön sausage, gliding from the Wasserkuppe. Authentically rural Franconia.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-094": "The Schalke club anthem \"Blau und Weiß, wie lieb ich dich\" (Blue and White, how I love you) is sung before every home game in the Veltins-Arena — 62,000 voices together. A composition from the folk music repertoire, with Schalke lyrics. A goosebumps moment for every royal-blue fan. Connected to the 1934 championship-winning Schalke team and the tradition as a miners' club. More than a song — a religion.",
  "alemannisch.al-091": "Furtwangen in the Black Forest, with 9,000 inhabitants, is THE German clock town — the German Clock Museum displays 8,000 exhibits spanning three centuries of clock history. This is where the Black Forest clock industry was born. The Furtwangen University of Applied Sciences specializes in microtechnology, medical technology, and computer science — a modern continuation of the precision tradition. Also the source of the Danube (Breg spring).",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-082": "A \"Dollbohrer\" is a fool or klutz — literally one who \"drills madly\" (toll bohrt), i.e. does nonsense. \"Du Dollbohrer, host de Schlissel im Auto eigschperrt!\" (You klutz, you locked the keys in the car!) An affectionately exasperated term of abuse, especially among men and colleagues. It ranks alongside Dappschädel and Schoofseggel in the rich Palatine repertoire of insults. It sounds harsher than meant, since genuine malice rarely lies behind it. A classic exclamation when, once again, something has gone wrong.",
  "hessisch.h-121": "Bethmännchen are a Frankfurt specialty — small, round marzipan cookies with three almond halves on the outside. Invented in 1838 by the banker Simon Moritz von Bethmann for his four sons — hence the originally four almonds. When one son died, they were baked with only three almonds from then on. Today a Frankfurt Christmas pastry and year-round specialty. Hessian marzipan heritage.",
  "berlinisch.b-117": "David Bowie lived in West Berlin from 1976 to 1978 (in Schöneberg, Hauptstraße 155) — one of his most creative phases. He recorded his \"Berlin Trilogy\" at the Hansa Studio near Potsdamer Platz: \"Low\", \"Heroes\", \"Lodger\". His song \"Heroes\" (1977) is an anthem about two lovers at the Wall. Bowie revolutionized pop and brought Berlin musically to the world. A memorial plaque hangs on his apartment.",
  "bayerisch.by-102": "The \"Goggerl\" is the Bavarian word for a hen or rooster — an onomatopoeic formation from the typical chicken sound (\"gock gock\"). The diminutive \"Goggerl\" for a little chicken is also often used affectionately. In rural regions of Bavaria, chickens are as much a part of the farm as the cows. The saying \"Mei Goggerl legt heid wieder a Oa\" (My hen is laying an egg again today) epitomizes rural idyll.",
  "saechsisch.s-088": "Spreewald gherkins are a GDR myth and cult product — since reunification a geographical indication protected throughout the EU. The gherkins are pickled in the Spreewald in brine with herbs (dill, mustard seeds, bay leaf). In the film \"Good Bye, Lenin!\" Spreewald gherkins play a central role as a symbol of Eastern identity. Today popular worldwide — above all as a nostalgia product. Various varieties: salt-dill, garlic, mustard gherkins.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-090": "\"Saustall\" (pigsty) is a classic Swabian term of abuse for a messy room or a chaotic situation. In the context of Swabian cleaning culture it is a harsh condemnation. \"Räum endlich dein Saustall auf!\" (Tidy up your pigsty at last!) is a standard saying of Swabian parents. Also used politically: \"Des isch a Saustall, was die da mache!\" (What they're doing there is a pigsty/mess!)",
  "koelsch.k-105": "Weiberfastnacht (Wieverfastelovend) opens the \"street carnival\" — the Thursday before Rose Monday. Women storm the town hall and cut off men's ties (a symbol of power). During this ritual there are Bützchen (little kisses) as an apology. A tradition dating back to the Middle Ages, which all women celebrate today. Schools and public offices close — the city is in carnival fever.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-093": "Brick Gothic is THE architectural style of Hanseatic Northern Germany — Gothic cathedrals, town halls, and city gates made of the characteristic red brick, because no natural stone was available in the north. Lübeck, Stralsund, Wismar, and Greifswald are exemplary towns. The Holstentor and St. Mary's Church in Lübeck are icons of this 800-year-old style.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-095": "Birchermüesli is the original muesli — invented by the Swiss physician Maximilian Bircher-Benner around 1900 at his sanatorium on the Zürichberg. The original recipe: rolled oats soaked overnight, grated apple, lemon juice, honey, almonds, condensed milk. Bircher-Benner believed in the healing power of raw food. The muesli spread worldwide. Today a breakfast classic — Switzerland's contribution to world cuisine.",
  "wienerisch.w-089": "Marillenknödel are a Viennese specialty — a whole Marille (apricot) is wrapped with sugar in a dumpling of quark or potato dough, boiled, and rolled in toasted breadcrumbs. Served dusted with powdered sugar. A main meal, not a dessert — the Viennese like to eat sweet dishes for lunch or dinner. The Marillenknödel season is summer, when the Wachau apricots are ripe.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-089": "The Haßberge are a low mountain range in the north of Lower Franconia, between Coburg and Schweinfurt. Little developed for tourism, but all the more unspoiled. Famous for: Bettenburg Castle, the \"castle corner\" (Burgenwinkel) with numerous medieval ruins. One of Franconia's insider-tip regions for hikers and lovers of quiet landscapes. Haßberge Nature Park.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-096": "The \"Pommesgabel\" (chips fork) is the small wooden fork served with the currywurst and chips at the snack stand — usually two-pronged, single-use. An iconic component of the Ruhr region snack experience. Anyone in the Pott who eats chips without a Pommesgabel is considered a tourist. A symbol of practical, down-to-earth enjoyment without any fuss. Together with Pommes Schranke (chips with ketchup and mayo) and currywurst, it's a set.",
  "alemannisch.al-093": "The Wiesental in the southern Black Forest follows the river Wiese from Todtnauberg down to Lörrach/Basel. One of the most beautiful Black Forest landscapes — gentle hills, Alemannic farmhouses, vineyards in the lower part. Home of the Alemannic poet Johann Peter Hebel (Hausen im Wiesental). Known for: Schopfheim, Zell, Schönau. The upper Wiesental is a ski area (Belchen, Feldberg).",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-083": "The \"Schlackworscht\" is the air-dried cured sausage, a hearty Palatine butcher's specialty. \"A Stick Schlackworscht uff a frisches Brot, herrlich!\" (A piece of Schlackworscht on fresh bread, wonderful!) Coarse, spicy, and long-lasting — ideal as a snack in the Wengerd (vineyard) or while hiking in the Palatinate Forest. The name comes from the slim, \"dangling\" (schlackernd) shape. Alongside Leberworscht and Blutworscht, it's a fixture at the Palatine sausage counter. With a Schorle and farmhouse bread, it makes a complete snack out in the open.",
  "hessisch.h-123": "Gefillde are Hessian stuffed potato dumplings — potato dough on the outside, meat or bacon filling inside. A traditional Hessian dish, especially widespread in Upper Hesse and the Vogelsberg. Usually served with sauerkraut and brown gravy. Filling, hearty, and typically Hessian — soul food of the Vogelsberg. The grandmothers have the best recipes, which are not divulged.",
  "berlinisch.b-118": "Liebesperlen are small, colorful sugar pearls — a Berlin sweet from the 1950s. They were sold in little paper rolls (\"Liebesperlen-Röllchen\") and are a classic childhood-memory symbol for GDR and West Berliners. Today a retro sweet. \"Liebesperlen\" symbolically stands for Berlin's culture of nibbling and the childhood of the 1970s.",
  "bayerisch.by-103": "The \"Hutschpferd\" is the Bavarian word for a rocking horse — from the verb \"hutschn\" (to rock). It was the classic children's toy on Bavarian farms and is part of childhood folklore. Today often a nostalgic symbol of carefree childhood days. The verb \"hutschn\" is also used generally for \"to rock\" or \"to sway\" — \"a Kind aufm Schoß hutschn\" (to rock a child on one's lap).",
  "saechsisch.s-089": "Pumphut is a legendary trickster and prankster of the Saxon-Lusatian folk legend — a miller's lad with magic powers who punishes unjust millers and helps poor people. His broad-brimmed hat is his trademark. The Pumphut legends have been collected many times and adapted for children's books and animated films. A Robin Hood-like figure of Upper Lusatia, who was especially popular in the GDR. A symbol of righteous mischief.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-091": "The Stocherkahn is the special Tübingen boat ride on the Neckar — a flat wooden boat that is punted (gestochert) through the shallow water with a long wooden pole (as in Cambridge or Venice). Students of the University of Tübingen hold Stocherkahn races. In summer a tourist magnet. A must-do on any visit to Tübingen.",
  "koelsch.k-106": "The Cologne Rose Monday procession is the climax of the carnival season — the largest carnival parade in Germany, with 12,000 participants, 130 themed floats, and 100 marching bands. Over a million spectators line the 6.5 km route. \"Kamelle!\" the children shout — 300 tons of sweets and 700,000 little bouquets of flowers are thrown into the crowd. Live broadcast on WDR. A Cologne high feast.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-094": "The Hanseatic Kontore were fortified trading posts of the Hanseatic League in foreign countries — the Steelyard in London, the Tyske Bryggen in Bergen, the Peterhof in Novgorod. Here the Hanseatic merchants often lived for years. In this way the North German Hanseats dominated Northern European trade from the 12th to the 17th century. The foundation of Hanseatic wealth.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-096": "The Swiss army knife (or \"officer's knife\") is a Swiss product known worldwide — above all the red Victorinox version with the white cross. Invented in 1891 by Karl Elsener for the Swiss army. The classic model has a blade, screwdriver, corkscrew, scissors, and much more in a single tool. A symbol of Swiss precision, versatility, and quality. Present on every Swiss farm, in every scout's backpack.",
  "wienerisch.w-090": "Zwetschgenröster is a Viennese plum compote — Zwetschken (plums) are cooked down with sugar, cinnamon, and sometimes red wine until they have a syrupy consistency. A classic side dish to Kaiserschmarrn, to Topfenknödel, and to Palatschinken. In autumn, when the plums are ripe, Zwetschgenröster is cooked up in stock in many Viennese households and stored in jars for the winter.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-090": "Tilman Riemenschneider (c. 1460–1531) is the most important Franconian sculptor and one of the most significant German artists of all. Born in Heiligenstadt (Thuringia), he worked mainly in Würzburg. His woodcarvings (the Marian altar in Creglingen, the Holy Blood altar in Rothenburg, the Madonna in Volkach) are world art. Also mayor of Würzburg — he was tortured during the Peasants' War.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-097": "\"Knipsen\" in the Ruhr region means to take photos — from \"Knipser\" for a cheap compact camera. Today jokingly used for any smartphone snapper. \"Mach mal n'Foto, knips!\" (Take a photo, snap!) Also used for thoughtless, quick action: \"Der hat's einfach durchgeknipst.\" (He just snapped it through / pushed it through without thinking.) It shows the humorous, light-hearted way the people of the Pott deal with modern technology.",
  "alemannisch.al-094": "The Hotzenwald is a rugged, remote high plateau in the southern Black Forest between the Wehra valley and the High Rhine — home of the \"Hotzen\", a headstrong Alemannic population group. Until the 18th century they had their own folk culture, with the \"Hotzen wars\" against the Habsburgs. Today a quiet, rural region with traditional Hotzen costume and Alemannic dialect. A true hidden Alemannia.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-084": "The \"Hutzel\" is dried fruit, especially the dried pear — wrinkled and sweet. \"Aus de Hutzle koche mer a Hutzelbrei zu Weihnachte.\" (At Christmas we cook a Hutzelbrei from the dried pears.) Figuratively, \"a alde Hutzel\" also means a wizened little old woman. In the Palatine gardens, fruit used to be dried for storage. The \"Hutzelbrot\" or \"Kletzenbrot\" is an old Christmas pastry. A classic word from the rural storage and preserving culture of the region.",
  "hessisch.h-124": "Käseschnitten — a Hessian and North Hessian specialty: slices of bread gratinated with cheese, often with ham, egg, or asparagus. A simple counterpart to Swiss Älplermagronen or French Croque-Monsieur. Especially popular in school canteens and simple restaurants. Hessian comfort food — quick, filling, and tasty.",
  "berlinisch.b-119": "Quark with linseed oil, jacket potatoes, and caraway — that's GDR comfort food, still very much alive in Berlin. A plain but substantial meal from working-class times. The linseed oil gives a nutty flavor, the quark is tangy and fresh. Still to be found in Berlin corner pubs and East German restaurants. A symbol of East German culinary tradition.",
  "bayerisch.by-104": "Markus Söder (b. 1967) has been Minister-President of Bavaria since 2018 and chairman of the CSU since 2019. Known for his adaptability, his love of bratwurst and carnival costumes, as well as his strong media presence. In Bavarian popular speech he is frequently the target of mockery and admiration in equal measure. He has modernized the image of the \"Bavarian father of the state\" and adapted it for the TikTok generation.",
  "saechsisch.s-090": "Lusatia and the Central German Mining Region have for decades been Germany's most important lignite open-cast mining regions — gigantic bucket-wheel excavators extract lignite from open pits. The Welzow-Süd, Nochten, and Reichwalde open-cast mines are active pits. As part of the structural transformation, these mines are to be closed by 2038 — the region faces enormous economic challenges. The former open-cast pits are being flooded into lakes (Lusatian Lake District).",
  "schwaebisch.sw-092": "Filderstadt, south of Stuttgart, is a town of 46,000 inhabitants on the fertile Filder plateau. Famous for the Filderkraut (pointed cabbage) and asparagus cultivation. The Filderhalle is an event center. Stuttgart Airport is also located partly on Filderstadt territory. A commuter town in the Stuttgart commuter belt.",
  "koelsch.k-107": "The Bläck Fööss (Standard German for \"bare feet\") have been Cologne's most famous dialect band since 1970 — founders of modern Cologne carnival music. Their hits like \"Drink doch ene mit\", \"Mer losse d'r Dom in Kölle\" and \"En unserem Veedel\" are part of Cologne's cultural heritage. They sing about simple life, love of home and solidarity. More than 5 million records sold. An institution.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-095": "In Low German, the \"Schipper\" is the boatman or captain of a smaller vessel. \"Schipperhose\" (skipper's trousers) and \"Schipperjacke\" (skipper's jacket) are the traditional attire. Until the 20th century, Schipper was a respected profession in the port towns. Today it is rather rare — container ships need fewer skippers. A romantically idealised image of the trade.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-097": "Bobsleigh has a long tradition in Switzerland — the St. Moritz Olympia Bob Run is the oldest bobsleigh track in the world (1903) and is rebuilt anew from snow and ice every year. The Cresta Run for skeleton is also legendary. Swiss bobsleigh athletes such as Beat Hefti have won Olympic gold several times. Besides the professional athletes, the St. Moritz track is also used by tourists — a wild ride.",
  "wienerisch.w-091": "The Donaukanal is a side arm of the Danube that flows right through Vienna — from the Nußdorf weir to the Danube near Albern. In recent years its banks have become a popular summer hotspot: beach bars like the Tel Aviv Beach, graffiti walls, cycle paths and open-air concerts. The historic Otto Wagner lock at Nußdorf is Art Nouveau architecture. The Donaukanal is Vienna's young, urban open-air living room.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-091": "Veit Stoß (c. 1450–1533) was a famous Nuremberg sculptor and painter. His Altarpiece of the Virgin Mary in St. Mary's Church in Kraków (1477–1489) is regarded as a masterpiece of the late Middle Ages. The Angelic Salutation in Nuremberg's Lorenzkirche is also by him. His life was turbulent — he was branded for forgery. Immortal nonetheless as an artistic genius.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-098": "\"Ne dat\" is the typical Ruhr-area negation — short, terse, direct. \"Ne, dat geht so nich\" (no, that won't work like that) or \"Ne dat is doch Quatsch\" (no, that's nonsense). The word \"ne\" as a negation comes from Low German, and \"dat\" replaces the Standard German \"das\". A classic example of Low German influences merging with Standard German — a hallmark of the Ruhr dialect.",
  "alemannisch.al-098": "For decades the railbus was the means of transport on the many Black Forest branch lines — small, robust diesel railcars for mountainous routes. Colloquially called the \"Roter Brummer\" (red rumbler) or \"Uerdinger Schienenbus\" (after the manufacturer). They combine tradition with history. Historic railbuses still run today on the Sauschwänzlebahn and the Wutachtalbahn — a tourist attraction.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-085": "The \"Babb\" is glue, paste or a sticky mush. \"Mach de Babb ned an dei Hose!\" (don't get the gunk on your trousers!) From the verb \"babbe\" (to stick). Also figuratively: \"des is alles Babb\" for inferior, mushy food. Something \"babbt\" when it is sticky. An onomatopoeic Palatine word that carries its sticky nature directly in its sound. Children often come home covered in Babb. Versatile, from wallpaper paste to soggy mush, vivid and concise in the Palatine manner.",
  "hessisch.h-125": "Hessians are not as dogged about their dialect as Bavarians or Swabians — Hessian is cultivated with self-irony and humour. Volker Bouffier, Roland Koch and many other politicians have spoken Hessian openly. The comedy series \"Bei uns dahem\" and \"Familie Heinz Becker\" (actually Saarlandic, but similar) celebrate the Hessian mentality. Hessians are easygoing speakers — never strained, always laid-back.",
  "berlinisch.b-120": "The \"Hähnchen\" or \"Halbe Hähnchen\" (half a chicken) is a Berlin and East German classic — called \"Goldbroiler\" in the GDR. Crispy roasted half chicken with salt, paprika and garlic. Sold at snack stands and at festivals. The \"Goldbroiler\" is pure GDR nostalgia — to this day a Berlin soul-food classic. Perfect with a bread roll and beer.",
  "bayerisch.by-105": "The \"Christkindlmarkt\" on Munich's Marienplatz is one of the oldest and most beautiful Christmas markets in Germany — first mentioned in 1310 as the \"Nikolaimarkt\". Mulled wine, gingerbread, roasted almonds, nativity figures and pewter-casting stalls — over 160 booths in front of the city hall. The Christ Child appears in person at the opening. The \"Mittelaltermarkt\" on Wittelsbacherplatz and the Schwabing market are also iconic. Bavarian Christmas spirit at its purest.",
  "saechsisch.s-091": "Clara Schumann (née Wieck, 1819–1896) was one of the most important pianists of the 19th century — born in Leipzig, trained as a child prodigy. By the age of 15 she was already a concert star in Vienna and Paris. Her marriage to Robert Schumann was one of the most famous artistic unions in music history. She championed Brahms in his rise. She composed outstanding works herself — songs and piano pieces. Her likeness adorned the last 100-Mark note.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-093": "Bernd Kohlhepp (b. 1961) is one of the most distinguished Swabian cabaret artists of the present day. With his character \"Herr Hämmerle\" and his dialect plays he gently mocks Swabian idiosyncrasies — stinginess, fussiness, club obsession. Actor, cabaret artist and dialect author all in one. A must-see in every town hall of Württemberg.",
  "koelsch.k-108": "The Höhner (chickens) have been one of the most successful Cologne carnival bands since 1972 — with hits like \"Viva Colonia\" (the unofficial carnival anthem), \"Wenn nicht jetzt, wann dann?\" and \"Die Karawane zieht weiter\". Their music blends dialect, rock and pop. The Höhner tour worldwide and regularly perform at major carnival sessions. A Cologne classic.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-096": "\"Sünn-up\" is Low German for sunrise — a poetic word that captures the beauty of morning on the North Sea. When the sun rises over the sea (\"de Sünn over de See up geiht\"), the spectacle is unforgettable. Fishermen and farmers traditionally rise with the Sünn-up to begin their work. The sunrises over the Wadden Sea are world-famous.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-098": "HC Davos is one of the most successful Swiss ice hockey clubs — 31-time Swiss champion. Famous above all for the Spengler Cup, the oldest ice hockey tournament in the world (since 1923), traditionally held between Christmas and New Year in Davos. Swiss and international stars have played at the Vaillant Arena for decades. The Davos atmosphere during the Spengler Cup is legendary. Ice hockey is Switzerland's number two national sport.",
  "wienerisch.w-092": "The Käsekrainer is a Viennese sausage speciality — a scalded sausage made of pork with embedded chunks of cheese. When sliced open, molten cheese oozes out, which leads Viennese to call it \"Eitrige\" (the festering one) or \"Schoaße\" (the black one) — the famous \"sausage-stand slang\". It is served with mustard, Kren (horseradish) and a bread roll. Available at every Viennese sausage stand. A cult product with its own vocabulary.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-092": "Peter Vischer the Elder (c. 1455–1529) was the most famous Nuremberg bronze caster of the Renaissance. His main work: the Shrine of St. Sebald in St. Sebald's Church in Nuremberg — a masterpiece of bronze-casting art with life-size figures of saints and apostles. Vischer inserted himself as a small figure in an apron — the hallmark of his workshop. A Renaissance genius.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-099": "The \"Mantaplatte\" is a humorous Ruhr-area term from the 1980s for the complete order at the chip stand: currywurst, fries and a beer. Named after the Opel Manta — the cult car of the Ruhr macho scene. The Manta driver came from the steelworks and ate his Mantaplatte after his shift. Today used jokingly for the classic snack-bar menu.",
  "alemannisch.al-099": "In the Alemannic-Baden region, \"Kraut\" means sauerkraut — part of almost every traditional dish. Filderkraut, Baden Kraut, Hotzenwald Kraut — every region has its own variety. Cooked with bacon, wine and onions, it is a vitamin C bomb. In winter it is indispensable with Schäufele, bratwurst or roast pork. A culinary tradition spanning centuries.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-086": "The \"Babblwasser\" (chatter water) jokingly refers to wine or alcohol that makes people talkative — from \"babbeln\" (to chatter) and \"Wasser\" (water). \"Noch zwää Schoppe Babblwasser un de Onkel verzählt alles!\" (a couple more glasses of chatter water and uncle will tell everything!) A tongue-in-cheek Palatine term for the sociability-boosting effect of wine. At the regulars' table the Babblwasser loosens tongues and fuels conversation. It reflects the humorous self-awareness of the wine region, where after a few glasses everyone turns into a storyteller.",
  "hessisch.h-127": "The Upper Germanic-Rhaetian Limes is the former border of the Roman Empire — running 550 km through Hesse, Baden-Württemberg and Bavaria. A UNESCO World Heritage Site since 2005. In Hesse lie the Saalburg (a fully reconstructed Roman fort in the Taunus), the Feldberg fort and the well-known Limes hiking trail. Anyone who hikes the Limes gets to know Roman history up close.",
  "berlinisch.b-122": "The Berlinale (Berlin International Film Festival) is one of the most important film festivals in the world — alongside Cannes and Venice. Held annually in February in Berlin. The \"Golden Bear\" and the \"Silver Bear\" are the main prizes. Over 400,000 tickets are sold — the Berlinale is one of the most popular festivals with audiences. Political films are often at the centre, which makes the Berlinale unique.",
  "bayerisch.by-106": "Franz Josef Strauß (1915–1988) was one of the most important and controversial Bavarian politicians — Minister-President, CSU chairman and candidate for chancellor. Known for his coarse rhetoric, his sharp mind and his fondness for beer. Munich Airport bears his name. His \"We are in the 21st century\" cemented Bavarian self-confidence. A polarising figure — to this day a role model or a bogeyman, depending on one's political point of view.",
  "saechsisch.s-092": "The St. Thomas Boys Choir of Leipzig (Thomanerchor) is one of the oldest and most famous boys' choirs in the world — founded in 1212, with more than 800 years of history. Its most famous cantor: Johann Sebastian Bach (1723–1750). Today the choir consists of around 90 \"Thomaner\" (aged 9–18), who are taught at the St. Thomas School. The weekly motets in St. Thomas Church are a highlight of Leipzig's musical life. World tours.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-094": "In Swabian, the \"Vereinsmeier\" is the overzealous club member who regulates everything — typical of the pronounced Swabian club culture. Swabians are organised in sports, choral, music, marksmen's and heritage clubs like no other region. The Vereinsmeier sits on the board, controls everything and takes his office very seriously.",
  "koelsch.k-109": "Brings have been a Cologne rock band since 1991, founded by the Brings brothers. With hits like \"Superjeilezick\", \"Kölsche Jung\" and \"Polka, Polka\", they are a carnival band with rock power. Brings is the bridge between carnival and modern pop. At their concerts a state of emergency prevails — Brings concerts are like little carnival sessions.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-097": "The \"Klönsnack\" is a cosy, relaxed chat — longer and more leisurely than small talk, but shorter than a deep conversation. Over tea and biscuits at the kitchen table, at the garden fence or at the baker's. The Klönsnack is an important social glue in the North. \"Sik to'n Klönsnack tosamenholen\" — to get together for a chat.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-099": "The Sturmgewehr 90 (Stgw 90) has been the standard weapon of the Swiss Army since 1990 — manufactured by SIG Sauer. Every male Swiss soldier takes his rifle home after recruit training and keeps it until he is discharged from his military obligations. This tradition makes Switzerland one of the most heavily armed countries in Europe, without high levels of gun crime. A symbol of Swiss trust in the citizens' militia.",
  "wienerisch.w-093": "The Wienerlied is a genre of music in its own right — usually in waltz time, with Viennese dialect lyrics, often with the Schrammelmusik line-up (two violins, accordion, contraguitar). Its themes are Viennese life, the Heuriger (wine tavern), death, love and \"Schmäh\" (Viennese wit) — always with a mix of melancholy and joie de vivre. Famous performers: Hermann Leopoldi, Karl Hodina, Heinz Holliger, Wolfgang Ambros, Roland Neuwirth. Viennese folk art.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-093": "Walther von der Vogelweide (c. 1170–1230) is the most famous Minnesänger of the German Middle Ages. His origins are disputed — Franconia (the Würzburg region), Tyrol or Bavaria. His grave is said to lie in Würzburg, in the Lusam garden by the cathedral. He wrote about love, politics and religion — a universal medieval poet. Today part of the school curriculum.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-100": "Doppelkopf — \"Doko\" for short — is THE card game of the Ruhr region. Four players, 48 cards, complex rules. Miners played it after their shift at the kiosk (Trinkhalle) or at home. Today Doko regulars' tables keep the tradition alive in every Ruhr town. More than just cards — a social ritual, a bond between generations, everyday poetry. Whoever plays Doko belongs to the Pott.",
  "alemannisch.al-100": "In Alemannic, the \"Schlemmer\" is someone who appreciates good food and drink — a gourmet in the most positive sense. In the Black Forest, the Markgräflerland and on Lake Constance, gourmet culture is deeply rooted: fine spirits, Pinot Noir, game dishes, Black Forest ham, Black Forest gateau. \"Mir simma Schlemmer!\" (we are gourmets!) people say proudly. The Alemannic attitude to life: eat well, drink well, live well.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-087": "A \"Hanswerschd\" is a buffoon, a joker or someone who is not taken seriously. \"Mach ned de Hanswerschd vor de Leut!\" (don't play the fool in front of people!) From \"Hans\" and \"Worscht\" (sausage) — an old figure of folk theatre. Anyone who behaves foolishly is a \"Hanswerschd\". Used affectionately yet chidingly among friends and within the family. A classic term of abuse with a long tradition, coloured in the Palatinate with the typical \"Werschd\" instead of \"Wurst\". It expresses head-shaking more than real anger.",
  "hessisch.h-130": "Heinrich Heine (1797-1856) — actually from Düsseldorf — spent formative years in Frankfurt am Main. He did not meet the young Goethe directly here, but the banking city shaped his view of the bourgeoisie. His \"Loreley\" (1822) is part of world cultural heritage. The Hessians claim him for his involvement with the book fair and the brief Frankfurt episode. Hesse combines banker and bookish culture.",
  "berlinisch.b-123": "Berlin claims that the currywurst was invented there in 1949 by Herta Heuwer. Her original snack stand, \"Imbiss Heuwer\", stood on Stuttgarter Platz. In 2009 the German Currywurst Museum opened in Mitte — about the history and culture of the currywurst. Berliners and Bochumers argue to this day over who has the real currywurst. In Berlin it is part of the cityscape like the Brandenburg Gate.",
  "bayerisch.by-107": "The \"Wadelboatzn\" — also \"Wadlbeißer\" (calf-biter) — was originally, in Bavarian, a small, yapping dog that bites people in the calves. Figuratively the term is used for quarrelsome, aggressive people — usually small, energetic characters who are always looking for trouble. In politics, awkward troublemakers are also called this. Meant affectionately and mockingly, not really insulting.",
  "saechsisch.s-093": "The Dresden Kreuzchor is a world-famous boys' choir with 800 years of history — founded in the 13th century. The Kruzianer (as the choir members are called) are housed in the Kreuzschule and trained in the famous tradition. The Kreuzchor sings regularly in the Kreuzkirche on Dresden's Altmarkt — the largest Protestant church in Saxony. World tours, many recordings. A rival to the Leipzig Thomanerchor — both at the highest level.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-096": "Mönsheim is a municipality of 3,000 inhabitants in the Enzkreis district west of Stuttgart. A classic Swabian wine village in the Heckengäu with a rich medieval heritage. The local wine cooperative and the Mönsheim Storch tower (Storchenturm) are landmarks. Representative of the many small, charming wine villages of the Württemberg wine country.",
  "koelsch.k-110": "The goat \"Hennes\" has been the living mascot of 1. FC Köln since 1950. Today Hennes IX (born 2014) lives at Cologne Zoo and accompanies the team to every home game. The name goes back to the coaching legend Hennes Weisweiler. Hennes is a cult figure — on shirts, fan merchandise and in the club's history. When Hennes enters the stadium, the whole of Müngersdorf cheers.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-098": "Glückstadt on the Elbe was founded in 1617 by the Danish king Christian IV as a rival to Hamburg — the name (meaning \"City of Luck\") was a statement of intent. Today it is a small town of 11,000 inhabitants, but famous for the \"Glückstädter Matjes\" (pickled herring), which rank among the best in Germany. There is an annual Matjes Festival in June.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-101": "The \"Bundesbrief\" (Federal Charter) of 1291 is the founding document of the Swiss Confederation — the charter in which the men of Uri, Schwyz and Unterwalden pledged themselves to an \"eternal alliance.\" Today it is kept in the Federal Charter Museum in Schwyz — National Symbol No. 1. Written on parchment in Latin. Rather pragmatic in content (mutual aid), but symbolic in effect (the Swiss founding myth). Constitutionally disputed, culturally central.",
  "wienerisch.w-094": "The Bosna is a Viennese sausage specialty, originally from Salzburg but very popular in Vienna: two small bratwursts in a long white bread roll with onions, mustard, curry powder and sometimes ketchup. Served with plenty of pepper and a spicy sauce. A midnight snack after long evenings at the tavern. The name \"Bosna\" probably comes from the Bosnian ćevapčići tradition. Fast food with character.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-095": "The Main Valley is the central wine landscape of Franconia — from the Spessart to the Steigerwald. The bends of the Main form characteristic scenery. The best Franconian wines grow here: Würzburger Stein, Volkacher Ratsherr, Iphofener Julius-Echter-Berg. It is also a tourist route, the \"Mainradweg\" (Main cycle path) — from the source near Bayreuth to the confluence in Mainz.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-101": "The Schalker Markt is the heart of the Schalke district in Gelsenkirchen — a historic center with market days, corner pubs and the Schalker Meile. It was here in 1904 that FC Schalke 04 was founded as Westfalia Schalke. Royal-blue history everywhere: Schalke souvenirs, old mining families, everyone knows everyone. An authentic Ruhr neighborhood with identity and pride.",
  "alemannisch.al-101": "The Black Forest house (Schwarzwaldhaus) is one of the best-known farmhouse forms in Germany — a massive timber-and-stone building with a deeply drawn-down hipped roof of straw or wooden shingles that reaches almost to the ground. Living room, stable, threshing floor and barn under one roof — everything in the tightest space, for the harsh mountain climate. There are three main types: the Kinzigtäler, the Gutachtäler and the Heidegger house. The Vogtsbauernhof open-air museum in Gutach displays several original buildings.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-088": "The \"Bornkippel\" or \"Born\" is a spring or well in the Palatinate Forest where hikers find fresh water. \"Am Bornkippel mache mer Rascht un fille die Flasch\" (\"At the Bornkippel we take a rest and fill our bottles\"). From \"Born\" (well, cf. the German \"Quell-Born\") and \"Kippel\" (a small rise). The numerous wells and springs in the forest are popular hiking destinations and meeting points. Anyone who roams the Palatinate Forest knows its Born spots. A classic word from the hiking and nature culture of the region.",
  "hessisch.h-131": "Friedrich Stoltze (1816–1891) was Frankfurt's most famous dialect poet — his Hessian wit and his feel for local color made him a Frankfurt legend. His work \"Die Frankfurter Bibel\" parodies the Bible in Hessian. The Stoltze Foundation preserves his legacy. To this day, lovers of all things Hessian gather at his grave in Frankfurt's main cemetery. Stoltze's sayings are everywhere in Frankfurt.",
  "berlinisch.b-124": "\"Pommes mit allem\" (\"fries with everything\") is the Berlin order at the snack stand: fries with curry sauce and ketchup, sometimes also with mayo. Unlike the Ruhr region (Pommes Schranke), Berlin has its own fries culture. \"Curry mit Pommes Schranke\" comes with half mayo, half ketchup. The fries-mayo-ketchup combo is a Berlin essential.",
  "bayerisch.by-108": "Bad Aibling in the district of Rosenheim is a Bavarian spa town, world-famous thanks to the ZDF series \"Die Rosenheim-Cops\" and the comedy \"Aibling Cops.\" Famous for its mud baths and the nearby Federal Intelligence Service (BND) listening station. It lies picturesquely in the Bavarian foothills of the Alps. The very embodiment of the small Bavarian town idyll, which has achieved cult status through crime series.",
  "saechsisch.s-094": "The Dresden Striezelmarkt is Germany's oldest Christmas market — first mentioned in 1434. It takes place every year during Advent on the Altmarkt in Dresden. The name comes from the \"Striezel,\" a forerunner of today's Stollen. At the annual Stollenfest, a giant Christmas Stollen is paraded through the city and sold. Smoking-man figures, pyramids, gingerbread, mulled wine — the Striezelmarkt is the Saxon Advent in its purest form. Over 2 million visitors a year.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-097": "In Swabian, the \"Hocker\" (stool) is far more than just a simple piece of seating furniture — it is a way of life. From the kitchen stool at snack time, to the workshop stool while tinkering, to the garden stool during a break from the Kehrwoche (cleaning duty). Pragmatic, sturdy, not tall — the stool stands for Swabian plainness and functionality. Often kept in the family for decades.",
  "koelsch.k-111": "1. FC Köln — the \"Effzeh\" — was founded in 1948 and is Cologne's traditional club. Players like Lukas Podolski grew up here. The club colors are red and white. Home stadium: the RheinEnergieStadion in Cologne-Müngersdorf. Club anthem: \"Mer stonn zo dir, FC Kölle\" — sung by the Höhner. The identification of Cologne's people with their club is legendary. \"Spielt der FC, schließt die Stadt!\" (\"When the FC plays, the city shuts down!\").",
  "plattdeutsch.p-099": "The Schnoor is Bremen's oldest quarter — a tangled maze of alleys from the 15th and 16th centuries. The name comes from the ropes (\"Schnüren\") that were once made here. Today it is a tourist magnet with galleries, small shops and cafés. One of the best-preserved medieval old towns in northern Germany.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-102": "The \"Steinstossen\" is a traditional Swiss sporting discipline: the \"Unspunnenstein\" (83.5 kg) is thrown as far as possible. It has been a discipline at the federal Älplerfest in Unspunnen (Bernese Oberland) since 1805. The record stands at over 4 meters. The original stone has been stolen several times — most recently in 2005 by Basque separatists. A symbol of archaic Swiss tests of strength. More tradition than sport.",
  "wienerisch.w-095": "The Burenwurst is a traditional Viennese sausage specialty — a coarse parboiled sausage made of pork and bacon, smoked and scalded. A classic at the Viennese sausage stand: Burenwurst with mustard, Kren (horseradish) and a bread roll. The sausage is often served warmed up in hot water or broth. A hearty, savory sausage — no frills, just good. The name \"Buren\" has nothing to do with South Africa.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-096": "Marktheidenfeld on the Main, with 11,000 inhabitants, lies in the Main triangle. It is known for Warema (an awning manufacturer and world market leader) and Bürkert (measurement and control technology). It has a beautiful medieval old town with a historic bridge over the Main. Located in the western Spessart, it is a classic Lower Franconian medium-sized town idyll. Economically surprisingly strong for its size.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-102": "The Borsigplatz in Dortmund's north is the birthplace of Borussia Dortmund — founded in 1909 in the pub \"Zum Wildschütz.\" To this day it is a place of pilgrimage: after every championship title, BVB drives across the square in a convertible. A working-class neighborhood with a history of migration, shaped by the former Borsig locomotive factory. Black-and-yellow murals adorn the houses. Hallowed ground.",
  "alemannisch.al-102": "The witch is a central figure in Alemannic legends — mysterious women with knowledge of nature, standing between healing and harmful magic. In the Black Forest and on the Swabian Alb there are hundreds of witch legends. Walpurgis Night (April 30) and the witch fire to drive away evil spirits are ancient customs. In the Fasnet (carnival), witch figures appear — wooden masks with a long nose, a brushwood broom and a black cloak.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-089": "The \"Gequängel\" is constant whining, grumbling or nagging, usually from children. \"Hör uff mit dem Gequängel, mir gehe gleich!\" (\"Stop whining, we're leaving in a minute!\"). From the verb \"quängele\" (to whine). Parents know the Gequängel at the supermarket or before bedtime all too well. Adults can \"rumquängele\" too. An onomatopoeic word that nicely captures the maddening persistence. It belongs to the everyday family vocabulary of the Palatinate and is used half exasperated, half indulgent.",
  "hessisch.h-132": "\"Battonn\" refers to the Frankfurt district of Bornheim and its inhabitants — a Viennese-sounding diminutive form with an \"-onn\" ending. It is also an affectionate term for someone from Frankfurt-Bornheim. \"En echte Battonn\" is someone with a genuine Bornheim mentality — humorous, rough around the edges, warm-hearted. The term is rarely used today — insider knowledge for true Frankfurt originals.",
  "berlinisch.b-125": "The Lange Nacht der Museen (Long Night of Museums) is a Berlin event that has run since 1997 — twice a year, more than 80 museums open their doors late into the night. A combined ticket grants admission to all the venues and free use of shuttle buses. Thousands of Berliners and tourists move from museum to museum. Berlin has the second-highest density of museums in Europe — and makes them accessible.",
  "bayerisch.by-109": "The \"Fluchtbier\" (\"escape beer\") is a Bavarian tavern tradition: the last beer, quickly downed before leaving — often secretly, before facing the wife at home or before closing time. It dates from the era when women did not come to the tavern and men had to quickly have one more before heading home. Today it is used jokingly for any hastily drunk beer. A cultural testament to the Bavarian tavern mentality.",
  "saechsisch.s-095": "Meissen on the Elbe is the oldest town in Saxony and home of the famous Meissen porcelain — Europe's oldest porcelain manufactory (founded in 1710 under Augustus the Strong). The crossed blue swords are its trademark. In Albrechtsburg, the oldest castle in Germany, the secret of porcelain was developed by Johann Friedrich Böttger. Today Meissen is a candidate for UNESCO World Heritage status. Meissen wine has also been grown here since the 12th century.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-098": "Ehinger are the inhabitants of Ehingen (on the Danube), a town of 26,000 inhabitants near Ulm. Ehingen is a \"city of beer culture,\" with five breweries in a small area — the highest density of breweries in southern Germany. It is also home to Liebherr's truck-mounted concrete pumps. A typical Swabian medium-sized town with tradition, economic strength and down-to-earth character.",
  "koelsch.k-112": "Bonn — south of Cologne on the Rhine — was the federal capital of West Germany from 1949 to 1990. Today it is a university city of 330,000 inhabitants, a UN location and the seat of many federal agencies (the Federal Court of Audit, the BfArM). Beethoven was born here in 1770. The Beethoven House is a place of pilgrimage. Bonn is more refined and quieter than Cologne — the two Rhine cities complement each other.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-100": "The Buddelschiff — a model ship inside a glass bottle — is a North German seafarer's craft. On long sea voyages, sailors built small ships and placed them in bottles whose necks seem far too narrow. The masts are inserted lying flat and then raised upright — the secret of the ship-in-a-bottle maker. Popular souvenirs from North German port cities.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-103": "The \"Saaserwii\" — also called \"Heida\" or \"Païen\" — is an old Valais white wine grape variety that grows in Europe's highest-altitude vineyards (Visperterminen, up to 1,150 m). Dry, mineral, with complex aromatics. One of the oldest grape varieties in Europe — possibly introduced by the Romans. Valais is Switzerland's number 1 wine canton, with specialties like Heida, Cornalin and Humagne. Genuine Swiss wine tradition.",
  "wienerisch.w-097": "The \"Cafetier\" (French for the owner of a coffeehouse) is a figure all of his own in Viennese culture — host, psychologist, guardian of manners and head of the family all in one. The Cafetiers of traditional Viennese coffeehouses like the Hawelka, the Central or the Sperl became legends in their own right. They knew their guests, knew everything about what was happening in Vienna and shaped the atmosphere. Today they are an almost dying breed.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-098": "The town of Coburg is the historic residence town of the Dukes of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha. The Veste Coburg, the \"Franconian Crown,\" is one of the mightiest castles in Germany — Martin Luther spent half a year here in 1530 during the Diet of Augsburg. Through the Coburg line, high nobility spread across Europe — Prince Albert married Victoria. Famous: the Coburg bratwurst.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-103": "The Westfalenpark in Dortmund, at 70 hectares, is one of the largest inner-city parks in Europe — laid out in 1959 for the Federal Garden Show. Its landmark is the 209-meter-high Florian Tower with a revolving restaurant and observation deck. There is a rosarium with 3,000 species of roses, a lakeside stage, summer concerts and a festival of lights. Local recreation for the people of Dortmund — walks, picnics, family outings. A green oasis in the middle of the Ruhr.",
  "alemannisch.al-103": "The \"Wilde Jagd\" (Wild Hunt) is an Alemannic legend — a ghostly procession of riders that sweeps across the Black Forest and the High Rhine at night. It is led by \"Wuetes\" or \"Wuetesher\" (a precursor of Wotan). Anyone who encounters it is said to suffer misfortune or be struck dumb. It appears especially during the Rauhnächte (the nights between Christmas and Epiphany). The legend is widespread throughout the Alemannic region — from the Black Forest to Alsace and Vorarlberg.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-090": "A \"Schlawwes\" is an easy-going, somewhat crafty but likeable fellow — a rascal. \"Da Schlawwes hot widder a Auge uff a Maad geworfe\" (\"That rascal has set his eye on a girl again\"). Used affectionately and mockingly for someone who lives life on his own terms and doesn't take things too seriously. Related to \"Schlawiner.\" Among men it is often used almost approvingly. It belongs to the colorful Palatine study of human nature, which has a fitting word for every character. A Schlawwes is never really bad, just a bit sly and charming.",
  "hessisch.h-134": "Heinz Schenk (1924–2014) was one of the best-known Hessian folk actors — the TV show \"Zum Blauen Bock\" (1957–1987) made him known to an audience of millions. \"Et hat noch immer gut gegange\" (\"It has always turned out fine\") was his catchphrase. With a ribbed wine glass (Gerippte) in hand, he embodied the Hessian way of life. To this day he remains an icon of remembrance for older Hessians.",
  "berlinisch.b-126": "The Pergamon Museum on Museum Island displays monumental structures of antiquity: the Pergamon Altar, the Ishtar Gate from Babylon and the Market Gate of Miletus. Opened in 1930, it is one of the most visited museums in Germany. It is currently partly closed for renovation (until 2027/30). On Museum Island (a UNESCO World Heritage Site) stand also the Alte Nationalgalerie, the Bode Museum, the Neues Museum and the Altes Museum.",
  "bayerisch.by-110": "The \"Kraxn\" was originally a wooden back-carrying frame with which Bavarian farmers and alpine herdsmen transported loads. By extension, \"Kraxn\" also denotes an old, rickety car (\"mit der oidn Kraxn fahr i nimma!\" — \"I'm not driving that old jalopy anymore!\") or a shabby contraption. \"Aufkraxln\" still means \"to climb up the mountain\" today. A lively term, somewhere between tradition and modern mockery.",
  "saechsisch.s-096": "Pulsnitz gingerbread (Pulsnitzer Pfefferkuchen) from the town of Pulsnitz (between Bautzen and Dresden) is documented since 1558 — the oldest gingerbread tradition in Germany. Eight gingerbread bakers still practice the craft in Pulsnitz today. It has held an EU protected geographical indication since 2010. Classic varieties: glazed gingerbread, chocolate gingerbread, jam gingerbread, Spitzkuchen. Indispensable at Advent. The annual gingerbread festival in Pulsnitz draws thousands.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-099": "In Swabian, the \"Bauer\" (farmer) is more than just someone who works the land — he is a symbol of down-to-earth solidity, hard work and rootedness across generations. Swabian farms are often kept in family hands for centuries. \"Bauernschlau\" (farmer-shrewd) is a Swabian virtue: pragmatic cleverness without academic theatrics. It is also a surname in many Swabian families.",
  "koelsch.k-113": "The rivalry between Cologne and Düsseldorf is legendary — Kölsch (Cologne) vs. Alt (Düsseldorf), 1. FC Köln vs. Fortuna Düsseldorf, carnival vs. the Altstadt. Both cities are on the Rhine, 40 km apart, but culturally like sworn enemies. People from Cologne and Düsseldorf trade jabs almost as a sport. \"Tölzer\" is the Cologne term for someone from Düsseldorf — meant as a harsh insult.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-101": "Otto Waalkes (born 1948 in Emden) is the most famous East Frisian comedian — known for his Ottifanten (cartoon elephants), his films (\"Otto — Der Film\") and his unmistakable East Frisian humor. He made the East Frisian joke socially acceptable and taught a whole generation to laugh at East Frisians — and with them. He lives in Hamburg today. A symbol of North German self-irony and joie de vivre. Otto is a cult figure.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-104": "Saas-Fee in the Saas Valley (Valais) is the \"Pearl of the Alps\" — a car-free village at 1,800 m, surrounded by 13 four-thousand-metre peaks. Famous for year-round glacier skiing, the world's highest revolving restaurant (Allalin, 3500 m) and its mountaineering tradition. Unlike fashionable Zermatt, it is more familial and closer to nature — a \"genuine\" Valais village with old stone huts and dry-stone walls. An insider tip among skiers and mountain lovers.",
  "wienerisch.w-099": "Adolf Loos (1870–1933) was one of the most influential Viennese architects and pioneers of modern architecture. His famous essay \"Ornament and Crime\" (1908) condemned decoration as a regression — a revolutionary thesis. His buildings, such as the Looshaus on Michaelerplatz (which Emperor Franz Joseph hated as the \"house without eyebrows\") and the American Bar, are milestones in architectural history. Viennese modernism at its purest.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-099": "Federweißer is the still-fermenting, young wine of autumn — slightly sweet, lightly sparkling, low in alcohol. In Franconia it is served with onion tart as a seasonal speciality from September to October. \"Federweißer season\" is a social event — families and friends gather at the winemaker's. Beware: the wine keeps fermenting in your stomach! Drink it casually, or you'll get a stomach ache.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-104": "The Phoenix-See in Dortmund-Hörde is a 24-hectare artificial lake flooded in 2010 on the site of the former Hoesch Phoenix-Ost steelworks. An exemplary case of structural change: where blast furnaces once smoked, boats now sail. A circular path, restaurants and an upmarket residential quarter. Some Ruhr locals see the lake as a betrayal of their industrial heritage — others as a sign of hope.",
  "alemannisch.al-104": "The capercaillie is Europe's largest grouse and is threatened with extinction in the Black Forest — only about 200 individuals remain in the higher reaches of the Black Forest. Its courtship dance in spring is a natural spectacle. An emblem of the Black Forest, it appears in the coats of arms of many municipalities. Conservation projects are trying to stabilise the population. Anyone who sees a capercaillie in the wild is among the lucky few.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-091": "The \"Riwwelkuche\" is the classic Palatine crumble cake — a fluffy yeast dough densely covered with butter-and-sugar crumbles (\"Riwwele\"). \"On Sundays there's Riwwelkuche with coffee, as always.\" The Sunday pastry par excellence, baked at home in every Palatine family. While the \"Riwwele\" are the crumbles themselves, the Riwwelkuche is the whole creation. Enjoyed with a glass of wine or a coffee, often so large that half a baking tray is enough. The epitome of the cosy Palatine coffee table.",
  "hessisch.h-135": "The TV comedy series \"Bei uns dahem\" (HR) portrays Hessian family life in a caricatured yet realistic way — generational conflicts, apple-wine culture and everyday Frankfurt life. With Hessian dialect and a wink of the eye. A cult favourite among Hessians, less known beyond. Such dialect comedies are a hallmark of Hessian TV culture — the HR produces them with loving care.",
  "berlinisch.b-127": "Friedrichstraße runs 3.5 km through Berlin-Mitte — from Friedrichstraße station to Mehringplatz. One of Berlin's most historic streets, home to Galeries Lafayette, the Friedrichstadt-Palast (Europe's largest revue stage) and the former Checkpoint Charlie. An elegant shopping and business avenue that became one of Berlin's lifelines again after reunification.",
  "bayerisch.by-111": "The \"Russ\" is a Bavarian mixed beer drink: wheat beer topped up half-and-half with lemon soda. Invented in Munich in the early 20th century. Similar to the Radler, but with wheat beer instead of lager. Popular in summer, as it tastes lighter and sweeter than pure wheat beer. \"A Russ, bittschön!\" is a standard order in every Bavarian beer garden on hot days. A classic of Bavarian drinking culture.",
  "saechsisch.s-097": "\"Görliwood\" is the ironic nickname for Görlitz because of its popularity as a film set. Films such as \"The Grand Budapest Hotel\" (Wes Anderson), \"Inglourious Basterds\" (Tarantino), \"The Reader\" (with Kate Winslet) and \"Around the World in 80 Days\" were shot in Görlitz. The perfectly preserved old town, with over 4,000 listed buildings — Gothic, Renaissance, Baroque, Art Nouveau — offers every architectural era. Film crews love the city for its authenticity.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-100": "The Swabian \"Tüftler\" is the inventor type who toils tirelessly in the garage or workshop on solutions. Gottlieb Daimler, Robert Bosch, Ferdinand Porsche — all tinkerers. The Swabian tinkering tradition has made the region a stronghold of German engineering. \"Tüftler spirit\" is the Swabian blend of persistence, precision and pragmatism.",
  "koelsch.k-117": "The Rheinauhafen is a modern district in the south of Cologne's old town — on the site of a former industrial harbour. The striking \"Kranhäuser\" (three crane-shaped high-rises) are its landmark. With a chocolate museum, a sports museum and many restaurants. An office location by day, a nightlife strip by evening. A symbol of Cologne's structural change — from an industrial to a creative hub.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-102": "Theodor Storm (1817–1888), born in Husum (North Frisia), was the most important North German lyric poet and storyteller. His most famous text: \"The Rider on the White Horse\" — a novella about the power of water and the forces of nature. Poems such as \"The Town\" (\"By the grey shore, by the grey sea\") also shaped the North German self-image. Husum bears the epithet \"the grey town by the sea\". North German literature of world rank.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-105": "The \"Sackmesser\" is the famous Swiss pocket knife — the epitome of Swiss engineering and pragmatism. Mainly made by Victorinox (Ibach, Schwyz) since 1884. The classic officer's pocket knife has a blade, screwdriver, can opener, corkscrew and more. Used by the Swiss army, NASA and worldwide as a status symbol. The red-and-white cross is the Swiss trademark par excellence.",
  "wienerisch.w-100": "The Vienna Giant Ferris Wheel in the Prater is Vienna's landmark par excellence — built in 1897 by Walter Bassett to mark the 50th jubilee of Emperor Franz Joseph I's accession. At 64.75 m high, it was once one of the largest Ferris wheels in the world — today a tourist magnet and film backdrop. Made famous by the Orson Welles film \"The Third Man\" (1949). A ride lasts 12 minutes and offers a 360° view over Vienna — a must on any visit to Vienna.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-100": "The \"Kärwa-Buam\" (or \"Kärwabuam\") are the unmarried young men of a Franconian village who organise the church fair — putting up the beer tent, digging out the Kärwabaum (maypole), arranging the dance and keeping the tradition alive. An honourable task passed down through the generations. With their Kärwa-Heiß they get the girls dancing. Genuine Franconian folk culture, still alive in many villages today.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-105": "The Ruhr Carnival is a variety of its own — more down-to-earth and less pompous than Cologne's. Instead of carnival princesses and guard dancers, there are club festivities, carnival sessions in multipurpose halls and earthy comic speeches about toil and politics. The Bochum and Recklinghausen carnival societies keep the tradition alive. In the Ruhr you drink beer, not Kölsch — and laugh at yourself.",
  "alemannisch.al-105": "The lynx is slowly returning to the Black Forest — after being wiped out there at the beginning of the 20th century. Since the 1980s, individual animals have been migrating in from Switzerland and the Vosges. Europe's largest wild cat, a shy loner. Sightings are rare and are reported. Conservation projects encourage its return. The lynx as a symbol of an intact Black Forest wilderness.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-092": "\"Bsuff\" means drunk, plastered — after too long an evening with Schorle. \"Der war geschtern owend ganz schee bsuff!\" (\"He was pretty plastered last night!\") Contracted from \"besoffen\". In a wine region, quite a common state, usually commented on with an indulgent grin. Intensified: \"voll bsuff\" or \"bsuff wie a Haubitz\" (\"drunk as a howitzer\"). Part of the sociable vocabulary surrounding wine and wine festivals. Whoever has peered too deep into the Dubbeglas is simply bsuff — and \"hungover\" the next day.",
  "hessisch.h-136": "The Battenbergs were a Hessian noble family that later married into the British royal house — becoming the Mountbattens. Prince Philip, husband of Queen Elizabeth II, belonged to this family. The Hessian noble line thus left its mark on the British monarchy. A little-known Hessian-British story, which can be explored at Heiligenberg Palace in Seeheim-Jugenheim.",
  "berlinisch.b-128": "Unter den Linden is Berlin's historic grand boulevard — from the Brandenburg Gate to the Spree (1.5 km). Here stand the Humboldt University, the German Historical Museum (Zeughaus), Berlin Cathedral and the State Opera. The lime trees down the middle gave the street its name. On postcards and in films, \"Unter den Linden\" is synonymous with the classic Berlin of the Weimar era.",
  "bayerisch.by-112": "The \"Drachenstich\" (\"dragon slaying\") in Furth im Wald (Upper Palatinate) is the oldest German folk play, first mentioned in 1590. Every August the legend of Saint George slaying the dragon is performed. The mechanical dragon is 15.5 m long, weighs 11 tonnes — the largest four-legged robot in the world. Hundreds of extras in medieval costumes. Bavarian folk culture and a tourist spectacle in one.",
  "saechsisch.s-098": "In some Saxon folk legends the \"Sandgreafen\" appear — mysterious beings said to dwell in the sandy soil of Lusatia and Upper Lusatia. They dig invisible tunnels and sometimes embody loss and transience. These regional legendary figures are less known than Pumphut, but belong to the rich treasury of Saxon-Lusatian mythology. Today they are cultivated in folklore studies and revived in regional children's books.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-101": "\"Schaffe, schaffe, Häusle baue\" (\"Work, work, build a little house\") — the famous Swabian life motto. The verb \"schaffe\" stands for the Swabian work ethic: industrious, conscientious, thrifty. Swabians see work as identity and virtue, not as a burden. \"Net schaffe is g'fährlich\" — idleness is dangerous. This mentality has made Baden-Württemberg the richest German federal state. Cliché and reality in one.",
  "koelsch.k-118": "The Chocolate Museum in the Rheinauhafen is one of Cologne's most popular museums — founded in 1993 by chocolate manufacturer Hans Imhoff. With a 3 m high chocolate fountain, live production and a historical collection. Over 600,000 visitors a year. In the foyer stands a true-to-life 3.5-tonne chocolate tropical tree. A sweet place of pilgrimage for chocolate lovers.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-103": "Lübeck marzipan is a protected speciality made of almonds, sugar and rosewater — produced in Lübeck since the 15th century. Niederegger is the most famous brand (since 1806). At Café Niederegger in Lübeck, marzipan comes in every shape: little pigs, loaves, roses, Holsten Gates. An almond content of at least 70 percent — that is what makes the quality. North German world heritage of the confectioner's art.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-106": "\"Bündnerfleisch\" is a speciality from Graubünden — air-dried beef, thinly sliced and seasoned with mountain herbs. The cold mountain air of the Engadine gives it its unmistakable flavour. Served on a wooden board, classically with bread and cornichons. The Swiss answer to Italian bresaola — but heartier and more savoury. A speciality classic of the Swiss apéro.",
  "wienerisch.w-101": "The \"Konditorei\" (patisserie) is almost a sanctuary in Vienna — places like Demel, Sluka, Aida, Heiner and Gerstner are UNESCO-worthy institutions. The imperial court confectioners supplied emperor and nobility — the imperial-and-royal tradition of sweet seduction lives on. Sacher tortes, Dobos tortes, Esterházy, Punschkrapfen, poppyseed strudel. The Viennese patisserie is a cultural treasure — like the coffee house, a whole life philosophy of slowing down.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-101": "Müller-Thurgau is one of the most widely planted white wine grape varieties in Franconia — bred in 1882 by the Swiss Hermann Müller from the Thurgau. Light, floral, low in acidity, early-ripening. Perfect for the Franconian drinking occasion: with Schäuferla, with a cold supper, with a snack. It thrives wonderfully on the loess soils of the Main Valley. In the QbA class a reliable everyday wine, in higher qualities surprisingly elegant.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-106": "The \"Büdchenkönig\" (\"kiosk king\") is the personality behind the counter of a Trinkhalle — usually rooted in the neighbourhood for decades, knowing every regular, every bit of gossip, every heartache. He sells not only beer and lottery tickets, but listens, mediates and dispenses words of wisdom. A neighbourhood original who is often more personal than any therapist. The Trinkhalle as a second home.",
  "alemannisch.al-106": "The European wildcat lives hidden in the Black Forest woodlands — not a feral domestic cat, but a species in its own right. Larger and stockier than house cats, with a bushy tail. After a long absence it is returning, especially to the Southern Black Forest Nature Park. Wildlife biologists rejoice at every confirmed record. A symbol of the recovery of the Black Forest wilderness.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-093": "The \"Maad\" is a girl or young woman, and in former times also the maid on a farm. \"Die Maad vum Winzer is a fleißigs Ding.\" (\"The winemaker's girl is a hard worker.\") Plural \"Määd\" or \"Mädle\". Related to the standard German \"Magd\" and \"Maid\". A \"Pälzer Maad\" is proverbially rosy-cheeked and full of life. A classic word for young women in the rural Palatinate. Used quite naturally and without any disparagement, unlike how the standard German \"Magd\" sounds today.",
  "hessisch.h-137": "The Lahn is a 246 km long river that flows through Central Hesse — from Marburg via Wetzlar to Limburg and on into Rhineland-Palatinate. The Lahn is a popular canoeing and hiking region. The town of Marburg lies picturesquely on the Lahn. The Lahn meadows, with the famous Fritzlar region, also shape Hesse's natural landscape. The Lahn is Hesse's water heritage.",
  "berlinisch.b-129": "The Charité is Europe's largest university hospital — in Berlin-Mitte, with over 3,000 beds and 17,000 staff. Founded in 1710 as a plague hospital. Famous physicians: Robert Koch, Rudolf Virchow, Christian Drosten (coronavirus). Several Nobel laureates. Dramatised in the ZDF series \"Charité\". A landmark of German top-tier medicine and a symbol of Berlin science.",
  "bayerisch.by-113": "The \"Spotzl\" or \"Spatzl\" is a Bavarian term of endearment, derived from the sparrow — a small, lively bird. It is used above all for women, girls or children as an affectionate name. \"Mei Spotzl\" is a loving form of address between partners. In the tavern, too, you can hear older waitresses say \"Was wuist denn, Spatzl?\" (\"What would you like, dear?\") to younger guests. Pure warmth and familiarity.",
  "saechsisch.s-099": "Pillnitz Palace on the Elbe, east of Dresden, was the summer palace of the Saxon electors and kings — built in the 1720s. A unique blend of Chinese-inspired architecture (chinoiserie) and Baroque splendour. Situated right on the banks of the Elbe, with a large palace park. The palace houses the Museum of Decorative Arts. The Bergpalais, the Wasserpalais and the Neues Palais form an ensemble. The famous 230-year-old camellia blooms every spring.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-102": "\"Linsa mit Spätzla ond Saitawürschtle\" (lentils with Spätzle and Saitenwürstchen) is THE Swabian national dish. Classic home cooking: lentil soup with homemade Spätzle and Vienna sausages (\"Saitenwürstchen\"). Refined with a dash of vinegar. Found in every Swabian tavern. Filling, cheap, traditional — everything the Swabian loves. The phrase \"Linsa mit Spätzla\" is more than a dish — it is identity.",
  "koelsch.k-119": "\"Kölner Lichter\" (\"Cologne Lights\") is Cologne's biggest fireworks event — held every July on the banks of the Rhine. Up to 800,000 spectators line the riverbanks. Ships sail up the Rhine in an illuminated convoy, followed by a 35-minute synchronised firework display. Top-class pyrotechnics. The high-rises by the harbour glow in colour. A magical spectacle — many people from Cologne picnic on the banks of the Rhine.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-104": "The \"Reetdach\" — thatched with reed (Reet) — is the typical roofing of North German farmhouses, especially on the North Sea and Baltic coasts. It lasts 50–100 years, is breathable and naturally insulating. The thatchers (\"Dackdecker\") are highly esteemed craftsmen. On Sylt, Föhr and Rügen in particular, thatched houses shape the landscape. Romantic, expensive and a status symbol. A craft worthy of UNESCO recognition.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-107": "The \"Käsewähe\" is the Swiss answer to the French quiche — a flat tart of shortcrust pastry, filled with cheese, an egg mixture and cream. Especially popular in Aargau, Solothurn and Basel. It is served in various variations: \"Zibelewähe\" (onion), \"Chrutwähe\" (chard), \"Speckwähe\" (bacon). Available fresh at the baker's. A Swiss spring classic, often for a light supper. A pure cheese-indulgence experience from the Swiss cheese country.",
  "wienerisch.w-102": "The Hotel Sacher across from the State Opera is Vienna's most distinguished traditional hotel and home of the \"Original Sacher-Torte.\" In 1832 the 16-year-old apprentice Franz Sacher invented the famous chocolate cake with apricot jam for Prince Metternich. A decades-long legal dispute with Demel over the original was settled in 1963. A Sachertorte with whipped cream at the Café Sacher is a must-do in Vienna.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-102": "Bacchus is a white wine grape variety especially widespread in Franconia — bred in 1933 at Geilweilerhof from Silvaner, Riesling and Müller-Thurgau. Very aromatic with notes of elderberry, muscat and exotic fruits. Often used as a blending partner or made into a typical \"Heuriger wine\" alongside Federweißer. Despite its aromatics it remains dry and elegant. A Franconian specialty, hardly found outside Franconia.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-107": "The Eckkneipe is the classic Ruhr-region pub on the street corner — a small, often smoky tavern with a regulars' table, a bar counter, a dartboard and always the same landlord. People meet here after their shift, listen to Schlager music and argue about BVB and Schalke. With every Eckkneipe closure, a piece of Ruhr culture dies. The few that remain are at once museum and social space.",
  "alemannisch.al-107": "The Hohlbeil is a traditional Alemannic woodworking tool — a special axe with a semicircular blade for hollowing out troughs, basins and wooden bowls. Black Forest carvers and wheelwrights used it for centuries. Today only a few craftsmen keep the tradition alive. Old Hohlbeil axes are on display at the Black Forest costume and local history museum in Haslach. A symbol of the woodworking culture of the Alemannic region.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-094": "The \"Buwe\" are the boys or lads — singular \"Bu\" or \"Bub.\" \"Die Buwe spiele Fußball uff em Sportplatz\" (The boys are playing football on the sports field). The proverbial \"Pälzer Buwe\" are sturdy, fun-loving and stand for the down-to-earth youth of the region. Related to the southern German \"Bub.\" Also immortalized in songs and sayings (\"Pälzer Buwe, Pälzer Woi\"). A classic word for young men that nicely captures the warm, somewhat rough-hewn character of Palatine youth.",
  "hessisch.h-138": "Frankfurt Central Station, with over 500,000 passengers daily, is Germany's second-largest station (after Munich). Opened in 1888, with three huge hall roofs. An important hub for ICE trains, regional trains and commuter rail. Connection to Frankfurt Airport in 11 minutes. In front of the station lies the Bahnhofsviertel with its red-light district and drug scene — the notorious \"Frankfurt Bahnhofsviertel.\"",
  "berlinisch.b-130": "The Olympiastadion in Charlottenburg was built in 1936 for the Summer Olympic Games — architect Werner March. With 74,000 seats. Today it is the home ground of Hertha BSC and the venue for the DFB-Pokal final. The 2006 World Cup final was held here. Architecturally very impressive, historically burdened (a Nazi-era building). One of Germany's most famous stadiums.",
  "bayerisch.by-114": "The \"Schuachplattler\" is a traditional Bavarian-Tyrolean folk dance in which men in lederhosen rhythmically slap their shoes, knees and thighs. It dates from the 19th century but is rooted in old courtship rituals. Today it is kept alive by traditional-costume clubs and is part of every proper Bavarian festival. \"A guter Plattler\" masters over 100 different slaps — a genuine art form.",
  "saechsisch.s-100": "The Monument to the Battle of the Nations in Leipzig commemorates the Battle of Leipzig of 1813 — the largest battle of the Napoleonic Wars, in which an alliance of Prussia, Russia, Austria and Sweden decisively defeated Napoleon. Over 600,000 soldiers fought, 100,000 died. The 91-metre-high monument was inaugurated in 1913 on the 100th anniversary — one of the largest monuments in Europe. A symbol of German-national pathos of the Wilhelmine era. Today a tourist attraction and memorial.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-103": "The \"Maultaschenstreit\" is the Swabian debate over the origin of Maultaschen. One legend: in the 17th century, the monks of Maulbronn invented the \"Herrgottsbescheißerle\" in order to secretly eat meat during Lent — by hiding it in dough they \"deceive\" the Lord. Tübingen also claims the invention. Today \"Schwäbische Maultaschen\" is a protected geographical indication. Swabian local pride par excellence.",
  "koelsch.k-120": "Müngersdorf is a western district of Cologne — known for the RheinEnergieStadion (FC Köln) and the Müngersdorfer Stadtwald (Cologne's \"green lung\"). The Müngersdorfer Heide is a popular local recreation area. On FC home-game days there's a carnival atmosphere here. Otherwise it's a rather quiet, middle-class residential area with lots of greenery. A classic western Cologne district.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-106": "\"Bützen\" in northern German means the kiss on the cheek as a greeting — also \"Bützchen\" or \"Bützke.\" It is exchanged among friends, family and sometimes even between business partners. During carnival (in the Catholic parts of northern Germany) the \"Bützchen\" is especially common. In the stricter Low German regions it is more of a family custom. East Frisians tend to be reserved with Bützchen — Mecklenburgers are more relaxed about it.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-108": "The \"Murmeli\" is the alpine marmot — a cute animal with a whistling warning call that lives in family colonies high in the mountains. They hibernate from October to April. A symbolic figure of the Swiss Alps — on posters, in advertisements, as a cuddly toy. Marmot-horn oil is traditionally used against rheumatism (controversial). Swiss nature philosophy: the marmot shows that even idleness can be a virtue. Pure Swiss mountain wildlife.",
  "wienerisch.w-103": "Ludwig van Beethoven (1770–1827), born in Bonn, spent his 35 most productive years in Vienna. Here he composed his 9 symphonies, piano sonatas and string quartets. He moved house over 60 times — the Viennese called him \"the madman.\" His apartment in the Pasqualatihaus and the Beethoven House in Heiligenstadt are museums today. His funeral in 1827 became a day of public mourning — 20,000 Viennese accompanied the coffin. Viennese music history.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-103": "Domina is a Franconian red wine grape — bred in 1927 at Geilweilerhof from Portugieser and Spätburgunder (Pinot Noir). A deep-dark wine with a full-bodied flavour, aromas of dark berries and chocolate. Its robust growth character makes it ideal for Franconian soils. It is often aged in oak barrels. In the Maindreieck and across the Franconian wine region it is steadily gaining followers — the Franconian answer to international red wines.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-108": "The Hüttenarbeiter (ironworks worker) was, alongside the miner, the second great profession of the Ruhr region — he worked at the blast furnace, the converter or the rolling mill of the steelworks. Amid heat, noise and mortal danger he shaped the steel that built Germany. Krupp, Thyssen, Hoesch — these names are interwoven with the Hüttenarbeiter. Today an almost extinct occupational group, but a proud memory in families.",
  "alemannisch.al-108": "Black Forest woodcarving has a centuries-old tradition — originally for furniture, crucifixes and Fasnet masks. Today there are training workshops in Triberg and Furtwangen, and carving academies for tourists. The mask faces of the Fasnet (witches, devils, fools) are works of art collected worldwide. A woodcarver needs years to create a life's work. The Alemannic woodworking culture lives on through these craftsmen.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-095": "A \"Bähmull\" is a crybaby, a whining, perpetually moaning person. \"Sei kää Bähmull, des dut doch gar ned weh!\" (Don't be a crybaby, that doesn't even hurt!). From \"bäh\" (imitating crying) and \"Mull\" (mouth). It is mainly said to children who cry at every little thing, sometimes also to squeamish adults. An affectionately scolding Palatine word that calls for bravery. Onomatopoeic and apt, it belongs to the rich repertoire of Palatine descriptions of people.",
  "hessisch.h-139": "The \"Schoppen-Hannes\" is a traditional Frankfurt carnival figure — a fat, easygoing man with a glass of cider (Apfelwein) and a Hessian Schoppen mentality. He embodies local politics with a wink. A caricature that celebrates the Hessian way of life: cosy, somewhat sluggish, but warm-hearted. Always present at Frankfurt carnival. A symbol of the Hessian zest for life.",
  "berlinisch.b-131": "Hertha BSC is Berlin's oldest and largest football club — founded in 1892, blue-and-white colours, \"Die alte Dame\" (the Old Lady). Home stadium: the Olympiastadion. Twice German champions (1930, 1931). Currently in the 2nd division. Sebastian Kehl, Marko Pantelić and Salomon Kalou were Hertha greats. The fans have an emotional, sometimes frustrating relationship with \"their Old Lady.\"",
  "bayerisch.by-115": "The night from 30 April to 1 May is considered, in Bavarian folk belief, Walpurgis Night (Hexennacht), when evil spirits are abroad. Young lads roam the village playing \"Lausbubenstreiche\" (mischievous pranks): garden gates are unhinged, wheelbarrows hoisted onto roofs, things rearranged. It stems from pagan spring customs. In some villages a maypole is also raised — Bavarian-Bairian folklore in its purest form.",
  "saechsisch.s-101": "Heinrich Schütz (1585–1672) was the most important German Baroque composer before Johann Sebastian Bach — court Kapellmeister in Dresden for over 50 years. He brought the Italian madrigal art to Germany and created sacred vocal music of world rank (\"Symphoniae sacrae\"). Born in Köstritz, died in Dresden. His work made Dresden the \"German music metropolis\" of the 17th century. Father of the German musical tradition.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-104": "Count Ferdinand von Zeppelin (1838–1917), born in Constance, invented the airships named after him — the \"Zeppelins.\" In 1900 the \"LZ 1\" took off over Lake Constance. In the 1920s Zeppelins were a symbol of German engineering and crossed the Atlantic. The Hindenburg disaster of 1937 ended the era. Today modern Zeppelin NT airships exist again, built at Lake Constance. A Swabian inventor legend.",
  "koelsch.k-121": "Reibekuchen are Cologne's potato pancakes — raw potatoes grated and fried golden-brown in the pan with onions, eggs and flour. They are eaten with apple sauce or dark bread. In Cologne there are Reibekuchen stalls that open only at weekends — the queues are long. They are also indispensable at carnival and Christmas markets. \"Reibekuchen mit Apfelmus\" is a classic Cologne dish.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-107": "The \"Schimmelreiter\" (The Rider on the White Horse) is the most famous northern German legend — immortalized in Theodor Storm's novella (1888). It tells the story of the dike reeve Hauke Haien from North Frisia, who fights against the forces of nature and superstition. His white horse still rides through the mudflats today — whoever sees it is threatened by the flood. A classic of northern German literature, filmed several times. A symbol of the struggle with storm tides and transience.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-109": "\"Heidiland\" is the tourism brand for the region around Maienfeld (Graubünden) — home of the Heidi stories by Johanna Spyri. The Heidi village in Maienfeld is a reconstructed farming hamlet with Heidi's house, the Alm-Öhi's hut and goats. A tourist attraction for Asian visitors who love the Heidi anime series from the 1970s. The A13 motorway also bears the \"Heidiland\" logo. Touristically successful, culturally contested.",
  "wienerisch.w-104": "The Lipizzaners are an old Austrian horse breed, bred since 1580 in the Slovenian Lipica (then part of the Habsburg Empire). Famous through the Spanish Riding School in Vienna, where they perform the classical riding art of the \"Haute École\" — levade, capriole, courbette. Lipizzaners are born black and turn white over the years — usually only fully white at 6–10 years of age. A UNESCO World Cultural Heritage of riding art.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-104": "Franconia's convents shaped the region spiritually and economically. Famous ones include Kitzingen Abbey (the Lioba convent), Wechterswinkel Abbey and Tückelhausen Abbey. Many were dissolved during the Reformation or secularization, some have remained active monasteries. They ran hospitals, schools and vineyards. The Bürgerspital Würzburg and the Juliusspital are descendants of the monastic wine and welfare tradition.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-109": "The \"Vatter\" is, in the Ruhr region, the affectionately direct term for one's father — a bit coarser and warmer than the standard German \"Vater.\" The double-T pronunciation is typical of Low German, which still echoes in the Pott. The Vatter is the figure of authority in the house, often a miner or steelworker, who passes on his life wisdom in terse sentences. The family patriarch in the traditional Pott family.",
  "alemannisch.al-109": "The Black Forest Railway (Offenburg–Constance) is one of the most important railway engineering works in Europe — opened in 1873. It overcomes 600 metres of elevation through 39 tunnels and is the most spectacular railway line in Germany. Built by Robert Gerwig — a technical masterpiece of the Gründerzeit. Today a tourist railway — the journey from Hornberg past the Triberg waterfalls to Sankt Georgen is breathtaking. Living history to experience.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-096": "The \"Knorze\" is the crusty end piece of the loaf, the heel of the bread. \"Ich krieg de Knorze, der schmeckt am beschte!\" (I get the heel, it tastes the best!). Also called \"Knerzel.\" In Palatine families there's often a friendly tussle over the coveted Knorze. From the word stem for \"gnarled, hard.\" Especially popular with butter and salt or as part of a Vesper (snack). An affectionate word for the best piece of the bread, showing the Palatine's appreciation for good farmhouse bread.",
  "hessisch.h-140": "The term \"Hessischer Apfelwein\" is protected EU-wide as a geographical indication — only cider from Hesse may be called this. Tart, clear, with 5–7% alcohol. Pressed from special cider apples (Bittenfelder, Bohnapfel). The tradition goes back to the Middle Ages — Charlemagne already had cider pressed. Hesse produces over 40 million litres a year. Apfelwein is Hessian cultural heritage.",
  "berlinisch.b-132": "The 1. FC Union Berlin is the \"Iron Union\" from Köpenick — founded in 1906, red-and-white colours. The main club of East Berlin, with a loyal fan base. In 2019 it was promoted to the Bundesliga for the first time, and in 2021/22 even reached the Conference League. Home stadium: An der Alten Försterei. Unlike Hertha, Union is considered \"down-to-earth,\" \"genuine\" and to have cult appeal. A turning point for the East Berlin club.",
  "bayerisch.by-116": "The \"Reibekuacha\" are the Bavarian variant of potato pancakes — made from grated raw potatoes, egg and flour, fried crispy in the pan. They are often served with apple sauce. Indispensable at every Bavarian folk festival — the smell of Reibekuachen is as much a part of the Wiesn experience as the haze of beer. Also popular at home as a hearty homemade dish. Enjoyable sweet or savoury.",
  "saechsisch.s-102": "Robert Schumann (1810–1856), born in Zwickau, was one of the most important composers of German Romanticism. Together with his wife Clara Schumann (née Wieck, 1819–1896), one of the most famous pianists of her time, he formed the most celebrated artist couple of the 19th century. Both lived for a time in Leipzig and Dresden. Robert suffered from mental illness and ended up in an asylum in Bonn. Saxon music history par excellence.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-105": "The \"Gaisburger Marsch\" is a hearty Swabian stew from Stuttgart-Gaisburg: beef in broth, with potatoes, Spätzle and onions. Legend has it that in the 19th century Stuttgart soldiers had to march to Gaisburg as a punishment — the stew was their reward. It is often served on Sundays or as a winter dish. A Stuttgart identity dish — whoever eats the original knows what Swabian really is.",
  "koelsch.k-122": "\"Himmel un Äd\" (Heaven and Earth) is a classic Cologne dish — mashed potatoes (earth) and apple sauce (heaven), served with black pudding and roasted onions. The sweet apple contrasts with the hearty mash and the savoury sausage. A down-to-earth, honest Cologne home cooking — less common today, but still found in traditional Kölsch taverns.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-108": "\"Birnen, Bohnen und Speck\" (pears, beans and bacon) is THE northern German summer dish — boiled green beans with whole cooking pears and bacon. The sweet-and-salty combination is a pure taste experience. It comes from the farmhouse cuisine of Schleswig-Holstein and Lower Saxony. It is cooked between July and September, when beans and pears are in season. A classic of northern German home cooking. A sweet-and-hearty combination that often baffles southern Germans — northern Germans rave about it.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-110": "The \"Alpaufzug\" is a traditional Swiss custom in early summer (May/June): the farmers lead their livestock — cows with flower wreaths and large bells — from the valley farms up to the summer alpine pastures. Accompanied by the herdsman (Senn), dog, family and tourists. A march of several hours to several days through the village. The autumn \"Alpabzug\" is its counterpart. Pure mountain culture, worthy of UNESCO.",
  "wienerisch.w-105": "The Vienna Boys' Choir is a famous boys' choir with a tradition of over 500 years — founded in 1498 by Emperor Maximilian I. Joseph Haydn, Franz Schubert and Anton Bruckner were members as boys. Today there are four separate choirs with around 100 boys altogether, aged 9 to 14. They sing at Mass in the Hofburg Chapel on Sundays and tour the world. A Viennese cultural export of world rank.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-105": "The State Court Cellar Würzburg beneath the Residenz is one of the oldest and most important wineries in Germany — founded in 1128 by the Würzburg prince-bishops. 120 hectares of vineyards in top sites such as Würzburger Stein. The barrel-wine cellars beneath the Residenz cover 4,000 m² — a unique atmosphere. Guided tastings are a must for wine lovers. Tasting history.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-110": "In the Ruhr region the \"Mutter\" (mother) is the family's secret boss — while the \"Vatter\" (father) toiled underground, she held everything together at home. She cooked, cleaned, raised the children and managed the meagre pay packet. Mother figures like Aunt Erna, Helga or Inge shape whole neighbourhoods. The Ruhr mother is warm, strict and indestructible — the true backbone of the miners' families.",
  "alemannisch.al-110": "The Höllentalbahn (Hell Valley Railway) from Freiburg through the Höllental to Donaueschingen is one of the most dramatic rail lines in Germany — through wild gorges, over viaducts and through tunnels. Gradients of up to 5.5 percent. The Hirschsprung rock landmark marks the narrowest point. Today a tourist attraction with panorama cars in summer. In winter it is an important connection to the ski areas of Hinterzarten and Titisee.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-097": "\"Allmächd!\" is an exclamation of astonishment or fright — a short form of \"Allmächtiger Gott!\" (Almighty God!). \"Allmächd, host du mich verschreckt!\" (Goodness, you startled me!). It expresses surprise, dismay or even admiration. Related to the Franconian \"Allmächd na!\". A hearty Palatinate sigh of exclamation that has to serve in many situations. It is pronounced with a grand gesture and a drawn-out \"ä\". Along with \"Mei!\" it is one of the classic exclamations at the Palatine regulars' table and in everyday life.",
  "hessisch.h-141": "The Speierling (service tree) — a Sorbaceae similar to the rowan — yields the famous Speierling berries that are added to Hessian apple wine. They give it tannins and its typically tart taste. The Speierling tree is rare today — service trees are deliberately planted to preserve the apple-wine tradition. The Speierling also enjoys the status of a heritage tree.",
  "berlinisch.b-133": "The Eisbären Berlin are Berlin's most successful ice hockey club — nine-time German champions in the DEL. Home venue: Uber Arena (formerly Mercedes-Benz Arena) by the Ostbahnhof. Over 14,000 spectator capacity. The club mascot is the polar bear \"Bully\". The fans are loyal and loud. In Berlin's sporting calendar a must-attend event alongside Hertha and Alba Berlin.",
  "bayerisch.by-117": "The \"Bavaria\" is an 18-metre-high bronze statue of a woman on the Theresienhöhe in Munich, above the Theresienwiese. Created from 1843 to 1850 by Ludwig Schwanthaler on commission from King Ludwig I. The personified female symbolic figure of the Free State of Bavaria. Inside there is a staircase — visitors can climb up into the head and look down on the Oktoberfest through the eyes. A landmark of Munich alongside the Frauenkirche.",
  "saechsisch.s-103": "Bautzen (Sorbian Budyšin) in Upper Lusatia is the political and cultural centre of the Sorbian minority in Saxony. Famous for its historic townscape with 17 towers, Bautzen mustard (yellow, hot) and the traditional Bautzen sausage market. Also sadly known for the GDR Stasi prison \"Bautzen II\". Today a lively bilingual town with Sorbian schools and Sorbian-Wendish folklore.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-106": "\"Stuagert\" — also written \"Schduagerd\" — is the Swabian pronunciation of Stuttgart, the state capital of Baden-Württemberg. A city in a basin valley, surrounded by vineyards. Home to Daimler, Porsche, Bosch — the capital of the German automotive industry. For years embroiled in dispute over the \"Stuttgart 21\" station construction. Swabian identity: rural and down-to-earth yet high-tech and modern at the same time. The VfB fans sing: \"Hier gibt's nur ein VfB!\" (There's only one VfB here!).",
  "koelsch.k-123": "The Cologne brewpub is an institution — establishments like Päffgen, Sünner, Früh, Gaffel often have their own breweries. Here Kölsch is poured straight from the barrel into the slim \"Kölsch glass\" (0.2 l) and served by the \"Köbes\" (waiter) on a tray. As long as the glass is not turned upside down, the next Kölsch comes automatically. The tally on the beer mat keeps growing.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-109": "The \"Buschwindröschen\" (wood anemone, Anemone nemorosa) is the quintessential North German spring flower — in April it covers the beech forests with carpets of white blossoms. An indicator of old, near-natural woodlands. Butterflies threatened with extinction depend on it. It grows en masse in North German conservation areas such as the Lüneburg Heath or the Sachsenwald. A symbol of the spring awakening in the north.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-111": "The \"Föhn\" is in Switzerland a warm, dry downslope wind from the Alps — particularly strong in Ticino and the valleys of central Switzerland. With a Föhn the visibility is crystal clear — you can see 100 km away. It triggers headaches (\"Föhnchopfweh\"), migraines and bad moods. Also an increased avalanche risk in winter. A weather phenomenon that not only the Bernese but also the Valaisans and the people of Graubünden watch with love-hate.",
  "wienerisch.w-106": "The \"Eitrige\" (literally \"the festering one\") is the rather unappetising but affectionate nickname for the Käsekrainer sausage at the Viennese sausage stand. The cheese spurts out when you bite into it — hence the name. At the sausage stand you order the famous combination: \"A Eitrige mit an Buckel und an 16er-Blech, scharf!\" — a Käsekrainer with a bread end and an Ottakringer beer, with mustard. Viennese sausage-stand slang is a subculture of its own — without translation there is no understanding.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-106": "The Bürgerspital zum Heiligen Geist in Würzburg is a charitable foundation founded in 1316 — to this day a care home with a clinic and at the same time one of the best wineries in Franconia (110 hectares). The sites Stein, Pfaffenberg and Würzburger Pfaffenstuhl belong to it. The proceeds finance the elderly care — foundation economics for 700 years. In the Bürgerspital wine taverns in the old town you can taste fresh Franconian wines.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-111": "In the Ruhr region the \"Oma\" (grandma) is the keeper of family traditions — she cooks the Sunday roast, tells of the grandparents' toil and watches over the grandchildren. When the \"Vatter\" (father) worked the night shift and the mother was at work, Oma was there. She crochets pot holders, grumbles about the rubbish and secretly hands out sweets. Generational bonding in its purest form. A Ruhr grandma is worth her weight in gold.",
  "alemannisch.al-111": "Triberg in the central Black Forest is famous for the Triberg Waterfalls (163 m, the highest in Germany) and for the largest cuckoo clock in the world. With 5,000 inhabitants it is a tourist magnet — Asians and Americans in particular come. The pilgrimage church Maria in der Tanne, the Black Forest Museum, a traditional spa town. The Black Forest image par excellence: fir trees, waterfalls, cuckoo clocks, Black Forest gateau.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-098": "D'\"Latwerge\" is the dark, boiled-down plum spread that is stirred for hours until it is thick and sweet. \"Aufs Bauernbrot a dicke Schicht Latwerge, herrlich!\" (A thick layer of Latwerge on the farmhouse bread, wonderful!). An old Palatinate preserve made from the abundant plum harvests. In the past the Latwerge was cooked communally in a large cauldron. From the Latin-medical \"electuarium\". On bread, in cake or with Buwespitzle, it is a delight. A classic word from the rural larder culture of the region.",
  "hessisch.h-142": "\"Bembelfresser\" (Bembel guzzler) is the humorous term for someone who drinks an especially large amount of apple wine from the Bembel — a Frankfurt original. Here the affectionate Hessian mentality is expressed: whoever empties the Bembel belongs to the group. Never meant as an insult, but as a sign of drinking prowess and love of one's homeland. Whoever is a Bembelfresser has Hessian pride.",
  "berlinisch.b-134": "Alba Berlin is Berlin's most successful basketball club — eleven-time German champions, eight-time DBB Cup winners. Home venue: Uber Arena. They play in the Basketball Bundesliga and the EuroLeague. Known for aggressive pressing and a fast game. Coach Israel Gonzalez. At home games the atmosphere is legendary. Berlin loves its albatross squad.",
  "bayerisch.by-118": "The \"Wuiderer\" — also \"Wildschütz\" (poacher) — is a romanticised folk figure in Bavarian-Austrian folklore. The most famous was probably Georg \"Girgl\" Jennerwein (1848–1877), shot dead at the Schliersee — his death was sung about in the \"Jennerwein song\". Wuiderer were regarded as rebels against the nobility, for whom the forest was a privilege of the rich. Today a folklore motif in many folk songs and Heimat films. A Bavarian Robin Hood.",
  "saechsisch.s-104": "The gingerbread (Pfefferkuchen) from Pulsnitz and Bautzen is a Saxon speciality that has been baked since the 16th century. Unlike Nuremberg gingerbread, Saxon Pfefferkuchen is lighter, softer and strongly flavoured with spices (anise, cinnamon, cloves). It is produced and eaten all year round, but especially at Christmas time. Pulsnitz proudly calls itself the \"gingerbread town\". A genuine Saxon heritage — worthy of UNESCO.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-107": "The \"Lemberger\" is the more robust Swabian red wine — deep dark, spicy, with ageing potential. From the Blaufränkisch grape variety, which in Württemberg has been called \"Lemberger\" since the 19th century. Unlike the light Trollinger, the Lemberger is a wine for special occasions. A popular cuvée: \"Trollinger mit Lemberger\" — the Swabian classic. It is also made as a late harvest and an ice wine. Württemberg is Germany's Lemberger stronghold.",
  "koelsch.k-126": "Carnival Friday (the day before Nelkensamstag) is the day of the first big sessions and of the Schull- un Veedelszöch (school and neighbourhood parades). Here schools and neighbourhoods show off their carnival creativity. The atmosphere is slowly heating up for the hot days from Sunday to Tuesday. Important carnival societies such as the Rote Funken rehearse their programmes. The start of the intense carnival phase.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-110": "\"Krabben\" or \"Granat\" are the small, pink North Sea shrimp from the Wadden Sea — a North German delicacy. They are caught fresh, boiled and usually peeled by hand (\"Krabben pulen\") — a time-consuming activity that many North Germans master expertly. Classics: shrimp on bread, shrimp salad or Pannfisch with shrimp. A tourist magnet in Büsum, Greetsiel and Sylt. A North German world heritage of coastal cuisine.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-112": "The \"Glace\" is ice cream in Swiss German — a French loanword that has displaced the German \"Eiscreme\". \"En Glace go ässä\" (going to eat an ice cream) is a summer must. Famous Swiss Glace brands: Mövenpick, Frisco. \"Hörnliglace\" is ice cream in a waffle cone. In Ticino it is called \"Gelato\". Also used figuratively: \"Es isch mer Glace\" — I couldn't care less (rather rare).",
  "wienerisch.w-107": "The \"Topfengolatsche\" is a classic Viennese pastry: a square Danish pastry filled with sweet Topfen (quark) and raisins. The word \"Golatsche\" comes from the Czech \"koláč\" (cake) — a legacy of the migrations of the multi-ethnic Austro-Hungarian Empire. It is served in every Viennese bakery with the breakfast coffee. Also available as an \"Apfel-\" (apple) or \"Powidlgolatsche\" with plum jam. A sweet Viennese classic with Bohemian roots.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-107": "The Hesselberg, at 689 metres, is the highest mountain in Middle Franconia — located in the district of Ansbach, visible from afar in the Hahnenkamm region. A sacred mountain of the Hermunduri, later a cult site. The Nazi era misused it as the \"Frankenberg\" for large rallies — today a memorial serves as a reminder. In summer a Mecca for hang-gliders, with hiking opportunities and a magnificent view over the Franconian countryside.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-112": "Grönemeyer's anthem \"Bochum\" (1984) is more than a song — it is the official signature tune of the entire Ruhr region. \"Du bist keine Schönheit, vor Arbeit ganz grau\" (You're no beauty, all grey from work) describes the Ruhr area honestly and lovingly at the same time. At VfL Bochum it is played before every match, and 30,000 sing along. It even made it into the Bochum city council — an official avowal of identity.",
  "alemannisch.al-112": "Schiltach in the Kinzig valley is one of the most beautiful preserved half-timbered towns in Germany — a historic rafters' town where Black Forest logs were floated all the way to Holland. The market square with its steep half-timbered houses is a picture-postcard scene. Famous: Hansgrohe (faucets, world market leader) and the Hansgrohe Aquademie. 4,000 inhabitants, a great history. In summer the Rafters' Festival.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-099": "Da \"Kappes\" is white cabbage — and figuratively also nonsense or rubbish. \"Schwätz kää Kappes, des stimmt doch gar ned!\" (Don't talk Kappes, that's just not true!). From the Latin \"caput\" (head), because of the head-shaped cabbages. In the kitchen, Kappes is turned into sauerkraut or coleslaw. \"Des is doch alles Kappes\" means \"that's all nonsense\". A word with a double life — vegetable and gibberish. It belongs to the vivid Palatine vocabulary that loves to link the edible with sayings.",
  "hessisch.h-144": "\"Schunkeln\" — linking arms at the table and swaying back and forth — is a Hessian and generally German tradition, above all at festivals, in apple-wine taverns and at the Kerb. To Hessian songs like \"En Mool dahem an unsrem schee Frankfurt\", people automatically sway. A harmless, merry tradition that fosters a sense of community. Hessians like to schunkeln, and do so with devotion.",
  "berlinisch.b-137": "The Berlin Marathon is, alongside Boston, London, Chicago, New York and Tokyo, one of the \"World Marathon Majors\". Held since 1974, every year at the end of September. Known for its flat, fast course — numerous world records have been set here. Eliud Kipchoge set the then world record here in 2018 (2:01:39). Over 47,000 runners from 150 countries, a million spectators. A Berlin sporting highlight.",
  "bayerisch.by-119": "The \"Hagebutten\" (rose hips) — in Bavarian also \"Hetscherl\" or \"Hiffen\" — are the red fruits of the dog rose that glow in autumn. They are processed into jam, tea, syrup and schnapps. Very rich in vitamin C — Bavarian grandmothers used to make a winter supply from them. In folk songs they appear as an image of the sparse beauty of late autumn. A symbol of the wild nature of the Bavarian hedges and forest edges.",
  "saechsisch.s-105": "The \"Trabi\" (Trabant) was the most famous car of the GDR — built from 1957 to 1991 in Zwickau (Saxony). A body of Duroplast (pressed cotton waste), a two-stroke engine with 26 hp, blue smoke and an unmistakable rattle. Waiting times of up to 15 years! Today a cult object, a symbol of the GDR and of reunification. Trabi tours through Berlin are a tourist attraction. \"Mein Trabi, mein Schatz!\" (My Trabi, my treasure!).",
  "schwaebisch.sw-108": "The \"Cannstatter Wasen\" is the largest Swabian folk festival — the \"Bavarian Oktoberfest\" in Swabian. Founded in 1818 by King Wilhelm I as a harvest festival in Bad Cannstatt. Today three weeks of beer tents, carousels, a Ferris wheel — over 4 million visitors. The landmark: the 26-metre-high \"Fruchtsäule\" (fruit column). Swabia's answer to Munich — smaller, but just as merry. The \"Wasenrummel\" is the Swabian entertainment highlight in autumn.",
  "koelsch.k-127": "The \"Nubbelverbrennung\" on the evening of Shrove Tuesday is a Cologne carnival ritual: a straw figure (the \"Nubbel\") is burned in front of every pub — it symbolises all the carnival sins of the season. With it, all transgressions go up in flames. Humorous speeches are held, after which the Ash Wednesday phase begins. An almost religious carnival tradition.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-111": "The \"Pannfisch\" is a classic Hamburg dish — essentially a leftover meal: fillets of various kinds of fish (plaice, cod, pollock) fried in the pan, served with fried potatoes, mustard sauce and pickle. Originally from the Hamburg harbour — whatever was left of the boiled fish went into the pan the next day. Today a tourist classic in every Hamburg fish restaurant. North German leftover cuisine par excellence.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-113": "The \"Zibelemärit\" is the famous Bernese onion market — held every year on the fourth Monday in November. Over 50 tonnes of onions braided into artful plaits, mulled wine, onion tart, cheese tart. Over 800 stalls in Bern's old town, 250,000 visitors. A tradition since the 19th century. A tourist highlight and at the same time a genuine folk festival of the Bernese. With confetti battles in the morning — pure Swiss folklore.",
  "wienerisch.w-108": "Helmut Qualtinger (1928–1986) — \"Quasi\" for short — was Vienna's most famous cabaret artist, actor and admonisher. His \"Der Herr Karl\" (1961) was a merciless reckoning with the Viennese philistine of the Nazi era. With Carl Merz and Gerhard Bronner he raised Viennese cabaret to the highest level. He played the \"Bockerer\" and the \"Aufbahrer\". Viennese originality personified — critical, blackly humorous, tragic.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-109": "Johann Andreas Eisenbarth (1663–1727), the legendary itinerant surgeon from Upper Franconia, is the hero of the well-known mocking song \"Ich bin der Doktor Eisenbarth\". In reality a respected physician of his time, mocked in legend as a quack. Bayreuth and Hann. Münden dispute over his grave. A symbol of Franconian folk medicine and market-crier showmanship. In the song: \"Glory, Viktoria, Glory, Viktoria!\"",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-113": "Marius Müller-Westernhagen (born 1948 in Düsseldorf) is a native of Düsseldorf, yet his sound from \"Sexy\", \"Freiheit\" and \"Mit Pfefferminz bin ich dein Prinz\" also shapes the Ruhr region. His rough, straightforward manner fits the Pott mentality. Concerts in the Schalke Arena or the Westfalenstadion are mass events. A bridge between the Rhineland and the Pott through direct, honest rock music.",
  "alemannisch.al-113": "Wolfach in the Kinzig Valley is famous for its Dorotheenhütte — the only still-operating mouth-blown glassworks in the Black Forest. Visitors can watch the glassmakers at work. Famous Wolfach Fasnet carnival with its own fool figures (the \"Wohlauf\" call). Also schnapps distilleries (the Alfred Schladerer family) and Wolfach Castle. A small town with a great tradition. The Black Forest Costume Museum tells the history of the region.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-100": "The \"Fastnacht\" is the fifth season, the Palatine carnival with parades, comedy sessions (Kappensitzungen) and masked balls. \"At Fastnacht the whole village goes wild!\" Unlike the Rhenish \"Karneval\", the Palatine usually says \"Fastnacht\" or \"Faasenacht\". Strongholds are Mainz and many Palatine villages with their own clubs. Comic speeches, guard dances, the fools' call — a boisterous time before Lent. A deeply rooted custom that celebrates the convivial and humorous side of the Palatinate.",
  "hessisch.h-146": "The \"Kerbborsche\" are the young men of a Hessian village who organize and celebrate the Kerb (parish fair) — as a rite of passage from boy to man. They wear traditional costume, raise the Kerb tree, give the \"Kerb speech\" and take care of the festival. An important tradition in many Hessian villages. Whoever was once a Kerbborsch belongs to the village community.",
  "berlinisch.b-138": "The Christopher Street Day in Berlin is one of the largest Pride parades in Europe — held annually in July with over 750,000 participants. The demonstration for LGBTQ+ rights moves through Berlin-Mitte and ends with a large closing rally at the Brandenburg Gate. Political demands meet a colorful festival atmosphere. Berlin is one of the queerest cities in the world — even without the CSD.",
  "bayerisch.by-120": "The \"Wadlbiss\" is a Bavarian customary bit of fun — during the Schuhplattler or folk dance, someone jokingly pinches or bites the calf of their dance partner. Also in a figurative sense: little digs and teasing remarks among friends. Bavarian male friendships are often shown through such coarse jokes. Today it is more folklore than living practice.",
  "saechsisch.s-106": "\"SG Dynamo Dresden\" — \"Dynamo\" for short — is the most famous Saxon football club, founded in 1953. Eight East German championships (1953–1989), today in the 3rd division. The fans (the \"Dynamo family\") are notorious for their passion and loyalty; the Rudolf Harbig Stadium is a cauldron. Lokomotive Leipzig was also a significant GDR club. Saxon football folklore with myth and pain — the glory days are long gone, but the pride is alive.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-109": "The \"Seele\" is an elongated, crusty Upper Swabian bread with caraway and coarse salt — a specialty from Weingarten and the surrounding area. Crusty on the outside, airy and light on the inside. It is eaten as a snack, with the Vesper meal or with wine. \"Seelen\" were traditionally baked on All Souls' Day (November 2) — hence the name. Today they are available year-round in Upper Swabian bakeries. Swabian bread heritage.",
  "koelsch.k-128": "The Cologne Carnival has been part of UNESCO's intangible cultural heritage since 2014. With over 600 years of history (first documented in 1341), it is one of the oldest carnivals in the world. The fifth season begins on November 11 at 11:11 a.m. and ends on Ash Wednesday. Over 100 carnival societies, 14,000 active participants, 5 million spectators at the Rose Monday parade. Cologne pride.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-112": "The \"Watt\" is the Wadden Sea — the unique coastal landscape on the North Sea, walkable at low tide and flooded at high tide. A UNESCO World Natural Heritage site since 2009. A habitat for millions of migratory birds, crabs, mussels and worms. \"Wattwandern\" (mudflat hiking) is a popular tourist sport — best done with a knowledgeable mudflat guide, because the tide comes in faster than you think. A North German natural wonder, defining the culture of the coastal inhabitants.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-114": "Ferdinand Hodler (1853–1918) was one of the most important Swiss painters — a pioneer of Symbolism and Art Nouveau. Known for monumental landscapes of the Swiss Alps, allegorical paintings (\"The Night\", \"The Day\") and history paintings (\"The Departure of the Jena Students\"). His \"Parallelism\" theory shaped Swiss modernism. Today immortalized on the 200-franc note. Swiss art history with European resonance.",
  "wienerisch.w-109": "The \"Tschecherl-Wirt\" is the owner of a small Viennese stand-up tavern — usually a smoky corner pub with regular customers. Until 2019 it stood for the Viennese way of life; the bar area was a living room without seats. Tschecherl landlords have known their guests for decades, know every story, give credit. A vanishing profession — but a symbol of original Viennese culture. It lives on in films and novels.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-110": "The Frankenwald is a low mountain range in Upper Franconia — gentle heights up to 800 m, extensive spruce forests, clear streams. A border region with the Thuringian Forest and the Vogtland. The Frankenwald Nature Park offers hiking trails, raft trips on the Saale and winter sports. Kronach (Cranach's town), Kulmbach (the beer capital) and Hof are the most important towns. Economically weak, but landscape-wise beautiful and unspoiled.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-114": "Although BAP comes from Cologne, their sound also has a loyal fan base in the Ruhr region — the mix of rock, socially critical lyrics and dialect appeals to Pott folk too. Wolfgang Niedecken's voice sounds like the working-class milieu and hard truths. \"Verdamp lang her\" is also sung in the Pott pub. A bridge between Cologne and Ruhr culture via the dialect-rock route.",
  "alemannisch.al-114": "Vorarlberg is the westernmost state of Austria and speaks the purest Alemannic — more closely related to Swiss German than to Austrian standard German. Its capital is Bregenz on Lake Constance; other towns are Dornbirn, Feldkirch and Bludenz. The Vorarlbergers feel culturally drawn to Bavaria and Switzerland, less to Vienna. Economically strong, scenically beautiful, with its own identity. Ski resorts like Lech and Zürs are world-famous.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-101": "A \"Dummbeidel\" is a fool — literally a \"dumb bag\". \"You Dummbeidel, we could have told you that!\" An affectionately annoyed term of abuse, without real malice. It ranks alongside Dollbohrer, Dappschädel and Schoofseggel in the extensive Palatine lexicon of insults. The \"Beidel\" (bag) is used in many dialects as a base word for good-natured insults. A classic exclamation at the regulars' table or in the family when someone has done something rash.",
  "hessisch.h-147": "The Hessian coat of arms shows the blue-and-white striped \"Hessian lion\" — one of the oldest surviving heraldic images in Europe. The red-and-blue striped lion figure comes from the House of Brabant (12th century). Today the lion adorns the Hessian coat of arms, the Hessian flag, the Hessian police and all state symbols. At Eintracht matches, Hessian flags are waved.",
  "berlinisch.b-139": "The Karneval der Kulturen (Carnival of Cultures) is Berlin's great multicultural event — held annually at Whitsun in Kreuzberg. Colorful parades with drummers, dancers and musicians from 80+ countries. Unlike the Rhenish carnival, it celebrates cultural diversity, not traditional customs. A million visitors come every year. A symbol of Berlin's multicultural soul and against racism.",
  "bayerisch.by-121": "The typically Bavarian curse \"Kruzifix!\" — or even coarser \"Kruzitürken!\" — is a classic exclamation of annoyance or surprise. It comes from Catholic popular piety but has degenerated into a mere exclamation. \"Kruzifix nochamoi!\" is the standard cry when something goes wrong. Today it is mostly used jokingly, without religious connotation. A classic of Bavarian pub language.",
  "saechsisch.s-107": "The \"Räuchermännel\" is an Ore Mountain wooden figure with an incense cone placed in its belly — the smoke rises up through the mouth. Typical figures: miner, forester, robber, mushroom woman. It has been handcrafted in Seiffen and the surrounding area since the 19th century. A classic Christmas decoration that belongs in every Saxon living room. UNESCO-worthy folk art. Together with Schwibbögen and pyramids, part of Ore Mountain folklore.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-110": "The \"Schwabenstreich\" was invented in 2010 during the protests against Stuttgart 21: every day at 7 p.m. demonstrators made noise together with whistles, cooking pots and vuvuzelas — for one minute. It derives from the \"Seven Swabians\" of the fairy tale. Today it is a symbol of the Swabian civil rights movement and of creative democracy. It was adopted by other protest movements — from Swabia out into the whole world.",
  "koelsch.k-129": "\"Dat Wasser vun Kölle\" is a famous Cologne carnival song by the Bläck Fööss — a humorous homage to the drinking water of the Rhine. The song celebrates Cologne directness and stubbornness — even if the Rhine water is controversial, it tastes good to every Cologne native. An unofficial Cologne anthem, albeit meant ironically. A hit at carnival.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-113": "The \"Niederdeutsches Theater\" or \"Plattdüütsch Theater\" — above all the Ohnsorg Theatre in Hamburg (founded 1902) — keeps the Low German language alive on stage. Heinz Rühmann, Heidi Kabel and Henry Vahl performed classics here such as \"Tratsch im Treppenhaus\" and \"Das Hörrohr\". In the 1970s the ZDF brought the performances into the living room — millions understood Low German for the first time. North German language preservation par excellence.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-115": "The \"Sennenhund\" — above all the Bernese mountain dog — is THE Swiss dog breed. Large, black-white-brown, friendly, protective. It comes from the Bernese Oberland, where it helped the herdsmen at their work: guard dog, draft dog (for small carts), drover. There are four Sennenhund breeds: Bernese, Appenzeller, Entlebucher and Greater Swiss. A popular family dog worldwide. Swiss animal folklore.",
  "wienerisch.w-110": "The \"Heurigenmusik\" is the special musical accompaniment at the Heuriger (wine tavern) — usually with a Schrammel quartet, sometimes with zither, accordion and singing. Repertoire: old Viennese songs such as \"I hab di gern\" or \"Wien, du bist a Tafel voll Träume\". Wandering musicians move from table to table — whoever listens gives a tip. A Viennese tradition since the 19th century. Increasingly rare today — but still alive in real Heurigen like \"Mayer am Pfarrplatz\".",
  "fraenkisch.fr-111": "The \"Vadder\" is the familiar Franconian term for father — a bit more affectionate and down-to-earth than the standard German \"Vater\". The doubling of the T reflects the Franconian tendency to reinforce soft consonants. The Vadder is the family patriarch — usually a craftsman, farmer or civil servant, passing on words of wisdom in terse Franconian sentences. A generational bridge in the traditional Franconian family.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-115": "\"Dat\" is the typically Ruhr form of \"das\" (that/the) — an unmistakable feature of the dialect, derived from Low German. Without \"dat\" there is no genuine Ruhr sound: \"Dat is dat\", \"Dat geht net\", \"Wat is dat denn?\". Anyone who grows up in the Pott says it automatically. North German parents passed it on; Polish and Czech migrants adopted it. An identity marker.",
  "alemannisch.al-115": "Mulhouse (Mülhausen) is an industrial city in Alsace — until 1798 a free republic (allied with the Swiss Confederates). Today it has 110,000 inhabitants and a great automobile tradition (Peugeot, Bugatti). The Musée National de l'Automobile (the Schlumpf collection) is the largest car museum in the world. In terms of language history, Mulhouse was Alemannic-speaking for centuries — today only traces remain, but a cultural closeness to Baden persists.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-102": "The \"Quetsch\" is the accordion or concertina — because you squeeze (quetschen) it together. \"Get your Quetsch, we're singing a Palatine song!\" At every Kerwe, in every wine tavern, someone plays the Quetsch for singing and swaying. A central instrument of Palatine folk music and conviviality. Named onomatopoeically after the playing motion. Whoever masters the Quetsch is welcome at every festival. A classic word from the region's lively music and festival culture.",
  "hessisch.h-148": "Hesse has a rich tradition of farmers' rules — folk wisdom about weather, harvest and the seasons. \"March snow harms the crops\" or \"April sun and a woman's favour don't last long\". These rhymes have been passed down over generations. In rural regions of Hesse (Vogelsberg, Westerwald, Rhön) they are still alive. Rural orality as a Hessian heritage.",
  "berlinisch.b-140": "The Wannsee in the southwest of Berlin is a popular local recreation area — actually a widening of the Spree. With the famous Strandbad Wannsee (one of the largest inland lidos in Europe, opened in 1907). Here the Wannsee Conference (the planning of the Holocaust) was held in 1942 — today a memorial. \"Pack die Badehose ein\" is the classic Berlin summer song about the Wannsee.",
  "bayerisch.by-122": "The \"Wuzler\" is the Bavarian and Austrian word for the table-football machine (foosball table). \"A round of Wuzln\" is part of the standard repertoire in every Bavarian pub corner. It comes from \"wuzeln\" — to turn, to roll. The Wuzler is a social meeting point across generations, where regulars beat students and vice versa. Popular too in the beer tents at the funfair. Bavarian pub culture in playful form.",
  "saechsisch.s-108": "The Wendelstein in Saxon Switzerland is part of the Elbe Sandstone Mountains — a via ferrata and viewpoint. Not to be confused with the Bavarian Wendelstein. Saxon Switzerland, with the Bastei, Königstein and Lilienstein, is one of the most beautiful low mountain ranges in Germany. Famous for its striking sandstone rocks, through which generations of Romantics have hiked since Caspar David Friedrich. A Saxon natural paradise.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-111": "The \"Saitenwurscht\" is the Swabian word for the Vienna sausage (Wiener Würstchen) — longer and thinner, with a natural casing. \"Saiten\" as in a violin, because the sausages are long and straight. A must with lentils and Spätzle. They are heated in hot water (\"simmered\", not boiled, otherwise they burst). Also known as \"Rote\". Standard fare of every Swabian snack and Vesper. As down-to-earth as the Swabian himself.",
  "koelsch.k-130": "The \"Stippeföttche\" (also \"Bützchengala\") is a traditional Cologne carnival dance: two dancing couples turn back to back and bump their backsides together. A humorously suggestive choreography from the 19th century. It is celebrated especially in the Rote Funken (a carnival society). A Cologne specialty seen nowhere else.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-114": "The \"Pharisäer\" is a North Frisian hot drink: strong coffee with brown rum (or Asbach brandy) and a cap of cream on top. The point: the cream hides the alcohol — so you could drink secretly at the Sunday coffee table in front of the strict pastor. When the pastor's wife discovered the rum, she is said to have exclaimed: \"Oh, you Pharisees!\" — hence the name. North German drinking culture with a sense of humor.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-116": "The \"Pöstler\" is the Swiss German word for the postman — a familiar figure in every village. \"Ds Pöstli\" comes by every day and knows every resident. In the mountains, postal workers once delivered by mule or sledge — the yellow post horn (the symbol of the Swiss postbus) was blown to announce them. Today they are often out on e-bikes. The \"Postauto\" lines bring the Pöstler to even the most remote valley.",
  "wienerisch.w-111": "The \"G'spritzte\" is THE Viennese summer drink: white wine (usually Grüner Veltliner) mixed with mineral water, about 1:1. It is drunk at the Heuriger, in the Beisl and at street festivals. \"Sauer g'spritzt\" with mineral water, \"süß g'spritzt\" with lemonade. Invented to make the wine last longer to enjoy — a Viennese compromise between the joy of life and moderation.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-112": "\"Muddi\" is the Franconian affectionate form for mother — warm, intimate, childlike. It is also used lovingly by adults for their own mother. Unlike the Bavarian \"Mutta\", the Franconian Muddi sounds softer and more intimate. The Franconian mother is the keeper of family traditions, cooks the Schäuferla on Sundays and holds the family together. The very heart of the family.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-116": "\"Wat\" is the Ruhr form of \"was\" (what) — like \"dat\", derived from Low German. \"Wat willste?\" (What do you want?), \"Wat is los?\" (What's up?), \"Wat soll dat?\" (What's that supposed to be?). The W-word shapes every Pott dialogue. The pronunciation with a hard T instead of a soft S makes the sound direct and honest. Whoever says \"was\" instead of \"wat\" is either a newcomer or stands for standard German. In the Pott, \"wat\" reigns.",
  "alemannisch.al-116": "Strasbourg is the capital of Alsace and seat of the European Parliament — a bridge between German and French culture. Strasbourg Cathedral is one of the most important Gothic buildings in Europe. Petite France, with its half-timbered houses, canals and Alsatian charm, draws millions of tourists. Historically Alemannic-speaking — today Alsatian German (an Alemannic-Franconian blend) is endangered.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-103": "The \"Ähnl\" is the grandfather or forefather — an old Palatine word for grandpa. \"Mei Ähnl hot mir des Wengerd-Schaffe beigebrocht.\" (My grandpa taught me the work in the vineyard.) Related to \"Ahne\" (ancestor). The feminine form is \"Ähnel\" or \"Ahnel\" for the grandmother. Still in use in rural areas, especially among the older generation. The Ähnl passes on knowledge of wine, gardening and customs to the grandchildren. A classic family word that expresses the close bond between the generations in the Palatinate.",
  "hessisch.h-150": "\"Hessen 3\" — today officially \"hr-fernsehen\" — is the third channel of Hessischer Rundfunk (HR). With shows like \"herrlich ehrlich\", \"Hessenschau\" (local news), \"Service: Reisen\", \"Maintower\" or \"Friedrichs!\". For many Hessians, Hessen 3 is the home-grown channel — informative, entertaining and with a clear Hessian identity. Older Hessians watch it every day.",
  "berlinisch.b-141": "Hans-Wilhelm Müller-Wohlfahrt — born in Bensheim, but a Berlin cult figure — is Germany's most famous sports physician. From 1977 to 2015 (with interruptions) he was the FC Bayern doctor. Nickname \"Mull\". He treated Becker, Beckenbauer and countless top athletes. His practice on Munich's Lindenstraße is legendary. Even though he works in Munich, Berlin claims him as a celebrity connection.",
  "bayerisch.by-124": "The \"Marterl\" is a typically Bavarian-Tyrolean wayside cross with a small picture — usually commemorating a fatal accident at that spot. It comes from the Middle High German \"marter\" (martyrdom, suffering). It is found along hiking trails, mountain paths and roads. Folk art, often hand-painted, with an inscription and saints. A testament to deep popular piety and mountain folklore. It has also been immortalized in folk plays.",
  "saechsisch.s-109": "The \"Knusperhäuschen\" (gingerbread house) from the fairy tale \"Hansel and Gretel\" (Brothers Grimm) is especially rooted in Saxon-Thuringian folklore — the story is thought to be set in the Thuringian Forest or the Ore Mountains. At Christmas time bakers make small gingerbread houses modeled on it. A symbol of the folk-tale tradition that has shaped the Ore Mountains and Saxony. A childhood culture with a dark depth.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-112": "The \"Fasnet\" is the Swabian-Alemannic carnival — far older and more archaic than the Rhenish carnival. With elaborately carved wooden masks (\"Larven\"), bells and eerie figures such as witches, Hansel and Spättle. Strongholds: Rottweil, Villingen, Überlingen, Schwäbisch Gmünd. Every town has its own figures and traditions. UNESCO-worthy cultural heritage. Unlike the Cologne carnival, it is more about tradition than partying.",
  "koelsch.k-131": "The Höhner have been indispensable to Cologne's carnival since 1972 — with countless hits like \"Viva Colonia\" (2002), \"Wenn nicht jetzt, wann dann?\" (1992), \"Die Karawane zieht weiter\" (1981) and \"Echte Fründe\". Their songs are played at every carnival session — from small club gatherings to live broadcasts on WDR. Henning Krautmacher (until 2020) shaped the band as its frontman.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-115": "The \"Schluck\" is, in northern Germany, the short, strong schnapps taken to aid digestion — usually Korn, Kümmel or aquavit. \"Wat to'n Schluck nehmen\" (having a nip) is part of the North German farmer's breakfast, of funerals, of weddings. \"Lütt un Lütt\" is the Hamburg variant: a small beer with a small Köm. The Schluck is social lubricant and a cultural constant on the coast. No North German celebration without a Schluck.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-117": "The \"Alphornblasä\" — playing the 3-4 m long alphorn — is, alongside yodeling, Switzerland's sound symbol number one. The keyless wooden wind instrument produces only the natural harmonic series. Originally used for communication between the Alps and the valley, today it is folklore. Every year there is a Federal Alphorn Meeting — hundreds play together on the mountain pass. UNESCO-worthy folk culture. It can be heard at weddings, tourist receptions and mountain evening gatherings.",
  "wienerisch.w-112": "The \"Wirti\" is, in Viennese, the landlord of the Beisl or tavern — a key figure in Viennese society. He knows his regulars, their stories and their loved ones. The Wirti is confidant, psychologist and creditor all in one. \"Beim Wirti um's Eck\" (at the landlord's around the corner) is the standard meeting point. The diminutive ending \"-i\" reflects Viennese familiarity — even authorities are affectionately and mockingly cast in this light.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-113": "The \"Oma\" (grandma) is, in Franconia, the keeper of family traditions — she knows the old recipes, the stories of the ancestors and the dialect proverbs. Often living in the same house or right next door, she is the babysitter, cook and confidante of the grandchildren. A Franconian grandma makes Schäuferla, dumplings and Krapfen better than any star chef. The bond between generations is strong in Franconia — grandma is a cult figure.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-117": "\"Datt\" with a double T is the especially hard, emphatic form of \"dat\" — when someone from the Pott wants to be insistent. \"Datt iss so!\" (That's the way it is!), \"Datt geht garnich!\" (That just won't do!). Doubling the T signals emphasis, sometimes even indignation. Linguistically a form of intensification, in everyday life an expression of Pott directness. Whoever says \"datt\" means it seriously.",
  "alemannisch.al-117": "The Feldberg, at 1,493 meters, is the highest mountain in the Black Forest and the highest north of the Alps outside the central uplands. A ski area with 28 lifts, ski huts and a snow-sure location. In summer a hiking paradise — the Feldsee lake, the Feldbergsteig trail, the view from the Bismarck monument. Climatically a world of its own: often fog and snow while the sun shines in the valley. \"The local mountain of the Badeners\" — important for regional identity.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-104": "\"Gewidder!\" or \"Sapperlot, des Gewidder!\" is a curse of annoyance, derived from \"Gewitter\" (thunderstorm). \"Gewidder nochemol, jetz reißt de Faden schun widder!\" (Damn it, now the thread breaks again!) It expresses irritation and impatience without really being crude. Comparable to \"Donnerwetter\" or \"verflixt\". The approaching thunderstorm over the vineyards provided the image for this earthy exclamation. It belongs to the mild Palatine repertoire of curses with which one lets off steam without truly swearing.",
  "hessisch.h-151": "Ash Wednesday ends the Hessian-Rhenish carnival season — the day on which Lent begins. \"An Aschermittwoch ist alles vorbei\" (On Ash Wednesday it's all over) is an old Hessian saying. In Hessian cider taverns, eating herring is a tradition. A reflective day after the time of fools — doing penance, fasting, contemplating. A highlight of the Hessian church year.",
  "berlinisch.b-143": "The Hertha song \"Nur nach Hause\" — written by Frank Zander — is the official anthem of Hertha BSC. Sung at every home game in the Olympiastadion, it is an emotional hymn about home and loyalty to the club. \"Nur nach Hause, nur nach Hause gehn wir nicht ...\" (We're not going home, not going home ...) The Hertha fans sing it with tears in their eyes, especially during relegation battles or moments of promotion.",
  "bayerisch.by-125": "The \"Hoamatgfui\" is the deeply rooted sense of homeland of the Bavarians — a mixture of pride, attachment and longing for the mountains, the beer, the language and the customs. It is often triggered by the sound of a brass band, the sight of the Alps or the first sip of wheat beer after a long absence. Bavarian identity is more intense than elsewhere in Germany — the \"Hoamatgfui\" is its core. More than nostalgia: lived culture.",
  "saechsisch.s-110": "The \"Nußknacker\" (nutcracker) is a famous wooden figure from the Ore Mountains — traditionally depicted as a king, soldier or miner, with a movable mouth for cracking nuts. From Seiffen since the 19th century. A symbol of rebellion against authority (miners portrayed nobles as nutcrackers). Tchaikovsky's ballet \"The Nutcracker\" (1892) is based on a Hoffmann fairy tale with Ore Mountains origins. Saxon folk art known worldwide.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-113": "Swabian pride feeds on the awareness of achieving a lot and talking little about it. \"Mir kennat ällas außer Hochdeutsch\" — we can do everything except standard German — is the famous advertising slogan of the state of Baden-Württemberg. It describes Swabian self-confidence: tinkerers, inventors, hardworking, thrifty, with their own dialect. A tourism slogan that became a philosophy of life. Swabian identity in a single sentence.",
  "koelsch.k-132": "Trude Herr (1927-1991) was one of Cologne's best-known actresses — theater, film, comedy. She founded her own Trude Herr Theater on the Lower Rhine. Her roles, her drinker plays and her musical performances are unforgettable. An idol for the women of Cologne and a symbol of Cologne's joie de vivre. Her grave in Cologne-Müngersdorf is a place of pilgrimage.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-116": "The \"Strandkorb\" (roofed wicker beach chair) is the quintessential North German invention — created in 1882 by the Rostock basket weaver Wilhelm Bartelmann at the request of a noblewoman suffering from rheumatism. It protects against wind, sun and curious glances on the beach. Today there are two main forms: the Baltic Sea form (more open) and the North Sea form (more enclosed). Strandkörbe are rented by the day or bought. A symbol of the German seaside holiday. North German world heritage.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-118": "The \"Töff\" is, in Swiss German, the motorcycle — an onomatopoeic word from the \"töf-töf\" sound of the engine. A moped is also called \"Töffli\" or \"Vespa\", while a car is almost never called a Töff. \"Töffler\" are motorcyclists. \"Im Sommer schwingt jede Schwiizer ufs Töff\" (In summer every Swiss hops on the motorbike) — a cliché, but true. The \"Töff-Riibä-Lärm\" (din of revving motorbikes) is also a constant background noise in summer in Ticino or Valais.",
  "wienerisch.w-113": "The Krampus is, in the Alpine region, the sinister bogeyman who punishes naughty children on December 5 — the counterpart to the kindly Saint Nicholas. Half devil, half goat, with horns, a switch, bells and a long tongue. At \"Krampusläufe\" (Krampus runs), costumed young men roam the streets and frighten passers-by. Pure folklore with pagan roots. Tamer in Vienna than in Tyrol — but present.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-114": "A \"Saubär\" is, in Franconia, an untidy, dirty person — literally \"pig-bear\". A medium-strength swear word, mostly used within the family or among friends when someone comes into the house with dirty shoes or trashes their room. \"Du Saubär!\" the mum exclaims indignantly when the kids have been playing in the mud. More eye-rolling than real anger.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-118": "A \"Dödel\" is, in the Ruhr area, a lovable fool — someone who is clumsy or slow on the uptake but not a bad person. More of a friendly than a harsh swear word, often used among friends or in the family. \"Du Dödel!\" you say when someone has done something silly. The Pott cultivates these mild swear words that are more teasing than insult.",
  "alemannisch.al-118": "Skiing has a long tradition in the Black Forest — Germany's first ski school was founded in Todtnau in 1891. The ski areas of Feldberg, Belchen, Schauinsland and Notschrei offer downhill and cross-country options. Compared to the Alps it is more modest, but family-friendly. Black Forest skiers are proud of their local mountains. The FIS World Cup events in Schonach in the Black Forest are part of the winter sports tradition.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-105": "The \"Pärsching\" is the peach, especially the red-fleshed Palatine vineyard peach. \"Aus de Pärsching koche mer Marmelad un Likör.\" (From the peaches we make jam and liqueur.) The vineyard peach traditionally grows among the vines and yields an aromatic, slightly tart treat. From the Latin \"persica\". It is made into jam, cake and the famous \"Pärsching liqueur\". An almost forgotten Palatine specialty that is appreciated again today. A classic word from the region's rich fruit culture.",
  "hessisch.h-152": "The \"Frankfurter Wäldche\" is Frankfurt's city forest — at 4,800 hectares one of the largest urban forests in Europe. A local recreation area for the people of Frankfurt: jogging, hiking, picking mushrooms, having picnics. The Goetheturm in the forest was rebuilt after a fire in 2017. \"Mer geh ins Wäldche\" (We're going to the little forest) is the standard Hessian phrase for a weekend nature outing.",
  "berlinisch.b-145": "\"Bützchen\" is actually Cologne dialect, but it has also taken hold in Berlin — little kisses, often as a greeting or farewell. In Berlin mostly only among friends and family. Unlike in Cologne, it is not so ritualized. The younger, multicultural Berlin generation has adopted the term — as an expression of warmth and connection. Berliners aren't always cold!",
  "bayerisch.by-126": "The \"Trachtenverein\" (traditional costume association) is a Bavarian institution for preserving folk dance, traditional dress and customs. Founded in the 19th century by Joseph Vogl (Bavarian Costume and Heritage Association, 1890). Today there are thousands of associations in Bavaria, from Berchtesgaden to Aschaffenburg. Members meet for dances, festivals and processions — the Tracht is maintained with pride and meticulous care. More than folklore: a lived cult of homeland, often spanning generations.",
  "saechsisch.s-111": "The \"Dresdner Christstollen\" is THE Saxon Christmas cake — a protected designation of origin since 2010. A heavy yeast cake rich in butter and raisins, with marzipan, candied fruit, candied lemon peel and plenty of powdered sugar. It is baked four weeks before Christmas so that it can mature. The Dresden Stollen market in Advent is legendary — the \"giant Stollen\" weighs several tons. Saxon world heritage of the baking arts.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-114": "Hermann Hesse (1877–1962), born in Calw in the Black Forest, is Swabia's most famous writer and a Nobel laureate (1946). Works such as \"Steppenwolf\", \"Siddhartha\", \"Demian\" and \"The Glass Bead Game\" are world literature. He grew up Swabian but wrote in standard German. The 1960s youth in the USA rediscovered him — a Hesse boom. Calw honors him with a museum and a Hesse festival. A Swabian genius of global standing.",
  "koelsch.k-133": "The \"Stunksitzung\" has, since 1984, been the alternative to the traditional carnival sessions — political, sharp, satirical. In the Volksbühne am Rudolfplatz, carnival is celebrated as socially critical comedy. Tickets are sold out months in advance. The Stunksitzung is Cologne's intellectual-progressive carnival venue — it criticizes precisely what traditional sessions celebrate. Brilliant satirical artists.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-117": "\"Möwen\" (gulls) are the typical coastal birds of the north — herring gull, lesser black-backed gull, black-headed gull. Very social animals, they live in flocks and are omnipresent in port cities. Notorious for their cheekiness: they steal chips off your plate, screech loudly and poop on cars. A North German love-hate relationship: the gull belongs to the coast like beer belongs to a snack. Several gull songs are part of North German cultural heritage.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-119": "The \"Beck\" is, in Swiss German, the baker — a profession with high social status. Swiss bakeries are small, local and quality-conscious. Famous for Zopf (braided yeast bread), Bürli, Weggli, Nussgipfel and Buttergipfel. Every village has its \"Dorfbeck\" (village baker) — a social meeting point in the morning. \"Beim Beck go Brot reichä\" (popping to the baker to fetch bread) is a Swiss family ritual. Despite industrial competition, small bakers hold their ground through quality and tradition.",
  "wienerisch.w-114": "The \"Knödl\" is, in Viennese, the dumpling — not a single dish but a whole family. There are Marillenknödel (sweet, with apricot), Powidlknödel (with plum butter), Topfenknödel (with quark), Semmelknödel (for frying), Erdäpfelknödel (potato). The Viennese dumpling tradition is UNESCO-worthy. Every Viennese grandmother has her own secret recipe. \"A guater Knödl\" (a good dumpling) is Viennese art of living.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-115": "A \"Schaffix\" is, in Franconia, an especially hardworking, capable person — derived from \"schaffen\" (to work). \"Der is a richtiger Schaffix!\" (He's a real worker!) is high praise for someone who doesn't whine but rolls up their sleeves. In Franconia, diligence and a sense of duty count for much more than wealth or education — the Schaffix is respected. A classic craftsman's virtue that is held in high esteem in Franconia.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-119": "A \"Pinöckel\" is, in the Ruhr area, a small, often clumsy person — usually meant in an affectionately chiding way. It can also be used for a child who is up to something. It sounds absurd and is popular precisely for that reason: the playful sound makes the mockery friendly. Pott swear words are rarely truly nasty — most of the time there's affection in the mix.",
  "alemannisch.al-119": "Winter sports have a rich history in the Black Forest — cross-country skiing, downhill, tobogganing, ski jumping. The ski jump in Schonach hosts a stop of the Four Hills Tournament tour. The cross-country trail network in the High Black Forest is over 1,000 km long. Skiing is a family tradition for many Alemannic families. In winter the Black Forest becomes the winter sports center for Baden-Württemberg, Alsace, northern Switzerland and even the Dutch. Hotels and ski schools live off it.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-106": "D'\"Schnegg\" is the snail — and, affectionately, also a pretty girl or one's sweetheart. \"Komm her, mei Schnegg, gib mir a Bussel!\" (Come here, my Schnegg, give me a kiss!). In the garden the Schnegg annoys the gardener; as a term of endearment it gladdens the heart. The double meaning makes the word especially charming. Also \"a flotte Schnegg\" for an attractive young woman. It belongs to the tender as well as everyday Palatine vocabulary and shows how the dialect turns a garden creature into a pet name.",
  "hessisch.h-153": "The Frankfurt Main riverbank, with the Museumsufer on the Sachsenhausen side, is one of the city's most beautiful walks. Across the old Main bridge (Eiserner Steg) it connects the Old Town and Sachsenhausen. In summer the Museumsuferfest and the Mainfest take place here. Water taxis ferry tourists. Frankfurters jog along the Main and picnic on the steps. Hessian riverside feeling.",
  "berlinisch.b-146": "Schöneberg is a traditional West Berlin district — birthplace of Marlene Dietrich and David Bowie's Berlin home. Schöneberg Town Hall is where John F. Kennedy gave his \"Ich bin ein Berliner\" speech in 1963. Wittenbergplatz with the KaDeWe belongs to the district. Schöneberg is queer, creative and laden with history — one of Berlin's most diverse neighbourhoods.",
  "bayerisch.by-127": "The \"Goaßltanz\" or \"Goaßlschnalzen\" is a traditional Bavarian-Tyrolean custom dance in which the men crack long whips (Goaßln) rhythmically. It stems from Alpine carting culture — the farmhands would crack their whips to draw attention to themselves. Today it is an artful men's dance in traditional costume, often performed at folk festivals and cattle drives (Almabtriebe). The whip-cracking clubs keep the art alive to this day. Acoustically impressive, technically difficult — tradition with noise.",
  "saechsisch.s-112": "\"Hellerau\" on the outskirts of Dresden is the first German garden city (founded in 1909) — a global pioneer of modern housing reform. Architect: Richard Riemerschmid, the concept inspired by the English Garden City movement. The Festspielhaus was a meeting place for the European avant-garde: Mary Wigman, Émile Jaques-Dalcroze and Le Corbusier were guests here. Today it is a lively cultural centre and a listed quarter. A hidden gem of Saxony.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-115": "\"Lichtenstein Castle\" on the Swabian Alb (near Reutlingen) is the \"fairy-tale castle of Württemberg\" — built from 1840 to 1842 by Count Wilhelm von Württemberg, inspired by the novel \"Lichtenstein\" (1826) by Wilhelm Hauff. The neo-Gothic castle stands spectacularly on a 250 m high rocky spur above the Echaz valley (Albtal). It holds a collection of medieval weapons and armour. Today it is a tourist magnet and film backdrop. A Swabian Romantic classic.",
  "koelsch.k-134": "A \"Veedels-Sitzung\" is a traditional carnival session in a Cologne district (Veedel) — smaller, cosier and more grounded in the community than the big show sessions. Local bands, local carnival folk, local audience. Here the Cologne carnival shows itself in its genuine, unembellished form. Not a spectacle for tourists, but folk culture. Every Veedel has its own session.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-118": "The \"Reepschläger\" was the rope-maker in historical northern Germany — a craftsman who made ropes (\"Reep\") for ships. A very important trade in the port cities of Hamburg, Bremen and Lübeck. Hamburg's famous \"Reeperbahn\" got its name because the Reepschläger drew their long ropes here — that is why the street is so long and straight. Today an almost extinct trade. But the name lives on in Hamburg's entertainment district.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-120": "The \"Apéro\" is the Swiss institution before dinner — a relaxed get-together with wine, beer or champagne and small bites (cervelat slices, cheese cubes, savoury crackers). It derives from the French \"apéritif\" but is widespread throughout Switzerland. The \"Apéro riche\" (with a hearty buffet) often replaces dinner. No Swiss business, club or private celebration is complete without an Apéro.",
  "wienerisch.w-115": "The \"Hetz\" is, in Viennese, fun or amusement — from \"Hatz\" (a chase or hunt). \"A Hetz haben\" means to have a good time. \"A Mordshetz\" is enormous fun. \"Nur a Hetz\" excuses a prank. Viennese life philosophy: nothing should be taken too seriously, in the end everything is \"nur a Hetz\". Also in the phrase \"aus Hetz\" — for a laugh, for fun. A core word of the Viennese mentality.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-116": "The \"Handi\" is the Franconian, affectionately simplified form of the word \"Handy\" (mobile phone) — the English -y ending becomes the childlike -i ending. It shows how Franconian gently integrates modern anglicisms into the dialect. Even older generations say \"Handi\" — a linguistic softening of the sometimes hostile technology. The charm of Franconian sound-play meets modern life.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-120": "The Wuppertal Suspension Railway (Schwebebahn) is a technical sensation and the landmark of Wuppertal — opened in 1901, it travels 8 to 12 metres above the Wupper river. 13.3 km long, it is the oldest electric suspension railway system in the world. Wuppertal itself is regarded as the \"gateway to the Ruhr region\" — the Bergisches Land with a connection to the Pott. Tourists from all over the world come for the unique ride experience.",
  "alemannisch.al-120": "The Westweg is the classic among German long-distance hiking trails — opened in 1900 by the Schwarzwaldverein (Black Forest Association). 285 km from Pforzheim through the Black Forest to Basel, it crosses all the major Black Forest heights including the Feldberg and the Belchen. Waymarking: a yellow diamond on a white background. Classically ten stages, with overnight stays in Black Forest huts. One of the most beautiful long-distance trails in Europe. Whoever completes it is a true connoisseur of the Black Forest.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-107": "Da \"Gruschd\" is junk, clutter or useless stuff that piles up. \"Im Keller leit so viel alder Gruschd rum!\" (There's so much old Gruschd lying around in the cellar!). Related to \"Krempel\" (odds and ends). Whoever clears out throws away the Gruschd. Also \"Gruschdkischd\" for a box full of bric-a-brac. A typical Palatine word for all the things one doesn't really need anymore but keeps anyway. In the attic and the shed of every Palatine house there is plenty of Gruschd that outlasts generations.",
  "hessisch.h-154": "The Museumsufer on the Sachsenhausen bank of the Main is Frankfurt's cultural artery — 15 museums in the tightest of spaces: the Städel (paintings), the Liebieghaus (sculptures), the Communication Museum, the Film Museum, the Architecture Museum and more. A unique concentration of German cultural treasures. The annual \"Museumsuferfest\" draws 3 million visitors. Hesse's concentration of high culture.",
  "berlinisch.b-147": "On 26 June 1963, US President John F. Kennedy gave his famous speech at Schöneberg Town Hall with the sentence \"Ich bin ein Berliner\" — a declaration of solidarity with West Berlin, hemmed in by the Wall. 450,000 people cheered him. The cultural-historical significance of this moment is immeasurable. The famous \"Berliner = doughnut\" anecdote is, by the way, a myth — the speech was grammatically correct.",
  "bayerisch.by-128": "The \"Watzmann\", at 2,713 m, is the third-highest mountain in Germany and the main peak of the Berchtesgaden Alps. It is striking with its three-peaked massif above the Königssee. Legend tells of the cruel King Watzmann, who was turned to stone along with his family — the \"Watzmann family\" (smaller peaks) confirms this in popular belief. Deadly for many mountaineers (the Watzmann east face). A symbol of Bavaria like the Hofbräuhaus lettering. Also immortalised in Wolfgang Ambros's opera \"Der Watzmann ruft\".",
  "saechsisch.s-114": "The East German \"Ampelmännchen\" (little traffic-light man) — designed in 1961 by the traffic psychologist Karl Peglau — has become a cult symbol with its distinctive hat. After reunification it was to be abolished, but protest from East German citizens saved it. Today it is also used in western Germany and can be found on souvenirs, T-shirts and chocolate figures. A symbol of East German identity and a fond memory of the GDR — not everything was bad.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-116": "The \"Schwarzwald\" (Black Forest) is Germany's largest low mountain range — in the south-west of Baden-Württemberg. 160 km long, with dense fir forests, idyllic valleys, cuckoo clocks, Black Forest ham and Black Forest gateau. The Danube rises here. It is also immortalised in literature: the \"Schwarzwaldmädel\" films, Hebel's Alemannic poems. A tourist magnet — hiking, winter sports, wellness. Swabians and Badeners argue over whom the Black Forest belongs to. To both — but they will never admit it to each other.",
  "koelsch.k-135": "Tanzcorps (dance guards) are the traditional dance companies of the carnival societies — men and women in historical uniforms who perform demanding choreographies. The Rote Funken have their Tanzcorps, the Blaue Funken too. Getting into a Tanzcorps can be a life's ambition — the applications are tightly limited, the tradition is truly lived. At the Rose Monday parade they dance in rank and file.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-120": "The \"smartphone\" also has its own term in Low German — jokingly \"dat Daddelding\" (the fiddle-thing) or \"de Tüddelkasten\". Younger Low German speakers often simply adopt the English words. The older generation coins its own terms: \"Mien Daddelding piept ümmer\" — \"My smartphone keeps beeping\". Low German shows its vitality in dealing with modern technology through humorous adaptation.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-121": "The \"Tram\" is the streetcar in Zurich, Basel, Bern and Geneva — the standard Swiss urban means of transport. Punctual, clean, running at tight intervals — known for Swiss reliability. Zurich's VBZ and Basel's BVB are cornerstones of public transport. \"Mit em Tram zum Hauptbahnhof\" (Take the tram to the main station) — pure city daily life. The old trams (from the 1930s) still run today as a tourist attraction. Swiss pride in public transport.",
  "wienerisch.w-116": "Empress Elisabeth (1837–1898), nicknamed \"Sisi\" (or \"Sissi\", through the Romy Schneider films), was the beautiful, shy, eccentric wife of Emperor Franz Joseph I. Famous for her 1.50 m long hair, her 50 cm waist, her wanderlust and her tragic death by an anarchist's attack in Geneva. To this day a Viennese myth — the Sisi Museum in the Hofburg, Sisi cups and endless films. A Viennese cult.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-117": "In Franconia the car is taken especially seriously — one's own vehicle is status, identity and a passion. Nuremberg and Ingolstadt are automotive centres with MAN and Audi. Franconian men maintain their cars meticulously, wash them on Sundays and park them carefully in the garage. \"Mei Audi\" or \"mei Beemwehr\" (my BMW) is often referred to by a first name — almost like a member of the family. Proud pragmatism.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-121": "The rivalry between the Ruhrpott and Düsseldorf is legendary — the Pott folk see the people of Düsseldorf as arrogant, posh and conceited; the Düsseldorfers see the Pott as grey, uncouth and old-fashioned. Königsallee versus the Trinkhalle (kiosk). Fortuna versus BVB and Schalke. Altbier versus Pils. In football, in carnival, in lifestyle — the competition between the NRW metropolises is hearty.",
  "alemannisch.al-121": "The Mittelweg is, alongside the Westweg, the second classic Black Forest long-distance trail — 230 km from Pforzheim via Wildbad, Freudenstadt, Triberg and Hornberg to Schaffhausen at the Rhine Falls. Waymarking: a black-and-white diamond. Less demanding than the Westweg, but culturally richer — it passes through towns and historic places. It is also a work of the Schwarzwaldverein, dating from 1903. Family-friendly, well marked, with good infrastructure.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-108": "Da \"Worschtekessel\" is the large cauldron in which, at the home slaughter, the sausages are scalded and the soup is cooked. \"De Worschtekessel dampft schun, gleich gibt's frische Worscht!\" (The Worschtekessel is already steaming, fresh sausage coming up soon!). The centrepiece of the \"Metzeltag\" (slaughtering day), when the whole neighbourhood helps out and eats together. From the Worschtekessel come Saumagen, Bratwurst and the rich broth. A word that brings the rural slaughtering custom to life. It belongs to the hearty Palatine food culture and the village community.",
  "hessisch.h-155": "The Städel Museum on Frankfurt's Museumsufer is Germany's oldest civic art museum — founded in 1815 by Johann Friedrich Städel. Famous works: Tischbein's \"Goethe in the Roman Campagna\", Vermeer's \"The Geographer\", Botticelli, Rembrandt, Picasso, Beckmann. Over 380,000 visitors a year. The modernised building (extended in 2012) is architecturally impressive. The crown of Hessian culture.",
  "berlinisch.b-148": "\"Kotti\" — the Kottbusser Tor in Kreuzberg — is an infamous and cult Berlin hub: an underground station, traffic junction, drug hotspot and creative meeting point all at once. The \"Kotti\" is a symbol of the raw, unembellished, multicultural life of Kreuzberg. Here hipsters, Turkish families, junkies, tourists and punks all come together. Loved and hated by Berliners alike.",
  "bayerisch.by-129": "The \"Andechser\" beer comes from Andechs Monastery on the \"Holy Mountain\" above the Ammersee. The Benedictine monks have been brewing there since 1455 — to this day a pure Bavarian monastery beer made according to the purity law (Reinheitsgebot). The \"Doppelbock Dunkel\" (over 7%) and the wheat beer are well known. Andechs is a place of pilgrimage, a brewery and a tourist magnet all in one. \"Auf Andechs gehen\" means: hiking uphill, then stopping in at the monastery beer garden. A classic Bavarian Sunday outing.",
  "saechsisch.s-115": "\"Wahnsinn!\" (Madness!) — spoken in the Saxon sing-song — became a catchphrase during the Peaceful Revolution of 1989/90. Thousands of Saxons shouted it at the opening of the Wall, when they travelled to the West for the first time. Even earlier, in Leipzig: \"Wahnsinn, wir sind das Volk!\" (Madness, we are the people!). A symbol of the East German enthusiasm and bewilderment after the fall of the Wall. To this day a typically Saxon exclamation of joyful surprise.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-118": "\"Gscheid\" is an important all-purpose word in Swabian: clever, smart, sensible, proper, right. \"A gscheids Vesper\" is a proper snack. \"Schwätz net so gscheid!\" — don't talk so cleverly! \"Gscheidle\" is ironic — a smart aleck, a know-it-all. \"Net gscheid sei\" means \"to be not quite right in the head\". A Swabian all-rounder term with sub-meanings that outsiders rarely grasp in full.",
  "koelsch.k-136": "Tünnes and Schäl are the two main figures of the Cologne folk play and caricature — the fat, easy-going Tünnes and the thin, cunning Schäl. They embody the Cologne folk character with its wit, slyness and humour. Their anecdotes (\"Tünnes jokes\") are part of Cologne's cultural heritage. There are statues of them at the Eigelstein and in many Cologne pubs. They are Cologne on two legs.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-119": "The \"Elphi\" — the nickname for the Elbphilharmonie — is Hamburg's new landmark, opened in 2017 after 10 years of construction and a horrendous cost overrun (789 million instead of the planned 77 million). The architects were Herzog & de Meuron. On top of an old quayside warehouse, the wave-shaped glass façade rises 110 m high. The best concert acoustics in the world. The \"Plaza\" (37 m high) is freely accessible — a tourist magnet. A symbol of modern Hamburg.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-122": "The \"Putzfee\" (cleaning fairy) is the cleaner in Swiss German — a euphemistic and more positively connoted term than \"Putzfrau\" (cleaning woman). \"Mini Putzfee chunnt jede Mittwuch\" (My Putzfee comes every Wednesday) is Swiss middle-class everyday life. The term reflects the Swiss attitude: housework is respected, cleaners are served tea and chocolate (Schoggi). Often an honourable occupation for women from Eastern Europe or southern Italy. Swiss culture of politeness.",
  "wienerisch.w-117": "\"Tschuschn\" is a derogatory Viennese term for people from south-eastern Europe, especially the former Yugoslavia. The term is today rightly classified as racist, but has a complex history: some communities have reclaimed the word self-ironically. In the famous \"Tschuschen comedy\" the word is used satirically as a self-designation. A difficult past of the Viennese language.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-118": "The internet has also arrived in Franconia — the older generation often regards it with scepticism (\"Des hammer doch früher au ned braucht!\" — We didn't need that in the old days either!), the youth use it as a matter of course. Erlangen, with Siemens and the Friedrich-Alexander University, is an important IT location. The Franconian economy too (Schaeffler, Adidas, Puma) is digital. The tension between tradition and modernity shapes Franconian life.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-122": "Pott honesty is the most important virtue of the Ruhrpott dweller — no beating around the bush, no false smiles, no airs and graces. Whoever has something to say in the Pott says it straight to your face. That can sometimes come across as harsh, but it is meant as a sign of respect: you matter enough to me for the truth. This directness shapes every workplace, every pub, every family in the region.",
  "alemannisch.al-122": "Hiking is more than a sport in the Alemannic region — it is a philosophy of life. The Schwarzwaldverein, Black Forest tourism and countless hiking clubs keep the tradition alive. From the family stroll to Westweg trekking — every Badener hikes. Off you go with the Vesper rucksack (snack pack) and the hiking map. Mountain huts, snack rooms (Brotzeitstuben) and viewpoints are part of it. The Alemannic answer to the stress and hectic pace of modern life.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-109": "Da \"Bensel\" is the paintbrush — and, figuratively, a clumsy or conceited person. \"So a eigebildter Bensel, der meint, er kann alles!\" (Such a conceited Bensel, who thinks he can do everything!). From the High German \"Pinsel\" (brush) with Palatine pronunciation. Whoever is called \"a Bensel\" has either acted foolishly or shown off. Used affectionately and mockingly among acquaintances. Another example of the Palatine fondness for turning everyday objects into nicknames for people. It sounds harsher than it is meant.",
  "hessisch.h-156": "The Goethe House on the Großer Hirschgraben is Goethe's birthplace — he was born on 28 August 1749. Destroyed in the war, it was faithfully reconstructed. Today it is a museum with Goethe's original furniture. The adjacent Goethe Museum showcases his influence. A place of pilgrimage for lovers of German literature. Hesse's proudest son — even though Goethe spent more time in Weimar than in Frankfurt.",
  "berlinisch.b-149": "The „Görli\" — Görlitzer Park in Kreuzberg — is Berlin's most notorious park: created after reunification on a former railway site, it is today a meeting point for families, drug dealers and police. Despite its reputation, it is a lively piece of Kreuzberg reality — multicultural, chaotic and vibrant. The „Görli debate\" about security and social peace is a perennial Berlin topic.",
  "bayerisch.by-130": "The „Hofbräuhaus\" am Platzl in Munich is the most famous beer hall in the world. Founded in 1589 by Duke Wilhelm V, it was opened to the public in 1828. „In München steht ein Hofbräuhaus\" — everyone knows the song. Three floors, a taproom (Schwemme) with 1,300 seats, a brass band, giant litre steins — a tourist magnet and a symbol of the Bavarian way of life. Lenin drank here (supposedly), Mozart composed here. More show than genuine Munich dining — but culturally indispensable.",
  "saechsisch.s-116": "„Bautz'ner Senf\" is THE East German mustard — founded in 1834 in Bautzen. Very hot, bright yellow, medium-coarse — an unmistakable flavour profile. It is eaten with sausage, pork knuckle and Bockwurst. In the East, West German „Düsseldorfer Senf\" eaters are eyed with suspicion. The brand survived reunification thanks to East German brand loyalty. Today it is sold nationwide, but it has remained a cultural symbol of East Germany.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-119": "The „Mostbirne\" is the Swabian-Allgäu cider pear — small, tart pear varieties unfit for eating but yielding excellent cider (Most). A tradition of standard-trunk trees on the Swabian orchard meadows (Streuobstwiesen). Today a UNESCO-worthy cultural heritage of the region. „Mostbirnenfest\" is held in many villages. The Swabian says with pride: „Aus a Mostbirne kann ma nur Most mache!\" — from a cider pear you can only make cider! — and cider is a national speciality.",
  "koelsch.k-137": "The „Heinzelmännchen zu Köln\" are little gnomes from the Cologne legend — at night they secretly helped the craftsmen and townspeople, until a curious tailor's wife scared them away. Ever since, the people of Cologne have had to do everything themselves. A famous legend that August Kopisch turned into a poem in 1836. The Heinzelmännchen monument on the Eigelstein commemorates it. A secret wish: their help.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-121": "„Friesenstolz\" is the pronounced self-confidence of the East Frisians, North Frisians and Saterland Frisians — coupled with a certain stubbornness (also meant positively). „En echte Fries gifft nich op\" — a true Frisian never gives up. It is rooted in the centuries-old tradition of „Frisian Freedom\" — the Frisians were long subject to no feudal lord. To this day it is a tangible mark of identity in the marshland regions. A virtue, not a quirk.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-123": "The „Gotthard\" is the most famous Alpine pass in Switzerland — 2,106 m high, linking German- and Italian-speaking Switzerland. Strategically central since the Middle Ages. Today there are three tunnels: the railway tunnel (1882), the road tunnel (1980) and the Gotthard Base Tunnel (2016, at 57 km the longest railway tunnel in the world). On the pass stands the famous Suvorov monument — a symbol of Swiss engineering and history.",
  "wienerisch.w-118": "The Viennese „Hochzeitsuppe\" (wedding soup) is a clear beef broth with special garnishes: Frittaten (sliced pancakes), liver dumplings, marrow dumplings, fried peas (Backerbsen) — all served together. Classically for weddings or festive occasions. It goes back to the imperial-royal (k.u.k.) wedding tradition. Several garnishes can also be combined in an ordinary Sunday soup — the Viennese then call it „Hochzeitsuppe\" too. A classic of Viennese festive cuisine.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-119": "Volker Heißmann (b. 1969) is one of the best-known Franconian cabaret artists — as „Waltraud Heißmann\" in women's clothing he performs with his partner Martin Rassau at the Comödie Fürth. Winner of the Bavarian Cabaret Prize and the German Kleinkunstpreis. His boulevard-style humour, with Franconian dialect and the art of disguise, has been filling theatres for over 25 years. A symbol of the lively Franconian entertainment culture.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-123": "In the Pott, „Schnauze\" (gob/mouth) is direct, unvarnished speech — a famous character trait. „Die hat ne Schnauze!\" is a compliment: the person tells it like it is. „Schnauze halten!\" is also a coarse demand to be quiet. Whoever knows how to use their Schnauze in the Pott earns respect. With your Schnauze you survive down the coal seam and at the steelworks.",
  "alemannisch.al-123": "The Loipe is the prepared cross-country skiing trail — in the Hochschwarzwald there are over 1,000 km of groomed Loipen. Classic diagonal and skating tracks. The Hochschwarzwald Tourism Association coordinates their maintenance. Classic Loipe areas: Hinterzarten, Schluchsee, Bernau, Notschrei. In February the Schwarzwald Marathon takes place — 100 km on skis. Cross-country skiing is an Alemannic popular sport, from kindergarten children to seniors.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-110": "The „Herrgottswinkel\" (Lord's corner) is the devout corner of the farmhouse parlour with a crucifix and often a holy-water font. „Im Herrgottswinkel hängt s'alde Kreuz vun de Urgroßeltern.\" — in the Lord's corner hangs the old cross of the great-grandparents. Traditionally the corner opposite the door, where the family prayed. It reflects the Catholic character of large parts of the Palatinate. Today often preserved only as a keepsake, but still found in old farms. A classic word from the religious customs and domestic culture of the rural Palatinate.",
  "hessisch.h-157": "The Frankfurt School is a philosophical movement — emerging at the Institute for Social Research, founded in 1923. Adorno, Horkheimer, Marcuse and Habermas were its main figures. „Critical Theory\" continues to shape sociology, political science and philosophy worldwide. Frankfurt was an intellectual centre — making Hesse a place of global intellectual significance. Students still make pilgrimages to the IfS today.",
  "berlinisch.b-151": "The Victory Column (Siegessäule) at the Großer Stern in the Tiergarten is, at 67 m, Berlin's best-known landmark — erected in 1873 to commemorate the Prussian victories. The „Goldelse\" — the gilded Victoria statue on its top — is a Berlin postcard classic. 285 steps lead to the observation platform with its panoramic view. It was a main location in the Love Parade soundtrack of the 1990s. Also a filming location for „Wings of Desire\".",
  "bayerisch.by-131": "The „Marienplatz\" has been the pulsating heart of Munich since 1158 — marketplace, gathering place and tourist magnet in one. Named after the Marian column (Mariensäule, 1638), erected in thanks for being spared the Swedish siege during the Thirty Years' War. Here stand the New Town Hall (with the famous Glockenspiel that gathers tourists daily at 11 a.m. and noon) and the Old Town Hall. When FC Bayern triumphs, hundreds of thousands of fans celebrate here. The centre of Munich identity.",
  "saechsisch.s-117": "The „Heidschnucke\" is an old breed of sheep that originally grazes on the Lüneburg Heath but also occurs in Saxon heathlands. Robust, undemanding, with a grey-brown wool fleece and twisting horns. It keeps the heath short and rich in biodiversity — a symbol of sustainable landscape management. Heidschnucke meat is a delicacy with a strong flavour. Popular in slow-food restaurants.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-120": "The „Goggolore\" or „Gockel\" is the rooster in Swabian — the symbol of the farmyard and rural romance. „Im Dorf kräht no a Goggolore\" — a rooster still crows in the village — epitomises rural idyll. It is also used figuratively for puffed-up, vain men: „Der is a Goggolore\" — he's a pompous show-off. A Swabian animal image with a double meaning. Affectionately ironic.",
  "koelsch.k-138": "„Eau de Cologne\" — Kölnisch Wasser — is one of the oldest perfumes in the world, invented in Cologne in 1709 by Johann Maria Farina. „4711\" is the house number on the Glockengasse where production took place. A brand over 300 years old. A fresh, citrusy fragrance. In the Middle Ages it was used as a remedy. Today it is marketed worldwide as a Cologne souvenir — the 4711 buildings are landmarks in Cologne.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-122": "The „Heesterhuus\" is a traditional North German farmhouse with the characteristic porch („Heester\") — an entrance area with steps under a covered canopy. It protects from rain and wind and is a social meeting point in front of the house. Found mainly in Schleswig-Holstein and the Emsland. Architecture adapted to the weather of the coast. Pure heritage-protection idyll.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-124": "The „Banker\" is a traditional profession in Switzerland with high social status — especially in Zurich, Geneva and Lugano. UBS and Credit Suisse (before its 2023 collapse) operated worldwide. Swiss bankers stand for discretion (the famous „banking secrecy\", now eroded), precision and reserve. The cliché: a subdued suit, a groomed appearance, polite distance. A Swiss identity marker with an ambivalent reputation.",
  "wienerisch.w-119": "The „Wuiderer\" is, in Austrian folk belief and folk songs, a romanticised figure — the poacher who steals the game from the nobility or the state. In songs like „Es war einmal ein Jäger\" or „Wildschütz Jennerwein\" he is celebrated as a folk hero. In real life, poaching was long a capital crime, punishable by the gallows. Today it is a purely folkloric motif in songs and films.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-120": "Wolfgang Lippert (b. 1952 in Plauen) is admittedly a native Saxon, but through decades of appearances he has become a fixture of the Franconian entertainment world. „Erna kommt!\" became a hit. As a show host and Schlager singer he shaped Franconian television. Today he is often seen at folk festivals and in beer tents. His down-to-earth style suits the Franconian mentality — no airs, just folksiness.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-124": "The Ruhrpott mentality combines directness, warmth, solidarity and pragmatism. Shaped by hard work underground and at the steelworks, by migration from Poland and Italy, by structural crises and reconstruction. Pott people help one another, grumble about everything and still mean well. Whoever has once experienced Pott mentality knows: it's not about money, but about dignity and community.",
  "alemannisch.al-124": "At 1,414 metres, the Belchen is the second-highest mountain in the southern Black Forest after the Feldberg — one of the finest panoramic summits in Germany. In clear weather you can see the entire Alpine chain from Mont Blanc to the Zugspitze, the Vosges and the Swiss Jura. Reachable by the Belchen cable car. A sacred mountain of the Celts — its name comes from the Celtic sun god „Belenus\". Solstice fires burn here at the summer solstice.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-111": "A „Schlappschwanz\" is a coward or a spineless weakling who lacks courage and drive. „Sei kää Schlappschwanz un trau dich endlich!\" — don't be a wimp and finally dare to do it! From „schlapp\" (limp) and „Schwanz\" (tail). Said to someone who doesn't dare or gives up quickly. Meant affectionately egging-on or mockingly. In the down-to-earth Palatinate, where pitching in counts during work in the vineyard (Wengerd), the Schlappschwanz holds little regard. A classic insult meant to spur on courage and perseverance.",
  "hessisch.h-158": "St. Paul's Church (Paulskirche) in Frankfurt is the „cradle of German democracy\" — here, in 1848/49, the first German parliament of the National Assembly convened. The Frankfurt Constitution was drafted here (even though it failed). Today it is a hall of honour and a symbol of democracy. The federal government and the Bundestag gather here for important occasions. Hesse is the birthplace of democracy.",
  "berlinisch.b-152": "The Bötzow Brewery in Prenzlauer Berg was one of the most famous Berlin breweries of the 19th century — founded in 1864, shut down in 1949. Today the brewery site is a monument to Berlin's industrial culture. There are plans to reopen it. Berlin once had hundreds of breweries — today only a few remain (Berliner Kindl, Berliner Pilsner, Schultheiss).",
  "bayerisch.by-132": "„BMW\" — Bayerische Motoren Werke — founded in 1916 in Munich as an aircraft-engine manufacturer. Today one of the most prestigious car companies in the world. The blue-and-white logo recalls a spinning propeller against a Bavarian sky. The BMW Tower (the „Four-Cylinder\") and BMW Welt at the Olympic Park are Munich landmarks. „A BMW fahrn\" — to drive a BMW — is considered the status symbol par excellence in Bavaria. Munich's largest private employer. Bavarian industrial pride.",
  "saechsisch.s-118": "In Saxon, „Mucke\" has two meanings: firstly, the insect (Mücke, mosquito/midge) — „die Mucken zwicken wieder!\" — the midges are biting again! Secondly, slang for a job, gig or engagement — especially in the music scene. „A Mucke spielen\" means to perform a gig. „Eine schöne Mucke\" is a good, well-paid job. Also figuratively: a minor occupation or side job. A special word of the Saxon-Thuringian musician and artist scene.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-121": "The „Muggaseggele\" is the smallest Swabian unit of measure — a tiny droplet, a touch, a hint. „A Muggaseggele Salz\" is a very small pinch. Literally „the member of a male housefly\" — a drastically comical coinage documented since the 19th century. In 2009 it was voted the „most beautiful Swabian word\". Swabian understatement art at its purest. The epitome of Swabian linguistic creativity.",
  "koelsch.k-139": "The „Kölner Lichter\" (Cologne Lights) are Germany's biggest pyrotechnic spectacle — held annually on 12 July. 35 minutes of synchronised fireworks over the Rhine, accompanied by music. Over 800,000 spectators line the banks. The ships sail in an illuminated convoy. The Kölner Lichter are the highlight of summer and a magnet for tourists. The best experience: from the Rheinauhafen or the Hohenzollern Bridge.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-123": "The „Heimatleed\" — the North German homeland song — is an expression of deep attachment to the North, the sea and the land. Famous examples: „Wo de Nordseewellen trecken an den Strand\", „Schleswig-Holstein meerumschlungen\", „An de Eck steiht'n Jung mit'n Tüddelband\". They are sung at weddings, funerals and during Klönschnack (cosy chats). A source of identification despite modern beats and streaming services.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-125": "The „Heimatgfühl\" is the deeply rooted Swiss identification with one's home town, canton and the whole of Switzerland. It is triggered by the sound of the alphorn, the sight of the mountains, the first sip of Rivella after a trip abroad, or the voice of Roger Federer. Despite its diverse language regions, the Swiss sense of homeland is surprisingly strong — united by federalism, direct democracy and shared values. More than nostalgia: a lived identity.",
  "wienerisch.w-120": "„Herr Ober\" is the respectful form of address for the Viennese waiter — obligatory in the coffee house and restaurant. Viennese waiters are often quick-witted, gruffly charming and regarded as the epitome of „Wiener Schmäh\" (Viennese wit). „Herr Ober, zahlen!\" — Waiter, the bill! — is standard. Famous sayings of Viennese waiters have been immortalised in aphorisms. The pastry chef is called „Frau Konditorin\", the waitress „Frau Ober\" — Viennese etiquette.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-121": "The „Drud\" (or „Trude\") is, in Franconian folk legends, an evil spirit or witch who sits at night on the chest of sleeping people and causes nightmares. A folk belief from the Middle Ages, long alive in Franconian villages. „Druddrücken\" describes the feeling of sleep paralysis. Protection was provided by Drudenfuß symbols (the pentagram) on doors. Legendary motifs from Franconian folk belief.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-125": "In the Ruhrpott, a „Halbacht\" is someone who is not quite all there — a bit eccentric, odd or not quite right in the head. The term probably comes from a time reading („halb acht\" = half past seven, i.e. not full, not right). A mild insult, meant more head-shaking than hurtful. In the Pott there are plenty of Halbachte — characters everyone in the neighbourhood knows and who are part of the local colour.",
  "alemannisch.al-125": "The Dorotheenhütte in Wolfach is the last active mouth-blown glassworks in the Black Forest — in operation since 1947. Visitors can watch the glassmakers at work: at the 1,400-degree melting furnace, glass is blown into drinking glasses, vases and Christmas tree decorations. A tradition going back more than 800 years. Wolfach glass art is a collector's item, and the glass village shows three centuries of history. Hands-on industrial heritage.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-112": "The „Bredschler\" is the pretzel baker or pretzel seller who hawks his wares at festivals. „De Bredschler kummt, hol uns a paar frische Brezle!\" — the pretzel seller is coming, fetch us a few fresh pretzels! The „Bredsel\" (pretzel) is, in the Palatinate as everywhere in the south, a staple food. At the Kerwe (fair), the Wurstmarkt and the weekly market, the Bredschler makes his rounds with a basket or stall. A traditional trade that belongs to the festive bustle. A classic word from the Palatinate market and baking culture, closely tied to Schorle and conviviality.",
  "hessisch.h-159": "The „Hessenstreich\" is a humorous term for Hessian originality, often with a wink: whoever pulls off a Hessenstreich has done something typically Hessian — shrewd in a rustic way, honest and direct, with local pride. The Hessians are known for their directness and their humour, which is sometimes subversive. There have been many political Hessenstreiche in the state's history.",
  "berlinisch.b-154": "The Schaubühne in Charlottenburg is Berlin's second internationally celebrated theater — directed since 1999 by Thomas Ostermeier. Housed in a former Bauhaus cinema on the Kurfürstendamm. Famous for modern stagings of the classics (Ibsen, Shakespeare). Guest performances all over the world. Tours to New York, Tokyo, São Paulo. Berlin stagecraft at world-class level.",
  "bayerisch.by-133": "The \"Siemensianer\" is an employee of the Siemens corporation, headquartered in Munich. Werner von Siemens founded the company in Berlin in 1847; since 1953 Munich has been its headquarters. Siemens stands for German engineering — energy, medical technology, mobility. In Munich with its striking main building at the Wittelsbacherplatz. Working \"at Siemens\" is traditionally considered secure and prestigious. A Bavarian economic heavyweight alongside BMW and Audi.",
  "saechsisch.s-119": "Martin Luther (1483–1546) worked in Wittenberg, yet he shaped all of Saxony — the Reformation began in 1517 at the Castle Church in Wittenberg, then part of the Saxon Electorate. Luther translated the Bible at the Wartburg and preached in Leipzig and Dresden. His protector was Frederick the Wise of Saxony. Without Saxon support, the Reformation would have failed. A Saxon legacy of global significance — UNESCO World Heritage.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-122": "The \"Großmuatter\" or \"Oma\" (grandmother) is, in Swabia as everywhere, the beloved family elder — but in Swabia especially associated with Spätzle-making skill, Kehrwoche (cleaning-rota) discipline and the art of crocheting. \"Oma's Spätzle\" is the ultimate praise, \"Oma's Maultaschen\" something sacred. Swabian grandmothers pass on values and recipes across generations. They are called \"Großmuatter\", \"Großmama\" or simply \"Oma\". A family anchor with mountains of Vesper (snacks).",
  "koelsch.k-140": "The Cologne Marathon has been held every October since 1997 — 25,000 runners, 200,000 spectators. The route runs through the most beautiful parts of Cologne: the Cathedral, the Hohenzollern Bridge, the Rheinauhafen, Kalk and back. The Berlin and Frankfurt marathons are bigger, but the Cologne Marathon has that carnival character — colorful, warm-hearted, with music on every corner. Cologne sports culture.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-124": "The \"Bötel\" is a northern German specialty: cured and boiled pork knuckle, classically served with braised cabbage (Schmorkohl/sauerkraut) and pea purée. The Berlin version is called \"Eisbein\"; in Schleswig-Holstein and Mecklenburg it is \"Bötel\". It is offered as a winter dish in every northern German tavern. Hearty, calorie-rich, suited to cold north-wind days. A classic of northern German home cooking — nobody leaves the table hungry.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-126": "\"Wilhelm Tell\" is the legendary Swiss national hero from Uri who, according to legend, shot the apple off his son's head with an arrow in 1307. Friedrich Schiller's drama (1804) made him world-famous. Historically probably a myth, but identity-forming for the Confederation. A symbol of freedom, courage and resistance against tyranny (the bailiff Gessler). The Tell monument stands in Altdorf, and the Tell plays are performed every year in Interlaken and Altdorf. The Swiss founding myth par excellence.",
  "wienerisch.w-121": "The \"Krügerl\" is, in the Austrian beer vocabulary, half a liter of beer — the standard measure in the Beisl (pub). Unlike the Bavarian \"Maß\" (1 liter) or the German \"großes Bier\" (0.4–0.5 l), the Krügerl is exactly 0.5 liters. \"A Seidl\" (0.3 l) is the smaller version, \"a Pfiff\" (0.1 l) the mini beer. Viennese beer-speak has its own precision — whoever orders just \"a beer\" is taken for a tourist.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-122": "The \"Wilde Jagd\" (Wild Hunt) is a central myth in Franconian folk belief — a ghostly hunting procession that moves across the fields at night, led by \"Wodan\" or the Devil. Whoever meets it is said to suffer misfortune or be swept away. The legend is still alive in the Frankenwald, Steigerwald and Spessart. Passed down from grandparents to grandchildren. Today's heavy-metal bands and folklorists keep the motif alive.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-126": "Wattenscheid has been a district of Bochum since 1975 — but the Wattenscheiders themselves see it differently: \"We're Wattenscheiders, not Bochumers!\" Its own town center, its own history, its own football tradition (SG Wattenscheid 09, once in the Bundesliga). The 1975 incorporation remains a source of local patriotism to this day. Anyone who grows up in Wattenscheid stresses their distinct origin. Classic Ruhr-area pride in the district.",
  "alemannisch.al-126": "The Triberg Waterfalls in Triberg in the Black Forest are, at 163 meters high (over seven cascades), the highest natural waterfalls in Germany. The Gutach plunges through a wooded granite gorge. A tourist magnet in summer, magical in winter with icicles. The trail is well developed, with viewpoints and the chance to get almost right up to the waterfall. The squirrels come astonishingly close — they're used to visitors.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-113": "\"Owacht!\" is the warning \"Achtung!\" (Watch out!) or \"Pass auf!\" (Be careful!) — derived from \"Obacht\". \"Owacht, de Karre kummt!\" (Watch out, the cart's coming!) It is shouted to warn someone of danger or urge caution. Also \"gib Owacht!\" (be careful). A short, pithy Palatine warning cry that rings out in everyday life, on the street and at work. Part of the practical everyday vocabulary and uttered emphatically when things have to happen fast and caution is called for.",
  "hessisch.h-160": "The Wetterau is a fertile plain north of Frankfurt — the \"granary of Hesse\". Known for sugar beet, wheat, onions and, more recently, asparagus. Bad Vilbel, Friedberg and Butzbach are its main towns. The Wetterauers are known as down-to-earth and friendly. Geologically interesting: limestone-rich soils with groundwater that feeds mineral-water springs (Vilbel water).",
  "berlinisch.b-155": "The Babelsberg film studio in Potsdam (just outside Berlin) is the oldest film studio in the world — founded in 1912. It was here that \"Metropolis\" (Fritz Lang) and \"The Blue Angel\" (with Marlene Dietrich) were made, and today Hollywood productions such as \"Inglourious Basterds\" and \"Matrix Resurrections\". Tom Cruise, Quentin Tarantino and George Clooney shoot here. Babelsberg is the German Hollywood.",
  "bayerisch.by-134": "\"Bavarian humor\" is dry, direct, often crude and loves the double meaning. Karl Valentin and Liesl Karlstadt shaped Munich wit early on, later Gerhard Polt, Bully Herbig and the \"Goldene Zitronen\". Unlike northern German sarcasm or Viennese Schmäh, Bavarian humor is earthy, often with a tavern scene. Loriot too (born in Brandenburg, but Bavarian by choice) shaped the subtle mockery. Bavarian laughter is usually mixed with a knowing smile.",
  "saechsisch.s-120": "The \"Klempner\" is, in Saxon usage, the sanitary fitter (plumber) — unlike in Standard German, where it tends to mean a sheet-metal worker. \"Calling the Klempner\" when a pipe bursts is everyday Saxon life. A classic East German trade, often a family tradition. \"Klempner jokes\" — about the ever-late, expensive tradesmen — are Saxon cabaret material. A profession with high social standing, but a complicated reputation.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-123": "The \"Wachturm\" (watchtower) or \"Türmer\" (tower-keeper) is still a living tradition in many small Swabian towns: in Esslingen, Schwäbisch Hall and Nürtingen, tower trumpeters still call out from the town tower on festive occasions to this day. The Esslingen castle gate with its bell and watchman's house is the emblem of the fortified burghers' town. \"Climbing the watchtower\" — a Swabian tradition since the Middle Ages. Swabian custom lives on in towers too.",
  "koelsch.k-141": "A famous Cologne carnival phrase — it's called out while the beer is still flowing. \"Mer han noch lang nit geneuch jesoffe\" (\"We haven't drunk nearly enough yet\") is a friendly, encouraging toast, not a duty to drink. Cologne drinking culture is social, not extreme. The phrase is also used ironically, when you actually don't want any more at all. Carnival in its own Cologne way.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-125": "The \"Hering\" (herring) — in Low German \"Heering\" — has been the most important food fish of the North since the Middle Ages. The Hanseatic League grew rich on the herring trade with Scandinavia. It is prepared in numerous varieties: Matjes, Bismarck herring, Rollmops, fried herring, herring in cream. The \"herring market\" was once the most important trading tradition. Also figuratively: \"Pack di wie en Hering\" (packed like herrings) — crammed tightly together. A North German heritage of fish culture.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-127": "\"Heidi\" — Johanna Spyri's fictional character (1880) — is the world-famous Swiss mountain girl who grows up with the Alpöhi (Alpine grandfather) on the mountain pasture. A story of homesickness, love of the mountains and friendship with Peter and Klara. Translated into over 70 languages, filmed many times (the legendary 1974 anime, a new feature film in 2015). Heidiland in the Toggenburg/Maienfeld region is a tourist spot. Heidi shapes the international image of Switzerland more strongly than any tourism campaign. Naive mountain romance as a Swiss export.",
  "wienerisch.w-122": "The real \"Wiener Schnitzel\" must be made from veal — anything else is \"Schnitzel Wiener Art\" (Viennese-style schnitzel) and a sacrilege. Pounded thin, breaded with flour, egg and fine breadcrumbs, fried in plenty of clarified butter so that it \"souffles\" (forms waves). Classically served with parsley potatoes, potato salad and a slice of lemon. A dispute over origin: Milan vs. Vienna. A UNESCO-worthy piece of Viennese cultural heritage. A must on any visit to Vienna.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-123": "The Spessart is a low mountain range in western Lower Franconia — Germany's densest oak and beech forests. Notorious through Wilhelm Hauff's \"Wirtshaus im Spessart\" (The Inn in the Spessart) and the historical robber bands. Today a nature park with quiet valleys, castle ruins and hiking trails. Mespelbrunn, Lohr and Aschaffenburg are the most important Spessart towns. The Schweinfurt economy historically profited from Spessart timber.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-127": "The Ruhrfestspielhaus in Recklinghausen is one of the most important theaters in the Ruhr area — home of the Ruhrfestspiele, which have been held since 1947. They were founded as a thank-you to the miners who, in the winter of 1946, traded coal for theater performances — art for warmth. Today it is a renowned festival with an international program. A symbol of the union of working-class culture and high culture in the Ruhr. Festival time is May to June.",
  "alemannisch.al-127": "The Schwarzwaldhochstraße (B 500) runs 60 km from Baden-Baden to Freudenstadt along the ridge of the northern Black Forest — one of the most beautiful panoramic roads in Germany. Laid out as a tourist route in 1932. Viewpoints: Hohe Möser, Mummelsee, Hornisgrinde, Schliffkopf. Winter sports areas in winter. Famous hotels such as the Bühler Hof or the Schliffkopfhotel. In clear weather you can see the Vosges, the Alps and the Rhine valley. A classic bus and motorcycle tour.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-114": "The \"Schwoowe\" are the Swabians — the southern neighbor the Palatine likes to tease. \"Die Schwoowe sin' arg sparsam, hääßt's immer!\" (The Swabians are awfully thrifty, so they say!) Like the teasing of the Hessians, the good-natured mockery of the Swabians is part of the regional local color. It's about the proverbial Swabian thrift and tinkering. Rarely truly ill-meant, more a wink of the eye. It reflects the strong Palatine regional consciousness and the friendly rivalry among neighboring regions.",
  "hessisch.h-161": "The Hessische Bergstraße is a small wine region on the eastern edge of the Rhine plain between Darmstadt and Heppenheim — a very mild climate thanks to the shelter of the Mainz lowlands. The Bergstraße is \"Germany's spring garden\" — almond trees blossom here first, followed by fruit trees. The wines: Riesling, Müller-Thurgau and Burgunder. Heppenheim and Bensheim are the wine centers.",
  "berlinisch.b-156": "The Potsdamer Platz was Europe's busiest square in 1920, completely destroyed in the war, and in the GDR it lay in the death strip of the Wall. After reunification one of Europe's biggest building projects took place — today's skyline with the Sony Center, DB Tower and Beisheim Center. Today a tourist magnet, but also an object of Berlin love-hate: too modern, too artificial. Nevertheless a symbol of Berlin's reconstruction.",
  "bayerisch.by-135": "The \"Heimatfilm\" is a typically Bavarian-Austrian genre of the postwar period. Stars like Hans Albers, Heinz Rühmann and above all Hansi Hinterseer rode through the Alps, sang folk songs and rescued dairymaids. Its heyday was in the 1950s and 60s. Today often smiled at (think \"Schwarzwaldklinik\" or \"Forsthaus Falkenau\"), but culturally formative for Bavaria. Edgar Reitz's \"Heimat\" trilogy too shows a different level. A world of feeling between mountain peak, Tracht (folk costume) and longing.",
  "saechsisch.s-121": "The \"Bergmännel\" is an Ore Mountains wooden figure in a miner's uniform — a symbol of the centuries-old mining tradition in Saxony. Together with the \"Engel\" (angel, a symbol of the women waiting at home), it is set up as a light-bearer at Christmas time. It recalls the era when ore mining flourished in Annaberg, Schneeberg and Freiberg. UNESCO World Heritage \"Erzgebirge/Krušnohoří Mining Region\".",
  "schwaebisch.sw-124": "The \"Bodensee\" (Lake Constance) — also called the \"Swabian Sea\" — is Germany's largest lake and the third largest in Central Europe. The border between Germany, Austria and Switzerland. Famous for the island of Mainau (flower island), the monastery island of Reichenau (UNESCO World Heritage) and the stilt dwellings of Unteruhldingen. Konstanz and Friedrichshafen are the largest German lakeside towns. A holiday paradise with an Alpine panorama. A Swabian piece of water identity.",
  "koelsch.k-142": "\"Niemols allein\" (Never alone) is a song by the Höhner — and at the same time a Cologne attitude to life: in Cologne, no one is alone. The sense of community, the cohesion of the Veedel (neighborhood), the carnival tradition — everything fosters connection. \"Niemols allein\" is also a promise: whoever lives in Kölle always has people around them who will take them in. Cologne solidarity in a single sentence.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-126": "St. Peter-Ording on the North Frisian west coast is one of Germany's most popular North Sea resorts — famous for its 12 km long, 2 km wide sandy beach and its iconic stilt-house restaurants. The German championships in beach sailing and kitesurfing are held here. Over 3 million overnight stays per year. The Ording district has preserved its character as a fishing village. A North German beach paradise par excellence.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-128": "The \"Rütlischwur\" (Rütli Oath) on the Rütli meadow on Lake Lucerne is regarded as the founding act of the Confederation in 1291. The envoys of the original cantons Uri, Schwyz and Unterwalden swore the Eternal Alliance against the Habsburgs. Friedrich Schiller immortalized the scene in Wilhelm Tell. On August 1 (the national holiday) the Rütli meadow becomes a place of pilgrimage. Political speeches, mountain bonfires, the ringing of bells. The Federal Council pays an official visit. More symbol than historically documented — but formative for Swiss self-understanding.",
  "wienerisch.w-124": "The \"Pülcher\" is, in Viennese, a petty crook, an idler, a small-time criminal — a Viennese specification of the \"Strizzi\". Half shabby, half charming — part of Viennese folklore like the sausage stand. In the 19th century a real social type — today more of a literary figure. Helmut Qualtinger played the Pülcher in many sketches. Viennese Schmäh in its coarsest form.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-124": "The Franconian Brotzeit (cold snack/meal) is a sacred ritual — usually in the afternoon or evening. Farmhouse bread, Franconian Bratwurst, Pressack, Leberkäs, cheese, gherkins, mustard, pickled onions. With it a Seidla of cellar beer or a Schoppen of Franconian wine. In summer in the tavern garden, in winter in the parlor. More than a meal — a social event, family time, pleasure. Taken for granted in every Franconian tavern.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-128": "Mülheim an der Ruhr lies between Duisburg and Essen, right on the Ruhr — with 170,000 inhabitants one of the smaller Ruhr cities, but with its own character. Headquarters of Aldi Süd (the parent house of the Albrecht brothers), the Camera Obscura in the water tower, the Theater an der Ruhr. Somewhat more upscale than other Ruhr cities, considered the \"green city on the river\". By Ruhr standards, the Mülheimers come across as more genteel — which earns them friendly mockery.",
  "alemannisch.al-128": "The \"Hornberger Schießen\" (the Hornberg shooting) is a proverb for a grandly announced affair that begins with pomp but ends pitifully. In 1564 Hornberg, in the Kinzig valley, wanted to greet the Duke of Württemberg with salute cannons — when the scouts reported the dust of a carriage, they fired off all their supplies. But it was only a cattle cart. When the Duke actually arrived, there was no powder left. \"That ends like the Hornberger Schießen\" is a German proverb to this day. The Hornberg local festival commemorates it.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-115": "The \"Buddik\" is a small shop or store — from the French \"boutique\". \"Geh schnell in die Buddik un hol a Pund Mehl!\" (Quick, go to the shop and get a pound of flour!) Again a French loanword in Palatine everyday life. It means the little corner shop, not the big department store. Also used slightly disparagingly for a disorderly establishment: \"a komische Buddik\" (a strange little outfit). Once more it shows the deep French influence on the dialect. Part of the everyday Palatine vocabulary around shopping.",
  "hessisch.h-163": "Friedrichsdorf in the Taunus is famous for its Zwieback (rusk) tradition — the Brandt Zwieback factory has produced the famous Brandt Zwieback here since 1912. Also famous: the Philanthropinum (an 18th-century educational institution). The town was founded in 1687 by French Huguenots fleeing religious persecution. A piece of Hessian history of tolerance.",
  "berlinisch.b-157": "The Sony Center with its distinctive glass dome is the main attraction at the Potsdamer Platz — opened in 2000. Architect: Helmut Jahn. The forum with its fountains and the self-supporting, light-flooded dome is a landmark. Until 2017 Sony Europe had its headquarters here. Today office towers, restaurants and the film museum. An architectural symbol of modern Berlin.",
  "bayerisch.by-136": "The \"Maibaumstehlen\" (maypole stealing) is a central custom before May 1st. Young lads from the neighbouring village try to \"steal\" the maypole before it is raised — usually at night, sometimes with great effort. If the tree is captured, the home village must redeem it with beer and a Brotzeit (snack). Strict unwritten rules apply: the tree may only be guarded, not defended with force. More theatre than theft — pure Bavarian custom-play with centuries-old tradition.",
  "saechsisch.s-122": "Riesa on the Elbe is a medium-sized Saxon town — known as the \"city of steel and pasta works\". This is where the famous \"Riesa noodle\" is produced (even though the company has long been part of a corporation). A sports town with tradition: SC Riesa (ice hockey), but also sadly famous as the location of the NPD's federal headquarters. The industrial history of Saxon provincial towns between GDR heritage and the present.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-125": "The \"Heimatgfühl\" (sense of home) is the deeply rooted Swabian attachment to land, language and people. It is triggered by the sight of the Swabian Alb, the sound of a pretzel vendor at the market, or the first bite of Maultaschen after a long absence. Swabian identity is strong — with pride in tinkerers, beautiful scenery and one's own language. Despite globalisation, as alive as ever.",
  "koelsch.k-143": "In Cologne's carnival, \"Maintenor\" or \"Eitle-Schal\" is a humorously mocking term for a vain man who takes himself too seriously. During carnival, such types are knocked off their pedestal with swaying and jokes. Cologne egalitarianism: nobody is too big, nobody too important. The social dimension of the Cologne mentality is famous.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-127": "Husum, the \"grey town by the sea\", was made literarily immortal by Theodor Storm (1817–1888). The North German poet was born here, lived here as a magistrate and wrote his most famous novellas — including \"Der Schimmelreiter\" (The Rider on the White Horse, 1888). His birthplace in the Wasserreihe is now the Storm Museum. His main lyrical work \"Die Stadt\" (\"On the grey shore, by the grey sea ...\") is school material. Husum still breathes Storm atmosphere to this day — grey, melancholic, beautiful.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-129": "The \"Eidgenössisches Schwingfest\" (ESAF for short) takes place every three years — the highlight of Schwingen, the Swiss national sport. Over 250 wrestlers grapple in sawdust rings, and the winners are crowned \"Schwingerkönig\" (king of wrestlers). Up to 350,000 spectators over the weekend — Europe's largest open-air sporting event! The prize: a live Muni (bull). Brienz, Burgdorf and Estavayer-le-Lac have hosted it. More a folk festival than a competition — pure Swiss tradition.",
  "wienerisch.w-125": "\"Schrammelmusik\" is the typical Viennese folk music, named after the brothers Johann and Josef Schrammel (1850s–1890s). Classic line-up: two violins, clarinet (or button accordion) and contra-guitar. It is played at the Heuriger, in the Wienerlied and in Viennese operetta. The term stands for the Viennese soul in sound — wistful, melancholic, with \"Schmäh\". A UNESCO-worthy piece of Viennese cultural heritage. It still lives on today in Vienna's Heuriger taverns.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-125": "\"Bassd schoo\" with a drawn-out \"oo\" is the intensified Franconian form of \"bassd scho\" — Franconian composure at its highest level. It means roughly \"it's perfectly fine\" or \"it doesn't matter at all\". It is said when someone apologises, when something goes wrong, or when you want to be generous. The stretching of the vowel shows Franconian warmth and tolerance. True Franconian art of living in a single word.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-129": "The CentrO in Oberhausen is one of the largest shopping centres in Europe — opened in 1996 on the site of the decommissioned Thyssen steelworks. Symbolic: where steel once flowed, consumption now flows. 250 shops, a Coca-Cola oasis, Sea Life, the Gasometer. For many people of the Ruhr it's the weekend destination, for others the symbol of structural change — good or bad, depending on your point of view. Fact: without CentrO, Oberhausen would be less today.",
  "alemannisch.al-129": "The Hirschsprung rock in the Höllental valley is the narrowest point of the Höllental railway — only 9 metres wide between the steep rock faces. The legend: a stag leapt from one rock face to the other to escape hunters. A stag statue commemorates this. The Freiburg–Donaueschingen railway line was completed in 1887 and had to cross the valley through tunnels and over viaducts. The Hirschsprung is one of the most famous Black Forest postcard motifs. A geological and legendary wonder.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-116": "\"Schunkele\" means to sway — the collective swaying back and forth in time with the music, arms linked, at festivals. \"Wann die Quetsch spielt, fange mir alle aa zu schunkele!\" (When the accordion plays, we all start swaying!). At Kerwe (the village fair), the wine festival and Fastnacht, swaying is simply part of it. You link arms with your neighbour and sway to the rhythm of the wine songs. A symbol of Palatine conviviality and festive joy. A classic word from the music and festival culture that expresses community and exuberant cheer.",
  "hessisch.h-164": "Darmstadt is the \"city of science\" of Hesse — TU Darmstadt (one of Germany's best technical universities), GSI (research centre for heavy-ion research — it has discovered 7 chemical elements!), the ESA control centre. The Mathildenhöhe (UNESCO World Heritage) showcases the Art Nouveau legacy. Also home to the Darmstädter Echo and SV Darmstadt 98. Hesse's intellectual centre.",
  "berlinisch.b-158": "The Friedrichstraße station in Berlin-Mitte was, during the Wall era, the infamous \"Tränenpalast\" (Palace of Tears) — where families had to part between East and West. Today a museum and memorial. Architecturally one of Berlin's most important stations. A direct hub for S-Bahn, U-Bahn and ICE. A magnet for history tourists.",
  "bayerisch.by-137": "The \"Trachtenball\" (costume ball) is the social highlight of the Bavarian-Austrian winter season. While the Viennese aristocracy holds the \"Opernball\", Bavaria dances in full traditional dress — Dirndl, Lederhose, Joppe. A classic appearance of the traditional costume clubs, with a standard repertoire (Boarischer, Zwiefacher, waltz, polka). In Munich there's the \"Oberlandler Ball\" or the \"Kocherlball\". Taken very seriously, with strict dress regulations. Here custom blends with high culture — Bavaria's social self-affirmation.",
  "saechsisch.s-123": "\"Heeschen\" is the Saxon diminutive for little bunny — a term of endearment for loved ones, especially between partners and within families. \"Mei Heeschen\" (my little bunny) conveys warmth and affection. The Saxon diminutive ending \"-schen\" turns any word into a loving pet name: Mauseschen, Schatzeschen, Bärsche. A characteristic element of the Saxon language of relationships — warmer than most Standard German variants.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-126": "The Swabian town of Reutlingen has a long brewing tradition — the Reutlinger brewery was founded in 1873 and produces classic Swabian beers such as Pils and Weizen. The smaller private brewery Härle in Reutlingen is also regionally esteemed. While the Swabian breweries are smaller than the large Bavarian ones, they maintain a tradition of their own. Reutlingen beers go perfectly with the Swabian Vesper (cold platter).",
  "koelsch.k-144": "\"Halv elf\" — 10:30 a.m. — is the magical carnival hour in Cologne, derived from the carnival number 11. Carnival events often begin at 10:30 or 11:11. The \"Drei mal Kölle Alaaf um halv elf\" (three times Cologne Alaaf at half past ten) is a mandatory choreography. A time only carnivalists understand. The world stands still for the fifth season.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-128": "Eckernförde on the Baltic Sea is a charming harbour town of 22,000 inhabitants between Kiel and Flensburg. Known for the Eckernförder Sprotten (smoked sprats) — a protected geographical indication since 2007. The smokehouses along the harbour promenade are a tourist magnet. The Mecklenburger shipyard also builds submarines here. The white sandy beach of the Borby peninsula and the historic old town make Eckernförde an insider's tip.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-130": "\"Hornussen\" is a unique Swiss national sport, similar to cricket/baseball — played mainly in the Bernese Mittelland. A player (\"Stöcker\") strikes a hard rubber \"nuss\" (the Hornuss) with a long rod towards the opposing team, who must fend off the flying object with Schindeln (shovel-like boards). It dates from the 17th century. The highlight is the \"Eidgenössisches Hornusserfest\". It sounds quirky but is a serious sport with clubs and a league. A Swiss folk-sport peculiarity.",
  "wienerisch.w-126": "Karl Kraus (1874–1936) was Vienna's sharpest polemicist — editor of the journal \"Die Fackel\" (1899–1936), which from 1911 he wrote almost single-handedly. His readings in the Mittlerer Konzerthaussaal filled halls. \"Die letzten Tage der Menschheit\" (The Last Days of Mankind) — an 800-page anti-war drama. Viennese coffeehouse culture, Jewish enlightenment, merciless language criticism. His wit was so sharp that even friends feared to meet him. Today a synonym for intellectual Viennese polemic.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-126": "Würzburger Hofbräu is one of the oldest breweries in Franconia — founded in 1643 as a prince-bishop's court brewery. Headquartered on Würzburg's Höchberger Straße, it is known for Würzburger Hofbräu Pils and the Bayerisch Hell. The Hofbräu huts with beer gardens in Würzburg are popular meeting places for students and locals. Tradition meets modern brewing craft — Franconian beer culture preserved over 380 years. Popular beyond Franconia too.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-130": "Hagen, on the south-eastern edge of the Ruhr area, is regarded as the \"gateway to the Sauerland\" — the transition from the industrial Pott to the green low-mountain landscape. 188,000 inhabitants, home of the FernUniversität Hagen (Germany's only state-run distance university). Famous: the Karl Ernst Osthaus Museum, Walgemüt Park. People from Hagen are considered down-to-earth and somewhat more reserved than the central Pott folk. The city was hit hard by the 2021 flood disaster.",
  "alemannisch.al-130": "The Adler ski stadium in Hinterzarten is the most important ski jumping hill in southern Germany — a training centre for many Olympic ski jumpers (Sven Hannawald, Martin Schmitt). The Hochfirstschanze is an FIS-certified large hill. Black Forest skiing tradition: Germany's first ski school was founded here in 1891. FIS competitions draw thousands of spectators. Today Hinterzarten is a well-known Black Forest health resort with a winter-sports history.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-117": "\"Glotzbobbe\" are bug eyes — or someone who stares with big eyes. \"Mach kää Glotzbobbe, des is doch nix Bsondres!\" (Don't make goggle eyes, it's nothing special!). From \"glotze\" (to stare) and \"Bobbe\" (doll/round thing). It's said to someone who gawps openly or looks dumbfounded. A vivid, slightly mocking Palatine word. It belongs to the rich vocabulary about the body and people, which is never stingy with onomatopoeic compounds. It sounds funny and disarming at once, very much in Palatine fashion.",
  "hessisch.h-165": "The Mathildenhöhe in Darmstadt has been a UNESCO World Heritage Site since 2021 — an artists' colony from around 1900 with Art Nouveau buildings, the Wedding Tower, the Russian Chapel and artists' studios. Grand Duke Ernst Ludwig of Hesse-Darmstadt brought the colony to life — painters, architects and designers worked here. One of the most important artists' colonies in Europe. Hesse's Art Nouveau capital.",
  "berlinisch.b-159": "The Eberswalder Straße in Prenzlauer Berg is famous for \"Konnopkes Imbiss\" — Berlin's oldest currywurst stand (since 1930). The currywurst is supposedly said to have been invented here (disputed, with Heuwer in Charlottenburg). Located directly beneath the elevated U-Bahn track, the Konnopke stand is a place of pilgrimage for currywurst lovers. A cult spot among GDR nostalgics and tourists.",
  "bayerisch.by-138": "\"Aiwanger\" — Hubert Aiwanger (b. 1971) — is chairman of the Freie Wähler Bayern and deputy minister-president. With his Lower Bavarian dialect, Lederhosen appearances and folksy rhetoric, he became a symbolic figure of an independent Bavarian politics apart from the CSU. In 2023 he was caught up in a leaflet affair. He loves to speak in the tavern and to thunder in the beer tent. He polarises between closeness to the people and scandal-proneness. A current Bavarian political figure.",
  "saechsisch.s-124": "\"Lurchi\" is the famous Salamander shoe advertising figure — created in 1937 by Heinrich Werner, who was born in Erlangen. The Lurchi booklets were a coveted childhood read in the GDR too — even though Salamander shoes were almost unattainable for GDR citizens. The rhymes \"Salamander lebe hoch\" (long live Salamander) are familiar to whole generations. A nostalgic symbol of shoe-shopping experiences in the 20th century.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-127": "Stuttgarter Hofbräu is the best-known Stuttgart brewery — founded in 1872. With its distinctive white-and-red logo and its Swabian Pils, it is part of the obligatory range of every Stuttgart pub. At the Cannstatter Wasen, Hofbräu is one of the dominant brands. Now part of the Radeberger Group, Hofbräu has retained its Swabian identity. Stuttgarter Hofbräu is omnipresent in the Talkessel (Stuttgart's bowl-shaped valley) — Swabian beer heritage.",
  "koelsch.k-145": "Köln-Kalk is a district on the right bank of the Rhine — formerly an industrial quarter, today multicultural with a Turkish and Arab community. The Kalk-Hauptstraße is a shopping mile. The district is cheaper than the inner-city Veedel and popular with young families. \"Kalker\" have their own pride: down-to-earth, direct, without frills. Real Cologne off the tourist routes.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-129": "Flensburg is the northernmost city in Germany — right on the Danish border. 90,000 inhabitants. Famous above all for three things: the Federal Motor Transport Authority with the \"Flensburg points\" (the traffic-offenders register), the Flensburger brewery with its characteristic swing-top beer, and the Danish influence (bilingual signs, a Danish minority). A beautiful fjord, a Hanseatic townscape, a multicultural atmosphere.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-132": "\"Verbier\" in the Valais Bagnes valley is one of the most fashionable Swiss ski resorts — linked to the \"Four Valleys\" (4 Vallées), 410 km of pistes. Internationally famous for off-piste and freeride. The Verbier Festival (classical music in summer) attracts pianists like Daniil Trifonov. James Blunt has a house here. In winter the international jet set meets here — Madonna and Diana Ross have been guests. Very expensive, very exclusive. Swiss winter-sports glamour.",
  "wienerisch.w-127": "Egon Schiele (1890–1918) — Viennese expressionist, pupil and friend of Gustav Klimt. The embodiment of \"Viennese Modernism\" between Eros and death. His angular, often self-tormented nude studies provoked the bourgeoisie. In 1912 he was imprisoned for \"causing public offence\". He died at 28 of the Spanish flu — three days after his wife Edith. Today Viennese museum gold in the Leopold Museum and the Albertina. A Vienna art icon alongside Klimt.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-127": "Franconian bread is famous — hearty sourdough breads with rye, wheat and caraway, baked in wood-fired ovens. Franconian bakers cultivate old recipes, often handed down over generations. Famous varieties: Fränkisches Bauernbrot, pumpernickel, Steinmetz bread. The crumb is dark and moist, the crust crispy. \"A guads fränkisches Brot mit Salzbutter\" (a good Franconian bread with salted butter) is a simple but unbeatable treat. Indispensable at the Brotzeit.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-131": "The most famous suspension-railway incident: in 1950 the little circus elephant Tuffi leapt from an advertising carriage of the Wuppertal suspension railway into the Wupper — falling 12 metres and surviving unharmed. The pictures went around the world, and Wuppertal became the \"elephant city\". A Tuffi statue commemorates the stunt today. The suspension railway is not just technology, but a history full of bizarre anecdotes. To this day tourists ride it especially for the Tuffi story.",
  "alemannisch.al-131": "The Belchen cable car takes you in 12 minutes from the valley up to the 1,414-metre-high Belchen — the second-highest mountain in the southern Black Forest. Opened in 2001, it replaced the mountain road and protected nature conservation. At the summit: a 360-degree panorama with Mont Blanc, the Swiss Alps, the Vosges and the Black Forest. The Berghotel Belchen offers overnight stays. A sacred mountain of the Celts — the name \"Belchen\" derives from the Celtic sun god Belenus. A summer hiking paradise.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-118": "The \"Worschdmarkt-Schoppe\" is the half-litre of Schorle (wine spritzer) you drink in the Schoppen glass at the Dürkheim Wurstmarkt. \"Mir hole uns a Worschdmarkt-Schoppe un setze uns ins Festzelt.\" (Let's get ourselves a Wurstmarkt Schoppe and sit down in the festival tent). At the world's largest wine festival, the generously measured Schoppe is simply part of it. Unlike the normal glass, the Worschdmarkt-Schoppe is proverbial for its size. A classic word from Palatine festival culture, closely tied to conviviality, wine and the legendary Wurstmarkt revelry.",
  "hessisch.h-166": "TU Darmstadt — one of Germany's best technical universities — was founded in 1877. A member of the Excellence Initiative. Over 25,000 students. Known for mechanical engineering, electrical engineering, computer science and materials science. The TU shapes Darmstadt as a science hub and makes Hesse a technology region. Together with the Goethe University (Frankfurt) and the Justus Liebig University (Gießen), it forms a Hessian university triumvirate.",
  "berlinisch.b-160": "The Berlin Philharmonie by the Tiergarten is home to the Berlin Philharmonic — founded in 1882. The concert hall, built in 1963 by Hans Scharoun, is architecturally revolutionary: the orchestra sits in the middle, with the audience all around. Acoustically one of the best concert halls in the world. Karajan, Abbado, Rattle and Petrenko have directed the orchestra. A mecca of classical music.",
  "bayerisch.by-139": "The \"Goggomobil\" was built in 1955 at Hans Glas in Dingolfing (Lower Bavaria) — the classic of the Bavarian microcar era. With a 250 cc two-stroke engine it reached up to 80 km/h. Very popular during the economic miracle, it was produced until 1969. Today a cult object among classic-car fans. The Glas works were taken over by BMW in 1966 — pure Bavarian industrial history. \"Goggo fahrn\" (to drive a Goggo) still refers today to rather leisurely, sluggish travel.",
  "saechsisch.s-125": "The SDAG \"Wismut\" was the Soviet-German joint-stock company that mined uranium for Soviet nuclear weapons in Saxony and Thuringia between 1947 and 1990 — the world's third-largest uranium producer. Over 400,000 people worked under brutal conditions. It left behind mining damage and long-term health consequences (\"Wismut cancer\"). Remediation is ongoing today. A tragic chapter of Saxon economic and social history.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-128": "The Stuttgart Market Hall is one of the most beautiful Art Nouveau market halls in Germany — built in 1914 by architect Martin Elsaesser. On 3,500 m², 30 vendors sell specialties from around the world: Swabian Maultaschen, Italian cheese, French wines, Asian spices. The vast open interior with its glass roof is impressive. A popular lunch destination for the Stuttgart office crowds. Swabian gastronomic tradition paired with heritage architecture.",
  "koelsch.k-147": "The KölnTriangle in Deutz — a 103 m office tower opened in 2006 — offers from its \"Triangle Panorama\" viewing platform the most beautiful view of the cathedral and city center. On clear days you can see the Siebengebirge and the Eifel. Admission is cheap (5 euros), opening hours flexible. A real insider tip for tourists who want to experience the classic cathedral view.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-130": "The Kieler Woche (Kiel Week) in June is one of the largest sailing events in the world — held since 1882. Over 5,000 sailors from 50 nations gather in the Kiel Fjord. It is accompanied by a folk festival with over 3 million visitors. The highlight: the international Windjammer Parade with large sailing ships. The Olympic sailing competitions of 1936 and 1972 took place here. Pure Kiel sailing culture and maritime identity. For one week, Kiel becomes the world capital of sailing.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-133": "The \"Lauberhorn race\" in Wengen (Bernese Oberland) is, at 4.5 km, the longest and, at over 160 km/h, the fastest downhill in the Ski World Cup. It takes place every January — a must-attend for ski fans. Famous course sections: Hundschopf, Wasserstation, Hannegg-Schuss, Ziel-S. Winners like Pirmin Zurbriggen, Beat Feuz and Didier Cuche are Swiss heroes. A live-TV spectacle. Swiss skiing history put on stage.",
  "wienerisch.w-128": "Otto Wagner (1841–1918) — Vienna's city architect around 1900, the father of modernism. He designed the Vienna Stadtbahn (today the U4 and U6 subway lines), the Postsparkasse, and the Kirche am Steinhof. His slogan: \"Something impractical cannot be beautiful.\" A transition from historicism to modernism, a forerunner of Bauhaus and functionalism. Teacher of Adolf Loos and Joseph Olbrich. Vienna's cityscape bears his signature to this day. Architecture as a social program.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-128": "The Mainfränkisches Museum at Marienberg Fortress in Würzburg is the most important museum for Franconian art and history. It houses the world's largest collection of Tilman Riemenschneider sculptures — the late Gothic master worked in Würzburg from 1483. Franconian folk art, the history of viticulture and Main fishing are also on display. The fortress itself is over 1,000 years old. A must-visit for anyone who wants to understand Franconia.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-132": "Manfred \"Manni\" Breuckmann (1951–2024) was a WDR sports reporter for over 40 years and THE voice of Ruhrpott football in the Bundesliga's multi-game radio broadcasts. His laconic, dry Ruhr-area wit, mixed with expertise, made him a cult figure. \"Goal in Dortmund!\" in his voice — pure Pott sound. The Henri Nannen Prize in 2009. His death in May 2024 was mourned throughout the Ruhr region — an era came to an end.",
  "alemannisch.al-132": "The Münstertal is a picturesque Black Forest valley between the Belchen and Staufen — crossed by the Klemmbach stream. It is famous for the monastery ruin of St. Trudpert (founded in the 7th century by the Irish wandering missionary Trudpert), today a pilgrimage site. Beautiful hiking trails, mountain pastures with Black Forest cows, traditional farmhouses. Mining history: silver was mined here in the Middle Ages. The Münstertal is an Alemannic idyll away from mass tourism.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-119": "A \"Hewwel\" is a small hill or rise, often planted with vines. \"Vum Hewwel aus siehscht de ganze Rheineben\" (From the Hewwel you can see the whole Rhine plain). The gentle hills at the edge of the Palatinate Forest shape the landscape of the Wine Route. Related to the standard German \"Hügel\" (hill). From a Hewwel you have the best view over the vineyards all the way to the Rhine. A classic word from the region's nature vocabulary, closely tied to viticulture and the typically rolling Palatinate landscape.",
  "hessisch.h-167": "Justus von Liebig (1803–1873) was one of the most important chemists of the 19th century — he worked in Gießen. The founder of modern organic chemistry and of fertilizer chemistry. He devised \"Liebig's law of the minimum\" (plant growth), the Liebig condenser and the mass production of fertilizers. The Justus Liebig University of Gießen bears his name. Hesse's greatest scientist.",
  "berlinisch.b-161": "The Staatsoper Unter den Linden — Berlin's main opera house — was opened in 1742 by Frederick the Great and is one of the oldest opera houses in Europe. General music director Daniel Barenboim shaped it for 30 years. It reopened in 2017 after a lengthy renovation. With both classic operatic standards and avant-garde productions. A must of Berlin high culture.",
  "bayerisch.by-140": "At \"Lederhosen contests\" held at fairs and traditional costume gatherings, the most beautiful, oldest or most original pair of Krachlederne (leather shorts) is awarded a prize. Judges assess the patina (the older, the better), embroidery, suspenders and the traditional \"fit.\" A genuine pair of Lederhosen is often worn for 30+ years — stains count as a badge of honor. In Munich there are dedicated \"patina contests.\" A well broken-in pair is regarded as Bavarian heritage — often passed down from father to son.",
  "saechsisch.s-126": "Otto Mücke is a famous Saxon original character — embodied by the cabaret artist Walter Sparbier and later popularized as the epitome of the typical Saxon. With his hat, moustache and earthy Saxon dialect, he embodies the lovable petty bourgeois. Today a synonym for Saxon idiosyncrasies and way of life. Original figures like Otto Mücke keep the Saxon character alive in language and demeanor.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-129": "Stuttgart has the second-largest mineral water deposits in Europe (after Budapest) — over 22 million liters bubble up daily from 19 healing springs. The most famous mineral baths: Leuze, Berg, Cannstatt. Here you bathe in warm, mineral-rich water and relax after hard Swabian work. Even the Romans valued the springs 2,000 years ago. Stuttgart's mineral baths are a UNESCO-worthy bathing heritage and part of Swabian wellness culture.",
  "koelsch.k-149": "In Cologne there's a saying: \"Wer in Kölle wohnt, der is' jeck\" (Whoever lives in Cologne is jeck/crazy) — Carnival is more than a festival, it is a philosophy of life. Being jeck means: staying relaxed, not taking everything seriously, playing with life. Carnival compensates for supposedly hard times. In Cologne you have to be able to be jeck, otherwise you lose your mind. Carnival spirit all year round.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-131": "The Ohnsorg Theater in Hamburg is the most famous Low German theater in Germany — founded in 1902 as the \"Niederdeutsche Bühne.\" It is known for Low German comedies such as \"Tratsch im Treppenhaus,\" \"Das Hörrohr\" and \"Mein Mann, der fährt zur See.\" Heidi Kabel, Henry Vahl and Heinz Lanker were Ohnsorg legends. Since the 1950s the plays have been regularly broadcast on television — the ARD/NDR recordings made Low German understandable throughout Germany. Northern German language preservation at the highest level.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-134": "The \"Adelboden giant slalom\" on the Chuenisbärgli (Bernese Oberland) is one of the most prestigious races of the Ski World Cup. It takes place every January. The course is considered the most technically demanding in the giant slalom World Cup — steep walls, the \"Adelboden wave\" at the finish. Marcel Hirscher (Austrian) won here 7 times. Swiss winners: Daniel Albrecht, Carlo Janka, Marco Odermatt. Over 20,000 spectators line the slope. High-alpine ski culture at its purest.",
  "wienerisch.w-129": "Adolf Loos (1870–1933) — Viennese architect, shaped modernism with \"Ornament and Crime\" (1908). His Loos House on Michaelerplatz (1910) provoked the emperor because it was unadorned. The famous \"Café Museum\" (1899) — today Café Loos. Creator of the Adolf Loos Bar (American Bar) at the Kärntnerdurchgang. A forerunner of Le Corbusier and Mies van der Rohe. He lived between Vienna and Paris. Vienna's contribution to global modernism.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-129": "A \"Käpsele\" is, in Franconian, a clever, sharp-witted person — someone who tackles things smartly without being fooled. It derives from the Italian \"capo\" (head) and means \"someone with a good head.\" It is meant positively, sometimes with a slight wink. People from Würzburg are especially proud of their Käpsele mentality — pragmatic, worldly-wise, with Franconian native wit. \"Die is a Käpsele!\" (She's a Käpsele!) is high praise.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-133": "The WDR's \"Lokalzeit\" is the most important regional news program in the Ruhr region — produced separately for Ruhr, Dortmund, Duisburg and the Bergisches Land. At 7:30 p.m., right before the Tagesschau. It reports on neighborhood politics, crime, club life, BVB and Schalke. For many Pott people it is the daily window onto their home region. Presented by familiar faces who are better known in the Pott than any national politician. A must-watch in the living room.",
  "alemannisch.al-133": "The Schluchsee in the southern Black Forest is, at 5 km², the largest lake in the Black Forest — a reservoir at 930 meters altitude. It is popular for water sports: sailing, surfing, swimming, diving, stand-up paddling. In summer temperatures reach up to 23 degrees. An 18 km hiking trail runs around the lake. In winter, ice fishing and skiing. Its landmark is the striking hotel and spa-resort ensemble. Family holidays in the Black Forest often take place at the Schluchsee.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-120": "A \"Boddschamber\" is the chamber pot — from the French \"pot de chambre\" (chamber pot). \"Frieher stand de Boddschamber unterm Bett\" (In the old days the Boddschamber stood under the bed). Another vivid French loanword in the Palatinate vocabulary. Indispensable before the days of indoor toilets, today mostly just a keepsake or a flowerpot. It is gladly cited as an example of Napoleonic linguistic influence. A classic word from the old rural everyday life that attests to the close linguistic neighborhood with France.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-121": "\"Filusel\" are bits of fluff, fibers or little woolly bobbles that cling to clothing. \"Du host a Filusel uff em schwarze Pulli\" (You have a Filusel on your black sweater). Onomatopoeic for the small, annoying bits. Also \"a Filusel im Aug\" for a speck of dust or a stray eyelash. A charmingly sounding Palatinate word for something tiny and insignificant. It belongs to everyday vocabulary and shows the Palatinate's delight in soft, playful sound sequences. It is used quite naturally when removing fluff.",
  "hessisch.h-170": "The multi-volume Hessian Dictionary of the Philosophical-Historical Class of Mainz has systematically documented the Hessian vocabulary since 1965. Over 70,000 headwords. A scholarly feat — comparable to the Swabian or Bavarian dictionary. Hesse researchers and linguists use it. The dialect heritage is thus preserved for the future.",
  "berlinisch.b-163": "The Friedrichstadt-Palast in Mitte is Europe's largest revue stage — with the world's biggest stage ring (60 m in diameter). The most elaborate show productions run here, with 100+ dancers, spectacular technology and 3D effects. The famous chorus line \"The Lipsticks\" celebrates classic revue culture. Every April–May sees the premiere of a new show.",
  "bayerisch.by-142": "The \"Berchtesgaden Salt Mines\" have been in operation since 1517 — the oldest active salt mine in Germany. The \"white gold\" made Berchtesgaden rich in the Middle Ages. Today it is a tourist attraction with an underground tour, slides and a raft ride on the salt lake. Salt is still extracted for food and industry. Culturally and historically closely linked to the Archbishop of Salzburg and the Munich court — Bavarian economic history you can touch. Fully booked every summer.",
  "saechsisch.s-127": "Olaf Schubert (born 1967 in Plauen) is one of the best-known Saxon cabaret artists — with his sleeveless sweater, childlike voice and naive-philosophical wit. His shows \"Schuberts Welt\" and \"Olaf Schubert und seine Freunde\" fill halls all over Germany. He plays with the Saxon stereotype while making it endearing at the same time. His remarks about everyday life have cult status. Plauen and Dresden are proud of their Olaf.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-130": "The Mercedes-Benz Museum in Stuttgart-Untertürkheim is one of the most spectacular automobile museums in the world — opened in 2006. The building, designed by UN Studio with its double-helix form, leads visitors chronologically through 130 years of automotive history. 160 vehicles on 16,500 m². Highlights: the first Daimler car (1886), Silver Arrows, popemobiles, Schumacher's racing cars. Over 900,000 visitors a year. Swabian economic heritage and an automotive place of pilgrimage.",
  "koelsch.k-150": "\"En unserem Veedel\" is Bläck Fööss's best-known song (1980) — a hymn to the Cologne sense of neighborhood (Veedel). The verses tell of everyday life in the Veedel, of the neighbors, the baker, the publican, the church. An emotional declaration of love for the concept of the Veedel. A mandatory song at every Carnival session. It has sold over 4 million singles. Cologne identity in a single song.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-132": "The Low German Bible translations are an important cultural asset of northern Germany. The first complete Low German Bible — the \"Lübeck Bible\" — appeared in 1494, even before Luther's translation. The modern translation \"De Bibel — Plattdüütsch\" (completed in 1985) made Low German accessible again as a religious language. Low German church services are still held today in many northern German parishes. Preservation of the language through faith.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-135": "The \"bob\" or \"bobsleigh\" is part of Switzerland's winter sports heritage — St. Moritz has had the world's only natural ice track since 1904 (the Olympia Bob Run St. Moritz–Celerina). Invented around 1860 in St. Moritz by English tourists. A multiple Olympic venue (1928, 1948). Four-man and two-man bobs, reaching up to 145 km/h. Swiss successes: the Hiltebrand brothers, Beat Hefti. Skeleton and the Cresta Run as its \"relatives.\" A Swiss winter sports innovation.",
  "wienerisch.w-130": "The \"Vienna Secession\" (1897) was the Viennese artists' association of Art Nouveau modernism — its founders were Klimt, Kolo Moser, Otto Wagner and Josef Olbrich. The famous \"Secession Building\" on Karlsplatz with its golden dome of leaves (nicknamed \"Krauthappel\" — cabbage head) still stands today. Motto: \"To every age its art, to art its freedom.\" It houses Klimt's \"Beethoven Frieze\" (1902). A landmark of European art history. Vienna's answer to the academic establishment.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-130": "Schweinfurt — jokingly called \"Schweinekrim\" by locals — is the Franconian industrial city on the Main with 53,000 inhabitants. It is home to the global corporations FAG (rolling bearings), Schaeffler and Bosch Rexroth. In the Second World War it was heavily bombed because of its ball-bearing production. Economically strong, culturally with the Theater am Roßmarkt and the Kunsthalle. The people of Schweinfurt are proud industrial workers and are considered down-to-earth. Not to be confused with Schwerin!",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-134": "Frank Goosen (born 1966 in Bochum) is THE chronicler of the modern Ruhr region — author (\"Liegen lernen,\" \"Pokorny lacht\"), cabaret artist and VfL Bochum fanatic. His books capture the Pott mentality, the corner pubs of Bochum and the family stories of the post-mining generation. Together with his \"Tresenlesen\" partner Jochen Malmsheimer he shaped Ruhrpott cabaret. His novels are mostly set in his beloved Bochum.",
  "alemannisch.al-134": "Höchenschwand, at 1,015 meters altitude, is one of the highest-lying villages in Germany — self-styled \"the highest village in Europe.\" In the southern Black Forest near the Swiss border, with 2,500 inhabitants. A climatic health resort, known for its mountain sun and mountain air. Tuberculosis sanatoriums had their heyday here. Today tourism and spa stays. A panoramic view of the Swiss Alps, the Rhine plain and the Vosges. Stillness and mountain air as an Alemannic specialty.",
  "hessisch.h-169": "Hessian folk songs are kept alive in the Hessenpark, at Hessian festivals and within families. \"Wir Hessen sind ein froh Geschlecht\" (We Hessians are a cheerful breed) and \"Wo der Main entlang strömt\" (Where the Main flows along) are classic Hessian songs. Friedrich Stoltze wrote many songs. Hessian song heritage is less well known than Bavarian, but it is identity-forming for Hesse.",
  "berlinisch.b-162": "The Deutsche Oper Berlin in Charlottenburg is Berlin's western opera house — founded in 1912, destroyed in the war, rebuilt in 1961. With its famous foyer in 1960s brutalist style. Christof Loy and other top directors have staged productions here. With 1,865 seats, it is the largest opera house in Germany. Charlottenburg high culture.",
  "bayerisch.by-141": "The \"Almhüttn\" are the simple wooden huts of the Alpine farmers in the Bavarian mountains. In summer the \"Sennerin\" (dairymaid) lives up there with the cows and makes Alpine cheese and Alpine butter. In winter the huts stand abandoned. Today they are often ski huts or wedding venues — working Almhüttn are a hiking destination offering a Brotzeit (snack) and schnapps. A romanticized image in Schlager songs and Heimat films — but real Alpine farming is hard work. The Bavarian highlands symbol par excellence.",
  "saechsisch.s-128": "Tom Pauls (born 1959 in Dresden) is one of the most distinguished Saxon cabaret artists and actors — known for his stage role as \"Ilse Bähnert\" (an elderly Saxon lady). With his \"Pauls Salon\" in Pirna he cultivates the Saxon dialect and culture. He is also known as a film actor (\"Nikolaikirche,\" \"Sonnenallee\"). With wit and warmth he embodies the Saxon soul. An honorary citizen of the town of Pirna.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-131": "The Porsche Museum in Stuttgart-Zuffenhausen opened in 2009 — an architectural marvel with a seemingly floating structure. 80 vehicles across 5,600 m², including all the key Porsche models from the Porsche 64 (1939) to the 918 Spyder. Right next to the main plant where the 911 is produced. Over 250,000 visitors a year, among them car enthusiasts from all over the world. Together with the Mercedes Museum, it makes Stuttgart the automobile capital — Swabian tinkerer tradition at its purest.",
  "koelsch.k-151": "St. Aposteln am Neumarkt is one of Cologne's twelve great Romanesque churches — an emblem of Cologne's 11th-century ecclesiastical architecture. Its striking twin-tower front is a city icon. Destroyed in the war, it was rebuilt faithfully to the original. The Cologne Romanesque churches (St. Maria im Kapitol, Groß St. Martin, St. Severin, etc.) are candidates for UNESCO World Heritage status. Cologne's sacred history.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-133": "Hannes Wader (born 1942 in Gadderbaum, now part of Bielefeld) is one of Germany's best-known singer-songwriters — he also wrote numerous Low German songs that enriched the northern German song repertoire. With songs like \"Heute hier, morgen dort\" and his Low German folk song adaptations, he shaped the folk music scene. Politically left-wing and socially critical. Low German songs were a fixed part of his repertoire. A contribution to preserving the Low German language through music.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-136": "\"Capuns\" are the national dish of Graubünden — chard leaves filled with spätzle dough, Bündnerfleisch and Salsiz, cooked in bouillon, then baked au gratin with béchamel and cheese. Hearty farmhouse cuisine from Graubünden. Every valley has its own recipe. It is served in mountain restaurants and Heidi huts. A classic of Graubünden tourism. Elaborate to prepare — whoever cooks Capuns cooks love. Swiss mountain cuisine par excellence.",
  "wienerisch.w-131": "The \"Belvedere\" — Upper and Lower Belvedere — is the Baroque palace complex of Prince Eugene of Savoy, built between 1714 and 1723 by Lucas von Hildebrandt. Today it houses Austria's most important art collection: Klimt's \"Kiss,\" Schiele's self-portraits, Kokoschka. The garden is considered a highlight of Viennese Baroque. In 1955 the State Treaty was signed in the Marble Hall (Austrian sovereignty). Vienna's top-3 tourist destination alongside Schönbrunn and St. Stephen's Cathedral.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-131": "Johannisburg Castle in Aschaffenburg is one of the most important Renaissance complexes in Germany — built from 1605 to 1614 for the Mainz archbishop-electors. With four identical corner towers, it looks like a perfect fortress. Inside: the Pompejanum (a reconstruction of a Roman house), the castle chapel, and a painting gallery with works by Cranach. Aschaffenburg lies in the westernmost part of Lower Franconia on the Main — a Franconian town with a connection to Hesse.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-135": "Herbert Knebel is the most famous comic character of the Essen cabaret artist Uwe Lyko (born 1954) — a grey-haired Ruhr pensioner with a flat cap, glasses and \"igittigittigitt\" gripes about everything modern. Since the 1980s on the WDR show \"Herbert Knebels Affentheater\" and on theatre stages. He embodies the slightly grumpy but endearing Ruhr pensioner mentality. Lines like \"Da kann man ja nur den Kopf schütteln\" (you can only shake your head) are cult.",
  "alemannisch.al-135": "St. Blasien in the southern Black Forest houses one of Europe's largest domed buildings — the St. Blasius Cathedral with a 36-metre diameter (the third-largest church dome in Germany, on a scale akin to St. Peter's). Built from 1768 to 1783 by the architect Pierre-Michel d'Ixnard in the Classicist style. The former Benedictine monastery is now a Jesuit college. For centuries St. Blasien was a spiritual centre of the region. Breathtaking acoustics, a popular concert venue.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-122": "D'\"Schäs\" is an old, rickety car or vehicle — from the French \"chaise.\" \"Mit der alde Schäs fahr ich nimmer in Urlaub!\" (I'm not going on holiday in that old jalopy anymore!) Mockingly for a vehicle that has seen better days. Yet another French loanword that originally referred to a carriage. The same word is also found in \"Bobbeschees\" (pram). Whoever drives an old Schäs takes it with humour. A classic Palatine word that vividly illustrates the French linguistic influence.",
  "hessisch.h-171": "The Brothers Grimm from Hanau and Kassel began the \"Deutsches Wörterbuch\" (German Dictionary) — the largest German-language dictionary in the world. Started in 1838 and finished in 1961 (!) — over 123 years of work, 32 volumes, around 400,000 words. A scholarly achievement of historical dimensions. The Brothers Grimm not only collected fairy tales but also documented the German language scientifically. Hessian linguistic heritage.",
  "berlinisch.b-164": "The Berliner Ensemble at Bertolt-Brecht-Platz — founded in 1949 by Bertolt Brecht and Helene Weigel — is Berlin's Brecht theatre. The programme focuses on Brecht plays (\"Mother Courage,\" \"The Threepenny Opera\") and political theatre. Architecturally notable for the auditorium with its striking iron curtain. Brecht's legacy is cultivated here — sometimes traditionally, sometimes radically anew.",
  "bayerisch.by-143": "\"Bad Kissingen\" in Lower Franconia (Bavaria) is one of Germany's most famous spa towns. Used since the 16th century, it became a world-class spa resort in the 19th century. Emperor Wilhelm I, Bismarck, Tolstoy and Theodor Fontane took the waters here. In 2021 it became a UNESCO World Heritage Site as one of the \"Great Spa Towns of Europe.\" Classic spa facilities, drinking fountains, pump rooms — the water is rich in iron and sodium. Today a conference venue and wellness destination. Bavaria's most distinguished spa town.",
  "saechsisch.s-129": "The miners' songs of the Erzgebirge are an important part of Saxon folk music — born of centuries of mining tradition. Well-known songs: \"Glück auf, der Steiger kommt,\" \"Steigerlied,\" \"Bergmannsgruß.\" They are sung at miners' parades and in miners' choir concerts. The Steigerlied is regarded as the \"unofficial anthem of mining\" and is part of UNESCO's intangible cultural heritage. They preserve the memory of the hard work underground.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-132": "BMW (Bayerische Motoren Werke) in Munich is the Bavarian counterpart to the Swabian carmakers Mercedes-Benz and Porsche. While Swabia shines with the star and the 911, Bavaria has its own automotive giants in BMW and Audi (Ingolstadt). There is friendly rivalry between the Swabian and Bavarian carmakers. Swabians often say jokingly: \"A Bayer fährt BMW, a Schwob fährt Mercedes — und beide reden des Hochdeutsch nit g'scheit.\" (A Bavarian drives a BMW, a Swabian drives a Mercedes — and neither speaks proper standard German.)",
  "koelsch.k-152": "Groß St. Martin at the Fischmarkt is one of Cologne's most famous Romanesque churches — its striking crossing towers date from the 12th century. The silhouette with its clover-leaf ground plan is a classic of Cologne postcards. Severely damaged in the war, it only reopened in 1985. Located in the shadow of the cathedral, but just as significant in art-historical terms. A place of pilgrimage for architecture lovers.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-134": "Manuel Andrack (born 1965 in Cologne) became known as Harald Schmidt's sidekick on the \"Harald Schmidt Show.\" Today he is a bestselling author of hiking books — above all about northern Germany and the Eifel. With his relaxed, north German style and Hanoverian roots (he lives in Lower Saxony), he brings northern German nature and mentality to a broad audience. His hiking guides are both tongue-in-cheek and profound. A north German lifestyle ambassador.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-137": "The \"Bürli\" is the standard Swiss bread roll — round, dusted with flour, with a crispy crust and soft dough. It is eaten as a \"Znünibürli\" (mid-morning snack) or at breakfast. Variations: \"Mehlsuppe-Bürli,\" \"Sesam-Bürli,\" \"Doppelweggli.\" Swiss bakeries like Hiestand or Schwarzenbach uphold the tradition. Compared to the German roll, it is softer, rounder and more robust. A symbol of identity for the Swiss breakfast. With butter and jam: a weekend staple.",
  "wienerisch.w-132": "The \"Schönbrunner Schlosspark\" is the Baroque garden of Schönbrunn Palace — Vienna's imperial summer residence. On a hill stands the Gloriette (1775), and below it fountains, statues, a maze and the world's oldest zoo (Tiergarten Schönbrunn, 1752). A UNESCO World Heritage Site since 1996. Maria Theresa and Franz Joseph resided here. Today it draws 5 million visitors a year. During the Vienna Philharmonic's \"Summer Night Concert,\" the palace turns into an open-air stage.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-132": "Wertheim am Main lies on the border between Franconia (Bavaria) and Baden-Württemberg — strictly speaking it is Badenese, but linguistically Franconian in character. Famous for its medieval castle ruins, the historic Glass Museum and the large \"Wertheim Village\" designer outlet — one of the largest outlet centres in Germany. Wertheim is a link between Franconia and Tauberfranken. The people of Wertheim speak a transitional dialect.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-136": "Karl Konietzny — the name stands representatively for thousands of families of Polish descent among the miners of the Ruhr region. From 1880 onwards, Polish miners (the Ruhr Poles) migrated to the region en masse — at times they made up a quarter of the population. Surnames ending in -ski, -czyk and -ny are still common today. Konietzny is emblematic of the Polish roots of the Ruhr dweller — hard graft, family, Catholic folk piety. Ruhr identity is always also Polish identity.",
  "alemannisch.al-136": "The German Clock Museum in Furtwangen is the most important clock museum in the world — over 8,000 exhibits spanning 1,200 years of timekeeping. Founded in 1852 by Robert Gerwig (also the builder of the Black Forest Railway). Furtwangen is the traditional centre of the Black Forest clock industry — cuckoo clocks, painted-shield clocks, atomic clocks. The Furtwangen University of Applied Sciences carries on the tradition. At the museum you learn how the Black Forest taught the world to measure time. A must-visit for technology enthusiasts.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-123": "\"Plärre\" means to cry, scream or bawl loudly. \"Hör uff zu plärre, mir kaafe dir a Eis!\" (Stop bawling, we'll buy you an ice cream!) It is used above all for loud children's screaming, but also for overly loud music (\"des Radio plärrt\" — the radio is blaring). Onomatopoeic, after the piercing sound. Whoever \"rumplärrt\" makes a real racket. It belongs to the vivid Palatine vocabulary surrounding feelings and noises. Parents know the Plärre only too well, and the word itself already sounds like the loud protest.",
  "hessisch.h-172": "\"En Sechsbacher\" is a humorous term in Frankfurt's cider taverns for six Schoppen of cider — roughly a sitting of 1.8 litres made up of 0.3-litre Schoppen glasses. Proof of Hessian drinking stamina. \"Hessen können was vertragen\" (Hessians can hold their drink) is a fondly proud self-image. Drinking cider is sport, art and social activity all in one.",
  "berlinisch.b-165": "The Berlin Zoo in Charlottenburg is Germany's oldest zoo (founded in 1844) and, with over 20,000 animals, one of the most species-rich in the world. Famous: the polar bear Knut (2006–2011), who caused a worldwide sensation. The aquarium next door is one of the most spectacular in Europe. The \"Bahnhof Zoo\" station and Christiane F.'s novel \"Wir Kinder vom Bahnhof Zoo\" have made the district immortal.",
  "bayerisch.by-144": "The \"Münchner Kindl\" is Munich's heraldic figure — a monk in a black habit with a Bible and red shoes. It recalls the city's founding by monks (\"München\" = \"by the monks\"). The city's coat of arms since the Middle Ages, it is now usually depicted as a childlike figure. At the Oktoberfest parade a \"Münchner Kindl\" rides along — usually a young woman in a monk's robe. Omnipresent on posters, advertising and the Hofbräuhaus logo. Munich's identity symbol number one.",
  "saechsisch.s-130": "The Pulsnitz gingerbread manufactories cultivate a 500-year-old baking tradition — each of the eight traditional bakeries has its own secret recipes, passed on only to the next generation. The famous varieties: Spitzkuchen, Eiserkuchen, filled gingerbread with marzipan or jam. The EU-protected geographical indication guarantees quality. At the Pulsnitz Gingerbread Museum you can watch the bakers at work.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-133": "Ludwig van Beethoven (1770–1827) was born in Bonn — and is therefore not a Swabian, even if some Swabians would like it to be otherwise. His setting of Schiller's \"Ode to Joy\" as the final movement of the 9th Symphony does, however, connect him with the Swabian poet. The European anthem is based on Beethoven's melody for Schiller's text — a link between Rhineland music and Swabian poetry. Beethoven was a Viennese by choice, not a Stuttgarter by choice.",
  "koelsch.k-153": "\"Loss mer singe!\" is the Cologne call to sing together — especially during Carnival. It is also the name of the most important initiative for promoting new Carnival songs (\"Loss mer singe e.V.\"). New Carnival songs are tested here — if the audience can sing along, the song has a chance of becoming a hit. Cologne's song democracy.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-135": "Wencke Myhre (born 1947 in Oslo) is a Norwegian singer who became a star in Germany in the 1960s and 70s — with hits like \"Beiß nicht gleich in jeden Apfel\" (1968) and \"Er hat ein knallrotes Gummiboot\" (1970). She lived in Hamburg for a long time and often sang with a north German touch. She represented Germany at the Eurovision Song Contest in 1968. A symbol of German-Scandinavian musical relations and of the north German Schlager tradition.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-138": "\"Tessiner Risotto\" (Ticino risotto) is the southern Swiss variant of the Italian classic. Ticino lies south of the Alps and is Italian-speaking — hence a Mediterranean cuisine with a Swiss touch. Classically: risotto with porcini mushrooms (funghi porcini) and Merlot del Ticino, seasoned with Sbrinz or Parmigiano. The rice fields in the Magadino plain near Locarno are the northernmost in Europe. It is served in the \"Grotto\" (a Ticino tavern). A Swiss-Italian culinary bridge.",
  "wienerisch.w-133": "\"Wiener Eis\" (Viennese ice cream) has a long tradition — the first Italian ice cream makers arrived in the 19th century. Today Vienna's ice cream parlours (Tichy on Reumannplatz, Eis-Greissler, Schwedeneis on Schwedenplatz) compete for places on the summer best-of lists. Specialities: \"apricot-dumpling ice cream\" and \"Mozartkugel ice cream.\" In summer, queues stretch around the block. Strongly Italian-influenced, but with Viennese flavour variations. A Viennese summer ritual for generations.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-133": "Marktbreit is a picturesque little town on the Main with 4,000 inhabitants in the district of Kitzingen — a historic Main crossing with an old ferry. The Renaissance town hall of 1579 is one of the finest in Franconia. A pretty harbour, half-timbered houses, much tranquillity. Alois Alzheimer, the discoverer of the disease named after him, was born here in 1864. An insider tip for tourists seeking authentic, peaceful Franconia.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-137": "The \"Gelbe Wand\" (Yellow Wall) is the famous south stand of the Signal Iduna Park — 25,000 standing fans, the largest standing terrace in Europe. Before every match, gigantic choreographies of images, banners and confetti are created, planned for months in advance by fan groups like \"The Unity\" and \"Desperados.\" During Champions League matches the choreos are famous worldwide — even opposing coaches like Pep Guardiola have praised them. Ruhr football culture at world-class level.",
  "alemannisch.al-137": "Schramberg in the central Black Forest — 21,000 inhabitants — is famous for the Junghans watch factory, once the largest watch factory in the world. The Junghans architecture by the Bauhaus architect Heinrich Lersch is a listed monument. Today it houses the Junghans Terraced Building Museum. Also: Schramberg Castle and the Berneck power station (one of the oldest hydroelectric plants in Germany). Economically weak after the watch crisis, but with a rich industrial history. Local culture is alive and well.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-124": "The \"Hannickel\" was originally the Palatine migrant worker who toiled in the mines of the Ruhr region — from the first names \"Hann\" (Johann) and \"Nickel\" (Nikolaus). \"Mei Urgroßvadder war a Hannickel im Pott.\" (My great-grandfather was a Hannickel in the Ruhr.) Many Palatines moved away as seasonal workers in the 19th century. Today it is also used generally for a simple, down-to-earth man. A piece of Palatine social history is contained in this word. A classic term that keeps alive the migration for work and the origins of many Palatine families.",
  "hessisch.h-173": "\"Saure Rippche\" or \"Saure Rippchen\" are Hessian pork ribs that have been cured and marinated in vinegar, then cooked. A traditional Frankfurt home-style dish, often served with sauerkraut and potatoes. The sour note comes from the vinegar. A hearty, savoury Hessian meal — perfect after a long day's work and to go with cider.",
  "berlinisch.b-166": "The Tierpark Berlin in Friedrichsfelde was founded in 1955 in the GDR as an \"anti-Western zoo.\" With 160 hectares it is Europe's largest animal park. Today it is run in parallel with the Berlin Zoo (Förderverein Berlin). The animals have more space here. Popular with families. The Tierpark reflects Berlin's dual structure: the West zoo and the East animal park, both significant.",
  "bayerisch.by-145": "In a \"Schweinshaxn-Wettessen\" (pork-knuckle eating contest) at Bavarian fairs, the aim is to eat as many pork knuckles as possible in the shortest time. A knuckle weighs 1–1.5 kg, and the record stands at over 3 kg in 30 minutes. More spectacle than sport, often with beer sponsorship. A classic at Oktoberfest imitations and smaller fairs. The Bavarian counterpart to the American \"hot dog eating contest\" culture. Proof that Bavarians and meat have a special relationship.",
  "saechsisch.s-131": "Wernesgrüner Pils from the Vogtland has been documented since 1436 — one of the oldest breweries in Germany. The flagship brand is called \"Pilsner Legende\" — a lean, malty pilsner with a fine hop note. The brewery in Saxon Wernesgrün was, in GDR times, one of the few permitted private breweries (Carl-Ludwig-Brauerei) and stood for quality despite the shortage economy. Successfully modernised after reunification. Today part of the Bitburger Group. Saxon beer heritage.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-134": "Schillerplatz in the heart of Stuttgart is the historic centre of the city — adorned with the Schiller monument by Bertel Thorvaldsen (1839). Here you also find the Old Castle with the Württemberg State Museum and the Collegiate Church, where the dukes of Württemberg are buried. On Wednesdays and Saturdays the traditional Stuttgart weekly market takes place here — Swabian market atmosphere at its purest. Schillerplatz is Stuttgart's historic heart.",
  "koelsch.k-154": "Heinrich Böll (1917-1985) — born in Cologne — was one of the most important German writers of the post-war era. Nobel Prize in Literature in 1972. His works \"The Clown,\" \"Group Portrait with Lady\" and \"The Lost Honour of Katharina Blum\" are classics. Politically engaged, often critical. The Heinrich Böll Foundation of the Green Party bears his name. Cologne's most significant writer.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-136": "Marteria — real name Marten Laciny (born 1982 in Rostock) — is one of Germany's most successful rappers. His hometown of Rostock and the state of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern shape his lyrics. Hits like \"Lila Wolken\" (with Yasha & Miss Platnum) and \"Kids (2 Finger an den Kopf)\" became chart successes. He embodies a new generation of North German artists who move between Rostock's underground and the mainstream. He made North German hip-hop socially acceptable.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-139": "The \"Berner Platte\" is the hearty national dish of Bern — sauerkraut and/or beans with pork, bacon, sausages, tongue and sometimes smoked ham. Invented in 1798 after the Battle of Neuenegg as a victory meal. Today a classic at the Schmiedstube restaurant in Bern. A huge portion, often for two people. The Swiss counterpart to the Berner Geschnetzeltes, but more rustic. Traditional Bernese tavern cuisine in its original form. Filling, not for the faint of stomach.",
  "wienerisch.w-134": "The \"K.u.K. Hofzuckerbäckerei Demel\" on Kohlmarkt (founded in 1786) is, alongside Sacher, the most famous Viennese confectionery. Empire-style elegance, waitresses in white with lace caps. Known for the Anna torte, cream slices and the eternal \"Sacher torte war\" with Hotel Sacher (Demel had acquired the original recipe in 1888). A tourist magnet, but of first-class quality. Sitting at Demel is a staging of Vienna's imperial era. Café-confectionery history in its purest form.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-134": "Veitshöchheim near Würzburg is famous for two things: the Baroque Rococo court garden of the Würzburg prince-bishops (one of the most beautiful in Germany) and \"Fastnacht in Franken\" — the annual carnival TV show from the Mainfrankensäle, which has drawn millions to their screens since 1987. Stars like Peter Kuhn and Volkmar Halbleib appear there. Veitshöchheim has thus become synonymous with Franconian carnival humour. A must-see Main-Franconian broadcast.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-138": "The Schalke myth lives on through seven German championships (the last in 1958), the 1997 UEFA Cup, the most loyal fans in the world and a bond with the mining tradition. \"We are Schalke\" is more than club membership — it is identity, often passed down through generations. Despite relegations and crises, over 160,000 members remain. The Veltins-Arena is a royal-blue place of pilgrimage. \"Glück auf Schalke!\" unites the miners' tradition with footballing faith.",
  "alemannisch.al-138": "The Rottweil Fasnet is the oldest Swabian-Alemannic carnival — first documented in 1394. Its most famous fool figures: Schantle, Federahannes, Gschell, Biß, witches. The highlight: the \"Narrensprung\" on Carnival Monday, when hundreds of Schantles parade through the main street. Elaborate hand-carved wooden masks and ornate Häs (costumes) — some over 200 years old, passed down from generation to generation. UNESCO intangible cultural heritage. Rottweil at Fasnet is a must for Alemannic identity.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-125": "\"Bibbeleskäs\" is quark or cottage cheese, often seasoned with onions and chives. \"Grumbeere mit Bibbeleskäs un Leinöl, des is a Pälzer Klassiker!\" (potatoes with Bibbeleskäs and linseed oil, that's a Palatine classic). Originally from the Alemannic region, but also widespread in the southern Palatinate. It is eaten with jacket potatoes or spread on bread. The name comes from \"Bibbele\" (little lumps). Fresh, hearty and simple — the epitome of down-to-earth home cooking. A classic word from the Palatine dairy and food culture.",
  "hessisch.h-175": "For decades Hesse has been a politically shifting state — from Hans Karry (SPD) through Roland Koch (CDU) and Volker Bouffier (CDU) to Boris Rhein (CDU). Every Hessian premier has had his own Hessian touch. Hessian politics is considered humorous and pragmatic. The \"Hessenrunde\" on the hr broadcaster is a must for politically interested Hessians. Politics with a Hessian wit.",
  "berlinisch.b-167": "Berlin Central Station, opened in 2006 for the football World Cup, is Europe's largest crossing station — four platform levels intersect. A glass cathedral of steel and glass, designed by Meinhard von Gerkan. 320,000 travellers per day. A hub for ICE, regional trains and the S-Bahn. Berlin station architecture of the very highest class.",
  "bayerisch.by-146": "The \"Wiesn-Hit\" is the schlager song that brings the masses in the beer tents to sway together every year at Oktoberfest. Classics: \"Ein Prosit der Gemütlichkeit,\" \"Hey Baby,\" \"Skandal im Sperrbezirk,\" \"Cordula Grün.\" Mickie Krause, Andreas Gabalier and DJ Ötzi deliver fresh material every year. Bands like Münchner Zwietracht play five times a day, all in traditional dress. The Wiesn hits later dominate folk festivals and après-ski all year round. A Bavarian mass-culture phenomenon.",
  "saechsisch.s-132": "Radeberger Pilsner from Radeberg near Dresden has been Germany's oldest Pilsner since 1872 — brewed as the first German Pils following the Bohemian model. Chancellor Bismarck drank it at the Berlin Hofbräu, and King Friedrich August III declared it the court beer in 1905. A distinctive hop-bitter note, lean in character. Today the flagship of the Radeberger Group (Germany's largest brewing group). A symbol of Saxon brewing art and tradition.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-135": "The Markgröningen Shepherds' Run is one of the oldest folk festivals in Swabia — documented since 1723. Young shepherdesses and shepherds run barefoot across a stubble field — the winners become Shepherd King and Queen. The tradition goes back to the Swabian sheep farming of the Swabian Alb with its juniper heaths. The festival is intangible UNESCO cultural heritage. The run is demanding, painful and honourable — Swabian tradition in its purest form.",
  "koelsch.k-155": "Jürgen Becker is Cologne's best-known political-satirical cabaret artist — seen since 1983 on the \"Mitternachtsspitzen\" (WDR). Nicknamed \"Der Mitschnitt.\" He embodies Cologne directness and wordplay. With catchphrases like \"Schönen guten Abend, wer in seinem Lehnstuhl heut Abend sitzt ...\" he is regarded as a Cologne comedy legend. Known for his sharp yet warm-hearted style.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-137": "Helene Fischer (born 1984 in Krasnoyarsk, Russia) is Germany's most successful schlager singer. Her mega-concerts in Hamburg, Hanover and Bremen regularly sell out. With hits like \"Atemlos durch die Nacht\" she also reached the North German public. The Helene Fischer Show on ZDF is often broadcast from Hamburg — the Hanseatic city is a schlager stronghold. North German love of schlager is at a new high thanks to her.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-140": "The \"Bundesfeier\" on 1 August is the Swiss national holiday, introduced in 1891 for the 600th anniversary of the Confederation. Bonfires on every mountain, lanterns, a Federal Council speech on the Rütli meadow and in the municipalities. Grilling Cervelat sausages, waving Swiss flags, bells ringing at 8 p.m. Celebrated in a civic, less pompous manner than other national holidays. Swiss federal identity in a single night. Private and public fireworks (now regulated).",
  "wienerisch.w-135": "The \"Café Hawelka\" on Dorotheergasse (founded in 1939) is the Viennese artists' pub legend par excellence. Helmut Qualtinger, H.C. Artmann, Friedensreich Hundertwasser and later Falco — all were regulars. The interior seems unchanged since 1955: wooden chairs, yellowed light, dense smoke (before the smoking ban). Specialty: Buchteln at midnight. Leopold Hawelka died in 2011 at the age of 100. Far more than a café — a museum of Viennese subculture.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-135": "The court garden in Veitshöchheim is one of the most important Rococo gardens in Germany — laid out in 1763 for the Würzburg prince-bishops. 130 sandstone figures by court sculptors Wagner and Materno Bossi, artificial grottoes, water features and a lake with a palace pavilion. Symmetrically and strictly arranged, yet playful in detail. In summer it is the setting for concerts. For people from Würzburg it is a local recreation area, for tourists a Baroque jewel.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-139": "Pommes-Mayo is the Ruhr region standard at the chip stand — French fries with a generous dollop of mayonnaise, often combined with currywurst. Compared to \"Pommes rot-weiß\" (with ketchup and mayo) or \"Pommes Schranke\" (the same mix), it is the pure form. At every snack stand, in front of every stadium, next to every kiosk. The right mayo is a matter of taste — some swear by Thomy, others by Heinz. A Pott classic.",
  "alemannisch.al-139": "The original Black Forest cuckoo clock — invented around 1730 in Schönwald — is one of the best-known German products worldwide. A wooden cuckoo springs out of its little house on every full hour and calls as many times as the hour. Genuine Black Forest clocks bear the VdS certificate (Verein die Schwarzwalduhr). Three styles: the Bahnhäusle (with a water wheel), the chalet style (with dancing couples), the hunting style (with a stag's head). Especially collected in Japan and the USA. A symbol of the Black Forest worldwide.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-126": "A \"Schdriwwelkopp\" is a Struwwelkopf — someone with tousled, uncombed hair. \"Komm her, du Schdriwwelkopp, ich kämm dir die Hoor!\" (Come here, you tousle-head, let me comb your hair!). Said affectionately to children who emerge dishevelled from bed or come home from playing. Related to \"Struwwelpeter\" (Shock-headed Peter). From \"schdriwwele\" (to tousle) and \"Kopp\" (head). A tender, everyday Palatine word from family life. It shows the dialect's fondness for vivid compounds with \"-kopp.\"",
  "hessisch.h-176": "The Hessenring is the unofficial term for the motorway ring around Frankfurt — the A3, A5, A66 and A661 enclose the Rhine-Main region. With the Frankfurter Kreuz, one of the most important motorway interchanges in Europe. Commuters know the traffic jams \"auf'm Ring\" — up to 200,000 vehicles per day at the Frankfurter Kreuz. Everyday Hessian traffic.",
  "berlinisch.b-168": "The Federal Chancellery on the Spreebogen has been the seat of the Federal Chancellor since 2001 — designed by Axel Schultes and Charlotte Frank. Nicknamed the \"washing machine\" because of its characteristic curves. Together with the Federal Archives headquarters and the Paul-Löbe-Haus, it forms the political centre of Germany. Olaf Scholz works here — before him Merkel, Schröder, Kohl.",
  "bayerisch.by-147": "The \"Schuhplatteln\" is the most iconic Bavarian-Tyrolean men's dance. The dancers rhythmically slap their shoes, thighs and trousers while the \"Dirndl\" girls turn elegantly. It presumably originated in Alpine courtship rituals — originally the lads wooing the girls. Today it is a highly technical club dance with strict choreography. A mandatory part of every Bavarian traditional-costume society performance. Both a tourist cliché and genuine folk art — Bavarian identity in motion.",
  "saechsisch.s-133": "Felix Mendelssohn Bartholdy (1809–1847) was one of the most significant composers of the Romantic era and decisively shaped Leipzig's musical life. From 1835 until his death he was Gewandhaus Kapellmeister in Leipzig and in 1843 founded the first German conservatory (today the University of Music and Theatre \"Felix Mendelssohn Bartholdy\"). Works such as the Violin Concerto in E minor, the \"Hebrides\" Overture and the oratorio \"Elijah\" are world literature. His home in Leipzig is today the Mendelssohn Museum.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-136": "The Stuttgart Spring Festival is the Swabian answer to the Munich Spring Festival — three weeks in April/May on the Cannstatter Wasen. With festival tents, carousels and the traditional opening by the Mayor of Stuttgart. Smaller than the Cannstatter Volksfest in autumn, but just as cheerful. Swabia's \"folk festival trilogy\": Spring Festival, Volksfest, Christmas market — three highlights of the Swabian festive year. Lederhosen are optional.",
  "koelsch.k-156": "Wolfgang Niedecken (born 1951) is the frontman of BAP — Cologne's most successful rock band (since 1976). The band sings almost exclusively in Kölsch. Hits like \"Verdamp lang her,\" \"Kristallnaach\" and \"Et jitt kein Wood\" are cult. Niedecken is also known as a painter and political activist. BAP turned Kölsch into a rock-capable language — a historic act.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-138": "North Sea brown shrimp fishing is the economic and cultural foundation of many North German coastal towns — from Greetsiel and Neuharlingersiel to Cuxhaven. The shrimp cutters go out two or three times a day, dragging trawl nets across the seabed. The shrimp are cooked on board and then sent abroad (Morocco, the Netherlands) for peeling — a controversial practice. EU quotas strictly regulate the catch volumes. A dying craft with centuries of tradition.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-141": "The \"Bundeshaus\" in Bern (opened in 1902) is the seat of the Swiss parliament and Federal Council. In Florentine Renaissance style with a green dome over the old town. Inside is the famous domed hall with the Bundeshaus motto \"Unus pro omnibus, omnes pro uno.\" The Bundesplatz in front, with its 26 fountains (one for each canton), is often used for demonstrations. In summer there is an open-air cinema on the square. The centre of Swiss democracy. Politically and architecturally central.",
  "wienerisch.w-136": "The linguistic confusion: what is called \"Wiener Würstchen\" (Vienna sausages) in Germany is called \"Frankfurter\" by the Viennese — and vice versa! Both refer to thin pairs of scalded sausages. The Viennese variant (pork, milder) was actually invented in Vienna in 1805 by a butcher from Frankfurt. At the sausage stand they are a must: \"A Frankfurter mit'm Eitrigen\" (i.e. with hot mustard). A Viennese curiosity that makes ordering complicated. Sausage diplomacy.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-136": "The Main Trilogy comprises the three most famous Würzburg wine sites: Würzburger Stein (one of the best-known German wineries, the oldest documented vineyard, from 779), Würzburger Pfaffenberg and Würzburger Innere Leiste. These south-facing slopes above the Main produce Silvaner, Riesling and Müller-Thurgau of the highest level. To drink \"vom Stein\" is, for lovers of Franconian wine, like a pilgrimage. The Würzburger Stein was even named \"Mountain of the Year\" in 1990.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-140": "Manta jokes were the most popular joke genre in the Ruhr region in the 1980s — they targeted the clichéd Opel Manta driver: a fox tail on the antenna, a hairdresser as the front passenger, more guts than brains. Films like \"Manta — Der Film\" (1991) with Til Schweiger made the myth popular. In the Pott the Manta was THE car of working-class youth — cheap, fast, with a fat spoiler. Today cult, back then a way of life.",
  "alemannisch.al-140": "The monastery ruins in the Black Forest are popular motifs of Romantic painting — such as Allerheiligen in the northern Black Forest, once a Premonstratensian monastery (founded in 1196), today a picturesque ruin in the Lierbach valley. Waterfalls right next to it. Caspar David Friedrich was inspired by such Black Forest monastery ruins. The Allerheiligen ruin with its waterfalls is one of the most beautiful natural monuments of Baden — a place of pilgrimage for lovers of Romanticism. A piece of history in the middle of nature.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-127": "\"Dorscht\" is thirst — in the wine region a welcome guest. \"Ich hab a Dorscht, hol mer schnell a Schorle!\" (I'm thirsty, fetch me a spritzer quickly!). A saying: \"A Dorscht wie a ganze Kompanie\" (a thirst like a whole company). Anyone who \"kää Dorscht hot, is krank\" (has no thirst is ill), the Palatine says with a wink. The soft \"r\" and the \"scht\" are typical of the dialect. Thirst belongs to the Palatine way of life, since it is most happily quenched with a cool glass of wine. A classic everyday word, closely tied to wine and conviviality.",
  "hessisch.h-177": "Bad Vilbel, north of Frankfurt, is a small town famous for its mineral springs — \"Bad Vilbeler Wasser\" is one of the best-known table waters in Hesse. The Hassia springs and the Vilbel castle shape the town. With the annual Burgfestspiele, a regionally significant open-air theatre. Hessian water culture in a small town.",
  "berlinisch.b-169": "The Holocaust Memorial between the Brandenburg Gate and Potsdamer Platz consists of 2,711 concrete slabs in a grid pattern — designed in 2005 by Peter Eisenman. Directly beneath it is the information centre documenting the crimes of the National Socialists. With it Berlin shows responsibility for German history. Visited by tourists, but never as a selfie spot — dignity is required.",
  "bayerisch.by-148": "\"Bavarian etiquette\" has its own unwritten rules: \"Griaß Gott\" on entering, \"Pfiat's eich\" on leaving, \"A Maß, bittschön\" when ordering beer, and never wash the Lederhosen. On a visit to the tavern the man goes to his regular pub, and at the morning pint no bread is ordered. At the folk dance no sneakers. Bavarian decorum mixes Catholic customs with tavern culture. Anyone who doesn't master it remains forever a \"Zuagroaster\" (a newcomer).",
  "saechsisch.s-134": "Friedrich Schiller (1759–1805) spent decisive months in 1785 in Leipzig and the suburb of Gohlis — here he wrote his famous ode \"An die Freude\" (Ode to Joy), which Beethoven later set to music as the final chorus of his 9th Symphony (today the European anthem). The Schiller House in Leipzig-Gohlis is the only original Schiller residence open to the public. In Leipzig, Schiller found refuge from his financial difficulties with Christian Gottfried Körner and his friends.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-137": "The Strohgäu northwest of Stuttgart is a fertile loess hill landscape — one of the best arable soils in southern Germany. The name comes from \"Stroh\" (straw) — for centuries the region was the granary of Württemberg. Today it is a mix of agriculture (asparagus, maize), viticulture and residential areas for Stuttgart commuters. Adjoining it is the Heckengäu with its hedgerow landscapes. A Swabian cultural landscape with a long agricultural tradition.",
  "koelsch.k-157": "Wim Wenders (born 1945) — actually a native of Düsseldorf — spent formative years in Cologne. His \"Wings of Desire\" (1987) is an international film classic. Wenders belongs to the German film avant-garde and usually shoots in English. Even though he is from Düsseldorf, he shaped Cologne's cinema spirit. Berlin film history with a touch of Düsseldorf.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-139": "The cutter tradition of Northern Germany dates back to the 19th century — the iconic, often brightly painted wooden and steel boats are a symbol of the coast. Greetsieler Sieltief and Neuharlingersiel have especially picturesque cutter harbours. The boats often bear names like \"Hoffnung\", \"Anna\" or \"Nordstern\". In stormy seas they stay in port — and the red and blue hulls are reflected in the water. A tourist magnet and a way of life at the same time.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-142": "Albert Einstein lived in Bern from 1903 to 1909 — as a clerk at the Swiss Federal Patent Office. Here, in 1905, he wrote his famous four papers (\"Annus Mirabilis\"), including the theory of relativity. He lived at Kramgasse 49 (today the Einstein House Museum). His office window at the patent office on Genfergässli can be visited. A Bern local fact with world-historical weight — where else did the theory of relativity arise over sausages? Swiss scientific pride.",
  "wienerisch.w-137": "The \"Congress of Vienna\" (September 1814 – June 1815) reorganized Europe after Napoleon's fall. Its initiator: Prince Metternich. Representatives of all European powers convened in Vienna — Talleyrand for France, Wellington for England, Hardenberg for Prussia. \"The Congress dances, but it makes no progress\" — a Viennese joke about the endless balls. A lasting peace order until 1914. Vienna as the centre of Europe. A history-book classic.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-137": "The Würzburg city wall is one of the most impressive surviving medieval town fortifications in Germany — over 4 km long, with numerous towers, gates and ramparts. Built from the 13th century onward, it secured the free imperial city against attacks. Today large sections can be walked. Important gates: the Spitäle Gate, the Hauger Gate. The city-wall walk is one of the loveliest strolls in Würzburg. An atmosphere like in the Middle Ages.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-141": "\"Pottliebe\" is the deep, often inexplicable love of home felt by the people of the Ruhr region — a mix of pride, defiance and affection despite all its ugliness. Grönemeyer captured it perfectly in \"Bochum\": \"You're no beauty, but...\". Pott folk move away and come back. They grumble about the Pott, but won't let anyone else grumble about it. This love unites all generations, all origins, all neighbourhoods. Pottliebe is identity.",
  "alemannisch.al-141": "The Lake Constance climate is mild enough for extensive apple orchards — the region around Friedrichshafen, Meersburg and Konstanz is one of Germany's most important fruit-growing areas. In April, millions of apple trees blossom — the \"Lake Constance apple blossom\" draws tourists. Main varieties: Elstar, Gala, Boskoop, Rubinette. Also pears, plums, cherries. Traditional orchards shape the landscape. The fruit growers have perfected direct marketing — apple juice, cider, apple brandy. An economic pillar of the region.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-128": "A \"Krischer\" is a loudmouth or noisy person who is constantly bawling — from \"krische\" (to shout). \"Sei kää solcher Krischer, mer hört dich bis ins Nochbarhaus!\" (Don't be such a Krischer, they can hear you in the next house!) Said to someone who talks or yells too loudly. A screaming baby can also be \"a Krischer\". Onomatopoeic and apt. Part of the colourful Palatine vocabulary for people. In the sociable but usually easy-going Palatine manner, a loud Krischer quickly stands out unpleasantly.",
  "hessisch.h-182": "Sababurg Castle in northern Hesse is known as the \"Sleeping Beauty Castle\" — the Brothers Grimm are said to have drawn inspiration here for their fairy tale. The castle on a hill is today a hotel and restaurant, surrounded by the Sababurg Animal Park (a more than 900-year-old park with rare domestic animal breeds). Fairy-tale Hessian idyll for romantics.",
  "berlinisch.b-170": "The \"Topography of Terror\" is a documentation centre on the former Gestapo and SS grounds in Mitte. The building presents German Nazi history with images, documents and a partly preserved strip of the Wall. Over 1 million visitors a year. Here Berlin's history is examined without embellishment — important for education and remembrance.",
  "bayerisch.by-149": "\"Bavaria One\" was the mocked 2018 space vision of Minister-President Markus Söder — Bavaria as a high-tech hub of spaceflight. International ridicule erupted at once (including on \"Heute Show\" and the \"Late Show\"), because Söder came across as a bit too grandiose when announcing it. Despite the mockery, research funds were actually mobilized, among others for TU München. Today \"Bavaria One\" is the byword for overambitious CSU symbolic politics. A Bavarian political insider joke.",
  "saechsisch.s-135": "Richard Wagner (1813–1883) was born on 22 May 1813 in Leipzig — at Brühlgasse 88. The creator of \"Tannhäuser\", \"Lohengrin\", \"Tristan und Isolde\" and the \"Ring des Nibelungen\" spent his first years in Saxony and studied composition in Leipzig. Later he was court conductor in Dresden (1843–1849), until he had to flee after the May Revolution. The Wagner monument and museum in Leipzig honour the city's greatest son. Saxony decisively shaped his early work.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-138": "Filderstadt, south of Stuttgart, was formed in 1975 from the merger of five Filder municipalities — today, with 46,000 inhabitants, one of the most important commuter towns in Stuttgart's wealthy belt. Famous for Filderkraut (pointed cabbage) — a protected geographical indication. Stuttgart Airport and the Stuttgart trade fair also lie partly within Filderstadt's territory. Typical Swabian suburbia — modern, clean, well organized. Economically successful, culturally mixed.",
  "koelsch.k-158": "Westdeutscher Rundfunk (WDR) is Germany's largest ARD broadcaster — based in Cologne. With over 4,000 employees. It produces Tatort episodes featuring Cologne detectives, \"Mitternachtsspitzen\" and \"Aktuelle Stunde\". The WDR broadcasting house on Wallrafplatz is an architectural icon (with its \"Schmuckwand\" decorative wall). Today an important cultural institution of Cologne. The WDR children's channel KiKa also comes from Cologne/Erfurt.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-140": "Salting herring was for centuries the most important preservation method in the North — the Hanseatic League grew rich on it. Freshly caught herrings were salted and sold in barrels (tonnen). \"Matjes\" are young herrings, not yet ready to spawn, in a mild brine. The salting was seasonal work from summer to autumn. Still practised today in Holland (especially in Scheveningen, a rival of Glückstadt) and in Glückstadt on the Elbe. North German culinary world heritage.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-143": "\"Mani Matter\" (1936–1972) was the most important Swiss singer-songwriter of the 20th century — a Bernese-dialect chansonnier. A trained lawyer, he wrote subtle songs full of Swiss wit. \"Hemmige\", \"Dr Sidi Abdel Assar vo el Hama\", \"Bim Coiffeur\" — cult songs. He died at 36 in a car accident. His work: 80 songs, all cultural treasures. The Swiss counterpart to Brassens. Still learned in schools today. The Mani Matter legacy is upheld by the Mani Matter Encouragement Award.",
  "wienerisch.w-138": "Maria Theresa (1717–1780) — Archduchess of Austria, \"mother\" of the Habsburg monarchy. Mother of 16 children (including Marie Antoinette and Joseph II). With the Pragmatic Sanction she pushed through female succession. She reformed administration, schooling (compulsory education in 1774), the military and the economy. Tobacco monopoly, potato cultivation, census — all her doing. Schönbrunn Palace was her summer extravagance. The defining empress of Vienna and Austria. The \"Maria Theresa thaler\" remained the currency for a long time.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-138": "Main river fishing has a centuries-old tradition in Würzburg, Schweinfurt and Bamberg — the Main fishermen caught eel, pike, carp and zander for the markets. Today only a few professional fishermen remain on the Main, keeping their tradition alive. \"Main fisher\" smoked carp is a Franconian delicacy. The Würzburg Main fishermen's festival in summer recalls this old trade. Water sports and fishing on the Main remain part of Franconian identity.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-142": "The Steigerlied \"Glück auf, der Steiger kommt\" is the official anthem of German mining — and of the Ruhr region in particular. Originating in the 16th century in the Saxon Ore Mountains, it was adopted by Ruhr mining. It is sung before every kick-off at Schalke home matches — one of the most moving stadium rituals in Germany. It is also a must at the funerals of former miners. The Steiger was the foreman in the shaft. The end of mining in 2018 made the song even more important.",
  "alemannisch.al-142": "Most is a central drink in the Alemannic region — fermented apple juice, slightly alcoholic (4–6%). Every farmer with an orchard traditionally had his own Most in the cellar. It is served in the \"Mostkeller\" (cider taverns). The difference from Apfelwein: Most is more tart, less sweet. In the Markgräflerland and around Lake Constance, the Most culture flourishes. \"Möstle drinkers\" are the regulars. Traditional orchards are preserved through Most production. Alemannic farming culture in a glass.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-129": "\"Dehääm\" means home, at home — one of the most heartfelt Palatine words. \"Dehääm is es halt am scheenschte!\" (Home is simply the nicest place!) It is full of the sense of homeland that is so cherished in the Palatinate. A saying: \"Dehääm is dehääm\" (home is best). The long \"ää\" is characteristic of the dialect. Whoever is \"widder dehääm\" (back home again) has arrived where they belong. A classic word that expresses the strong Palatine attachment to home and the region's cosy way of life.",
  "hessisch.h-183": "Bad Wildungen is Germany's largest spa town — with over 6 million overnight stays a year. Famous for the Wildungen springs (Helenenquelle, König Otto Quelle). Also the birthplace of Wilhelm Heinrich Riehl, an ethnographer of the Hessians. With Friedrichstein Castle and the historic old town. The Hessian spa-town way of life.",
  "berlinisch.b-171": "Berliners often have particular \"meeting points\" for gatherings — the World Clock at Alex, the Victory Column, the Goldelse, Bayerischer Platz, the Brandenburg Gate. These places are firmly anchored in Berlin culture: \"Let's meet at Alex at 6 p.m.\" Understood without further explanation. Social-geographic anchors of a metropolis.",
  "bayerisch.by-150": "The \"Bayernhymne\" (\"Gott mit dir, du Land der Bayern\") is the official song of the Free State of Bavaria, lyrics written in 1860 by Michael Öchsner. It is sung at state occasions, sporting events and CSU party conventions. Unlike the German national anthem, it is cherished very emotionally — many Bavarians know it by heart. Three verses, the last especially grandiose (\"Heil unserm König\"). It is also sung in football stadiums (FC Bayern!). Bavaria's musical self-affirmation.",
  "saechsisch.s-136": "The Thomaskirche in Leipzig was for 27 years the place of work of Johann Sebastian Bach (1723–1750) as Thomaskantor. Here he composed most of his church cantatas, the Mass in B minor and the St Matthew Passion. His grave has been in the chancel of the church since 1950 — a place of pilgrimage for music lovers from all over the world. The Thomaner choir still sings motets in the church weekly. The famous Bach monument in front of the Thomaskirche is a photo motif.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-139": "Sindelfingen, southwest of Stuttgart, has 64,000 inhabitants and is the most important Mercedes-Benz production site — over 35,000 employees at the plant. Here the S-Class, E-Class and CLS are built. Without Mercedes, Sindelfingen would be a different town — the Mercedes identity shapes everything. The Sindelfingen district of Maichingen is also a Mercedes industrial zone. Swabia's car town par excellence — when Mercedes coughs, Sindelfingen catches a cold.",
  "koelsch.k-159": "The WDR broadcasting house on Wallrafplatz in Cologne is part of German media history — built from 1948 to 1952 by Peter Friedrich Schneider. The sober post-war broadcasting house was the workplace of many notable journalists and presenters. Architecturally one of the most important works of the post-war period. Today the WDR headquarters. Wallrafplatz is also a meeting place for Cologne's culture enthusiasts.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-141": "Königsberger Klopse are an East Prussian speciality that was brought to Northern Germany by expellees after the expulsion in 1945 — above all to Schleswig-Holstein and Lower Saxony. Meatballs made from minced meat with anchovies, served in a caper-cream sauce, with boiled potatoes and beetroot. A classic GDR restaurant dish. Despite their East Prussian name, they are today a firm part of North German cuisine. Comfort food and a memory of lost territories.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-144": "\"Schwiizerdeutschi Mundartmusik\" (Swiss-German dialect music) experienced a boom from the 1970s on — Polo Hofer and his Schmetterband founded Bernese-German rock. Stephan Eicher, Patent Ochsner, Züri West, Plüsch, Bligg — dialect is now mainstream. Festivals like the Gurten Festival or Open Air Frauenfeld have launched Swiss acts to fame. Unlike High German pop: dialect feels authentic, regional, locally patriotic. Swiss self-affirmation in sound. The art of identity.",
  "wienerisch.w-139": "Franz Joseph I (1830–1916) — Emperor of Austria-Hungary, reigned for 68 years (1848–1916). Married to Elisabeth (\"Sisi\"). The embodiment of the long-lived Habsburg myth. Devoted to duty, an early riser, living simply (Tafelspitz instead of luxury). Tragically: his brother Maximilian shot in Mexico, his son Rudolf's suicide at Mayerling, his wife Sisi murdered in 1898. His death in 1916 ushered in the end of the Habsburg monarchy. Vienna still lives off the Franz Joseph image: Schönbrunn, Hofburg, Sisi Museum.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-139": "The Hesselbergfest is the great Middle Franconian mountain festival on the 689-metre-high Hesselberg near Wassertrüdingen. A farmers' market, medieval spectacle, concerts, hang-gliding. In summer the viewing platform and the trail up to the \"Wallburg remains\" draw thousands of hikers. After the Nazi era, the \"Frankenberg\" had to reinvent itself — today a symbol of democratic folk culture in Middle Franconia. The farmers from the Hahnenkamm region celebrate here.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-143": "The \"Karneval-Verteidiger\" (carnival defender) is a humorous Pott expression for someone who resists the Rhineland carnival craze and sits with a beer in the corner pub while everyone else runs around in costume. In the Pott, carnival is different — more down-to-earth, less pompous. True Pott folk defend their peace and quiet against the \"Helau madness\". A mix of self-irony and quiet pride in the Pott's distinctive character.",
  "alemannisch.al-143": "\"Schäfle\" is the Alemannic diminutive of \"Schaf\" (sheep) — meant affectionately and rurally. In the Black Forest and on the Swabian Alb there are still numerous sheep farmers who graze their animals on the steep hillsides. The Black Forest sheep is an endangered breed. Schäfle-Schmaus (roast lamb) is a traditional Alemannic dish. Also used figuratively: \"Du bisch a Schäfle\" — a gentle, somewhat naive person. Alemannic animal diminutives are popular.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-130": "A \"Schlawwerschnut\" is a sweet tooth, a glutton for sweets who licks their lips at anything sugary. \"Du klää Schlawwerschnut, host schun widder vum Riwwelkuche genascht!\" (You little Schlawwerschnut, you've been nibbling the crumble cake again!) From \"schlawwere\" (to lick) and \"Schnut\" (snout/mouth). Said affectionately to children with a sweet tooth. A warm, vivid Palatine word from everyday family life. It shows the dialect's fondness for vivid compounds around the mouth and eating. Anyone who is a Schlawwerschnut can't walk past a single sweet.",
  "hessisch.h-185": "The Waldecker Land in the northwest of Hesse is a region rich in tradition — until 1929 the Principality of Waldeck. Shaped by forests, the Edersee and the Kellerwald (UNESCO World Heritage beech forests). With the residence town of Bad Arolsen and Waldeck Castle. Rural, rich in nature, with its own culture. Hesse's green heart.",
  "berlinisch.b-172": "The World Clock on Alexanderplatz, erected in 1969 by Erich John, is a GDR design icon. The rotating column shows the current time in 148 cities worldwide. Above it, a stylized solar system. A classic meeting point for Berliners. Also architecturally interesting — socialist pop brutalism. A survivor of the GDR era.",
  "bayerisch.by-151": "The \"Dirndlgwand\" is the traditional women's dress in Bavaria and Austria — consisting of a bodice, blouse, skirt and apron. Originally the working clothes of country maids, today it is festive traditional dress for the Oktoberfest, weddings and folk costume festivals. The position of the apron bow signals relationship status (left = single, right = taken, back = widow or waitress).",
  "saechsisch.s-137": "The Karl Marx Monument in Chemnitz — a 7.1-metre-high bronze sculpture of Marx's head — was created in 1971 by the Soviet sculptor Lew Kerbel and is, after Mount Rushmore, the second-largest portrait sculpture in the world. The people of Chemnitz affectionately and ironically call it \"Nischel\" (Saxon for head). Despite the renaming of Karl-Marx-Stadt back to Chemnitz in 1990, the monument remained standing and is today a landmark and tourist attraction. Socialist heritage and pop-art icon at once.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-140": "Böblingen, south of Stuttgart, has 51,000 inhabitants and is a high-tech stronghold — an IBM site (European headquarters), Hewlett-Packard, Daimler research. The Nürtingen-Geislingen University of Economics and Environment also has campuses here. Together with Sindelfingen, Böblingen forms a twin complex of Swabian industry. Despite its modernity, Böblingen preserves Swabian tradition — half-timbered houses in the old town, Swabian club culture.",
  "koelsch.k-160": "Hans Imhoff (1922–2007) was Cologne's chocolate king — he founded Stollwerck AG in 1972 (with the Sarotti brand) and the Chocolate Museum on the Rhine in 1993. His company produced over 20% of all chocolate in Germany. A private philanthropist and patron of Cologne sport. His chocolate fountain (3 m high, 200 kg of chocolate!) in the museum is a cult attraction. Sweet Cologne economic history.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-142": "Bratheringe are fried herrings marinated in a vinegar-and-onion marinade — a North German classic that often arose as a way of using up leftovers. They used to be made at home in every North German family: dredge the herrings in flour, fry them, place them in a glass container with vinegar marinade and let them steep for at least 24 hours. Served with fried potatoes and dark rye bread. A must at every North German snack bar and at weddings. Creamy, tangy, salty — the perfect combination.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-145": "\"Hörnli\" are small, curved Swiss durum-wheat noodles — the counterpart to Italian maccheroni, but thicker and coarser. Classically used in \"Älplermagronen\" — a Swiss mountain dish with Hörnli, potatoes, cheese, bacon and applesauce. A school-canteen staple. Originally a hearty leftovers dish from the dairy-farming world. Today a symbol of Swiss home cooking — cheap, filling, kid-friendly. \"Hörnli mit Hackfleisch\" (with minced meat) is a classic. A Swiss pasta tradition.",
  "wienerisch.w-140": "The \"Karlsplatz\" is Vienna's largest transport hub — U1, U2, U4, plus Wien Mitte station within walking distance. Here stand the baroque Karlskirche (1737), the Secession building, the Wien Museum and the university of music. Otto Wagner's legendary urban-railway pavilions (1898) on Karlsplatz are Art Nouveau icons. In summer the \"Popfest Wien\" festival takes place here. For a long time a 1990s drug hotspot — now upgraded. A Viennese urban space with both history and present.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-140": "The Berga brewery in Bad Rodach near Coburg is a traditional Upper Franconian family brewery — founded in 1864. Classic specialities: Berga Hell, Berga Pils, Berga Bock. With the highest density of breweries in the world found in Franconian Switzerland and Upper Franconia, Berga is one of hundreds of small breweries that have preserved their regional identity. Pride: brewed by hand, distributed regionally, with local hops and malt.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-144": "The \"Tante-Emma-Pott\" is the affectionate Ruhr-region version of the classic Tante-Emma (corner) shop — a small grocery store, often on a street corner, run by a family. The owner knows every customer, keeps a tab, gives tips. In the Ruhr, Polish, Turkish and Kurdish families have taken up and expanded this tradition. Where the corner shop dies, a piece of Ruhr-region neighbourliness dies too. Aldi and Rewe can't replace the chat.",
  "alemannisch.al-144": "The \"Hofgut\" is, in the Alemannic region, the term for a larger farming estate with dwellings, stables and outbuildings. In the Black Forest it is often built as an enclosed Black Forest farmhouse (Schwarzwaldhof). Many Hofgüter have been worked by the same family for centuries — some for over 500 years. Today they are often combined with holiday flats (farm-stay holidays). The Alemannic farmstead culture shapes the landscape and the farmers' sense of identity.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-131": "\"Alla hopp!\" is the Palatine rallying cry par excellence — \"come on, let's go now!\". \"Alla hopp, mir misse loslaafe, sunscht versaume mir de Bus!\" (Come on, we have to get going or we'll miss the bus!). The \"alla\" comes from the French \"allez\" (go!) and is one of the most-heard Palatine words of all. Reinforced with \"hopp\", it expresses drive and a call to action. Used when setting off, getting stuck in and spurring others on. A classic Palatine exclamation that nicely captures the people's determined, pragmatic manner.",
  "hessisch.h-186": "The Bergpark Wilhelmshöhe in Kassel has been a UNESCO World Heritage Site since 2013 — the largest hillside park in Europe, with the famous Hercules statue, Wilhelmshöhe Palace and the world's largest artificial water features. When the water runs on Sundays, it flows 250 m down over cascades — an impressive spectacle since 1714. Hesse's showpiece park.",
  "berlinisch.b-173": "Unlike the famous Dresden Stollen, Berlin also has its own Stollen tradition — a fine yeast dough with almonds, raisins and candied lemon peel. Berlin Stollen is usually lighter and less dense than the Saxon kind. It is baked in the run-up to Christmas by Berlin bakers — an old address: \"Bäckerei Wiener Conditorei Caffeehaus\" in Charlottenburg. A quiet Berlin baking tradition.",
  "bayerisch.by-152": "A \"Watschn\" is a hefty slap in the face. In Bavarian it is often used in a humorously coarse way — a \"bayerische Watschn\" is considered unmistakably hearty. Also in a figurative sense: \"dei Watschn baumlt\" means a defeat or a setback. In the inn, it used to be a punishment for uncooperative behaviour at cards too.",
  "saechsisch.s-138": "\"Aha!\" is, in Saxon usage, a universal exclamation — from sudden realisation to sceptical confirmation. With the typical Saxon melody it becomes an art form: raised in pitch it sounds surprised, spoken low it is wait-and-see and sceptical, with a smile it is approving. The \"Aha!\" is one of the first words by which non-Saxons recognise the dialect from its sound. Also a stylistic device of Saxon cabaret artists such as Olaf Schubert. More than a word — a whole attitude to life.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-141": "Calw in the northern Black Forest is a town of 24,000 inhabitants — above all famous as the birthplace of Hermann Hesse (1877). His birthplace and the Hermann Hesse Museum are pilgrimage sites for Hesse admirers from all over the world, especially from Japan and South Korea. Hesse described his home town in \"Unterm Rad\" (Beneath the Wheel) and \"Hermann Lauscher\". The half-timbered old town on the river Nagold is one of the most beautiful in Swabia. Swabian cultural heritage par excellence.",
  "koelsch.k-161": "Cologne Zoo in Riehl was founded in 1860 — one of the oldest zoos in Germany. With its elephant park, the Hippodrome and the tropical house, it is one of Germany's most beautiful zoological gardens. Famous: the red-bellied short-necked turtles and the Asian adventure world. Hennes the billy goat (FC Köln's mascot) has lived here since 1950. Popular with families — over 1.8 million visitors a year.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-143": "Hamburg Pannfisch is a classic leftovers dish from Hamburg harbour — boiled fish from the day before is reheated in the pan with onions and fried potatoes, served with mustard sauce and gherkin. Various kinds of fish (cod, coley, plaice) are cut small and fried. The mustard sauce with shallots and cream is the secret weapon. North German leftovers cooking raised to culinary heights — today Hamburg Pannfisch is a must for tourists in every fish restaurant.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-146": "The \"Älplerchilbi\" is the Swiss cattle-descent festival — celebrated in autumn when the livestock comes back down from the alpine pastures into the valley. Important in central Switzerland (Engelberg, Stoos, Rigi). A procession of herdsmen in traditional dress, blessing of the cheese, Älplerchilbi songs, giant cheese carts. The cows wear flower crowns and bells. A folk festival with church and feasting. Embedded in a centuries-old herding tradition. An important customary event. A tourist magnet and at the same time a genuine tradition.",
  "wienerisch.w-141": "The \"Burgtheater\" on the Dr.-Karl-Lueger-Ring is one of the most important German-language drama theatres in the world. Founded in 1741 by Maria Theresa, new building 1888. The huge double staircase was painted by the Klimt brothers. Viennese call it simply \"die Burg\". Director Claus Peymann caused scandals from 1986 to 1999 (Bernhard, Jelinek). A visit to the Burgtheater is a social ritual. Standard repertoire: Schiller, Nestroy, Schnitzler, Bernhard. The stage of German-language theatre.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-141": "Spalt hops from Spalt in Middle Franconia are among the finest hops in the world — one of the four globally recognised \"noble hop varieties\" (together with Tettnang, Hallertau and Saaz). The growing area covers only 400 hectares, but the quality is legendary. Aroma: floral, spicy, with fine citrus notes. Premium breweries worldwide pay top prices. The Spalt farmers are proud of their hops — sometimes worth more than gold.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-145": "The Hoheward spoil tip between Herten and Recklinghausen, at 152 metres, is one of the highest mining spoil tips in Europe — on the plateau stands the spectacular \"Horizon Observatory\", two huge steel arches that mark the solstices and equinoxes. A walkable sundial. A vantage point over the whole Ruhr region — in clear weather you can see from Cologne to Münster. A showcase project of renaturation — where spoil once lay, there is now recreation.",
  "alemannisch.al-145": "The \"Älpler\" is, in the Alemannic region, a mountain farmer or herdsman who spends the summer with the livestock on the alpine pastures. A living tradition in the southern Black Forest and in Vorarlberg. The Älpler tend the livestock, milk the cows and make cheese and butter directly up on the alp. In autumn the cattle come down to the valley in a festive cattle descent — a cultural duty. The Älpler's life is hard but proud. A connection to nature and tradition, pure and simple.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-132": "\"Alla gut\" means \"all right then, fine\" — the Palatine formula for agreement or giving in. \"Alla gut, dann komm ich halt aach mit zur Kerwe.\" (All right then, I'll come along to the fair too.) Also used as a farewell: \"Alla gut, mir sähn uns!\" (All right then, see you!). The versatile \"alla\" (from the French \"allez\") here introduces a calm consent. It expresses composure and agreement without big words. A classic everyday Palatine word that reflects the region's relaxed way of life and crops up in every other conversation.",
  "hessisch.h-188": "Hesse has many \"secrets\" — little-known places and customs that only locals know. From the \"Loreley of Hesse\" (the Lorelei on the Rhine, actually in Rhineland-Palatinate, but Hessians claim it) to small gorges, old breweries and forgotten monasteries. Hesse's \"secrets\" are the charm of the region. Insider knowledge is a source of pride.",
  "berlinisch.b-177": "Charlottenburg is West Berlin's traditionally wealthy district — with Charlottenburg Palace (one of the most important Hohenzollern palaces), the Kurfürstendamm, the KaDeWe and the Deutsche Oper. Olympic Stadium, radio tower, exhibition grounds — all Charlottenburg. Genteel and bourgeois in the west, more working-class in the north. A West Berlin identity.",
  "bayerisch.by-154": "\"Brotzeit\" is the Bavarian between-meal snack — usually mid-morning or mid-afternoon, with bread, cheese, sausage, radish, pickled gherkins and, of course, a litre of beer (a Maß). More than just a snack: a social ritual. On hikes, building sites, in the garden — the Brotzeit is part of the Bavarian attitude to life. Brotzeit-Brettl: the wooden board on which it is all served.",
  "saechsisch.s-139": "The making of incense cones in the Erzgebirge (Ore Mountains) — above all in Crottendorf and the surrounding area — has been documented since 1856. From charcoal dust, sawdust, tragacanth gum and natural aromas (frankincense, sandalwood, myrrh), the small incense cones are pressed. Burned inside an incense smoker figure or smoking house, they give off the unmistakable Christmas scent of Saxon living rooms. The Crottendorfer company is the market leader. UNESCO-worthy craftsmanship and Saxon cultural heritage.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-143": "\"Du bisch a Käpsele!\" is, in Swabian, an affectionate compliment — it describes a clever, sharp person. The \"Käpsele\" derives from \"Köpfchen\" (little head) and describes someone with brains and skill. It embodies the Swabian tradition of tinkering: Käpsele are the inventors, tinkerers, problem-solvers. Also used ironically: \"Du bisch mir a Käpsele!\" — when someone thinks they are especially smart. A Swabian saying that combines recognition with a wink.",
  "koelsch.k-162": "Aachen — west of Cologne on the border with Belgium and the Netherlands — was Charlemagne's residence. Aachen Cathedral (a UNESCO World Heritage Site) houses his tomb. The Aachen Charlemagne Prize is awarded each year to European figures. Aachen and Cologne are both Rhinelanders, but culturally different. Aachen is more \"Öcher Mundart\" than Kölsch.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-144": "The Mecklenburg Lake District, with over 1,000 lakes, is the largest contiguous lake region in Central Europe. The Müritz (Germany's largest inland lake), the Plauer See, the Kummerower See — embedded in forests and gentle rolling hills. Müritz National Park is a UNESCO biosphere reserve. Water hikers, houseboaters, anglers and birdwatchers (cranes!) love the region. Castles and manor houses also shape the picture. A North German natural paradise — the \"blue province\".",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-147": "Roger Federer (born 1981 in Basel) is a Swiss tennis legend — 20 Grand Slams, 310 weeks as world number one, eight Wimbledon titles. He played top-level tennis from 2003 to 2022. The embodiment of Swiss elegance, courtesy and multilingual charm (Swiss German, standard German, English, French). Beyond sport: a symbolic figure of Switzerland worldwide. After ending his career, celebrated like a head of state. \"RF\" as a brand. Switzerland's number-one ambassador. More than tennis: a synonym for Switzerland.",
  "wienerisch.w-142": "The \"Volksoper\" on the Währinger Gürtel is Vienna's \"second opera\" — a venue for operetta, comic opera and musicals. Founded in 1898 as the Emperor's Jubilee City Theatre. Strauss operetta (Die Fledermaus, Der Zigeunerbaron) is traditionally performed here, alongside musicals (The Sound of Music). A more relaxed atmosphere than at the State Opera, with Viennese wit. Marcel Prawy filmed operetta here and shaped its image. The Viennese home of operetta since the 20th century. Underrated touristically, important culturally.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-142": "Spalt, in the district of Roth, is the Franconian hop town — the centre of the world-famous Spalt hop cultivation since the 8th century. At the Spalt HopfenBierGut museum you learn everything about hops and beer. The town of 5,000 inhabitants has its own brewery (the Stadtbrauerei Spalt — one of the oldest municipal breweries in Germany). In September there is a hop festival and harvest thanksgiving. Anyone who really understands beer has been to Spalt.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-146": "The Ruhr-region wedding is a genre all of its own — usually Catholic-Polish in flavour, with a big family (all 80 cousins invited), a club house instead of a castle, Schäufele and fries instead of Tafelspitz, Polish music and beer instead of champagne. The day lasts until morning, everyone dances with Uncle Karli and Aunt Helga, and on Sunday there's the leftovers meal. Authentic, down-to-earth, warm-hearted — and guaranteed without any fuss. That's how the Ruhr celebrates.",
  "alemannisch.al-146": "The Bermatingen cherry (also \"Markdorf cherry\") from the hinterland of Lake Constance is a particularly prized regional variety — especially aromatic thanks to the mild climate. Bermatingen, Markdorf and Salem are cherry villages. In June there is the traditional cherry festival. The cherries are also distilled into Lake Constance cherry brandy (Kirschbrand). The cherry trees blossom in mid-April — a tourist highlight. Meadow orchards with old cherry trees are home to rare birds.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-133": "A \"Dapp\" is a clumsy oaf or awkward person, someone who \"dappt\" — that is, treads about clumsily and stumbles. \"Du Dapp, jetz host de Eimer umgschtoße!\" (You oaf, now you've knocked over the bucket!). An affectionately exasperated Palatine word; the same root is found in \"Dappschädel\". Anyone called a Dapp is usually good-natured but clumsy. Used within the family and among friends without any real malice. A classic regional term of abuse that expresses more head-shaking than anger and belongs to the rich Palatine vocabulary for klutzes.",
  "hessisch.h-189": "Frankfurt has a special underground railway — the Stadtbahn runs partly above ground (as a Stadtbahn) and partly underground (as a U-Bahn). The RMV network (Rhine-Main Transport Association) is one of the largest in Germany. Nine underground lines, plus an S-Bahn ring. A constant source of Frankfurt pride — and of frustration when there are delays. Hessian mobility.",
  "berlinisch.b-178": "Charlottenburg Palace is the largest palace in Berlin — built at the end of the 17th century for Queen Sophie Charlotte. The famous Golden Gallery, the Porcelain Cabinet and the palace gardens draw the tourists. Badly damaged in the war, it was faithfully rebuilt. With the mausoleum of the Prussian Queen Louise and the Belvedere in the park. Berlin's royal heritage.",
  "bayerisch.by-156": "The \"Madl\" is, in Bavarian, any girl or young woman — from childhood to marriage. Affectionate and respectful at once. \"A fesches Madl\" is a pretty girl; a \"Diandl\" is often a more old-fashioned synonym. Omnipresent in folk songs, Schlager hits and at traditional-costume festivals: \"Bayrisch Madl\", \"Mei Madl\", \"Schean is mei Madl\". Also in love letters: \"Liebes Madl…\" (Dear girl…).",
  "saechsisch.s-140": "The Erzgebirgsverein (Ore Mountains Association) was founded in 1878 in Schneeberg and today, with over 12,000 members in more than 130 local groups, is one of the largest regional heritage associations in Germany. It cultivates the Ore Mountains dialect, traditions, hiking trails and mining culture. It organises the famous miners' parades in Annaberg, Schneeberg and Marienberg. Preserving folk art (Schwibbögen candle arches, incense smoker figures, miner figures) is also a concern of the association. Saxon heritage care at the highest level.",
  "koelsch.k-163": "The International Charlemagne Prize of Aachen — awarded every year since 1950 on Ascension Day — honours people who have rendered outstanding services to European unification. Laureates: Winston Churchill, Konrad Adenauer, Henry Kissinger, Helmut Kohl, Tony Blair, Bill Clinton, Emmanuel Macron. A symbol of German-European reconciliation. The Rhineland's contribution to world politics.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-145": "The Müritz in Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania, at 117 km², is the largest lake lying entirely within Germany — Lake Constance is bigger, but belongs to three countries. \"Müritz\" comes from the Slavic \"morcze\" (little sea). Indeed the Müritz feels like an inland sea. The Müritz National Park is home to white-tailed eagles, ospreys and cranes. In summer a water-sports paradise, in spring and autumn a birdwatchers' Eldorado. A North German natural wonder.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-148": "The \"Gotthard\" is both a pass and a tunnel — the heart of Swiss transport through the Alps. The pass was already central to north-south traffic in the Middle Ages. The railway tunnel opened in 1882 (the first connection of its kind in the world), the road tunnel in 1980, the base tunnel in 2016 (at 57 km the longest railway tunnel in the world). It connects German-speaking Switzerland with Ticino and Italy. A traffic jam at the Gotthard is a Swiss summer plague. It is also mentioned in the national anthem (\"Trittst im Morgenrot daher\"). A Swiss symbol of identity and transport.",
  "wienerisch.w-143": "The \"Musikverein\" on Karlsplatz, opened in 1870, houses the \"Golden Hall\" — the most beautiful-sounding concert hall in the world. The Vienna Philharmonic and Vienna Symphony play here. An annual global highlight: the \"New Year's Concert\" of the Vienna Philharmonic, broadcast on television worldwide (over 100 countries, 50 million viewers). Architect: Theophil Hansen. A seat in the Golden Hall is a cultural privilege. Vienna's mecca of music.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-143": "Forchheim is the gateway town to Franconian Switzerland — 32,000 inhabitants, historic timber framing, an imperial palace (Kaiserpfalz) from the 14th century. Famous for the Forchheim \"Annafest\" — one of the largest folk festivals in Upper Franconia, with the 23 beer cellars in the Kellerwald. Here cellar beer (Kellerbier) is served straight from the mountain — pure Franconian tradition. The people of Forchheim are proud of their brewing tradition: the density of breweries in the Forchheim district is the highest in the world.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-147": "Pride in hard graft (Maloche-Stolz) is the core of the Pott identity — pride in honest, hard work, often physical, often dirty, always valuable. In the Pott it's not an academic degree that counts, but what you've achieved with your hands. The miner, the steelworker, the dock worker — they built up Germany. This appreciation of physical labor sets the Pott apart to this day from the perceived academic world of other regions. Dignity through hard graft.",
  "alemannisch.al-147": "Black Forest ham is a protected geographical indication (PGI) — only ham smoked over fir wood in the Black Forest may bear this name. Deep red color, robust aroma, slightly sweet taste from the smoking. The hams are cured for several weeks and then smoked repeatedly with fir and spruce smoke. Famous producers: Adler-Schwarzwaldhof, Hans Adler, Schiessle. Breakfast with Black Forest ham and farmhouse bread — the very essence of Alemannic indulgence.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-134": "\"Haarisch\" is a Palatine intensifier meaning \"awfully, very, immensely.\" \"Des war haarisch schee gestern owend!\" (That was awfully nice last night!). Also \"haarisch viel\" (a great deal) or \"haarisch heiß\" (very hot). It's used to express an intensification forcefully, similar to \"arg\" or \"mächtig.\" A typically sounding Palatine adjective that often crops up in everyday speech. It expresses both enthusiasm and excess in equal measure. A classic dialect word that underscores the Palatines' emotional, vivid way of speaking.",
  "hessisch.h-190": "Hesse has its own burger culture — from \"Bembel & Burger\" in Frankfurt to local restaurants offering unusual combinations (apple wine burger, green sauce burger). Modern Hessian gastronomy combines tradition with innovation. Hessian food culture today is often unconventional and creative. Young Hesse.",
  "berlinisch.b-179": "The Kurfürstendamm — \"Kudamm\" for short — is West Berlin's most famous shopping street. 3.5 km long, with upscale boutiques, restaurants and cafés. The Kaiser Wilhelm Memorial Church (war-destroyed) stands at its beginning. Formerly Berlin's counterpart to the Champs-Élysées. Today less glamorous than Friedrichstraße, but traditional. Berliners are fond of the Kudamm.",
  "bayerisch.by-157": "In Bavarian, the \"Hax'n\" is both the famous pork knuckle (crispy roasted, with sauerkraut and dumplings) and a person's leg. \"Hax'n her!\" means \"come here!\" or \"get moving!\". A culinary legend: the Bavarian pork knuckle is regarded as the crowning glory of tavern cuisine, often served with beer and mustard. \"Sich auf d'Hax'n machen\" means to set off on one's way.",
  "saechsisch.s-141": "Plauen embroidery and lace is a worldwide unique embroidery tradition from Plauen in the Vogtland — developed in the 19th century. The dissolving of lace backing in acid baths was a Plauen invention. Plauen lace adorns wedding dresses around the world, including royal weddings. The Plauen Lace Museum documents the tradition. The embroidery boom at the end of the 19th century made Plauen the richest city in Saxony — until the Great Depression of 1929. Today small but fine manufactories remain.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-144": "Swabian proverbs are life philosophy in a single sentence: \"Mer kennat ällas außer Hochdeutsch\" (We can do everything except standard German), \"Schaffe, schaffe, Häusle baue\" (Work and save), \"Saving is the most Swabian virtue.\" These sayings shape Swabian identity and are taken up in every advertising slogan, in every cabaret program. They are not just stereotypes, but embody actual values: diligence, thrift, down-to-earthness, ingenuity.",
  "koelsch.k-164": "Ottostraße in Cologne-Ehrenfeld is a cult student living address — cheap, lively, multicultural. Turkish, Arab and Cologne communities mingle. A late-night corner shop (Späti), a snack bar, a hipster café — all in one street. Ottostraße is the honest answer to the gentrified Belgian Quarter. Cologne reality without frills.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-146": "Greetsiel is the most beautiful fishing village in East Frisia — a place of 1,500 inhabitants with a picturesque shrimp-cutter harbor, traditional twin windmills (two windmills side by side!) and lovingly restored brick architecture. A tourist magnet, especially in summer. Here the shrimp cutters with their colorful hulls set out. Also known through Klaus-Peter Wolf's \"Friesland\" crime novels (filmed for ZDF). East Frisian idyll in its purest form — a postcard motif.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-149": "\"Älplermagronen\" is the Swiss farmers' national dish — cooked Hörnli (pasta) and potatoes, mixed with cream and mountain cheese (often Sbrinz or Gruyère), topped with fried onions. Side dish: homemade applesauce. A farmers' dish from the leftover cuisine of the Alpine huts — cheap, filling, simple. A main meal in ski resorts and mountain huts. \"Magronen\" with applesauce sounds odd, tastes fantastic. Swiss comfort food. A winter-sports favorite.",
  "wienerisch.w-144": "The \"Wiener Festwochen\" (founded in 1951) are Vienna's great May–June festival — theater, music, dance, performance, all international. The opening on Rathausplatz traditionally features a huge concert with a live broadcast. The program runs from the Burgtheater to Hall G in the MuseumsQuartier. The artistic direction changes — it has been shaped by Markus Hinterhäuser, Frie Leysen and others. One of the most important European festivals alongside Avignon, Edinburgh and Salzburg. A cultural highlight of Vienna.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-144": "The Forchheim Annafest is the most important folk festival in Upper Franconia — held annually in July on the Kellerwald since 1840. 23 beer cellars where cellar beer is served straight from the mountain, thousands of beer benches under oaks and beeches. A million visitors in 11 days. Unlike the Munich Oktoberfest, it's family-friendly and cozy, with no beer-tent noise. \"Auf de Keller geh\" (going to the cellars) is the Forchheim way of life in summer.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-148": "Pott solidarity is the famous helpfulness in the Ruhr region — when a neighbor needs help, you're there without asking. It is rooted in the miners' tradition: underground you depended on one another. Today it shows itself during a move, in illness, at neighborhood festivals. \"In the Pott no one is left alone\" — that's more than a saying, it's lived practice. This solidarity has survived all the structural crises.",
  "alemannisch.al-148": "The Schäppel is the famous Black Forest bridal crown — an elaborate, tall headdress made of glass beads, little mirrors and colorful ribbons. It was traditionally worn by brides and unmarried women at high feast days. Some historic Schäppel weigh several kilos and have been family heirlooms for centuries. In St. Georgen, Triberg and Furtwangen there are still Schäppel wearers at major occasions. A masterpiece of craftsmanship and a symbol of female Alemannic tradition.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-135": "A \"Schlabbeflicker\" is a bungler or botcher — literally someone who only patches slippers instead of making proper shoes. \"Der Handwerker is a Schlabbeflicker, des hält kää drei Daag!\" (That craftsman is a botcher, it won't last three days!). Used mockingly for someone who works sloppily or unprofessionally. From \"Schlabbe\" (slipper) and \"flicke\" (to mend). A vivid Palatine term of abuse for a lack of care. It belongs to the colorful vocabulary about poor work and expresses a tongue-in-cheek disdain for botched jobs.",
  "hessisch.h-191": "The Friedrich Stoltze Fountain on the Hühnermarkt in Frankfurt honors the Hessian dialect poet. A bronze sculpture of Stoltze with his characteristic ribbed glass (Geripptes). A symbol of the cultivation of Hessian dialect and culture. Reconstructed in the \"New Old Town.\" A highlight of the Hessian cityscape.",
  "berlinisch.b-180": "The Kaiser Wilhelm Memorial Church on Breitscheidplatz is a West Berlin landmark — the ruin of the war-destroyed main tower was deliberately not rebuilt, as a memorial. The \"hollow tooth\" stands beside the new octagonal church by Egon Eiermann. A symbol of Berlin's history: destruction, remembrance, new beginning. Classic Berlin architectural history.",
  "bayerisch.by-158": "A \"Bazi\" in Bavarian is a lovable rascal — clever, cheeky, charming and not always entirely honest. It can be meant affectionately (\"du Bazi du!\") or slightly pejoratively for a scoundrel. In Munich dialect it's also a synonym for a Munich native (\"Münchner Bazi\"). Karl Valentin and Karl Stranzinger cultivated the Bazi type. Its origin is unclear, probably from \"Lumpazi.\"",
  "saechsisch.s-142": "The Cottbus brewery in Lusatia has a long tradition — brewing is mentioned in Cottbus as early as 1492. Today's Cottbuser Aktien-Brauerei produces traditional Lusatian beers with local hops and water from the Spreewald. In the GDR era an important supply enterprise, successfully privatized after reunification. The \"Cottbuser\" and \"Lausitzer\" brands are valued in eastern Germany. The Sorbian heritage is reflected in bilingual labels.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-145": "The Dinkelacker private brewery in Stuttgart was founded in 1888 by Carl Dinkelacker and is, alongside Hofbräu, the most important Stuttgart brewery. CD-Pils (Carl Dinkelacker Pils) and Schwabenbräu are the main brands. Compared to the Bavarian corporate breweries, Dinkelacker has remained family-run and Swabian down-to-earth. The red-white-blue Dinkelacker umbrellas are a fixture of Swabian beer gardens. A Swabian beer heritage in its third generation.",
  "koelsch.k-166": "A \"Schlachten Pott\" (slaughter pot) is a humorous carnival term for a large cauldron in which everyone gets \"stirred together\" — the carnival-goers as a colorful mix. Symbolically: Cologne is a melting pot of cultures, religions and professions. At carnival everyone comes together. An old Cologne metaphor with a political undertone: Cologne is tolerant, multicultural, warm-hearted.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-147": "Since the 2000s, Low German has been taught as an elective in more and more North German schools — in Lower Saxony, Schleswig-Holstein, Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and Hamburg. The EU Charter for Regional and Minority Languages protects Low German as a regional language. Over 150,000 pupils actively learn Low German. Initiatives such as \"Platt in de Schaul\" and the \"Institute for Low German Language\" drive the revitalization forward. Language rescue in the North.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-150": "\"Direkti Demokratie\" (direct democracy) is the core feature of Swiss politics — citizens decide directly on issues in popular votes (4 times a year). Popular initiatives (100,000 signatures) and referendums (50,000) allow citizens to influence matters at the constitutional and legislative level. Worldwide unique in this intensity — over 600 votes since 1848. At the municipal level often directly via an assembly. Despite its slowness, a factor of stability. Swiss political identity: not representation, but participation. The \"sovereign\" is the people.",
  "wienerisch.w-145": "The \"Donauinselfest\" on Vienna's Danube Island is Europe's largest open-air festival with free admission — up to 3 million visitors over three days in June. Founded in 1984 by the SPÖ (politically organized, party-independent line-up). Over 600 hours of program on about 13 stages — rock, pop, folk music, DJ sets. Niki Lauda and Falco have performed here. A must-attend of the Viennese summer. Often politically controversial (an SPÖ staging?), but culturally indispensable.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-145": "The Frankenwald Nature Park covers 102,500 hectares of low mountain range in Upper Franconia — from the Frankenwald to the Thuringian border. Extensive spruce and beech forests, clear streams (Saale, Rodach, Steinach), high moors. A hiking and mountain-biking paradise. Raft trips on the Wild Rodach are a highlight. A structurally weak region — not economically rich, but a landscape treasure. Those seeking quiet will find it here. The Frankenwald is the \"green lung\" of Franconia.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-149": "Structural change (Strukturwandel) describes the painful transformation of the Ruhr region after the end of coal mining (2018) and the steel industry (from the 1980s). Collieries became cultural centers (Zollverein), steelworks became parks (Landschaftspark Nord), slag heaps became viewpoints. Hundreds of thousands of workers had to reorient themselves — many families affected. Today a services region, an IT hub, a university region. Successful, but with a sense of loss. Structural change is the Pott's fate.",
  "alemannisch.al-149": "The island of Mainau in Lake Constance is one of the most beautiful garden islands in Europe — across 45 hectares, the mild Lake Constance climate allows palms, orchids and butterflies to thrive. It is owned by the Bernadotte family (Swedish nobility). Tulip bloom in April, rose bloom in June, dahlia bloom in autumn. The largest butterfly garden in Germany. Over 1.2 million visitors a year. Connected to the mainland by a bridge. A botanical paradise in the midst of the Alemannic language area.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-136": "A \"Lallbeb\" is a windbag, someone who talks a lot without sense — from \"lalle\" (to speak indistinctly) and \"beb/Bebbel.\" \"Hör ned uff de Lallbeb, der schwätzt nur dummes Zeug!\" (Don't listen to the windbag, he only talks nonsense!). Used affectionately-mockingly or in annoyance for a chatterbox. Related to \"Lalleworscht,\" but a notch more disparaging. A typical Palatine word from the dialect's rich study of human types. It describes someone whose words you needn't take seriously, because only idle chatter comes out.",
  "hessisch.h-192": "The New Old Town in Frankfurt was completed in 2018 — a reconstruction of historic timber-framed and stone houses that were destroyed in the war. 35 houses, 15 of them reproductions. With the Golden Scales (Goldene Waage), the Stoltze Fountain and narrow alleys. A mix of tourist magnet and historical restoration. A top-class Hessian reconstruction project.",
  "berlinisch.b-181": "The \"Mauerstreifen\" — the former death strip between the two walls — is today preserved in Berlin as green Wall trails. It is marked by a double row of cobblestones in the asphalt. The \"Berlin Wall Trail\" — a 160 km cycle path around West Berlin along the former Wall — is today a popular hiking route. History you can touch.",
  "bayerisch.by-160": "A \"Schmankerl\" is a special culinary delicacy — usually a Bavarian specialty like apple strudel, Kaiserschmarrn or Dampfnudeln. Also in a figurative sense: a \"real Schmankerl\" is something special, a highlight. A \"Schmankerl tour\" is a culinary journey through Bavaria. It derives from the Middle High German \"smackvol\" (tasty). It is often used on menus as a temptation.",
  "saechsisch.s-143": "The Lower Lusatian Sorbs — also called \"Wends\" — are the northern variant of the Sorbian people, settled mainly in the Cottbus area and the Spreewald. They speak Lower Sorbian (different from the Upper Sorbian in Bautzen). They have their own costumes and customs, such as the \"bird wedding\" festival (Vogelhochzeit) on January 25 and the Zampern (a Shrovetide custom). The Lower Sorbian language is severely endangered — only a few thousand active speakers remain. A UNESCO heritage of endangered languages. A Saxon-Brandenburg cultural heritage.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-146": "The Heuberg is the highest plateau of the Swabian Alb — over 1,000 meters high, in the south of the Swabian Alb massif between Tuttlingen and Albstadt. A barren limestone landscape with juniper heaths, sheep farming and the harshest climate in Württemberg. \"Heuberger\" are proverbially tough and taciturn. The pilgrimage site of Heiligenkreuztal and the Beuron monastery shape the picture. The Swabian Alb in its harshest form.",
  "koelsch.k-167": "A \"Schoofs-Sitzung\" is a very informal, often private carnival session — in the living room, in the back room of a corner pub, in a club house. No big program, no Dreigestirn (carnival trio) — just friends celebrating together during carnival. These mini-sessions are the heart of Cologne carnival: unembellished, warm-hearted, local.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-148": "The Lüneburg Heath in Lower Saxony is one of the oldest cultural landscapes in Europe — 230 km² of protected heathland. In August the heath blooms purple — hundreds of thousands come to the \"Heather Blossom Festival\" (Heideblütenfest). Heidschnucken (an old sheep breed) and beekeepers (heather-blossom honey) shape the region. The Wilseder Berg, at 169 m, is the highest elevation. Hiking, carriage rides, covered-wagon tours. The heath poet Hermann Löns also shaped the image. North German natural idyll par excellence.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-151": "\"Hoi zäme!\" is the Swiss greeting for several people — \"zäme\" means \"together.\" It is used when entering a room with several people — informal, friendly, uncomplicated. Swiss greeting culture has many gradations: \"Grüezi\" (formal), \"Hoi\" (among friends), \"Sali\" (casual). \"Hoi zäme\" is the most common form among acquaintances in a group situation.",
  "wienerisch.w-146": "The \"Karlskirche\" on Karlsplatz, built in 1737 by Johann Bernhard Fischer von Erlach, is the masterpiece of Viennese Baroque. Emperor Charles VI had it erected as thanks for the end of the plague in 1713. Two flanking columns recall Trajan's Column and the Column of Marcus Aurelius — Viennese syncretism between antiquity and Christianity. The interior has dome frescoes by J.M. Rottmayr. Today also a concert venue (Vivaldi concerts). A UNESCO World Heritage Site as part of Vienna's old town.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-146": "Mainfranken is THE wine-growing region of Franconia — along the Main from Aschaffenburg to Bamberg. 6,000 hectares of cultivated land, 3,500 winegrowers, 50% Müller-Thurgau, 25% Silvaner, plus Bacchus, Domina, Spätburgunder. Climate: continental with warm days and cool nights — ideal for dry, mineral wines. The Bocksbeutel bottle is the iconic hallmark. With the GG classification, top wines rank among Germany's best. Mainfranken wine is identity.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-150": "\"Glück Auf forever\" — on 21 December 2018, the Prosper-Haniel colliery in Bottrop, Germany's last hard-coal mine, was closed. 150 years of mining in the Pott came to an end. The Steigerlied was sung, miners wept. But \"Glück Auf\" remains an eternal greeting — at Schalke, at family celebrations, at funerals. The miner is gone, but his spirit and his greeting live on in the Pott. An entire era has shaped the memory — and goes on shaping it.",
  "alemannisch.al-150": "The Alemannic identity unites four countries: Southern Baden, Switzerland, Vorarlberg and Alsace. This linguistically and culturally coherent region was politically split in the 19th century, but the Alemannic consciousness remains strong. Shared: dialect, mentality, customs (Fasnet, maypole, witches' fire), cuisine (Wähe, Maultaschen, Käsknöpfle). Alemannic dialect poets such as Johann Peter Hebel or Carl Spitteler created identity. \"We speak Alemannic!\" is a self-affirmation. A cross-border cultural community with over 10 million speakers.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-137": "The \"Babbe\" is the father or dad — a warm, everyday Palatine family word. \"Mei Babbe schafft im Wengerd, seit ich denke kann\" (My dad has worked in the vineyard for as long as I can remember). Related to the Rhenish and Hessian \"Babbe.\" The mother is the \"Mamme,\" the father simply the Babbe. Used with no formality at all, it expresses the close, warm family bond. A classic word from everyday Palatine family life, passed on in every generation and reflecting the familiar relationship between children and parents.",
  "hessisch.h-193": "Bembel craft is a Hessian pottery trade — the characteristic blue-gray stoneware jugs are still handmade by a few workshops. Original Bembel come from the Westerwald (actually Rhineland-Palatinate), but Hesse associates them with its cider culture. Genuine Bembel are no mass-produced goods — connoisseur pieces cost 50 to 200 euros.",
  "berlinisch.b-182": "The Tempodrom at Anhalter Bahnhof is Berlin's distinctive event venue — the two tent-shaped halls recall a sporting circus. Opened in 2001 (after years of delay), for concerts, comedy and events. A Berlin architectural icon of the 2000s. With the historic city boundary (the S-Bahn ring) in the background.",
  "bayerisch.by-161": "A \"Trumm\" is a large, chunky piece of something — a \"Trumm Brot\" (hunk of bread), a \"Trumm Kuchen\" (slab of cake), a \"Trumm Mannsbild\" (hulk of a man). It expresses size and often also heaviness or bulk. \"A oarechts Trumm\" is a huge specimen. Used for people too: \"a wuchtiges Trumm\" is a sturdily built man. Usable in both a positive and a negative sense. It comes from Middle High German \"trum\" (piece, block).",
  "saechsisch.s-144": "The Bockwurscht — the Saxon pronunciation of Bockwurst — is classic snack-bar food in Saxony. Heated up in hot water, served with sharp Bautzen mustard and a bread roll. At every train station, in every market hall, at every snack stand. In the GDR the Bockwurscht was a mass product and a status symbol — a Bockwurscht with a roll was a Sunday luxury. Today a culinary symbol of East German identity. Unthinkable without mustard.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-147": "The classic Swabian way of serving Maultaschen: floating in a hearty beef or chicken broth, sprinkled with chives. \"Maultaschen in der Brüh\" (Maultaschen in broth) is the original form — filled with sausage meat, spinach and bread cubes, cooked in the broth. In summer they are also served fried with onions. Homemade Maultaschen are a family ritual — the making of Maultaschen is passed down over generations. Swabian soul food par excellence.",
  "koelsch.k-168": "At the Rose Monday parade the children shout \"Kamelle un Strüssjer!\" — sweets and little bouquets of flowers. These are thrown from the floats into the crowd. 300 tonnes of sweets, 700,000 little bouquets per Rose Monday parade. A traditional carnival practice with a social meaning: the powerful (on the floats) provide for the people (along the roadside). Cologne carnival politics.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-149": "With 926 km², Rügen is Germany's largest island — located in the Baltic Sea off Stralsund. Famous: the chalk cliffs of the Königsstuhl (Caspar David Friedrich's \"Chalk Cliffs on Rügen\"), the seaside resort of Binz with its resort architecture, the Jasmund National Park with Europe's oldest beech forests (UNESCO World Heritage). 7.5 million overnight stays per year. Also Prora — the monumental Nazi holiday complex. Northern German Baltic beauty in its purest form.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-152": "\"Schaffe\" is the everyday Swiss German word for \"to work\" — Standard German \"arbeiten\" is rarely used. \"I schaffe i de Bank\" (I work at the bank). The word has a practical, hands-on ring to it that suits the Swiss work ethic. \"Schaffisch hüt?\" (Are you working today?) is the typical question. The noun is \"d'Schaffi\" or \"d'Arbet.\" Similarly common throughout the Alemannic region (including Swabia).",
  "wienerisch.w-147": "The \"Servite Church of the Annunciation\" in the 9th district (Alsergrund) is the only Viennese church in the Italian Early Baroque style, built 1651–1670. It stands in the picturesque Servite quarter — a quiet corner with cobblestones, boutiques and cafés. The quarter is a Viennese insider tip, almost Mediterranean in feel. Inside the Servite Church is the Peregrini Chapel, popular for quiet devotion. An example of Vienna's lesser-known but charming sacred architecture.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-147": "A \"Hafele\" is a small pot or cooking vessel in Franconian — a diminutive of \"Hafen\" (pot, from Middle High German). The Würzburg \"Hafenmarkt,\" where pottery was once sold, also derives from it. \"Die Suppn im Hafele auf'n Herd stelln\" (to put the soup in the little pot on the stove) — everyday Franconian kitchen talk. The word shows how conservatively the Franconian dialect preserves old terms. Rare today, but still alive at grandma's.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-151": "\"Wat soll dat denn?\" is the classic Ruhr region question of incomprehension or indignation. The \"was\" becomes \"wat,\" the \"das\" becomes \"dat\" — typical Ruhr-area consonant softening. The sentence can range from genuine bewilderment to angry accusation — tone and facial expression decide. In the Pott people wear their heart on their tongue: if something's not right, they say so.",
  "alemannisch.al-151": "The \"Bähnli\" is the Alemannic diminutive for \"Bahn\" (train/tram) and usually refers to the tram or smaller narrow-gauge railways such as the Mittenwaldbahn or the Black Forest railways. In Freiburg you ride the \"Bähnli\" through the old town, and in Basel the \"Drämmli\" (tram) is a symbol of the cityscape. The diminutive expresses familiarity in Alemannic.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-138": "The \"Mamme\" is the mother or mum — the warm Palatine counterpart to the \"Babbe.\" \"D'Mamme hot heut Riwwelkuche gebacke\" (Mum baked crumble cake today). Related to the Rhenish \"Mamme.\" In the Palatine family, Babbe and Mamme are the familiar names for the parents. Used affectionately and quite naturally, often kept for a lifetime. A classic word from the region's everyday family life, expressing the warm, down-to-earth bond between children and mother and living on across generations.",
  "hessisch.h-194": "The Löwentaler — a historic Hessian coin — depicts the blue-and-white striped Hessian lion. Today a collector's item and souvenir. The \"Hessen-Taler\" was also issued for the 800th anniversary of Hesse in 2013. Hessian coinage heritage for numismatists and friends of the homeland. Pride in Hesse's history cast in metal.",
  "berlinisch.b-183": "Sigmund Freud — a Viennese, actually — had close ties to Berlin. His son Ernst was an architect here, and many of Freud's pupils worked in Berlin. The Berlin Psychoanalytic Institute (founded in 1920) was a world center. Berlin's urban therapy culture is also a Freud legacy. Berlin intellectuals and therapists keep the heritage alive.",
  "bayerisch.by-162": "The \"Stüberl\" is a small, cozy parlor or an inviting living room. A diminutive of \"Stube\" (parlor). In Bavaria it often denotes the homey atmosphere of a village inn with wood paneling, a tiled stove and a regulars' table. \"Aufs Stüberl gehen\" means to go to the inn. Also common in hotel names (\"Müllerstüberl\"). The epitome of Bavarian coziness and conviviality.",
  "saechsisch.s-145": "The \"Pfaffe\" is the Saxon, mildly mocking term for the pastor or clergyman — slightly disparaging, but rarely really ill-meant. In GDR times, when the Church was under pressure, the word took on an ironic yet respectful undertone. Despite secularization, Saxony is a region with a rich tradition of church music (the Thomaner, the Kreuzchor). The \"Pfaffe\" is part of it — sometimes mocked, often valued.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-148": "The \"Seven Swabians\" are the famous fairy-tale figures of the Brothers Grimm — seven clumsily brave Swabians who set off on adventures armed with a long spear. Allgäuer (the leader), Seehasle, Nesselheinz, Geli, Marli, Veitli and Jockli. The tale mocks Swabian thrift and caution. Today an identification figure — from the \"Schwabenstreich\" to the \"Seven Swabians\" cocktail. Swabian self-irony at the highest level.",
  "koelsch.k-169": "\"De Vrang\" or \"Vränge\" are Cologne nicknames for carnival societies — derived from \"Vorrang\" (precedence) or \"Frunschaff\" (friendship). Every carnival club has its own nickname. The \"Red Sparks\" are \"de Funke,\" the \"Blue Sparks\" too, and so on. Insider knowledge for Cologne carnival-goers. It helps you find your way around the complex Cologne carnival scene.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-150": "Usedom is Germany's second-largest island — shared with Poland (the eastern third is Polish). The \"Sun Island\" thanks to its 1,917 hours of sunshine per year (a German record). The three imperial spas of Heringsdorf, Ahlbeck and Bansin, with their magnificent 19th-century resort architecture, draw tourists from all over Europe. Europe's longest seaside promenade (12 km) links the towns. Peenemünde, with its V2 history, is a memorial. A northern German Baltic paradise.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-153": "\"Stei\" is the Swiss German form of \"Stein\" (stone) — through the dropping of the final \"n.\" Omnipresent in the mountains, frequent in idioms: \"En Stei vom Härz falle\" (a stone falling from one's heart), \"chli Steiwiifer\" (wine that's worth little). Stone-throwing (\"Steistosse\") is a traditional Swiss sport at Schwingfest gatherings. Stones play an important role in Alpine culture.",
  "wienerisch.w-148": "The \"Stadtbahn pavilions\" at Karlsplatz, built in 1898 by Otto Wagner, are Art Nouveau architectural icons. Originally entrances to the Vienna Stadtbahn (today U-Bahn lines U4 and U6). With floral patterns, wrought iron and the elegance typical of Vienna. One pavilion today houses an Otto Wagner museum, the other a café. A rescued treasure of the cityscape. In contrast to the Classicist Karlskirche ensemble — Viennese architecture in layers.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-148": "The Würzburg bratwurst is different from the Nuremberg Rostbratwurst — bigger, thicker, more coarsely seasoned. It is served above all with sauerkraut and a bread roll, not in the small 7–9 cm version. People in Würzburg insist: \"We have our own bratwurst!\" Even if the Nuremberg ones are world-famous, the Würzburg one has its loyal fans. The differing bratwurst traditions are a piece of Franconian local patriotism.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-152": "\"Hömma!\" is the Ruhr region's call to listen up — a contraction of \"Hör mal!\" (Listen!). It's used to get attention or to announce a story. \"Hömma, ich erzähl dir wat!\" (Listen, let me tell you something!) introduces a story. No Pott conversation works without \"Hömma.\" The tone ranges from friendly and familiar to threatening and admonishing — all in one word.",
  "alemannisch.al-152": "The \"Bobbele\" is the Alemannic term for a baby or infant — an affectionate diminutive widespread in Southern Baden, Switzerland and Alsace. It can also be used metaphorically for someone very delicate or sensitive. The double \"bb\" and the drawn-out \"ele\" give the word a warm-hearted, cuddly note.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-139": "The \"Määdsche\" is a girl — the affectionate diminutive of \"Maad.\" \"Des klää Määdsche vum Nochbar is arg lieb\" (The neighbor's little girl is so sweet). The ending \"-sche\" or \"-che\" is the typical Palatine diminutive, similar to the Standard German \"-chen.\" Used tenderly for little girls or young women. A classic word from the family and everyday vocabulary, showing the soft, warm-hearted side of the dialect. A Määdsche is always meant with warmth and affection.",
  "hessisch.h-195": "Eppertshausen is a small Hessian municipality in the Darmstadt-Dieburg district — 6,000 inhabitants, representative of hundreds of similar villages. With cider culture, clubs and a Schoppen tradition. Hessian village life with its characteristic features — the mayor knows everyone, the clubs are active, the Kerb (parish fair) is celebrated. Hessian countryside in its purest form.",
  "berlinisch.b-184": "Bertolt Brecht (1898–1956) — born in Augsburg, in East Berlin from 1949 — founded the Berliner Ensemble with Helene Weigel. His \"Threepenny Opera,\" \"Mother Courage\" and \"Galileo\" shape world theater. The Brecht House on Chausseestraße is a museum today. His political theater and his epic alienation revolutionized the stage. Berlin high culture.",
  "bayerisch.by-163": "The \"Lederhosen\" are the traditional men's costume in Bavaria and Tyrol — usually made of deer or chamois leather, with suspenders and elaborate embroidery. Originally the working clothes of mountain farmers and hunters. Today a folk-costume symbol at the Oktoberfest, weddings and traditional-dress festivals. The older and greasier, the more authentic (\"no nia gwaschn\" — never washed — is proudly recounted). Short, mid-length and knee-length versions.",
  "saechsisch.s-146": "Köstritzer Schwarzbier from Bad Köstritz in Thuringia (on the border with Saxony) has a 480-year tradition — documented since 1543. A deep-dark, mild-sweet beer with a roasted-malt aroma. Johann Wolfgang von Goethe drank it to ease his illness. Otto von Bismarck, too, valued the \"dark gold.\" Today one of Germany's best-known brands. Saxon-Thuringian beer cultural heritage. The Schwarzbier is often mixed with cola as a \"Bismarck.\"",
  "schwaebisch.sw-149": "The Esslingen medieval market in the Advent season is Swabia's unique Christmas market — across two squares an authentic medieval market is held with performers in historical dress. At the same time, the classic Christmas market with mulled wine, roasted chestnuts and Stollen. The combination makes the market unique throughout Germany. Knights, jesters, swordsmen and plague musicians shape the atmosphere. Over 700,000 visitors per season. A Swabian Advent highlight.",
  "koelsch.k-170": "Unlike the Moselle or the Rheingau, Cologne has no winegrowing of its own — the climate is too harsh, the soil unsuitable. Nevertheless, there are experimental winegrowing projects today in the Cologne hinterland (Köln-Worringen). Cologne folk mainly drink Moselle Riesling and red wine from Italy. Kölsch (the beer) is and remains the main drink. Wine is secondary here.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-151": "\"Schietwetter\" is the notorious bad weather in Low German — rain, wind, storm and cold all at once. \"Schiet\" means \"muck, shit\" and is no taboo word in Low German but an everyday expression. \"Bei Schietwetter blifft man tohuus\" (In foul weather you stay at home) is a classic. On the North Sea coast Schietwetter is everyday life, especially in November. The North Germans bear it with humor and a cup of Pharisäer (coffee with rum).",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-154": "\"Schniposa\" is the Swiss favorite meal of children and students: Schnitzel, fries, salad — the classic restaurant side-dish combination. The acronym took hold especially in the 80s and 90s in student slang. Orderable in any restaurant, always a hit with kids. A pragmatic coinage that shows how the Swiss play with language.",
  "wienerisch.w-149": "The \"Hofburg Chapel\" in the Vienna Hofburg has been a Viennese royal place of worship since 1296. Here, on Sundays, the Vienna Boys' Choir sings the High Mass together with members of the Vienna Philharmonic and the State Opera Choir — a tradition over 500 years old. Tickets are sought-after, the atmosphere intimate. Haydn, Mozart and Schubert composed masses especially for the Hofburg Chapel. Viennese music history in the original. A touristic insider experience.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-149": "The Pressack is a Franconian and Bavarian sausage specialty — a brawn of pig's-head meat, rind, blood and spices, pressed into a pig's stomach. There is red Pressack (with blood) and white Pressack (without blood). It is cut into slices and served with vinegar, oil, onions and farmhouse bread as a Brotzeit (snack). A traditional way of using up leftovers, today prized as a delicacy. Part of every Franconian Brotzeit.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-153": "\"Boah ey!\" is the typical Ruhr-area exclamation of astonishment, indignation or surprise. An extension of \"Boah!\", intensified by the appended \"ey\". \"Boah ey, dat is geil!\" expresses enthusiasm, \"Boah ey, dat geht doch nich!\" expresses indignation. The combination sounds just like the 1980s Ruhr region, when Manta jokes and Pott slang were at their peak.",
  "alemannisch.al-153": "The \"Brägel\" or \"Brägeli\" are fried potatoes in Alemannic, often with onions and bacon. In southern Baden and Switzerland a classic supper, served with sausage salad or a fried egg. The potatoes are boiled, cooled, sliced and then fried crispy in the pan. A real \"Brägel\" has to be crisp on the outside and soft on the inside.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-140": "The \"Grumbeersupp\" is the hearty potato soup — cooked from \"Grumbeere\" (potatoes), a classic of Palatine home cooking. \"In winter there's a hot Grumbeersupp with sausage in it.\" Cooked with carrots, leek, celery and often a sausage or bacon, it warms you up on cold days. At home in every Palatine kitchen and as filling as it is tasty. A classic dish of the region's down-to-earth food culture, underlining the importance of the potato as a staple food of the Palatinate.",
  "hessisch.h-196": "The \"Hessenwall\" is a historical term for the town fortifications of many Hessian towns — Marburg, Friedberg and Wetzlar still have preserved rampart structures. In the Middle Ages they protected the townsfolk. Today they are parks and hiking trails. Hessian medieval heritage as a green ring around the town.",
  "berlinisch.b-185": "Helene Weigel (1900-1971) — Brecht's wife and an actress — ran the Berliner Ensemble after Brecht's death. Her portrayal of Mother Courage is considered iconic. She was a Jewish Viennese woman, went into exile and returned with Brecht to East Berlin. A strong woman in Berlin's theatrical Olympus. Helene-Weigel-Platz honours her.",
  "bayerisch.by-164": "A \"Ratschkathl\" is a real chatterbox — usually female, prone to village gossip, with a pronounced curiosity about the neighbours' affairs. \"Ratschen\" means in Bavarian to chatter or gossip at length. The term is affectionately mocking: not a real insult, but no compliment either. The male equivalent would be \"Ratschkathlbua\" (rare) or \"Schmatzbruada\". A stock character in the Bavarian village.",
  "saechsisch.s-147": "The Soljanka is a sour and tangy soup of Russian origin that became a cult soup in the GDR — found on every menu. Prepared with pickled cucumbers, tomatoes, sausage, bacon, peppers and lemon. Cream is often added too. Especially popular in Saxony — Saxon inns often serve their own house variant. Post-socialist comfort food that remained popular even after reunification. Today a symbol of East German food culture.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-150": "The \"Schwobaland\" is the affectionately proud name the Swabians give to their homeland — Württemberg, Baden-Württemberg and Bavarian Swabia. The Swabians cultivate a strong sense of home and see their land as economically successful, culturally rich and scenically beautiful. \"Mir sin'em Schwobaland verwurzelt\" — we are rooted in Swabia — is a typical Swabian sentence. Despite globalisation and immigration, Swabian identity remains alive. In Swabia, home is more than just geography.",
  "koelsch.k-171": "The \"Kölsche Roten Funken Artillerie von 1823\" is Cologne's oldest and most renowned carnival society — founded in 1823. They wear red hussar uniforms with white trim. Their dance corps is among the best of the carnival guards. Becoming a member is a lifetime distinction — waiting lists span generations. A symbol of Cologne's carnival tradition and its social interconnection.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-152": "The \"Klaben\" is a traditional North German Christmas pastry — above all in Bremen and the Bremen region. Similar to Stollen, but denser, darker and with more dried fruit (raisins, currants, candied lemon peel, almonds). It is baked before Christmas and stored for several weeks so it can \"mature\". Served spread with butter. The \"Bremer Klaben\" has the status of a protected regional speciality (PGI).",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-155": "\"Glacé\" (from the French) is the Swiss German word for ice cream — it is called this throughout Switzerland, including German-speaking Switzerland. \"Es Glacé go ässe\" is the classic summer outing. Swiss ice-cream culture is highly developed: Mövenpick (founded 1948 in Zurich) is known worldwide, alongside small artisanal gelaterias. The French linguistic influence reflects the Romance influence.",
  "wienerisch.w-150": "The \"Café Central\" on Herrengasse (founded 1876, Palais Ferstel) was the intellectual centre of Vienna around 1900 — Stefan Zweig, Hugo von Hofmannsthal, Egon Friedell, Adolf Loos and Leon Trotsky (better known at the chessboard as \"Herr Bronstein\") met here daily. The famous inscription \"Café Central — Stefan Zweig's Stammtisch\" still marks the spot today. High columns, coffee to piano accompaniment. It has become touristy, but is culturally and historically indispensable. The Viennese coffee-house myth in its purest form.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-150": "Franconian identity is strong — the Franconians belong politically to Bavaria but feel themselves culturally to be their own people. \"Mir sind Frangen, net Bayern!\" (We are Franconians, not Bavarians!) is a standard phrase. Their own dialect, their own cuisine (Schäuferla instead of pork knuckle), their own wine (Franconian wine instead of Bavarian beer), their own history (Free Imperial Cities). The Bavarian government in Munich is seen by some as foreign rule. Bavarian Broadcasting has its own Studio Franken. This independence shapes Franconian self-confidence to this day.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-154": "\"Pommes Schranke\" is the classic of the chip shop in the Ruhr area: chips with mayonnaise AND ketchup — striped like a railway barrier (hence the name). \"Pommes rot-weiß\" is the other term. Orders are ritualised: \"Eine Pommes Schranke und eine Currywurst, bidde!\". The trip to the chip shop after school, after the shift or after a stadium visit is as much a part of Pott life as the miners' song is to the miner.",
  "alemannisch.al-154": "\"Hoorig\" literally means \"hairy\" in Alemannic, but is mostly used figuratively for \"complicated\", \"tricky\" or \"delicate\". A \"hoorige Situation\" is one in which you have to be careful. During the Fasnet, \"Hoorig\" is also a fools' cry: \"Hoorig, hoorig isch d'Katz!\" — a battle cry of the Fasnet fools in Rottweil and Villingen.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-141": "The \"Grumbeersalad\" is the Palatine potato salad — usually dressed with broth, vinegar, oil and onions, not with mayonnaise. \"A good Grumbeersalad belongs with a Saumagen!\" From \"Grumbeere\" (potatoes) and \"Salad\". Served lukewarm, it is the classic side dish to sausage, schnitzel and Saumagen. Made in every family to its own recipe and unthinkable at any celebration without it. A classic dish of Palatine food culture, showing the region's fondness for hearty, down-to-earth fare.",
  "hessisch.h-197": "The Frankfurt horse market was historically important — today this tradition lives on in annual equestrian events and riding tourism. The Frankfurt racecourse in Niederrad is also of regional significance. Hesse cultivates its equestrian tradition — from Grand Duke Ludwig (Ludwigsburg) to the present day. Hessian riding culture.",
  "berlinisch.b-186": "The 6th floor of the KaDeWe — the \"gourmet floor\" — is Europe's largest delicatessen department, with 7,000 m². Over 1,300 kinds of cheese, 1,700 sorts of sausage and ham, fresh fish, exotic fruit from all over the world. Here you can enjoy star restaurants in miniature. Tourists love the floor, Berlin's high society shuttles in regularly. Pure Berlin luxury.",
  "bayerisch.by-165": "\"Sauwetter\" is extremely bad weather — rain, storm, cold and snow mixed together. \"Sau-\" as an intensifying prefix is typically Bavarian (Sauglück, Sauhitz, Saukälte, Sauarbeit). It goes back to the pig as a symbol of \"coarse\" and \"dirty\" in farming life. When it is \"sau-saukalt\", it is extremely cold. Bavarian through and through: pithy, coarse, spot-on.",
  "saechsisch.s-148": "Pittiplatsch der Liebe (\"Pitti\" for short) is one of the most famous GDR Sandmännchen characters — a little goblin puppet with bulging eyes. On GDR television since 1962. Together with Schnatterinchen (a duck) and Moppi (a dog) they formed the trio of the \"Abendgruß\". Pitti's catchphrase \"Ach, du meine Nase!\" became cult. Formative for generations of East Germans — almost every Saxon between 30 and 60 grew up with Pittiplatsch. Preserved after reunification, today a cult figure and souvenir.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-151": "The \"Spätzlespresse\" is THE kitchen tool of Swabian housewives — a perforated mould through which the dough is pressed into hot water. Swabian Spätzle are a symbol of identity: scraped by hand from the board is considered even more authentic than pressed. With cheese (\"Käsknöpfle\"), with lentils, or as a side dish to roast beef. Every family has its own recipe. At weddings the bridal couple is often given a Spätzlespresse — a symbol of culinary identity.",
  "koelsch.k-173": "The Dombauhütte at Cologne Cathedral is one of the oldest masons' lodges in Germany — continuously active since 1248 (the start of the cathedral's construction). Today stonemasons, sculptors and glass painters permanently restore the cathedral here — it is never entirely \"finished\". The traditional craft is passed on here. UNESCO-recognised intangible cultural heritage. The Dombauhütte is a lifelong task of Cologne.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-153": "\"Mors\" is the backside in Low German — coarse and direct, but not taboo in northern Germany. \"En Tritt in den Mors kriegen\" means to get a kick in the backside. Also in sayings: \"Du kannst mi mal an de Mors lecken\" is the Low German version of the Götz quotation. In standard German it would sound more vulgar; in Low German it is part of everyday usage. Characteristic Low German directness.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-156": "\"Es lit Schnee\" is the Swiss German way of describing the weather in winter — \"lit\" is the form of \"lies\" (lies/is lying). In a mountainous country like Switzerland, snow plays a central role: skiing, tourism, avalanche danger, hydropower. \"Es het g'schniit\" (it has snowed) or \"es schniit\" (it is snowing) are daily reports in winter. Snow is Swiss identity.",
  "wienerisch.w-151": "The \"Wuzzler\" is the Viennese word for table football, also called Kicker. In Viennese taverns (Beisln) and student pubs there is often a Wuzzler in the corner — popular between a beer and a schnitzel. The word \"wuzln\" means \"to turn, to roll\" — fitting for the movement of the game. Pros play the Wuzzler as a sport: there are even Austrian Wuzzler championships. A charming Viennese linguistic invention.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-151": "\"Allmächd!\" or \"Allmächd Goddla!\" is probably the most characteristic Franconian exclamation of astonishment, alarm or regret. A short form of \"Allmächtiger Gott!\" (Almighty God!). In Nuremberg, Erlangen and Bamberg it can be heard on every street corner. The expression ranges from a mild \"oh dear\" to \"for heaven's sake!\" — depending on the tone. A true Franconian can hardly get through the day without this word.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-155": "The \"Pillemann\" is the colloquial, rather childish term for the penis in the Ruhr area. Parents explain to small children: \"That's your Pillemann!\". It can also be heard again and again in Pott comedy (Herbert Knebel, Tana Schanzara). The expression is mild and harmless — not vulgar. Related to the Low German coinages that merge into the Ruhr region.",
  "alemannisch.al-155": "A \"Hudel\" is in Alemannic an old rag or a cloth — the Putzhudel for wiping up, the Tellerhudel for drying. Figuratively, a \"Hudel\" can also be an untidy, slovenly person. The verb \"hudle\" means to bungle, that is, to do something hastily and sloppily — hence the proverb: \"Was schnell gschafft isch, isch g'hudlet.\" (What is done quickly is botched.)",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-142": "The \"Grumbeerkichelcher\" are potato pancakes or hash browns — grated potatoes, baked golden brown in the pan. \"Grumbeerkichelcher with apple sauce, the kids love that!\" From \"Grumbeere\" (potatoes) and \"Kichelcher\" (little cakes). They are eaten with apple sauce or plum butter, crispy and hearty at the same time. A popular dish of Palatine farmhouse cooking that delights young and old. Classic home cooking that shows how versatile the potato is in the region.",
  "hessisch.h-198": "Even though it is classically Swabian — \"Schaffe schaffe\" is widespread in Hessian vernacular as an expression of diligence and work ethic. Immigrant Swabians brought the saying with them. In Frankfurt people more readily say \"Babbeln un Schaffen\" — talking and working. Hessians work differently from Swabians, but with a similar result. The region's work ethic.",
  "berlinisch.b-187": "The Russian Embassy Unter den Linden is one of the largest embassy buildings in Europe — built in the 1950s in the style of socialist classicism. A huge complex with a park, consulate and cultural centre. Highly controversial politically today — a symbol of the diplomatic tensions between Germany and Russia. Berlin's place in geopolitics.",
  "bayerisch.by-166": "\"Spezi\" has two meanings in Bavarian: 1) A good friend, a buddy (\"mei beste Spezi\" — my best buddy). 2) The mixed drink of cola and orange soda (called \"Mezzo-Mix\" in other regions). A play on words: the \"Spezi-Spezi\" is a friend who likes to drink Spezi. It comes from the Italian \"specie\" (kind, sort). The \"Spezi\" as a friend is affectionate, the Spezi as a drink omnipresent in Bavaria.",
  "saechsisch.s-149": "The folk music of the Ore Mountains (Erzgebirge) is one of the richest regional musical traditions in Germany — with its own songs, dance forms and instruments. Famous exponents: Anton Günther (1876–1937, folk poet and composer of \"Da drubn afn Beraga\"), the Erzgebirge ensembles and miners' choirs. Classic songs: \"Da drubn af'n Beraga\", \"Ufm Sandhübel\", \"Mei Vaterhaus\". Today alive in choirs, music societies and at the Erzgebirgsverein. Saxon-Erzgebirge intangible cultural heritage.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-152": "The \"Maultäschle\" are the Swabian Maultaschen — filled pasta pockets with a filling of meat, spinach, onions and breadcrumbs. Legendary as \"Herrgottsbescheißerle\" (little God-cheaters): monks are said to have hidden meat in dough to get around Lent. Whether in broth as a soup, fried with onions, or as \"Maultäschle in Soß\" — one of the most important dishes of Swabian cuisine. Today also available frozen in every supermarket.",
  "koelsch.k-174": "The \"Schull- un Veedelszöch\" are smaller carnival processions on Carnival Friday — schools and city districts show off their carnival creativity. With home-made float decorations, dance groups and marching bands. A warm-hearted prelude to the Rose Monday parade. Here schoolchildren present their creative contributions — mostly politically or socially critical, as is Cologne tradition.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-154": "The \"Klönschnack\" is THE North German social phenomenon — cosy, extended chatting in a relaxed atmosphere. \"Klönen\" means to chat, \"Schnack\" the talk. It takes place at the garden fence, in the pub, over coffee, or across the counter. \"En lütten Klönschnack\" (a little chat) is part of every visit. Standard German visitors often have to learn that \"just a quick Klönschnack\" can happily mean several hours. North German conviviality in its purest form.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-157": "\"Verreckt!\" is the Swiss German curse of indignation or annoyance — a coarser form than \"verdammt!\" (damn it!). Also intensified: \"So es verreckts Züg!\" (What a damned thing!). In tone it is mostly not nasty, but an expression of frustration. The Swiss rarely curse, and when they do, not as crudely as the Germans — \"verreckt\" is a relatively harmless version.",
  "wienerisch.w-152": "\"Hawi\" is the Viennese short form of \"Hawara\" — the friend, the buddy. \"Servas Hawi!\" is a typically Viennese greeting among male friends. Also in the variant \"Hawerl\". The expression comes from Yiddish (\"chawer\" = comrade) and shows the influence of the Jewish language on Viennese — many words have their origin in the multilingual Austro-Hungarian monarchy.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-152": "A \"Bambala\" is a small child, a baby or a little girl in Franconian — the diminutive sounds warm-hearted and familiar. Related to the Italian \"bambino\", which could go back to Nuremberg's trade relations with Italy. \"Mei Bambala\" the grandmother says lovingly to her grandchild. A true gem of a word in Franconian.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-156": "The \"Klüngelskerl\" was, in the Ruhr area and the Rhineland, the man who drove through the streets with horse and cart, collecting rags, scrap metal, bones and old things — the forerunner of today's scrap trade. \"Klüngels\" are old fabrics. The cry \"Lumpen, Knochen, Altpapier!\" (Rags, bones, waste paper!) echoed through the streets of the Pott. Today almost vanished, but the word \"Klüngelskerl\" lives on as a memory — also used for modern scrap dealers.",
  "alemannisch.al-156": "A \"Bähämbel\" is, in the South Baden Alemannic dialect, a clumsy, somewhat awkward person — usually not meant unkindly, but with affectionate mockery. The word has no clear etymology, but with the doubling of \"äm\" it sounds as if it came from a child's world of language. Related to \"Bobbele\" in its sound coloring — both sound warm and cozy, even when they mean mockery.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-143": "The \"Dampfnudle\" are the famous Palatine steamed dumplings — yeast dumplings baked in a pan with a salt crust, served with potato soup or wine sauce. \"Dampfnudle mit Weinsoß, des is a Pälzer Festesse!\" (Steamed dumplings with wine sauce, that's a Palatine feast!) Crispy on the bottom, fluffy on top, a Sunday and holiday dish. Served sweet with vanilla sauce or savory with soup. The epitome of Palatine pastry culture. A classic dish around which real competitions arise in the region over who makes the best salt crust.",
  "hessisch.h-199": "The Hessian Civic Guard of 1830 was a democratic movement in Hesse-Kassel — citizens demanding a constitution and the rule of law. An important episode on the road to German democracy, long before 1848. Hesse was thereby a pioneer region for civil rights. The Hessian tradition of democracy is still cultivated today.",
  "berlinisch.b-188": "The French Embassy on Pariser Platz — right by the Brandenburg Gate — was newly built in 2003 by architect Christian de Portzamparc. Modernist compared to the Prussian buildings all around it. A symbol of German-French friendship. On special occasions, German-French meetings are held here. Berlin diplomatic architecture.",
  "bayerisch.by-167": "\"Liederlich\" describes in Bavarian a person who neglects their duties or their appearance — sloppy in the household, unfocused at work, untidy in demeanor. Stronger than standard German \"nachlässig\" (negligent), with a moralizing undertone. \"Liederlicher Hund\" (slovenly dog) is a common reproach to unreliable men. Women are \"liederlich\" if they don't keep the house in order.",
  "saechsisch.s-150": "Anton Günther (1876–1937) from Gottesgab in the Ore Mountains is Saxony's best-known dialect poet — he wrote over 200 songs in the Ore Mountain dialect, including \"Da drubn afn Beraga\" (\"Up there on the mountain\"), \"Feieromd\" and \"Mei Hamit\". His songs are folk hymns of the Ore Mountains and are still sung today in choirs and by the miners' choir. A tragic ending: despairing over the political conditions, he took his own life in 1937. He remains an unmatched role model of Ore Mountain song artistry.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-153": "The \"Kehrwoche\" (sweeping week) is a Swabian institution — the duty to clean the stairwell or the sidewalk in front of the house once a week. In apartment buildings the duty rotates among the tenants. Whoever's turn it is hangs a Kehrwoche sign on the door. Swabians take their Kehrwoche extremely seriously — violations lead to neighborhood dramas. A symbol of Swabian love of order and sense of duty. Whoever slacks on the Kehrwoche is considered un-German.",
  "koelsch.k-175": "\"Drink doch ene mit\" (Have a drink with us) is Bläck Fööss' best-known carnival hit — released in 1973. The song about a lonely old man who is invited to share a beer with others became a hymn of Cologne solidarity. It plays on a social theme: no one should be alone. Today every person from Cologne can sing along to the lyrics. The song is played at the funerals of Cologne originals. Cologne humanity in its purest form.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-155": "\"Krabbenpulen\" is the meditative activity of peeling fresh North Sea shrimp (prawns) by hand — a North German test of patience. \"Een Pund Krabben pulen duurt en Stunn\" (Peeling a pound of shrimp takes an hour). On shrimp cutters in Büsum, Cuxhaven and Greetsiel, tons are peeled every day. The shrimp are small and fiddly, but the result is legendary: \"Krabbenbrot mit Spiegelei\" (shrimp on bread with a fried egg) is an East Frisian specialty. A family ritual on Sundays.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-158": "\"Chrüsimüsi\" is, in Swiss German, an affectionate word for a hopeless muddle — literally \"cabbage and mush\", that is, everything mixed together. The word itself also has a tangled, playful sound. \"I min Chopf isch es Chrüsimüsi\" — there's chaos in my head. One of those wonderful Swiss German words that, through onomatopoeia, illustrates its own meaning.",
  "wienerisch.w-153": "\"Schmatten\" is Viennese for nonsense or rubbish — mostly used disparagingly. From the Yiddish \"schmate\" (rag, cloth). \"Red kan Schmatten!\" (Don't talk rubbish!) the Viennese says to someone talking nonsense. A coarser variant of \"Quatsch\". Also used in the form \"Schmattes\" for Jewish tips or small gifts — the meaning has shifted.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-153": "\"Saggradi!\" is a Franconian curse — a softened form of \"Sakrament!\" (the Catholic sacrament becomes a swear word). It can also be heard as \"Saggrament noamol!\". The expression reflects Franconia's Catholic character (especially in Würzburg and Bamberg), where religious terms were turned into curses. Mild to coarse, depending on the situation.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-157": "\"Mutterns\" is, in the Ruhr area, the genitive form of \"Mutter\" (mother) — \"bei Mutterns\" means \"at the parents' place\". Also \"Vaterns\" for \"at father's\". The form is typical of the communicative Pott language, which knows many simplifications and contractions. \"Wir gehen morgen zu Mutterns essen\" (We're going to eat at Mom's tomorrow) is a typical family arrangement. The expression is warm and familiar.",
  "alemannisch.al-157": "\"Goggolori\" is Alemannic-Bavarian for nonsense, rubbish or a muddled plan. In folk theater, the \"Goggolori\" is a literary figure (Wilhelm Hauff's fairy tale) — a goblin who plays tricks on people. \"Mach koi Goggolori!\" (Don't make a mess!) is a call to stay sensible. Thanks to the doubled \"go\" it sounds like a sing-song and conveys something playful.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-144": "The \"Flääschknepp\" are meat dumplings or minced-meat balls from Palatine cuisine — related to the Lewwerknepp (liver dumplings), but made of minced meat. \"Flääschknepp in dr Brieh, des wärmt im Winter.\" (Meat dumplings in broth, that warms you up in winter.) From \"Flääsch\" (meat) and \"Knepp\" (dumplings). They are simmered in a hearty broth and served with bread or potatoes. A hearty specialty of down-to-earth home cooking. A classic dish that shows how Palatines conjure hearty, filling meals from simple ingredients.",
  "hessisch.h-200": "\"Wir Hessen\" (we Hessians) is an affectionate term of community — it expresses Hessian self-confidence. Hessians are aware of their identity: apple-wine drinkers, Eintracht fans, Book Fair visitors, honest and direct in dealings. \"Wir Hessen sind anders\" (We Hessians are different) — said with humorous pride. The Hessian \"we\" is tolerant and welcoming — whoever lives here is part of it.",
  "berlinisch.b-189": "Knut (2006-2011) was a Berlin polar bear, born in the Berlin Zoo and hand-raised by a keeper. His cute appearance made him a worldwide sensation — he was on magazine covers, in films, on T-shirts. Knut died tragically young of a brain disease. Berlin has a Knut memorial in the zoo. Berlin animal love as a pop phenomenon.",
  "bayerisch.by-168": "A \"Hupfdohle\" is a lively child, hard to keep in check — usually a girl who is constantly romping about, hopping and unable to sit still. \"Hupfen\" is Bavarian for to hop, and the \"Dohle\" (jackdaw) is actually a bird. The word combination describes the bouncing creature. Affectionately mocking, often used by grandparents for their grandchildren. Synonyms: \"Quirl\" (whisk), \"Zappelphilipp\" (fidget, for boys).",
  "saechsisch.s-151": "\"Mor halt\" is a typical Saxon filler particle — a mix of \"aber\" (but) and \"halt\" (just), expressing resignation or acceptance. It is often used at the start of a sentence or as a rhetorical pause: \"Mor halt, was solls\" (Oh well, what can you do). Similar to the North German \"nu ja\". It expresses a deliberate, resigned attitude — typically Saxon and sly. Hard to translate into standard German, because the meaning lies in the tone of voice.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-154": "A \"Schaffer\" is, in Swabian, a diligent, hard worker — the embodiment of the Swabian work ethic. \"Schaffe, schaffe, Häusle baue\" (Work, work, build a little house) is the classic Swabian motto of life. Swabians are considered industrious, thrifty and hardworking — qualities embodied in the economically successful region of Baden-Württemberg. Mercedes, Porsche, Bosch — all founded in Swabia by \"Schaffern\". The Schaffer is the hero of Swabian moral teaching.",
  "koelsch.k-176": "A \"Krätzche\" is, in Cologne dialect, a short, often mocking song — usually sung in a carnival context. The \"Krätzcher singers\" perform at carnival sessions and use brief songs to poke fun at current topics. Well-known Krätzcher singers include Willibert Pauels and Bernd Stelter. The tradition goes back to the 19th century — the Krätzcher are Cologne mini-cabaret pieces with a punch line.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-156": "The \"Klabautermann\" is the ship spirit of North German and North Frisian mythology — a helpful house spirit aboard ships. It comes from the Low German \"klabastern\" (to make noise). The Klabautermann ensures the crew's safety if treated kindly; whoever behaves disrespectfully toward him risks misfortune. It is kept alive in seamen's tales and North German folklore. Today also used metaphorically for streaks of bad luck or inexplicable problems.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-159": "The \"Tütschi\" or \"Eiertütschen\" is a Swiss Easter custom: painted hard-boiled eggs are knocked against each other — whoever's egg breaks has lost. Whoever's egg remains whole in the end is the \"Tütschi king\". A tradition in many families at the Easter Sunday breakfast. Also widespread in other regions, but especially cultivated in Switzerland — there are even commercial Tütschi competitions.",
  "wienerisch.w-154": "\"A Bisscherl\" (a little bit) is, in Viennese, formed with a tender diminutive — the Viennese \"-erl\" turns every word into something dear and likeable. \"Komm, gib ma a Bisscherl davon!\" (Come on, give me a little bit of it!) The Viennese \"-erl\" form (instead of standard German \"-chen\") is a hallmark of the dialect: \"Heferl, Sackerl, Krügerl, Hunderl, Maderl\". It lends the language a cozy, inviting tone.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-154": "A \"Buddabäääm\" is, in Franconian, a particularly soft, sweet pear — the \"butter pear\". But the word is also used figuratively for a soft, sentimental person: \"Sei kei Buddabäääm!\" (Don't be such a softie!) The Franconian pronunciation with the drawn-out \"ää\" makes the word especially distinctive. Onomatopoeically it sounds like something sweet and gentle.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-158": "\"Pommes Spezial\" is the upgrade of the \"Pommes Schranke\" (fries with ketchup and mayo) — with diced raw onions added on top. Some snack stands also add curry sauce. This variant is standard in the Ruhr area and is understood without any explanation. The fry-stand culture of the Ruhr region is an important part of the local identity: simple, honest food that fills you up and tastes good.",
  "alemannisch.al-159": "The Spätzlebrett (Spätzle board) is a traditional Alemannic-Swabian kitchen tool: a flat wooden board with a handle on which the Spätzle dough is spread out and scraped thinly into the boiling water with a scraper. Unlike the modern Spätzle press, the board requires skill and experience — good Spätzle makers scrape with a steady hand and an even rhythm. A family heirloom in many Alemannic households.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-145": "The \"Brez\" is the pretzel — in the Palatinate a staple food, fresh from the baker or \"Bredschler\" (pretzel maker). \"Hol mir a Brez mit Butter zum Frühstick!\" (Get me a pretzel with butter for breakfast!) Also called \"Bredsel\", with a thick belly and crispy little arms. Speyer even celebrates its own pretzel festival. It's eaten plain, with butter, or with a white-sausage breakfast. Available at every fair and market. A classic baked good of Palatine baking and eating culture, fitting from morning to night and for any occasion.",
  "hessisch.h-201": "The \"Ebbelwoi-Express\" is a Frankfurt tourist institution — a historic tram that travels through the city and serves Ebbelwoi (apple wine) and pretzels on board. Opened in 1977, it runs through Frankfurt every Saturday and Sunday today. Tourists and Frankfurters celebrate on board with live music and Hessian singing. A symbol of Frankfurt's joie de vivre and apple-wine culture. Not to be confused with the regular transit trams.",
  "berlinisch.b-190": "The Berlin Bear Pit in Köllnischer Park (Mitte) housed the city's official \"heraldic bears\" from 1939 to 2015. The animals, with names like Schnute and Maxi, were living symbols of the city. After protests against the non-species-appropriate husbandry, the pit was closed in 2015. Today a piece of Berlin city history. The Berlin bear now only symbolic.",
  "bayerisch.by-169": "\"Resch\" describes in Bavarian the perfect crispiness — a resch loaf of bread, a resch pork knuckle, a resch bread roll. Bavarians have a pronounced sense for textures in food: bread must be crisp on the outside and soft inside, the roast pork roasted crisp, the pretzel baked crisp. \"Reschern\" means to crunch. The word \"Reschkrust'n\" for the crispy bread crust also derives from this.",
  "saechsisch.s-152": "The \"Bemme\" is, in Saxon, the slice of bread with a topping — usually with butter, sausage, cheese or jam. Omnipresent in childhood and school: \"Bemmenbüchse\" for the snack box. \"A Bemme mit Schmalz\" (a slice of bread with lard) is a classic break-time snack. The etymology is unclear, perhaps Slavic. \"Bemmernschmiere\" is the spread for topping. Still in daily use in Saxony today — no Bemme in the snack box would be unthinkable.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-155": "\"Häusle baue\" (building a little house) is the Swabian dream of life — your own house instead of renting, with a garden and garage. It's tied to the proverb \"Schaffe, schaffe, Häusle baue, und net nach de Mädle gschaue\" (Work, work, build a house, and don't go chasing the girls). A symbol of Swabian thriftiness and a goal in life. Many Swabian families save for decades for their own home. The home-ownership rate in Baden-Württemberg is one of the highest in Germany.",
  "koelsch.k-177": "\"Höös\" is the Cologne form of \"Hose\" (trousers) — with the typically Ripuarian dropping of the final \"-e\" and the drawn-out \"ö\". \"Zieh dich Höös an!\" (Put your trousers on!) is an everyday command. Also in compounds: \"Lederhöös\", \"Knieböös\". The soft sound is characteristic of Cologne dialect, which on the whole stands out for its melodic, almost singing pronunciation. A true Cologne sound.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-158": "A \"Schnacker\" or \"Schnackerin\" is, in Low German, someone who likes to talk a lot — from \"schnacken\" (to chat). Affectionate to mocking: a good Schnacker can however keep a whole group entertained. The \"lütte Schnacker\" (little chatterbox) is also a term for a talkative child. Plural: \"Schnackers\". In North German villages the Schnacker is a fixed part of the social fabric — usually at the regulars' table or the coffee circle.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-160": "The \"Schlitten\" is, in Swiss German, both the winter sports device (sledge) and colloquially the car (\"en geile Schlitten\" — a cool car). Sledging is a Swiss popular sport — many mountains have prepared sledge runs. Famous are the \"toboggan run on the Bürgenstock\" or the Big Pintenfritz in Grindelwald. \"Schlittele\" (to sledge) is the corresponding verb.",
  "wienerisch.w-155": "\"Hoanzn\" is Viennese for \"to harass\", \"to bully\", \"to make fun of\". \"Den hams gscheit g'hoanzt!\" (They really gave him a hard time!) Also used in the sense of teasing and annoying. The expression comes from schoolyard language but has found its way into adult vocabulary — especially in sports, when the opponent is mercilessly outplayed.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-155": "\"Schmarrn\" is, in Franconian as in Bavarian, the word for nonsense or rubbish — \"Red kei Schmarrn!\" (Don't talk rubbish!). Originally a sweet dish (Kaiserschmarrn), then transferred to everything muddled and warped. \"Saudummer Schmarrn\" is an intense intensification (bloody stupid nonsense). Also known in Franconian cuisine as \"Buchweizenschmarrn\" or \"Apfelschmarrn\".",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-159": "A \"Halbe\" is, in the Ruhr area, usually half a bread roll with cold cuts — the classic at the breakfast break on the job or during the break. \"Eine Halbe mit Mett und Zwiebeln\" (a half with minced pork and onions) or \"Eine Halbe mit Käse\" (a half with cheese) are typical orders at the baker's. A half beer can also be a \"Halbe\". The word saves time — and time is money, especially in the hardworking Pott.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-146": "The „Weck“ is the bread roll — a typically southwest German word. „Hol fünf Weck beim Bäcker, mir wolle frühstücke!“ (Get five rolls from the baker, we want to have breakfast!) In the Palatinate, in Hesse and along the Rhine people say Weck instead of Brötchen. Plural „Weck“ or „Wecke“. The famous „Weck, Worscht un Woi“ is the quintessential Palatine triad: roll, sausage and wine. A classic word of Palatine everyday speech that comes up at the baker’s and at every festival, shaping the regional food culture.",
  "hessisch.h-202": "Sachsenhausen, south of the Main, is THE apple-wine quarter of Frankfurt. Here you find the traditional Ebbelwoi taverns like „Zur Sonne“, „Atschel“, „Lorsbacher Thal“ and „Wagner“. In summer you sit in the garden under chestnut trees. „Sachsenhäuser Hut“ is a promenade spot. The quarter has its own self-confidence — the people of Sachsenhausen call themselves „die Hibbdebach“ (on this side of the brook). The epitome of Hessian coziness.",
  "berlinisch.b-191": "The Mauerpark Sunday is Berlin pop culture — a huge flea market with vintage, handmade goods, art and culinary delicacies. Next to it the „Bearpit Karaoke“ in the amphitheater, where hundreds of spectators cheer on the performers. A mix of old GDR subculture and new Berlin hipster vibe. In summer a must-do for tourists.",
  "bayerisch.by-170": "A „Rotzbua“ is a cheeky, impertinent boy with a tendency toward mischief and little impudences. Literally: a „snot boy“ — someone who is still wet behind the ears. Meant affectionately when grandparents call their grandchildren this, harsher when strangers use it as a term for good-for-nothing youths. The female form „Rotzgöre“ has a similar meaning. Derives from Middle High German.",
  "saechsisch.s-153": "„Schniegel“ describes in Saxon an affected pride, ostentatious smartness or playful spruceness. „Geschniegelt und gebügelt“ (spruced and ironed) is a well-known idiom. A „geschniegelter Bursch“ is a haughty, excessively elegantly dressed man. In the Erzgebirge it is also used positively for someone carefully groomed. Comes from the old word for cleaning and adorning. Sounds affectionately mocking.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-156": "The „Briagle“ is in Swabian the bread roll or bread — a diminutive of „Brot“ (bread). At the baker’s you order „a Briagle mit Butter und Käs“ (a roll with butter and cheese). Ubiquitous in Stuttgart and the surrounding area. In northern Württemberg people also say „Weckle“. Swabian bakers are famous for their variety: Seele, Wibele, Krapfen, Brezel. The „Schwarzwälder Briagle“ is a well-known classic. Bread is identity in Swabia — no meal without it.",
  "koelsch.k-178": "A „Müsje“ is in Kölsch a young girl — the diminutive with „-je“ is typically Kölsch (while the Viennese say „-erl“ and the Swabians „-le“). „Süßes Müsje“ is a nice girl. Also in phrases: „Drei Müsjer“ are three young women. The sound is playful and childishly warm. During Carnival many „Müsjer“ and „Junge“ (boys) are sung about — the Kölsch appreciation of youth.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-159": "The „Buddel“ is the Low German bottle — usually beer, schnapps or water. „En Buddel Köm“ is a bottle of grain spirit. „Buddelschiff“ is a ship in a bottle, a North German craft tradition. „Aus der Buddel trinken“ (drinking from the bottle) as a rustic gesture. In many depictions the Bremen Town Musicians hold Buddeln in their paws. Also metaphorically: „Sich an de Buddel hängen“ means to drink too much. Omnipresent in the North German vocabulary.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-161": "A „Bünzli“ is in Swiss German a typical Swiss philistine — excessively tidy, thrifty, narrow-minded, fixated on order and security. The term has a self-ironic note: the Swiss know that many of them have Bünzli traits. „So es Bünzli-Hus“ (such a philistine house) with a perfect front garden and little arborvitae shrubs. A character type much described in Swiss literature.",
  "wienerisch.w-156": "A „Käfertaler“ or „Aus’n Hinterhof“ is in Viennese often a derogatory term for someone from the outer districts of Vienna (Floridsdorf, Liesing, Donaustadt). The inner-city Viennese (1st–9th district) historically developed a slight feeling of superiority over the residents of the suburbs and working-class districts. Today often used self-ironically: „I bin a Käfertaler, na und?“ (I’m a Käfertaler, so what?). Sociologically interesting.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-156": "The „Wammerla“ is in Franconian the diminutive of „Wamme“ — the belly, especially the belly meat or a protruding paunch. „En Wammerla ahält“ means to get a beer belly. Also at the butcher’s: „Wammerl“ is the streaky belly meat from pork that is cured and smoked — a Franconian specialty.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-160": "A „Wattebällchen“ (little cotton ball) is in the Ruhrpott someone who is too delicate, too soft or oversensitive — not someone with „Pott mentality“. „Stell dich nich so an, du Wattebällchen!“ (Don’t make such a fuss, you little cotton ball!) the Pott person says to someone who whines. The hard daily life of the miner created a certain notion of „being tough“: a real Pott person grits their teeth and carries on. The Wattebällchen does not.",
  "alemannisch.al-160": "The „Briigel“ is in Alemannic a small bread roll or a chunk of bread — also in the sense of „a small piece of bread“. In the bakers’ language there are „Briigeli“, small crusty rolls served as a snack. Related to „Bröckle“ (little crumb). The expression shows the Alemannic preference for diminutive forms that express everything cozy and homemade.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-147": "The „Schoppe“ is the half-liter of wine or wine spritzer in the Dubbeglas — the Palatine measure of conviviality. „Mir trinke noch a Schoppe, dann gehe mir heim.“ (We’ll drink one more Schoppe, then we’ll go home.) In the Palatinate wine is not measured in glasses but in Schoppen. Whoever „a Schoppe stemmt“ enjoys themselves in a relaxed way. Saying: „Noch a Schoppe in Ehre kann niemand verwehre.“ (No one can deny an honest Schoppe.) A classic word of Palatine wine culture, inseparably linked to the Dubbeglas, the wine festival and the relaxed lifestyle of the region.",
  "hessisch.h-203": "The „Geripptes“ is THE Frankfurt apple-wine glass — a 0.3-liter glass with a characteristic diamond pattern (16 diamonds). It was developed in the 19th century so that greasy hands would not slip thanks to the ribbed profile. It is poured to the brim — „the apple wine has to reach the last rib“. Whoever drinks a Geripptes empty is a true Frankfurter. An iconic symbol of Frankfurt, known worldwide. Tourists buy it as a souvenir.",
  "berlinisch.b-193": "The Rotes Rathaus (Red Town Hall) at Alexanderplatz is Berlin’s town hall — built in 1869, brick architecture with a characteristic red facade. Seat of the Governing Mayor and the Berlin Senate. The Berlin „Bär“ (bear) above the entrance. Inside, the famous hall with murals of Berlin’s history. Tourists can visit the foyer and some halls free of charge.",
  "bayerisch.by-171": "The „Loabbrot“ or „Loab“ is a whole, unsliced loaf of bread — usually farmhouse bread made of rye and sourdough. In Bavarian villages it is rich in tradition to this day: bread was baked every Saturday, and the Loab lasted a week. „Vom Loab a Scheiberl runter“ means to cut a slice off the loaf. When buying bread you say „I hätt gern an Loab Bauernbrot“ (I’d like a loaf of farmhouse bread). A symbol of down-to-earthness and home cooking.",
  "saechsisch.s-155": "„Frischling“ has two meanings in Saxon: 1) The young wild boar, striped and curious — known above all in the Erzgebirge and Lusatia. 2) A beginner, a „greenhorn“ — a new employee, a young adult in their first job, an apprentice. „A grüner Frischling“ is an awkward novice. Meant affectionately, condescendingly, but not insultingly. Common in standard German, but especially cultivated in Saxony.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-157": "The „Hocketse“ is a typical Swabian village festival — literally a „squatting session“ or „seating arrangement“. A club, sports or fire-brigade festival with benches, tables, beer, sausage, Spätzle and live music. It usually takes place in summer in the festival tent or under pavilions. Every village has its own Hocketse — from the Liederkranz-Hocketse to the Schützenhocketse. The pinnacle of Swabian conviviality. The epitome of cozy, down-to-earth festival culture.",
  "koelsch.k-179": "„Et kütt wie et kütt“ (it comes as it comes) is the third of the famous „Kölsche Grundgesetze“ (Kölsch basic laws) — alongside „Et es wie et es“ (it is as it is) and „Et hätt noch immer jot jejange“ (it has always turned out well). The phrase expresses the fatalistic yet serene attitude of the people of Cologne: what happens, happens — no reason to get worked up. It is a philosophy of life connected with the Carnival, the joy of living and the tolerance of the city. „Pragmatically cheerful.“",
  "plattdeutsch.p-160": "The „Snuten un Poten“ are in Low German the snout and paws (of animals) — literally, but also idiomatically for the whole outward appearance. „Sien Snuten un Poten hett he ümmer in d’Bidder“ describes someone who is constantly sticking their hands into everything. In Hamburg it is also a traditional specialty: Snuten un Poten as a mash of pig’s snout and trotters, hearty and very rich. Rarely served today.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-162": "„Wytertue“ is the Swiss German form of „weitertun“ — that is, to carry on, to continue. „Mir tüend wyter!“ or „Mach wyter!“ (Carry on!). The verb „tue“ (to do) is used much more often in Swiss German than in standard German and forms numerous compounds. „Wyter“ is the Swiss German form of „weiter“. An everyday, frequently used expression in working life.",
  "wienerisch.w-157": "A „Tschapperl“ is in Viennese a likeable but somewhat clumsy person — a lovable klutz. „Mein Tschapperl!“ (My little Tschapperl!) the mom says affectionately to the somewhat awkward child. Also figuratively for adults who seem helpless in a situation. The expression is never really mean — it expresses more pity and affection. A warm-hearted description.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-157": "„Bassd!“ is the short Franconian way of agreeing — a word that says it all. It means „All right“, „Fine“, „Accepted“. Longer versions: „Bassd scho“, „Bassd so“. The „p“ shifts to a „b“ (the typical Franconian-Bavarian consonant softening). Spoken with a raised eyebrow it can also mean slightly skeptical agreement — typical Franconian complexity.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-161": "A „Stulle“ is in the Ruhrpott a slice of bread with toppings — with sausage, cheese, lard or jam. The word comes from Low German and is widespread throughout the north. The „Maloche-Stulle“ was what the miner took with him into the pit for his shift: thickly topped, filling, unpacked during the breakfast break from the lunch tin. Today the Stulle is a nostalgic symbol of Pott culture.",
  "alemannisch.al-161": "The „Stube“ is in Alemannic the living room or the cozy taproom. Traditionally furnished with a tiled stove, a corner bench and a Herrgottswinkel (Lord’s corner). In inns the „Stube“ is the main room — the „Wirtsstube“, „Bauernstube“ or „Schwarzwaldstube“ as a culinary institution. The word expresses something homely and warm: here people talk, eat and celebrate. „Stuben-arrest“ (being grounded to the room) has a friendlier ring here.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-148": "The „Schorlestoss“ is a hearty gulp or swig from the spritzer glass. „A ordentlicher Schorlestoss aus em Dubbeglas, des is Pfalz pur!“ (A proper Schorlestoss from the Dubbeglas, that’s pure Palatinate!) From „Schorle“ and „Stoss“ (gulp, push). It denotes the pleasurable swig of wine spritzer, often taken with relish. A vivid Palatine word from the wine drinkers’ language. It expresses the delight in enjoying a Schorle, which is celebrated in the Palatinate. A classic term of wine culture that captures the conviviality around the Dubbeglas.",
  "hessisch.h-204": "„Stöffche“ is the endearing, affectionate term for apple wine — from „Stoff“, which actually means material. It stands for the familiarity of the Frankfurters with their Ebbelwoi. „A klees Stöffche“ is a small glass of apple wine. It is often combined with „bittsche“ („bittschön“ / please): „A klees Stöffche, bittsche!“ (A small apple wine, please!). It expresses a feeling of home and enjoyment. Omnipresent in apple-wine songs and Frankfurt folklore.",
  "berlinisch.b-194": "The Nikolaiviertel on the Spree is Berlin’s oldest preserved district — the founding area of the city in the 13th century. Rebuilt by the GDR in the 1980s (for Berlin’s 750th anniversary). With the Nikolaikirche, the Knoblauchhaus and the Ephraim-Palais. Today a tourist quarter with restaurants, arts and crafts and Berlin-bear souvenir shops. A Berlin-in-a-nutshell tour.",
  "bayerisch.by-172": "„Sauglück“ denotes outrageous, enormous luck — often unexpected and hard to grasp. „Sau-“ as an intensifying prefix is typically Bavarian (see Sauwetter, Sauhitz). „Da hast a Sauglück ghabt!“ (You had such luck!) is said when someone has narrowly escaped a misfortune or has stumbled upon a huge win by chance. Synonyms: „Ramsch“, „Schwein gehabt“ (got lucky). It expresses astonishment and admiration at the same time.",
  "saechsisch.s-156": "„Drauchsala“ is Saxon for a chaotic muddle, chaos or noise. It comes from the Slavic „dracha“ (quarrel, noise). It is often used to describe when there is a traffic jam on the street, when everything is topsy-turvy in the kitchen or when children make noise. „A Drauchsala wie auf dem Jahrmarkt“ (a Drauchsala like at the fairground) is a proverbial exaggeration. It sounds more affectionately rueful than angry.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-158": "The „Dächle“ is in Swabian the small roof — usually the canopy of a house, the covering over the front door or an awning. A diminutive of „Dach“ (roof), typically Swabian with the -le ending. „Sich unter’s Dächle stellen“ means to take shelter from the rain. Swabian houses often have very elaborately designed Dächle — a symbol of craftsmanship quality and attention to detail. Also metaphorically for shelter and security.",
  "koelsch.k-180": "A „Möhn“ is in Kölsch an aunt or an older woman — usually meant affectionately and respectfully. „Tant Möhn“ is the beloved aunt. Also in compounds: „Möhneabend“ is the women’s evening of Weiberfastnacht (Women’s Carnival). The term has a warm, familial note and belongs to Kölsch family culture. Derived from the Old German „mohne“ for mother / mother’s sister.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-161": "A „Kabuff“ is in Low German a small, often cramped room — a cubbyhole, a tiny flat or a storage room. „He wahnt in en lütten Kabuff“ describes someone’s small, modest living situation. It comes from the Middle High German „kavuff“ or from the French „cabuche“ (hut). It has a pejorative note, but also a certain cozy connotation. In harbor districts and old parts of town, Kabuffs were common in the past.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-163": "The „Beizli“ is the diminutive of „Beiz“ — a small, cozy restaurant or tavern. „Beiz“ comes from the Hebrew „bait“ (house). Swiss Beizli are unpretentious, with wood paneling, a regulars’ table and a menu of classics: Cordon Bleu, Älplermagronen, fondue. A meeting place for regular guests, often a family business spanning generations. A central institution of Swiss dining culture.",
  "wienerisch.w-158": "„Pamperletsch“ or „pampig“ describes in Viennese cheeky, impudent, disrespectful behavior — mostly in children or adolescents. „Sei net so pamperletsch!“ (Don’t be so cheeky!) Also a „Pamperletsch“ as a noun for a cheeky person. The sound of the word mirrors its meaning — it sounds „pampig“ itself due to the frequent plosive consonants. A vivid Viennese word.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-158": "The „Hutzelbrot“ is a traditional Franconian Christmas baked good made of „Hutzeln“ (dried pears), nuts, figs, prunes and spices. It is baked during Advent and matures for a few days until it develops its full aroma. It is a specialty especially in Franconian Switzerland and the Steigerwald — often given as a gift for St. Nicholas’ Day or Christmas.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-162": "The „Pömpel“ is in the Ruhrpott the plunger with which you unblock clogged drains or toilets. Also metaphorically: someone who „pömpelt“ muddles their way through without using much brain. „Klo-Pömpel“ (toilet plunger) is the full word. In the Pott the Pömpel is a self-evident household tool that fulfills its purpose plainly — like everything in the Pott.",
  "alemannisch.al-162": "„Goofe“ is Alemannic and Swiss German for „children“ — usually several children, sometimes also just a single one („Goof“). The expression sounds friendly and familiar, but depending on the tone of voice it can also seem slightly disparaging („die Goofe machen wieder Lärm!“ — the kids are making noise again!). Used within the family, it is an affectionate collective word for one’s own offspring.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-149": "The „Fedderweißer“ is the „new wine“ — fermenting grape must, sweet, sparkling and treacherously strong. „Im Herbscht gibt’s Fedderweißer mit Zwiwwelkuche!“ (In autumn there’s Fedderweißer with onion cake!) Cloudy-whitish and in the process of fermenting, it is drunk only fresh and on the spot. The combination with onion cake is a firm Palatine autumn tradition. Also called „neuer Woi“ (new wine). A classic drink of the wine season that shapes Palatine conviviality in autumn and must not be missing at any Keschdefescht or Federweißer evening.",
  "hessisch.h-205": "„Handkäs mit Musik“ (hand cheese with music) is THE Frankfurt national dish — sour-milk cheese in a marinade of vinegar, oil, onions, caraway and pepper. „Mit Musik“ (with music) because the onions cause flatulence later (= the music). Served with bread and Ebbelwoi (apple wine). Dates back to the 18th century. Polarizing: Hessians love it, tourists look on skeptically. The best example of Hessian culinary directness — it smells strong and tastes spicy.",
  "berlinisch.b-195": "The BVG (Berliner Verkehrsbetriebe) is Berlin's public transport company — subway, bus, tram, ferry. With the ironic ad campaign „Weil wir dich lieben“ (Because we love you), the BVG transformed its image: chaotic, but funny. Well known: the singing voice at the subway stations that sometimes cracks jokes. Berliners have a love-hate relationship with the BVG.",
  "bayerisch.by-173": "„Pfiat di“ is the traditional Bavarian farewell — a short form of „Behüt dich Gott“ (May God protect you). It's used among acquaintances and friends, usually with a name added: „Pfiat di, Hansi!“. More formal: „Pfiat eich“ (plural). It has a warm, almost touching note and expresses more connection than the ordinary „Tschüss“. Also common in eulogies and farewell greetings.",
  "saechsisch.s-157": "„Bibbern“ means to tremble in Saxon — from cold, fear or excitement. „Vor Kälte bibbern“ (to shiver from cold) is the literal meaning. „Vor Angst bibbern“ (to tremble from fear) is the figurative one. It's onomatopoeia for chattering teeth. Ever-present in childhood stories: „Mer bibberten vorm Lehrer“ (We trembled before the teacher). Also positive usage: „Vor Vorfreude bibbern“ (to quiver with anticipation) when Christmas approaches. A deep Saxon root-sound combination with b-b.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-159": "A „Gschmackle“ is, in Swabian, an unpleasant aftertaste or a suspicious matter — something that doesn't seem quite kosher. „Die Sach hat a Gschmackle“ means that something is dubious or questionable. It's a diminutive of „Geschmack“ (taste). Often used in political or business contexts. Pure Swabian skepticism — the Swabians are wary of offers that are too good to be true and express this with the Gschmackle.",
  "koelsch.k-181": "„Knies“ in Kölsch means dirt, grime or generally „unpleasant stuff“. „Op de Stroß litt vill Knies“ (There's a lot of dirt on the street). Also figuratively: „Mach kei Knies!“ (Don't make a fuss). The word comes from the Lower Rhine and is closely tied to the idea of something sticky and unpleasant. A drastic, vivid coinage.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-162": "„Lütt un lütt“ is the Hamburg term for a small beer with a small schnapps — the classic dockworker combination. Literally: „Small and small“. Downed in one go. Still popular today in traditional harbor pubs like the „Aalkate“ or „Onkel Otto“. „En Lütt un lütt to'n Fierabend“ (A Lütt un lütt for knocking-off time) is part of Hamburg's working-class culture. Friedrich Hebbel and Theodor Storm mentioned it in their works.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-164": "The „Pfnüsel“ is the common cold in Swiss German — derived from the sound „pfnusen“ (to sniffle). A wonderfully onomatopoeic coinage: you can hear the stuffed-up breathing in the word itself. „I ha en Pfnüsel“ (I have a cold) is standard in winter. A humorous variant: „Pfnüsel-Saison“ refers to the cold season. One of the most characteristic words of Swiss German.",
  "wienerisch.w-159": "The „Schaberndak“ is, in Viennese, a prank, a trick or a funny stunt — related to „Schabernack“ (mischief). „Mach kane Schaberndaks!“ (Don't play any pranks!). With the characteristic Viennese „d“ at the end, the word sounds almost dance-like. In Viennese cabaret and folk comedy, the Schaberndak is an important element — typical of the Viennese love for polished wit (Schmäh).",
  "fraenkisch.fr-159": "The „Worschdsuppm“ is a Franconian specialty — the hearty broth in which sausages were cooked, eaten with bread, onions and sometimes eggs. Especially after home slaughtering, the sausage soup was the first meal the helpers got. Today a hearty starter or served as supper with strong farmhouse bread. „Worscht“ is the Franconian form of „Wurst“ (sausage).",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-163": "The „Pöter“ is, in the Ruhr region and the Rhineland, the bottom or behind — a harmless, often joking term. „Hau ab auf deinen Pöter!“ (Sit down!). Derived from the Low German „Pötjer“. Parents like to use the word in baby talk: „Wisch dir den Pöter ab!“ (Wipe your bottom!). The sound is cozy and down-to-earth — very Pott.",
  "alemannisch.al-163": "In Alemannic, and especially in Swiss German, „Häfeli“ is both a little pot and the first year of kindergarten. In Basel and Zurich, children go to the „Häfeli“ — the younger level before the „Chindsgi“. Literally „little harbor/pot“, because the children there still sit in pots. In southern Baden it's more of a kitchen term for small pots.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-150": "The „Zwiwwelkuche“ is the savory onion tart on a baking sheet — topped with onions, bacon, cream and caraway. „Zwiwwelkuche un Fedderweißer, des is Pälzer Herbscht!“ (Onion tart and new wine, that's Palatinate autumn!). From „Zwiwwel“ (onion) and „Kuche“ (cake). Eaten lukewarm with Federweißer (young, fermenting wine), an inseparable Palatinate autumn combination. Available at every Strausswirtschaft (wine grower's tavern) and every Keschdefescht (chestnut festival). A classic seasonal dish that embodies the conviviality of Palatinate autumn and forms a perfect unity with the new wine.",
  "hessisch.h-206": "The „Frankfurter Kranz“ is a famous buttercream cake from Frankfurt — ring-shaped, with brittle (Krokant), vanilla buttercream and cherries. Invented in the 18th century, when Frankfurt was a free imperial city. It's said to commemorate the imperial coronations in Frankfurt Cathedral (wreath-shaped like a crown). Today a confectionery classic throughout Germany. Every Hessian patisserie has it — some better, some worse. A family cake recipe often passed down through generations.",
  "berlinisch.b-196": "„Weil wir dich lieben“ (Because we love you) is the famous BVG ad campaign since 2015 — self-ironic, hipster-friendly, often viral. With commercials that present the reality of Berlin's BVG (delays, chaos) with humor. The campaign turned the BVG into a cult phenomenon. Young Berliners sport BVG black-and-yellow looks. The best German transit-authority advertising of recent years.",
  "bayerisch.by-175": "A „Halbe“ is a beer mug holding 0.5 liters — the medium size between „Seidla“ (0.33l) and „Maß“ (1l). In taverns, especially in the Franconian-influenced part of Bavaria, beer is often served in Halben. At the Oktoberfest the Maß dominates, but at home and in the local pub the Halbe is standard. Order: „A Halbe Helles, bittschön“ (A half-liter of light beer, please). The Halbe is practically the Bavarian glass of wine.",
  "saechsisch.s-158": "In Saxony, „Schlampe“ historically meant a sloppy, untidy person — not the insult common today. It comes from Middle High German „schlampen“ (to hang down loosely). „A liederliche Schlampe“ describes someone who doesn't keep the house in order. Today increasingly taboo because of its ambiguous meaning. Some older Saxons still use it in the traditional sense without hesitation.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-161": "„Mädle“ is, in Swabian, any girl or young woman — a diminutive of „Mädchen“. „A fesch Mädle“ is a pretty girl. Omnipresent in love songs and Swabian dialect literature. „Schaffe, schaffe, Häusle baue, und net nach de Mädle gschaue“ (Work, work, build a little house, and don't look at the girls) warns against letting yourself be distracted by girls. Plural: „Mädle“ (same as singular) or „Mädles“. Affectionate and respectful at the same time.",
  "koelsch.k-182": "„Hött dr Schnüss!“ is the Kölsch, rather coarse demand to be quiet — „Schnüss“ is the mouth, the gob. „Hött“ is the Kölsch form of „halt“ (hold/stop). Not meant kindly, but in the Kölsch tone it still sounds softer than the standard-German variant. Heard in arguments between siblings or during carnival with annoying acquaintances. Kölsch wit (Schmäh) permits such directness.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-163": "A „Buschen“ is, in Low German, a bunch or bundle — usually of flowers, herbs or twigs. „En Buschen Tulpen“ for a bunch of tulips. „Buschen vun Petersilie“ for a bunch of parsley. Derived from Middle High German „bosch“ (bush). Also metaphorically for a group: „En Buschen Kinner“ means a lot of children. A characteristic Low German quantity expression with strikingly concrete imagery.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-165": "„Hudigäggeler“ is the Swiss German, often jokingly derogatory term for folksy music (Ländler, schlager in traditional-costume style). The sound of the word itself caricatures the swaying rhythm of this music. Popular Hudigäggeler performers: Oesch's die Dritten, Calimeros. Often smiled at in urban Zurich, an important part of musical culture in the rural regions. Tribute concerts draw thousands.",
  "wienerisch.w-160": "The „Pfropfn“ is, in Viennese, the cork of a wine bottle or a stopper. „Mach den Pfropfn aussa!“ (Pull the cork out!) is the call to open the wine. Figuratively also for a blocked throat or dense traffic: „A Pfropfn am Gürtel!“ (A jam on the Gürtel — Vienna's ring road of the outer districts). The Viennese „pf“ is typical — almost hissed out.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-160": "„Zenndla“ is the Franconian diminutive of „Zähne“ (teeth) — small teeth or children's milk teeth. „Die ersten Zenndla kommen“ (The first little teeth are coming) is said when a baby starts teething. Also figuratively: „Knoblauch-Zenndla“ are cloves of garlic. The Franconian diminutive with „-la“ makes the word warm-hearted and child-friendly.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-164": "„Wat geht ab?“ is the youthful Pott greeting — a question about the current state of things. Today it often replaces the traditional „Glück auf“ or „Tach“. „Wat geht ab im Pott?“ or shortened „Wat geht?“ — the answer usually: „Nix, alles ruhig“ (Nothing, all quiet) or „Geht so“ (So-so). A casual, laid-back form of communication, typical of the easygoing Pott mentality.",
  "alemannisch.al-164": "„Brut“ is the Alemannic pronunciation of „Brot“ (bread) — the „o“ shifts to a „u“, which makes up the soft sound of Alemannic. In southern Baden, Alsace and Switzerland people say „Brut“, „Schwarzbrut“, „Weißbrut“. Bread holds a special place in Alemannic: with the Vesper (snack), with wine, with cheese — Brut is basically present everywhere.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-151": "The „Zwiwwel“ is the onion — indispensable in Palatinate cuisine, whether in Wurschtsalad (sausage salad), Zwiwwelkuche or Grumbeersalad (potato salad). „Schneid mir a Zwiwwel klää fer de Salad.“ (Chop me an onion small for the salad). Spoken with a soft „w“, typical of the dialect. Whoever chops an onion gets teary eyes. Also „a Zwiwwel uff em Kopp“ (an onion on the head) for a bump. A classic everyday word from Palatinate cuisine, appearing in nearly every hearty dish of the region and shaping its down-to-earth cooking culture.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-152": "The „Kraut“ is sauerkraut — a firm component of hearty Palatinate cuisine, with Saumagen, with bratwurst or with Buwespitzle. „Saumache mit Kraut un Grumbeere, des is mei Sonndagsesse!“ (Saumagen with sauerkraut and potatoes, that's my Sunday meal!). Fermented from white cabbage, sour and hearty. Cooked in big pots and served with almost all meat dishes. The Palatinate is also a growing region for cabbage. A classic word of the regional food culture, underscoring the Palatines' fondness for hearty, traditional side dishes.",
  "hessisch.h-208": "The „Wertheimer“ is a Frankfurt apple-wine tradition — a wooden tray with holders for several Geripptes (ribbed apple-wine glasses), so the glass jugs don't tip over. It dates from a time when Frankfurt taverns were cramped. Today a collector's item. Often used as decoration in apple-wine pubs. It recalls the conviviality of old Sachsenhausen taprooms. Also available as a souvenir item.",
  "berlinisch.b-198": "Berlin's waste separation is legendarily chaotic — sometimes with yellow bags, sometimes with bins, sometimes with special rules per district. Berliners are not waste-separation pros (compared to southern German cities). But the city cleaning service BSR still does a good job. With the \"BSR garbageman calendar\" — an advertising-sketch comedy classic.",
  "bayerisch.by-178": "\"Habidere\" is a polite, almost archaic Bavarian greeting or farewell — a short form of \"Habe die Ehre\" (I have the honor of greeting you). It is used above all by older generations and cultivated in traditional-costume circles. It expresses respect and refined courtesy. More than just \"hello,\" less than a compliment — the exact level between formal and warm. At formal occasions, with a hat: \"Habi(d)ere, gnä Frau!\" (Madam!).",
  "saechsisch.s-160": "In Saxon, \"Zerwerfung\" is a serious falling-out, the quarrel between friends, siblings or spouses. \"A Zerwerfung gehabt\" means to have experienced a rift. Stronger than \"argument,\" weaker than \"breakup.\" It sounds almost literary and old-fashioned, but has survived in the Saxon vocabulary. Frequently used in homeland films and folk plays from Saxony. It sounds like it has irrevocable consequences.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-163": "\"Knöpfle\" has two meanings in Swabian: 1) the diminutive of \"Knopf\" — a small button on clothing. 2) A variety of Spätzle: thicker, round dumplings of dough, often served as Käsknöpfle (baked with cheese). \"Knöpfle\" are the shorter, more bite-sized version of the long Spätzle. A specialty in many Swabian inns. Also very widespread in the Allgäu. Both meanings coexist peacefully in usage.",
  "koelsch.k-184": "In Kölsch, the \"Quetschebüggel\" is the accordion — literally \"squeeze-bag.\" The humorous term vividly describes the instrument: a bag for squeezing. Indispensable in Cologne's folk music — from classics like Willi Ostermann to modern carnival bands. The Quetschebüggel accompanies every genuine carnival march and gives the music its characteristic touch.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-165": "\"Lütt Dirn\" is the little girl in Low German — a diminutive form of address for daughters, granddaughters or little girls in general. \"Komm her, mien lütt Dirn\" (Come here, my little girl) is a tender form of address. \"Dirn\" comes from the Middle High German \"dierne\" (maid, young girl), which became pejorative in High German but has remained affectionate in Low German. Omnipresent in folk songs and northern German literature. A symbol of family warmth.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-167": "A \"Värs\" is, in Swiss German, a saying, a verse or a short story — also an episode from life. \"Erzähl mer en Värs!\" (Tell me something!). At the Sechseläuten in Zurich, traditional \"Värs\" are recited. In Swiss German dialect poetry (Mani Matter, Endo Anaconda), the \"Värs\" is a central form. Also in children's language: rhymes, little verses to recite.",
  "wienerisch.w-162": "In Viennese, a \"Gschnas\" is a masked ball, especially during Carnival. Famous are the historic \"Künstlergschnasen\" (artists' balls) of the Vienna Secession (early 20th century), at which Klimt, Schiele and their friends dressed up and celebrated. Still popular today: every Carnival has its Gschnasen — in the Sofiensäle, the Hofburg, in dance schools. A Viennese festive culture where costume and Schmäh (wit) meet.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-162": "\"Dischbedirn\" is the Franconian corruption of \"disputieren\" (to dispute) — to discuss or argue passionately. The word has something mocking about it, because it bends the highbrow foreign word into Franconian. \"Sie hen wieder dischbedirt!\" (They've been quarreling again!) is said of a married couple who have had a fight. The typical Franconian consonant softening (b instead of p) makes the word cosier than its standard German counterpart.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-166": "A \"Bömmel\" in the Ruhr region is a tuft of hair or a ponytail — also the pom-pom on a cap. \"Mach dir mal n Bömmel\" (Put your hair up in a bun) says the mother to her daughter with loose hair. In a broader sense, also all sorts of little appendages, tassels, decorations. The word is warm and suited to everyday life; it comes from the Low German \"bommel\" for a small ball.",
  "alemannisch.al-166": "The \"Hüseli\" is the Alemannic-Swiss diminutive of \"Haus\" (house) — a little house, often with an affectionate connotation. \"E Hüseli im Grüne\" (a little house in the countryside) describes the ideal image of a home in nature. The diminutive form with \"-eli\" is typically Alemannic and occurs from Switzerland to Alsace. It expresses warmth, familiarity and fondness.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-153": "The \"Worschtsoss\" is a hearty sauce served with sausage, or a braised dish made with sausage. \"Im Beischt gibt's die beschte Worschtsoss mit Grumbeere.\" (At the wine tavern there's the best sausage sauce with potatoes.) From \"Worscht\" (sausage) and \"Soss\" (sauce). It denotes the rich gravy in which sausages are braised, often with onions and mustard. Served with potatoes or bread, a hearty tavern dish. Classic home cooking of the Palatinate wine-tavern kitchen, showing how sausage and sauce turn into a filling meal.",
  "hessisch.h-209": "\"Eintracht!\" is the battle cry of the Eintracht Frankfurt fans — a mantra in the Commerzbank Arena. Eintracht Frankfurt was founded in 1899, won the German Championship in 1959, the DFB Cup in 1980 and 2022, and the Europa League in 2022. Pure Hessian football identity. \"Black and white\" are the club colors. Fans call themselves the \"black-and-white carousel.\" The Bornheimer Hang is their home turf. Eintracht defeats are part of the Hessian life cycle.",
  "berlinisch.b-199": "The Tegeler See in the north of Berlin is a popular recreational area — water sports, a lido, boat tours. Also famous for the \"Tegeler Insel\" (Tegel Island) — where the Berlin Tegelsee brewery stood. With the former Tegel airport in the background (closed in 2020). In summer a Berlin stronghold for families and athletes. Capital-city nature.",
  "bayerisch.by-179": "In Bavarian, the \"Hocker\" is a three-legged or four-legged stool — usually of wood, without a backrest, often by the entrance or in front of the Brotzeit (snack) bench. Indispensable in alpine huts and farmhouses. \"Sich auf an Hocker setzen\" (to sit down on a stool) or \"an Hocker rüberziehen\" (to pull a stool over) are everyday phrases. Also metaphorical: to sit \"auf m Hocker\" for a shaky position. The \"Melkschemel\" (milking stool) is a special form for the stable.",
  "saechsisch.s-161": "The \"Stulle\" is, in the north of Saxony (Leipzig, Dresden), the open-faced sandwich — to the south of there (Erzgebirge) it is more commonly called \"Bemme.\" It comes from the Middle High German \"stollen\" (support). \"A Stulle Schmalz\" (a slice of bread with lard) is a classic snack-break meal. In GDR usage absolutely omnipresent: every schoolbag had its Stullenbüchse (sandwich box). Still common today in Leipzig vernacular. Berlin and Brandenburg share the term.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-164": "The \"Dialler\" is, in Swabian, the colloquial term for the roofer (regionally also the chimney sweep). It comes from \"Dial\" (roof, ceiling). Swabian craft tradition: roofers used to be important village figures who maintained houses across generations. Today a specialized trade. \"A guater Dialler\" (a good roofer) is valued in the village — a sloppy roofer leads to generations of problems.",
  "koelsch.k-185": "\"Pingelich\" describes, in Kölsch, an overly precise, pedantic person — someone who pays attention to every detail and cannot let go. \"Sei net so pingelich!\" (Don't be so finicky!). In Carnival and in the Cologne mentality, fussiness is rather smiled at — the people of Cologne are fundamentally more easygoing and focus more on the essentials. The word comes from Dutch and has found a home in the Rhineland.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-166": "\"Suttje\" describes, in Low German, a quiet, cosy, relaxed state — \"Suttje an't Werk gahn\" means to go about one's work calmly and deliberately. \"Suttje\" is a virtue word: don't rush, don't bluster, act with care. It comes from the old North German \"suttisch\" (gentle). Especially popular in Hamburg: \"Suttje, suttje, dat löppt all\" (Easy, easy, it'll all work out) — meant reassuringly. It expresses North German composure.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-168": "\"Es Säuli\" is the Swiss German diminutive of \"Sau\" (sow) — either literally a small pig or, figuratively, a dirty child (\"du chliis Säuli, jitz bisch ganz dreckig!\" — you little piggy, now you're all filthy!). Also in children's language: \"Säulispiel\" (something that gets you dirty). The expression is affectionately teasing, not insulting. Very typical of the Swiss fondness for diminutive forms with \"-li.\"",
  "wienerisch.w-163": "The \"Reindling\" is a traditional yeast-dough bake from Carinthia and Vienna — filled with raisins, cinnamon, sugar and sometimes nuts. It is baked at Easter, Christmas or for special occasions. In Vienna it is often served as a sweet main dish (in the \"Mehlspeisen\" — sweet flour-based dishes — tradition). The word comes from \"Rein\" (a large pot) — baked in the large pot. A specialty of old Austrian cuisine.",
  "fraenkisch.fr-163": "\"Saumäßich\" is a common intensifier in Franconian and means \"very,\" \"extraordinarily\" or \"extremely.\" \"Saumäßich guad\" (very good), \"saumäßich kalt\" (very cold). The literal meaning \"like a sow\" has faded; today the expression is used in a completely value-neutral way. A typical example of the Franconian love of drastic intensifications.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-167": "\"Datt is mir wurscht\" or \"Wurschtegal\" is the Ruhr-region form of \"I don't care.\" Here, sausage becomes a symbol of indifference — perhaps because sausage is something arbitrary, interchangeable? The turn of phrase occurs throughout the German-speaking world, but in the Ruhr region it sounds especially down-to-earth thanks to the typical pronunciation \"datt\" and \"wurscht.\"",
  "alemannisch.al-167": "A \"Tüpfli\" is Alemannic for a little dot or a tiny detail. \"S'i-Tüpfli\" (the dot on the i) is the last fine little touch that completes a work — \"the dot on the i\" (the finishing touch). In Swiss German, \"tüpflisch\" is an adjective for someone who is pedantically precise. A \"Tüpflischiisser\" is a pedant — a wonderfully vivid Alemannic coinage.",
  "alemannisch.al-168": "The \"Föhn\" is, in the Alemannic region (Black Forest, Switzerland, Vorarlberg), a warm, dry downslope wind from the Alps that occurs especially in spring and autumn. It can melt snow, clear visibility and cause headaches — \"Föhn sickness\" is a well-known phenomenon. \"Föhntag\" (a foehn day) means unusually clear views of the mountains — during a foehn you can see from Lake Constance all the way to the Alps.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-155": "The \"Leberworscht\" is liverwurst — a spreadably soft Palatinate sausage specialty, fine or coarse, spread on farmhouse bread. \"A Brot mit frischer Leberworscht un a saure Gurk!\" (A slice of bread with fresh liverwurst and a pickled gherkin!). Freshly made at the home slaughter and distributed to the neighbors. From \"Leber\" (liver) and \"Worscht\" (sausage). Mildly or strongly seasoned, it is part of every Palatinate Vesper (snack). A classic word of the regional sausage and food culture, reflecting the importance of home slaughtering and the Brotzeit in the Palatinate.",
  "pfaelzisch.pf-154": "The \"Bratworscht\" is the Palatinate bratwurst — coarse, spicy, off the charcoal grill, available at every festival and market. \"A Bratworscht im Weck mit Senf, des g'hört zur Kerwe!\" (A bratwurst in a bun with mustard, that's part of the parish fair!). From \"brate\" (to fry/roast) and \"Worscht\" (sausage). The Palatinate butchers are famous for their bratwurst; each region has its own recipe. In a bun, with mustard and Schorle (wine spritzer), a complete festive meal. A classic word of the regional food culture, inseparably linked with the wine festival, the Kerwe and the Palatinate Wurstmarkt.",
  "hessisch.h-210": "The \"Adler\" (eagle) is the heraldic animal of Eintracht Frankfurt — stylized in black and white. It refers to the imperial eagle from the time when Frankfurt was a free imperial city. \"Mir san die Adler!\" (We are the eagles!) is an Eintracht chant. Also a nickname for the team: \"the eagles\" won the Europa League. A tattoo motif for many fans. An eagle statue in the stadium. A symbol of Frankfurt's greatness — historically and sportingly. The black-and-white eagle jerseys are recognizable worldwide.",
  "berlinisch.b-200": "\"Ick bin Berliner\" (I am a Berliner) is Berlin's local self-affirmation — the typically Berlin pride in the capital. No matter where you originally come from: whoever lives in Berlin is a Berliner. Berlin is a city of multiculturalism, of immigrants, of former West and East residents. \"Being a Berliner\" is a choice, not a birthright. Berlin identity — open, cheeky, warm-hearted.",
  "bayerisch.by-180": "The \"Zwetschgendatschi\" is THE Bavarian-Franconian yeast cake with plums — spread out flat, topped with halved plums and sprinkled with cinnamon sugar. \"Datschi\" comes from \"datschen\" (to press, to flatten), because the dough is pressed flat. A seasonal classic in autumn, when the plums are ripe. With whipped cream, a delight. The dispute over whether yeast dough or shortcrust pastry makes the real Datschi runs through all of Bavaria.",
  "saechsisch.s-162": "The \"Eierschecke\" is THE Saxon cake landmark — a three-layered quark cake of shortcrust base, quark layer and an egg-almond crust. Invented in the 17th century in Dresden, it is regarded as the \"queen of Saxon baked goods.\" Available at coffee time in every patisserie between the Erzgebirge and Lusatia. \"Eierschecke mit Schlagsahne\" (Eierschecke with whipped cream) is a Sunday specialty. The dispute over which bakery makes the best one runs through all of Saxony.",
  "schwaebisch.sw-165": "The \"Knöpfla\" is, in Swabian, the door knocker — usually a metal element on the front door. It comes from \"klopfen\" (to knock). Old Swabian houses have elaborate Knöpfla of brass or iron. \"Anklopfen\" (to knock) thus refers to the traditional sound before entering. Today mostly replaced by the doorbell, but preserved as a historic detail in old buildings. Also used as a diminutive for any small knocking mechanism.",
  "koelsch.k-186": "\"Bützcher\" is the plural of \"Bützje\" — the Cologne carnival kisses that, during the foolish season, are pressed onto everyone's cheeks or mouth everywhere. \"Bützcher verdeile\" (handing out kisses) is a Cologne carnival tradition. Unlike the erotic kiss, Bützcher are harmless and social — an expression of the general carnival friendliness. \"Bützcher-Gefahr\" (kiss danger) is the jocular warning against excessive carnival kisses.",
  "plattdeutsch.p-167": "\"Pott\" has two meanings in Low German: 1) Pot, kettle — \"Wat is in den Pott?\" (What's in the pot?) is a cooking question. 2) Ship — above all a freighter or a fishing cutter. \"En oler Pott\" is an old ship, often meant affectionately. In Hamburg dialect: \"Vun Pott to Pott\" means from ship to ship. North German maritime culture pervades the language. Also metaphorical: \"in een Pott smieten\" means to throw together.",
  "schwizerduetsch.ch-169": "\"Üse Bundi\" is the affectionate, almost familial term for \"our Federal Council\" — the seven-member Swiss government. Instead of a president, Switzerland has a collective of seven equal-ranking Federal Councillors who rotate the chairmanship annually (Federal President). This collective leadership is part of Swiss consensus democracy. The Swiss often speak with benevolent mockery about \"üse Bundi.\"",
  "wienerisch.w-164": "\"Tachles redn\" means, in Viennese, \"to speak plainly,\" \"to talk directly and honestly without sugarcoating.\" \"Jetzt redn wir Tachles!\" (Now let's talk turkey!) — an end to beating around the bush. From the Yiddish \"tachles\" (purpose, point). A term that shows the Yiddish-German linguistic blend in old Vienna. In business, in relationships, in politics — when things get serious, the Viennese say \"Tachles!\"",
  "fraenkisch.fr-164": "\"Naa\" is the Franconian form of \"no\" — with a short or long \"a,\" depending on the situation. A \"Naa!\" said with emphasis is final. \"Naa, naa\" (doubled) expresses pity or regret (\"What a shame!\"). The expression differs from the Bavarian \"Naa\" through a somewhat softer pronunciation. Characteristic of the Franconian dialect, which works a lot with short vowels and hard consonants.",
  "ruhrdeutsch.ru-168": "A \"Möp\" in the Ruhr region is a somewhat plump, chubby person — often meant affectionately and teasingly, not nastily. Also used for animals (especially small dogs like pugs). \"Komm her, mein Möpchen\" (Come here, my little pug) says the grandma to her somewhat chubby grandchild. The expression is mild and belongs to the Pott language with its fondness for direct but not heartless terms. Pott humor allows itself such liberties among intimates.",
  "hessisch.h-211": "\"Mainmetropole\" (Main metropolis) is Frankfurt's official self-promotion — the city on the river Main. It is used in tourism advertising and business press releases. Frankfurt is Germany's banking capital (\"Bankfurt\"), a trade-fair metropolis and the seat of the European Central Bank. \"Skyline am Main\" (skyline on the Main) is the iconic image. The Hessians are proud of their Main metropolis — but also a little mocking about the bankers' image-polishing.",
  "berlinisch.b-201": "A \"Molle\" is, in Berlinish, a glass of beer — usually a pale lager. \"Eene Molle mit Korn\" (a beer with a shot of Korn schnapps) is the classic Berlin order (beer with a schnapps on the side). The expression comes from the 19th-century Berlin corner-pub slang and is a genuine Berlin original. Still in use in the corner pubs of Kreuzberg and Friedrichshain — the hipster says \"craft beer,\" the real Berliner says \"Molle.\"",
};
